</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Experts doubt a libel lawsuit would succeed
 &HT;    By Jay Croft
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Much of the media coverage of JonBenet Ramsey's murder
has focused on the girl's parents, who have maintained their
innocence while authorities said John and Patsy Ramsey were under
suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   Now that a Boulder, Colo., grand jury has declined to indict
anyone in the 6-year-old beauty queen's killing, could the Ramseys
pursue defamation suits against news organizations?
</P>
<P>
   It would be difficult, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Most states, including Colorado, have a one-year statute of
limitations on libel claims, said Tom Kelley, an attorney for The
Denver Post and other newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   JonBenet's death three years ago drew worldwide attention, and
the Ramseys quickly became public figures after investigators said
they were under suspicion, Kelley said.
</P>
<P>
   As public figures, the Ramseys would have to prove a ne
</P>
</TEXT>
