<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMSEY14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ramsey grand jury ends its probe with no charges
 &HT;    By Craig Schneider
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOULDER, Colo. _ District Attorney Alex Hunter announced
Wednesday that after a year of grand jury investigation of the
killing of JonBenet Ramsey, their work is done and no one has been
indicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``No charges have been filed,'' Hunter said during a brief press
conference outside the Boulder Justice Center. ``I and my
prosecution task force believe we do not have sufficient evidence
to warrant the filing of charges against anyone who has been
investigated at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision may effectively end the official inquiry into the
3-year old mystery that has attracted widespread attention. Even if
police decide to continue their investigations, many believe the
grand jury was the best chance of finding justice for the slaying
of the 6-year-old beauty queen.
</P>
<P>
   One person not willing to call it quits was Colorado Gov. Bill
Owens. He vowed Wednesday to review the case and decide whether to
appoint a special prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I am not presently in a position to comment on the work
of this grand jury, I do know one fact: A little girl was brutally
murdered in Boulder, Colorado, and the killer or killers remain
free today,'' Owens said.
</P>
<P>
   For the Ramsey family and their supporters, Wednesday's
announcement was received as vindication for JonBenet's parents,
John and Patsy Ramsey, who now live in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Ramseys issued a statement Wednesday night, saying ``the
Ramsey family lives in a nightmare'' and asking that the
investigation continue. ``We take no satisfaction in this result
because a child killer remains free and undetected,'' the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
   Linda McLean, a longtime family friend, said she spoke to
JonBenet's mother after the grand jury's decision. She said Patsy
Ramsey told her: ``We're thankful to God. We were on our knees
praying to God when the decision was announced. Now let's get on
with finding out who did this.''
</P>
<P>
   McLean, 65, who lives in Patsy Ramsey's hometown of Parkersburg,
Pa., said even if police stop searching for the killer, the Ramseys
have vowed to look ``until their last dollar, until their last
breath.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's decision brings to a head three years of trying to
find the killer of the vivacious girl. From the start, Boulder
police and other authorities came under scrutiny and criticism, and
some believe the grand jury's decision not to indict anyone is the
culmination of bad police work and misguided efforts by the
district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's preposterous to think an intruder did all those things in
that house,'' said Craig Silverman, a former chief deputy district
attorney in Boulder. Silverman left the district attorney's office
before JonBenet was killed and has had no official standing in the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Silverman thrust blame at the present district attorney, saying,
``We haven't had many murders in Boulder, but Alex Hunter has
consistently failed to be able to put a person behind bars.''
</P>
<P>
   Other critics say police are to blame for not sealing off the
crime scene. Instead, police allowed John Ramsey to search the
home, and he found the girl's body in a basement and brought it
upstairs, compromising the crime scene and evidence, some charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was a flawed case from the start. The evidence at
the crime scene was contaminated and the body was moved,'' said
William Pizzi, a law professor at the University of Colorado and a
former federal prosecutor in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The case was handed over to a grand jury after the investigation
stalled amid infighting between the police and the district
attorney's office, much of which was played out publicly through
press leaks.
</P>
<P>
   But for the past year, the grand jury of 12 Boulder residents
have met in secret, hearing from witnesses and reviewing more than
30,000 pages in the case file.
</P>
<P>
   ``The grand jurors have done their work extraordinarily well,
bringing to bear all of their legal powers and life experiences and
shrewdness,'' Hunter said during his brief remarks Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Hunter's comments left several unanswered questions, which
may be addressed during an afternoon news conference today. For
instance, under state law a grand jury can vote to bring an
indictment but a district attorney can chose not to follow their
recommendation. It is unknown exactly what action was taken
Wednesday by the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   JonBenet, with her pretty face and cascading blond curls, was a
rising star in child beauty pageants when she was found strangled
and beaten in the basement of her family's upscale Boulder home the
morning after Christmas Day in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   John Ramsey said he found her body about eight hours after his
wife found a ransom note demanding $118,000 for the girl's safe
return.
</P>
<P>
   From the outset the case stirred controversy. No crime since the
O.J. Simpson case held such a sustained fascination both for the
tabloids and the mainstream media. When Hunter made his
announcement Wednesday, it was to a throng of nearly 200
journalists from across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery has created a stream of books, documentary films,
headlines and nightly news segments. There was Patsy Ramsey
speaking on CNN just days after the slaying, warning Boulder
residents a killer was on the loose. There was the autopsy
information released in February 1997, revealing indications that
JonBenet may have been sexually assaulted.
</P>
<P>
   The media attention has become a whole separate tragedy for the
family, said Patsy Ramsey's sister, Pam Paugh of suburban Atlanta.
In one moment of angst she told a reporter, ``If Geraldo Rivera
calls my sister a murderer one more time, I will probably lose my
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Speculation swirled when police experts eliminated John Ramsey
as the possible author of the 2 1/2-page ransom note, but they
would neither clear nor accuse Patsy Ramsey of writing it.
</P>
<P>
   When the Ramseys hired separate lawyers and a press relations
representative, and held off formal interviews with law enforcement
authorities, criticism and suspicion mounted.
</P>
<P>
   John Ramsey eventually came to brand the police ``a lynch mob
hiding behind the authority of police badges.'' He accused them of
failing to investigate the possibility that an intruder killed his
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1997, Hunter declared that the homicide would be
solved, charges filed and the killer vigorously prosecuted. ``We
will see that justice is served in this case,'' the district
attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1997, then-Police Chief Tom Koby promised, ``Our guy
won't walk.''
</P>
<P>
   But it became apparent that the investigation was bogged down in
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, two investigators quit, having opposing opinions on
who could have killed the girl. In August 1998, detective Steve
Thomas resigned, saying the district attorney had all but joined
sides with the Ramseys and undermined attempts to investigate the
family.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, Lou Smit, a retired homicide detective brought in
to work on the case, submitted his resignation, saying had
unduly persecuted the Ramseys.
</P>
<P>
   For all the criticism leveled at the investigation, some people
saw the grand jury announcement as the proper ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows that the grand jury system works,'' said James
Peters, 50, of Boulder. ``The grand jury had access to evidence
that we never saw. I think it's right to honor the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, for many people, the announcement of no indictment came
as a hollow end to a case they've been following for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody is going to be disappointed. We were hoping
the grand jury would point to someone,'' said Gary Devine, 61, a
computer specialist in Boulder.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
