A6362 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CALVES-EUTHANASIA14-C     10-14 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALVES-EUTHANASIA14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Video of calf shootings forces changes at dairies
 &HT;    By Thomas R. Collins
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Video footage of an Okeechobee dairy
worker shooting newborn calves has led to an outcry over the way
some unwanted calves are disposed of in the dairy industry.
</P>
<P>
   Already the footage, made public this week, has led to the
drafting of new rules governing how ``cull'' animals, the name
given to unwanted or unmarketable calves, are disposed of, a
practice now completely unregulated.
</P>
<P>
   Since the footage was obtained, industry codes on the unwanted
calves have been drafted, said Orlando attorney Peter Latham, who
represents Southeast Milk Inc., an association that includes nearly
all of Florida's dairy farmers. A final hearing on the rules, which
would be enforced by the state Department of Agriculture, is set
for November, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The extent of the calves' suffering in the video _ taken in
January at McArthur Farms in Okeechobee by an undercover Humane
Society investigator _ is the subject of debate, but reaction to it
has led the state attorney's office to force the dairy to tighten
its policies on how the cull animals are killed.
</P>
<P>
   The Okeechobee footage could change the way dairies across
Florida and the nation kill sick and injured calves and calves that
are birthed for the sole purpose of allowing milk-bearing cows to
continue to produce milk.
</P>
<P>
   A report by the Humane Society of the United States based on
information from the dairy industry, says that 2 million or more
such calves are killed every year, said the society's David
Kuemmerle, who works on agricultural issues.
</P>
<P>
   Animal rights advocates and dairy farmers agree that's not
likely to change soon. In dairy farming, some of the calves born
each year are kept to become milk-bearing, and others are killed
later for veal. But most male calves are killed usually within a
day or two of birth. Unlike cows slaughtered for meat, there are no
rules governing how the unwanted calves are killed.
</P>
<P>
   The Humane Society dispatched investigators after getting a tip
about the calves' slaughter from a McArthur Farms worker, Kuemmerle
said. He said he didn't know how they managed to get onto the
private farms and document calf-killings, something nearly
impossible to do.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators were out of the country on another assignment
Wednesday and not available for comment, said a spokeswoman, who
added, ``I can definitely assure you that it was obtained
legally.'' Kuemmerle said the society has never obtained footage
like that from McArthur Farms.
</P>
<P>
   In the video, a worker carries live black and white calves by
their legs from a cart to a makeshift mass grave about 5 feet deep.
After either flinging or dropping the day-old calves into the
ditch, some of them try to wobble their way out of the hole on
still-shaky legs. When three or four are in the ditch, the worker
shoots them in the head one by one, then repeats the process until
about 15 lie in a heap in about a foot of rainwater. Many of the
calves' legs writhe after the shooting, prompting the worker to
shoot them again.
</P>
<P>
   Kuemmerle said he fears that many of the unwanted calves suffer
during execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the animals were obviously still alive after being
shot,'' Kuemmerle said. ``The animals seemed to be left unattended.
Many of them are struggling to keep their heads above the water.
This is after they had been shot. So certainly it is conceivable
that some of these animals were buried alive.''
</P>
<P>
   But McArthur Farms attorney, T. Charles Shafer of Fort Pierce,
said that the movement of the animals after the shootings is
``neurological function,'' according to large animal veterinarians
he has consulted. The Humane Society is trying to shock people to
try to make a point, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the shock value wears off ... it's not what it appears to
be at first glance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the dairy acknowledged that the worker violated its
policy at the time, which was simply to shoot the calves
point-blank in the center of the forehead. He said the dairy agreed
to enter into a pretrial intervention agreement _ a disciplinary
measure in lieu of criminal prosecution _ ``to put it behind
them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a corporate entity, you have to take
responsibility for the negligence of your employees and that's what
McArthur Farms did,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement calls for the dairy to ``support and actively
assist in the passage of legislation designed to provide for the
human euthanasia of sick and cull animals,'' and to host and
participate in a training program on the matter. Until statewide
rules are enacted, the dairy has to adopt policies for humane
treatment, including where to hold the weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant State Attorney Nikki Robinson, who worked the case,
said the agreement was preferable to prosecution because it will
probably yield results more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Kuemmerle said he hopes rules are on the books soon as a result
of the footage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that this is what the public needs to see,'' he said.
``We refer to this as one of the industry's dirty little secrets.
We want people to know where the food they purchase comes from.''
</P>
<P>
   Latham, who said even he was shocked at first by the McArthur
Farms footage but said the calves probably didn't suffer much,
acknowledged a ``void'' in the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an initial shock value that everyone needs from time
to time _ that everything we do has consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
