<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALCS-NOTES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    R. Martinez regroups
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A season that began with his audition for a set of
suspicious scouts in the Dominican Republic, that continued with
minor-league sentences to City of Palms (Fla.), Sarasota, Lowell
(Mass.) and Pawtucket, comes full circle tonight for Ramon
Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen months after his right rotator cuff was surgically
repaired, Martinez starts in Game 2 of the ALCS.
</P>
<P>
   ``(There's) a difference in my velocity maybe, but everything
else, it is there,'' Martinez said. ``I can throw all my pitches. I
don't have any kind of problem with my arm. And I feel better and
better.''
</P>
<P>
   In four September starts, Martinez went 2-1 with a 3.05 ERA,
allowing 14 hits while striking out 15 in 20 2/3 innings. He has
never faced the New York Yankees, but pitched effectively in Game 3
of the Division Series with Cleveland (two runs, five hits, six
strikeouts in 5 2/3 innings) and was an easy choice for manager
Jimy Williams to start tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got progessively better with each of his starts,'' Williams
said. ``I think he has got his trunks under him, got good legs. And
even though he pitched seven innings a couple times, I didn't think
he was tired. So experience-wise, you go with the man, you know?
Believe in him.''
</P>
<P>
   LEYRITZ ODD MAN OUT
</P>
<P>
   October rolls on without one of its former heroes. Jim Leyritz
was left off the Yankees' ALCS roster.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill started in right field Wednesday night, but because
he has a broken rib, Yankees manager Joe Torre, faced with a
potential outfielder shortage, dropped Leyritz, kept rookie
outfielder Clay Bellinger and added Shane Spencer. Leyritz was
0-for-2 in the Division Series and hit .185 in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very difficult,'' said Torre. ``I mean, even though
Jimmy struggled toward the end of the season, that didn't keep me
from going to him in Games 1 and 2 against Texas in situations. So
I just felt with O'Neill's possible condition, that if we happen to
lose him _ which I don't even want to think about _ I needed
another outfielder.''
</P>
<P>
   MERCK PLAYS FALL BALL
</P>
<P>
   Game 1 starter Kent Mercker is back in October after a
three-year absence. He appeared in both the 1991 and 1995 World
Series for the Braves and the following year pitched for two
playoff teams (Baltimore and Cleveland) but was left off the
Indians' postseason roster. He joined the Red Sox on Aug. 24 in a
trade with St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a part of it,'' Mercker said of his short stint in New
England. ``Baseball is a fraternity. I have been here a short time,
but they welcomed me. I have pitched decent for them down the
stretch. I'm not going to say they needed me to win those games.
They were in a good position when I got here, but I definitely feel
a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercker and outfielder Darren Lewis are the only Red Sox on the
roster with LCS experience.
</P>
<P>
   Tribute to Hunter
</P>
<P>
   The family of the late Catfish Hunter threw out the first pitch
in the Hunters' first public appearance since the Hall of Famer's
death Sept. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
