<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-DUCKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS DEFEAT MIGHTY DUCKS, 3-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Devils fans who found the Yankees and
Mets more entertaining on Wednesday than the Anaheim Mighty Ducks
missed a victory but little else.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils played their second consecutive game without
inspiration _ barring the overtime in the tie at Ottawa three days
ago _ but managed a 3-2 victory over Anaheim thanks to Lyle
Odelein's game-winning goal with 7 minutes 26 seconds left, and
three spectacular saves by Martin Brodeur in the waning moments of
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Odelein's first goal of the season, on a shot from the right
point, found its way over Guy Hebert's glove after it deflected off
the skate of Anaheim's Steve Rucchin, who was part of a crowd in
front of Hebert.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to put it on net and hope for a deflection or a
rebound, hoping that something would happen,'' Odelein said. ``We
didn't play too well at times, but Marty made the big saves as
usual.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur allowed Paul Kariya's first goal of the season in the
first period, and a soft goal to Rucchin early in the second.
Brodeur had an average game, but he got stronger as the game
progressed. It reached its zenith in the waning moments when he
denied Kariya and Teemu Selanne with spectacular saves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to make a few big saves at the end,'' said Brodeur, who
made a total of 28 saves, 6 of them on Selanne and 4 on Kariya.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little lucky at the end when the guy could get it
up,'' Brodeur said about his save on Kariya with 65 seconds left in
the game. ``I was looking down for my lenses and it came to me. We
were fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Holik and Sergei Brylin scored the first two goals for the
Devils (3-1-1).
</P>
<P>
   Kariya, who has 39 goals last season, and Selanne are two of the
most dangerous scorers in the National Hockey League, but the
Devils kept them at bay for the most part thanks primarily to
effective play by the defensive pairing of Odelein and Scott
Niedermayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun playing against their best players,'' Odelein said.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was announced at 11,109, but it seemed much smaller at
a rather quiet Continental Arena, where the Devils also played
before about 5,000 empty seats in their previous home game, the 1-0
victory over the Tampa Bay Lightning last Saturday night. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
