<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 00:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6366 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     10-14 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATLANTA _ You scan his statistics, going back to rookie league in
1986. Under the ``SV'' column, you find nothing but zeros.
</P>
<P>
   John Smoltz had never saved a game in his professional career
before Wednesday. Secretly, he had always wanted to, it turns out,
but nobody had ever given him the chance to try.
</P>
<P>
   That changed against the Mets. He got the word to manager Bobby
Cox he had an inning in him, if it was needed. And Cox decided to
give him one _ the ninth, with the Braves clinging somewhat
precariously to a 4-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different feeling,'' Smoltz said, admitting the
experience of preserving Kevin Millwood's victory for a 2-0 Atlanta
lead with the National League Champ Series heading to New
York had left him ``numb.''
</P>
<P>
   Nauseous also. He joked about looking for a place to throw up.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to build momentum as a starting pitcher,'' said
Smoltz, who has started 356 major-league games for the Braves,
winning 157 of them and going the full nine innings 47 times. ``You
try to go nine. In relief, it's all or nothing. You come out
throwing as hard as you can. There is no room for error. I've
gained a far greater appreciation for what those guys (in the
bullpen) go through.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I ran out there, I really wasn't sure what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The fans were in a frenzy, and Smoltz's heart was caught in his
throat. He found the extreme intensity of the situation startling,
but he calmed himself down, once he made pinch hitter Shawon
Dunston pop out leading off. He is John Smoltz, after all, a former
Cy Young Award winner with a 12-3 record in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I knew,'' he said, ``is how important it was to get the
first man out.''
</P>
<P>
   The second and third followed in short order. Roger Cedeno
grounded to short, and Bobby Bonilla, pinch hitting for Rey
Ordonez, struck out without ever taking the bat off his shoulder.
As much as Bonilla hates Mets manager Bobby Valentine, you'd almost
suspect collusion, except two of the three called strikes
definitely appeared to miss the outside corner.
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly where Smoltz wanted them. If he caught a break
from umpire Jeff Kellogg, then he caught a break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going to give him (Bonilla) anything over the
plate,'' he said. ``If he hit the outside pitch for a single, then
he hit a single. I didn't want him hitting a pitch over the plate
for a double.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the portly Bonilla simply stood there, looking like a
Buddha-esque statue.
</P>
<P>
   Has Smoltz been reincarnated as a fireman? Will he be the second
coming of Dennis Eckersley, a successful starter who reinvented
himself as the game's premier reliever?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he replied. ``I still prefer to start. But everything in
my career from here on out is gravy. I'll do whatever I can to
contribute, whatever it takes to help us keep winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, he resumes his normal role Saturday. He starts
Game 4 at Shea, as scheduled. If Tom Glavine can best Al Leiter on
Friday, Smoltz will be trying to pitch the Braves to a sweep and
their first appearance in the World Series since they lost to the
Yankees in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Gravy? Three months ago, Smoltz said, ``I wasn't sure I'd throw
again this season.''
</P>
<P>
   He had to go on the disabled list twice _ May 17-June 1 and July
5-24 _ with elbow pain. He ultimately returned to the rotation with
a new three-quarter-arm delivery but was still throwing in the
mid-90s. He hit 96 mph on the radar gun against Dunston, proof of
the adrenaline streaming through his wired body.
</P>
<P>
   He went to the bullpen in the fifth inning, but it didn't occur
to him he would be asked to pitch the ninth until he was actually
summoned. Cox, for his part, admitted he wouldn't have risked
wasting Smoltz under any other circumstances, such as a tie game.
Special circumstances dictated a special role.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's regular closer, John Rocker, had worked a demanding 1
innings in Game 1, then come on in relief of Millwood in the
eighth, striking out his personal pigeon, John Olerud, and Robin
Ventura to again hold the Mets at bay.
</P>
<P>
   Asking one more inning of Rocker, however, would have been
pressing his luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``John has been pitching an awful lot,'' Smoltz observed. ``He
deserved the save today, not me. I was glad just to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz appeared to feel self-conscious about taking a
front-and-center role in the pen. Afterward, he repeatedly heaped
praise on Atlanta's regular relievers, saying: ``They've had an MVP
year for us.''
</P>
<P>
   But if you are Bobby Cox and you have a John Smoltz available to
you under such circumstances, you don't worry about hurting
anyone's feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, he had called upon Millwood and Greg Maddux to relieve
in Game 3 against the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``To pitch for our club,'' Smoltz noted, ``you have to check
your ego at the door. We have so many great pitchers on this
staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Versatile ones, too, apparently.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
