<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6369 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBA-ALCS-REDSOX-YANKE     10-14 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALCS-REDSOX-YANKEES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Williams homer gives Yankees extra boost
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bernie Williams homered off Boston's Rod Beck leading
off the bottom of the 10th inning Wednesday night to give the New
York Yankees a 4-3 victory over the Red Sox in Game 1 of the
American League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   The win, on a rainy night in the Bronx, extended the Yankees'
postseason winning streak to 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   New York's Scott Brosius had a homer, a triple and a single in
his first four at-bats but the Yankees, highly favored against the
wild-card Red Sox, never led through the first nine.
</P>
<P>
   New York finally caught up in the seventh, when Red Sox reliever
Derek Lowe inherited a 3-2 lead from Rich Garces after he had
thrown two hitless innings. But Brosius, the first man Lowe faced,
singled and was advanced to second on a Chuck Knoblauch sacrifice
bunt.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter next sent a soft single into right field, which
rookie Trot Nixon sent back to the plate on one hop and in plenty
of time to catch Brosius. But catcher Jason Varitek never gloved
the throw off the rain-slicked grass and was then wiped out by
Brosius' slide, tying it 3-3. Lowe let two more runners reach
scoring position before striking out Chili Davis to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Former Brave Kent Mercker, in the first ALCS start of his
career, was used up after four innings. He threw 83 pitches to 20
hitters, allowing six hits, including a two-run Brosius homer, but
Boston still held a 3-2 lead when he was pulled for Garces.
</P>
<P>
   New York starter Orlando Hernandez, after allowing seven of the
first 10 men he faced to reach base, settled down to permit just
three hits from the third through the eighth, when he was removed
for Mariano Rivera. He faced the minimum over his last four
innings, and two of the three runs he allowed were earned.
</P>
<P>
   The most dominant force on the field early was Boston shortstop
Nomar Garciaparra, who twice took away New York runs with his
glove. He made a leaping catch of a Davis liner with two men on to
end the first inning before following it up with a running leap to
take down Tino Martinez's liner with two men on to end the third.
</P>
<P>
   The first two innings took 55 minutes to complete, proving only
that both teams were tight, if not sloppy. Jeter took advantage of
the first ALCS grounder hit to him at shortstop by throwing down
the right field line on an attempted force-out at second.
</P>
<P>
   That led to an unearned run, with Jose Offerman scoring from
first on the play. One batter later, the lead became 2-0 following
Brian Daubach's RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's advantage stretched to 3-0 the next inning when, with
Darren Lewis on third, Offerman bounced a soft grounder to the
right of the mound. Hernandez made a weak pass at it, third baseman
Brosius could not cut it off and by the time Jeter caught up with
in on the edge of the grass, Lewis had scored and Offerman was
standing on first.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees cut it to 3-2 in the bottom of the second. After
Shane Spencer sent a two-out single to left. Brosius, the World
Series MVP last fall, worked a full count against Mercker before
launching a two-run homer to left field. The homer was Brosius'
first of this postseason but his fifth in 16 career postseason
games.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
