<HEADER>
A6370 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-METS14-COX     10-14 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-METS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cox outfoxes 'em
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The postseason was supposed to give the Mets a clean
slate in their quest to unseat the Braves. Somebody forgot to tell
the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were bemoaning the same tired story by the end of their
4-3 loss at Turner Field on Wednesday. Atlanta now leads the
National League Championship Series two games to none as the teams
head to New York for Game 3 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the sixth inning, the Mets had a 2-0 lead on Kevin
Millwood. Their starter, Kenny Rogers, was coasting. And their lead
had temporarily stalled the Braves' foam tomahawk-chopping fans.
</P>
<P>
   But it wouldn't last.
</P>
<P>
   Managerial moves on both sides changed the flow of the game
beginning in the sixth. The decision of Mets manager Bobby
Valentine to leave Rogers in led to a four-run inning for the
Braves, while Braves manager Bobby Cox used John Rocker and John
Smoltz in relief to secure the team's first 2-0 lead in an NLCS
since 1995, when they swept the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to go out and try to kick them when they're down,''
said Brian Jordan, whose two-run homer tied the score 2-2. ``We
know the Mets are not going to quit. They're going to come at us
hard, and we have to be prepared to go at them hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' sixth started with a Chipper Jones walk to end his
nine-pitch standoff with Rogers. It ended with Valentine beating
himself up for leaving Rogers in long enough to give up a single to
Andruw Jones and a home run to Eddie Perez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no reason to keep him in,'' Valentine said. ``It was ...
absolutely the wrong move.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Mets' lead evaporated, so did the quiet that had fallen
over the crowd of 44,624, considerably less than capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden Brian Jordan hits a ball out and everybody
gets invigorated,'' Chipper Jones said. ``Then Eddie gets his
homer. Man. This place was loud.''
</P>
<P>
   It fell silent again in the eighth. An error by Chipper Jones
and a double by Edgardo Alfonzo cut the lead to 4-3. But the Braves
called on Rocker, who came up large for the fourth consecutive
postseason game.
</P>
<P>
   John Olerud, 0-for-9 in his career against Rocker, struck out
flinging as he lost his grip swinging at a slider. After an
intentional walk to Mike Piazza, Rocker struck out Robin Ventura to
end the eighth with the tying run at second.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz, making his first relief appearance after 379
major-league starts, retired the Mets in the ninth for the save.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
