<SLUG> BC-HOECHST-ANNOUNCE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOECHST EXPECTED TO ANNOUNCE FATE OF 1,650 JOBS IN KC AREA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH and MARK P. COUCH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ An announcement about the future of Hoechst
Marion Roussel in Kansas City is imminent, coming perhaps by the
weekend, and the news may not be good.
</P>
<P>
   At stake are the jobs of about 1,650 area employees of Hoechst
Marion, the pharmaceutical arm of German chemical giant Hoechst AG.
Hoechst AG and Rhone-Poulenc SA of France are merging their
pharmaceutical units to form Aventis SA, which will be the world's
largest drug company.
</P>
<P>
   One of the unanswered questions raised by the merger is the
effect on Kansas City, where Hoechst Marion has roughly 1,000
employees at its North American headquarters and extensive
manufacturing operations that employ about 700 others.
</P>
<P>
   The merger could result in the Kansas City headquarters moving
to Bridgewater, N.J., where Hoechst and other major drug companies
have major operations, or to Collegeville, Pa., the North American
headquarters of the Rhone-Poulenc Rorer pharmaceutical unit.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Roos, president of the Somerset County Chamber of
Commerce in New Jersey, said company officials tentatively had
scheduled a news conference there Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not heard anything officially,'' Roos said. ``But they
have spent a tremendous amount of resources here. Many of us
anticipate that the company would like to be near other companies
in its industry. We have not heard anything official. There is
gossip, and they have unofficially scheduled a news conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Rouse, a Hoechst Marion spokesman in Kansas City, said
Hoechst was working on many decisions related to the merger, which
is expected to be completed in December. He said an announcement on
the North American headquarters could come any time. He would not
elaborate on plans for a Friday news conference in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could be,'' Rouse said.
</P>
<P>
   In Philadelphia a television news report this week indicated
that 900 Hoechst Marion jobs might be moving from Kansas City to
Collegeville, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not accurate,'' Rouse said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Kansas City Area Development Council and at the
office of Mayor Kay Barnes said they had not been notified of an
impending announcement. The city established a tax-increment
financing district to assist development of the south Kansas City
complex.
</P>
<P>
   A consultant's report conducted before the merger announcement
last year estimated that the combination could result in job cuts
totaling about 11,000 worldwide and the closing of more than half
of the combined company's production facilities. In 1997 the two
companies had about 95,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   In February a state delegation went to Bridgewater in hopes of
retaining at least part of the local Hoechst Marion operation,
which is the remaining corporate legacy of the late Ewing Marion
Kauffman, former Royals owner, philanthropist and founder of Marion
Laboratories Inc.
</P>
<P>
   A decision to move Hoechst Marion jobs from Kansas City would
follow closely upon the recent news that MCI WorldCom plans to buy
Sprint Corp., the area's biggest private employer. An MCI-Sprint
merger, if approved, raises questions about possible job cuts and
the future of Sprint's new campus under construction in Overland
Park, Kan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 0034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 00:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6378 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-REDSOX-ART-     10-14 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-REDSOX-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES WIN ALCS OPENER, 4-3, ON WILLIAMS' HOMER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The underdog Boston Red Sox, who might need a little
bit of luck to beat the New York Yankees in the American League
Championship Series, were victimized by an umpire's call in the top
of the 10th inning. Then Bernie Williams finished them off in the
bottom of the 10th, just a few ticks past midnight early Thursday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Williams crushed a leadoff home run against Rod Beck, snapping a
3-3 tie in Game 1 at Yankee Stadium. Orlando Hernandez allowed all
the Red Sox runs in the first two innings, then shut out Boston
over his last six innings of work, before Mariano Rivera pitched
the final two innings.
</P>
<P>
   David Cone will pitch the second game of the four-of-seven-game
series on Thursday night at the Stadium, against Boston's Ramon
Martinez. Cone has had 11 days of rest since his last start. The
last time he had that much rest, he pitched a perfect game, against
the Montreal Expos July 18.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Offerman opened the Boston 10th with a line single to
right. John Valentin followed with a grounder to third, a possible
double-play ball; Scott Brosius fielded and threw to second, where
Chuck Knoblauch set himself to pivot, with Offerman bearing down on
him.
</P>
<P>
   But Brosius' throw went in and out of the webbing of Knoblauch's
glove, and the 57,181 fans umpiring from the stands groaned
together at the apparent mistake. The one umpire who counted,
however, Rick Reed, called Offerman out, ruling that Knoblauch had
dropped the ball as he got it from his glove. Jimy Williams, the
Boston manager, argued with Reed, without luck. Instead of having
first and second and nobody out, the Red Sox had one out and a
runner at first, and the next batter rolled into an inning-ending
double play.
</P>
<P>
   Beck relieved for the Red Sox in the bottom of the 10th, and
Williams, leading off, crushed his second pitch to straightaway
center field, where Boston's Darren Lewis turned, stopped and
watched. When the ball disappeared over the wall, Williams thrust
his fist into the air, and the crowd exploded simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   The calm demeanor of Hernandez instills confidence in his
teammates, in his manager. Hernandez passed Joe Torre in the
clubhouse the other day, smiled and waved, and Torre wished
Hernandez a happy birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't care how old you are,'' Torre said, referring to
Hernandez's publicly fluid age, and Hernandez laughed.
</P>
<P>
   El Duque strolled confidently across the field before the game,
stopping to pluck a piece of grass and toss it to see which way the
wind was blowing, as relaxed as chipping on the 10th hole on a
Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But the Red Sox changed all that quickly. Right after
Hernandez's first pitch, Boston's Offerman glared toward Hernandez.
It appeared words were exchanged, and the home-plate umpire, Tim
McClelland, stepped in. Four pitches later, Offerman lined a single
through the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin pulled a grounder toward the shortstop hole, where
Derek Jeter ranged to his right, backhanded the ball _ a
spectacular play, to that point _ jumped, twisted, threw toward
second, and into right field. Offerman wheeled around the bases as
Paul O'Neill chased down the ball along the right-field line, and
Valentin reached third.
</P>
<P>
   Then Brian Daubach dumped Hernandez's next pitch into right
field, a single, Valentin scored. Seven pitches into the game,
Hernandez already had allowed more runs than he had in three
previous post-season starts combined, and the Red Sox had scored
more runs than the Texas Rangers had against the Yankees in the
first round of the playoffs. Right away, Boston marked its
presence.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez walked the leadoff batter, Lewis, in the second
inning, to deep-throated, concerned murmurs from the crowd. Lewis
stole second and stopped at third when Trot Nixon singled sharply.
When Offerman hit a slow roller past the mound, third baseman
Brosius closed on the ball _ then let the grounder pass, thinking
Jeter would be in a better position to field it. Except that Jeter
thought Brosius would make the play.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis scored, the Red Sox led, 3-0, they had runners at first
and second and nobody out, and the Yankees looked flat.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin failed to advance the runners with nobody out and
Hernandez, as he often does, escaped further trouble and went on to
pinch off the Red Sox offense. It was a just a question of whether
the Yankees could rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Manager Jimy Williams is not a schmoozer. He doesn't like
talking about himself. He doesn't feel obligated to explain his
choices _ ``Managerial decision,'' he says, with the tone of a
security guard. He is as uncomplicated as a doorjamb, with one
simple purpose: to win baseball games. By whatever means necessary,
Williams directed the Red Sox to a division series victory over the
Cleveland Indians, using two of his starters, Bret Saberhagen and
Pedro Martinez, to win the decisive game. Ramon Martinez, who
pitched last Saturday and is coming back from shoulder surgery,
could not have pitched Wednesday night's game on shortened rest.
</P>
<P>
   So Williams turned to Kent Mercker, a left-hander only three
days removed from his last start. But Williams wasn't expecting
Mercker to throw a complete game; he just wanted Mercker to get the
Red Sox into the middle innings, preferably with a lead.
</P>
<P>
   In Mercker's time on the mound, the Yankees hit 21 foul balls,
swinging and missing just twice. But Nomar Garciaparra was playing
behind him. The Yankees had runners at second and third and two out
in the first and Chili Davis stretched to reach a changeup and hit
a hump liner over short, where Garciaparra snatched the ball with a
leap. Two runs saved.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius crushed a two-run homer off Mercker in the second
inning, and Jeter doubled leading off the third. Garciaparra nearly
picked off Jeter at second after intercepting Williams grounder in
the shortstop hole _ Jeter was far off the bag, thinking the hit
would roll through to left _ and when the throw from the Boston
shortstop got away, Jeter took third.
</P>
<P>
   But then, again with two outs, Garciaparra again soared high to
catch Tino Martinez's line drive, falling on his back. Twice
Garciaparra had prevented Jeter from scoring in the inning, first
by keeping Williams's hit in the infield, and then when he caught
Martinez's shot. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox manager went to his bullpen in the fifth, Rich
Garces assuming the 3-2 lead, shutting out the Yankees for two
innings before giving way to Derek Lowe, at the start of the
seventh. Brosius greeted Lowe with a single to left and moved to
second on Knoblauch's bunt.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter then laced a single to right, Nixon rushing the ball and
gloving it on one hop; Willie Randolph, the Yankees' third-base
coach, waved Brosius around third, a blunder, it appeared, for
Nixon's throw reached the catcher ahead of the runner.
</P>
<P>
   But Boston catcher Jason Varitek was unable to hold Nixon's
throw, the ball rolling away as Brosius _ late arriving _ crashed
into the catcher and slapped his hand on home plate. Tie game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
