<HEADER>
A6380 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-ABDUCT-KANSAS-KAN &LR;      10-14 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABDUCT-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEW ANSWERS IN ABDUCTION OF 10-YEAR-OLD GIRL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STACY DOWNS and RICHARD ESPINOZA  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ While more than 100 FBI agents and police
officers searched Wednesday for 10-year-old Pamela Butler, all
Cherri West could do was wait and hope for news about her abducted
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day _ in fact, from Tuesday evening when Pamela
was abducted in Kansas City, Kan. _ facts kept trickling to West:
</P>
<P>
   The pickup truck in which the girl was last seen was found
abandoned in Kansas City, Mo.; police fruitlessly searched an area
in Grain Valley where the truck was seen; near 10th Street and
Central Avenue in Kansas City, Kan., police spotted a man whom they
wanted to question about the case.
</P>
<P>
   Despite helicopters, police dogs and door-to-door searches,
there were no definitive answers about Pamela on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   As the night wore on, police still were looking for Keith D.
Nelson, 24, of Kansas City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson's employer said later Wednesday that Nelson had access to
the company truck that police believe was used in the abduction.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson is a white man, 5 feet 7 inches tall, 200 pounds with
blue eyes. West said she did not know Nelson and had never heard of
him.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela, who was abducted about 5:45 p.m. Tuesday while skating
near her house, is a white girl, 4 feet 5 inches tall, 65 pounds,
with blond hair and blue eyes. She was wearing a white Everlast
sports bra, tan pants and in-line skates with pink straps.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hectic,'' said West, 33. ``I haven't slept, and my eyes
feel like they're 10,000 pounds. People I've never even seen before
keep coming here.''
</P>
<P>
   Strangers stopped their cars on the street in front of West's
house in the 500 block of South 11th Street and asked for news. It
was the same area where Pamela was last seen.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday evening 11-year-old Penny Butler was sitting on the
front porch of their home watching her younger sister, Pamela,
skating on their street while holding a soft drink and cookies. A
man in a white pickup stopped a few feet from Pamela, got out,
grabbed her around her waist and threw her across the driver's seat
and into the passenger seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started screaming, and so did she,'' said Penny, who yelled
for an older sister to call the police.
</P>
<P>
   Another driver wrote down the pickup's license-plate number and
chased the truck as it sped west on Kansas Avenue but lost it near
Mill Street and Southwest Boulevard. The driver said the man he was
chasing was driving with one hand and holding something down with
his other hand, although he did not see anyone else in the truck,
FBI spokesman Jeff Lanza said.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 Ford pickup belongs to the foundation-repair business
where Nelson works.
</P>
<P>
   David Cunningham, Nelson's employer at DynaTech, said he was
surprised to hear that police were looking for Nelson, who has
worked at DynaTech for the last year-and-a-half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something like this is totally, totally uncharacteristic,''
Cunningham said. He said he thought it was possible that someone
stole the company truck from Nelson and abducted the girl. Nelson
might be hiding from police, Cunningham said, because he had been
in trouble with the law before.
</P>
<P>
   Larry McCormick, agent in charge of the FBI in Kansas City, said
authorities were seeking Nelson on a felony warrant from Butler,
Mo., for obstruction and assault on an officer.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Kniest, a Missouri Department of Corrections spokesman, said
Nelson went to prison for second-degree burglary on April 23, 1996,
and was paroled on Feb. 18, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Several people called police Tuesday night after hearing about
the abduction. A maintenance worker at Grain Valley Christian
Church reported seeing a truck matching the description parked in
the church parking lot between 6 p.m. and 8 p.m. He wrote down the
truck's license-plate number because he did not recognize the
vehicle, which appeared empty.
</P>
<P>
   A tracking dog and a team of divers searched a field and a pond
behind the church Wednesday but found nothing. An FBI agent brought
clothes from Pamela's room to help a dog lock onto her scent.
</P>
<P>
   The dog also tried to track the suspect from the truck, which
was dropped near 14th Street and Bales Avenue in Kansas City.
Police said it was the truck used in the abduction. Police planned
to tow the truck to an unspecified place for evidence processing.
</P>
<P>
   Police traced Nelson's whereabouts Tuesday night and found that
about 8:30 p.m. he was at his mother's house, about 10 blocks from
where the truck was found.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Nelson, who identified herself as Nelson's mother, called
The Star Wednesday evening and said she did not believe her son
abducted Pamela.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has never hurt nobody,'' Nancy Nelson, 43, said. ``I would
expect him to break into a place. But I would never expect him to
hurt anyone, especially a kid.'
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Nelson said she saw her son after the abduction. ``He was
right here last night and the truck was out in front,'' she said.
``I know he was here until about 10:30 or 11:30. I left then and
went to my brother's because I don't have an alarm clock.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Wednesday, people stopped at West's home to pick up
fliers. Many cars and businesses in the neighborhood had Pamela's
picture and her description plastered on them.
</P>
<P>
   Children at Fiske Elementary School, where Pamela is a
fifth-grader, made the family cards and a multicolored
construction-paper chain.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Yadrich, Pamela's teacher, said she had a picture of
pumpkins that Pamela recently colored for her on her desk Wednesday
morning. ``It was the first thing I saw,'' Yadrich said, wiping her
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   She and the school principal visited West and the family at
their two-story white frame house. Many television crews were
parked in a gravel lot next to the house in the mostly industrial
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Family members spent their time standing in front of the house,
wiping their eyes with tissues, smoking cigarettes and being
interviewed by reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just hoping and praying for the best,'' said Pamela's
father, Paul Butler of Kansas City, Kan. ``My main concern is that
she's still alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler and West were never married and do not live together now,
Butler said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve McBride, executive director of the local branch of the
National Center for Missing and Exploited Children, said more than
3,000 children were reported missing nationally every day. An
average of 150 a year nationally are classified as stranger
abductions, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
