<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARATON-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: BERNIE WILLIAMS A SYMBOL OF THE RIVALRY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 2nd and 3rd grafs for updating, rewriting)  (rk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It would have been entirely appropriate, if
completely out of character, for Bernie Williams to have taken a
moment before the first pitch of the latest Yankee-Red Sox hoedown
Wednesday night by doffing his cap and saluting Jimy Williams and
the entire Boston bench.
</P>
<P>
   Here's to you, your well-intentioned offer and your delusions of
luring an authentic Yankee center fielder to that charming little
dump you call home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have only the best things to say about the Red Sox
organization,'' Williams said before thanking it by winning Game 1
of the American League Championship Series, 4-3, with a 10th-inning
home run off Rod Beck. ``We had a very nice, productive
communication.''
</P>
<P>
   If ever there was one, this was a unilateral summation of what
had been a joint endeavor. Williams got $87.5 million. The Red Sox
wound up with a .240 hitter, Darren Lewis, in center field as
opposed to Wednesday night's hero.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was talking about a sit-down with Jimy Williams, the
Red Sox manager, in Atlanta last November, which preceded a $91
million offer to the free-agent center fielder when the Yankees, at
the time, were asking him to survive on $30 million less.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, after the Yankees experienced a bout of temporary
insanity and unsuccessfully pursued Albert Belle, they upped the
ante for their placid, homegrown star, who was practically pleading
with them to not make him go.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the rivalry and the fans, that would have been
something I would've had to deal with had I gone,'' Bernie Williams
said. ``But you start to think about playing for an organization,
how it works, and that makes it hard.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Williams knew the Yankees were truly the better fit,
the more fashionable locale. George Steinbrenner realized his
hard-line bluff was called. The Red Sox recognized they had lost to
the Yankees one more time.
</P>
<P>
   They have always been an American League afterthought, one
crucial little detail that too often gets overlooked when people
begin to rhapsodize Yankees-Red Sox as the best rivalry in sports.
The Los Angeles Lakers and the Boston Celtics in the 1980s, that
was a rivalry. The San Francisco 49ers and the Dallas Cowboys at
least took turns beating each other in important postseason games.
Muhammad Ali and Joe Frazier battered each other silly. When
Martina Navratilova and Chris Evert played in the final of a Grand
Slam, you didn't sleep easily after betting the mortgage on the
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Russians won a couple of Olympic basketball gold medals
by directly beating the United States. When the World Series
tabulation in the last 81 years is Yankees 24, Red Sox 0, what we
are talking about is less a definitive rivalry and more a case of
one invading army occupying the territory of another.
</P>
<P>
   Passions run deep, even if the results are one-sided.
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn about the Yankees and the Red Sox the first time you
come in here,'' Bernie Williams said. ``I remember one year, I
think it was '93, we opened here against Boston and Roger Clemens
was their starter. It was amazing to see the fans, the
electricity.''
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, Clemens is emotionally unplugged from New
England, having defected to the Yankees, by way of Toronto. He
believed he had to put his money on the Yankees to finally get him
a championship ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys in here, they expect to win,'' Clemens said.
</P>
<P>
   After all these years, after all their disappointments, it would
surely be sweeter for Red Sox fans if they could somehow win at the
expense of Clemens. John Valentin is the only player left from when
Clemens was in Boston, but he's a friend. That is another angle
that gets distorted in the rush to create the event of the decade
every other month. This is not personal. It's all about uniforms
and history.
</P>
<P>
   Their overall pitching is typically shallow. Their payroll isn't
as large. But it would be a wonderful boost to the propagandists if
the Red Sox could finally beat the Yankees, deprive Clemens of a
World Series, and the Yankees of the chance to stamp the century
with their 25th World Series title.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have much to lose, so the pressure's on them. If the
Red Sox can claw their way to Game 7, they would likely have Pedro
Martinez and the indisputable edge.
</P>
<P>
   They've had their feel-good years, the Red Sox have. Four World
Series since 1918. A couple of ACLS appearances in the late 1980s
when the Yankees were Cleveland, an All-Star lineup with a 10-cent
staff. But the World Series tally is what it is. The one-game
playoff in 1978 stands as a nine-inning synopsis of Boston's
endless pursuit of the Yankees, like the Road Runner cartoon.
</P>
<P>
   Now they finally meet in the postseason. It's time for the Red
Sox to stand up and win. The so-called best rivalry in sports can't
be a rout.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
