<SLUG> BC-RUN-BOXER-RUNNER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CROSS-TRAINING BOXER NOW TEAM'S TOP RUNNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DONALD EMMONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ Running long distances is necessary
training for boxing but not necessarily an enjoyable part of the
sport.
</P>
<P>
   However, Agustin Molina, a two-time defending area Golden Gloves
champion, always has enjoyed running as an aspect of training for
boxing.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Molina's fondness for running has led him to
running miles at a time as the No. 1 runner on the Grand Prairie
High School cross country team this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always liked running, and I've become more dedicated over
the years,'' Molina said.
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Prairie junior isn't the best distance runner in the
area. Nonetheless, the dual-sport competitor consistently has
crossed the finish line as the Gophers' top runner this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told that if I'm going to train (for boxing), I might as
well have fun, so I decided to run cross country,'' Molina said.
``It's kept my legs in shape, and they don't get weary when I'm
boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   Grand Prairie cross country coach Kelley Turley isn't surprised
about Molina running in the No. 1 spot this season. Considering he
was a key member of the Gophers' regional-qualifying team as a
freshman, she saw early on how the 119-pound Molina was light on
his feet and showed exceptional stamina.
</P>
<P>
   However, after missing nearly half the Gophers' meets last
season because of conflicts with his boxing schedule, Turley wasn't
sure Molina was committed to cross country other than using the
sport as a training tool for boxing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ran well as a freshman, but last year as a sophomore he was
kind of off because he missed several meets and that included the
district meet,'' Turley said. ``This year he's turned it on. He's
much more focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Molina, who fights in the 119-pound United States amateur boxing
open division, recently posted a top-10 finish in cross country at
the Country Day Invitational and a top-20 showing at the Martin
Invitational in Arlington. Molina admits he has increased his
intensity for cross country from last season.
</P>
<P>
   The change was a result of a simple conversation with his
father.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad told me if I'm going to compete in cross country I
might as well go all the way and not just half way,'' Molina said.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since then, Molina has approached cross country the same
way he approaches boxing. He runs every morning and has missed only
one meet this season because of boxing.
</P>
<P>
   No one has appreciated Molina's dedication to running this fall
more than Turley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of concerned about him, but it's been working out
well this year,'' Turley said. ``He is very focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Molina will lead the Gophers into the Lewisville Invitational
this weekend. The meet gives him an opportunity to run against
several of his District 5-5A opponents. The event also serves as a
gauge for the Gophers' top runner in terms of reaching his main
goal this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making regionals is my goal,'' Molina said. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 0059EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
