<HEADLINE>
YANKEES WIN ON WILLIAMS' 10TH-INNING HOME RUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shortstop Johnny Pesky held the ball in the 1946
World Series and first baseman Bill Buckner let the ball go through
his legs in the 1986 Series. Those are two plays that live in
infamy in Boston Red Sox baseball lore.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the club, Jason Varitek and Rod Beck.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox catcher and relief pitcher were part of the two
plays that Boston fans will long remember when they look back at
the New York Yankees' 4-3 victory in Game 1 of the American League
Championship Series at Yankee Stadium Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Beck gave up the big one, a leadoff home run to Bernie Williams
in the 10th inning. Williams also won Game 1 of the 1996 American
League Championship Series against the Baltimore Orioles with an
11th-inning home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bernie does big things for us,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre
said. ``He comes up so large, so often.''
</P>
<P>
   But Varitek's failure to hold a one-hop throw from right fielder
Trot Nixon on a play at the plate in the seventh was just as
crucial. This allowed the tying run to score in a game the Red Sox
led, 3-0, in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius had a two-run home run in the second off Red Sox
starter Kent Mercker and also had the leadoff single in the seventh
against reliever Derek Lowe that led to the crucial play at the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch bunted Brosius to second and Derek Jeter
followed with a line-drive single to right. Nixon charged the ball
hard and made a strong, accurate throw to the plate. But Varitek
couldn't control it as Brosius came barrelling in for a collision.
Instead, Varitek dropped it, allowing Brosius to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were lucky to score there,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good execution but bad results,'' Red Sox manager Jimy
Williams said. ``I couldn't tell about the hop, if it was a bad
hop. But the ball was there before the runner. If he holds onto the
ball ...''
</P>
<P>
   Brosius said, ``I didn't know if he was expecting me to hit him
or what. I had nowhere to go. My only chance to get to the plate
was to go over him.''
</P>
<P>
   There was much in this game that keep Red Sox fans talking well
into the next millennium. But the 10th inning was painful in two
ways.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Offerman led off the Red Sox's 10th with a single and John
Valentin followed with a double-play grounder to third. Knoblauch
dropped the ball on the exchange, but umpire Rick Reed ruled he was
taking it out of glove and Offerman was out. Replays showed
Knoblauch never had it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like that rule ... if it hits his glove, he's out,''
Williams said. ``But it didn't look like he had possession.''
</P>
<P>
   The inning died and Williams then invited second-guessing by
taking out left-hander Rheal Cormier and bringing in Beck, a
right-hander, to face the heart of the Yankees order. The Yankees
have been much tougher on right-handers this year and Williams
proved that by hitting Beck's second pitch for a home run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to have a good at-bat and hit the ball
hard,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox needed only three batters to score more runs against
the Yankees than the Rangers did in three games in the Division
Series. They jumped on Orlando Hernandez with two runs in the
first, a rally that started with Offerman's single to center.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin then hit a grounder to the left side, where Jeter made
a backhanded stop, then pirouetted in mid-air and threw to second.
It looked nice, but the throw to second was wild, allowing Offerman
to score and Valentin to reach third. Valentin scored on Brian
Daubach's single to right.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox made it 3-0 in the second when Darren Lewis led off
with a walk, stole second, went to third on Nixon's bloop single
into right-center and scored on Offerman's infield single.
</P>
<P>
   That left the Red Sox with runners at first and second, but
Hernandez came back, getting Valentin on a fly to right, Daubach on
a pop to third and Nomar Garciaparra on a fly to right.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez allowed seven of the first 10 batters he faced to
reach base before retiring 20 of the next 23. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
