<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASSIC RIVALRY PRODUCES CLASSIC POSTSEASON GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ We're told that if we ignore history, we are doomed
to repeat it. When it comes to the Yankees and Red Sox, that's a
good thing.
</P>
<P>
   History just keeps getting better and better when these two
teams come to dance.
</P>
<P>
   At the very stroke of midnight, Bernie Williams, leading off the
bottom of the 10th, waved his magic wand and sent a pitch from Rod
Beck over the center-field fence for a game-winning home run as the
Yankees clipped the Red Sox, 4-3, in a dramatic opening game of the
American League Championship Series on Wednesday night at Yankee
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It was Beck's second pitch of the game, a high fastball, and
Williams drove it high and deep into the New York night. The ball
cleared the fence just to the left of the 408-foot sign as Red Sox
center fielder Darren Lewis watched helplessly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't sure the ball was out until I looked at Darren,''
Yankees manager Joe Torre said. ``When he turned on it, I knew it
was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The surprise to me was that he hit the first pitch, home run,
bang, the game's over. The way the game was going, I thought it was
going to be one of those 14- or 15-inning games. I was talking to
(pitching coach) Mel (Stottlemyre) about who was going to pitch the
next inning.''
</P>
<P>
   It was, for Yankees fans at least, the perfect ending to the
perfect game, the beginning of the first-ever playoff series
between these two storied rivals.
</P>
<P>
   If they're all like Wednesday night's game, which was played
through sporadic rain showers over the final five innings, it might
go down as one of the most entertaining playoff series of all-time.
</P>
<P>
   Their pasts are as intertwined as an old Afghan comforter,
knitted together in a colorful tapestry of triumphs and tragedies,
from the Curse of the Bambino, to the dramatic Bucky Dent playoff
home run; from the controversial writers' vote that made the
popular Joe DiMaggio the 1941 MVP over the irascible Ted Williams,
to the heated and animosity-filled rivalry between Thurman Munson
and Carlton Fisk.
</P>
<P>
   This is no ordinary ALCS, and so we should have expected a
less-than-ordinary opening game Wednesday night at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The track record of events when these two teams clash is so well
established, we should never have been lulled into some pedestrian
notion that the defending world champion Yankees were an automatic
shoo-in the first game.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, that was the early story line in the New York tabloids
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   There the Yankees were, fresh and cheeky after their annual
sweep of the Rangers in the Divisional Series while the frazzled
Red Sox had to rally from two games down to win three straight
against dangerous Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, the Yankees were able to set their thoroughly rested
pitching rotation to manager Joe Torre's exact specifications,
while Jimy Williams, his Boston counterpart, was shrugging and
saying, ``We'll find somebody to pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   He did. Several somebodies.
</P>
<P>
   Williams started with left-hander Kent Mercker, beaten up by the
Indians and working on just two days' rest. He was opposed by the
Yankees' mesmerizing Cuban, Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez, who had
combined with two Yankees relievers to shut out the Rangers on a
two-hitter eight days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   What started as a mismatch became, instead, another chapter in
the legacy.
</P>
<P>
   It was like watching two fighters schooled by the same trainer,
mirror-images, each familiar with the other's style and moves.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra and Derek Jeter, the two All-Star shortstops
and the centerpieces of their respective teams, were almost
identical in their play, even down to out-of-character matching
wild throws to second base.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear from the beginning that this was not the same
Yankees team that so casually and confidently dismissed the Rangers
just last weekend. And those weren't the cowed and psyche-whipped
Rangers in the other dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, who had painted the corners like Rembrandt against
the Rangers, was more like your average sloppy house painter in the
first inning, and the Red Sox nicked him for two early runs, one of
them unearned thanks to Jeter's one-hop throw from deep short that
skipped into right field. Brian Daubach's single to right scored
another.
</P>
<P>
   In just one inning, in which the Yankees looked extremely
mortal, the Red Sox had doubled the Rangers' run production in
three futile games.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's speed produced another run in the second when Darren
Lewis walked, stole second and scored on back-to-back singles by
Trot Nixon and Jose Offerman.
</P>
<P>
   That's triple what the Rangers ... oh, never mind.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Yankees were still the Yankees. Bernie Williams?
Well, the Rangers know all about him, now don't they?
</P>
<P>
   What makes good history is a rivalry. It takes two for that
dance, and history tells us there's no better match than the
Yankees and the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   They proved it again Wednesday night. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
