<HEADLINE>
STARS HOLD TEAM MEETING AFTER SHUTOUT LOSS TO SHARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Stars held a welcome back party for Mike Modano and
Darryl Sydor on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody forgot to bring the goals.
</P>
<P>
   So, the Stars were left scrambling for one in the final 1:17.
They came up with five shots on goal, two close enough to be goals,
but no goals. The party ended with San Jose walking away from
Reunion Arena on Wednesday night with a 2-0 victory and the Stars
players having a 25-minute, closed-door meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been shut out twice in our first six games,'' Stars
defenseman Richard Matvichuk said, ``and we had to address it.''
</P>
<P>
   The players decided the problem was a simple failure to finish
the chances they had. Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said the problem
was the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I think that was about as uncommitted as I've seen our
group in a long time, especially in gritty, physical areas we
needed to have to win the hockey game,'' Hitchcock said. ``When
your best players are your most casual players, you're in
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars didn't exactly play a strong game, but they weren't
without their chances. They outshot the Sharks, 20-6, in the third
period.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of finish can be attributed to a little bit of
tentativeness and a lot of Sharks goalie Steve Shields. He stopped
all 35 Stars shots he faced, including two good chances by forwards
Jamie Langenbrunner and Joe Nieuwendyk with 2:45 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   There was also Blake Sloan, Derian Hatcher and Brett Hull and on
and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny,'' Modano said. ``The shot thing always comes into
play.'' Modano and Sydor returned after a 10-day, injury-induced
layoff, and both said aside from a few nerves they felt fine.
</P>
<P>
   Sydor suffered a hairline fracture to his left eye socket after
being punched repeatedly in the back of the head by Anaheim winger
Jim McKenzie on Oct. 2. Modano suffered a broken nose, ligament
damage in his neck and a mild concussion after crashing awkwardly
into the boards when Mighty Ducks defenseman Ruslan Salei pushed
him from behind in that game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew they wouldn't be up to speed so it was up to everybody
else to pick up the slack,'' Hitchcock said, ``and they didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks first goal came at 3:49 of first period when forward
Mike Ricci threaded a pass through Matvichuk to Niklas Sundstrom
for an easy, tap-in goal. Sundstrom had beaten Stars defenseman
Brad Lukowich. Sharks forward Jeff Friesen got an empty-net goal
with 24 seconds remaining in the game to seal the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``They score that one goal and we just deflated,'' Sydor said.
``That's not our team.''
</P>
<P>
   That was what the meeting was mainly about, not so much the
score or loss but the way they played. Stars forward Guy Carbonneau
said the 2-on-1 breaks, the lack of goals, the loss were only
symptoms of the problem. The team, he said, was slowly but surely
getting away from the defensive-style of game that won them a
Stanley Cup last season.
</P>
<P>
   The players reminded themselves of that fact in their meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always good to get things on the table before problems
occur,'' Carbonneau said. ``I think we're searching for our game
from last year.''
</P>
<P>
   And a few goals. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
