<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS TECH HOPES FOR BETTER BOUNCES
</HEADLINE>
 TECH-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Colorado coach Gary Barnett is taking a predictable approach to
Saturday's game at Texas Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched them play Texas A&AMP;M and was totally impressed,''
Barnett said, taking note of the Red Raiders' impressive 21-19
upset of then-No. 5 A&AMP;M. ``That's the team I'm going to prepare
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnett, as would Tech's players if they could, chose to dismiss
the Red Raiders' 41-21 loss at Oklahoma State. Not only was Tech
suddenly inept on offense, its defense was befuddled by a
never-before-seen OSU offensive scheme. The Red Raiders' special
teams were victimized by Terance Richardson's punt returns (5 for
90 yards). But the defensive failings were the most notable. After
allowing only five offensive touchdowns in four games, Tech's
defense was stunned by the Cowboys' four touchdown drives _ in the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes a Colorado attack ranked 10th nationally (455.6 yards
per game), directed by quarterback Mike Moschetti, who is third in
the Big 12 and 12th nationally in individual total offense (287.6
yards) and who in Marcus Stiggers has one of the nation's top
big-play receivers.
</P>
<P>
   The Buffaloes (3-2, 2-0 Big 12) are coming off a 46-39 overtime
victory at Missouri; Tech off what coach Spike Dykes said was his
team's worst defensive performance this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really,'' Dykes protested, ``we've played pretty doggoned good
defense this year. We've just given up a few big plays. Those are
the things that have killed our defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Not giving up big plays has been a hallmark of Tech defenses
throughout the 1990s. Big plays, however, were instrumental in
losses at Arizona State and to the University of North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus has always been to stop the run and not give up big
plays,'' defensive coordinator John Goodner said. ``This year, we
haven't done a very good job (of the latter).''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Raiders traditionally have also ranked high nationally
in turnover margin. This year, however, Tech is minus-6 in turnover
ratio, last in the Big 12 and 104th nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Against A&AMP;M, things bounced our way. Against Oklahoma State,
they didn't,'' said senior defensive end Taurus Rucker, who has
been Tech's steadiest defender this season. ``Some things just
haven't gone our way this season.''
</P>
<P>
   Typical of the wrong bounces, Rucker pointed out, was the play
on which two Tech defenders tipped an OSU pass that Cowboys
fullback Kevin Brown eventually caught for a 4-yard touchdown and a
21-0 lead early in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've dropped a lot of balls this year,'' said sophomore Kevin
Curtis, one of those players who had a shot at the pass Brown
caught. ``Sometimes getting things to bounce your way takes a lot
of luck. But we just haven't been able to create a lot of turnovers
this year and from now on, when we get our hands on a ball we've
got to grasp it.''
</P>
<P>
   OSU used a variety of offensive schemes _ running reverses, fake
reverses, using a no-huddle offense and sending five receivers out
of the shotgun offense _ to neutralize Tech's famed pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give Oklahoma State credit,'' Goodner said. ``They ran some
stuff we were not prepared for. We got back on our heels and never
recovered.''
</P>
<P>
   Rucker said, however, the Red Raiders defense will be
rejuvenated Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows the Swarm defense has been one of the best in
the country the last four or five years,'' Rucker said. ``Against
A&AMP;M, our defense was about the best you'll see. Last week, we
didn't play the way we're capable of playing. But we'll adjust.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're tied (in the loss column) with four other teams in the
Big 12 South and we know those teams aren't going to quit. We're
not either.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
