<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL SUPERINTENDENT CLAIMS CONTROL DESPITE NEW CEO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
Staff Writers Rick Orlov and David R. Baker contributed to this
story 
BY GREG GITTRICH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Los Angeles schools Superintendent Ruben Zacarias
met face-to-face Wednesday with the district's new chief executive
officer, a lawyer who a day earlier assumed the bulk of the career
educator's responsibilities with approval from the school board.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a board resolution placing new CEO Howard Miller in
charge of all the district's administrative and academic
departments, Zacarias defiantly argued he is still in charge of not
only the district but also his newest administrator.
</P>
<P>
   While Mayor Richard Riordan praised the organizational shake-up,
one of Zacarias' strongest supporters on the school board said the
board president should step down for pushing the move through.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is only one superintendent in charge of this district,
and you are looking at him,'' Zacarias said, emerging from his
half-hour discussion with Miller at district headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I absolutely want to work this all out,'' Zacarias said later
in the day. ``I can always use an extra pair of hands. Mr. Miller
does report to me. He takes direction from me.''
</P>
<P>
   Zacarias said he believed he and Miller could have a positive
relationship and argued they would have to clarify Miller's role.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who will serve in the new post through June 2000,
acknowledged that the superintendent can veto any of his decisions.
But he said there is nothing to clarify when it comes to the
district's new chain of command.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt that I do report to the superintendent,''
Miller said. ``But the board resolution is clear on the reporting
relationship between all the departments. As chief executive
officer, I will be involved in every aspect of the district's work
and manage all the departments.''
</P>
<P>
   Riordan said the school board, which he helped elect, did not
inform him of the move to appoint Miller in advance. He agreed with
the board, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a key move that will benefit the children of Los
Angeles,'' he said. ``This action will liberate Ruben Zacarias to
focus on a vision of creating an education system so every child in
the city has the tools to compete in a global society.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the hallways of the Los Angeles Unified School
District's downtown headquarters, the surprise installation of
Miller was perceived by many as an administrative coup. The move
has temporarily flung the administrative offices into chaos and
apparently isolated board member Victoria Castro, an ardent
supporter of the superintendent, from the rest of the Board of
Education.
</P>
<P>
   Castro urged board President Genethia Hayes to step down as the
leader of the seven-member panel. She said the board president, who
took office in July, has repeatedly skirted the intent of state
laws in place to ensure that the public is properly notified of the
board's agenda for closed and open meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it is appropriate for her to step down to assure the
public that all Brown Act (the open public meetings act)
requirements will be complied with,'' Castro said. ``With only
three months on the job, the intricacies of these rules are easy to
misinterpret and fumble, and this was a major fumble.''
</P>
<P>
   Castro pointed out the board president repeatedly changed the
posted agenda for Tuesday's closed meeting during which Miller was
appointed.
</P>
<P>
   A review by the Daily News confirmed the agenda had been altered
at least four times. The final version, which was scrawled in
freehand, not typed, was distributed to board members as they
entered the meeting, Castro said.
</P>
<P>
   State law requires a final, clearly defined agenda to be posted
at least 24 hours in advance.
</P>
<P>
   The board approved the motion by a 4-2 vote behind closed doors.
Hayes, Caprice Young, Mike Lansing and Valerie Fields voted in
favor of hiring Miller. Castro and David Tokofsky dissented. Julie
Korenstein abstained. There was no public discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Castro, who served as board president last year, said she would
not take steps to remove Hayes if she refused to abdicate her post.
</P>
<P>
   While Hayes did not respond to repeated requests for comment, it
appeared unlikely Castro would see the appointment of a new board
president any time soon. Every other board member told the Daily
News they would not support a call for Hayes to step down as
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ms. Hayes has a lot of energy and a purpose that can be good
for the system,'' Tokofsky said. ``I don't think this was handled
as precisely as it could have been handled. But Ms. Castro's
request is not going to find me supporting it.''
</P>
<P>
   Other school board members praised Hayes' tough management style
and vowed to back her.
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: vowed to back her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Genethia is a strong president, and she's got my vote,'' said
Caprice Young, who was elected with Hayes this spring.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Tom Hayden, D-Los Angeles, a frequent critic of the
district, called Miller's appointment a clear move to undercut
Zacarias. If a majority of board members wants to get rid of the
superintendent, he said, they should simply do so and not take such
``humiliating'' partial steps.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a meeting of the Valley Industry and Commerce
Association, Hayden argued that Miller's appointment was another
attempt to fix a broken system by adding more bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crisis management and crisis management only,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The idea to appoint Miller to the powerful post was brought to
the board by LAUSD legal consultant Barry Groveman. Groveman, who
is running for district attorney, has been instrumental during the
last year in efforts to expose toxic problems at the Belmont
Learning Center and combat incompetence in the school district.
</P>
<P>
   Miller has been given until Oct. 22 to assemble a crisis
management team and bring recommendations to the board on the
appropriate discipline for administrators who allowed Belmont to be
built atop an oil field without adequate environmental review.
</P>
<P>
   Miller and Groveman said they met only two weeks ago when Miller
joined the district as the head of facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Scott Wildman, D-Glendale, perhaps the most vocal
critic of the school district throughout the Belmont debacle, met
Miller's appointment with optimism and caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many ways, I'm pleased Mr. Miller will be in charge of
reorganizing the district,'' Wildman said. ``I'm confused about the
scope of Mr. Miller's responsibilities, as many people are. But my
understanding is Ruben Zacarias is still in charge as
superintendent. It's now up to him to rise to the occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
