<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6403 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-BIG12REPORT-TEX     10-14 1514
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BIG </SLUG>
 12 REPORT-TEX 
ATTENTION! LiSTEN TO THIS AND WIN 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seven weeks down, seven weeks remaining in the Big 12 football
season.
</P>
<P>
   This seems an ideal time to take stock of where we've been and
determine the levels of inspiration and perspiration needed by
contenders to reach the league title game, Dec. 4 in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   To assist in our efforts, we've expanded a concept originated by
Colorado coach Gary Barnett. To inspire his players before the
Kansas game, Barnett dressed in camouflage gear and showed excerpts
from the movie Patton, with Kansas-specific references dubbed into
George C. Scott's famous monologue.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado won, 51-17.
</P>
<P>
   So, we're one-upping Barnett. With help from buddies with
psychic connections (verified through infommericals on late-night
TV), we've summoned the spirit of the real Gen. George S. Patton to
provide a surprise, midseason inspection of Big 12 football teams.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Patton, the troops are assembled, in descending order of
conference record, for your inspection. What follows are Patton's
words of inspiration (expletives deleted, of course):
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska (6-0, 3-0): Ground troops ... solid! Defense systems
... superior! Air-strike capabilities ... dubious! Keep working on
that, men. I've seen progress. But not enough to subdue the
ultimate foe.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State (5-0, 3-0): Fifteen takeaways, seven giveaways. I
like that, men! Make the enemy bow to your will. But don't get
cocky, Bill Snyder. And wipe those cupcake crumbs off your lips!
</P>
<P>
   Colorado (3-2, 2-0): Get tough, huh? That was your plan, wasn't
it, Barnett? Then why are you still passing for twice as many yards
(308.8) every week as you get by pounding it on the ground (146.8)?
Enough of this mamby-pamby stuff! More trench warfare, soldier! Or
do I need to get you a sweater vest to match Rick Neuheisel's?
</P>
<P>
   Texas (5-2, 2-1): I believe the game is called FOOT-ball, isn't
it, Mack Brown? Then why, in tarnation, can't your guys kick it
past the line of scrimmage with regularity? Seven blocked kicks!
Those are self-inflicted wounds, soldier! You'll never win a war
that way.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M (4-1, 1-1): Great marching band, men. I love their
choice of tunes. But enough about that. I see your offense is off
the MIA list. That's good. But dadgummit, R.C. Slocum, you can't
keep misplacing that thing! Wars have been lost on lesser tactical
errors.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma (3-2, 1-1): I can't lie to you, men. You entertain me
greatly. But where in the world have you stashed the ground troops,
Bob Stoops? You can't force a surrender by just lofting grenades
all day.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State (3-2, 1-1): Soldiers, you've fought the good
fight without your triggerman. You control your destiny. You can
win the South Division if quarterback Tony Lindsay comes back Oct.
23 with a healthy knee. Personally, I think you'll need more than
that to get the job done. But if he inspires you to greater things,
good luck and Godspeed.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Tech (2-3, 1-1): For heaven's sake, Spike Dykes, you're
running a football team, not a charity ward! Look at this: 13
giveaways, seven takeaways. Worst turnover ratio in the conference!
Men, you'd better clean this up before your coach gets
court-martialed.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State (3-2, 0-2): Men, I admire your spunk. You've got no
air support, so just keep smashing them with those tanks! Focus on
that Davis model. It seems to work best.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri (3-2, 0-2): Good grief, men, your net punting average
ranks below Texas (27.3 yards, 112th in Division I-A). Only two
teams in America are worse! Unless we start seeing something
special from those special teams, this could be a loooooooong
season.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas (2-4, 0-2): Remember this, soldiers. When the going gets
tough ... the tough play basketball! Now, quit wasting time and
report to Roy Williams with your best jump shots. On the double!
</P>
<P>
   Baylor (1-5, 0-3): This message is for your coach, men. As a
general, I learned long ago that when the enemy raises the
surrender flag, you stop shooting and accept his offer. There's a
lesson in there for you, Kevin Steele.
</P>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA, IOWA STATE DREAM OF BOWL BERTHS
</P>
<P>
   At the halfway mark of the season, nine of 12 league schools are
on pace to qualify for bowl berths. That number will dwindle in the
coming weeks as losses mount for also-rans during conference play.
</P>
<P>
   But it is appears likely that the Big 12, for a second
consecutive year, will produce more bowl-eligible teams than its
guaranteed allotment of six postseason berths. For that, league
administrators can thank a first-year NCAA rule that could propel
Oklahoma and Iowa State into the bowl mix with 6-5 records that
would not have been acceptable in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Sooners (3-2) and Cyclones (3-2) opened their respective
seasons with victories over Indiana State, a Division I-AA school.
In past years, triumphs over I-AA opponents did not count toward
bowl eligibility. This year, a new NCAA statute allows teams to
count one victory within a four-year span over a I-AA foe as part
of a school's six-victory minimum to accept a bowl bid.
</P>
<P>
   Big 12 officials confirmed yesterday that the Sooners and
Cyclones need to finish only 6-5 to qualify for postseason
consideration. Under similar circumstances last season, the minimum
would have been 7-4.
</P>
<P>
   The key for the Sooners, said first-year coach Bob Stoops, is
maximizing opportunities for victories during a rebuilding season.
Oklahoma last posted a winning record in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't waste any opportunities and get to a bowl game,''
Stoops said. ``And I don't believe we have, to this point. We're
getting better and more familiar with what we're doing each week.
If we get some things polished in this off week, we can finish
strong in the second half of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   IQ TEST
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State will play the Big 12's final nonconference game of
the regular season Saturday against Utah State. The contest is
sandwiched between matchups against archrival Kansas (a 50-9
victory) and an Oct. 23 game at Oklahoma State. Snyder said the
timing of the game ``is a concern'' for him in motivating his
ninth-ranked Wildcats, but he's found a remedy: videotape
highlights of the Aggies' 34-31 overtime loss to No. 21 Brigham
Young as well as the team's 400-yard offensive performance in a
season-opening, 38-7 loss to No. 14 Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's still a concern after they watch those tapes, then I'm
concerned about the IQ level of people on our team,'' Snyder said.
``Utah State is one of those teams that seems to play up, or down,
to the level of their competition.''
</P>
<P>
   NO SECOND THOUGHTS
</P>
<P>
   Because of his baseball background, Texas A&AMP;M quarterback Mark
Farris found it difficult to bypass Monday's telecast of the
deciding game in the Boston-Cleveland playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   Farris, a 24-year-old freshman, spent five seasons in the
Pittsburgh Pirates' minor-league system before enrolling at A&AMP;M in
January. As he watched Monday, Farris said he felt no desire to be
part of the action. His feelings were much different while watching
college football telecasts during September road trips as a
minor-leaguer.
</P>
<P>
   ``That reinforced to me that I don't miss baseball,'' said
Farris, who shares the backup role with fellow freshman Vance
Smith, a Fort Worth Christian graduate. ``I didn't really watch
during the regular season and I didn't get excited (Monday) about a
big playoff game. But I really, really missed football when I was
playing baseball. I'm done second-guessing myself. I know I'm where
I need to be.''
</P>
<P>
   AFTER THE UPSET
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum said he was not surprised to see
Texas Tech fall to Oklahoma State, 41-21, the week after the Red
Raiders upset the Aggies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like that's their pattern every year,'' Slocum said.
``They put everything into our game and they've had difficulties in
games the next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Statistics support Slocum's conclusion. In 13 seasons under
coach Spike Dykes, Tech has a 6-7 mark against A&AMP;M. But the Red
Raiders are 3-10 in games the next week, including 1-5 after
victories over the Aggies.
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, the Red Raiders prosper after games against Texas in
the Dykes era. Dykes is 6-6 against the Longhorns and 10-2 in games
the next week, including a 5-1 mark following Tech victories.
</P>
<P>
   Dykes discounts any significance to the statistics, saying his
team's up-and-down efforts are ``the part of the game that makes it
mind-boggling.''
</P>
<P>
   PICK A VENUE
</P>
<P>
   Big 12 officials said yesterday that a decision on the site of
the league's football championship game in 2000 will not be reached
until Oct. 20, at the earliest. That is the next scheduled meeting
of the league's chief executive officers. Cities bidding to host
the game include Kansas City, Dallas, St. Louis and San Antonio.
During the league's spring meetings, Big 12 officials agreed to
consider open-air stadiums as potential venues rather than
continuing the game's four-year rotation between the TWA Dome in
St. Louis and the Alamodome in San Antonio. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
