<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6408 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     10-14 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRAN BLINEBURY  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
SEATTLE _ Nurse, where am I?
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pass the smelling salts.
</P>
<P>
   This sounds crazy, but I think I just saw the Rockets run.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was a dream. I might be having flashbacks from watching
too much ESPN Classic in the aftermath of Wilt's passing.
</P>
<P>
   It could even have been from all the garlic that was on my
chicken dinner.
</P>
<P>
   But I thought I saw ...
</P>
<P>
   I swear I saw ...
</P>
<P>
   Hakeem Olajuwon wrapping his mitts around a defensive rebound
and very quickly turning to fire an outlet pass to a racing Walt
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   I thought I saw ...
</P>
<P>
   I swear I saw ...
</P>
<P>
   The live-wire rookie Steve Francis pushing the ball up the
court, weaving through traffic and sending a laser-beam pass to an
elevating Shandon Anderson along the baseline.
</P>
<P>
   I thought I saw ...
</P>
<P>
   I swear I saw ...
</P>
<P>
   Even Charles Barkley hustling from end to end, keeping up with
the suddenly fast-moving basketball in the new-look, fuel-injected
offense.
</P>
<P>
   I know it was only the first exhibition game of a very long
season, but it was as welcome a sight as the first halter top of
spring.
</P>
<P>
   If the Rockets can keep this up, then there is hope that someday
a plowhorse might throw off his yoke and win the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every team I ever played on or coached, from high school to
college to the NBA to any playground out there anywhere, every
single player always said that he wanted to run,'' said head coach
Rudy Tomjanovich. ``That includes our old `water buffalo' team with
Billy Paultz. But you know what they say about talk being cheap.
The thing is, you have to make the commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Another thing is, you've got to have the horses and the legs.
</P>
<P>
   While it is far too early and way too wildly premature to
project the Rockets into the forefront of the race for the Western
Conference title after a 101-88 loss to the SuperSonics, at the
very least you can say they have the talent and the speed and at
least an inclination to not make you nod off to sleep in your
high-priced seat.
</P>
<P>
   It's like catching Queen Elizabeth smoking a cigar. Or spotting
Calista Flockhart with a full plate at an all-you-can-eat buffet.
</P>
<P>
   If it weren't for the striped clown suits, you almost wouldn't
recognize them. Come to think of it, you might still need a program
just to match up all of the new faces with the new names.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I've been reborn in a way,'' Olajuwon said. ``I
cannot believe that I left the team that lost in the first round of
the playoffs in May and came back to this.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's deep. It's exciting. It's a team that I think is going to
surprise a lot of the old Rocket fans, because it has a lot of
potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Mainly for three reasons:
</P>
<P>
   No poutin' Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   An upbeat style that feels as if much of the game is being
played with somebody's finger pressed on the fast-forward button.
</P>
<P>
   And Francis.
</P>
<P>
   He is the equivalent of a live wire sparking and jumping in the
middle of a crowded street, both breathtaking and dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   There is Francis taking the whip to the offense, getting the
ball over the midcourt line in a heartbeat, feeding the ball into
Olajuwon and getting a fast return pass to bury a 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   There is Francis backpedaling at full speed to guard Seattle
All-Star Gary Payton on a fast break and then leaping as if off a
springboard to make a spectacular fingertip block on what appeared
to be a sure layup.
</P>
<P>
   Payton was shocked. Francis was jubilant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got that ...! I got that ...!'' Francis shrieked with glee.
And that sent Cuttino Mobley and others on the Rockets bench into
convulsions of laughter.
</P>
<P>
   There is Francis receiving a sideline inbounds pass from fellow
rookie Kenny Thomas, darting around defenders like a skier through
an obstacle course and throwing down a two-handed slam dunk and
chinning himself on the rim to draw a technical foul.
</P>
<P>
   No, that is not your father's Oldsmobile. And these are not the
Rockets that you have so often wanted to light a fuse under in
recent seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that most people don't want to believe it, because
they've watched me dribble down in the box so much lately,'' said
Barkley. ``But this is gonna be easier for me and for Hakeem. And
it's gonna be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Believe it or not, more than six minutes had passed in the game
before the first post-up play to Barkley was called, and there was
not a steady diet.
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of sprinting and hustling and trying to beat
the defense down the floor in the transition game.
</P>
<P>
   There was Anderson finishing on the break, showing why the
Rockets courted him for so long.
</P>
<P>
   There was Williams going inside, going outside, doing a little
of this and a little of that.
</P>
<P>
   There was Kelvin Cato, perhaps an underappreciated part of the
Scottie Pippen deal, with a monster seven blocked shots in 22
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   There was Carlos Rogers hitting turnarounds on the baseline and
pursuing hard on defense, showing why a 6-11 jumping jack who now
with his fourth NBA team in six seasons has been one of the
surprises of camp.
</P>
<P>
   When Brent Barry tried to go inside in the second quarter,
Rogers swooped in like a hungry hawk and plucked the shot from
midair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, Brent!'' yelled Barkley, from a seat along the baseline.
``Haven't you ever heard of Carlos Rogers? He's a household name
... in his own house.''
</P>
<P>
   It was fast. It was open. It was entertaining. It was a start.
The Rockets were running.
</P>
<P>
   Nurse, am I dreaming?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
