<HEADLINE>
NEW TCU WOMEN'S BASKETBALL COACH KEEPING A HECTIC PACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DARRIN SCHEID 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Picture a guy running full-speed up an
escalator that's headed down almost as fast.
</P>
<P>
   This was Jeff Mittie in his first month as the new TCU women's
basketball coach. No matter how fast Mittie settled into a new
town, new university and new job, there were a thousand more steps
getting ready for the Frogs' season, which opens with their first
practice on Saturday. That explains why Mittie, who was hired Aug.
19, has yet to hang a picture in his office at Daniel-Meyer
Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   An empty desk and bare walls, he said, will have to stay that
way for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plaques and pictures are still in my vehicle,'' Mittie
said. ``That's the least of my concerns, a nicely decorated office.
We found out right away that there aren't enough hours in a day.
Maybe I'll look back in April or May and take a deep breath.''
</P>
<P>
   Mittie and TCU jumped on the escalator a little late this
season, thanks to the vacancy created when former coach Mike
Petersen resigned in August to take a job as an assistant men's
coach at Minnesota. Petersen guided the Frogs to a school-record 16victories last season.
</P>
<P>
   TCU quickly moved to hire Mittie, 33, the head coach at Arkansas
State the past four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first met him, I'm sure we had our defenses up,'' TCU
junior guard Jill Sutton said. ``He made a good impression. He made
us feel comfortable. That helped make this transition a lot
easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Mittie said the basketball stuff _ recruiting and preseason
conditioning drills _ has been easy compared with all the normal
headaches associated with moving, and quickly hiring a staff and
helping them adjust to a new job. He hired a staff that includes
Larry Tidwell, a former Baylor assistant coach, and Lonnette Hall,
one of his assistants at Arkansas State.
</P>
<P>
   He met with current players and told them not to worry about
wholesale changes or losing their scholarship after this year. The
biggest change, he told them, would be more freedom on offense. He
wants to run an offense that uses the 3-point shot more and a
defense that presses. In Mittie's four years at ASU, the Indians
were among the nation's leaders in 3-pointers made per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unknown is scary,'' Mittie said. ``What I did was reassure
them that the reasons I came to TCU were the same reasons they came
to TCU. We would try to build on what has already been in place and
help them reach their goals. That will not change.''
</P>
<P>
   Mittie and Tidwell, the recruiting coordinator, then compiled a
list of possible recruits. Some of the athletes on Mittie's list
from Arkansas State were carried over to his new list at TCU. Some
local talent was added because of Tidwell's knowledge of the Fort
Worth-Dallas area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is full of adjustments, and these kids have adjusted
well,'' Tidwell said. ``It's a very unique and special group. They
have made this a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the getting-acquainted period, Mittie was trying to
get his wife and three children settled in Fort Worth. They sold
their house in Jonesboro, Ark., in six days and closed on a house
in Fort Worth on Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Mittie says he will always remember that day because he closed
on the house at 9 a.m., the moving truck arrived at 9:30 a.m., and
he was on a plane to Houston by 2 p.m. to visit with a potential
recruit. In addition to days like that, there was the four-hour
orientation that all TCU employees have to attend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't stop thinking about what I needed to be doing while
they were going over things like fire safety,'' Mittie said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two weeks, Mittie said things have started to fall
into place, and TCU feels like his team.
</P>
<P>
   Players have learned the preseason drills and followed the
off-season workout programs. Frogs senior forward Diamond Jackson
said TCU is ready for practice to start on Saturday. The first
exhibition game is scheduled Nov. 10. The season opener is
scheduled Nov. 15 in the Preseason Women's National Invitation
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was barely a bump in the road,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing still unfinished is Mittie's bare office. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
