<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-WAC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOWDOWN BUILDUP BEGINS FOR TCU, RICE
</HEADLINE>
 INSIDERS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WHIT CANNING 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is belaboring a point, of course, to suggest that nothing
seems to last very long in the Western Athletic Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, it is a rule of thumb that if you intend to inflict
praise, do it fast.
</P>
<P>
   So, we wish to present a quick reminder that TCU and Rice were
the kings of WAC World last week. Alas, each must play again
Saturday, and both could end up living out the life saga of your
average fruit fly. After all, these are two teams with a combined
5-6 record.
</P>
<P>
   But since an 18-13 loss to Texas, the Owls have won three in a
row and stand 2-0 in WAC play. Last week they made the Killer Road
Trip to Hawaii and convincingly whipped what had become the WAC's
surprise team.
</P>
<P>
   Reverting to form after some early-season turnover problems,
Rice ran 66 times for 354 yards (adding 28 yards in the air), held
the ball for more than 38 minutes, and smothered the Rainbow
Warriors and their four-game winning streak, 38-19.
</P>
<P>
   TCU, meanwhile, is coming off its biggest blowout victory in
years, a 42-0 wipeout of the league's ``other'' surprise team, San
Jose State. The Spartans had won three in a row and were averaging
34 points a game, but they were overwhelmed by TCU's defense and
gave up 300 rushing yards to LaDainian Tomlinson, who incidentally
is the WAC offensive player of the week and the nation's leading
rusher (176.4 yards a game).
</P>
<P>
   In the WAC, it is normally risky to look beyond the next down
marker, but it is reasonable to assume that the Horned Frogs and
Owls can dispose of this weekend's obstacles and create an
interesting collision in Houston on Oct. 23.
</P>
<P>
   Rice's guest this week is San Jose State, reeling from a
shattering loss and forced to make a second consecutive long road
trip to Texas. The Spartans allowed the Frogs 418 yards on the
ground and the Owls are, let's see _ the 11th best rushing team in
the country (TCU is 15th).
</P>
<P>
   TCU will entertain Tulsa (1-4), which has at least had an off
week for extra preparation. But the Golden Hurricane is not only
staggering, it is bandaged from head to foot in keeping with a
recent tradition of suffering several key injuries at once.
</P>
<P>
   TCU coach Dennis Franchione is making no promises about Tulsa,
but he is hardly surprised at the Owls' resurgence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said from the beginning they have a good shot at winning
it all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aw, after what they did to San Jose, that'll just get those
guys fighting mad for us,'' Rice coach Ken Hatfield said. ``I'm
just glad we got out of Hawaii.'' AROUND THE LEAGUE
</P>
<P>
   _ Banished to the far side of the island because their hotel
rooms were eaten up by a convention of 30,000 dentists, the Owls _
who arrived on Tuesday _ used the episode to their advantage.
Fearing spies after 300 people showed up at their first practice,
they worked out in privacy the rest of the week on the abandoned
10th hole of a remote golf course. Finally starting to jell, the
Owls have rushed for 663 yards in the past two games.
</P>
<P>
   _ In TCU's victory against San Jose State, defensive end Aaron
Schobel had 10 tackles, including a sack and a rushing loss, broke
up two passes, and caused a fumble.
</P>
<P>
   _ Not only is Tomlinson the nation's top rusher but Fresno
State's Billy Volek is fourth in passing efficiency (151.9), and
Hawaii's Dan Robinson is sixth in total offense (315.3 yards a
game). Hawaii's Dwight Carter is fifth in receiving yards (117.2)
and San Jose State's Deonce Whitaker is fifth in scoring (12.4).
Whitaker (180) and Tomlinson (179) are sixth and seventh in
all-purpose yards per game. TCU's Reggie Hunt (33.9 yards per
return) and Cedric James (28.2) are the WAC's top two kickoff
returners, with Hunt ranking sixth nationally and James 17th. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
