<HEADLINE>
TONY AYALA LIKELY TO FACE TAYLOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CALVIN WATKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The comeback of boxer Tony Ayala Jr. apparently will move up to
the next level.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala, who is 2-0 in a comeback that started this summer after
he served 16 years in a New Jersey prison for aggravated sexual
assault, is expected to face former two-time world champion
Meldrick Taylor on Dec. 11, promoter Lester Bedford said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not prepared for an announcement yet,'' Bedford said.
``I think we can make it official in the next four or five days.
Right now, we're working on contracts, and it looks good we will
fight Meldrick Taylor.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed junior middleweight bout between Ayala and Taylor
would take place in San Antonio, Ayala's hometown, and be televised
on pay-per-view.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good fight for Tony,'' said Ayala's father, Tony
Ayala Sr. ``He's improved a lot in this comeback. I'm following the
pattern of George Foreman. What we want to do is stick with
defense, because Tony is thick up the middle, to move along.''
</P>
<P>
   In Ayala's last fight, Sept. 25, he knocked out Robert Koon in
the fourth round in Corpus Christi. Ayala hurt his hand in the
victory, butAyala Sr. said his son will be healthy for the December
fight.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, 32, is well past his prime. He is known for winning a
gold medal in the 1984 Summer Olympics and for his disputed loss to
Julio Cesar Chavez in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala Sr. said he thinks his son, one of the top boxing
prospects in the country before his legal problems, is still
championship caliber.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy is only 36 years old, and I really feel we can fight
for a title in a year,'' Ayala Sr. said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, if we lose badly in this fight, I might tell him to hang
them up,'' Ayala Sr. said. ``But I expect him to win. If we lose in
a close decision and that sort of thing, we can go on. In 22
fights, Tony has never been beaten up,
</P>
<P>
   and after prison he came back and beat two guys.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
