<SLUG> BC-CAR-WORLD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD EXPANDING FOR OUTLAWS SEVEN MONTHS AFTER BRAINSTORM
</HEADLINE>
 OF OUTLAWS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEN HAYWARD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Saturday morning after the Pennzoil World of Outlaws played
to a packed grandstand at the Las Vegas Motor Speedway, new track
general manager Chris Powell had a visit from Lowe's Motor Speedway
president Humpy Wheeler.
</P>
<P>
   Powell said he could almost see Wheeler thinking. And when
Wheeler conceives of new promotions, things start happening _
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that when Humpy came to Las Vegas in March that
he came out thinking about the World of Outlaws,'' Powell said.
``But Saturday morning when he walked into my office, he just shook
his head and said that is a great event.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, Wheeler was on the phone with Pennzoil World
of Outlaws president and founder Ted Johnson, talking about
building dirt tracks at Speedway Motorsports, Inc. venues. A little
more than seven months later, plans are in place for the Outlaws to
have a 2000 schedule filled with new events at SMI tracks. Dirt
tracks are under construction at Lowe's Motor Speedway and Texas
Motor Speedway in Fort Worth, Texas, with plans underway to put
dirt on the high banks at Bristol Motor Speedway. LMS and TMS will
each play host to two World of Outlaws events next season.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 20 years, the nomadic Sprint Car series has been
packing grandstands from New York to California. At last, the
larger motorsports community is finding out about the Sprint Car
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something is happening out there with the racing public, and
they seem to want to go back a little bit. This is almost retro
racing,'' Wheeler said. ``This was the kind of racing that was
popular in the '40s and '50s.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditional Outlaws venues such as Devil's Bowl Speedway in
Mesquite, Texas, and Knoxville Raceway in Iowa will continue to
have events, but the Outlaws' hectic schedule could change next
season. Johnson said there will be fewer midweek events, and more
events will be on television. Much like it did for Winston Cup
racing in the 1980s, television is helping propel a grassroots
organization into the limelight.
</P>
<P>
   The Nashville Network owns a portion of the Outlaws and had 12
live telecasts this season. But next season, many more events will
be televised, including most of the events at SMI tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only venues that were making money in Las Vegas was the
Winston Cup race and our race,'' Johnson said. ``And one thing
about Bruton Smith is that if you are making money, he likes you.
He bought that track and opened up all these other venues.''
</P>
<P>
   But where does this leave the smaller facilities that have
supported the series since its inception?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is going to be a better deal for the World of
Outlaws,'' said Devil's Bowl owner Lanny Edwards, who promoted the
first Outlaws race in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler said he sees some similarities between the Outlaws and
Winston Cup. He said he remembers the days when Winston Cup venues
were far different from the speed palaces of today.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the mid to late '70s there were plenty of places to run,
but the tracks were pretty run down,'' Wheeler said. ``Winston Cup
racing started growing when the facilities started to improve. Dirt
tracks by nature are dirty, but what Ted Johnson is trying to do is
put them in a first-class facility and have no dust.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have the right place and right event, it could be of a
major caliber.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 0146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
