r s BC-CAR-100GREATEST-TEX     10-14 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-100 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAYTONA, TV AUDIENCE TREATED TO GREAT RACE, `THE FIGHT'
</HEADLINE>
 GREATEST-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
EDITORS: This is No. 79 in a series looking at the 100 most
memorable moments in the century of sports. 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As hard as it may seem in these days of ``RPM 2Night'' and
NASCAR videos for all occasions, there was a time when not every
Winston Cup race was shown live on network TV.
</P>
<P>
   CBS executives took a huge gamble when they decided to carry the
season-opening Daytona 500 live in February 1979. The telecast
introduced the terms ``The Great American Race'' and ``flag-to-flag
coverage'' to the motorsports lexicon _ and gave a curious and
mostly snowbound nation an extended inside look at what was still a
Southern sport.
</P>
<P>
   The race produced the sixth of Richard Petty's seven Daytona 500
victories, a fast fact that became a footnote in the wake of ``The
Fight'' between Cale Yarborough and brothers Bobby and Donny
Allison after the checkered flag.
</P>
<P>
   Yarborough and Donnie Allison were chasing victory on the last
lap in their Oldsmobile Cutlasses when Yarborough _ who was in
second _ tried to put one of his trademark slingshot passes on
Allison halfway down the backstretch of the 2.5-mile Daytona
International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   In this era of Cup racing, nine years before introduction of
carburetor restrictor plates at the Daytona and Talladega (Ala.)
superspeedways, second place on the last lap was the preferred
position. A skilled driver like Yarborough would use the draft
created by the lead car to tuck up close and then pass into the
lead at the last possible moment.
</P>
<P>
   But Allison, well-versed on Yarborough's bag of aerodynamic
tricks, closed off the inside lane. The two engaged in a series of
body slams, which eventually drove Yarborough onto the infield
grass. In his attempt to recover, Yarborough made a hard right turn
_ and hammered into Allison again. The impact sent both cars up the
31-degree banking in Turn 3, where they hit the outside wall and
slid down to the infield.
</P>
<P>
   A stunned Petty outraced Darrell Waltrip and A.J. Foyt past the
wreckage and into Victory Lane.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Bobby Allison stopped at the crash scene, where
Donnie and Yarborough had exited their battered machines. Donnie
Allison said that Yarborough walked over to Bobby _ still seated
inside his car _ and said something to him. Yarborough then hit
Bobby Allison with his helmet through the car's window netting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew what was going to happen next,'' Donnie Allison said.
``I'd seen that look on Bobby's face before.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison clambered out of his car _ as CBS commentator Ken Squier
probably said that day _ and scored a unanimous decision against
Yarborough.
</P>
<P>
   The day's dose of testosterone captivated a crowd of 120,000 and
the TV audience. A series of storms had kept people already
suffering from cabin fever inside that Sunday afternoon, helping
CBS rack up an impressive 10.5 rating.
</P>
<P>
   The Daytona 500 since has become a staple of CBS' NASCAR
coverage. Combined with ``The Fight,'' it paved the way for the
wall-to-wall racing shows that we take for granted 20 years later.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 0149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6420 &Cx1f; tth-z
r p BC-GORE-SPI &LR;      10-14 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE TAKES CAMPAIGN TO NORTHWEST; CRITICIZES GOP, BRADLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ With a freshly minted AFL-CIO endorsement under his
belt, Vice President Al Gore flew here yesterday to excoriate
Senate Republicans, take on a vexing Northwest issue, and taunt his
rival for the Democratic presidential nomination, former New Jersey
Sen. Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in a fundraising speech at Benaroya Hall Wednesday night,
decried as ``breathtakingly irresponsible'' Senate Republicans'
rejection of a landmark treaty banning nuclear testing. ``It was
one of the most reckless votes ever cast in Congress,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier appearance, to cheers from a crowd of about 600
Boeing Aerospace Machinists, Gore pledged: ``With your support, my
first act as president of the United States will be to resubmit
this treaty.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, speaking of some Republican senators, said: ``I think they
have a hatred of President Clinton that eats them up.''
</P>
<P>
   He described Bradley to the machinists as ``a good man, and I'm
not going to run him down.'' A few moments later, however, he was
calling the former New York Knicks forward a quitter.
</P>
<P>
   In an obvious reference to Bradley's decision to leave the
Senate in 1996, after Republicans had taken control of Congress,
Gore declared: ``Some people decided at that moment to walk away,
but I chose to stay and fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also was working behind the scenes to mollify Northwest
environmentalists over a promise he made last year, but which the
Clinton administration failed to keep.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Gore said in an interview that the Clinton
administration was moving toward resolving conservation groups'
calls for a tug escorts for oil-laden tankers plying the Strait of
Juan de Fuca west of Port Angeles, Wash. He promised that the
process would ``be completed before the rough seas of winter drive
up the risk factors again.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, as Gore flew to Seattle, the White House worked to
come up with money to station a rescue tug at Neah Bay this winter.
The U.S. Department of Transportation said it would commit $250,000
toward the estimated $1.2 million pricetag of stationing a rescue
tug at Neah Bay this winter. Other sources of federal funding were
being sought.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a downpayment. ... I am confident we're going to get the
money,'' said Gov. Gary Locke, who was traveling with Gore last
night. Locke said he has committed $100,000 in money from the
governor's emergency fund to help pay for the tug.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview as he drove between Seattle appearances
Wednesday night, Gore said: ``We will get this solved.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also faces pressure from Bradley in Washington state. The
former New Jersey senator has been a frequent low-key campaigner in
Washington, his activities ranging from cerebral speeches on race
relations to basketball games with teenagers at Central Area youth
centers.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing many people into first-time political giving, Bradley
raised an estimated $300,000 at a Seattle dinner in April. Mayor
Paul Schell became the first major urban politician in America to
endorse Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Gore also raised about $300,000 at his Benaroya
Hall fundraiser. A crowd of about 350 supporters were on hand. With
Bradley making gains, they were given a full dose of reassurance
that Gore is ready to fight for and win the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to tell all our neighbors, friends and family about
the real Al Gore,'' Locke told the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The governor then introduced Jim Frush, an attorney-mountaineer
who guided Gore and his son, Albert Gore III, to the summit of
Mount Rainier in July. Frush presented the vice president with the
ice axe he used on the climb, which saw repeated hail and lightning
storms.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man is not a quitter: This man was our sparkplug,'' said
Frush, who has summited Mount Everest and climbed around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Gore recalled the climb in vivid detail later in the evening,
from howling winds when the party camped at Ingraham Flat to the
horizontal blowing snow.
</P>
<P>
   In seeking to energize his campaign, and liberate it from the
confines of Washington, D.C.'s lobbyist-laden streets, Gore has
sought to bring out the Tennessee part of his upbringing. The vice
president lives in an official residence on Massachusetts Avenue,
the same street where he grew up and went to St. Alban's School as
the son of Sen. Albert Gore, Sr.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, however, Gore talked of the small home where his
family lived summers in Carthage, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   He described his mother as ``a poor girl from west Tennessee,''
who worked at an all-night coffee shop to pay her way through
college, and later became the first woman to graduate from
Vanderbilt University law school.
</P>
<P>
   While his father, Sen. Albert Gore, Sr., prospered as a
corporate director in his later years, the vice president yesterday
depicted him as a courageous populist and talked about his father's
service as Tennessee's labor commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He presided over the first minimum wage, 25 cents an hour,''
said Gore. ``Sounds like the Republican platform. Only they were
against 25 cents an hour then.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad was against the poll tax in the 40's, for civil rights
in the 50's, for the Voting Rights Act in the 60's and against the
Vietnam War,'' said the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Gore talked about how he was disillusioned with politics after
his father was defeated for reelection in 1970. An anti-war
activist at Harvard, the younger Gore eventually enlisted in the
military and served as an Army journalist in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was interesting to come home in uniform with short hair,''
he said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gore used his Seattle trip to unveil a remodeled presidential
campaign, shedding his formal reputation for a down-home
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president's speech to Boeing machinists was full of
references to his childhood ``buddies and guys I went to school
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Fresh from an acceptance speech at the AFL-CIO convention in Los
Angeles _ the 13 million-member labor federation's endorsement
resolution was approved on voice vote that was not unanimous _ Gore
defended labor's right to organize. ``We need to get rid of striker
replacement,'' he argued. He decried what he called ``fancy
union-busting law firms.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday marked Gore's 11th visit to the Puget Sound area since
the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   One visit _ the Mount Rainier climb _ was private. On other
occasions, Gore has gone mainly to Seattle institutions, from
Recreational Equipment, Inc., to technology firms such as Real
Networks. He has ventured outside the city limits only as far as
Everett, where he addressed Boeing workers.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, GOP frontrunner Gov. George W. Bush of Texas is
blanketing the state. The Texas governor visited Spokane in July,
and has scheduled a photo opportunity with Hispanic schoolchildren
in Yakima Thursday before heading for appearances in Seattle. GOP
candidates Elizabeth Dole and Steve Forbes will also speak this
weekend to the National Federation of Republican Women.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
