<SLUG> BC-CAR-BIFFLE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIFFLE TRUCKING TO SUPERSTAR STATUS WITH ROUSH RACING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The people who work on his race truck already are convinced that
Greg Biffle is Roush Racing's next certifiable superstar.
</P>
<P>
   Like any NASCAR fan, Biffle can rattle off their names.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell ya, Mark Martin, Jeff Burton and Matt Kenseth have
definitely set some standards in the Winston Cup and Busch
series,'' said Biffle, a nine-time winner and points runner-up in
the NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series. ``I hope that I'm the next
superstar in the Jack Roush group. But there's a lot of folks that
still don't know who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Those ranks began thinning, however, just as the summer began
heating up. And following the outcomes of the past two races,
Biffle has become headline news as the series rolls into Texas
Motor Speedway in Fort Worth for the O'Reilly 300K on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Biffle's 14th-place finish in the crash-marred Kroger 225 at
Louisville (Ky.) Motor Speedway on Friday night knocked him out of
a points lead he had held since Aug. 5, a span of five races.
Biffle trails nemesis Jack Sprague by 24 points (3,437-3,413)
heading into the series' second visit this year to the 1.5-mile,
high-banked quadoval in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Biffle suffered through a miserable weekend in Kentucky, where
he crashed his primary No. 50 Grainger Ford during practice. He
scrambled to qualify his backup road-course truck ninth, but was
reduced to an also-ran in a battered vehicle. That result was
compounded by a star-crossed outing at Las Vegas Motor Speedway on
Sept. 24.
</P>
<P>
   Biffle won The Orleans 250 night race, capping a dizzying
stretch during which he had captured eight of 12 starts over four
months. Combined with his first career truck victory in May at
Memphis, Tenn., Biffle's nine victories established a series
single-season record. The victory in Vegas also clinched Ford's
first manufacturer's title in the truck series and moved team owner
Jack Roush closer to his first NASCAR championship.
</P>
<P>
   But the celebration was short-lived. During a postrace
inspection of Biffle's truck, NASCAR deemed the engine intake
manifold as an ``unapproved part.'' Crew chief Randy Goss
subsequently was fined $46,800, and 120 points were lopped off
Biffle's lead, leaving him with a 10-point advantage over Sprague.
</P>
<P>
   Roush Racing, contending that the manifold in question had been
run on eight occasions this season, appealed NASCAR's penalty. But
the National Stock Car Commission sided with the sanctioning body
last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disappointing, but I have nothing to do with what parts
we run on the truck,'' said Biffle, 29, of Vancouver, Wash. ``I was
surprised by the severity of the penalty, but the fact is that I
can't do anything about it now. I'm just going to _ and so is the
Grainger team _ focus on winning these races. We have so much
confidence and so much momentum right now that we like our
chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprague's fifth-place finish in a Chevrolet at Louisville
allowed him to outscore Biffle, 155-121. The 1997 Craftsman Truck
champion, Sprague has a 24-point lead over Biffle, the closest
differential in series history with two races remaining. And
third-place Dennis Setzer, winner of the Pronto Auto Parts 400K at
TMS on June 11 in a Dodge Ram, has pulled to within 44 points.
</P>
<P>
   Biffle did everything but win a race en route to
rookie-of-the-year honors in 1998. He finished second twice, led
five of the last seven races and captured a rookie-record four
poles, including three in succession.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we were there. We just never led the right laps,''
said Biffle, who won a series rookie-record $359,782 in 1998.
``We've fine-tuned our program, been more consistent at the end of
the races, been making way better pit decisions. I mean, we lost
probably three races _ just flat lost 'em _ in the pits (in 1998).
And I probably gave away three races as far as driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where we're at right now, we've really got it figured out.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
