<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6424 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-REDSOX-ART-     10-14 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-REDSOX-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Subs for rewriting throughout)  
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Maybe it wasn't the Curse of the Bambino that
finished off the Boston Red Sox on Wednesday night, a few ticks
before midnight. Maybe it was the Hex of Jeffrey Maier.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Umpire Rich Garcia's blown call on the
interference by Maier, a fan, in Game 1 of the American League
Championship Series, propelled the Yankees to victory over the
Baltimore Orioles. Similarly, a botched call in the 10th inning on
Wednesday night contributed generously to a 4-3 Yankee victory over
Boston in Game 1 of the ALCS at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   After the umpire's mistake, Bernie Williams led off the bottom
of the 10th inning with a home run off Rod Beck, snapping the 3-3
tie in a game played in intermittent showers. In 1996, after
Maier's catch, Williams homered leading off the 11th inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we feel very fortunate to have won this game,''
said Derek Jeter, the Yankee shortstop. ``You get to this point,
you don't care how you win.''
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Hernandez allowed all the Red Sox runs in the first two
innings, then shut out Boston over his last six innings of work,
before Mariano Rivera pitched the final two innings. David Cone
will pitch the second game of the four-of-seven-game series on
Thursday night at Yankee Stadium, against Boston's Ramon Martinez.
Cone has had 11 days of rest since his last start. The last time he
had that much rest, he pitched a perfect game, against the Montreal
Expos July 18.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's Jose Offerman opened the Boston 10th with a line single
to right. John Valentin followed with a grounder to third, a
possible double-play ball; Scott Brosius fielded and threw to
second, where Chuck Knoblauch set himself to pivot, with Offerman
bearing down on him. But Brosius' throw went in and out of the
webbing of Knoblauch's glove, and many of the 57,181 fans umpiring
in the stands groaned at the apparent error. But the one umpire who
counted _ Rick Reed _ called Offerman out, ruling that Knoblauch
had dropped the ball as he got it from his glove and that the
putout stood.
</P>
<P>
   Jimy Williams, the Boston manager, argued with Reed. ``In my
mind, he didn't have any possession at all,'' Williams said later,
evenly. ``You've got to have some kind of possession of the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of having first and second and nobody out, the Red Sox
had one out and a runner at first, and the next batter, Brian
Daubach, rolled into an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Reed viewed a videotape of the call, and just as Garcia
did after his mistake in 1996, Reed acknowledged that he had blown
the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he had possession before he dropped the ball,'' Reed
said. ``After we went in and looked at the tape, we decided that
wasn't the case. As an umpire, it was my job to get it right. I
didn't. You feel bad about it. I feel awful.''
</P>
<P>
   When Beck relieved for the Red Sox in the 10th, Williams watched
him warm up. Before Williams had stepped out of the dugout and into
the on-deck circle, he had talked briefly with Chris Chambliss, the
Yankees' batting coach, and Williams recalled his at-bat against
Beck last month. The right-hander had beaten him with an outside
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Chambliss agreed with Williams that the best way to hit against
Beck was to not try to pull the ball; just try to go to the
opposite field, or up the middle. Williams thought about this as he
went through his usual routine of drawing a line across the face of
the batter's box, to set his feet.
</P>
<P>
   Beck threw a strike. Williams stepped out. Beck fired a
fastball, and Williams swung.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' teammates in the dugout saw the ball in flight toward
center field and rushed out of the dugout, some screaming, others
silent; Ricky Ledee watched Darren Lewis, the Boston center
fielder, and when Lewis turned his back, Ledee was sure he was
preparing to field the carom of the center field wall.
</P>
<P>
   But Lewis, the back of his jersey to home plate, had stopped
only because there was nothing he could do to stop what happened
next. The ball disappeared over the wall, and when Williams thrust
his fist into the air, the crowd exploded simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   The calm demeanor of Hernandez instills confidence in his
teammates, in his manager. On Wednesday night, El Duque strolled
confidently across the field before the game, stopping to pluck a
piece of grass and toss it to see which way the wind was blowing,
as relaxed as chipping on the 10th hole on a Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But the Red Sox changed all that quickly. Right after
Hernandez's first pitch, Boston's Offerman glared toward Hernandez.
It appeared words were exchanged, and the home-plate umpire, Tim
McClelland, stepped in. Four pitches later, Offerman lined a single
through the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin pulled a grounder toward the shortstop hole, where
Jeter ranged to his right, backhanded the ball _ a spectacular
play, to that point _ jumped, twisted, threw toward second, and
into right field. Offerman wheeled around the bases as O'Neill
chased down the ball along the right-field line, and Valentin
reached third.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Then Daubach dumped Hernandez's next pitch into right field, a
single, Valentin scored. Seven pitches into the game, Hernandez
already had allowed more runs than he had in three previous
post-season starts combined, and the Red Sox had scored more runs
than the Texas Rangers had against the Yankees in the first round
of the playoffs. Right away, Boston marked its presence.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez walked the leadoff batter, Lewis, in the second
inning, generating concerned murmurs from the crowd. Lewis stole
second and stopped at third when Trot Nixon singled sharply. When
Offerman hit a slow roller past the mound, third baseman Brosius
closed on the ball _ then let the grounder pass, thinking Jeter
would be in a better position to field it. Except that Jeter
thought Brosius would make the play.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis scored, the Red Sox led, 3-0, they had runners at first
and second and nobody out, and the Yankees looked flat.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin failed to advance the runners with nobody out and
Hernandez, as he often does, escaped further trouble and went on to
pinch off the Red Sox offense. It was a just a question of whether
the Yankees could rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's manager, Williams, is not a schmoozer. He doesn't like
talking about himself. He doesn't feel obligated to explain his
choices _ ``Managerial decision,'' he says, with the tone of a
security guard. He is as uncomplicated as a doorjamb, with one
simple purpose: to win baseball games. By whatever means necessary,
Williams directed the Red Sox to a division series victory over the
Cleveland Indians, using two of his starters, Bret Saberhagen and
Pedro Martinez, to win the decisive game. Ramon Martinez, who
pitched last Saturday and is coming back from shoulder surgery,
could not have pitched Wednesday night's game on shortened rest.
</P>
<P>
   So Williams turned to Kent Mercker, a left-hander only three
days removed from his last start. But Williams wasn't expecting
Mercker to throw a complete game; he just wanted Mercker to get the
Red Sox into the middle innings, preferably with a lead.
</P>
<P>
   In Mercker's time on the mound, the Yankees hit 21 foul balls,
swinging and missing just twice. But Nomar Garciaparra was playing
behind him. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had runners at second and third and two out in the
first and Chili Davis stretched to reach a changeup and hit a hump
liner over short, where Garciaparra snatched the ball with a leap.
Two runs saved.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius crushed a two-run homer off Mercker in the second
inning, and Jeter doubled leading off the third. Garciaparra nearly
picked off Jeter at second after intercepting Williams grounder in
the shortstop hole _ Jeter was far off the bag, thinking the hit
would roll through to left _ and when the throw from the Boston
shortstop got away, Jeter took third.
</P>
<P>
   But then, again with two outs, Garciaparra again soared high to
catch Tino Martinez's line drive, falling on his back. Twice
Garciaparra had prevented Jeter from scoring in the inning, first
by keeping Williams' hit in the infield, and then when he caught
Martinez's shot. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another run saved.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox manager went to his bullpen in the fifth, Rich
Garces assuming the 3-2 lead, shutting out the Yankees for two
innings before giving way to Derek Lowe, at the start of the
seventh. Brosius greeted Lowe with a single to left and moved to
second on Knoblauch's bunt.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter then laced a single to right, Nixon rushing the ball and
gloving it on one hop; Willie Randolph, the Yankees' third-base
coach, waved Brosius around third, a blunder, it appeared, for
Nixon's throw reached the catcher ahead of the runner.
</P>
<P>
   But Boston catcher Jason Varitek was unable to hold Nixon's
throw, the ball rolling away as Brosius _ late arriving _ crashed
into the catcher and slapped his hand on home plate. Tie game.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter reached second on Nixon's throw and held there when
Garciaparra bobbled Paul O'Neill's grounder. First and second, only
one out. Lowe recovered, though, getting Williams to ground into a
forceout at second before striking out Davis with a slider spinning
toward the slugger's feet.
</P>
<P>
   Late innings, the outcome completely in doubt, Red Sox and
Yankees. The way it's supposed to be.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
