<HEADLINE>
HARPER COULD SECURE ROLE WITH COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Former Cowboys receiver Alvin Harper's brief
cameo at the Cowboys' headquarters last week could soon turn into
something substantive.
</P>
<P>
   With receiver Michael Irvin and his bruised spine sidelined for
at least the next month, the Cowboys are considering adding a
veteran receiver to bolster their attack. And Harper, who left the
Cowboys after the 1994 season and played with Tampa Bay, Washington
and New Orleans, is at the top of the list. His workout last week
got a good review from coaches and scouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to look at that very closely over the next few
days,'' Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said. ``I don't feel we are in
dire straits. But if we find something and it's a good fit, we
always want to improve our football team.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper has the size (6 feet, 3 inches) to fill in at Irvin's
outside receiver spot and the speed to make big plays down the
field. Other veterans on the market are Michael Jackson and Randall
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   If the Cowboys add another player, they will have to release a
player. Receiver Chris Brazzell, who has been inactive the past
three games, is the likely choice. SANDERS HAPPY AT CORNERBACK
</P>
<P>
   The search for a big-play receiver will not include
multitalented star cornerback Deion Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders, who started at receiver and cornerback for the Cowboys
in 1996 and has played receiver part time the past two seasons,
said he's comfortable in his role as a punt returner and cornerback
and is not looking to increase his load.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys never looked at Sanders as option because his
lengthy absence and rehabilitation from April toe surgery prevented
him from working with the offense. STRAHAN READY FOR MATCHUP
</P>
<P>
   Facing the Cowboys is like preparing for a pro wrestling match
for New York Giants defensive tackle Michael Strahan, who says
Cowboys tackle Erik Williams is deserving of his reputation as one
of the league's dirtiest players.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get hit in the face, kicked, (and) your face mask
grabbed,'' Strahan said. ``He is a crafty veteran. And he is nasty
every play he goes against you.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Strahan said he looks forward to facing Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun,'' Strahan said. ``But you can't take a play off. You
have to be ready every down.'' TURNOVERS CONCERN GAILEY
</P>
<P>
   With 12 turnovers in four games, the Cowboys are well on their
way to surpassing the 15 they amassed in 16 games last season.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of quarterback Troy Aikman's seven interceptions can be
excused as tipped balls, but coach Chan Gailey said the Cowboys
must start taking better care of the ball. NO IMPACT ON COWBOYS
</P>
<P>
   Giants coach Jim Fassel ended the quarterback suspense
Wednesday, choosing Kent Graham to start Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel said Graham, the starter since last season, gives them a
better chance to win because of his familiarity with the offense.
Kerry Collins, who played for an injured Graham in last week's loss
to ARizona, was a high-priced, free-agent signee in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel said his offense, which ranks 26th in the league, must
start playing better or there could be many changes.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said who starts at quarterback doesn't
matter to his team because Graham and Collins are drop-back passers
with similar skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to stop their offense,'' Gailey said. ``The
difference between the two quarterbacks is not that drastic. They
still run the same offense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 0157EDT &QL; 
