r s BC-OUT-DEBATE-LADN     10-14 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-DEBATE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIKERS VS. HORSES HEATS UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAMMOTH LAKES _ Can't we all just get along?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently not in the backcountry _ a place where one would
assume everything is just peachy.
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be tension between pack-station operators and
those who do away with the trampling hooves, grazing and unseemly
manure of their stock animals.
</P>
<P>
   The argument _ heated at times, though not widely known _
revolves around the use of packhorses to carry freight and riders
into the Sierra Nevada mountain range and the impacts on its
terrain and other visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have concerns about pack stock in the wilderness, and
this issue is the big issue,'' said Bill Bramlette, deputy
supervisor of the Inyo National Forest, the eastern gateway to the
High Sierra. ``A lot of the packers do feel under pressure about
the amount of use they have in certain places.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the feud is mostly finger-pointing. Though it has
been taken to the trail _ where packers say they have been hassled
by hikers, and even have had rocks tossed at their animals _ and to
the table _ where the interests of both sides have been hashed out
more amicably. Bramlette is unaware of any legal or legislative
wranglings involving the issue to date.
</P>
<P>
   Chief among the concerns of stock detractors, Bramlette said, is
the notion that the Sierra is being damaged by horseshoes and
overgrazing, that the wilderness should not be commercialized and
that professional horse packers are not regulated in the same
manner as other visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impacts of stock use in fragile alpine and subalpine areas
has been well documented,'' Tom Suk, spokesman for the High Sierra
Hikers Association, told the San Diego Union-Tribune last year.
``Some of the commercial packers show a lot of care for the land
back there, but some of them don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Suk, whose nonprofit affiliation of 700 members was initiated in
1991, on Tuesday declined to discuss much about his group's
concerns for fear he would be misrepresented in print. But the
South Lake Tahoe trekker did offer this statement: ``There is
absolutely a place for stock use on public lands. We have never
been against stock use on public lands.''
</P>
<P>
   So what, exactly, is the problem?
</P>
<P>
   Suk balked at providing any further comment _ even about whether
his association is interested in the possibility of curtailing the
number of commercial stock allowed into the Sierra _ instead
referring to the group's Web site, highsierrahikers.org, for the
answers.
</P>
<P>
   To outsiders, it may all seem confusing.
</P>
<P>
   To packers, the thought of removing packhorses and mules from
the backcountry is a bunch of, well, manure _ which happens to be
at the heart of the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be able today to live in the modern age in a huge urban
environment and pooh-pooh manure, complain about it, I mean that's
really hypocritical and inconsiderate and it's putting on airs,''
said Eastern Sierra horse packer Jim Macey of Keeler in Inyo
County. ``Because these animals are what have brought you to your
urban environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Horses, cattle and animals have offered their lives to sustain
humans since the beginning of time. And to suddenly look back and
go, `Eww, I can't stand that manure,' I mean come on, give me a
break.''
</P>
<P>
   Packers note that horses originally blazed the Sierra's trails
and should be more revered. Horses provide backcountry access to
those who can't walk in, they argue. To allow their stock to ruin
the environment would be a slap in the face of their own love of
outdoors, they claim. And, they wonder, what's next? If commercial
stock is done away with, will the animals of recreational
equestrians then be prohibited, followed by a ban on hiking?
</P>
<P>
   Some answers may be provided in the spring, when the second
draft of a management plan for four Sierra wilderness areas is
expected to be released by the U.S. Forest Service. A key element
within it is the use of stock animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to deal with the issues,'' Bramlette said. ``The
problem is there aren't simple answers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
