<HEADLINE>
BRAVES HIRE WREN TO BE ASSISTANT GM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Braves hired former Orioles general manager Frank
Wren yesterday as their assistant general manager.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles fired Wren seven days ago, hours after the franchise
announced that it would not exercise the option on the contract of
manager Ray Miller for the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles dismissed Wren after a ``seasonlong series of
incidents involving a variety of personnel matters, both with
front-office staff and players,'' said Joe Foss, the Orioles' vice
chairman and chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   One of the incidents included Wren's order that the Orioles'
charter flight to Anaheim, Calif., on Sept. 17 leave without third
baseman Cal Ripken Jr., who telephoned traveling secretary Phil
Iztoe from his car to explain that a traffic delay would make him a
few minutes late.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves also signed left-hander Mike Remlinger to a two-year
contract extension. Remlinger went 10-1 with a 2.37 earned-run
average in 73 appearances and recorded 81 strikeouts in 83 2/3
innings. Opponents hit only .215 against Remlinger.
YOSHII ACHING
</P>
<P>
   Mets right-hander Masato Yoshii, who left Game 1 in the fifth
inning after spraining his left ankle, is questionable for his
scheduled start Sunday should Game 5 be necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yoshii's ankle is sore,'' Mets manager Bobby Valentine said.
``He has been in the training room. It doesn't feel that bad, but
there's definitely something there that hopefully treatment will
cure.''
GALARRAGA TO INCREASE WORK
</P>
<P>
   Braves first baseman Andres Galarraga has received clearance to
begin the next step in his rehabilitation from lymphoma.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga, who missed all of the 1999 season, underwent a CT
scan Tuesday, and the examination revealed that the bone in his
lower back _ once stricken with cancer _ continues to grow
stronger.
</P>
<P>
   Galarraga's rehabilitation will progress from walking on a
treadmill and stair-climbing to jogging and lifting light weights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'll be able to swing \Ra bat\S and lift the
heavy stuff until December, but it's good news,'' Galarraga said.
``This will give me some time to go step-by-step and be ready for
spring training.'' No problem with fans Mets left-hander John
Franco praised the behavior of those seated near the Mets' bullpen
during Game 1 at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no problems with them \RTuesday\S night,'' Franco said.
``The last time we were here, it was a handful of people in the
bullpen that were nasty to myself and Dennis Cook and all the guys
down there.
</P>
<P>
   ``They start drinking and get sauced up, and that's what
happens. Most of it was all in fun \RTuesday\S night, but the last
series we were here _ in the 16 years coming here _ was probably
the worst I've seen.''
WEISS MAKES MOST OF START
</P>
<P>
   Reserve infielder Walt Weiss, one of the Braves' heroes from
Game 1 of this NLCS, made his second consecutive start at
shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss replaced shortstop Jose Hernandez in the lineup for Game 1
and went 3-for-4 with a run batted in and scored what proved to be
the game-winning run after his fifth-inning double.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had thought a couple of days ago that I'd probably play
Hernandez against \RKenny\S Rogers and with \RKevin\S Millwood
pitching, but the fact is Walt had a great night,'' Braves manager
Bobby Cox said. ``He looked good at short, and he swung the bat
well. He's swinging the bat a little better from the right side
than he is the left side, so we're going to go ahead and go with
the hot hand right now.''
HE SAID IT
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the highlight film, and time and again you don't know how
he gets to the ball or make the plays, but he makes them.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Mets left-hander John Franco, on shortstop/defensive wizard
Rey Ordonez Briefly
</P>
<P>
   _ Mets left fielder Rickey Henderson left the game during the
second inning after experiencing nausea and light-headedness.
Reserve Melvin Mora replaced Henderson and became the seventh
player to hit a home run in his first NLCS at-bat. Joe Morgan, Bob
Dernier, Rick Sutcliffe, Glenn Davis, Mark Grace and Orlando Merced
also accomplished that feat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Right-hander John Smoltz, the Braves' scheduled starter for
Game 4, earned the save yesterday with a scoreless ninth in the
first relief appearance of his career. The 11-pitch appearance will
not prevent Smoltz from starting Game 4 on Saturday, manager Bobby
Cox said. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
