<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOX-ADS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIOLENCE IN `FIGHT CLUB' GRABS ATTENTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- A fight over ``Fight Club'' ended before
developing into a big-time brawl within Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   20th Century Fox apparently threatened to withdraw all film
advertising from The Hollywood Reporter after the trade journal's
editor wrote a scathing commentary about the ultraviolent Brad Pitt
movie opening Friday. But after a day of ``no comments,'' the
studio backed off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our relationship with The Hollywood Reporter has not changed
or been impacted by this article,'' studio spokeswoman Florence
Grace said late Wednesday. She declined to elaborate further.
</P>
<P>
   The article in question appeared in Tuesday's edition. ``In
scene after blood-soaked scene, it preaches personal growth through
acts of calculated violence,'' Editor Anita M. Busch wrote. ``
`Fight Club,' no doubt, will become Washington's poster child for
what's wrong with Hollywood. And Washington, for once, will be
right. The film is exactly the kind of product that lawmakers
should target for being socially irresponsible in a nation that has
deteriorated to the point of Columbine.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox had originally planned to release the movie this summer but
delayed it until the fall, following April's massacre at Columbine
High School in Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Busch, a veteran entertainment journalist who became editor
earlier this year, also wrote, ``The ultragraphic violence of Fox
2000's `Fight Club' has drawn more gut anger from the industry than
I've ever heard. And for good reason.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Fox to stop advertising was reported in
Wednesday's editions of The New York Times with an unnamed studio
executive saying, ``At this point the film studio is not
advertising in The Hollywood Reporter.''
</P>
<P>
   Had Fox followed through, the ad boycott could have cost the
Reporter hundreds of thousands of dollars in revenue. Studios are
about to launch their Academy Awards campaigns, which are
advertised extensively in the Reporter and its larger competitor,
Daily Variety.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the ``for your consideration'' ads are purchased not so
much with the intent of promoting the film for an Oscar as they are
for maintaining cordial relations between the studios and their
top-drawer talent. Costs of ads vary based on day of the week and
placement but the basic full-page color rate is more than $9,000
for the Reporter.
</P>
<P>
   The paper had no comment Wednesday on the dispute, which
reflects the ongoing battle between Hollywood and the ``trades,''
as the Reporter and Variety are known. But taking the step of
pulling the plug on all advertising would have been extremely rare.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's decision may have also been sparked by a story in Friday's
Reporter, which described the ``angry and agitated'' reaction of
the audience at a prerelease screening in Westwood. ``It's
loathsome to use the medium this way,'' an unnamed producer told
the publication. Another unnamed spectator said, ``It's the most
horrible movie I've ever seen!''
</P>
<P>
   The movie, which also stars Edward Norton and Helena Bonham
Carter, is expected to dominate the weekend box office when it
opens at between 1,900 and 2,000 theaters. ``Fight Club,'' based on
a 1996 novel by Chuck Palahniuk and costing a reported $65 million,
follows a fictional group of men in an underground society that
evolves from no-holds-barred fights to assaulting strangers to
committing terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Bagdikian, a prominent media industry observer and former
dean of the graduate school of journalism at the University of
California at Berkeley, said Fox's threat of an ad ban proves it is
``going to protect the high level of violence (it produces) because
it's cheap and repeatable and makes them a whole lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fox Network pioneered such ``reality-based'' shows as
``America's Most Wanted'' and ``Cops.'' ``I hope Fox's response
attracts attention to the issue of compulsive broadcasting of
violence,'' said Bagdikian, a former editor at The Washington Post.
``I earnestly hope it backfires on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Norton and Pitt have defended the film, directed by David
Fincher, and portrayed it as a satire on issues that needs
discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you didn't make art that was critical of what's unhealthy
in this society, then you've got a society that's in denial,''
Norton told the Daily News in a recent interview. ``This film,
whatever you want to take out of it, it's a very substantive and
provocative critique of the dynamics that create certain kinds of
feelings in people in the culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Busch's column also criticized the ratings board of the Motion
Picture Association of America for assigning ``Fight Club'' an R
rating, which allows children under 17 to attend if accompanied by
an adult. She contended it should have been assigned an NC-17,
which would bar anyone under 17.
</P>
<P>
   MPAA President Jack Valenti said Wednesday he could not comment
on the rating because he has not seen the film and noted that it's
difficult to establish that acts of violence can be inspired by
films. ``The answer is that no one knows if that's true,'' he said.
``I'm not equipped to say and neither is anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Box office tracker Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel
Source service, said ``Fight Club'' will probably take in $18
million during its Friday-Sunday opening weekend and could hit $75
million by the end of its run. He said it was unlikely that the
movie will provoke violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the film was anti-violence,'' he said. ``Sometimes
you have to be brutal in your message to get the theme across. I
don't think anyone is going to take this and go out and start
bombing buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
