<HEADER>
A6438 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-14 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST SIT BACK AND ENJOY THE SHOW AT SHORTSTOP 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nomar leaped to steal a hit from the Yankees, then
Derek leaped to swipe one back from the Red Sox, so Nomar leaped
even higher to pilfer another. Derek made a sweet play in the
shortstop hole, but then bounced the throw to second base for an
error. Then Nomar made an even sweeter play in shallow left field,
but unintentionally mimicked Derek by bouncing his throw to second.
</P>
<P>
   The game was only three innings old, but the intense matchup
between the Yankees and the Red Sox already featured a marvelous
duel between the dazzling shortstops whose surnames are not
necessary. Derek versus Nomar, Nomar against Derek. Who really
needed the Yankees and the Red Sox with the way Garciaparra and
Jeter were flying through the air like Keyshawn Johnson in a
baseball cap?
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the game eventually overtook the story of the two
shortstops. Nomar and Jeter are terrific, but neither wound up
being involved in the final run in the 10th inning because Bernie
Williams ripped a homer off Rod Beck that soared over the
center-field fence and catapulted the Yankees to a dramatic 4-3
victory over the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great,'' Jeter said. ``It's almost like we stole the
ball game.''
</P>
<P>
   But any of the 57,181 fans who were not studying the two most
provocative players at Yankee Stadium when Game 1 of the American
League Championship Series began on Wednesday night were gawking at
every move Jeter and Garciaparra made by the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   Which one would rob some runs from the other team next? It was
intriguing to watch the shortstops play a game within the game and
exciting to watch them fuel the debate about who is better. After
the gorgeous plays that Jeter and Garciaparra made, the question
should be answered with another question. Who is better? Who cares?
Just enjoy the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys are mvp-type players who play shortstop, which is
normally a defensive position,'' David Cone said. ``I don't know
how that's going to impact our future generations, but I know
there's a lot of kids who are playing shortstop because of those
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter and Garciaparra are talented, respectful, team-oriented
players who symbolize their teams, the businesslike Yankees and the
resilient Red Sox, and, therefore, the two shortstops symbolize
this rivalry. It is a different rivalry now, not built as much on
hatred anymore. That could change during this century-concluding
ALCS.
</P>
<P>
   As Roger Clemens said, ``This might rekindle it a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   It should. The rivalry between the Yankees and the Red Sox will
always be intense because they have a legendary history, because
they are in the American League East, because they are so close
geographically and because, for the next decade, it should continue
to be enhanced by Jeter and Garciaparra. Just as it was Wednesday
night when Jeter and Garciaparra combined for three errors and
still managed to put on a terrific defensive display.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I hear my name in the same sentence as his, I think
that's an honor,'' Garciaparra said. ``I think he's absolutely
tremendous.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter, who also had two hits and one run batted in to
Garciaparra's 0 for 4 night, countered by saying, ``He's a good guy
and he plays hard.''
</P>
<P>
   After Jeter made a nice play in the shortstop hole in the first,
he tossed the ball past second base to allow Jose Offerman to score
Boston's first run, then punched his glove with his fist. In the
bottom of the inning, there were men on first and third when Chili
Davis' looping shot toward left center looked like it might somehow
drop in for a single. But Garciaparra, who was perched where the
grass and dirt meet, leaped to corral it and preserve a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Two innings later, Jeter, who imitated Garciaparra's toe-tapping
batting stance after replacing him in the All-Star Game at Fenway
Park, imitated him on defense. Jeter helped Orlando Hernandez
strand a runner in the third by jumping to snag Mike Stanley's
liner.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom of the third featured more of Garciaparra's
athleticism. With Jeter on second, Williams slashed a grounder off
third baseman John Valentin's glove. Garciaparra was rushing to the
right, but when the ball deflected off of Valentin, he amazingly
reached to his left to snatch it. But he then tarnished the play by
throwing by Offerman while trying to nail Jeter straying off
second.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra's error helped the Yankees put runners on first and
third with one out, but, after Davis lined out to second, the
shortstop rescued the Red Sox and himself again. Tino Martinez
lashed a ball that, off the bat, seemed like it might roll into the
left-center-field gap. Instead, Garciaparra was a human pogo stick
one more time, jumping out of his cleats for the liner. All Jeter
could do was shake his head from third, a sign of admiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like that,'' said Jeter, when asked if he and
Garciaparra had a personal duel going on. ``He mentioned something
to me when I was on second base. He's a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the way Yankees-Red Sox should be. Fans still argue
about whether Ted Williams or Joe DiMaggio was the better hitter.
Thurman Munson hated Carlton Fisk and vice versa. Don Mattingly was
perturbed when Wade Boggs did not play in the last three games of
1986 because of a phantom hamstring injury and secured a batting
title over Mattingly by 5 points. Now the prolonged debates focus
on Jeter and Garciaparra. Who is better? Who cares? Just enjoy the
show.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
