<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 02:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6444 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-BAGGARLY-COLUMN-L     10-14 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BAGGARLY-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIG WEEK FOR HACKETT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREW BAGGARLY  
 San Bernardino County Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Here's a classic college football scenario:
</P>
<P>
   Coach of underachieving team pilots his weary squad into the den
of his team's greatest rival, with his job security so delicately
placed on the cliff's edge.
</P>
<P>
   A low rumble builds in the distance. The words ``intersectional
rivalry'' echo above the racket.
</P>
<P>
   This must be Notre Dame week.
</P>
<P>
   John Robinson knew this week. He embraced it. Relished it.
</P>
<P>
   It was his own personal life preserver. When USC was awash in a
mediocre season, already eliminated from the Rose Bowl and looking
up at the Washingtons and Arizona States in the standings, when
their fans were calling for Robinson's head and their alumni were
calling athletic director John Garrett's office, Robinson went and
beat the Irish. He saved his job.
</P>
<P>
   On more than one occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, now, Robinson is rolling dice in Las Vegas. A nice,
friendly, bespectacled man named Paul Hackett is in his second
season coaching the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   And Garrett's secretary already has begun to field calls.
</P>
<P>
   USC is again drowning in mediocrity halfway through Hackett's
second season. They're 3-2, with losses to Oregon and Arizona. They
beat San Diego State by a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Rose Bowl? Not this year.
</P>
<P>
   If they finish strong, maybe a return trip to the Sun Bowl.
Alumni can tour all the El Paso sights that time restrictions
prevented them from seeing the first time around.
</P>
<P>
   Many aren't thrilled with that prospect, and, as a result, they
aren't thrilled with Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   It's too early in his tenure to begin questioning his job
security, but Hackett isn't recoiling from the heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it. I love every bit of it,'' Hackett said at his
weekly news conference Tuesday. ``USC fans expect to win every
game. That's why I came here. That's why I love this place.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett conducts his weekly conference in the Varsity Lounge, a
maroon-and-gold-splashed banquet room located just off Heritage
Hall's trophy-crowded foyer.
</P>
<P>
   He brings highlighted notes _ in more than one shade of neon. He
always wears a crisply ironed shirt, a woven tie and a sharp
sportcoat.
</P>
<P>
   He is orderly. Neat. Under control.
</P>
<P>
   But he challenges that image as he begins to make one passionate
point after another. He punctuates each sentence by thumping his
heavy arms against the unsturdy banquet table.
</P>
<P>
   The air in the Varsity Lounge is jarred by the constant
thumping. Stat sheets and notepads play hopscotch a quarter-inch
off the table's reverberating surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the team is playing hard and playing to the end, I
cannot expect anything more,'' he said, his open-handed slaps
landing in combinations on the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a point when we will nose ahead of the rest of
the conference. There will be a point when we will be a contender
year after year. Whether we reach that status this year, well ...
we'll play the games and find out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans' two losses have come to conference favorite Arizona
by a touchdown and to Oregon in triple-overtime. Both on the road.
</P>
<P>
   But their three victories were over limp opponents, and except
for the season-opening victory over Hawaii, their performances have
been listless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am aware of the criticism,'' Hackett said, ``but my own
internal criticism is tougher than any outside hits I have taken.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett is a tall man, but hardly threatening. His cheeks appear
rouged and his eyes blink nervously behind wire-rimmed glasses.
</P>
<P>
   When he grins, laugh lines crinkle along his temples.
</P>
<P>
   It is too early for this nice, well-meaning, respectful man to
face harsh criticism. Too early for Notre Dame to be his life
preserver.
</P>
<P>
   But Hackett seems to know that the hourglass exists. That by
this time next year, if the Sun Bowl looms again, beating the Irish
might take on a greater significance.
</P>
<P>
   It might save his job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
