<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6447 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKEES-BROSIUS-B     10-14 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-BROSIUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROSIUS STILL MAN OF HOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE FAINARU  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The magical 1998 season for the Yankees ended with
the world champs gathered in their clubhouse, chanting, ``Scot-ty
Bro-sius, Scot-ty Bro-sius.''
</P>
<P>
   Brosius, the World Series MVP, had just put the finishing
touches on the season of his life. After coming to the Yankees from
Oakland in a trade for Kenny Rogers after the 1997 season, he
exploded out of obscurity, batting .300 with 19 homers and 98 RBIs,
anchoring himself at third base on one of the greatest teams in
history.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius's follow-up this year has been a struggle, personally
and professionally, but he reemerged as a postseason force
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night in Game 1 of the American League Championship
Series between the Red Sox and Yankees. He helped provide the
Yankees with three runs before Bernie Williams won the game, 4-3,
with a homer in the 10th inning off Rod Beck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brosius has had some big hits for us,'' said Yankee manager
Joe Torre. ``We didn't know a year ago what kind of player we were
getting.''
</P>
<P>
   Brosius hit a single, a triple, and a two-run homer, missing his
chance to hit for the cycle when he struck out in the ninth. In the
seventh inning, he scored the tying run from second on Derek
Jeter's single, barreling into catcher Jason Varitek and jarring
the ball loose before slapping the plate with his gloved hand.
</P>
<P>
   Some believed Brosius's 1998 season was a fluke. Although he had
one decent year with the A's, hitting .304 with 22 homers in 1996,
he was hardly a star. He had spent the better part of seven seasons
in the minors and was plagued by injuries even after he made it to
the majors.
</P>
<P>
   He seemed to be a perfect fit with the Yankees, though, hitting
ninth and playing steadily alongside shortstop Derek Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   The World Series was Brosius's coming-out party: He hit .471 and
slammed two home runs in Game 5 against the San Diego Padres,
including a three-run shot off closer Trevor Hoffman with the
Yankees trailing, 3-2, in the eighth inning. He finished the
postseason with 15 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   This season didn't go nearly as smooth. His father, Maury,
suffered from colon cancer and Brosius left the club to be with him
in McMinnville, Ore., in late August. Maury Brosius died Sept. 12,
and Brosius left the club again to attend to the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned, the Yankees had all but clinched the AL East
pennant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's going to affect me or not,'' Brosius said
when asked if it was difficult to concentrate because of his
father. ``Certainly when all of this is said and done, once I get
home it will affect me. But at this time of year I'm supposed to be
away. I'm supposed to be playing baseball, so I can kind of keep
some of these things where they're supposed to be until I get
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night was his first sparkling moment in a while. He
seemed to come up big in all the right moments. In the second, with
the Yankees down, 3-0, Kent Mercker threw a low 3-and-2 fastball
with a runner on base, and Brosius hammered it over the left-field
wall.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees stranded Brosius in the fourth when he hit a two-out
triple. The ball looped near the right-field line, skipped past a
diving Trot Nixon, and rolled into the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Then he led off the seventh with a single. After he moved to
second on Chuck Knoblauch's sacrifice, Jeter belted a single to
right and Nixon came up throwing as Brosius headed toward the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   The throw was slightly up the line, and the ball arrived just
before Brosius, who barrelled into Varitek. The ball ended up
behind him the catcher as Brosius tagged the plate with his hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he was expecting me to hit him,'' said
Brosius. ``I really had nowhere else to go. I knew I wouldn't be
able to slide around him, and that the only place to go was over
him or through him. It was my only chance to get to the plate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
