<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 02:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6455 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-YANKEES-HN     10-14 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-YANKEES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ Bernie Williams wondered what the chances were of
delivering in an almost identical situation to his heroic Game 1
homer in the 1996 American League Championship Series.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the Boston Red Sox have learned over the years, anything can
happen. And it mostly happens to them.
</P>
<P>
   Williams hit a leadoff home run in the 10th inning Wednesday as
the Yankees survived a scare with a 4-3 victory over the Red Sox in
Game 1 of the ALCS at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   After falling behind by three runs in the second inning, the
Yankees got a strong outing from starter Orlando Hernandez, rallied
to tie in the seventh and won on Williams' dramatic home run in the
10th.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius shared offensive honors for the Yankees, going
3-for-4 and coming within a double of hitting for the cycle.
</P>
<P>
   With the game tied at 3, Williams opened the 10th by sending an
0-1 pitch from Boston reliever Rod Beck _ an inside fastball _ to
straightaway center field.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Lewis thought he had a chance to make a play, but the
ball sailed over the 408-foot sign, setting off a wild celebration
by a rain-soaked crowd of 57,181 who came to see the first
postseason meeting between the traditional rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was due,'' Williams said. ``I was just able to get a good
pitch and turn on it. I was looking for a pitch out over the plate.
I definitely didn't want to pull out on the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   In the top of the 10th, the Yankees caught a break when
second-base umpire Rick Reed ruled the Yankees' Chuck Knoblauch had
possession of the ball before dropping it on a force play.
Television replays indicated he did not, and Reed _ after viewing a
replay following the game _ admitted he had blown the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an umpire, it was my job to get it right. I didn't,'' Reed
said. ``You feel bad about it. I feel awful.''
</P>
<P>
   With the go-ahead run at first and one out, Brian Daubach hit
into an inning-ending double play. Moments later, Williams
delivered the parting shot.
</P>
<P>
   The home run was reminiscent of the 1996 ALCS when Williams hit
a game-winning homer off Baltimore's Randy Myers in the 11th inning
to beat Baltimore 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was all I was thinking about the inning before,'' said
Williams. ``It was kind of a setup for the same situation I had in
1996. I tried to keep it off my mind because it is a different
pitcher, different team, but the setup was sort of the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what are the chances of that happening twice?''
</P>
<P>
   Boston, which lost its ninth consecutive ALCS game, has to be
wondering the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox blew a three-run lead and wasted a solid effort by
starter Kent Mercker and a strong performance by three relievers,
who combined to hold the Yankees to three runs over nine innings.
</P>
<P>
   If there were any questions whether they had anything left after
an emotional first-round series with Cleveland, the Red Sox erased
them in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Offerman led off the game with a single and scored from
first base when New York shortstop Derek Jeter threw into right
field on John Valentin's grounder. Valentin scored on a single by
Daubach as Boston scored two runs in the first inning for the third
consecutive game.
</P>
<P>
   In the second, Lewis walked, stole second and took third on Trot
Nixon's single before Offerman's second hit made it 3-0. But
Hernandez drew the line right there, setting down Valentin, Daubach
and Nomar Garciaparra in order.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox rarely threatened over the final eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius, the hero in last year's World Series sweep of San
Diego, hit a two-run homer off Mercker in the bottom of the second
to cut the lead to 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   He tripled in the fourth and singled in the seventh. With a
chance to become the first Yankee to hit for the cycle in a
postseason game, Brosius struck out looking against Derek Lowe in
the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brosius has had big hits for us,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre
said. ``We didn't know a year ago what kind of player we were
getting. He showed us a year ago that he was pretty impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   New York, which dominated the Texas Rangers in a first-round
sweep, had trouble cashing in on scoring chances early against the
Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had two runners in scoring position in the first
inning but were robbed by a leaping catch by Garciaparra, who later
committed two errors. In the third, the Yankees had two runners on
base but came up empty as Mercker worked out of the jam with a pair
of infield popouts. They stranded another runner at third in the
fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hernandez overcame a rocky start and held the Red Sox
to three hits after the second inning. He allowed two earned runs
and seven hits over eight innings. Reliever Mariano Rivera pitched
two scoreless innings to earn the victory.
</P>
<P>
   New York drew even in the seventh when Brosius led off with a
single, moved to second on a sacrifice by Knoblauch and scored on a
single by Jeter off Lowe.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon's one-hop throw from right field was on time, but catcher
Jason Varitek couldn't cleanly field the ball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
