<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 02:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6456 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-RYANCOLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-14 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RYAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO-HERO SHORT STORY A THRILLER 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Is this Yankee Stadium or is this Lamade Field in
Williamsport, Pa.? Is this the American League Championship Series
or is this the Little League World Series?
</P>
<P>
   We all know how it works in Little League. A manager identifies
his two best athletes as quickly as possible, and a vast percentage
of the time they turn out to be his primary shortstop and his
primary pitcher. Either that, or his shortstop is his primary
pitcher. You can bet your autographed picture of Cal Ripken (a
classic RHP/SS in high school) that the vast percentage of superior
Little League teams feature a shortstop as their clean-up hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Those kind of power-hitting shortstops have only occasionally
turned up in baseball history (Honus Wagner, Vern Stephens, Ernie
Banks, Ripken, etc.), and all too often the ball-bashing shortstop
in question was something of a mediocrity in the field. Not so in
the 1999 American League Championship Series. In this series we
have on display two-thirds of baseball's Holy Trinity of
shortstops, each that classic Little League model in full
professional flower.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in Seattle's magnificent Alex Rodriguez, and these three
shortstops are clearly 1, 1A, and 1B in the contemporary baseball
shortstop pecking order. Rodriguez aside, the Nomar
Garciaparra-Derek Jeter debate represents the ALCS answer to Wilt
vs. Russell. It will be the most watched and commented upon
play-within-a-play aspect of this unique postseason confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   In regulation play, neither man claimed an advantage.
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night the Yankee shortstop did make a first-inning error
in the middle of the two-run Boston first, but it was the direct
result of his tremendous range, as he roamed far to his right to
snare a John Valentin shot, only to throw the ball wild in an
attempt to get Jose Offerman at second. The ball rolled to the
right- field foul line, allowing Offerman to score.
</P>
<P>
   But Jeter made amends, first by doubling in the third, then by
tying the game at 3-3 with an RBI single off Derek Lowe in the
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   As for Nomar, his at-bats were uniformly gruesome. He flied out
three times, basically getting himself out by swinging at the first
pitch. His fourth at-bat, in the eighth inning, produced a foul out
to the catcher. And in the field he was wildly erratic. He had one
error on a throw quite similar to Jeter's, and he muffed a ground
ball. He also made two spectacular leaping snatches of line drives,
the first on a Chili Davis shot headed for left and the second an
even more acrobatic, Jordanesque aerial robbery on Tino Martinez
with two on and two out in the third. That one saved a run.
</P>
<P>
   Each shortstop is coming off a huge season. Jeter had career
highs in batting average (.349), hits (219), home runs (24), runs
batted in (102), doubles (37), triples (9), and walks (91). His
.349 average made him the runner-up in the batting race. And guess
who was No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries restricted Nomar to 135 games, but his final numbers
would have made him the envy of about 99 percent of shortstops who
have ever played. He augmented his .357 average with 27 homers. He
knocked in 104 runs and scored 103. He had 42 doubles. And here's
one: He fanned only 39 times, or once every 13.6 times at bat. In
modern baseball, this figure for a man who makes an offensive
living by slugging the ball, and who does not acknowledge the
existence of what you might call a ``defensive'' swing, is
extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   It harkens back to another era, calling to mind men such as
Johnny Mize, Joe DiMaggio, and Yogi Berra. If you're bored and
think thumbing through the Baseball Encyclopedia for an hour or so
is a pleasureable exercise, check out how many men in baseball
history with 500 or more at-bats have slugged in excess of .600
while striking out fewer than 40 times. Nomar did; his slugging
percentage was .603. (For the record, Jeter slugged .550 while
striking out 116 times.)
</P>
<P>
   The three errors between them Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night belie the fact
that each is a superior defensive player, if not necessarily on the
Rey Ordonez-Omar Vizquel level. Nomar originally was billed as a
defensive whiz; this slugging business is a bonus born out of
assiduous work in the weight room. Jeter was thought to be a dream
offensive-defensive combo from the day he was signed. Nomar is as
capable as Jeter of making the spectacular play. Jeter is a hair
more consistent on the routine play, and he has a more reliable
arm. Again, we are talking about a matter of degrees, and precious
few of those.
</P>
<P>
   People in baseball love dissecting their games, and it is very
rare that anyone arrives at the conclusion that there is a
significant difference, one way or the other. ``I don't think I've
seen anything better at the position,'' says Ernie Harwell, the
venerable announcer who called his first big league game in 1948.
``Their steadiness, their offensive ability, their defensive
ability, their capacity to make the big play _ they're just
amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   They are similar as players, but less so as people. The
25-year-old Jeter is a New York gossip columnist's dream. He is a
good-looking marquee athlete who had a well-publicized romance with
Mariah Carey and is hardly unfamiliar with the Gotham night scene.
Nomar, 11 months older, is Mr. Private, a classic no-frills guy.
The idea of being a celebrity, as opposed to being a high-profile
athlete, is repugnant to him.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar is notoriously obsessed with one thing: winning. He will
not allow even friends, let alone members of the media, to discuss
stats with him. It would not be a surprise if commissioner Bud
Selig were to open his mail one day soon and discover a letter from
the shortstop of the Boston Red Sox in which he formally rejects
the batting title as irrelevant. ``What does this have to do with
winning?'' Nomar might inquire.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter, though a looser personality, likes to win, too, and with
two championship rings in three years as a Yankee, he obviously
knows how to get it done.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night was Chapter One in a baseball novella of
indeterminate length. Reserve your copy at your favorite baseball
reading establishment immediately.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
