<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-HERNANDEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAME OLD STORY: HERNANDEZ SURVIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ According to Yankee records, Orlando Hernandez turned
30 last Sunday. But a recently translated birth certificate
revealed that the Cuban defector is actually 34.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by not only the age discrepancy but also his performance
in Game 1 Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night at Yankee Stadium, ``El Duque'' has a
penchant for deception.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox started the game with great success against the
righthander. At first, it seemed he would be lucky to last three
innings. But poor starts are not out of character for the Yankee
righthander. Many attribute his ability to escape from sticky
situations to the hardships he faced in Cuba and his difficulty of
fleeing his homeland. His personal history leads those who assess
Hernandez's talent to assume that nothing bothers the pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may look easy (to pitch out of jams), but I can tell you
it's not as easy as it looks,'' said Hernandez. ``It's difficult.
But I enjoy those kind of situations. I like the toughest
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez got off to his not-so-unusual shaky start against the
bulk of the Red Sox order. In the first, he faced seven batters and
allowed two runs before escaping the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Leadoff hitter Jose Offerman singled to center, and John
Valentin hit a grounder to short that Derek Jeter threw away,
allowing Offerman to score and Valentin to move to third. Brian
Daubach batted next and drove in Valentin with a single to right.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez didn't get his first out until Nomar Garciaparra flied
to left. Garciaparra had trouble hitting against Hernandez, getting
just three fly balls (two to left, one to center) and a foul tip
caught by the catcher for the first out of the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   In the second inning, Hernandez allowed the Sox third and final
run of the night. Darren Lewis drew a leadoff walk, stole second,
and came around to score on Trot Nixon's single to center and
Offerman's infield hit to short.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez, who was more effective as the game wore on, worked
eight innings, allowing seven hits, three runs (two earned), and
two walks (one each in the first two innings). He threw 112 pitches
(70 for strikes) and had four strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's been what, seven days since he pitched?'' said
Yankee manager Joe Torre, addressing the subject of Hernandez's
struggles at the start of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the same thing, really, he did against Texas (in
Game 1 of the Division Seres for a win). First couple of innings,
he had men on base in that game, then settled in. It looked like a
carbon copy of that game, except he escaped in that game without
giving up any runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``But here they hit some balls hard, other balls they found a
hole, but the thing about it, that's what Boston does.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the key inning in the game was the second inning,
when he only came away giving up one more run. I think that was
huge _ to get out of there with only one more.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez entered the game with a perfect postseason record of
3-0. But Monte Pearson (1936-39), Herb Pennock (1923-27), and Lefty
Gomez (1932-38) remained the only pitchers in Yankee history to win
their first four postseason starts, as Hernandez had to settle for
a no decision in start No. 4. Yet prior to facing the Red Sox in
Game 1 of the ALCS, he had allowed only one run in 22 playoff
innings for an astonishing 0.41 postseason ERA.
</P>
<P>
   His playoff highlight came in Cleveland during the 1998 ALCS.
With the Yankees down in the series, 2-1, Hernandez pitched Game 4
on 15 days' rest. He earned the victory with seven scoreless
innings of three-hit ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been able to maintain confidence because I'm
confident in the team,'' said Hernandez. ``I know that whatever
presents itself, we can get out of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
