<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERRORS PROVE COSTLY TO RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ERRORS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Make no mistake about it: Mistakes were a big part of
Game 1 of the American League Championship Series Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were the first offenders, on an unlikely throwing
error by star shortstop Derek Jeter only two batters into the first
game.
</P>
<P>
   After Jose Offerman opened the night with a single to center,
the sure-handed, strong-armed Jeter made a nice pickup of John
Valentin's hot grounder to the left side. Hoping to cut down
Offerman at second, Jeter turned and fired, but his throw was way
wide of the bag and his toss disappeared like a comet into foul
territory behind first base.
</P>
<P>
   Result: Offerman raced all the way around to score and Valentin
chugged his way to third. Moments later, Brian Daubach knocked a
single to right and Valentin trotted home with the 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   What a way to begin the night. Pennant-contending clubs
typically carry the hallmark of strong fundamental baseball. Yet
Jeter, with the rushed throw, handed two runs over before the
Yankees even had a chance to bat.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the inning, Sox catcher Jason Varitek was
charged with a rarely recorded error when he dropped a foul pop
near the Yankee dugout. Leadoff hitter Chuck Knoblauch hit the high
pop, sending Varitek racing to his right. After appearing to make a
nice catch, and holding the ball for less than a second, Varitek
saw it pop out of his glove and drop to the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   The official scorers ruled it an error, deeming that it
prolonged Knoblauch's at-bat. Perhaps they were missing key plays
on the field, but nothing was getting by the scorers' hawk-like
eyes. The good news for the Sox: Starter Kent Mercker eventually
got Knoblauch to roll out to short, and the Yanks didn't score a
run.
</P>
<P>
   If it were somewhat strange for Jeter to be making boo-boos, it
was even more peculiar for Sox shorstop Nomar Garciaparra also to
be fighting the ball. But Garciaparra had his problems as well,
committing errors in the third and seventh innings _ the latter
coming only moments after the Yankees had knotted it, 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   The slick-fielding Garciaparra, widely held to have one of the
strongest throwing arms in the game, was hoping to cut down Jeter
at second base after gobbling up a Bernie Williams roller to the
left side. Jeter, who had led off with a double, strayed too far
from the bag on the roller _ anticipating Garciaparra wouldn't be
able to handle it _ and had to hurry back to avoid being picked
off. But Garciaparra's toss went far wide of Offerman, who was
covering second, and Jeter advanced to third.
</P>
<P>
   Mercker made the bad throw a moot point, however, setting down
Chili Davis and then Tino Martinez. Garciaparra redeemed himself
nicely on the last out, employing about a 30-inch vertical leap to
snare Martinez's hard liner.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, the Yanks pushed across the tying run when Scott
Brosius led off with a single, moved to second on a sacrifice bunt,
and scored on Jeter's sharp single to right. Right fielder Trot
Nixon made a perfect peg to the plate and Brosius would have been
dead on arrival, except Varitek failed to field the one-hop throw.
The ball out of Varitek's glove, Brosius banged into the Sox
catcher and touched home with the 3-3 equalizer. It wasn't an
error, but a clean catch and tag by the steady Sox catcher would
have preserved the Boston lead.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill followed with a sharp roller to the left side, an
easy play for Garciaparra, but the All-Star watched it hit the heel
of his glove and pop high over his head. Error No. 3 for the Sox.
But it was not costly, as Derek Lowe pitched out of the inning
without further trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Another bit of questionable fielding had earlier nearly cost the
Sox dearly. With two outs in the fourth, Brosius looped a fly down
the right-field line and a charging Nixon attempted a shoe-string
catch. The ball landed just inside the foul line, just as Nixon
landed in a belly slide, and the ball rolled past him down the
line. Had it not been for a heads-up Offerman, who chased the ball
down from second base, Brosius would have wheeled around for an
inside-the-park homer. But Brosius had to pull up with a triple,
and Lowe tiptoed by Knoblauch (walk) and Jeter (roller to third) to
get out of trouble.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
