<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 02:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6468 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-UMPIRE-BOS &LR;      10-14 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-UMPIRE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMPIRE SAYS HE DROPPED THE BALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a night full of errors, one of the more costly
miscues came at second base.
</P>
<P>
   The official scoring on the play should read: Error, umpire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he had possession of the baseball before he dropped
the ball,'' explained veteran umpire Rick Reed, who botched a key
call in the top of 10th inning, calling Jose Offerman out on a
force play when Yankee second baseman Chuck Knoblauch clearly
dropped the throw from third baseman Scott Brosius. ``According to
the replay, it was not that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an umpire, it is my job to get it right. I didn't get it
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed's botched call came with the Red Sox and Yankees tied, 3-3,
leaving the Sox with a runner at first base (John Valentin) and one
out. Moments later, Brian Daubach bounced back to Mariano Rivera,
who fired to Derek Jeter covering second to start a 1-6-3 double
play.
</P>
<P>
   Then, two pitches into the bottom of the inning, the game ended
on a Bernie Williams homer. The Sox were left to wonder what might
have happened had Reed made the right call and the rally was
extended. For instance, if Daubach had sacrificed the runners up a
base, Nomar Garciaparra would have come to the plate with one out
and two runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, an umpire for 16 years, blamed himself on two fronts.
First, he said, he was anticipating a double-play attempt and
therefore tried to put himself in a better angle. In repositioning
himself slightly, he compromised his angle. And then, adding to his
own predicament, he anticipated the out call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Umpiring is angles and timing,'' said Reed. ``I didn't know if
they were going to make a double play, and I tried to get a better
angle so I could at least see the base runner _ which is Offerman _
sliding into the bag. In doing so, I lost the angle. If I probably
had not made the move that I did, I probably would have had a
better angle. The last thing you want to do as an umpire is
anticipate a play and have quick timing, and that's obviously what
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed waited some 25 minutes after the game before addressing the
media. He used the time, in part, to review the replay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel good about it,'' he said. ``You know, it's our
job to get the thing right, and when you don't you feel bad about
it. You take it home with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, Reed no doubt will hear from the Fenway Park
faithful, especially if the Sox come home with an 0-2 deficit.
Without a World Series win since 1918, the Boston crowd is ornery
enough without feeling that the umpires are aiding and abetting the
Yankee cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they don't decide to take 81 years of frustration out
on a call at second,'' said Reed, asked about the prospect of
facing the Boston boo-birds. ``Even though it was important at the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Yankee clubhouse, Knoblauch dodged the media, a clubhouse
attendant eventually bringing him his clothes in a room not
accessible to the print or electronic media.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman, although he was sliding on the play, said he got a
good look how it unfolded. ``He never got control of the ball,'' he
said. ``It's part of the game. Anything can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Offerman said he told Reed that Knoblauch didn't catch the ball
and told the same to Sox skipper Jimy Williams, who came out to
argue the call briefly.
</P>
<P>
   The play was eerily reminiscent of the 1975 World Series, when
Cincinnati's Ed Armbrister interfered with Carlton Fisk. That call,
too, went against the Sox, though the replay clearly showed that
Armbrister impeded Fisk's ability to handle his bunted ball.
</P>
<P>
   Reed may have been slow to emerge from the umps' room and face
the media, but he didn't hide the truth. He blew the call, as the
videotape made clear, and he made no attempt to cover up his fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt bad _ awful,'' he said. ``That's how you are supposed
to feel if you are an umpire. You are supposed to feel awful if you
miss things that you are expected to get right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
