<HEADER>
A6469 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKEES-WILLIAMS-     10-14 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-WILLIAMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS APPLIES FINISHING TOUCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He didn't think it was a home run. Bernie Williams
figured he'd be legging out a double, sliding, getting his uniform
filthy, setting the table for Chili Davis or whomever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it was going to be gone,'' Williams said after
his leadoff blast to center off Rod Beck in the 10th inning had
kayoed the Red Sox, 4-3, in the opening game of the American League
Championship Series Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night at Yankee Stadium. ``He
(center fielder Darren Lewis) had his back to me, and I figured he
would play the ball off the wall. I was so surprised. It was
unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Bucky Dent was surprised, too. He never figured that his wedge
shot would find the Fenway screen and win the 1978 playoff. So it
goes, this ancient curse, and this time it comes with a twist:
Williams could very well have been wearing carmine hose instead of
pinstripes Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox had wooed him after Mo Vaughn departed for mo' money
in Anaheim, and Williams had been tempted. ``I would say I was very
close,'' he said. ``We had a lot of conversations between my agent
and Mr. Duquette and Mr. (Jimy) Williams. I have nothing but good
things to say about them. But I guess I'm glad I'm here.''
</P>
<P>
   He had been here, in the same spot, three years ago. Game 1 of
the ALCS against the Orioles in the Stadium, and Williams cranked a
homer in the 11th to win it. Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night, as the game dragged
on and the rain fell and the pitchers came and went, Williams began
dreaming about a reprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all I was thinking about the inning before,'' he said.
``Paul O'Neill grounded out, and it was exactly the same situation
I had in the ALCS. Different pitcher, different team, but the same
setup. What are the chances of it happening twice? Not too much, I
think.''
</P>
<P>
   When Williams stepped in to face Beck, who'd just come in for
Rheal Cormier, he wasn't planning on ending the game with one blow.
Fantasizing, perhaps, but not planning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to get a good at-bat,'' Williams said. ``Just get
on base. I'm the first guy, starting off an inning, and there are
so many great guys hitting behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   But only one of them had done anything. Scott Brosius, the No. 9
hitter, had homered, tripled, and singled. Davis was 0 for 4 and
had fanned to end the seventh. Tino Martinez was 0 for 4 and had
struck out looking in the eighth. It was around midnight. If
Williams didn't step up, they might be serving bacon and eggs in
the dugouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the game was going,'' mused New York manager Joe
Torre, ``it looked like one of those 14-15-inning things.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had just gotten a huge break in the top of the 10th
when second baseman Chuck Knoblauch had dropped an easy forceout
toss but been awarded a putout by umpire Rick Reed that helped
choke off Boston's last gasp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying so hard to capitalize,'' Williams said. ``We
had a few men on base and a lot of opportunities to score, and we
just didn't do it. If it took a break like that to get us going, it
is welcomed.''
</P>
<P>
   So Willliams figured there was no point in waiting for someone
else to step up. He was the cleanup hitter, the man whose job is to
end an evening with one swing. Beck threw him an inside fastball,
and Williams looked at it for a strike. When Beck threw him
another, Williams lashed it to dead center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to stay inside the ball and hit it in a good part of
the bat and get my hips into it,'' he said. ``And it went out.''
</P>
<P>
   Unbelievable? All too believable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
