<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS PREMIERE RIVALS ALL THAT CAME BEFORE 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Advantage, Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Again.
</P>
<P>
   Six more of these might put New England into emotional
overdrive. Maybe it would be like too much cookie dough.
</P>
<P>
   One minute before the stroke of midnight Wednesday, in the
bottom of the 10th inning, Bernie Williams crunched Rod Beck's
second pitch, sending it over the wall in center to give the mighty
world champions a 4-3 victory over the Red Sox in the first game of
hardball's holy war.
</P>
<P>
   This being Red Sox-Yankees, naturally there was a controversial
call right before the defining moment. And, naturally, it went
against the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   In the top of the 10th, Boston had Jose Offerman on first with
no outs when John Valentin hit a hard grounder to third. Scott
Brosius fired the ball to second to force Offerman but the throw
hit Chuck Knoblauch's glove and bounced out. However, umpire Rick
Reed ruled Offerman out, claiming Knoblauch dropped the ball while
transferring it to his throwing hand. Brian Daubach, the Sox' next
batter, grounded into an inning-ending double play.
</P>
<P>
   Before you could say ``Larry Barnett,'' Williams was rounding
the bases, Beck was making that long, lonely walk to the dugout,
and delirious Yankee fans were waving banners taunting the Sox
about the Curse of You Know Who.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, he didn't have possession,'' said Sox manager Jimy
Williams. ``You've got to have some kind of possession of the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   If they're all like this, it might be too much.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox-Yankees. Side by side for an entire century and 1,832
regular-season games _ eyeballing one another from 200 miles on
opposite ends of Connecticut _ this was their first postseason
meeting. They get to play at least three more of these games. Maybe
six.
</P>
<P>
   Six more. That would be too good. Just try to imagine Pedro
Martinez vs. Roger Clemens in a Game 7 at Yankee Stadium for the
right to represent the American League in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the USAir/Delta shuttle series is inciting debate in
dormitories, brokerage houses, and law offices throughout New
England and New York. There was certainly plenty of energy in the
Bronx. It was not a night to be sporting Boston Red Sox garb. Only
fools rush into Yankee Stadium wearing Sox caps.
</P>
<P>
   It was a late-arriving crowd. Probably there is just too much to
do these days if you are a New York baseball fan. The Mets' playoff
game against the Braves was on television during the afternoon, and
fans who hung till the finish might have gotten stuck in traffic en
route to the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Jimy Williams said before the game he still had his lucky Baby
Ruth candy bar. The candy was on his desk for all three games of
the Sox' September sweep in Yankee Stadium and has been with him
ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The most spontaneous pregame roar came when the megaboard in
center flashed the image of Bucky Dent's 1978 pop fly homer off
Mike Torrez. The Sox had to sit through the entire video, which
also featured Dave Righetti's no-hitter against the Red Sox and
Wade Boggs riding a horse after the Yankees won in '96.
</P>
<P>
   The first game of Apocalypse Now was not particularly
well-played. Nomar Garciaparra made two spectacular leaping,
run-saving catches, then made two errors. The Sox had three errors
on the night.
</P>
<P>
   Boston led, 3-0, in the second, but Brosius homered in the
bottom of the inning, inspiring the first ``Boston Sucks'' chants.
An inning later, Bryce Florie was warming up in the Boston bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Yankee starter Orlando Hernandez settled down nicely and lasted
eight innings before yielding to Mariano Rivera. Red Sox starter
Kent Mercker yielded to Rich Garces, who gave way to Derek Lowe,
who handed the ball to Virtual Rheal Cormier. Rod Beck came on in
the 10th. For two pitches. And one loss.
</P>
<P>
   No one said this was going to be easy, but the Red Sox did what
Jimy promised they would do in the first game against the mighty
Yanks. They competed. They made Yankee Stadium quiet a few times.
This is what the Yankees too often have been able to do in Boston.
They've been able to make scared Red Sox fans sit on their hands
and wait for something bad to happen. Not now. It will not be quiet
at Fenway Saturday when Pedro and Roger match up for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   One down. Three, four, five, or six more left. The Sox go at 'em
with Brothers Martinez Thursday night and Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
