<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS FORCES ISSUE ON CALL 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ANALYSIS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jimy Williams is a guy with a high boiling point, but
his patience was severely tested Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   His anger was fueled mainly by a 10th-inning call by second-base
umpire Rick Reed. Jose Offerman, who led off with a single, was
called out at second on John Valentin's grounder to third, even
though Yankees second baseman Chuck Knoblauch dropped the ball on
the force play.
</P>
<P>
   But was it a putout? From Williams's view, the ball was never in
Knoblauch's glove and he never had possession. Reed ruled that the
runner was out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't go out (to argue) very often,'' said the Red Sox
skipper, clearly disgusted by the call. ``But it seems like the
rule is that if it hits the glove, you're out. But in my mind, you
have got to have possession of the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   After three straight postseason victories, the Red Sox finally
tasted defeat in a 4-3 loss to the defending world champion Yankees
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night. The winning homer by Bernie Williams brought a
quick ending in the bottom of the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   Yankee manager Joe Torre said he was surprised by how fast the
game turned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bernie is unpredictable,'' said Torre. ``He comes up large
sometimes, most of the time. I think the thing that surprised me
was that it was so quick. Two pitches, bang! and it was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the game was going, it looked like one of those
14-15-inning games. I wasn't sure the (home run) ball was out until
I looked at (center fielder) Darren Lewis and he had his back
turned. At that point I sensed the game was over.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a repeat of a game-winning homer by the Yankee center
fielder, who gave New York a 5-4 victory over Baltimore in the 1996
American League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   Jimy Williams had some other problems with the way the game was
played. Three errors, two by Nomar Garciaparra, deflated the
defensive confidence the Red Sox had showed in beating Cleveland in
the Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens,'' said Williams of Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night's misgivings.
``First, you tip a cap to their pitching. We had opportunities and
there were some good plays out there. But we made some errors that
hurt us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about it during the season. If you get some of those
base hits with men on base and two out, it helps you win
ballgames.''
</P>
<P>
   Starter Kent Mercker did his job, as did relievers Rich Garces
and Rheal Cormier. But not so with Derek Lowe and Rod Beck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mercker gave us 12 outs and they only scored two runs,'' said
Williams. ``That's a commendable job. Beck was in there because he
does a pretty good job against lefthanders. He tried to place his
pitch to Bernie. It just didn't work. But I believe in the guy and
the decision to bring him in.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercker was given a 3-0 lead in the first two innings, only to
give up a two-run homer to Scott Brosius in the home half of the
second.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee third baseman later scored the tying run in the
seventh inning on Derek Jeter's single. Lowe, the usually steady
Red Sox reliever, was the victim. The throw home by right fielder
Trot Nixon beat Brosius to the plate, but catcher Jason Varitek
couldn't handle the throw, and Brosius scored on a collision at
home plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be perfectly honest, I didn't think there would be a play
at the plate,'' Torre said. ``You have to give credit to Nixon, who
made a good throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know until I saw the replay on the scoreboard that
Varitek dropped the ball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
