<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEIGHT OF HISTORY TOO MUCH FOR GARCIAPARRA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Part of the reason some believe Nomar Garciaparra can
lead the Red Sox to baseball's Promised Land is that Garciaparra
does not believe.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't believe that the Red Sox are cursed.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't buy into the notion of a franchise snakebit by
decades of bad luck and horrific plot twists and tormented fans.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra never did accept the folklore that said it was the
gods, the fates and the furies denying the Red Sox a fair shot at
baseball immortality.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, in Game 1 of the American League Championship
Series, Garciaparra seemed bent on writing a new script for his
forlorn franchise.
</P>
<P>
   It started in the first inning, in the province of the Red Sox's
dreaded rival, just moments after Garciaparra's Yankee counterpart,
Derek Jeter, committed an error that opened the door to a 2-0
Boston lead.
</P>
<P>
   Lean, focused and spring-coiled like a rattler, the Red Sox's
best player levitated off the infield dirt at Yankee Stadium to rob
designated hitter Chili Davis of a hit.
</P>
<P>
   With a better vertical leap than some NBA players, Garciaparra
soared to snag Davis' screamer, saving at least one run, possibly
two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how high I can jump,'' Garciaparra said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless they try to hit them higher, I won't know. As long as
it's high enough to go get the ball, that's good enough.''
</P>
<P>
   But in those brilliant early moments, one got the feeling
Garciaparra was going to do what he was created to do _ upend the
Yanks and history, too.
</P>
<P>
   Then he did it again in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Playing like the best shortstop in the game, Garciaparra went
high to rob another Yankees hitter, this time Tino Martinez, ending
another inning with two runners stranded.
</P>
<P>
   Everything felt right. One sensed a long overdue reprieve for
the Sox, perhaps an end to 80 years of pain and suffering, of Bucky
Dent home runs and Bill Buckner blunders and assorted indignities
that millions of New Englanders have yet to recover from.
</P>
<P>
   But alas, for Garciaparra and the Sox, the crusade to crush the
so-called curse was temporarily postponed.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, defending World Champions and owners of 24 World
Series titles, got the huge benefit of a bad call last night.
</P>
<P>
   In the top of the 10th, second-base umpire Rick Reed called
Boston baserunner Jose Offerman out, even though Yankees second
baseman Chuck Knoblauch bobbled the ball and never had possession
on a potential double-play feed from Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox went quietly after that, never giving Garciaparra and
the heart of the Boston order another opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed the good omens of a quick start transmuted into more
bad karma for the Red Sox, unless you're Garciaparra, who refuses
to buy into any of that.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the 10th, it was Bernie Williams _ the Yankee
who nearly moved to Boston in free agency _ who hit the second
pitch from reliever Rod Beck over the wall in straightaway center,
securing a 4-3 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Now was the Curse of the Bambino back to haunt the Sox?
</P>
<P>
   Not if you ask Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't say that's the difference in the game,'' he said of
the kicked call at second base. ``They're going out there and doing
their job as best they can. I didn't see the play, but I'm sure he
made the right call.''
</P>
<P>
   That comment came just as Reed admitted to reporters that he had
indeed blown the call, leaving the ump feeling ``awful.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the new Red Sox mindset that there are no supernatural
elements influencing the outcome, Garciaparra refused to blame the
loss on the ump's call or anything else. That's just the way the
ball bounced.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nothing to hang our heads about,'' Garciaparra said,
smiling for the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either way, it's a good game when you go into extra innings
like that. Everybody did their job. It was a battle either way. Now
we just come back out (tonight) and play again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not happy with the loss, without a doubt. But am I going
to walk home with my head down? No, not at all. We've still got a
lot of baseball left. We've been in this position before. This is
nothing new.''
</P>
<P>
   Alluding to the American League Division Series, Garciaparra
made light of the fact that the Sox had their backs to the wall
against Cleveland, only to come back to win the series and a chance
to play the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that come-from-behind scenario is what made it easy for
Garciaparra to suggest that the best of the Red Sox is yet to come,
no matter how much everyone is stuck on counting them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we're down 0-1, but that's not where we want them.
(We'll be in good shape being) down 0-2,'' Garciaparra said
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, nothing is going to spook these Red Sox into
believing uncontrollable forces are against them. Not this time. No
matter what.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011 or
lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
