<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 02:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6474 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-BECK-BOS &LR;      10-14 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BECK WAS BRIEF IN HIS RELIEF 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-BECK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jason Varitek saw the pitch that Rod Beck threw and
almost winced. The fastball was sliding back over the plate ``and
Bernie (Williams) knows what to do when he gets a mistake,'' said
the Red Sox catcher.
</P>
<P>
   It was only Rod Beck's second pitch of the 10th inning but
Beck's first pitch, almost an exact precursor of the one to follow,
was also fat, a ball over the middle of the plate. But Williams
didn't swing at the first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a fastball, fastball inside,'' said Beck, who seemed to
get away with a near-death experience when New York's Williams
didn't swing at the first pitch. ``I wanted to repeat the same
pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   So Beck thought his first pitch had been good ``and I got the
first one in there, and it was a real good pitch, right on the
black (of the corner), and I felt I had the release point on that.
And I was going right back in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Rod Beck is a veteran reliever, with a thick hide and a short
memory, but Beck has seen enough extra-inning games to know ``games
like this are won by home runs a lot. Unfortunately, I threw the
pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   And it was a terrible pitch. ``It started out on the inside and
then it came back over the middle,'' he said. ``It was a bad time
for a bad pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   It's still unknown if Beck can be the closer he was with the
Giants and Cubs. Arm surgery has cut back his velocity and it's
just as unknown if Red Sox manager Jimy Williams might save Derek
Lowe for the closer's role the next time; but Lowe had to be used
as a set-up man Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night, and he gave up the tying run in
the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   And that time, too, Varitek had the perfect view of a ball that
just moved the wrong way at the last instant. That time the ball
was coming from the arm of right fielder Trot Nixon, whose perfect
throw beat the Yankees' Scott Brosius to the plate by several feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was blocking the plate, and I had nowhere to go but to go
over him,'' said Brosius. Which he did, bowling over Varitek an
instant after Nixon's throw arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon's throw had started up the line, said Varitek, ``and it
had a little tail on it. Then it skipped on the grass and . . .
well, it handcuffed me. So I never had a handle on it and therefore
I didn't catch it.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt he would have tagged Brosius out, said Varitek, if the
ball hadn't skipped on the wet infield grass.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball came in and I took it off the base of my glove, the
heel of my glove, and I never caught the ball before impact and the
impact didn't knock it out,'' said Varitek. ``If I would have
caught it, I would have held onto the ball and he would have been
out.''
</P>
<P>
   So the game was tied at 3-3, bringing the teams to the climactic
10th. In the Boston's half, Jose Offerman was called out at second
even though second baseman Chuck Knoblauch apparently never caught
the ball before attempting to wheel toward first and complete a
double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even on replay, he didn't even come close to catching the
ball,'' said Varitek. But the Red Sox catcher is ever the realist
and added, ``You can't ever say what would have happened after
that. Regardless, Bernie hit that homer.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rod Beck, he of the thick hide and short memory, vowed he
will forget about it quickly. ``I've been around way too long to
worry about something like that,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
