<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-CONE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORRE FINALLY TURNS TO CONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He hasn't thrown a pitch judged by an umpire in 10
days. David Cone is more tanned, rested, and ready than Richard
Nixon ever was. He may even have cobwebs hanging from his right
arm.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees rubbed out the Rangers so quickly in their Division
Series last week that Cone never got to take the mound. Thursday
night _ finally _ he gets the call and the ball in the second game
of the American League Championship Series against the Red Sox
here. Will he be loose and limber? Or stiffer than the Tin Man?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather be well-rested than the converse, coming in a
little tired, maybe a little hurt,'' says Cone, who hasn't appeared
in a game since he beat Tampa Bay, 3-2, Oct. 2. ``The last time I
had this much rest was during the All-Star break. Then I came out
and pitched a perfect game.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone has been decidedly imperfect since he zeroed out the Expos
July 18, going 2-5 with a 4.82 ERA in 13 starts. ``I've thought
about that a lot during the last six weeks,'' he says. ``After the
perfect game, I was so guarded because I didn't want it to affect
me. Especially for my next start.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone's next start, against the Indians, was harrowing. He
allowed six runs on six hits in four innings, walked four, threw a
wild pitch, and served up a grand slam to Robbie Alomar.
</P>
<P>
   That sent him into a downward spiral that bottomed out with a
winless streak that stretched across eight starts from mid-August
to late September, the longest of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I ever stopped and enjoyed the perfect game,''
Cone concluded. ``I only watched it once. I should have savored it
a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   Given his woes down the stretch, Cone wasn't upset when he
wasn't penciled into the rotation against Texas. And given New
York's starting depth, he knew he might get the ball only once
against Boston. ``If he (manager Joe Torre) wanted to just plug me
into Game 4, I was prepared to deal with that,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But Torre wasn't about to put a man on light duty who's pitched
in nine postseason games and had four World Series starts. So he's
scheduled Cone both for Thursday night and for Monday's Game 5 in
Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing I always know I'm going to get from David Cone
is the effort,'' Torre says. ``He may not have his sharpness, may
not have his good fastball, but he finds ways to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   By now, Cone has had enough time to savor his afternoon of
perfection, deconstruct his slump, catch up on his correspondence,
and even compose an operetta if he cared to. Some wars don't last
10 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times during the second half of the season when I
did have some doubts, but I'm eager to pitch,'' Cone says. ``I've
been in this position a lot. I relish the opportunity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
