<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMON MARTINEZ NICE SURPRISE PACKAGE FOR RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-R. MARTINEZ-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Red Sox team physician Arthur Pappas had to ponder
long and hard about which Martinez brother surprised him more:
Pedro, who pitched six no-hit innings Monday against Cleveland when
virtually no one _ including Pappas _ thought he could go more than
two innings, or Ramon, who underwent shoulder surgery 16 months
ago?
</P>
<P>
   ``Both surprised me,'' said Pappas, replying diplomatically.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox were confident when they signed Ramon Martinez March
11 that the 31-year-old righthander would pitch this season. Only
not here, not in the majors, and certainly not in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   But Ramon Martinez will take the mound Thursday night, just as
he took the mound Saturday afternoon at Fenway Park, his Red Sox
down 0-2 to the Indians. Martinez kept the Indians at bay that
afternoon until an offensive explosion revived the Red Sox' hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five days ago, we were in Fenway Park and it was a very tight
game because we were 0-2,'' said Ramon. ``(Now) I got that in my
mind and I think a lot about that game and (how we) got the chance
to get back in and win the last three games. This time I hope
everything goes the same way.''
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing he can say about the Yankee lineup, he went on,
``because I haven't faced them before. But I did watch (the
Yankees) many times.''
</P>
<P>
   New York, of course, also has never faced Martinez. Sox manager
Jimy Williams was forced to call on him late in the regular season
when he was short a starter. Since then, Martinez has flourished
and now is Williams's second choice.
</P>
<P>
   If it weren't for that fate, Martinez probably would not be on
the Red Sox' postseason roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I understood it,'' said the righthander, ``and I tell Jimy
that if I have any chance that I can get into games, to get that
chance, and that is what happened. So they give me that chance and
here I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Few who follow Boston baseball don't know the differences
between Pedro and Ramon, that Ramon has the quiet bearing of the
Dominican Republic's delegate to the United States while Pedro, 28,
is the seldom-silent cutup and chatterbox.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a little different,'' said Ramon. ``I mean, I don't
know . . . I am a little (more) quiet than him and he can talk a
little more than I do. He is a big competitor as well as me . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Ramon's story is well-known in Boston. He rehabilitated from
shoulder surgery 16 months ago and pitched in five leagues this
season (Gulf Coast, Florida State, Eastern, International, and
American).
</P>
<P>
   Many a time Ramon thought of quitting, and either his brother's
words or his own resolve kept him going. ``When I start my rehab,
when I start my throwing, that was the hardest part because there
was a lot of pain, sore days where I say, `I probably am not going
to make it,' '' Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of (soreness), but I never stopped, I never
give up. I mean, I am pretty much well right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Martinez thinks he is much the same pitcher who had been
the ace of the Dodgers' organization before his surgery. Martinez
said he doesn't really sense any difference between the pitcher he
was then and the pitcher he is now, except perhaps for his
velocity.
</P>
<P>
   ``But everything else is here,'' he said. ``I don't have any
problem with my arm. I can throw all my pitches. And I feel better
and better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
