<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 03:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6478 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-CANCER-RACIAL-SFCHRON     10-14 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-RACIAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 STUDY FINDS RACIAL DIVIDE IN LUNG CANCER TREATMENT  &HT;     By CARL T. HALL 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Black patients in the early stages of lung cancer are less
likely to have surgery than white patients with the same diagnosis,
and as a result are more likely to die of the disease, a new study
has found.
</P>
<P>
   In a nationwide look at how race influences medical care,
researchers at Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in New York
found a disturbing pattern of substandard treatment for African
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The study focused on Medicare patients and others over the age
of 65 with comparable medical circumstances. The researchers also
tried to take such factors as income and gender into account.
</P>
<P>
   The results, published in Thursday's New England Journal of
Medicine, show that only 64 percent of the black patients had
surgery, compared with 77 percent of the white patients.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks and whites who chose surgery had essentially the same
survival rates. But because so few black patients had the
procedure, their overall survival worked out to be substantially
below that of white patients.
</P>
<P>
   For every 1,000 black patients, 264 were still alive five years
after diagnosis (including those who had surgery and those who did
not), versus 341 of every 1,000 white patients. If the black
patients had received surgery at the same relative rate as their
white counterparts, the researchers estimated that 308 per 1,000
black patients would have survived.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were all patients with potentially curable lung cancer,
and all of them had insurance that would cover the procedure,''
said Dr. Peter Bach of Memorial Sloan-Kettering, lead author of the
new study.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is clear,'' he added. ``We need to understand
better what's happening in that interaction between doctors and
patients that leads to some patients having surgery less often than
other patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Previous studies also have found evidence of subtle racial
biases in the health care system, causing doctors to order less
elaborate diagnostic workups or otherwise treat minorities less
intensively than white patients.
</P>
<P>
   The new study went one step further by examining a relatively
straightforward medical circumstance in which surgery is the clear
option of choice.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers did not attempt to explain just why black
patients were less likely than their white counterparts to have the
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear, for example, whether doctors recommended surgery
and patients declined, or whether the physicians failed to
adequately explain the options. Nor did the researchers look at
what happens in cases where the patient and doctor are of the same
race.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Harold Freeman, an African American surgical oncologist who
serves as president of North General Hospital in New York, said
communication problems between black patients and white doctors may
explain part of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is: What assumptions do you make about someone of
a different race, and how are you communicating with the person?''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In an editorial accompanying the study, specialists at the
University of California at San Francisco said the study has
disturbing implications for health care providers.
</P>
<P>
   Results point to ``a difference in how physicians manage cancer
that is based on a patient's race, regardless of other attributes,
and that the consequence of these lapses in care is reduced
survival among blacks,'' wrote UCSF physicians Talmadge King and
Paul Brunetta.
</P>
<P>
   The study looked at nearly 11,000 patients nationwide, including
860 blacks and 10,124 classified as non-Hispanic white. All were
over the age of 65 and were being treated in one of 10 urban areas,
including San Francisco, in which health authorities operate a
detailed surveillance program known as SEER. Patient outcomes and
diagnoses also were cross-checked against Medicare records.
</P>
<P>
   All the patients had been formally diagnosed with operable,
non-small-cell lung cancer during the 1985 to 1993 study period.
Medical experts are nearly unanimous that surgery is the preferred
option for such patients.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that race could go a long way toward explaining
why the national five-year survival rate from lung cancer is only
11 percent among blacks, compared with 14 percent among whites.
Lung cancer is the deadliest form of malignancy in the United
States, killing more people than cancer of the breast, colon,
prostate and cervix combined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evidence that bias on the part of physicians (either overt
prejudice or subconscious perceptions) influences access to optimal
cancer care is disheartening,'' they concluded.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Feelings of Exclusion
</P>
<P>
   Earlier studies comparing black patients with white patients
have found the black patients more likely to feel excluded from
decisions, which could add to communication problems and feelings
of mistrust.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Brunetta also said that the new study may not
have fully accounted for differences in income and education levels
between the black and white patients, which could at least partly
account for the apparent differences in medical decisions.
</P>
<P>
   These adjustments were made largely on the basis of the median
income for the population residing within each patient's zip code
area. Researchers found essentially the same racial discrepancies
regardless of where the patients lived.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the racial aspects, Brunetta noted that a large number of
cases, 35.4 percent of the total, had to be excluded from the study
because of inadequate documentation of the tumor stage at
diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   That underscored the need for better efforts to identify
patients early on while cancer can still be cured, he said, noting
that patients diagnosed at the early stage have an overall survival
rate of 40 percent after five years, while those diagnosed too
late, or who do not have surgery, typically die within a year.
</P>
<P>
   Lung cancer of all types is the cause of about 150,000 deaths
annually in the United States. Only about one-third of those with
the most common form of the disease are diagnosed at the
potentially curable stage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
