<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 03:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6479 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-ADVICE-ADVICE_SFCHRON     10-14 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADVICE-ADVICE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Let Your Fingers Do the Asking  
 By Tom Stein 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Looking to put the spark back in your marriage? Or cure your
dachshund of separation anxiety? Or fix a leaky faucet?
<P>
   Maybe it's time to consider the Internet for help.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's what Net entrepreneur Courtney Rosen thought. An
avid Rollerblader, she fired up her computer one night and scanned
the Web for instructions on how to rotate the wheels on her inline
skates. It took four weeks of fruitless surfing before she finally
found the answer.
</P>
<P>
   So she decided to create a site where people could learn
everything from ``How to use chopsticks'' to ``How to celebrate New
Year's Eve the Filipino way.'' In August, she launched San
Francisco-based eHow.com, which features original step-by-step
instructions on more than 10,000 possible ``how-tos.'' The advice
is written by a team of 100 full-time and free-lance editors. The
site also accepts contributions from visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my case, starting the site was a better solution than
having to flirt with the store clerk to get him to rotate my skate
wheels for me,'' Rosen said.
</P>
<P>
   EHow is at the forefront of an emerging trend on the Web: expert
sites that put specific answers to direct questions at your
fingertips.
</P>
<P>
   Most sites, like eHow, offer prewritten advice on a range of
topics. Those sites are free. Their revenue model is: After they
tell you how to do something, they try to sell you the tools to do
it.
</P>
<P>
   Other sites, which usually charge a fee, connect so-called
e-seekers with live experts who can give them personalized advice,
whether it be romantic, financial, medical or career related.
</P>
<P>
   Companies with names like Exp.com, ExpertCentral.com, About.com,
How2hq.com and Ithority.com are appearing from the ether on a
seemingly daily basis to address the need. Many of them are heavily
funded by big-name venture capitalists who think they have hit on
the next big cyber-thing.
</P>
<P>
   The rationale for the free how-to sites goes something like
this: When the Web first gained popularity in the mid-90s, it was
all about pure content, with news sites like CNN.com garnering the
most eyeballs. A few years later, there was a dramatic shift to
e-commerce sites, with the likes of eBay and Amazon.com. The next
wave, according to some people, is the melding of these two
concepts through what they are calling contextual commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Type in ``How to fly a kite'' on the eHow site, for instance,
and along with kite-flying instructions, you'll find a shopping
list that links you to e-commerce sites that sell kites, kite
string, strips of cloth for the kite tail and even picnic baskets,
assuming you'll want to pack a lunch for a day of kite flying in
the park. eHow gets anywhere from a 5 percent to 25 percent cut of
all sales it drives to e-commerce sites.
</P>
<P>
   Other sites, like ExpertCentral, Exp.com and Ithority, make
money by acting as matchmakers and hooking up e-seekers with the
appropriate expert. The companies boast thousands of experts on
their sites who dispense advice on everything from pets to
parenting. So if an e-seeker pays an expert $100 for, say, tips on
preventing sweaty feet, the site itself may receive a $20 cut as
the middleman.
</P>
<P>
   Putting a twist on the eBay model, some of these sites allow
e-seekers to list the amount they are willing to pay for counsel
and then have experts bid on their business _ a reverse auction for
advice.
</P>
<P>
   The big question is whether people are willing to pay for advice
online.
</P>
<P>
   Deb Levine, a sexuality and relationship expert who doles out
wisdom on Exp.com, said she has found three new paying clients by
listing her services on the site about a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``One guy wanted to spice up a long-term relationship with his
wife,'' said the San Francisco resident. Through an e-mail
exchange, Levine asked probing questions about his particular
situation and then, for 50 bucks, recommended an action plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He e-mailed back a few days later and said the advice worked
like a charm,'' she said contentedly.
</P>
<P>
   Some people like the fact that the Internet allows them to
remain anonymous when seeking help for sensitive problems. But
others just don't feel comfortable getting advice via their
computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take a sociological metamorphosis before these sites
really take off,'' said Martin Debono, an analyst with Internet
consulting firm Gomez Advisors. ``I think there is an inherent
mistrust of anything technological, plus people are so used to
dealing with advice issues face to face.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Belforte, a 26-year-old San Francisco saleswoman, echoes
these concerns. She recently went on the Net in search of
information about ``which foods I could eat without getting fat.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she did pull up some good information, but was confused
about what was factual and what was not. ``There are so many random
people with their own Web pages these days, you could probably find
someone who says drinking gas makes you healthy,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She added that she would be even more reluctant to pay for
advice on the Web, since anyone could claim to be an expert on
anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the last thing we want on our site is a 12-year-old
giving out tax advice,'' acknowledged Mark Benning, chief executive
of Exp.com in Menlo Park.
</P>
<P>
   Benning said that every expert listed on his site is carefully
vetted by a investigation service that verifies the expert's
employment history. Moreover, advice sites let customers rate the
experts online and provide feedback about their experiences. The
idea is that certain experts will establish good reputations and
thus get loads of referrals.
</P>
<P>
   Exp.com and other expert sites are banking on the old proverb:
You get what you pay for.
</P>
<P>
   Experts and advice seekers can conduct their sessions via
e-mail, or, if they reside in the same city, they can agree to meet
face to face. Benning said that Exp.com is working on adding
instant messaging technology to its site, as well as
video-conferencing capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   One expert site that has been around for a couple years and does
not charge a dime is About.com in New York City. It makes money
through e-commerce links.
</P>
<P>
   The site features roughly 650 real-life guides who specialize in
everything from the literature of Mark Twain to the lost art of
quilting. These guides host online forums and chat sessions, write
articles, answer questions and highlight links to other relevant
sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't dare charge for my advice,'' said About.com dating
expert Brenda Ross, who earns a salary from About.com. ``I just
think it's bad karma.''
</P>
<P>
   So why are expert sites exploding on the Web? Courtney Rosen,
for one, argues that, in the past, advice was handed down from
generation to generation. But in today's mobile world, families are
less cohesive and basic skills, like how to boil an egg, often
don't get taught. That creates a real need for sites like hers, she
said. ``Our one true competitor is friends and family,'' said
Rosen.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrell McDonald is a 30-year-old entertainment executive in Los
Angeles who can't get enough of online advice sites.
</P>
<P>
   In the past month, she has learned to cook a Thanksgiving
turkey, make a wedding toast, prune a rosebush and break up a cat
fight on the eHow site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where else do you have the ability to talk to an expert every
day?'' she said. ``And no matter what question you ask, you don't
have to worry about looking like a fool.''
</P>
<P>
   As for breaking up that cat fight? ``Turn a garden hose on
them,'' said McDonald. And wouldn't you know it, eHow linked her
directly to the site selling the hose.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
