 _ SF CHRON  
 ONLINE ADVICE  &HT;     How-to Sites 
 &HT;     By Tom Stein 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; eHow.com: &LR;  A free site that gives people a fast way to find out how
to ask for a raise, treat a cold, raise a baby ... You get the
picture. Received $3.5 million in funding from Hummer Winblad
Venture Partners and Media Technology Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; How2HQ.com: &LR;  Launched in January, the site features four
categories: How 2 Work, How 2 Play, How 2 Home and How 2 Shop and
Save.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Learn2.com: &LR;  A public company that is transforming itself from a
``motley fool'' of life skills instruction, such as how to eat
exotic fruit, into a provider of more than 200 information
technology course offerings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Expert Advice Sites
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; About.com: &LR;  Staffed by 650 expert guides dedicated to helping users
get what they want quickly and easily. Does not charge a fee.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; Expertcity.com: &LR;  Offers screen-sharing technology that allows the
customer and expert to work together as if they were sitting next
to one another in front of a single screen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ExpertCentral.com: &LR;  Features more than 4,500 live experts who offer
advice for a fee. Raised $1 million in venture funding from J. H.
Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Exp.com: &LR;  Site's mission is to be an online marketplace for a wide
range of expert advice and services. In August, it announced
second-round funding of $25 million from Bowman Capital, Maveron
and Oracle Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Inforocket.com: &LR;  An information exchange site where anyone can post
a question and anyone else can bid to answer it for a mutually
agreed-upon price.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Ithority.com: &LR;  Site links people who have questions with people who
have answers. Focuses on career and financial advice.
</P>
