<SLUG> BC-PACBELL-PAC </SLUG>
 BELL _ SF CHRON  
 Disruptions Hit Pac Bell's DSL Service  &HT;     By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Pacific Bell's high-speed Internet service, which is supposed to
provide a fast, always-on connection to the Net, has been plagued
by periodic outages over the past two days, disrupting service to
some Bay Area customers for more than 24 hours.
<P>
   The outage, which began around noon Tuesday, disrupted service
to an undisclosed number of customers from Mountain View to Marin
County, Pac Bell officials said. The company said it was slowly
restoring service and trying to determine what caused the problem.
Officials would not say how many customers had been affected, but
Pac Bell DSL service representatives said yesterday they had been
receiving a steady stream of calls from users.
</P>
<P>
   While the outage was frustrating for residential customers,
several companies that rely on Pac Bell's digital subscriber line
service for Web access and e-mail said the blackout was crippling
for them. Some companies said they lost service for more than 24
hours, paralyzing their ability to do business.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is completely killing us,'' said Brett Adamcq &LR; , who runs
Verve, a software company in San Francisco. ``When our link is
down, we're cut off from the world and that means our customers
can't reach us.''
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell's &LR;  DSL uses existing phone lines to deliver Internet
service at speeds up to 50 times faster than with traditional
modems. It also lets users talk on the phone and surf the Web
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   As more companies start doing business on the Web, speedy,
reliable connections are becoming a necessity. Many small
businesses look to Pac Bell to get them on the Net. The phone
company is one of just one of a handful of companies that offer DSL
service in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Malone, whose software company Eba Systems also relies on
Pac Bell DSL, said the service is as crucial to his firm as the
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   ``DSL is incredibly important to our company,'' said Malone,
whose company is based in South of Market. ``We're losing business
because of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Dainas, a spokesman for Pac Bell, acknowledged there had
been ``intermittent outages'' and said service had already been
restored to some affected customers. Dainas said the company was
working to figure out what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our priority is to fix intermittent disruptions,'' Dainas
said. ``Pac Bell engineers are working to figure out the cause of
the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam, who pays about $200 per month for the highest level of DSL
service, said Pac Bell sold him the technology as a tool for
running his business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the premium service and pay a good amount for it and
it still went down,'' Adam said.
</P>
<P>
   DSL user Charlie Mahoney of San Francisco said his service has
been out for more than 36 hours and interfered with his ability to
make money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rely on it for work and I do a fair amount of investing
online,'' Mahoney said. ``I'm actively tied to the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first glitch to hit Pac Bell's DSL service. The
Internet service has suffered periodic outages in the past, with
customers losing service for several hours at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Pac Bell also ran into problems trying to
install the service after it lowered prices and was deluged with
requests from people who wanted to sign up. &UR;  &LR; Some people were
unable to access the Internet after DSL was installed; others were
told they could get the service but were then told on installation
day that their wiring couldn't accommodate DSL. Others complained
that technicians missed their appointments for installations.
</P>
<P>
   Pac Bell blamed those problems on ``growing pains'' and said the
quality of service would improve.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
