<SLUG> BC-APPLE-APPLE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Apple's Profit Falls for First Time in 2 Years  &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
For the first time since co-founder Steve Jobs regained control of
Apple Computer two years ago, the company yesterday reported a
decline in quarterly profits compared with the same period 12
months before.
<P>
   But the shortfall was not as bad as expected, and it was
accompanied by several pieces of good news. As a result,
after-hours traders pushed Apple shares up almost 7 percent
following the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   The Cupertino computer-maker reported profits from operations of
$90 million (51 cents a share) for its fourth quarter, down 15
percent from last year's net profits of $106 million (68 cents).
Sales for the quarter, which ended September 25, were $1.34
billion, off 14 percent from $1.56 billion in the same period a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Apple had warned on September 20 that its results would fall
below expectations because Motorola, its microprocessor supplier,
couldn't supply enough PowerPC G4 chips to meet demand for
high-end, high-margin Power Mac G4 machines.
</P>
<P>
   Data that Apple provided at the time suggested that earnings per
share could fall between 42 cents and 48 cents, and the consensus
among analysts prior to yesterday's release was that the figure
would be 45 cents. Yet the company did considerably better than
that, even though last month's earthquake in Taiwan caused
additional problems by cutting off power for more than a week at
the plants where Apple's laptops are produced.
</P>
<P>
   Counting several one-time items, profits amounted to $111
million (63 cents).
</P>
<P>
   Among the positive items Apple reported in its earning
announcement and a follow-up conference call with analysts:
</P>
<P>
   _Demand for its products remains strong. At the end of the
quarter, the company had an order backlog of 400,000 units,
amounting to $700 million in unrealized revenue. Orders for the
iBook, a new consumer-oriented laptop that has just begun to reach
customers, have reached 300,000, while orders for enhanced iMac
models announced just last week already total 250,000, according to
Fred Anderson, Apple's chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   _Apple's gross margins climbed to 28.7 percent, up from 26.8
percent a year ago. PC manufacturers generally are considered to be
doing well when their gross margins exceed 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   _Starting in the first half of next year, IBM will begin
manufacturing PowerPC G4 chips, giving Apple a second source
alongside Motorola. The three companies developed the chip
together, but IBM previously had elected not to make G4s even
though it has continued to manufacture the G3, the
previous-generation PowerPC microprocessor.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, though, Apple has reconfigured its G4 lineup to
accommodate the current shortage. A 500-megahertz model, originally
expected to ship in November, has been postponed until next year,
and the company now will offer models with 350-, 400-and
450-megahertz versions of the chips. Prices will correspond to
those previously announced for the 400-, 450- and 500-MHz models.
</P>
<P>
   In the current quarter, Apple's unit volumes and earnings will
both rise ``significantly,'' Anderson predicted, even though gross
margins are likely to decline because of higher holiday marketing
expenses and an industry-wide increase in memory prices.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company expects to catch up with the order backlog
on most of its products during the coming quarter, but iBooks are
likely to remain in short supply. Apple expects to produce between
200,000 and 250,000 of the curvy, colorful notebooks this quarter _
not enough to match even current orders, unless some are canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Kurtis King of Banc of America Securities in San
Francisco said he was pleased but not surprised by the Apple
report. ``Everything negative in it we'd heard before,'' he said,
``and now they're poised to put up some really big numbers in the
December quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Long bearish on Apple's prospects, King recently has turned
positive on the company's stock, at least for the short term. ``A
lot of good news will be coming out of Apple in the next six
months,'' he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   He remains more cautious for the long term, though. ``The jury
is still out on what kind of revenue growth the company can
generate,'' he said, noting that recent growth has been in
comparison to periods when Apple didn't have a complete product
line.
</P>
<P>
   In after-hours trading, Apple's shares rose as high as $68.44.
Earlier, it had closed at $64.03, down $3.65 for the day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
