<SLUG> BC-LEFTFIELD-LEFT </SLUG>
 FIELD _ SF CHRON  
 Differences Cause Left Field Ad Agency to Split Up  &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Left Field LLC, a San Francisco advertising shop specializing in
technology clients, is splitting into two new agencies due to
disagreements between its partners.
<P>
   Fred Schwartz and Kevin Burke, two of the three managing
partners, bought the equity interest of the third partner, Michael
McMahon, who started Left Field three years ago. Each of the two
groups will form a new agency; neither will use the name Left
Field.
</P>
<P>
   The split occurred, in part, because Schwartz and Burke were
more interested in being acquired than McMahon, the three partners
said in separate interviews yesterday. Many independent ad agency
partners these days are reaping windfalls by selling stakes to a
larger agency or conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   Burke and Schwartz also wanted to put more emphasis on
conventional media, as opposed to McMahon's specialty _ online
advertising, they said. But McMahon said he, too, wanted to beef up
the agency's offline business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like any partnership, sometimes you have people who skew
in different directions,'' said Burke. ``We just (concluded) that
the way we were approaching the business was different enough that
it didn't make sense for us to work together any longer.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority of Left Field's clients already have signed up with
Burke and Schwartz, the two executives said. Those clients, which
include Sun Microsystems, Macys.com, ImproveNet and Visto,
represent 70 to 75 percent of Left Field's revenues, according to
Burke.
</P>
<P>
   Other clients include Intelligent Life and Auto Trader.
</P>
<P>
   The two new agencies will work together to service all clients
through the end of the year. ``Inevitably, we're going to lose some
clients and staff,'' said McMahon. But ``there are an enormous
number of new opportunities out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Left Field's 110 employees were notified of the change on
Tuesday and asked to choose between the new entities. Schwartz, the
creative director, said many staff members are likely to stick with
their current bosses, which would mean that members of the creative
and account planning departments will stay with his team and that
the media planning division will go with McMahon.
</P>
<P>
   McMahon said he is moving forward with plans to open offices in
Atlanta and New York, and he expects to have 150 employees in the
three cities within a year. Both Auto Trader and Intelligent Life
are based in the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Left Field had been projected to earn $13 million in revenues
this year. Executives declined to disclose how much was paid for
McMahon's interest but said the agreement was signed late last
week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
