<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ETRADE-ETRADE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 E-Trade Ends Quarter Better Than Expected  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Powered by fast-paced account growth, E-Trade Group bucked a
slowdown in the online brokerage industry and lost less money than
expected in the quarter ended September 30.
<P>
   The No. 2 Internet brokerage said yesterday it lost $26.7
million, or 11 cents a share, in its fourth fiscal quarter,
compared to a loss of $15.2 million, or 8 cents a share, in the
comparable quarter a year ago. The company was expected to lose 13
cents a share in the most recent quarter.
</P>
<P>
   For all of fiscal 1999, Menlo Park's E-Trade lost $54.7 million,
or 23 cents a share, compared to a profit of $1.69 million, or one
cent a share, in fiscal 1998. E-Trade's stock rose 22 cents to
$25.63 yesterday after earnings were reported.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's revenue of $173.2 million was up sharply from a year
ago, but down 2.2 percent from the June quarter, due partly to
lower commissions charged to active customers.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said E-Trade's strategy of spending heavily on
advertising - even if that produces red ink in the short term -is
succeeding. The company added 310,000 net new accounts during the
quarter, raising its total to 1.56 million.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade ``is a marketing powerhouse, as shown by the number of
accounts they signed up,'' said Russell Keene, an analyst with the
brokerage firm of Putnam, Lovell, de Guardiola &AMP; Thornton.
</P>
<P>
   With the stock market in the doldrums, the growth of online
trading is slowing from its torrid pace of the first half of the
year. Several rival online brokers have reported trading declines
in the September quarter, compared with the previous period.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade handled 5.1 million total trades during the quarter,
about the same as the June period, as transactions by new customers
offset fewer trades by existing clients.
</P>
<P>
   The firm spent $198 in advertising for each new customer it
attracted in the September quarter, compared with $238 in the June
quarter and $424 a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade's total assets - $28 billion at the end of September -
grew relatively slowly, in part because it attracts many new
investors who haven't built up much wealth. For every ad dollar
spent, the firm drew in about $25 in customer assets, much lower
than Charles Schwab Corp.'s industry-leading ratio of about $900 in
assets for each ad dollar, Keene calculated. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
