 _ SF CHRON  
<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Thursday, October 14, on the New York
Times wire. For questions, please call Georgie Dennison at
415-777-6055 or the business desk at 415-536-5172. For business
stories running in main news, call the news desk at 415-777-7074.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; ADVICE &LR;  _ Courtney Rosen is an avid inline skater. One night, she
fired up her computer and scanned the Web for step-by-step
instructions on how to rotate the wheels on her skates. It took her
four weeks of aggressive surfing before she finally found the
answer. So she decided to create a site where knowledge-starved
people could learn everything from how to make new friends to how
to celebrate New Year's Eve the Filipino way. Rosen's site is at
the forefront of an emerging trend _ expert sites that put specific
answers to direct questions at your fingertips. Some sites are even
promising to connect so-called e-seekers with live experts who can
give them the personalized advice they want, whether it be
romantic, financial, medical or career related. By Tom Stein
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ADVICEBAR _ &LR;  A list of how to sites. By Tom Stein
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PAC BELL  &LR; _ An outage of Pacific Bell's high-speed Internet
access is causing pains across the Bay Area. Individuals and
businesses that rely on Pac Bell's digital subscriber lines say
they've been without service for more than 24 hours. Companies that
depend on Web access for their livelihood say the outage is more
than an annoyance _ it's crippling their business. By Deborah
Solomon
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; APPLE _  &LR;  For the first time since co-founder Steve Jobs regained
control of Apple Computer two years ago, the company yesterday
reported a decline in quarterly profits compared with the same
period 12 months before. By Henry Norr
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LEFT _  &LR;  Left Field LLC, a San Francisco advertising shop
specializing in technology clients, is splitting into two new
agencies due to disagreements between its partners. By Carol Emert
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; E-TRADE &LR;  _ Powered by fast-paced account growth, E-Trade Group
bucked a slowdown in the online brokerage industry and lost less
money than expected in the quarter ended September 30. By Sam
Zuckerman
</P>
