<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 09:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6559 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV17-C     10-14 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: AIN'T LIFE THE GRAND?
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Oct. 17.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ My paternal grandfather, Jakob Glass, a wealthy
investment banker in pre-war Poland, loved to travel but disdained
carrying any bags whatsoever. He would embark on his annual Grand
Tours of Europe without so much as a comb, having deposited in
advance full wardrobes at each of his luxurious hostelries.
</P>
<P>
   In visiting Berlin, an eight-hour train trip from Warsaw,
grandfather would put up at the Hotel Adlon on Unter den Linden
near the Brandenburg Gate. Well before his arrival, a butler would
lay out his personal cache in cherrywood cabinets that rested on
limestone floors covered with oriental carpets.
</P>
<P>
   The last time he stayed there was in 1933, shortly before the
Nazis marched through the Gate to proclaim by torchlight the start
of the 1,000-year Reich. Ten years later, they murdered him and
most of my family as Jews.
</P>
<P>
   The hotel, now known as the Kempenski Adlon, has been restored
to its pre-war splendor. (A seedier embodiment, in what was then
East Germany, appears in ``One, Two, Three,'' a 1961 movie that
stars James Cagney in the role of C.R. MacNamara, a Coca-Cola
executive.)
</P>
<P>
   I walked past the hotel the other day after visiting the newly
reopened Reichstag, which once abutted the Berlin Wall and where
nowadays the German parliament sits in the reclaimed German
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Several former Hungarian officials stood by the entrance. Since
they had once allowed thousands of East Germans to escape as
``tourists'' to the West, helping bring down the German Communist
regime, Berlin Mayor Eberhard Diepgen had invited them for the 10th
anniversary of the Wall's demise.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the forest of construction cranes rising above Berlin,
Diepgen threw a big bash at the Town Hall to mark German
Unification Day. While the party was under way, neo-Nazis knocked
over more than 100 graves at Berlin's Weissensee Jewish cemetery.
   As it turned out, I ate the last available sausage but returned
to my hotel, the Westin Grand on Friedrichstrasse, before the
champagne corks popped.
</P>
<P>
   On the way in from Tegel Airport, the taxi driver said he'd
never heard of the Westin, the name of the large chain that
recently acquired the place. But he was familiar with the Grand,
once the favorite hangout of the Stasi, the East German secret
police. Now German politicians like to stay there, a short stroll
from the Reichstag.
</P>
<P>
   After we became U.S. citizens in 1948, my father, an inveterate
world traveler, vowed he'd never return to Germany or Poland, a
pledge he kept until his death in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   My son Sam has yet to visit Poland, as I did briefly the other
day after a 90-minute drive on the autobahn. But while in college,
Sam spent a sumdying at Heidelberg University. Breaking with
the practices of his great-grandfather, Sam had checked his
knapsack in economy class.
</P>
<P>
   In Jakob's footsteps, Sam has recently begun a career in
investment banking. If his employers in New York like his work,
they may one day dispatch him here to Berlin, where he can use his
nearly fluent German. Perhaps they'll even put him up at the Adlon,
hard by the Brandenburg Gate, for $250 a night.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
