<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6605 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN-$AD     10-14 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEEWAX-Y2K-COLUMN-$ADV17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UNCERTAINTY OVER PRICES, PROBLEMS RUFFLES MILLENNIUM TRAVEL
 &HT;    Moving in (k) commentary and (t) travel categories for release
Sunday, Oct. 17.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They're up. They're down. They're rising. But will
they fall again?
</P>
<P>
   Prices for New Year's Eve vacation packages have flared and
contracted like beach umbrellas this year. They were up in the
winter, down by summer and rising in autumn. But would-be revelers
may want to hold out for better deals in December.
</P>
<P>
   No matter when you make up your mind, you can be assured that
most New Year's Eve celebrations are ``plain old bad deals,''
according to Laurie Berger, editor of Consumer Reports Travel
Letter.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking here recently at a meeting of the American Society of
Travel Agents, consumer advocate Berger called ``millennium''
packages ``the rip-offs of the century.'' Problems will include
price gouging, overcrowding, ``over-promising'' of amenities,
unfair refund policies and possible Y2K computer bug problems, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, millions are eager to do something special to welcome
2000, and the hospitality industry is even more keen to exploit
that urge. Hotel operators and cruise ship owners have been
juggling prices to determine just how much money travelers will be
willing to spend to feel special.
</P>
<P>
   Berger, who has been tracking rates throughout the year, found
that most companies started last winter with outrageously high
prices, and then began slashing them when consumers refused to go
along.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers not only were turned off by the price gouging, but
were concerned about the computer software flaw commonly called the
Y2K bug. The problem could cause many computers to fail when the
date changes to Jan. 1, 2000. Earlier this year, some experts were
predicting technological chaos on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the minimal interest in year-end travel, travel
promoters began cutting prices by as much as 50 percent from
February peaks. For example, one Carnival cruise package Berger
tracked was priced at $2,250 for New Year's Eve 1998. In February,
the company hiked the price to $3,700 for New Year's Eve 1999. That
drove away so many customers that Carnival dropped the rate to
$2,538 in June, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But since then, Y2K fears have diminished and many people have
seen their stock holdings rise. With the urge to celebrate growing
again, the Carnival trip is back up to $3,335, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is whether renewed concerns about the Y2K bug
will kill reservations in November and December, leaving cruise
ships with many vacancies. Travelers might want to wait and hope
travel companies will slash prices at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said the worst gouging will be found in the most popular
places for New Year's Eve parties: New York City, Las Vegas and
Orlando. The best deals are in ``secondary'' party cities such as
New Orleans and Houston, she said.
</P>
<P>
   And what about the Y2K bug? Berger says it remains a serious
concern, and notes that insurance companies are being extremely
vague in their promises to cover trips ruined by computer problems.
Her advice to millennium travelers is, ``Don't go. I think there
are a lot of risks.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 1020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
