<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHORTTAKES: The agony of Pius XII
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Vatican has defended the wartime pope, Pius XII, against
chargeti-Semitism and a peculiar moral torpor during the
Holocaust. Pius, his defenders said, pursued peace quietly,
discreetly, refusing to endanger even more potential victims,
agonizing over his self-imposed inability to speak out.
</P>
<P>
   Although the defense may be apt, it is not a case one makes for
sainthood. Saints do not wring their hands with a delicately poised
prudence. The case for the pope's sainthood is probably now doomed
by his defenders.
</P>
<P>
   Pius XII is a candidate for beatification, a step away from
sainthood. His candidacy has been sharply challenged by a new book,
``Hitler's Pope,'' by the English journalist John Cornwell.
Cornwell charges that the pope, a lifelong papal diplomat, was so
addicted to treaty-making and fine diplomacy that he failed to
connect with the larger picture of what was going on in
Nazi-occupied Europe. Cornwell's well-documented argument cannot be
balanced by pleas for prudence and discretion.
</P>
<P>
   Pius emerges as a figure less saintly than just human.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
E-mail: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
