<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 10:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6623 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN17-COX     10-14 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Practicing MAD politics
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even as a military coup was raising the risk Pakistan will
restart its nuclear arms race with India, the Senate was removing
the United States as leader of the international effort to contain
nuclear weapons, leaving the drive floundering. GOP leadership saw
a shot at paying President Clinton back for besting it on issue
after issue, and took it.
</P>
<P>
   It would be one thing if the treaty banning nuclear tests had
been soberly studied and voted down over substantive misgivings,
but that was not the case. This was partisan opportunism.
</P>
<P>
   The treaty formalized a testing moratorium initiated by
President George Bush. It has been signed by 154 nations, ratified
by 51. Most of the rest were waiting to see whether the Senate
would confirm President Clinton's signature.
</P>
<P>
   There are legitimate questions. Could cheaters be detected? Can
the U.S. nuclear arsenal be kept reliable by computer modeling and
other substitutes for major tests? The answers are ``probably.''
The treaty, for instance, would set up the most extensive
monitoring system ever. Whatever fudging there might be at the
margins, no nuclear breakout would seem possible.
</P>
<P>
   The current situation is hardly foolproof.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, where national security is at stake, rejection over the
doubts would at least be defensible. That did not happen. With
enough fatal opposition committed, the GOP leadership rushed the
treaty toward the floor with all the glee and decorum of a bunch of
frat boys depantsing a pledge, before the administration could
defend itself.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that Germany, England and France _ and allies who
depend upon our nuclear deterrent as much as we do _ were urging
ratification. Or that Russia and China, our biggest worries, will
now almost surely walk out on the deal. Or that nuclear newcomers
like Pakistan and India will probably crank up abated programs. Or
that wannabes will resume development.
</P>
<P>
   The major flaw in the treaty was not in its provisions but in
the maddening political fact that it was the hated Bill Clinton who
had pulled it off.
</P>
<P>
   The administration had persuaded, at least tentatively, even
such potent rivals as Russia and China to accept a status quo that
in effect locked in U.S. nuclear superiority and had added a
provision that would allow Washington to opt out if it ever
determined its nuclear arsenal was no longer safe or reliable.
</P>
<P>
   It is still technically possible for the issue to be revived in
the next administration.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, however, that the shaky international consensus
will now scatter irretrievably and that the best hope yet for
ending nuclear testing, and thus restraining nuclear spread, has
been lost.
</P>
<P>
   And for the immediate future, we may watch, sidelined by the
Senate, as a militarized and incidentally Islamicized Pakistan not
only decides whether to seek nuclear one-upmanship over India but
perhaps even ponders whether to provide the ``Muslim'' bomb that
the Middle East's anti-Israel extremists have always dreamed of.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
