<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6646 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-GEORGIA-WINES-$ADV16-     10-14 1246
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEORGIA-WINES-$ADV16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MELLOWING OUT: VINTNERS IN EX-SOVIET STATE LOOK TO THE PAST FOR
FUTURE PROMISE
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Oct. 16 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TELAVI, Republic of Georgia _ Wood shavings cover the concrete
floor of the tiny workshop. The only sounds are the clang and
scrape of tools on timber as Rubiko Batiashivili goes about his
solitary work.
</P>
<P>
   With graying hair and a weathered face, Batiashivili is
virtually the last man in this sunny mountain valley who knows how
to handcraft an oaken barrel, and he is suddenly in demand. Given
the importance of wine to the economy of this former Soviet
republic, Georgia's future well-being may rest in Batiashivili's
rough hands.
</P>
<P>
   The managers of the sprawling Soviet-era Achinebuli wine factory
here in the Telavi believe they have found the innovation that will
make their product competitive in the world. The breakthrough is
wood _ not-so-high-tech wooden barrels for storing wine and
mellowing its flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Quality grapes grow in abundance is this green valley, a
winemaking region called Kakheti, in the shadow of the Caucasus
Mountains. Georgia was the Napa Valley of the tsars. Georgian wines
were prized for their flavor and clarity.
</P>
<P>
   And then came the Soviet industrial revolution. The Soviet's
built mass-production plants in the 1950s and 1960s with gigantic
steel vats that d prized Georgian wines to the ordinary,
though they remain popular in Russia and Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Now, hoping to revive their winemaking skills and appeal to
lucrative Western markets, Georgian vintners are tapping into past
traditions with plans to store their wine in wooden barrels and
improve its flavor and reputation worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   The Achinebuli winery, one of the country's largest, hired
Batiashivili last year after locals identified the 63-year-old
woodworker as one of the last of a dying breed. He learned the
craft of making barrels to store wine as a teenager half a century
ago, and now he is again putting the skill to work.
</P>
<P>
   He spends his days in his workshop at a corner of the winery
hewing and assembling small barrels. One day soon, he will begin
making full-sized barrels to store wine. For now, they are content
to let him practice his craft, and teach it to others.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started, all the wineries used wooden barrels,'' said
Batiashivili. He added with a smile: ``This factory makes very good
wine, but of course my homemade wine is better.''
</P>
<P>
   Batiashivili's boastfulness is something of a national trait in
Georgia, where virtually every rural household produces its own
wine, as it has for generations.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Georgia's top wine producers want to live up to their
country's winemaking heritage.
</P>
<P>
   With the collapse of communism in 1991 and the global success of
such small wine-producing countries as Chile and Australia, the
Georgia wine industry believes it could find its niche in the world
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have great traditions. We used to produce very good wines.
But in the Soviet period, we were very backwards and our problem is
that our viniculture specialists don't know just how backward we
are,'' said David Dolmazashivili, director of the Achinebuli
winery.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, the quality is improving as the winery has sent its
winemakers abroad to see how Californians, Italians and the French
harvest and produce wines.
</P>
<P>
   Over the summer, Dolmazashivili toured the California wine
regions and returned to spread the word on how far Georgia must go
to compete with the likes of Robert Mondavi wineries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now at least we know what we want and need. We cannot afford
it, but at least we know, whereas before we thought we had the
best,'' Dolmazashivili said.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, the winery will import oak barrels from California to
begin storing what will become vintage, upscale wine. In the next
batch, they hope to use homemade barrels produced by Batiashivili.
</P>
<P>
   The winery already has begun to purchase stainless steel
processing equipment from Italy to replace the worn and corroding
Soviet-era equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The parent company, Georgia Wine and Spirits, was founded in
1993 as the state-owned vineyards were being privatized, and is
responsible for about half the country's production and sales. The
French beverage multinational Pernod Richard owns a share of the
Georgia company.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the former Soviet Union, the quest to compete
globally begins with the expensive task of updating the technology.
Decades of central planning and lack of competition have left
rusting factories unable to function profitably in a market
economy.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, though, winemakers have the grapes and the
reputation that has seen them through the rough decade. Wine
remains one of the small country's top exports, sold mainly to
Russia and other former Soviet states.
</P>
<P>
   Yet at its peak in Soviet times, Georgia exported about 120
million bottles of wine a year. Last year, the total was only about
10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Georgian wines sell sporadically in the United States, several
thousand bottles a year primarily in New York, Los Angeles and
Chicago, where Russian immigrants maintain a miniscule but steady
demand for them.
</P>
<P>
   Earning a reputation in the West will not be easy in a crowded
market of fine wines from Europe, California, South America and
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem facing producers in Georgia is the lack of
quality control. With some 500 varieties of grapes growing in the
country, Georgia needs establish an appellation system, similar to
France's regional controls that define in absolute terms what makes
a Burgundy, Bordeaux or Beaujolais.
</P>
<P>
   Producers agree that even Georgia's best-known varieties _ a dry
white wine called Tsinandali, similar to a Chablis, and a dry red
called Saperavi-Mukuzanik, akin to a Merlot _ suffer from widely
varying tastes depending on the winery. Georgia also grapples with
a problem of counterfeiting, claiming that illicit producers in
Russia, Ukraine, Romania and Slovakia bottle wines using Georgia
labels to exploit the good reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, winemakers said, the small and poor nation needs
economic freedoms that will encourage entrepreneurs to make and
market their own vintages.
</P>
<P>
   They already exist in abundance here. Virtually every Georgian
household traditionally has a cellar of homemade wine. But few can
find the capital to develop into full-fledged wineries to bottle
and market their product.
</P>
<P>
   Near the mammoth Achinebuli winery, locals in Telavi direct
visitors to a home surrounded by hanging grapevines. It is here, at
the residence of Vajha Nikolaishivili, where one can find the
finest wine in the valley, the locals say.
</P>
<P>
   A beefy man with a bronze face and a passion for wine,
Nikolaishivili talks in a constant stream about the skills his
great-grandfather taught him. He ages his wine in vats buried in
the clay floor of a storehouse on the property. He has more
customers than wine, and reserves a special vat, what he calls
``the grandchild'' for special family occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``With each harvest you have to produce the best wines you
can,'' said Nikolaishivili, 52, who's family has been producing
homemade wine for the past seven generations. ``Otherwise you shame
the family tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
