<HEADER>
A6649 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-PANDAS-WILD-$ADV16-CO     10-14 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANDAS-WILD-$ADV16-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RADICAL STEPS MAY BE NEEDED TO SAVE CHINA'S STILL ENDANGERED
PANDAS
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Oct. 16 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOLONG, China _ Normally, cabbages don't threaten giant pandas.
</P>
<P>
   But here the big green plants shoulder up to the very edge of a
winding, rock-pocked road, then creep in neat rows high up the most
impossible-looking mountain terrain.
</P>
<P>
   The cabbage is only one calling card of humanity inexorably
pushing itself into misty wilderness heights, fragmenting the
bamboo-forested mountainland that supports the last clusters of the
estimated 1,000 giant pandas still living in the wilds of southwest
China.
</P>
<P>
   Despite recent habitat protections, wildlife experts assess
continuing human pressures as intense. They are not at all
convinced that the enchanting animals will survive to amble through
many new chapters in their three million-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ``To save the panda species, we have a long way to go,'' Liu
Yongfan, vice-director of the State Forestry Administration, told
Chinese and American scientists gathered at this nature reserve for
a conference on pandas earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   China at least is inching down the route of protection.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Some efforts are being made to stop the human encroachment
that has cut up panda territory and divided the panda population,
making genetic in-breeding a potentially deadly problem and leaving
isolated, small groups susceptible to environmental crises that
larger numbers could weather.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Research is continuing to improve the achievements already
made in captive panda breeding, to assure the pandas survive
somewhere. China now has about 100 pandas living in captivity, most
of them bred at Chinese zoos and research institutes and the rest
captured from the wild.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  And now the Chinese are laying the groundwork for the
precarious possibility of reintroducing to the wild, pandas born in
captivity.
</P>
<P>
   But money, knowledge and national will are in short supply.
</P>
<P>
   That is partly because people don't know about the cabbages
snaking up nature reserve mountains, or the peasants still
stripping forests here for firewood, or about the poachers or the
hunters whose snares may grab pandas by mistake, but kill them
nonetheless, said Zhang Hemin, director of the China Research and
Conservation Center for the Giant Panda.
</P>
<P>
   ``In China, there is something wrong with the propaganda,''
Zhang lamented in an interview with Cox Newspapers. ``People read
about cloning, and they think there is no problem now with the
panda. Some say in the wild there are no problems.''
</P>
<P>
   His success is one reason for the blase attitude. Every time a
panda gives birth at Zhang's breeding center, the feel-good news is
trumpeted around the country by the official media.
</P>
<P>
   And before the panda conference here was half finished, Beijing
newspapers published optimistic accounts of the still tentative
hope Zhang had expressed in a speech to introduce captive-born
pandas to the wild.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of reintroduction may be an exciting, very
long-term project, but is fraught with difficulty under even the
best conditions. The newspapers did not mention that Zhang failed
to get state funding for the one-square-mile enclosure he wants to
build high on the mountain to begin experimental training, but will
be lucky to finance a semi-wild area of one-fifth of a square mile.
</P>
<P>
   If any pandas do become ready for release to the wild, a crucial
question is whether there is enough wild to support them.
</P>
<P>
   One key development that will help determine panda policy is a
panda survey that has been delayed several years for lack of funds,
according to Yan Xun, chief biologist for China's nature reserves.
</P>
<P>
   The survey is to begin early next year with the aim of
generating solid estimates of the numbers of pandas alive today and
where they live. The last survey was finished in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the population is decreasing very fast, maybe we will
formulate some strict policies to stop the spread of townships or
even to remove some co-inhabited areas,'' Yan said, referring to
areas where both pandas and humans live.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Wolong, a 720-square-mile nature reserve, attempts to
remove some peasant families who farm, hunt and collect wood simply
were called off. The issue was sensitive because many local
residents are ethnic Zang (of Tibetan origin) or Qiang, and the
central government has been under international fire elsewhere for
ham-fisted tactics against minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a question of the rights of animals versus the rights
of people,'' explained Deng Xiangsui, director of wildlife
conservation here in Sichuan Province, where 80 percent of the
giant pandas are believed to live.
</P>
<P>
   One  policy change already, he said, was the outlawing of
timber-cutting throughout the region last fall. Although Deng said
the tough regulation long had been in the works, the central
government acted only after last year's devastating summer floods
cost millions of dollars
</P>
<P>
   and hundreds of lives _ another by-product of deforestation.
</P>
<P>
   This summer the government went further and prohibited the
transport of lumber in protected areas, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another goal frequently cited at the conference, which was run
by the Minnesota-based Conservation Breeding Specialist Group, is
setting up ``panda corridors'' to link reserves and other panda
habitat now divided by roads or communities or forest
clear-cutting.
</P>
<P>
   Corridors would promote mixing of animals from different
geographic areas, potentially improving genetic diversity and
giving pandas wider areas to forage for food in the event of a
localized crisis such as fire or bamboo ``flowering.''
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1970s, a cyclical outburst of bamboo blooms killed
off large patches of bamboo, resulting in starvation deaths of 80
percent of the pandas in some isolated areas.
</P>
<P>
   Making such corridors is another tough goal, an example of
``nascent ecology'' that scientists don't quite know how to do yet,
according to Ulysses Seal, chairman of the American group.
</P>
<P>
   But something must be done to ease human pressure and better
protect the remnants of the panda population, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without intervention,'' Seal said, ``I'd say in the next 100
years we'd see these fragmented (panda) populations wink out one by
one.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
