<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   UNABOMBER-BROTHER _ (Albany, N.Y.) _ David Kaczynski has a deal
with a Los Angeles company for a movie about his life and a pivotal
moment in 1996: when he turned in his brother, Ted Kaczynski, the
Unabomber. The film will focus on Schenectady, N.Y., residents
David Kaczynski and his wife, Linda Patrik, who will be consultants
on the project. By CHRIS STURGIS.
</P>
<P>
   PATAKI-TOBACCO (Albany, N.Y.) _ The head of the
Hungarian-American Chamber of Commerce U.S.A. defends the group's
sponsorship of two trips that New York Gov. George E. Pataki took
to Hungary, saying she has no idea why a giant tobacco company
donated $10,000 to the chamber before each of those visits. By
DANIELLE FURFARO and EDWARD FITZPATRICK.
</P>
<P>
   DUTCH-AMERICA-HISTORY (Albany, N.Y.) _ For four hundred years,
the pages of this city's history have survived multiple fires,
years in a damp ship's hold, age, theft, neglect and hungry rats.
Now, 12,000 fragile pages minutely describing life in Dutch America
will be cleaned by experts and made sturdy enough to be handled by
the public. By ALAN WECHSLER.
</P>
<P>
   BREAST-CANCER (San Francisco) _ A conference Saturday on ways to
prevent and treat breast cancer by integrating Western medicine
with traditional healing practices will emphasize inclusion of
underserved minorities. By MARSHA GINSBURG.
</P>
<P>
   ANTI-ALCOHOL-AD (San Francisco) _ Contra County, Calif.,
residents and the Marin Institute for the Prevention of Alcohol and
Other Drug Problems are fighting a billboard company's refusal to
display an anti-alcohol advertisement in the county that
discourages under-aged drinking. By ANDREA WOO.
</P>
<P>
   SF-MAYORAL (San Francisco) _ Mayoral candidate Clint Reilly's
effort to raise more cash in his campaign has led a federal judge
to block a 1995 measure approved by San Francisco voters to rein in
spending in such races. By ILENE LELCHUK.
</P>
<P>
   HUMAN-RIGHTS (San Francisco) _ Six months after the FBI stepped
up its probe of the San Francisco Human Rights Commission's
handling of minority contracting and more than a year after the
city made its own inquiry into mismanagement, the troubled agency's
11 commissioners are focusing on the director. By JULIE CHAO.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-ER (Undated) _ One of television's most famous doctors is
back into the chaotic fray, of both a hospital and network
television, at least for a month or so. Alan Alda joined NBC's
``ER'' for the first installment of a five-episode run. The hotshot
young gun who was Hawkeye Pierce is now the mentor, Dr. Ted
Lawrence, a new attending physician at the Chicago hospital. By
MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   SUNSET-REVIEW (Undated) _ It's hard to watch Petula Clark play
Norma Desmond during the 2 1/2-hour touring version of Andrew Lloyd
Webber's ``Sunset Boulevard'' without feeling that she's been
terribly miscast. By ROBERT HURWITT.
</P>
<P>
   PROMISING-VIOLINIST (San Francisco) _ Anybody disturbed by the
possibility that schools and conservatories are disgorging
performers more concerned with technique than artistry will be
reassured by the excellent performance here of violinist Hilary
Hahn, 19. Rarely in the recent history of the San Francisco
Symphony has a debut offered more hope for the next generation of
musicians. By ALLEN ULRICH.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-BROSIUS (New York) _ This postseason is especially
meaningful for the New York Yankees' Scott Brosius, last year's
World Series MVP, who endured the death of his father on Sept. 12
from colon cancer. He missed five games in late August and early
September to visit with his father in Oregon, to say his goodbyes
and then return to his job playing third base for the defending
champions. His performance Wednesday night was stunning. By BRIAN
MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ If I had to pick a low point, it
would be Day Two when I took off the bandages and realized I looked
like one of the horriormed pig people in a classic TV
episode of the ``Twilight Zone.'' I saw the bruised and swollen
aftermath of some relatively minor facial surgery. No, not for
wrinkles or age spots. It was for the real epidermal bummer among
an aging Baby Boom population: skin cancer. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ This is the time of year you're a
damn fool Philistine if you're doing anything but watching
baseball. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
