<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SEATTLE-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE'S SALMON SOUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE PAUL  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Bill Robinson was standing along a railing, spotting
silvery shadows just beneath the surface of the dark emerald water
below.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good-looking chinook right there,'' he said, pointing
out what was likely to be a 12- to 14-pound specimen. ``That's one
of those endangered fish,'' he added with a wry smirk.
</P>
<P>
   The dark spots on its back distinguish chinook salmon from the
smaller sockeyes that also were swimming through what are
officially known as the Hiram Chittenden Locks but locally called
the Ballard Locks or just the Locks.
</P>
<P>
   The Locks are one of Seattle's biggest tourist attractions. And
a free one at that. On a gorgeous summer day, people sunbathed on
the grassy banks nearby, strolled the concrete walkways and took
pictures of the yachts and crabbers going through the ic
marvel that separates the salt water of Puget Sound from the
freshwater lakes of Seattle's inner port.
</P>
<P>
   And they watched the salmon _ noble fish of Indian legend, of
Indian identity, of biological heroics and of cultural dominance _
``climb'' the Locks' concrete ladder. After spending two to four
years maturing in the ocean, the fish return here.
</P>
<P>
   The Locks present just one more challenge in the fish's journey
to the distant streambeds where they were born and where they will
soon die, said Robinson, who is executive director of the Northwest
Steelhead and Salmon Council of Trout Unlimited, a major
conservation organization.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that chinook and sockeye are still passing through the
Locks is next to miraculous when you consider how the wild salmon
stocks of the Pacific Northwest (and elsewhere in the world) have
been decimated after 100 years of overfishing, urban growth and
extreme habitat degradation. Since 1991, more than two dozen salmon
population groups in the region _ usually identified by the waters
they inhabit or return to _ have been listed for protection under
the Endangered Species Act. Others are being closely watched.
</P>
<P>
   How much the average Seattleite thinks about the fate of salmon
is hard to say, but in many ways the fish remain a powerful symbol
for all that is right and all that is wrong with life in the
Emerald City on Puget Sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything having to do with salmon,'' Robinson said, ``by and
large will affect everything else. These fish are nothing more than
an indicator of our quality of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Big for its britches?
</P>
<P>
   I last saw Seattle on a quick weekend trip in the mid-1980s.
Microsoft was a fledgling public company, and the sleepy downtown
seemed to get sleepier at night. Things have definitely changed:
Like many rebounding cities yearning for respect and convention
business, downtown Seattle has been Pottery Barned and Wolfgang
Pucked.
</P>
<P>
   And in the midst of its prosperity and aliveness, you'll come
face to face with the flip side: the hordes of homeless and walking
wounded and young drifters who remind you that the raging bull
market has not been wonderful for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   The Downtown districts are gleaming with glass-walled shopping
palaces and an impressive concentration of fine and trendy dining
opportunities. The construction binge is hardly over, what with all
the high-tech billionaires pouring money on their nouveau dreams.
</P>
<P>
   If Seattle seems a little big for its britches, well, that's the
way of the with-it urban world right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all so in love with itself,'' said a friend who lives and
teaches there. ``It thinks it's London or something.''
</P>
<P>
   It's possible to find pockets of genuine Seattle. That fact
dawned on me as I was catching Bill Robinson's enthusiasm for the
sight of silvery salmon in the water at the Locks.
</P>
<P>
   Stem to stern
</P>
<P>
   Not everything in Seattle has to do with salmon, yet you're
never too far from water. At the Center for Wooden Boats, on the
south shore of Lake Union, you can find a gem of a place. Museum,
education complex and marina (instruction and rentals available),
the center celebrates boating. It operates on donations and
volunteer power.
</P>
<P>
   The center's slips and work areas offer a changing inventory of
boats needing repair and boats under construction. On the front
grounds, under an awning, rested a 600-year-old red cedar log from
Alaska, which is being carved into a 36-foot-long traditional Haida
canoe.
</P>
<P>
   One morning I found a restoration project under way. A blue tarp
covered the back end of a 60-foot ketch that is both obsession and
home to Seaton Gras. Gras is rebuilding the boat, the Merry Maiden,
from stern to stem, replacing rotted wood and thousands of corroded
bronze screws. ``Everything needs attention,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gras hopes that by next year he will have it seaworthy again and
can take his teen-age daughter, Tiare, on a round-the-world cruise.
It won't be the first time for Gras. When he was 13, his father
took the family on the adventure of their lives. In this very boat
the Gras family of suburban Boston spent six years circumnavigating
the globe. After they returned, Gras took the Merry Maiden out
again, going around the world by himself in the next seven years.
</P>
<P>
   The Merry Maiden had sat untouched for years until Gras, now 43
and still a self-described ``international spirit,'' decided to
take up his dream once more.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon struggles
</P>
<P>
   Bill Robinson prefers grilling fresh salmon at home _ with just
a bit of olive oil and some spices _ to eating the fish in
restaurants. Too often, he said, restaurant salmon is either
overcooked or oversauced.
</P>
<P>
   That might be true, but salmon justifiably is king in the many
restaurants that define Seattle's seafood cuisine. Ivar's and
Elliott's are old-line tourist attractions; Etta's, Chandler's,
Ray's, Anthony's _ locals line up behind their favorites just as
Kansas Citians square off over barbecue: Gates or Bryant's?
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the restaurant, fresh fish is as likely to be
hatchery-born or farm-raised as wild. Fishing regulations have
become so complex and seasons and allowable catches so variable
that finger-pointing by commercial fishermen, tribal fishermen,
sport fishermen, land interests and countries (the United States
vs. Canada, for instance) is common and the ranks of
self-supporting salmon boats are thinning. Yet, said Chris Mohr, an
Olympic Peninsula resort operator and sport-fishing lobbyist,
``Nobody wants to catch the last salmon.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite salmon's precarious status, the fishing industry remains
vital to Puget Sound. Halibut and cod are doing especially well,
industry people said. The great majority of the salmon boats based
at the Fishermen's Terminal, on the Lake Washington Ship Canal just
east of the Locks, take their catch in Alaska, where sockeye and
other species remain abundant, said Bill Anschutz of the city's
Port Authority.
</P>
<P>
   The early-morning bustle at Pike Place Market, home to four
fresh-fish companies, conveys one sign of health. Sockeye from
Alaska's Copper River region was the salmon du jour when I stopped
at Pike Place Fish. It was 7 a.m., still a couple hours before the
tourists would arrive, but an ideal time to see the historic market
coming alive. (Almost demolished in the early '80s, the market has
become the magnet of genuineness upon which Seattle's downtown and
waterfront revitalization depends.)
</P>
<P>
   At Pike Place Fish the garrulous, orange-slickered man known as
the Bear _ just the Bear, he said _ was stacking 300 pounds of
salmon, flown in overnight, on a freshly shoveled bed of ice. Later
in the day, the Bear turns into the archetypical
fishmonger//performance artist. His gruff voice will rise as he
banters with passing tourists. A voice will call out from behind
the counter _ ``Salmon'' _ the Bear will pick up one of the
20-pounders and fling it a dozen feet to the counter man, who'll
fillet it or wrap it up whole for a customer. ``Caution: Low Flying
Fish'' read the signs.
</P>
<P>
   And another thing ...
</P>
<P>
   One night, in search of a light dinner, I fell into Cafe
Campagne, a bistro and wine bar near Pike Place Market. I had
appetizers at the bar, including a delicately grilled salmon
brochette and a salad with smoked salmon and bits of orange.
</P>
<P>
   One thing led to another and soon I was talking salmon with a
nearby diner. A former biologist and natural historian who now
operates an adventure-tour business, John Tillotson lamented the
fate of the Duwamish River, which drains into Elliott Bay. Its
once-putrid mouth was mostly filled in by the manmade Harbor
Island, I'd learned from Bill Robinson. Yet in recent years it has
become cleaner and small stocks of brave fish still make their way
again upstream. I even had watched some Duwamish Chinook being
caught from a public pier in West Seattle, near the mouth of the
river.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you sit on its banks you could understand the whole
region,'' said Tillotson, who had explored the river as a boy. What
he meant was you could contemplate the history of industrial
pollution, unchecked growth and civic misguidance. ``The only place
the river truly speaks,'' he added, ``is where the glacier drips.''
</P>
<P>
   As I said, one thing leads to another and soon we were speaking
with a couple who had arrived for a late dinner at the bar, Ron
Zimmerman and Carrie Van Dyck. Turned out they ran the Herbfarm,
which, in addition to its nursery and catalog operation in the
exurbs east of Seattle, presents one of the most extraordinary
dining experiences you'd find around here: a legendary nine-course,
five-hour meal comprising fresh ingredients and herbs that define
the cuisine of the Pacific Northwest. Zimmerman considers salmon
and cedar to be the region's pillars.
</P>
<P>
   Their restaurant burned in 1997 and only recently had they
resumed serving their special weekend dinners.
</P>
<P>
   Two nights later, I was sitting at one of their tables in a
wine-tasting room in Issaquah. Some of Executive Chef Jerry
Traunfeld's delectable creations: a mussel speared by a sprig of
rosemary, Dungeness crab salad with chilled fennel foam, seared
weathervane scallops and summer chanterelles, breast of Muscovy
duck rubbed with lavender and black pepper, a sorbet made from
apricot and meadowsweet ...
</P>
<P>
   Did I mention the salmon? Traunfeld's king salmon came from
Humboldt Bay in northern California. He slow-baked it at 200
degrees. When the dish arrived, it was startling. The succulent
pink flesh had been wrapped in a now-transparent zucchini petal,
looking for all the world like (I really do apologize for this)
sheer lingerie.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly my search for the salmon soul of Seattle had taken an
unexpected turn.
</P>
<P>
   GOING TO SEATTLE
</P>
<P>
   Getting there
</P>
<P>
   Seattle is served by most major airlines and Amtrak. Southwest
Airlines offers nonstop flights from Kansas City; recent
promotional fares have been as low as $200 or so round trip, and
regular coach fares as much as $500 round trip in peak season.
</P>
<P>
   Getting around
</P>
<P>
   - By car: Interstates 5 and 90 meet near the heart of the city.
Driving around the city can pose a challenge, especially at rush
hour. ``You can't get there from here'' is a local motto. Ferries
connect Seattle with Bainbridge Island and other spots; for ferry
schedules and information: (206) 464-6400 or
www.wsdot.wa.gov//ferries/.
</P>
<P>
   - If you're staying downtown, the Metro Bus offers free service
in a large downtown zone. The Monorail connects Westlake Center and
Seattle Center ($1.25 each way for adults). The Waterfront
Streetcar ($1, or $1.25 at rush hour) runs up and down Alaskan Way
from Pier 70 to the International District, providing an easy
(although probably crowded) overview of ferry terminals, the
Seattle Aquarium and numerous bayfront attractions and eateries.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown accommodations
</P>
<P>
   Many of the major chains, from modest to high end, are
represented in or near downtown. Some other options:
</P>
<P>
   - Claremont Hotel, 2000 Fourth Ave. (at Virginia Street). This
locally owned redo has small-hotel charm, spacious rooms, a creaky
elevator, but exceptional service. $129-$189. (800) 448-8601.
</P>
<P>
   - Inn at the Market, 86 Pine St. A fine, cozy hotel right in the
thick of the Pike Place Market area. $155-$345. (800) 446-4484.
</P>
<P>
   - Pacific Plaza Hotel, 400 Spring St. A spartan, budget
alternative with small rooms but convenient to the Waterfront and
Pioneer Square. $104-$130; lower rates in winter. (800) 426-1165.
</P>
<P>
   - Houseboat Hideaways, various locations on Lake Union. Fully
furnished houseboats, including galley kitchens (but not food), can
be rented at prices rivaling those of elegant hotels. $165-$195.
(206) 323-5323.
</P>
<P>
   Dining out
</P>
<P>
   - Campagne, 86 Pine St., and Cafe Campagne, 1600 Post Alley (at
Pine). Top-notch French country cooking; the cafe is the casual
alternative to its more expensive partner upstairs. Campagne: (206)
728-2800; Cafe Campagne: (206) 728-2233.
</P>
<P>
   - Chandler's Crabhouse and Fresh Fish Market, 901 Fairview Ave.
North. A dockside location at South Lake Union makes this a
picturesque spot for reliably prepared fresh seafood, especially
Dungeness crab. (206) 223-CRAB (2722).
</P>
<P>
   - The Herbfarm Restaurant, temporarily located in Issaquah, 17
miles east of Seattle. Save up and plan ahead for a distinctive
dining experience: a nine-course, five-hour extravaganza of superb
food and wine. The menu changes weekly and with the seasons. It's a
fixed-price meal ($135 to $155 a person, plus tax and gratuity).
Make a reservation now; if it's booked, get on a waiting list or
keep trying, because late cancellations could open some spots for
you. (206) 784-2222.
</P>
<P>
   - Honey Court Seafood Restaurant, 516 Maynard Ave. S. In the
heart of the International District, this Chinese restaurant has
Vietnamese influences and many unusual seafood dishes. Not fancy
but reliable and reasonable. (206) 292-8828.
</P>
<P>
   - Longshoreman's Daughter, 3508 Fremont Place N., on the main
drag of the funky Fremont district. Try it for a stylish and
attitudinal spin on comfort food, including breakfast. (206)
633-5169.
</P>
<P>
   - Ray's Boathouse, 6049 Seaview Ave. NW, near Ballard Locks.
From pan-fried razor clams to house-smoked cod, and, of course,
whatever fresh salmon and other catches are available, Ray's is a
Seattle standby for finely prepared seafood with a gorgeous
waterside view of Shilshole Bay. Reservations are highly
recommended. (206) 789-3770.
</P>
<P>
   Attractions
</P>
<P>
   - Hiram M. Chittenden (or Ballard) Locks, 3015 N.W. 54th St.
Open daily 7 a.m.- 9 p.m. Free.
</P>
<P>
   - Center for Wooden Boats, 1010 Valley St. (South Lake Union).
Free admission. (206) 382-2628 or www.cwb.org.
</P>
<P>
   - Fremont, centered on Fremont Avenue North and 36th Street
North. You have to wonder about a wacky, anything-goes neighborhood
with its own walking-tour brochures. Organized anarchy is always
suspicious, but Seattle is nothing if not self-conscious. And
Fremont typifies it: The arts-oriented district has unusual shops,
some funky and fine dining and a famous collection of public
sculptures, such as a genuine Lenin statue, salvaged from the
Soviet bloc, and a '50s-era decorative rocket.
</P>
<P>
   - Gas Works Park, North Northlake Way and Meridian Avenue North,
near Fremont and Wallingford neighborhoods. The rusting hulk of
industrial pipes makes for an eerie public sculpture in this
offbeat gathering place. The former gas plant has been turned into
a rolling green space with a spectacular view of the downtown
skyline across the water. Home to outdoor movies, concerts and the
western terminus of a 121/2-mile hiking and biking trail. Don't
miss the hilltop mosaic sundial.
</P>
<P>
   - International District, South Washington Street to South
Weller Streets, between Fourth and 12th avenues. Seattle's various
Asian communities, immigrants from Japan, China, Vietnam, Korea,
the Philippines and elsewhere, come together in this lively
commercial neighborhood of shops and restaurants. The district is
south of Pioneer Square and within a Ken Griffey dinger of the new
Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   - Pike Place Market, on Pike Place from Pike Street to Virginia
Street. Two decades after it was saved from certain demolition,
this longtime farmer's market and merchandise mall is still the
first stop for tourists, and deservedly so, for its genuine mix of
food, flowers, fish and fun. People watching, romantic dining, a
buzzing streetscape, it's the major local antidote to the
same-as-everywhere retailing that has surged into Downtown.
</P>
<P>
   - Pioneer Square, along First Avenue from Columbia Street to
Jackson Street. Like Pike Place Market, this old-town neighborhood
still has a vibrant, alternative feel, with lots of shopping,
eating and drinking opportunities. The soul of Pioneer Square can
be found in the huge Elliott Bay Bookstore (101 S. Main St.),
recently saved by a new, deep-pockets owner.
</P>
<P>
   - Seattle Center, Fifth Avenue at Broad and Mercer streets. This
is ground zero for the Space Needle: No matter how often you see it
from around town, up close is something else again. It's also home
to seasonal events, such as Labor Day's Bumbershoot Festival, and
permanent fixtures such as the Opera House, Intiman Theater and the
Children's Museum. Coming in the spring of 2000 is the Experience
Music Project, a rock museum inspired by local hero Jimi Hendrix,
paid for by Microsoft gazillionaire Paul Allen and designed by
architecture's Wizard of Wild, Frank Gehry.
</P>
<P>
   A SALMON MISCELLANY
</P>
<P>
   - Fact: There are five species of wild Pacific Northwest salmon:
chinook (sometimes called king), sockeye, coho, pink, chum.
Steelhead trout is a close relative. ``Farming'' of Atlantic salmon
in the region has caused some debate over the genetic implications.
</P>
<P>
   - Excerpt: ``Aflame with the crimson color of marriage, the
salmon// Seek their lovers.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Mieko Chikappu, from ``Salmon Coming Home in Search of Sacred
Bliss''
</P>
<P>
   - Event: Salmon Homecoming, second weekend of September. The
Native American heritage celebration includes a coastal-tribe
gathering, a Plains-style powwow, entertainment events and public
forums on salmon and conservation issues. Based at Seattle Aquarium
and extending to locations along the waterfront area in both
directions. Information: (206) 386-4300.
</P>
<P>
   - Reading: David Hutchinson, proprietor of Flora &AMP; Fauna Books,
a Pioneer Square shop specializing in natural history, recommends
Salmon of the Pacific, by Adam Lewis (Raincoast Books; $14.95
paperback). The well-illustrated book introduces general readers to
salmon and their life cycles.
</P>
<P>
   - Trend: Pacific Northwest salmon stocks appear to have
rebounded a bit this year, at least partly helped by cyclical
changes in ocean conditions, according to reports. Yet two dozen
population groups in the region have been listed officially as
endangered. Puget Sound chinook, which is considered a Seattle
totem, joined the list just last March.
</P>
<P>
   - Excerpt: ``I am told by many of you that I must forgive and so
I shall after// that salmon leaps into the night air above the
water, throws// a lightning bolt at the brush near my feet, and
starts the fire// which will lead all of the lost Indians home//
...''
</P>
<P>
   _ Sherman Alexie, from ``The Powwow at the End of the World''
</P>
<P>
   - Object: ``Tulxoow,'' or ``Dog Salmon Robe,'' a
late-19th-century Tlingit garment, can be found in the permanent
collection of the Seattle Art Museum, First Avenue and University
Street; (206) 654-3100.
</P>
<P>
   - Event: Issaquah Salmon Days, first full weekend of October:
Family-oriented events, entertainment, a salmon bake and other
activities, most of them free, celebrate the salmon's return and
typically attract 200,000 people to this town east of Seattle off
Interstate 90. (This year's event was its 30th anniversary.)
Fish-watching is possible at a state hatchery there and on Issaquah
Creek throughout the town. Information: (425) 392-0661 or
www.salmondays.org
</P>
<P>
   - Eats: Hankering for a taste of the Northwest waters from your
own kitchen or grill? Some of Seattle's seafood purveyors will ship
their salmon (and other fish) overnight. Among them: Pike Place
Fish, (800) 542-7732 or www.pikeplacefish.com, and Wild Salmon Fish
Market, at the Fishermen's Terminal, 1-888-222-3474 or
www.wildsalmonseafood.com.
</P>
<P>
   Source: Poem excerpts from First Fish, First People: Salmon
Tales of the North Pacific Rim (One Reel//University of Washington
Press; $24.95 paperback).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
