<HEADER>
A6668 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-BOOKS-HEAT-MOON-KANSA     10-14 1334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-HEAT-MOON-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM LEAST HEAT-MOON CHRONICLES THE JOYS AND PERILS OF AN
AMERICAN JOURNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GEORGE GURLEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   River-Horse: The Log Book of a Boat Across America, by William
Least Heat-Moon (506 pages; Houghton Mifflin; $26)
</P>
<P>
   William Least Heat-Moon followed his peripatetic best seller,
Blue Highways, with PrairyErth, a ``deep map'' profile of Chase
County, Kan., that celebrated the wonders of a single place.
</P>
<P>
   He resumes his nomadic ways with River-Horse: The Log Book of a
Boat Across America (506 pages; Houghton Mifflin; $26), a magical
book that belongs among such American classics as the journals of
Lewis and Clark, Walden and Mark Twain's Mississippi River
writings.
</P>
<P>
   The cross-country saga unfolds aboard a 22-foot dory that
Heat-Moon named Nikawa, ``river horse'' in Osage. The narrative is
a web of adventures, anecdotes, encounters with colorful
characters, scraps of history, philosophical and lyrical musings
and occasional polemics against our depredations of the land. A
thread of humor runs through it all.
</P>
<P>
   The dream of this interior journey by rivers, lakes and canal
from Atlantic to Pacific _ more than 5,000 miles in a single season
_ was born in the creek that ran near Heat-Moon's boyhood home in
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``One afternoon, when I was 10 and messing about in it, I
suddenly realized it wasn't a dead end,'' Heat-Moon writes. ``That
flow around my ankles actually went somewhere. Just like a road, it
had a destination far beyond my sight.''
</P>
<P>
   Heat-Moon, of course, became a consummate American traveler: ``I
can now say I've visited every county in the contiguous United
States except for a handful in the Deep South, and those I'll get
to soon. Put your finger at random anyplace in this United States
atlas, and I've either been there or within twenty-five miles of
it, but for the desert of Nevada where the gap can be about twice
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years before Heat-Moon's Nikawa left Newark Bay, N.J., in
April 1995, the veteran roadrunner had another awakening that drove
him to watery highways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I noticed the web of faint azure lines, a varicose scribing of
my atlas,'' he writes in an echo of Marlowe's opening monologue in
Joseph Conrad's Heart of Darkness. ``They were rivers. I began
tracing those twistings in search of a way to cross America in a
boat.''
</P>
<P>
   Blue Highways and PrairyErth were solo efforts, and Heat-Moon
considers isolation ``almost a necessity for writers.'' But he
decided to invite friends along for River-Horse. They appear as a
``sequential composite'' character, Pilotis _ ``my pelorus of the
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   He wanted his trip to be a ``jolly'' one, and the running
dialogue between him and Pilotis provides much of the delightful
buoyancy of River-Horse. Like Don Quixote and Sancho Panza, the two
characters prod each other into friendly//disputatious banter.
Pilotis rises to the surface of a conversation ``like a hungry
pike'' and pursues ``thoughts as if they were mayflies,'' writes
Heat-Moon. Pilotis' prudence ``serves to raise my pluck.''
</P>
<P>
   Hiking in the Rocky Mountains, Heat-Moon takes a mouthful of
snow. ``There's one scoop of precipitation that won't make it to
the Atlantic,'' says Pilotis. Rethink that, says Heat-Moon. Pilotis
considers, then: ``Yes, I guess it still will _ unless we cross the
Divide tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pilotis device is a lovely evocation of friendship, a
friendship so close the two seem like poles of a single
personality.
</P>
<P>
   `Snowmelt imperative'
</P>
<P>
   Trees hurled by raging rivers, channels choked by nearly
impenetrable mazes of willows, violent weather and mechanical
problems threaten the passage of Nikawa. The crew cringes when
someone says ``things are going well.'' Great Ears _ the
cantankerous, vindictive Missouri River _ is sure to overhear and
make them pay.
</P>
<P>
   The ``snowmelt imperative'' _ the need to reach the Western
rivers in time to catch water running off the Rocky mountains _
gives the story a sense of urgency. River-Horse is not an idyll
about ``messing around in boats.'' It's a fear-haunted quest, a
race against time.
</P>
<P>
   When the action lags, Heat-Moon's writing keeps River-Horse
afloat. The Missouri is ``like a cross-grained grandfather,'' he
writes. It will ``do anything but bore us.'' An old fellow is
``pale as if he'd been partially erased.'' Adventure is ``putting
into motion one's ignorance.''
</P>
<P>
   Heat-Moon has a wonderful ear for dialogue. Waitresses
encountered along the way score some memorable lines: ``Now you
boys keep your mast up and your keel down,'' says one. (``Was that
sexual?'' wonders a crew member.)
</P>
<P>
   Heat-Moon doesn't exploit his Native American heritage _ he has
a bit of Osage blood _ but when it comes into play, you can hear an
eagle-bone whistle in his prose. On a riverbank stroll years before
this trip, about to give up looking for Indian pictographs, he
suddenly spots the Plains Indian sign for the Moon of Heat and
experiences another epiphany.
</P>
<P>
   ``On that eroded limestone was a drawing of my name. I realized
William Clark and Meriwether Lewis, whose names I also bear _
William Lewis Trogdon _ had seen it, the only piece of Indian
`picture writing' all of us _ red, white, mixed _ ever encountered.
A few months later, I moved to an old farm near the river bluffs,
and I began seriously hunting a water way across America.''
</P>
<P>
   Such coincidences are thematic in River-Horse. Whenever disaster
threatens, some saving agency intervenes. (According to Pilotis,
Heat-Moon's ``whilom wife'' said he's not smart, but he is lucky.)
In a stretch of unreadable river, the only man capable of guiding
them suddenly appears out of nowhere. ``You just got to look
ahead,'' Billy Joe Conrad tells them. Then he sits in the stern,
tells them he's blind in one eye and faces the wake where they've
been.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I'm not responsible if you hit something,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Characters as various and colorful as Canterbury pilgrims flow
through the pages of River-Horse. They meet a salesman more
interested in the problems of marketing store-brand detergent than
their quest and a ``loud, cigar-gnawing bantam'' official who won't
let them take Nikawa out of the flooding Missouri River. Strangers
rescue them, feed them and help them on their way. A chance meeting
with such a family on the river at Commerce, Mo., reads like a lost
chapter out of Huckleberry Finn.
</P>
<P>
   When Kansas City hoves into view, ``the city towers rose from
the river bluffs like Oz and gave us a remarkable riverscape,''
writes Heat-Moon. But he comes down hard on this city for
squandering its gift of nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kansas City, Missouri, is the preeminent city on the longest
river in America, but you would never know it from talking to the
inhabitants ... There is no spiritual link between them and it and
only a distant awareness of its connection to their iced tea,
potted geraniums, and baptized babies ... Kansas City, born of the
Missouri, has turned away from its great genetrix more than almost
any other river city in America.''
</P>
<P>
   River-Horse is an education, a rich book, a long book that I
wished were longer. It stirs a certain uneasiness of the kind
expressed on faces that watched the voyagers pass by. They
``betrayed a wistfulness, as if their lives were little more than
anchors.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the voyage, Heat-Moon lies down on warm soil
and muses in a fashion worthy of Melville's Ishmael: ``I thought
how far I was from where and when this journey began, how I was so
distant from that fellow passing for me 20 months ago, the one so
eager to learn the secrets of river passage. Could he _ the me of
that moment _ and I sit down together, he would want to know what I
knew and absorb what I had experienced, and he would regard me
enviously, just as I do those men who have returned from the moon.
But there would be forever a distance between him and me: I went
and he did not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
