<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-DENIM-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUE JEANS DANCE BACK INTO THE FASHION PICTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JACKIE WHITE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You could assume in today's space-age culture that 150-year-old
denim would fade into the background and like, say, big hair, the
color purple and mile-high stiletto heels, become merely the
favored choice of a few loyals.
</P>
<P>
   Not a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are jeans still a national uniform of sorts, but once
again, denim is also the hot topic on the fashion front.
</P>
<P>
   Almost everyone who is anyone in the apparel business is
offering a jeans line. Designer Anna Sui, for one example, launched
a new label this season.
</P>
<P>
   A significant number of the fashion media was decked out in
denim jeans jackets during the New York spring fashion week last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Then they watched high-end designers such as Oscar de la Renta,
Marc Jacobs and John Bartlett flood the spring runways with
everything from denim jeans suits to ballgown skirts and chemises.
</P>
<P>
   Two seasons earlier in Europe, Tom Ford's Gucci jeans, drenched
with a heavyweight dose of beaded embroidery and feathers, set off
the explosion of embellished denim. And just last week during the
French spring fashion collections, Christian Dior's designer John
Galliano sent out a high-cropped, belted denim jacket over a dress
cut from silk imprinted with jeans images.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk about shining moments. This is it for denim,'' declared
trade journal Women's Wear Daily in a special supplement recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``One beauty of the denim fabric,'' says Sarah Clancy, a product
developer with the Lee Co. in Merriam, ``is it can always take on a
different life.''
</P>
<P>
   As with most major fashion ideas, denim is a cyclical trend.
``Every time a designer doesn't know what to do, he pulls up denim
to stir up an audience,'' says Norman Karr, the executive director
of New York-based Jeanswear Communication, a public relations leg
of the jeans industry. ``The designer knows there is a universal
appeal. ... It's sort of, look what they've done to denim now.''
</P>
<P>
   Walk through most any department or discount store these days
and you'll fall into a sea of indigo _ dozens of shades from dark
to streaked to light _ with an overwhelming variety of labels and
styles ranging from boot cut and straight leg to the new, popular
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   And you can expect more to come. In the fashion category, dark
blue denim, which has been around awhile, is still a favorite. But
with fashion-oriented products capturing the consumer's attention,
you can expect to see a burst of new imaginative looks moving into
the forefront.
</P>
<P>
   Calvin Klein is marketing what he calls ``dirty denim'' for
spring 2000. It's stone-washed with a sanded finish, according to
Fairchild Publications. And Klein's product will come with a hang
tag that says it ``... looks and feels like it walked a thousand
miles, then crawled a few more. Lived a lifetime on horseback. Fell
off a motorcycle and got back up again ...''
</P>
<P>
   The Lee Co.'s version is called ``Metro denim,'' with two
finishes dubbed ``Corrosion'' and ``Petrol.'' Clancy says it is
sandblasted, laundered, sanded around the details and ultimately
washed with a colored tint.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the brightest spotlight is focused on decorated
denim. Reminiscent of the 1970s when denim was the canvas for
artistic adornment, jeans in stores are beaded, trimmed with silk
or contrasting fabrics, embroidered or printed. Hems are scalloped
or decked with prints.
</P>
<P>
   It's a decidedly more feminine look, says Tina Hodak, the
fashion director of the Jones Store parent company, who says the
adornment is driving the jeans resurgence.
</P>
<P>
   Other styling ideas involve cropped pants or cutoffs below the
knee. And spring is expected to bring high-rise ``flood pants.''
</P>
<P>
   But the jeans are only part of the story. The influence is also
lying heavily on the collective minds of the fashion industry. It's
like the practice of some designers and manufacturers who found
success by fashioning familiar sportswear shapes into luxurious
fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   Welt seaming and stitching, almost everyone's skinny pants in
leather or sequins, and jeanslike short jackets are some examples
of the impact, says Gregg Andrews, fashion director with Nordstrom
stores. ``It has a life unto itself,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   And denim is being mixed with silks and rayons to produce a
sheen. ``It makes it look a little dressier and the jeans are worn
with beaded tops and strappy sandals,'' Andrews notes.
</P>
<P>
   Is denim selling? Fashionable looks, yes. Basics have been
``soft,'' says Kathy Bradley-Riley, sportswear merchandise group
manager for Doneger, New York-based retail consultants.
</P>
<P>
   Troubles at Levi Strauss, which has closed some European plants
and laid off workers, have illuminated the difficulties of an
apparel business that often turns on a trend. Most observers put
blame on Levi's internal problems and perhaps the company's
inability to stay in touch with the customers and move quickly on
trends. Nevertheless, the company is introducing several labels
that include the basics and the decidedly trendy.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, jeans sales are up about 3 percent to 4 percent over
last year, Karr says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
