<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 11:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6672 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-BORDERS-COLUMN15-COX     10-14 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clearing up an earlier news story
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ ``Texas Constitution 2000'' is a small
group of people with a big idea: persuade 176 out of 254 counties
in the state to ratify a roughly 20-page proposed state
constitution to replace the present document. Why 176 counties?
Because the proportion of 176 out of 254 is the same percentage as
the nine of 13 colonies that were required to ratify the U.S.
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Sabine County was the first county to ``ratify'' this
constitution a few weeks ago, when 16 people showed up at the
ratification convention, held at the Fairmount Volunteer Fire
Department outside of Hemphill, the county seat. Attendees say the
vote among the 16 was unanimous. One down, 175 to go. Next stop,
according to a press release sent from the group last week, is
neighboring San Augustine.
</P>
<P>
   I pointed out to Wes Burnett, one of the writers of the proposed
constitution and a fellow newspaper publisher in West Texas, that
16 people is not an overwhelming number. He countered by saying the
event was well publicized, with the proposed constitution inserted
into the Sabine County paper, and several ads run announcing the
meeting. His analogy was to voter turnout: There's no requirement
that a minimum number of voters show up at the polls for an
election to be valid. Maybe so, but 16 is a pretty slim number for
ratifying a constitution, even in tiny Sabine County.
</P>
<P>
   There have been numerous efforts to rewrite the state's current
constitution, in existence since 1876. At the time, the Legislature
was dominated by rural interests who distrusted the big-city
politicians and drafted a document that compels voters to decide
matters usually decided by legislatures. That's why our
constitution has nearly 400 amendments, and why we'll head to the
polls again next month to consider another dozen or so proposed
amendments. As state Rep. Jim McReynolds (D-San Augustine) put it,
Texas has a cumbersome process that is probably not the most
democratic way to do things, since amendment-only elections
typically have turnouts of less than 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Bill Ratliff (R-Mount Pleasant) agrees. He and San
Angelo Democratic Rep. Rob Junell took a shot at rewriting the
constitution during the last session, an effort that went
absolutely nowhere. Ratliff told me last week that there are only
two ways to rewrite the constitution:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Legislature can hold a constitutional convention, as was
attempted in the 1970s;
</P>
<P>
   _ Or the entire constitution can be rewritten by one giant
amendment that would in effect replace the existing document, the
tact Ratliff and Junell tried.
</P>
<P>
   Either way the voters would have to approve a new document.
Ratliff doubts he'll try again in 2001, noting drily that ``the
Legislature doesn't particularly act in the absence of crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   There may not be a crisis, but eventually, as McReynolds said,
Texas is going to have to rewrite its constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Ratliff nor McReynolds had heard of Texas Constitution
2000, but both are understandably skeptical of the effort, mainly
because holding ``ratification meetings'' in separate counties
isn't described as a way that the constitution can be rewritten. I
suspect their skepticism will increase if and when they read the
proposed constitution. It would be a radical change. Under the
proposed new constitution:
</P>
<P>
   _ Texas in effect would become a separate nation and secede from
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   _ Taxation would be prohibited, and the government would exist
on voluntary contributions.
</P>
<P>
   _ No types of gun control would be permitted. You could own a
cruise missile if you wished and had the money.
</P>
<P>
   _ Texas would be prohibited from issuing currency. The new
nation would presumably have to rely on the gold standard.
</P>
<P>
   _ All ``foreign agents,'' including federal officers of the FBI,
DEA, etc. would be required to leave once the new constitution went
into effect.
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty more, and you can read if for yourself on the
Internet at www.tcrf.com.
</P>
<P>
   I called the toll-free number and talked to Dan Hollis, who is
on the ratification committee. He admitted I was the first person
to call the number, which just became active last week. I asked the
obvious question: Say this group actually manages to get this
ratified by holding meetings in 176 counties. Does anyone actually
believe the state of Texas will simply hand over the reins of
power?
</P>
<P>
   Well, no. Hollis doesn't know what would happen next, though he
assured me his group's motives are entirely peaceful, a sentiment
echoed by publisher Burnett.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're advocating is a lawful and peaceful transition from
what we have now,'' Hollis said.
</P>
<P>
   I find it sad that there are intelligent people out there who
feel so utterly alienated from our government. I'm no fan of
government; far too often, it's incompetent, overly intrusive and
uncaring. But I don't view government as the enemy, and I believe
it does a great deal of good. Government, through our taxes, funds
public schools, maintains roads, offers our children a college
education at a reasonable price, provides fire protection, runs
libraries and does a myriad other things. The idea of living in a
society without a representative government has no appeal to me _
though like most folks I think I pay too much in taxes.
</P>
<P>
   That people are able to band together and espouse such radical
notions without fear of prosecution or retribution is proof that
our system of government, however imperfect, is that best man has
been able to create. Messrs. Hollis, Burnett and company are
perfectly free to try, peacefully, to change our form of
government, to talk people into adopting a constitution that would
radically change our way of operating.
</P>
<P>
   I just think they're flat wrong, but I'll go to my grave
defending their right to say what they please.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Daily Sentinel in
Nacogdoches, Texas. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
