<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In Mexico, the idea of a free press takes hold
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ The air in this urban behemoth has been thick for
years, but in the past few has carried a whiff of democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Nationalist sentiment has always been part of Mexican political
rhetoric, but those words seldom matched the reality of a political
monopoly run for the benefit of the very few. These days, however,
you can see, feel and hear manifestations of political competition.
</P>
<P>
   It used to be that the nomination of the Partido Revolucionario
Institucional (the Institutional Revolutionary Party) was
tantamount to victory. No longer.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican press, so timid in criticizing government for so
long, is flexing editorial muscle.
</P>
<P>
   The road to democracy in Mexico has been widened, and there is
no turning back. What is amazing is the sudden nature of that shift
in political culture.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI dominance has been cracking as opposition parties
captured municipal and state power and won seats in the Congress.
These days, Mexicans are living proof that once you give people a
taste of democracy, they get hungry for more.
</P>
<P>
   The democratization movement is fueled by advances in technology
that make it possible for information to travel quickly and
broadly, making a mockery of borders, making it easy for people to
compare and contrast all facets of life.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican newspapers, for example, are looking north for new
models. The Mexico City daily, La Reforma turned to Max Jennings,
former editor of the Dayton Daily News, who spent months in the
Mexican capital, training the staff on news gathering North
American style.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Francisco Ealy Ortiz, the larger-than-life publisher of El
Universal, another Mexico City daily, used the 30th anniversary of
his administration earlier this month as a platform from which to
demand freedom of information and public-records legislation. Now
in its 83rd year, El Universal underwent an extensive format change
with the help of the American Press Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the newspaper's staff has been undergoing an overhaul
as well. Roberto Rock, editor of El Universal, joked with a group
of visiting North American newspaper editors that the staff used to
be so old that those wanting a job at the newspaper would scheme to
induce turnover. ``They plot to leave windows open in the winter
hoping that someone would catch pneumonia,'' he cracked.
</P>
<P>
   The staff is younger _ average age about 31 _ and better
educated. Moreover, they do business differently. Mexican
journalists of yesteryear generally fell into two very broad
categories: those who would trade favorable coverage for cash and
those who would probe relentlessly.
</P>
<P>
   Those who fell into the latter category could expect to be
threatened, harassed or killed.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a reporter for La Tarde was shot 12 times _ nine
times in the face _ as he walked down the street. No one can say
who did it.
</P>
<P>
   So for both political and professional reasons, Ealy's push on
press freedom issues is bold talk indeed, but the publisher is a
bold man.
</P>
<P>
   He is bright, articulate, well-connected and certainly
self-assured. He talks of fighting the enemies of El Universal for
the past 30 years and coming out on top. It was surely no
coincidence that each musical group hired to entertain _ and he
hired a bunch of them, everything from mariachis to a full
orchestra _ during a three-day bash to celebrate his three decades
of leadership played ``My Way.''
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, however, newspapers like El Universal play to
a small, affluent crowd. The medium with real reach is radio. As in
North America, talk radio in Mexico is very popular. That doesn't
mean, however, that politicians can ignore Ealy.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican talk-radio hosts, like their North American
counterparts, use newspapers as a springboard into their topics, so
while the direct influence may be limited, the indirect influence
is more widespread.
</P>
<P>
   Cynics may like to think that this democracy craze is
transitory, that it's possible for Mexico to return to old
political ways. It is not likely.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Ealy and other Mexican newspaper publishers, editors and
reporters truly have it their way in the future remains very much
to be seen. Nonetheless, the signs today are quite promising.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Garcia is the editorial page editor of the Austin
American-Statesman. He can be reached at agarcia(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
