<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sizing up early favorites to fill Luna's Senate seat
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ It's always a gift to state representatives when
a state senator chooses to resign in midterm rather than simply not
run for re-election. The early resignation gives them a shot at
moving up to the Texas Senate without giving up their House seats.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Greg Luna (D-San Antonio), who has represented the
center-city 26th District since 1992, resigned Sept. 24 for health
reasons. Gov. George W. Bush has called a special election for Nov.
2, to coincide with the vote on 17 proposed constitutional
amendments. If none of the Senate candidates gets a majority, the
governor will call a runoff a few weeks later between the top two
finishers, regardless of party.
</P>
<P>
   State Reps. Leticia Van de Putte, 44, and Leo Alvarado Jr., 60,
both Democrats, were among the five candidates who filed as of the
Oct. 4 filing deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Robert Puente, the dean of the San Antonio House
delegation, whose legislative district overlapped much less with
the Senate district than the other two, passed up the race because
of a young family and busy law practice. He would have had Luna's
support had he run.
</P>
<P>
   Luna, 66, was rumored to have been planning to retire after the
legislative session anyway _ and now his diabetes has caused him to
have both legs amputated in August. He had served eight years in
the Texas House of Representatives before election to the Texas
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Luna had missed much of the 1999 session because of
complications from his diabetes _ though at one point he had asked
that if a vote on vouchers was to be taken, he be given time to get
there, even if it was on a stretcher, to vote ``no.''
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio observers consider the race to be between the two
state representatives, and the question appears to be whether Van
de Putte, a pharmacist, will win it without a runoff. Alvarado is
recovering from esophageal cancer, and the main question seems to
be whether he will dip into his own pocket to finance negative
attacks against his colleague.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Lauro Bustamante, 48, a lawyer, also has filed to run.
He's a cousin of former U.S. Rep. Albert Bustamante, but any
benefit he picks up from sharing the surname is colored by his
cousin's defeat for re-election to Congress in 1992 in a cloud of
scandal over bribery allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Also running for the Senate seat are Republicans Mark Weber, 40,
who lists himself as self-employed, and Anne Newman, 52, a
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   The two Republicans are considered on the conservative side of
the Republican Party and are not expected to have much chance. The
26th ranks among the most Democratic-leaning of Texas' 31 Senate
districts.
</P>
<P>
   One question is how much an election on whether to pay for a new
sports arena for San Antonio with an increased hotel/motel/rental
car tax might have on the Senate election.
</P>
<P>
   Although Republicans normally turn out better than Democrats for
special elections, stadium backers are expected to spend money to
get Hispanic voters to the polls, because they tend to favor the
stadium. They also tend to favor Democrats, and the district is 65
percent Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   While a state representative does not have to give up his or her
seat to run in the special election, Van de Putte says she'll run
for the Senate seat next year even if she loses the special
election.
</P>
<P>
   Two candidates are already campaigning for Van de Putte's House
seat. Municipal Court Judge Robbie Vazquez resigned Oct. 2 in order
to be ready to run, and Mike Villareal, a computer database
developer, has already sent out a fund-raising letter signed by
former Mayors Henry Cisneros and Nelson Wolff.
</P>
<P>
   Trey Fischer, a lawyer, is looking at Alvarado's House seat, as
is John Elizondo, son of County Commissioner Paul Elizondo, a
former state representative. Others are expected to jump in.
</P>
<P>
   And so on . . . Sen. Judith Zaffirini, D-Laredo, who had been
pondering retiring, now says she'll seek re-election. That
sidelined the potential races of state Rep. Henry Cuellar
(D-Laredo) and former state Rep. Richard Raymond (D-Benavides), who
lost a statewide race last year for land commissioner. Both had
been gearing up for a Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at
dmcneely(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
