</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Why is it news when Christians talk environmentalism?
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ They came from all over the country _ authors,
scientists, scholars. They jammed reams of research and analysis
into two days, all focused on a riveting modern-day discovery:
</P>
<P>
   Christianity and environmentalism: Same thing!
</P>
<P>
   A equals B equals A. Take one. Substitute the other. Dismiss
one, dismiss both.
</P>
<P>
   Call it a modern-day discovery because any distinction seemed
silly centuries back, when man was tied so closely to the land.
Native Americans were Franciscans. They just didn't know it. Yes,
they took down a buffalo or two, but never three or four _ hundred
thousand.
</P>
<P>
   Saint Francis of Assisi, who many believe came as close to
perfection as any mortal, saw nature as his altar, his temple, his
place of worship. One would hear analogies over and over at
``Caring for Creation,'' a Baylor University conference
co-sponsored by the Baptist General Convention of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   For God so loved the world, interpreted
author/pastor/activist/TV host Tony Campolo for the Baylor
audience, that he gave his only begotten son to ``rescue his
messed-up creation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we take the Bible seriously, we'll be environmentalists,''
he said. We will hear the songs of whales as hymns. We will see the
torching of rain forests as pagan sacrifice. We will oppose
environmental degradation not just because it spoils God's gifts
but because the poor _ ``the least of these'' _ are most sure to
suffer.
</P>
<P>
   The conference was the first of a series sponsored by the BGCT
and reflects a break-out mentality among some believers.
</P>
<P>
   These Christians seemingly have one word they must battle: the
``dominion'' that Genesis 1:28 gives man over all, from prairie dog
to sea urchin.
</P>
<P>
   But only a foolish king would gobble up all the sea urchins like
jelly beans, disrupting food chains, setting off chains of gradual
cataclysm.
</P>
<P>
   Hence a working Christian term to sustain all: stewardship.
</P>
<P>
   As a bumper sticker at the conference read, a symbolic fish in
the center: ``Extinction is not stewardship.''
</P>
<P>
   Dudley Burton, chairman of the Baylor Department of
Environmental Studies, hosted a discussion on sustainability _ the
paradigm of consuming and conserving that leaves something there
for all in need and for future generations.
</P>
<P>
   As crucial and theological as this concept may be, ``The Baptist
Church has not been at the forefront of this movement,'' bemoaned
Burton.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see why churches might take a pass, judging by the
chief motivation that drives every day but Sunday. Greed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Homo-economicus'' is how University of Northern Arizona
Professor and author Max Oelschlaeger terms our modern-day bent. We
are defined not as inspired beings or stewards, but as consumers,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our freedom comes from picking Coke or Pepsi.''
</P>
<P>
   Criticism like this runs counter to the American way,
acknowledged Campolo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frugality is a subversive lifestyle,'' he said. And when the
greatest good is stated not by Scripture but by the Dow, the
disciples of ``ecumenical environmentalism'' have their work cut
out.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say that Pat Robertson and the Christian Coalition
can't talk about environmentalism without attaching ``radical'' to
the term.
</P>
<P>
   Why is it a news flash when Christian scholars get together to
discuss reverence for the gifts that manifest their maker?
</P>
<P>
   It may be that though Americans claim vociferously to be of
faith, most of them of Protestantism, they have their ``isms''
misaligned. Stewardship is for accountants. Faith is in the gold
standard. Capitalism is the one true religion.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
