<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Friday, October
15, 1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors can focus on one day's budget, CoxNet
produces themed features budgets each day. Here is the schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive, personal finance and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion and science &AMP; health
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   SAVE TIME: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available for
purchase in paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   HIGHPOINT _ HIGH POINT, N.C. _ Ready or not, here comes the
much-hyped year 2000, when stores were expected to roll out Space
Age furnishing designed for ``homes of the future.'' So what's
La-Z-Boy, known for its cutting-ege designs, pitching for next
spring? Try a wooden folding chair. Today as the world's largest
furniture market opens in High Point, N.C., with a preview of the
newest designs, this chair is bare-bones comfort. Trends aside, the
buzz at this market are the celebrities _ authors, artist,
designers, all lending their names to new collections. (Flanders,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BILINGUAL-BABIES _ Infant education in a second language is
catching on around the world, giving a whole new meaning to the
question: how low can they go? The Language Workshop for Children
in New York, for example, starts infants at six months. The
Atlanta-based Primrose Schools Franchising Company, with 70 schools
in seven states, includes Spanish in its core curiculum for 4- and
5-year-olds. We hone in on Kidspeak International. Based in Inman
Park, the four-year-old program dispatches 20 instructors of French
and Spanish to schools and pre-schools around the metro area,
specializing in teaching the very young. (Hulbert, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL_ (EDS: This is the CoxNet TRAVEL page for the
current week.)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL 1012 -- Inside North America's first shoe museum
is the world's largest, most comprehensive collection of shoes and
shoe-related objects. (Moss, Dayton Daily News). Art includes
3-column color photo of museum, three 1-column color photos of
fancy shoes and color headline graphic treatment.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL NEWS -- The Bahamas' colonial capital is quiet now.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Floyd's 150-plus-mph winds have ceased; the seas are
as calm as a lake, and at most hotels, it's business as usual,
although the pools and beaches are far from crowded. (Blackerby,
The Palm Beach Post). Art includes 2-colomn color photo from a
damaged resort in the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL BRIEFS _ Call it the garage sale of the century. Under a
huge tent set up on the Place de la Bastille, the Opera de Paris
will empty its bulging wardrobes and sell off 10,000 ballet and
opera costumes. (N.Y. Times News Service)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLORADO _MONTROSE, Colo. _ For any hike into the Black
Canyon of the Gunnison National Monument in Colorado, you must get
a backcountry permit. That's so park rangers can keep track of who
goes in. A pamphlet on hiking the inner canyon offers this chipper
bit of advice: ``Hikers are expected to find their own way and be
prepared for self-rescue.'' Self-rescue? Of the 220,000 people who
visit the monument each year, only about 3,000 accept the challenge
to hike in, says Paul Zaenger, a supervisory ranger at the
monument. ``It's a very demanding thing,'' he says. (Abramson,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 17.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY _ Black Rock Mountain State Park is one of autumn's
first stops in Georgia. Located north of Clayton not far from the
North Carolina border, the1,800-acre parcel of mountaintops is
Georgia's highest state park. The summit of Black Rock Mountain is
3,640 feet above sea level and most overnight visitors sleep above
3,000 feet. (Willams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-RED _ Women are seeing red so much the color has
replaced black as a must-have for fall. Here are some red hot looks
and tips on how to pull the color off. (Hill, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 10. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MAKEUP-THERAPY _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Any old lipstick can
colorize your mouth. A really great lipstick can ``calm and
revitalize your evolving mind.'' At least that's what the folks at
Tony &AMP; Tina's Vibrational Remedies believe. The fledgling makeup
company sells Mood Balance Lipstick, Color Frequency Eye Shadow,
Cosmic Lights powder and New Age wisdom. And, yes, they're serious.
(Sturrock, Palm Beach Post). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DENIM-FASHIONS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In the past few years,
the jeans business has been fueled by different shapes. Surely
you've worn or have studiously avoided one of the following: Legs
so wide they could easily slip over an elephant's foot; low-slung
waists that flirt with disaster; or highwater hems that bare the
meatiest part of your calves. Now, jeans are getting kicked in the
back pocket by a slew of new details that render them either more
refined or more rugged. (Sturrock, Palm Beach Post). MOVED. WITH
SIDEBARS
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAIN _ (EDS: This is the CoxNet ENTERTAIN page for
the current week. This layout is available today after 2 p.m. EDT.)
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAINMENT 1014 -- Wanna win a million bucks or maybe
just a measly $64,000? Well, you're about to have a lot more
chances _ or at least have the thrill of watching others get rich
quick. In the wake of ABC's phenomenally successful summer
experiment ``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire,'' the other networks
have several game shows in the pipeline. (Holloway, Austin
American-Statesman) Art includes one 3-column color photo of Regis
Philbin holding a wad of money, a 1-column color photo from ``Win
Ben Stein's Money,'' a 6-pica B&AMP;W photo of ``The Gong Show.''
</P>
<P>
   WITH: GAME SHOW LIST -- A list and decriptions of the greatest
TV game shows. (Holloway, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: GAME SHOW HISTORY -- A look at TV game shows through the
years. (Holloway, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: STAR FILE -- A Q&AMP;A with Molly Shannon, the latest
``Saturday Night Live'' star to appear in a movie. (Staff, Cox News
Service) Art includes a 1-column color photo of Molly Shannon.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: VIDEO REVIEWS -- Reviews of new video releases including
``10 Things I Hate about You,'' ``SLC Punk'' and ``The Rage: Carrie
2.'' (Staff, Cox News Service) Art includes 18-pica color photo
from ``10 Things I Hate about You.''
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CD REVIEWS -- Reviews of new CD releases from Indigo
Girls, 311 and Doug Stone. (Staff, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS _ (EDS: This is the CoxNet Books page for the
current week.) COXNET BOOKS 1012 -- Jedediah Purdy thinks like
Robert Frost and writes like Bertrand Russell. He looks like the
boy next door, the healthy and happy kid who wins all the school
awards and helps his dad fix the roof and his mom tend her garden.
His book has caught the publishing industry, pundits and perhaps
America napping. It might be waking them all up. (Reid, Palm Beach
Post) Art includes 3-column B&AMP;W photo of author and 2-column color
photo of book.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW WILLS -- Gary Wills' ``A Necessary Evil'' reads
like a history prof's lecture notes converted too quickly into book
form. (Bookman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW BAD EYE BLUES -- A new novel by Neal Barrett Jr.,
titled ``Bad Eye Blues'' is outrageous, downright silly in places,
has an impossible plot and often unbelievable characters, but I
couldn't put the darn thing down until I'd finished it. (Milner,
The Lufkin Daily News) Art includes 6-pica color photo of book
jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SKUBE ON BOOKS -- Legendary coach Vince Lombardi's family
life wasn't in the same league as the Packers. (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) Art includes 1-column color photo of
columnist and 6-pica color photo of book jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-ON-BOOKS _ ``We were getting calls from people hundreds a
miles away, people who couldn't even pronounce his name,'' Emory's
Claire Nouvet said moments before he would walk unassumingly from
the wings and begin to speak. ``We even got e-mails from New
Zealand.'' It's not every day that star power is given to a
philosopher, but this was Jacques Derrida, pied piper of literary
criticism for 20 years or more, enfant terrible of the strange
phenomenon known as deconstruction. Derrida came to Atlanta
recently to give the keynote lecture at Emory University's
International Symposium on Jean-Francois Lyotard, professor of
philosophy and French at Emory before his death in April 1998.
(Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 27.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, OCT. 17
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-MORRISON _ Toni Morrison on getting ``Those Bones Are Not
My Child'' into print. Also, a first look at the novel. (Boyd,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 62.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, OCT. 17
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ In a letter to his son in 1900, Joel Chandler
Harris bemoaned the fact that people no longer wrote letters.
``They dictate dispatches and scribble messages,'' he said. ``When
you are in the humor, you should take a peep at some of the letters
written by people long ago.'' In ``Letters of a Century,'' that's
exactly what Lisa Grunwald and Stephen Adler have done. The result
is a fascinating compilation of correpsondence from folks ranging
from presidents (Theodore Roosevelt, Harry Truman) to Elvis and
Groucho Marx. (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-MILNER _ Jay Milner's review of a recently released book.
(Milner, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   EYMAN-ON-BOOKS _ Oxford Press reissues classics in paperback.
(Eyman, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-RIDLEY _ Review of the book ``Everybody Smokes in Hell,''
by John Ridley. It's a title that promises a lot, and by God,
Ridley delivers. (Eyman, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-MCCAIN _ Review of book ``Faith of My Fathers,'' by John
McCain. It's a Vietnam War Story about John McCain's father and
gradfather, both Navy admirals, and the strength he took from them
as he stuggled to stay alive for more than five years as a prisoner
of war in Vietnam. (Crowley, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-GLYNN _ Long before Tom Brokaw's bestseller ``The Greatest
Generation'' recorded memories of Americans during World War II,
Sonja Kinard, 66, set out with her sister, Thora Kimsey, to record
the same kind of slice of life, focusing on what then was the tiny
port town of Brunswick in south Georgia. And they found out that,
for many residents of coastal Georgia, World War II really started
on April 8, 1942, four months to the day after Congress declared
war on Japan. They began interviewing coastal residents, and asking
others to record their memories, which they've recorded in a new
book, ``Memories from The Marshes of Glynn: World War II,'' which
will hit bookstores this week. It's a vivid, poignant, even painful
account that paints a picture of shows how small town people
handled, physically and mentally, what for most was the most
traumatic period of their lives, a time when what seemed like a
faraway war came to Georgia, literally. (Hendrick, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-TRENDS _ Today is not just another opening weekend at the
movies. Debuting across the country is mainstream Hollywood's
controversial ``Fight Club'' with Brad Pitt and a hefty $65 million
budget. Some advance screening audiences have slammed the film,
dubbing it socially irresponsible for its graphic depiction of
bloody pugilism in the wake of the Columbine and Buckhead
shootings. But also starting today is ``The Omega Code,'' an $8.5
million movie with name stars and a distinct religious message.
``Code'' is financed partly by Trinity Broadcasting Network, which
not only has used Hollywood talent to make a film patterened after
the Bible's book of Revelations, but is unabashedly promoting the
movie on its network, urging its Christian viewers to buy tickets
en mass. And many seem to be responding. More than 1,000 ``Omega
Code'' tickets, for instance, have been sold for weekend showings
at Regal's megaplex at the Mall of Georgia. Trinity's goal is not
to attack Hollywood to force changes in film content, but to join
the moneymaking machine and create Bible-based movies for an
untapped audience. (Longino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-FIGHT _ Movie review: ``Fight Club'' with Brad Pitt,
Edward Norton and Helena Bonham Carter about a secret confab where
guys beat each other to bloody pulps. It's a guy-flick kick, but a
controversial film that will likely turn off as many moviegoers as
it enthralls. Grade: A-. (Murray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
(Reviews also available to Cox papers from Dayton, West Palm.)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-US _ Movie review: ``The Story of Us.'' 15 years in the
life of an American family. With Bruce Willis and Michelle
Pfeiffer. Grade: B-. (Longino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-HAPPY _ Movie review: ``Happy, Texas.'' Two convicts
escape and pose as gay pageant directors in a small Texas town.
It's funny. GRADE: B+ (Ringel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-LIMEY _ Movie review: ``The Limey.'' Action/drama with
Terrence Stamp as Englander looking for culprits involved in his
daughter's death. Grade: A-. (Ringel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-ROMANCE _ Movie review: ``Romance.'' Is it art or porno.
Controversial unrated French film about apparently disturbed
woman's erotic adventures that descends into bondage and rape. And
it's not a very good movie. Grade: D. (Ringel, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-SOURCE _ Movie review: ``The Source.'' Documentary about
the Beat poets. Grade: C+. (Murray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-SIEGFRIED _ Movie review: 3-D Imax version of ``Siegfried
&AMP; Roy.'' (Longino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-FANATIC _ Review of ``My Son the Fanatic.'' (Luksic,
Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS _ Mini reviews of all currently playing
movies. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TELEVISION
</P>
<P>
   TV-SURVIVOR-COMMENTARY _ Commentary on CBS' new show
``Survivor,'' where 16 people are dropped on a deserted island with
no food, shelter, water or tools. The lone survivor wins $1million.
We talk to the producer and comment on this latest example of
Extreme TV. (Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   TV-CAULFIELD _ Review of ``Ryan Caulfield: Year One'' _ Fox's
new show that needs to succeed in the wake of the shaky start of
the season for the network. The show is about a young man who
chooses to be a cop instead of going to college. It's not very
good. (Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
