<P>
   SCOUTS-GAYS (San Francisco) _ An important board of the United
Methodist Church has taken a stand against the Boy Scouts' ban on
gays, intensifying the rift over homosexuality in one of the
nation's biggest denominations. By CAROL NESS.
</P>
<P>
   UNABOMBER-BROTHER _ (Albany, N.Y.) _ David Kaczynski has a deal
with a Los Angeles company for a movie about his life and a pivotal
moment in 1996: when he turned in his brother, Ted Kaczynski, the
Unabomber. The film will focus on Schenectady, N.Y., residents
David Kaczynski and his wife, Linda Patrik, who will be consultants
on the project. By CHRIS STURGIS.
</P>
<P>
   PATAKI-TOBACCO (Albany, N.Y.) _ The head of the
Hungarian-American Chamber of Commerce U.S.A. defends the group's
sponsorship of two trips that New York Gov. George E. Pataki took
to Hungary, saying she has no idea why a giant tobacco company
donated $10,000 to the chamber before each of those visits. By
DANIELLE FURFARO and EDWARD FITZPATRICK.
</P>
<P>
   DUTCH-AMERICA-HISTORY (Albany, N.Y.) _ For four hundred years,
the pages of this city's history have survived multiple fires,
years in a damp ship's hold, age, theft, neglect and hungry rats.
Now, 12,000 fragile pages minutely describing life in Dutch America
will be cleaned by experts and made sturdy enough to be handled by
the public. By ALAN WECHSLER.
</P>
<P>
   BREAST-CANCER (San Francisco) _ A conference Saturday on ways to
prevent and treat breast cancer by integrating Western medicine
with traditional healing practices will emphasize inclusion of
underserved minorities. By MARSHA GINSBURG.
</P>
<P>
   ANTI-ALCOHOL-AD (San Francisco) _ Contra County, Calif.,
residents and the Marin Institute for the Prevention of Alcohol and
Other Drug Problems are fighting a billboard company's refusal to
display an anti-alcohol advertisement in the county that
discourages under-aged drinking. By ANDREA WOO.
</P>
<P>
   SF-MAYORAL (San Francisco) _ Mayoral candidate Clint Reilly's
effort to raise more cash in his campaign has led a federal judge
to block a 1995 measure approved by San Francisco voters to rein in
spending in such races. By ILENE LELCHUK.
</P>
<P>
   HUMAN-RIGHTS (San Francisco) _ Six months after the FBI stepped
up its probe of the San Francisco Human Rights Commission's
handling of minority contracting and more than a year after the
city made its own inquiry into mismanagement, the troubled agency's
11 commissioners are focusing on the director. By JULIE CHAO.
</P>
