<SLUG> BC-TV-ER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALDA BURNISHES HIS MD FOR APPEARANCE ON `ER' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   He is now the grizzled veteran, 63 (63!), his shoulders more
stooped tha The white lab coat is still there, but he has
traded in his green fatigues for blue scrubs.
</P>
<P>
   One of television's most famous doctors is back into the chaotic
fray, of both a hospital and network television, at least for a
month or so.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Alda joined ``ER'' (NBC) Thursday night for the first
installment of a five-episode run. The hotshot young gun who was
Hawkeye Pierce is now the mentor, Dr. Ted Lawrence, a new attending
physician brought into the Chicago hospital by one-time student Dr.
Kerry Weaver (Laura Innes).
</P>
<P>
   After ``M-A-S-H'' (not to be confused with the dreadful spinoff
``AfterMASH''), Alda continued what has become a solid screen and
stage career. Among his post-Hawkeye highlights, Alda lists his
performance in the Broadway play ``Art,'' and his recently filmed
run on ``ER.'' Alda, who won Emmys as an actor, director and writer
for ``M-A-S-H,'' said the decision to return, albeit briefly, to
network television was not a hard one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said yes without reading anything,'' he said in a telephone
interview last week. ``The reason was is because I'm so impressed
with what I see on the air. Some of the sequences are some of the
best things I've ever seen on television. I'm in this wonderful
position that I can do things that are wonderful to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Expect tension to develop quickly between Lawrence (Alda) and
Dr. Mark Greene (Anthony Edwards).
</P>
<P>
   ``(Lawrence) is a teacher,'' Alda said. ``This character helped
invent ER medicine. He is one of the pioneers. He knows how it goes
and he likes to tell people. Some of the people who know how to do
it their way maybe don't want to hear it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the story, (Weaver) is the one who brings me into the
hospital. I was her mentor,'' Alda said. ``She had to hire him in a
hurry. She didn't really check it out with the Mark Greene
character. So he is not too happy about it.''
</P>
<P>
   When pressed, Alda said he can see some similarities between the
two medical shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see roots in `ER' that go back to `M-A-S-H,' and I think
they are aware of that,'' Alda said. ``There were things in
`M-A-S-H' they wanted to pick up on and carry forward. There is a
greater frankness about the wounds, for instance. And there is a
greater reliance on the technical talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``(But) the medicine that we were dealing with on `M-A-S-H' was
medicine of 50 years ago. The terms were different, the procedures
were different. For me it was a whole new world.''
</P>
<P>
   Alda is still seen regularly on television, as the host of the
PBS series ``Scientific American Frontiers,'' which taps into his
childhood fascination with science.
</P>
<P>
   So could the man who played one of the most legendary television
characters in history ever see himself returning to a network
series full time? ``I love working with these people (on `ER'),''
Alda said. ``But the idea of going in every day on a series, I
don't think ... I don't picture that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if I ever did picture it, I couldn't picture it unless it
was with people like this, because they are tops,'' Alda said. An
open door for a return? ``They left it open _ a crack,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His electronic mail
address is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
