<HEADLINE>
IN MEXICAN WORK FORCE, PREGNANCY IS PUNISHED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ After working 10 years as an accountant for a shoe
manufacturer, Carmen Rodriguez was dismissed because she was about
to have her second child.
</P>
<P>
   Maria, a successful 29-year-old sales representative for a
US-based cosmetics company, was fired without severance pay when
her bosses found out she was two months pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   Even though she passed a typing drill and two job interviews,
Ana Barbara Solis, 27, wasn't allowed to start work at a medical
supply firm until she provided a doctor's certificate stating that
she wasn't pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   Stories like these are heard everywhere in Mexico, where despite
the influx of tens of thousands of women into the country's work
force over the past three decades, public and private managers
routinely punish female employees for being pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   But three weeks ago, a glimmer of hope emerged when Mexico
City's first female mayor took power. In one of her first official
acts, Mayor Rosario Robles signed an order into the city's penal
code that would fine businesses that require pregnancy tests or
that fire an employee because she is pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The practice has continued, for years even by some branches of
US companies doing business here, despite heavy criticism from
human rights advocates and US government officials.
</P>
<P>
   Robles is trying to change a culture that often exacts an
emotional, physical and financially devastating price on a working
woman who is expecting.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the consequences, based on testimony gathered by women's
support groups, have included forced abortions, divorce and, most
often, dismissals from their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important that you have something that you can arm
yourself with against these businesses,'' said Maria, who asked
that her full name _ and that of her former employer _ not be
published for fear of retribution. ``These company decisions are
being made by people with no scruples.''
</P>
<P>
   The new law would require those who violate the antipregnancy
discrimination code to serve from 100 hours of community service to
three years in prison. In the most serious cases, a business can be
shut down, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's constitution prohibits discrimination, although
newspaper help wanted ads typically state up-front the age, gender,
marital status and ``presentability,'' that an applicant should
have. But labor laws do not specifically mention pregnancy tests or
dismissals based on pregnancy, a loophole that hundreds of
companies, both domestic and international, have used to justify
their methods.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for these corporations argue that the pregnancy tests
are necessary to protect female workers' safety and to shield
themselves from paying expensive government-mandated maternity
leave, which allows for three months leave with pay for a woman who
has worked at least 30 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   For years, among those conducting tests were some
</P>
<P>
   branches of US companies doing business here, despite heavy
criticism from human rights advocates and US government officials.
</P>
<P>
   The pregnancy-testing problem has been most evident in the
thousands of assembly plants that have sprouted along the
US-Mexican border, where officials have documented stories of women
who had to submit monthly urine samples or even show managers their
used sanitary napkins.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico City officials say they have also found several cases of
pregnancy discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no statistics to tell us how big the problem is, but
it's clear from the cases we're hearing that something has to be
done, especially on the local level,'' said Gabriela Delgado
Ballesteros, coordinator of Promujer, a city agency formed two
years ago to promote gender equality.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico is not the only Latin American country where female
applicants are asked to take pregnancy tests. The Brazilian
congress passed a law in May outlawing the practice as part of a
reform of its labor laws. Employer-requested pregnancy tests are
also against the law in Colombia and Venezuela, but still widely
practiced.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has come under more scrutiny, though, largely because of
its partnership with the United States and Canada under the 1994
North American Free Trade Agreement, and because so many American
corporations have set up thousands of assembly plants along the
border and interior regions of the country. The factories employ
mostly women, who put together everything from blue jeans to
computer monitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industries where (these tests) are done are predominantly
US corprations that would never do it in the United States,'' said
LaShawn Jefferson, a research director for the women's rights
division of Human Rights Watch, which filed a complaint under NAFTA
in 1997. A final report from the US Labor Department is expected to
be released soon.
</P>
<P>
   Companies inside the United States halted such pregnancy testing
more than two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, pregnancy discrimination is not just a prehire issue.
Many women also claim to have been harassed or fired for becoming
pregnant even after years of working for a company.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's problems at the shoe factory began soon after she
found out she was pregnant with her first child, Alan. Company
officials began harassing her and warning her that she might be
fired for giving her child more attention than her work. When she
became pregnant with her second child, the company fired her for
``neglecting her duties.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For Mexican men, a woman without children is disposable,'' she
said one day last week while sitting on a park bench with Alan as
she read the employment ads in a newspaper. ``For a business, a
women with a child is disposable.''
</P>
<P>
   When doctors discovered she had an at-risk pregnancy, Maria was
told to get plenty of bed rest, but her bosses at the cosmetics
firm refused. Because of that, she said, her baby girl died eight
days after being born.
</P>
<P>
   She became pregnant again six months later, as her doctor
recommended. When company officials found out, they fired her. She
took her case to Mexico's federal labor department, which
eventually arbitrated a settlement whose terms have been sealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only crime was to get pregnant,'' Maria said.
</P>
<P>
   There has been some progress toward ending pregnancy
discrimination. US automaker General Motors, which is one of
Mexico's largest private employers, ended its prehire tests in
March 1997. Five months ago, Mexico's Education Ministry announced
that teachers would no longer be asked to undergo pregnancy tests.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, attempts to revise the federal labor laws have so far
failed. A bill introduced last year in the Chamber of Deputies died
in committee, and another one introduced this year has yet to be
acted upon.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 5 out of 10 Mexican households, the woman helps with some
income support, so it's only fair that we stop discriminating
against them,'' said Maria Elena Cruz Munoz, a congressional
representative from the conservative National Action Party who
submitted this year's version of the antidiscrimination measure.
``We should also make it so that men play a more active role in
raising our children. Maybe then these problems will stop.''
</P>
</TEXT>
