<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; MEXICO-PREGNANT-BIAS (Mexico City) _ Despite the influx of
tens of thousands of women into the country's work force over the
past three decades, public and private managers routinely punish
female employees for being pregnant. By Richard Chacon. 1,200
words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; CAMPAIGN-FINANCE (Washington) _ As the Senate opens debate on
transforming the campaign-finance system, the overhaul plan faces a
serious challenge from an opposition movement led by a single
Republican senator. By Bob Hohler.
</P>
<P>
   INFORMATION-ACT (Undated) _ Scientists are expressing relief
after a federal agency narrows the scope of a new federal law that
allows anyone to file Freedom of Information Act requests for data
from any researcher receiving a federal grant. By Aaron Zitner. 900
words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MA-DOCTORS-FINED (Cambridge, Mass.) _ At a time when financial
rewards and penalties to physicians are burning issues for a
Congress bent on reforming the perceived abuses of managed care, a
physician group has adopted a controversial policy to begin
penalizing individual doctors in the group $250 a day for each day
a patient spends in a hospital that is deemed ``not medically
necessary.'' 1,100 words.
</P>
