<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6728 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-MCMANUS-DEBT-RELIEF-N     10-14 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCMANUS-DEBT-RELIEF-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYBE JESSE VENTURA COULD LEARN SOMETHING FROM JUBILEE 2000 
</HEADLINE>
   (Religion Commentary)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (``Consecrate the fiftieth year and proclaim liberty throughout
the land.... It shall be a jubilee for you.'' -- Leviticus 25:10)
 &HT;    
 By MIKE McMANUS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Sometimes people of faith change the world.
 &HT;    Jesse Ventura would disagree. Recently he said, ``Organized
religion is a sham and a crutch for weak-minded people who need
strength in numbers.''
 &HT;    Consider the story of Peggy Sandlin, a member of Bread for the
World, a group that mobilizes Christians to affect politics to help
the poor.
 &HT;    Shortly after her congressman, Spencer Bachus (R-Ala.), was
named chairman of a banking subcommittee, BFW asked her to call him
about ``Jubilee 2000,'' a proposal to forgive the debt of the
world's poorest nations. Peggy, a family friend, asked him if he
knew about debt relief.
 &HT;    ``I know nothing about it,'' he replied.
 &HT;    She told him that many sub-Saharan nations are being crushed by
their efforts to pay off debt for the purchase of military
equipment during the Cold War. Tanzania, for example, spends four
times as much on debt as on primary education, and nine times more
than on health.
 &HT;    She told him of a bill to forgive 41 such nations of $970
million.
 &HT;    ``What I like is they are not relieved of their obligation to
pay the debt, but it goes into a trust fund to be used only for
health, education and the environment,'' she said. ``If an
international agency found that money was not going into the trust
fund, debt relief is canceled,''
 &HT;    When BFW first heard of Bachus' appointment, and asked
colleagues if he would be open to Jubilee 2000, they said ``Good
luck.'' The very conservative congressman has an office full of
plaques from budget-cutting groups, ``The Sound Money Award.''
Jubilee 2000, meanwhile, was supported by the most liberal
religious denominations - Episcopalians and Methodists.
 &HT;    But Bachus is a deeply committed Southern Baptist. So he agreed
to meet with other BFW constituents from his Birmingham district.
 &HT;    Elaine Van Cleve told him ``Each day 34,000 people die of
hunger-related diseases.''
 &HT;    Bachus asked, ``Explain the connection between that and debt.''
 &HT;    ``All I know is that as a mother, if I had debt inherited from
my grandparents, and at the same time was trying to feed a child, I
would want to feed my child,'' she said.
 &HT;    In the United States, we spend $4,093 per person on health care.
In Ethiopia it is only $3, in Nigeria it is $5, in Nicaragua $37.
An average for the 41 countries is $22.
 &HT;    Bachus instantly agreed to sponsor the Debt Relief for Poverty
Reduction Act, and is now a passionate advocate: ``Please help 700
million of your brothers and sisters in the poorest countries of
the world,'' he wrote to other House Members. ``This legislation is
the first necessary step for raising the standard of living of
those in 41 impoverished countries, those in most need, the most
vulnerable, the most helpless.
 &HT;    ``What would it cost your constituents? Over three years it
would only cost each American a mere $1.20 a year for three years.
It is the cost of an ice cream cone, a gallon of gas, a Sunday
paper. Against this minuscule sacrifice, what is the cost of not
acting as it applies to 15 baby boys or girls born into the poorest
of countries?'' he asked.
 &HT;    ``Of those 15, three will die before a fifth birthday. Of the
remaining 12, four will suffer the scourge of malnutrition with
permanent consequences to their physical and mental development. Of
the remaining eight, they are in no way fortunate. Their chances of
... suffering disease and depravation, of being orphaned, are
great, sometimes as much as 50-50. Their burdens are day to day.
They are painful. They are heavy.''
 &HT;    What the bill can do can be seen in Uganda, which had $40
million of debt payments diverted into a Poverty Action Fund. In
two years, the number of children in elementary school more than
doubled from 2.6 million to 5.3 million.
 &HT;    The bill recently won support from President Clinton and has a
good chance of passage.
 &HT;    ``This decision will define us as either a loving people, a
people filled with grace and compassion, or it will define us as a
people focused on the monetary, the temporal,'' says the
congressman who took a phone call from Peggy Sandlin.
 &HT;    ``The bill is a gift of life,'' he told me. ``Jubilee 2000 is a
celebration of the 2000th birthday of Christ. What did Christ give
us? He gave us lives as Christians. What more appropriate time to
give to these poor in celebration of the birth of Jesus who gave us
life?''
 &HT;    Sometimes America's democracy works like it is supposed to.
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    (Mike McManus is a syndicated columnist whose ``Ethics &AMP;
Religion'' appears in almost 100 newspapers)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1999 Mike McManus
