<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6731 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-INFORMATION-ACT-BOS &LR;      10-14 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INFORMATION-ACT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. CURTAILS REACH OF LAW REQUIRING RESEARCH DISCLOSURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To the relief of universities and hospitals, a
federal agency has narrowed the scope of a new law that might have
forced thousands of researchers to disclose details of their work,
possibly including confidential interviews and trade secrets, to
anyone who asked.
</P>
<P>
   The law, approved last year with little debate, said the public
could obtain ``all data'' produced by researchers who receive
federal money, though certain restrictions applied. Universities
said the law would allow businesses to harass scientists conducting
research in sensitive areas such as the health effects of smoking
and air pollution.
</P>
<P>
   But the office charged with putting the measure into effect has
said it applies only to the research federal agencies use when
creating rules that have the force of law. Even then, researchers
may withhold trade secrets, confidential medical information,
messages to colleagues, and certain other material.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over what scientists must disclose is sure to
continue, however. The U.S. Chamber of Commerce, a major business
lobbying group, has threatened to file suit, arguing that White
House officials illegally narrowed the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is sleight of hand,'' said Bill Kovacs, a vice president
for the group. ``We're going to do something about it. We just
don't know what yet.'' As a first step, he said, the group may file
a request for information under the law with the expectation of
being denied.
</P>
<P>
   University officials said the law, though less onerous than they
first feared, might still place additional costs and burdens on
researchers. Moreover, the law could allow industry groups to file
``repetitive and expensive'' requests in order to thwart research
that might harm their business interests, said George Leventhal, a
policy analyst at the Association of American Universities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been concerned that this will scare scientists away
from sensitive areas like, hypothetically, the health effects of
environmental toxins or research into tobacco,'' Leventhal said.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco giant R.J. Reynolds used a state open-records law to
compel a Georgia researcher to release the names of children who
took part in a study that gauged the popularity of Joe Camel, the
cartoon character once used to pitch cigarettes. The state law was
amended before the researcher released any names, but some
scientists fear the new federal law would expose them to similar
requests from tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   The law arose from a complaint by industry groups that they
could not obtain data from the Harvard School of Public Health that
was later cited by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency in
setting tougher air-quality standards. Harvard said releasing the
data would violate the confidentiality of people who had offered
medical histories and other personal information.
</P>
<P>
   The law broadens the 32-year-old Freedom of Information Act,
which requires the federal government to release certain documents
on request, to include data from researchers who receive federal
money. The law drew little attention when it was approved by
Congress last year and signed into law by President Clinton as part
of a 4,000-page appropriations bill. But as word of the law spread,
it drew loud complaints from the research community, including
Harvard University, the Massachusetts Institute of Technology,
Partners Health Care, and the Boston University Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   The law was sponsored by Senator Richard Shelby, Republican of
Alabama, and supported by Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott. They
said the public has a right to see the details of research that was
paid for by public money.
</P>
<P>
   But as drawn by the Office of Management and Budget, the White
House agency charged with implementing it, the law provides access
only to data the government cites in writing rules that have ``the
force and effect of law.'' Those rules would include, for example,
the EPA's air-quality standards.
</P>
<P>
   David Litster, vice president for research at MIT, said the
agency has significantly narrowed the law so that ``it is not a
serious problem. If all research were suddenly to come under the
FOIA law, we'd have problems. Now, it's only research that's used
as a basis for government actions, which is a small fractioe
total, and philosophically I'm not sure I have a problem with that.
If the government is making laws based on research, we ought to be
able to get at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott and two other Republican senators have said, however, that
the Office of Management and Budget had rendered the law
``potentially meaningless.'' In a letter to the office last month,
they said agencies use research data to make many important rules
and decisions that do not have the force of law, and such
information should be available to the public.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, Kovacs said, the government ``forces'' states to
deny permits when too many industrial businesses want to build
factories in poor and minority neighborhoods. Any research used to
support that requirement should be public, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Chamber of Commerce has also complained that the law as
interpreted by the Office of Management and Budget applies only to
future research. This means that Harvard, for example, could not be
compelled to release data the EPA used in writing clean air rules,
Kovacs said.
</P>
<P>
   But Representative Rush Holt, Democrat of New Jersey, said he
believes the new law still goes too far. He said he will file
legislation to repeal the law because it requires researchers to
release too much data.
</P>
<P>
   Universities offered a mix review of the law, with many saying
that the Office of Management and Budget removed its most
burdensome aspects. But Ruth Flower, director of government
relations at the American Association of University Professors,
said her group ``has a problem with the Freedom of Information Act
being used with respect to individuals. It was created to get at
government agencies, to allow access to agency information.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
