<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6733 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-DOCTOR-FINES-BOS &LR;      10-14 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-DOCTOR-FINES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICAL GROUP STIRS OUTCRY FOR FINING DOCTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ At a time when financial rewards and penalties to
physicians are burning issues for a Congress bent on reforming the
perceived abuses of managed care, a physicians group in Cambridge,
Mass., has adopted a controversial policy to begin penalizing
individual doctors in the group $250 a day for each day a patient
spends in a hospital that is deemed ``not medically necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   The fine, outlined in an internal memorandum obtained by The
Boston Globe and effective Nov. 1, has unleashed a torrent of
criticism from physicians and provoked consternation from medical
ethicists who say the policy is too punitive and could lead to
denial of necessary health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pushing the envelope,'' said Dr. David Himmelstein, an
internist in the group, called the Mount Auburn Cambridge
Independent Practice Association Inc. ``We've been bordering on the
immoral for a long time. This clearly goes over that edge. I am
horrified, but not surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   The tempest surrounding the new penalty, which will apply to 350
physicians in the Mount Auburn practice, highlights a fundamental
dilemma of managed health care _ how to rein in escalating medical
costs by influencing doctor behavior while still preserving the
physician's ability to make independent clinical decisions.
</P>
<P>
   As managed care has evolved, health maintenance organizations
and physicians groups have deployed a number of means to deter
unnecessary hospitalizations and procedures, including the use of
monetary rewards and penalties to physicians. But the financial
incentives have for the most part been relatively indirect, with
hundreds of doctors in any given group sharing both risks and
rewards.
</P>
<P>
   The Mount Auburn policy, however, is drawing criticism because
it is aimed directly at the wallets of individual physicians, a
practice frowned upon by the Massachusetts Medical Society and the
American Medical Society, which represent physicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physician incentive payments should be based on performance of
groups of physicians rather than individual physicians,'' said Yael
Miller, director of health systems at the Massachusetts Medical
Society. ``That's AMA policy, and that's our policy.'' Miller said
direct penalties levied on physicians for violating group
guidelines are extremely rare.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how the rule is supposed to work, according to the memo,
dated Sept. 23. Case managers who scour hospital admissions to
identify unnecessary stays will call offending doctors and offer
``alternative treatment plans.'' If the case manager disagrees with
the physician over the hospital admission, the dispute is sent to a
committee of a dozen doctors in the Mount Auburn practice who
ultimately determine whether to dun the physician.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our work is to try to identify and eliminate waste and improve
the care we deliver to patients,'' said Dr. Rob Janett, medical
director of the Mount Auburn practice and a primary care physician
at Cambridge Hospital. ``An unnecessary day in the hospital is not
only expensive, it is also potentially harmful to patients. The
only penalty being meted out here is against ineffective clinical
decision making.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Dr. Efficiency, and I'm controversial for it, Janett
added. ``But I believe it's the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He explained that the $250 amount was deemed ``large enough to
capture physicians' attention, but not to be so large as to be
onerous.''
</P>
<P>
   Some physicians in the group, however, argue that the amount,
which would be multiplied by the number of days deemed unnecessary,
casts a pall over their decision-making, particularly in borderline
cases where the correct path is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a gray area, doctors are being encouraged to err
on the side of not hospitalizing rather than on what they think
patients need,'' said a Mount Auburn doctor who declined to be
identified. ``It will have a chilling effect on doctors who want to
look out for their patients but are constantly having to ask
themselves whether they're going to have to pay a financial penalty
for it out of their own pockets.''
</P>
<P>
   Many other physician groups do not levy such direct penalties
for inefficient practice. Harvard Vanguard, which has 500
physicians, pays its physicians a salary that varies based on the
physician's caseload and their patients' satisfaction. Neither does
Lahey Clinic in Burlington, Mass., which has 450 physicians, nor
Primary Care LLC, a group of 800 doctors based in Norwell. Both
Lahey and Primary Care officials say their groups instead use
education and peer pressure to try to get physicians to cut down on
waste.
</P>
<P>
   The battle over wasteful medical spending is a difficult, if not
ambiguous, one. Some health care observers point out that
physicians in California tend to rely much less on hospitals to
treat patients, without evidence that patients in California are
suffering worst health care outcomes. The number of days spent in a
hospital per thousand residents in California in 1997, the most
recently available data, was 499.5, compared to 700.1 days in
Massachusetts, according to a survey by the American Hospital
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Some take those figures as a sign that hospitalization could be
cut further without harming patients. Others, however, argue that
Massachusetts is below the national average, which is 719.3 days
per thousand residents, even though its teaching hospitals tend to
care for some of the sickest patients in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Bernard Lown, a well-known cardiologist and an outspoken
critic of the use of financial incentives to influence doctors'
behavior, argued that the policy will erode patients' trust in
their physicians. ``This is utter disdain of ethical principles,''
he said. ``It is an abandonment of the sick and vulnerable and it
makes doctors part of the conspiracy. The doctor essentially
becomes an employee of an organization to whom patients are just a
commodity. It's absolutely disquieting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
