<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALLING LEAVES SPREAD COLOR, PEACE, CLUTTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUTH S. FOSTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A stress encounter group I know recommends sitting quietly at
this time of year and watching the colored leaves fall. Sometimes,
they float slowly to the ground on sunny Indian summer days.
Sometimes they fly with fury in a whipping wind. Something for
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Steal a moment, take a deep breath and a few seconds to tame our
electronically chopped-up micro-time. Maybe even meditate.
</P>
<P>
   Can you name the trees in the forest by their colors? Each tree
has its distinctive time and hue. The fall pageant starts in
October with the glowing red maples, which I think have the most
vivid colors, ranging from yellow to red to maroon and every
nano-shade in between.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar maples turn a vibrant orange. Honeylocusts are yellow,
zelkovas unfold red-orange. Vivid red bushes of wild sumac, aronia,
euonymus (called burning bush with good reason), and enkianthus
explode. Dogwood leaves turn early with shades of deep red and hold
all fall.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 days later, a second wave of color unfolds. Dogwoods
are joined by Japanese maples in orange and red, birches turn pale
gold and Norway maple a deeper yellow. Incidentally, Norway maple
leaves don't compost well, they just turn to yucky mush.
</P>
<P>
   November brings the fall finale as oaks wear deep scarlet and
mahogany. Golden beeches fill the woodlands. On city streets,
Callery pears turn a deep, rich red. The last tree to truly delight
the eye is the Japanese red maple, which seems filled with blood as
the low sun shines through its leaves. In Japan, gardens often
include such a maple in the western corner to provide old folks
with a warm spot to sit in the setting sun.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the leaves fall is a little like meditating. While it
clears the mind, though, it unfortunately clutters the backyard.
Again, as always, tons of leaves will fall.
</P>
<P>
   An acre of oak forest drops 2 1/2 tons of leaves. An acre of
pine spreads 3 1/2 tons of needles. They're 70 percent nitrogen. If
left on the ground to decay, they turn into a layer of soft
compost, nourishing their mother tree with a protective matrix for
new feeding roots. Such is the forest's natural cycle.
</P>
<P>
   What about our backyard? The sheer bulk of beautiful leaves is
overwhelming. Who hasn't dragged endless bags of them from one
place to another, again and again?
</P>
<P>
   To reduce this nagging yard work, decide which leaves really
have to go and which can stay where they fall. On walks, they
become slippery when wet. On lawns, they cause problems. Too deep
on perennial beds, they can cause crown rot. Leaves serve as comfy
snowsuits for many fungi and insects. And what about our current
mantra, ``Make compost?''
</P>
<P>
   You can leave the leaves under trees, shrubs, and on sturdy
groundcover plants. Over the winter, the leaves will self-destruct
into compost. In spring, instead of paying for another two inches
of new red bark mulch, just sprinkle enough of that fancy stuff to
cover the leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Experiments repeatedly have shown that the larger the mulched
area under any tree, the healthier it is and the faster it grows.
Old beech trees really benefit from letting the leaves stay because
they feed the biotic activity necessary for healthy roots.
</P>
<P>
   Do definitely throw out (in the garbage) any plants that are
troubled by diseases or insects. Those needing fall sanitation
include roses, irises, peonies, phlox, stalks of spent perennials,
vegetables, raspberries, and fruit trees. (If you can get to it. I
never truly do.)
</P>
<P>
   If you really love your lawn and want decent grass, you get the
dreaded leaf chore. Don't just rush out in a swivet and rake the
endless fluffy fellows. First mow through them, right on the grass,
which reduces their volume by half.
</P>
<P>
   Then mow again, collect the chopped up bits in the lawnmower
bag, and pile them up. In two weeks, their height will shrink by
half. By spring, it'll reduce by half again. The mountain of
October will have become a few inches of good compost for summer
mulching.
</P>
<P>
   To make compost pie, throw on some dirt between each foot of
leaves and grass clippings. Add water if they're dry. Make as many
layers to the pie as you have patience for. You can make compost
pie on the vegetable bed if you add a sprinkle of lime or ashes. It
can be dug in in late November, and the soil formed into raised
furrows all ready for earlier spring planting. You also can wait
and just pull the mulch aside in spring. The ground will be soft
and ready to plant, the simple essence of that supposedly
mysterious science called no-till farming.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth S. Foster has been a landscape consultant in the Boston
area for many years and has written numerous articles on gardening
in New England.
</P>
</TEXT>
