<HEADLINE>
EASING STRESS WHEN CHILDREN APPLY TO COLLEGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With deadlines for college applications looming and a daughteing on procrastination, Jacqueline Lerner of Wayland was
getting nervous. Two weeks ago, she decided it was time to force
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew the source of her stress was the essay,'' says Lerner.
``I could imagine her thinking, `I have no idea what to say, I
can't write this,' so I told her that before the weekend ended, she
had to brainstorm with her dad about what to write.''
</P>
<P>
   By Sunday, Blair had written four essays. Clearly, she had
turned a corner. ``She was like a new person,'' says Lerner.
</P>
<P>
   For parents of high school seniors, October is the month of
reckoning. If the college application processis not under way, or
if it is moving along only with great ambivalence or foot dragging,
it's time to figure out why.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that they have to have visited colleges by now; many
students _ including Blair, a senior at Wayland High _
prefer to visit only after they are accepted. That's a strategy
that Cambridge educational psychologist and therapeutic tutor Ted
Sutton endorses. ``It's a different experience to go in the spring
when you know they want you than in the fall when you worry, `What
if I love them and they reject me?' '' he says.
</P>
<P>
   A senior also doesn't have to have choices prioritized by now.
But six or seven schools should be identified, applications should
be in hand, and essays should be under way, says educational
consultant Michael Spence of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   By far, the single biggest reason seniors pause in the process
or can't get started at all is fear of rejection.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, a certain amount of anxiety is normal; even the
senior engaged in the process feels it. ``Every child worries about
being embarassed in the eyes of peers, teachers, and parents. Their
sense of themselves, their value as a person, is tied to this,''
says developmental psychologist William Damon, director of the
Stanford University Center on Adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   For some seniors, however, fear of failure is so overwhelming,
they become stuck. They throw up roadblocks _ there's no good time
for campus visits; get hung up on a detail _ urban vs. suburban,
East vs. West, math major vs. biology; or become passive _
``Whatever you say, Mom'' _ or belligerent: ``I don't want to talk
about it!'' Says Damon: ``It's as if they say to themselves, ``I
don't want to embarrass myself, so I'm not even going to try.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Helping them is tricky. On the one hand, the senior who has
pretended to herself all summer and half the fall that this is
going to go away is probably now near panic. ``You see all your
classmates in a frenzy and you wonder, `What's wrong with me? How
come I don't know where to go?' '' says Damon. If a parent keeps
quiet, waiting for the child to make the first move, a senior feels
unsupported, as if you don't really care. Worse, she may take your
silence as confirmation of her fears: ``Even Dad doesn't think I
can get in anyplace.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, intervening inappropriately can add to her
pressure: ``I don't think I'm good enough to go anywhere, and
here's Dad pushing the Ivies on me again.''
</P>
<P>
   A good starting point is to get issues out on the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many families, the process of making choices gets tangled
up with the separation itself,'' says clinical psychologist Ann
Willard, who supervises counseling at Concord Academy. She says
parents can defuse anxiety about leaving home by focusing
discussion on finding the best college for him to do the next stage
of his growing up. In other words, to see this as part of a
continuum rather than the end of something and the start of
something else.
</P>
<P>
   We also need to explicitly take our ego out of the ring.
``Seniors feel unspoken pressure from the community, especially if
college is part of the culture; from their peers, who are
developmentally very competitive; and most of all from parents,''
says Willard.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there's been a lifelong assumption he'll go to the same
school as Dad, or that he'll be the first in the family to go to
college, or that his parents have sacrificed for years so he could
go. Asks Willard: ``What teen can say in the face of that, `I'm not
sure, I'm worried I can't cut it'?'' Indeed, Willard says students
frequently tell her, ``My parents say it doesn't matter where I go,
but I know it really does.''
</P>
<P>
   Her advice is to reiterate aloud and often that you will support
her wherever she goes and that she has many options, including
taking a year off to do something nonacademic.
</P>
<P>
   ``To hear you offer that up is very freeing,'' says Larry
Sullivan, assistant executive director of the National Association
of School Psychologists.
</P>
<P>
   For seniors who have not allowed themselves to think that
thought, there can be incredible relief: ``You know, I'm really not
ready yet.'' For others, having the freedom to talk about what's
been on their mind is sometimes the only way they realize that
``yes, I do want to go to college after all.''
</P>
<P>
   Take time to reach this decision, but not too much. ``Keep
talking about it, but set a deadline for mid-November,'' says
Sutton. Even if the decision is not to go to college next, a senior
still needs to make a plan now for June.
</P>
<P>
   ``If not, he'll be anxious and panicky all year,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   If the decision is to wait a year, that doesn't mean to wait to
apply. ``Applying when you're not in an academic environment is
psychologically hard,'' says Spence. Besides, he adds, colleges
almost universally look favorably upon students who seek deferrals.
``Their view is that these kids will be more mature, more serious
learners,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   If she decides to go forward after all, a key to unfreezing her
is to rid her of misconceptions. For instance:
</P>
<P>
   --``I need to decide my major now.'' The idea that some
classmates know exactly where they want to go and what they want to
major in can make someone who doesn't know feel inadequate _ ``I
should know this by now!'' _ and paralyzed: ``How can I decide on
college if I don't know my major?'' Sullivan says that more than
half of a typical freshman class changes majors and that some
schools don't even allow you to declare a major as a freshman. He
also encourages seniors to think about career direction, rather
than career choice.
</P>
<P>
   --``I have to apply early decision.'' Early decision is binding
_ you have to go if you get in _ yet it's increasingly popular.
Sullivan thinks that's due to the increased pressure seniors feel
as well as a kind of magical thinking: ``If I get into this school,
it means it's the perfect place for me.'' In fact, it often isn't,
he says: A teen can be a different person by April and rue the
commitment. If you must go early, he says, go for early action;
it's not binding.
</P>
<P>
   --``There's one perfect school for me.'' Too anxious to make
decisions, a student can use the search for perfection to keep
putting decisions off. Spence suggests she talk to a freshman who
ended up at a ``safety'' school and is deliriously happy.
</P>
<P>
   --``My SATs aren't good enough.'' A student may not want to take
them again because he's afraid he'll lower the one good score he
had. Not so, says Sullivan: The best score you get is what counts,
even if best math was achieved on a different day than best verbal.
(Deadline for the Dec. 4 test is Oct. 29.)
</P>
<P>
   Once there's movement in a senior's thinking, the typical parent
jumps into action. But Sullivan cautions us to walk a fine line
between being supportive _ picking up a pizza the night he's
working on an essay, offering to photocopy applications _ and being
directive: scheduling a visit without asking him first, telling him
what to do when. For a child who is disorganized, Damon recommends
providing structure and scaffolding _ ``I can help you make folders
and a timeline so you can keep a checklist'' _ but don't do the
work for him.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if you make an appointment at a school he's
agreed to visit, and he wants to back out and you let him, he won't
feel good about himself. ``Hold him to a commitment,'' says
Sullivan. ``Learning to be trustworthy is a developmental task of
the age.'' If he wants out of an appointment he never agreed to,
then you should cancel.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton says 95 percent of seniors need a gentle, supportive
push, much the way Jacqueline Lerner nudged Blair. But Lerner also
has had the opposite experience with her son, Justin, who knew
exactly where he wanted to go. In some ways that was harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling that you'll die if you don't get into that one
school is incredibly stressful,'' says Lerner. ``Because my
daughter doesn't have tunnel vision, she has more of an open mind
about where a good match might be.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ Recommended for helping kids of all ages use the
Internet wisely: ``300 Incredible Things for Kids on the Internet''
by Internet maven Ken Leebow (300Incredible.com, LLC).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Barbara F. Meltz welcomes letters and comments and can be reached
via e-mail at meltz(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
