<HEADLINE>
COULD THE PAIN BE A GENTLE NUDGE OF LOVE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jack, darling, I owe you an apology.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sorry I was late for dinner and left you wondering why I
hadn't called or left a note. I'd gone for an early autumn swim
with Lynn and then couldn't find my watch. Ordinarily, I'd run
around madly, then give up and rush home, but I've decided that
stress is playing a part in all the headaches I've been having
lately, and so I slowed way down, paid attention to my breathing,
and carefully retraced my steps until I found my watch by the
seawall. It was only then that I thought about where I was supposed
to be, and by then I was already 20 minutes late. I'm sorry.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy, how can I explain why I didn't return your call?
</P>
<P>
   I asked you for a favor and you called back to say yes. Then I
didn't get back to you. I know that's inexcusable because I
ordinarily would never be so irresponsible, but I'm coming to see
that the pressure I put on myself _ to return every call, to deal
with every e-mail, to answer every letter, to show up on time and
always keep my word _ may be ruining my health. This is what
happened. At the end of a very long day, I stared at my list of
things still to do, including returning your call. I registered my
reluctance. I noted the tension behind my eyes and . . . walked
away. I don't blame you for being annoyed. Recognizing that I'm
letting people down, then doing it anyway, bothers me terribly,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Paul, I'm sorry your secretary had to call to remind me I
was missing our appoint
</P>
<P>
   I'm trying to be less fragmented, and it's getting me in all
sorts of trouble. I'd decided to make pesto that morning. I was
trying to be fully present, cutting off basil leaves to music,
feeding nuts and cheese into my blender in a slow easy rhythm. I
wasn't reviewing lists in my head or checking the clock. I was so
peaceful and fully engaged that I completely lost track of the
time. When your secretary finally reached me, I was so deep in
another realm of experience that it took me a while to figure out
what she was talking about. I can't promise you it won't happen
again.
</P>
<P>
   This is really a scary time for me.
</P>
<P>
   All my life, I've been trying to hitch myself to schedules and
routines. As someone with adult attention deficit disorder, I'm
naturally distractible and forgetful. I've had to teach myself to
write everything down, to tie my keys to my pocketbook, to check my
calendar twice a day, and to take care of things the minute I think
of them. This degree of self-discipline is foreign to my nature.
It's been a terrible strain. And just when I've finally gotten the
organization of my life down to a fine art, my body has rebelled at
the price it's being asked to pay.
</P>
<P>
   I feel as if I'm entering dangerous waters, heading back into
the chaos I just got under control. I don't want to disappoint
anyone, but evidently I can't keep performing at this level.
Without my consent, pain has become my personal defensive lineman,
taking me down whenever I grab the ball and begin running down the
field at full speed.
</P>
<P>
   When I think I'm my own worst enemy, I despair. If I weren't
stuck with myself, I'd get a divorce. Yet when our Unitarian
minister said in church, ``Your life is held in a greater love,
encompassed by a larger mind, a deeper strength, an everflowing
creativity,'' I felt suddenly hopeful. I listened intently as Mary
went on: ``Rest in this greater love. And when you can't feel it,
or find its pulse, rest in the tangible love of your family, and
friends, and congregation. And when you can't feel that, rest in
the grace of the world. And when you can't find that, just rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly I thought, what if this greater love is what's slowing
me down? Perhaps what I call suffering is a tough-but-caring nudge,
the only thing capable of outfoxing my stubborn determination to
keep on doing more. Perhaps some knowing force with my best
interests at heart is taking me out of this stress-filled game as
gently as possible, using the only means at its command to stop me.
</P>
<P>
   When I peer straight ahead, it looks bleak. But what if love's
strong and certain hand is trying to point me in another direction?
There's something intriguing about that peaceful realm I visit so
rarely. Can I give myself permission to enter a world in which
people don't need to accomplish so much or drive themselves so
relentlessly?
</P>
<P>
   Mary said that no matter what we do, we are ``nestled in the
palm of love's hand.'' Invisible though it may be, if we rest, will
we discover it has the power to support us in our need and our
vulnerability?
</P>
<P>
   The sharp pain in my head won't listen to reason.
</P>
<P>
   It says, Try.
</P>
<P>
   (Linda Weltner's website is at www.shore.net(tilde)weltne 
</P>
</TEXT>
