<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-INDIA-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGGING INTO THE TRUTH OF `EARTH' 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES PAKISTAN-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: Photos are being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VANESSA E. JONES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Siddiq Abdullah was 3 when his Muslim family left
behind furniture and farmland in India 52 years ago. After a
desperate dash to the city of Lahore, Pakistan, the family was
forced to sleep on the floor of its new home until his parents
reestablished themselves enough to buy beds, recalled Abdullah, 55,
an economics professor at Pine Manor College and the University of
Massachusetts in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   From his hometown of Bareilly, India, Vinod Misra also witnessed
the human toll of the Aug. 14, 1947, partition, which turned
British-ruled India into the independent nations of
Hindu-and-Sikh-dominated India and Muslim-dominated Pakistan.
Bareilly, in the north of India, filled with Hindus and Sikhswho
had fled Pakistan. In Misra's memories, the displaced were always
broken people who had lost either a leg or a hand. Families were
broken, too, with a mother, a father, or a child lost to the
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Misra, Abdullah, and a group of 11 other local Pakistanis and
Indians recently wove together their personal tales of horror after
getting an early look at the new film ``Earth.'' The movie explores
how partition shattered friendships between Hindus, Muslims, and
Sikhs in Lahore.
</P>
<P>
   The division of India into two countries displaced 12 million
Hindus, Muslims, and Sikhs who crossed the new border in both
directions to evade religious persecution. More than 1 million
people were killed in the process.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Earth,'' Indian director Deepa Mehta, a Hindu, tells this
violent story through the eyes of 8-year-old Lenny. The child is
the daughter of upper-class Parsis, a group that remained neutral
as its country broke in two.
</P>
<P>
   It's international history that most Americans barely know
about. Yet, its effects are still felt in both countries today.
Since 1947, India and Pakistan have fought each other in three
wars. Earlier this year, they threatened each other with a nuclear
punch and engaged in 10 weeks of armed conflict over Kashmir, a
long-disputed territory that they jointly administer. News of a
military coup in Pakistan, which led to the ouster of the country's
prime minister and his government, could further heighten tensions
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   In an intense discussion that crested with raised voices and
then ebbed into relieved laughter, local Indians and Pakistanis
talked about partition's impact on families and the toll it has
taken on Indian-Pakistani relationships.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sad chapter in India's history but at least (the
film) will make people realize what happened,'' said Usha Vakil,
50, a delicate-looking woman who was born in New Delhi and now
lives in Hingham, Mass.. ``We talk about World War II, but we never
talk about the biggest partition that ever took place in the world.
What trauma did it leave behind? Nobody addresses that, and those
scars last from generation to generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Indian-born woman, however, thought partition was a
chapter of history best left in the books.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder why they made the movie at this time,'' said Jaya
Vorunganti, of Burlington, Mass., with a mixture of anxiousness and
anger. ``India is trying to be fair to everybody, and a movie like
this creates tension between different groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Mehta is accustomed to her work being the subject of intense
scrutiny and debate. Her 1997 movie, ``Fire,'' shed a controversial
light on lesbianism in India.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Fire,'' ``Earth'' has gotten mixed responses from Hindus,
Muslims, and Sikhs since opening earlier this year in India and 11
cities in the United States. (In keeping with the two nations'
strained relationship, Pakistan doesn't show Indian movies, and
India doesn't show Pakistani ones).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Rose-colored glasses'
</P>
<P>
   ``Some said it was anti-Hindu, some said it was anti-Muslim, and
some felt it was unbiased,'' said Mehta in a weary, gravelly growl,
speaking from her home in Montreal. ``It's about everybody being
overly sensitive about (being shown) in a light that's not
complimentary. We like to see life through rose-colored glasses and
not address things that are difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Tension has often existed between the Muslims and Hindus. In the
17th century, Hindus chafed under harsh Islamic rule. But when the
British gained power in the next century, Muslims and Hindus united
against a system that denied them jobs and high government
positions.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1930s, Muslim leaders thought Hindus, the majority group
in India, were becoming too powerful. Skirmishes between them
started to occur. Soon, some Muslims began demanding their own
country. They got their wish in August 1947.
</P>
<P>
   After a screening of ``Earth,'' the local group willingly delved
into who caused the unease among Hindus, Muslims, and Sikhs. The
Indians angled their accusations at British and Indian politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could pit one against the other just to control the
country,'' Govind Vakil, 51, an architect and Usha's husband, said
of the British.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 1312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6750 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-FILM-INDIA-PAKISTAN-2     10-14 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-INDIA-PAKISTAN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BOSTON: ... of the British  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Soft-spoken Vinod Chungi, 52, of Sharon, Mass., who was born in
Hyderabad, India, agreed, adding, ``The worst part is that the
politicians are continuing that policy. They play people against
each other for their own purposes.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Musadik Malik, 37, who writes medical reports for the
Stanford Research Institute in Quincy, sees another cause: the
economic disparities between Muslims and Hindus in Lahore, his
hometown.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hindu exodus
</P>
<P>
   Malik grew up in a city where Hindu domination was still
evident: hospitals, mansions, and streets bore Hindu names. Before
partition, Hindus held the professional jobs in Lahore, Malik said,
while Muslims were generally workers and peasants. Then, in 1947,
Hindus literally ran for their lives, leaving Muslims their
businesses and homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earth'' doesn't expis aspect of partition. Instead, it
tells the story by describing the friendship between Lenny's Hindu
nanny and her lovelorn circle of male Muslim, Sikh, and Hindu
friends. As the religious tension in the country intensifies, it
slowly chips away at their bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about the politics of partition,'' said Pakistani
author Bapsi Sidhwa, a Parsi who lives in Houston. ``Earth'' is
based on her award-winning, semi-autobiographical book, ``Cracking
India.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about what happened to the common people dislocated
because of the religious violence,'' Sidhwa continued.
</P>
<P>
   Friendships across religious lines existed before, during, and
after partition, agreed the Indians and Pakistanis. Misra, a Hindu,
confidently raised his voice above the din to describe his days at
a Muslim college in India. ``We respected each other's
differences,'' Misra, 56, who heads a management consulting company
in Burlington, said emphatically. ``I had the same relationship
with my Hindu and Muslim friends.''
</P>
<P>
   The less fortunate felt the ire of religious hatred. In
``Earth,'' Muslims burn Hindu neighborhoods, a train arrives in
Lahore from India filled with murdered Muslims, Sikh and Hindu
families flee to India, and those who remain in Pakistan convert to
Islam or Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Midnight's children
</P>
<P>
   The parents of Anita Raj-Silverman, a 28-year-old American-born
woman of Indian descent, never talked about those tumultuous
events. Raj-Silverman finally asked them about it after seeing
``Earth'' at a film festival earlier this year. Suddenly, the
stories tumbled out.
</P>
<P>
   Raj-Silverman's Hindu father was a 12-year-old boy who trekked
from Pakistan to India with his family. Her mother, a Sikh who
lived in India's Punjab region, could no longer play with her young
Muslim friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an uncle by marriage whose parents were decapitated in
front of him,'' said Raj-Silverman, an assistant research professor
at Boston University's School of Public Health. ``I was told,
`Don't talk to your cousins about it.' You don't talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Earth,'' said Mehta, encourages dialogue _ younger generations
now understand what caused the rift between Pakistan and India.
Those who lived through partition, she says, are finally talking
about their experiences.
</P>
<P>
   But it became clear during the group discussion that resentment
over the death, loss, and chaos still simmers. Shundana Tusaf, a
blunt-speaking architect studying architectural history at MIT,
said that as a child in Peshawar, Pakistan, she could hear the
anger in the words of her history teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used jargon, saying, `Hindus are bad,' '' recalled Tusaf,
29, ``or `The British were not as bad as the Hindus.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The statement caused many in the room to rumble in disagreement.
Until that point, no one had blatantly talked about the festering
hatred between the groups. Usha Vakil's voice finally rose above
the others: ``I was never taught like that. I don't remember
hearing in schools that Pakistan is bad, Muslims are bad.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, Malik revisited the subject in a phone
conversation. He wasn't taught to hate Hindus in school, he said,
but Tusaf's comments and the group's reaction to them illustrated
an important point.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're in Pakistan or India, no matter what we say publicly
for face saving, the truth is . . . there is a lot of hatred,
because there is a lot of blood. The pain is going to take a long
time to go away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
