<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF ONLY MARTHA COULD TIDY UP WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   William R. Mattox Jr., writing on the op-ed page of Tuesday's
USA Today, suggests that ``instead of paying so much attention to
an ever-growing cast of fruitcake candidates, (the Reform Party)
ought to be paying closer attention to America's premier fruitcake
maker, Martha Stewart.''
</P>
<P>
   Martha for president? It's a splendid idea, but unfortunately
it's not to be.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day, the business page of The New York Times
featured a story about the initial public offering of Martha
Stewart Living Omnimedia. The piece raised the question of what
might happen to Martha's conglomerate if there were no Martha to
run the operation. Martha is a micro-manager who has her hand in
every corner of her company. She's much too busy presiding over her
vast media and merchandising empire to run for president.
</P>
<P>
   While we may be denied Martha Stewart in the White House, why
shouldn't we insist on a president whose standards are as high as
Martha's? We need a president strong enough to march us into the
next millennium the Martha Stewart Way, a candidate who knows a
good thing when he sees it, one who can be relied upon to tend the
national compost heap as carefully as Martha would.
</P>
<P>
   Which of the many hopefuls could pass the Martha Stewart test?
When we weigh a presidential candidate, we should ask: What would
Martha do? What would Martha say?
</P>
<P>
   For example, Playboy magazine asks for the candidate's views on
religion. The candidate might respond:
</P>
<P>
   a) ``The separation of church and state is fundamental to
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   b) ``I support mandatory prayer in the classroom, as long as
it's Christian prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   c) ``Church-going could be a real money-maker, if a financial
genius like myself got behind it.''
</P>
<P>
   d) ``Organized religion is a sham and a crutch for weak-minded
people who need strength in numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   e) ``Beautiful flower arrangements add so much to any service of
worship.''
</P>
<P>
   At a photo op in a fly-blown New Hampshire doughnut shop, the
candidate is offered a cruller. The candidate:
</P>
<P>
   a) says, ``I tried one of these when I was at Harvard, but I
never digested it.''
</P>
<P>
   b) takes a big bite and smiles bravely for the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   c) says, ``Crullers are a crutch for weak-minded people who
can't handle doughnuts.''
</P>
<P>
   d) says, ``Crullers could be as big as bagels, if someone as
talented and innovative as I am decided to market them.''
</P>
<P>
   e) scrubs down the counter and the display case, then invites
the press into the kitchen to watch while he whips up a batch of
sugar-raised doughnuts from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Asked for an opinion on the controversial elephant-dung painting
of the Virgin Mary at the Brooklyn Museum, the candidate says:
</P>
<P>
   a) ``I understand the elephant's First Amendment rights weren't
abridged in the creation of this painting.''
</P>
<P>
   b) ``This painting is an insult to God-fearing people of every
religious persuasion.''
</P>
<P>
   c) ``Elephant dung is a crutch for weak-minded alleged artists
who can't handle paint.''
</P>
<P>
   d) ``A person with my amazing financial acumen could make a
fortune cornering the elephant-dung art market. If it weren't so
unsanitary.''
</P>
<P>
   e) ``Elephant dung has so many other uses. I always keep a
supply on hand. It makes cunning door stops, clever hostess gifts,
and it's the perfect medium for planting spring-flowering bulbs.''
</P>
<P>
   (Diane White is Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 1316EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
