<HEADLINE>
RODDY DOYLE LOOKS AT THE IRISH BIG PICTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Roddy Doyle smiles wryly as he politely _ but firmly _
declines an invitation to visit one of downtown Boston's many Irish
theme pubs. ``I don't like forced Irishness,'' explains the man who
has been hailed as the leading light of the current Irish literary
renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   In novels such as ``The Commitments,'' ``The Woman Who Walked
Into Doors,'' and ``Paddy Clarke Ha Ha Ha,'' Doyle has created a
host of memorable and three-dimensional characters: feisty,
foulmouthed types who are often down but never entirely out.
</P>
<P>
   His characters are Irish to the core, but bear little
resemblance to the lovable, stereotypical ``Paddies'' of stage,
screen, and much Irish-American nostalgia. Instead, his characters
reflect the gritty authenticity of the working-class suburbs of
North Dublin where he grew up and once taught school.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle was in town to launch his new book, ``A Star Called
Henry,'' the first volume in a literary sea change for the author:
It's an ambitious, unconventional trilogy that will sum up the
tumultuous history of 20th-century Ireland through the life and
voice of one character. Doyle's focus is on Henry Smart, a highly
sexed, clear-eyed, ruthless, and more or less indestructible son of
the Dublin slums who moves through the decades in tandem with a
changing Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every book I've written has been different,'' says Doyle, who
still lives in Dublin with his wife and three small sons. ``This
time the storyteller in me wanted to write about big history and
big politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Doyle himself is a far cry from any stereotypes. The affable
41-year-old has a shaved head, wears wire-rimmed glasses, and
sports a silver stud in his left earlobe. He looks like neither the
literary lion nor the former grade-school teacher (English and
geography) that he is. Doyle showed up for an interview at the
Swissotel _ where the somberly elegant decor suggests a bankers'
club in Zurich _ in a rumpled black jacket and an open-necked
bright red shirt.
</P>
<P>
   He could have passed for one of the likable musicians of the
Commitments, the eponymous soul band of his first novel, which was
made into a popular film, one of several of his books brought to
the screen. And the overall impression of Doyle is of the new
Irishman _ a citizen of the European Community who is completely at
ease in both his own country and the wider world. Irish
remorsefulness is not his forte.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a happy man,'' Doyle says, cheerfully. ``I'm doing what I
want to do and making a pretty good living at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his earlier books, ``A Star Called Henry'' has aroused
some controversy in Ireland because of a consistently irreverent
tone regarding the nation's formative history. The book portrays
such icons of Irish nationalism as Eamon De Valera, Michael
Collins, and Padraic Pearse as all too human: frequently vain,
sometimes petty, and often self-serving.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IRA anger?
</P>
<P>
   There have been reports that the book raised the ire of the
Irish Republican Army, but that possibility doesn't faze the upbeat
Doyle. ``In England, the press are always asking me if I'm afraid
for my life,'' he says, ``and the answer is that I'm not.''
</P>
<P>
   In the new novel, Henry, a strapping 6-footer, is age 15 at the
time of the Easter uprising. The son of an alcoholic mother and a
one-legged father who is both a bouncer in a brothel and a killer
for hire, Henry joins the Citizens Army and takes part in the 1916
uprising against British rule in Dublin, an event Doyle depicts as
a combination of farce and tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   A block off the old chip, Henry becomes an IRA gunman,
specializing in assassinating informers, policemen, and British
officials. Finally sickened by so much killing and disillusioned
with the rebel leadership, he leaves Ireland. Future adventures
will include a stint in America and a return to Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the revered heroes of the Irish war of independence whom
Henry encounters, Doyle implies, were really more interested in
improving their own fortunes than in freeing their country. ``I was
brought up to believe they were all saints, but I did my
homework,'' he says. ``And besides, I'm not the first one to make
fun of them.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are pitfalls to writing about Ireland's past, Doyle
acknowledges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing with Irish history is that's it's still happening,''
he says. ``There are lads out there fighting about the same things
they were fighting about in 1916. Irish history isn't safe.'' By
quitting the fight when he does, Henry _ and Doyle _ avoids taking
sides in the bitter civil war that broke out in 1922 between
Republican and Free State factions of the nationalist movement,
still a hot-button topic in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New Irish self-confidence
</P>
<P>
   Despite the controversy, Irish critics have generbraced
the book, which is selling briskly in Ireland and Britain. ``A lot
has changed in Ireland in the last 10 years, and there's a new
self-confidence now,'' Doyle says, so a book that reexamines the
past is finding a new audience. ``Some of the old statues have
tumbled down.'' The book also is selling well in this country.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle's first three novels _ ``The Commitments,'' ``The
Snapper,'' and ``The Van'' _ were all set in the fictional suburb
of Barrytown and chronicled the fortunes of various members of the
Rabbitte family. ``I thought I was writing three different books,''
he says. ``It was my publisher's idea to call them the Barrytown
Trilogy. Now, they're out in a boxed set.''
</P>
<P>
   Publishing wasn't always so good to Doyle. ``The Commitments''
had to be privately published in 1986, when Doyle was a full-time
teacher. After the manuscript made the rounds of publishers _ and
was returned unread by all of them _ he borrowed money from a
friend and published it himself, sending copies to reviewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't advise writers to do that  &UR; today &LR;  unless they're
prepared to lose a lot of money,'' he says. ``But there hadn't been
any interesting new Irish writing in a long time, and the book
attracted a lot of attention.'' Eventually picked up by a major
publisher, it became a bestseller on both sides of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Commitments'' launched his career as part of the new wave
of Irish novelists, who include Patrick McCabe (``The Butcher
Boy'') and Colm Toibin (``The South''). ``There's a staggering
amount of quality writing in Ireland now,'' Doyle says.
</P>
<P>
   His 1993 novel ``Paddy Clarke Ha Ha Ha,'' which describes the
disintegration of a marriage through the eyes and words of a
10-year-old boy, won the prestigious Booker Prize, the British
equivalent of the Pulitzer Prize for literature. The book is
already considered a modern classic, a coming-of-age story to rank
with ``Catcher in the Rye.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any book I ever write will sell more copies than
`Paddy Clarke Ha Ha Ha,' '' Doyle says. Far less popular was his
next book,``The Woman Who Walked Into Doors'' (1996), the story of
an alcoholic woman and battered wife trying to pull her life
together.
</P>
<P>
   Although praised by critics, it sold poorly, particularly in
this country. ``More copies were sold in Iceland than in the United
States,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Until ``A Star Called Henry,'' his writing has been cemented in
gritty realism, street-smart humor, and salty dialogue. But
``Henry'' adds fantasy and is peppered with symbolism.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Henry,'' Doyle slyly drops a few clues about what lies
ahead for his hero, including the fact that he gets shot in
Chicago. To research that part of the second book of the trilogy,
he says, he for a time considered moving there. ``I wanted to write
about the South Side Chicago of the 1920s with its speak-easies and
jazz clubs, but when I visited Chicago I discovered that it was all
gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Doyle won't even hint at what kind of trouble Henry Smart will
get into in the Chicago of Al Capone and Dutch Schultz. ``I don't
want to give too much away,'' he says, grinning.
</P>
<P>
   ``And besides, I'm still writing the book.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
