<HEADLINE>
ROVER MINI AGAIN TO PLAY GNAT TO VW'S BUG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the early 1960s, when for many in America big steel was in
and gas was cheap, the cult of the big car thrived.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, out there on the fringe, a true counterculture was nascent
and there lurked a market for small cars. Volkswagen, of course,
became the badge of that fringe and, later, the counterculture that
would emerge.
</P>
<P>
   The VW became the lovable Bug, scuttling across America,
veritably crawling along the roads. But if VW was the Bug, Mini was
the Gnat, a tiny British box of a car, buzzing and darting and
attracting a fringe following of its own.
</P>
<P>
   After time, both manufacturers stopped exporting their little
insects to the United States and the old models left behind became
cherished icons in the lingering cults of their faithful. Now,
Volkswagen, with its New Beetle, is back in a big way. And, now,
there is news on the Mini.
</P>
<P>
   First the good news: BMW, which has owned the British company
Rover and, hence, rights to the Mini since 1994, will produce a new
Mini in 2000. And just as the New Beetle _ though bigger and safer
and better than the old _ evokes the original, so too will the new
Mini.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news: BMW is not certain it will sell the car in the
United States. And that would dismay a hardy band of Mini devotees,
says Carl Zack, a Mini enthusiast from Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd be crazy not to keep the market alive overseas,'' Zack
says.
</P>
<P>
   This much is known.
</P>
<P>
   The new Mini will be launched next year, according to BMW
spokesman David Buchko. It will be front-wheel drive, just like the
original. Its motor _ 1.6 or 1.8 liters and four cylinders _ will
be a transverse mount.
</P>
<P>
   It will be slightly larger than the original 10-by-4-by-4-foot
box _ with 10-inch wheels _ that arrived on these shores 40 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Appearance-wise, says Buchko, ``it will be a modern
interpretation of the original Mini concept.''
</P>
<P>
   Read into that: It will still be a box, but the corners will be
rounded a bit.
</P>
<P>
   And modern technology will make it safer, more reliable, and
more sophisticated than the original. We know more about
front-wheel drive and transverse engine mounts than they did in
1959. Suspension systems are far more sophisticated. Just as the
New Beetle really isn't the old, the new Mini will have the aura of
the old with all the benefits of modern technology.
</P>
<P>
   Not that, in its day, the Mini was not a formidable little car.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first British car to win a European Rally
Championship. It won the Monte Carlo Rally three times. In the
United States, it became the terror of rally and gymkhana courses.
</P>
<P>
   The brainchild of the eccentric Sir Alec Issigonis, the Mini
offered a lightweight auto with front-wheel drive, a rubber
suspension system, and handling and performance in an economy car.
</P>
<P>
   It arrived here in 1960 under Morris and Austin badges, and its
most popular models were the Morris Minor and the Mini Cooper, the
latter being the car that caught the eye of the American sports car
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Other small cars, besides the Volkswagen, had come to these
shores at about the same time: Isettas, Messerschmitts, Goggomobils
_ but none performed like a Mini.
</P>
<P>
   At the base was the Austin 850, imported from 1960-67. It had an
848 cc engine that produced 35 thundering horses and 44 lb.-ft. of
torque.
</P>
<P>
   There were the Mini Van and Countryman, with the same engines as
the 850. The van was a light delivery vehicle for commercial use,
while the Countryman was an Austin wagon with wood trim around the
back of the body and twin rear doors.
</P>
<P>
   There was the Mini Pickup, again with the same engine, and
imported from 1961-67 and so rare it is highly sought after today.
</P>
<P>
   But most of all, there was the Mini Cooper, imported from
1961-67 with engines of nearly 1,000 cc, a three-gauge instrument
pod replacing the single speedometer, and a bizarre but effective
(when it didn't leak) suspension system: hydrolastic suspension
with a rubber bag at each wheel filled with an antifreeze-like
liquid. Hoses interconnected the four bags, and as wheels rose and
fell, liquid was displaced from bag to bag to control the pitch of
the car.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, the Mini Cooper S was introduced with a 1,071 cc engine
and by 1964 a 1,275 cc engine (hey, bigger than Harleys in those
days) had been planted in the little box.
</P>
<P>
   Like standard Coopers, the S models had two-tone paint and a
slanted grill. What gave them away, subtly, were gold or silver
brocade accents on the two-tone seats, and small chrome ``S''
emblems on hood and trunk.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, at the Frankfurt Motor Show, the BMW Group introduced a
prototype Mini Cooper to the world. And just as VW did with the
Bug, it is remarkable how the prototype, which will become the new
Mini, evokes the original.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
