<SLUG> BC-FBC-IVY-BOS </SLUG>
  
 HARVARD IS UP FOR REBOUND
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Harvard was on the verge of taking command in the Ivy League in
the final minutes of last week's game against Cornell in Ithaca,
N.Y. Though the Crimson lost, 24-23, coach Tim Murphy is optimistic
about the ability of Harvard (2-2 overall, 1-1 Ivy) to recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is any question that, when all is said and
done, Cornell will lose a game in the Ivy League,'' Murphy said
while preparing for Saturday's game at Fordham (0-5). ``They had
two miraculous comebacks and they can't do that all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember a game we controlled so much and didn't win
it. We were up by 13 points and playing quality football. But we
had a chance to put them away and we didn't, and you can't do that
against a good team. There were two penalties on fourth-down plays
and the game's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornell defeated Brown, 33-28, the previous week despite
trailing by 21 points.
</P>
<P>
   The visit to Fordham will be Harvard's final nonleague game. The
Rams have lost three successive games against Ivy League opponents,
the closest result a 35-18 defeat at Penn last week.
</P>
<P>
   In other Ivy League games, Brown (2-1, 3-1) meets Rhode Island;
Columbia (0-1, 2-2) plays Penn (1-0, 2-2); Cornell (3-0, 4-0)
visits Colgate; Dartmouth (0-1, 0-4) travels to Yale (0-1, 3-1),
and Princeton (0-2, 1-3) meets Lafayette.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard took the lead against Cornell behind the rushing of
Chris Menick and Chuck Nwokocha and passing of Brad Wilford.
Menick, who has gained 273 yards, is expected to lead the attack
this week. Fordham has surrendered 262 rushing yards per game and
has been outscored, 202-63.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fordham is playing extremely hard,'' Murphy said. ``Even
though they are winless, they are well-coached, and we have to
forget what their record is and play our game and continue to play
hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, it's a fairly wide-open offense and very aggressive
defense. I think we are a good team and I'm happy with how hard we
played against Cornell. When you lose, it creates a greater sense
of urgency. We have to maximize the opportunities we have left. I
don't think we needed to be woken up. We were up by 13 points and
with a fourth-down situation against a quality team, so we had to
be doing a lot of things right.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown recovered from its loss to Cornell by defeating Princeton,
53-30, as James Perry passed for 432 yards and three touchdowns and
moved within seven completions of the career record of 613 held by
John Witkowski of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Brown leads the league in scoring and is last in defense with a
141-115 differential overall and a 106-87 differential against Ivy
opponents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
