<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAY YOUR E-MAIL REST IN PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Suicide notes will soon be popping up all over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   These aren't messages from people who don't want to live.
Actually, they're from people who don't want their messages to
live. A couple of start-up firms have come up with ways to generate
e-mail messages with a limited lifespan. After a few days, weeks or
months, the messages are transformed into unreadable gibberish.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the attention has centered on San Francisco-based
Disappearing Inc., largely because they picked such a cool name.
But another company, QVTech Inc. of Colorado Springs, Colo., is
rolling out a similar product.
</P>
<P>
   Both rely on encryption _ the art of using computers to scramble
messages so completely that they're virtually impossible to
unscramble, unless you have a digital key. For years, people like
me have said that the day was coming when most e-mail would be
encrypted, in order to protect our privacy.
</P>
<P>
   We're still waiting for that day, because even the best mail
encryption systems are too hard to use. Many rely on a system that
creates two separate keys _ one to encrypt messages and one to
decrypt them. Both sender and recipient must have a key, and the
same brand of encryption software as well. This makes it very hard
to send encrypted messages to total strangers.
</P>
<P>
   The new suicide mail systems use simpler but still powerful
encryption systems with just one key to worry about. Everything is
managed behind the scenes. For instance, the Disappearing system
requires the sender to add a special software plug-in to his
existing e-mail program. This program connects to a server, which
creates the key used to scramble the message.
</P>
<P>
   The recipient uses a piece of free software to decode the
message. This software goes to the Disappearing server, picks up
the key, and uses it to read the message. If somebody doesn't have
the decoding software, they can also open the message inside a Web
browser that links to a decryption server.
</P>
<P>
   So how do these messages commit suicide? Simple. They're
encrypted, and can't be read without a key. So the sender tells the
Disappearing server to discard the key after a certain date. The
message doesn't really disappear; it's just permanently reduced to
nonsense. The QVTech system, though different in detail, works on
the same principles.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been able to shred paper documents for a long
time,'' says Dave Marvit, co-founder of Disappearing. ``Now you can
shred e-mail documents.''
</P>
<P>
   Just the thing for disposing of those embarrassing e-mail
messages from Microsoft Corp. chief executive Bill Gates that
turned up years later, during the company's antitrust trial. ``I'm
sure Mr. Gates would have preferred to say, any e-mail I send you
evaporates overnight,'' says Dan Geer, former head of security at
Burlington e-commerce firm Open Market Inc., and an advisor to
QVTech.
</P>
<P>
   No surprise, then, that Disappearing and QVTech think corporate
e-mail users will be their first big customers. But they also think
Internet service providers will sell it to ordinary consumers as a
premium service.
</P>
<P>
   The value of the idea goes far beyond privacy, and into a new
realm of ``e-mail sender rights.'' Today, when you send an e-mail,
it's forever beyond your control. Not any more.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the QVTech system lets you prevent the recipient
from forwarding a copy to others, or from printing out a copy. The
Disappearing system has a feature that lets you kill a message even
after it's been received. If you change your mind about that
insulting e-mail you just sent, you can go to a Web site and delete
its encryption key. The target of your insults will still get the
e-mail, but won't be able to read it.
</P>
<P>
   Sensible Internet users know that their every keystroke is
likely to be on file somewhere. Your old Usenet messages are
stashed at Deja.com, while Alexa Internet tries to archive every
single Web page. And your long-gone e-mails might still be alive,
on a backup tape at your Internet service provider.
</P>
<P>
   The only sure-fire defense is never to use e-mail for sensitive
communications, but that'll soon be impractical as e-commerce
sweeps the planet. Disappearing and QVTech offer the next best
thing _ e-mail with a death wish.
</P>
<P>
   (You can send Hiawatha Bray electronic mail at
bray(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 1327EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
