<HEADLINE>
METHODIST GROUP OPPOSES BOY SCOUTS' BAN ON HOMOSEXUALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL NESS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   An important board of the United Methodist Church has taken a
stand against the Boy Scouts' ban on gays, intensifying the rift
over homosexuality in one of the nation's biggest denominations.
</P>
<P>
   The United Methodists already are deeply divided over the church
decision three years ago to punish ministers who perform holy union
ceremonies for same-sex couples.
</P>
<P>
   The church's General Board of Church and Society, meeting in
Washington, D.C., on Sunday, voted to call on the Boy Scouts of
America to change its policy of excluding gays as members and
le
</P>
<P>
   The General Board said in a statement that the exclusion of
homosexuals from the Scouts is discriminatory and violates church
principles affirming the human rights and civil liberties of gay
people.
</P>
<P>
   Some two-thirds of the more than 75,000 Scout troops are
sponsored by churches of 31 denominations, many of which are under
pressure to treat gays equally.
</P>
<P>
   The Methodist Church provides meeting space, resources and
leadership for more Scouts than any other organization, religious
or otherwise. More than 400,000 Scouts in at least 11,000 packs and
troops meet in Methodist churches around the country, and scouting
often depends on church volunteers to serve as troop leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The General Board's vote does not change the United Methodist
Church policy on homosexuality. That is up to the church's General
Conference, a gathering of delegates from all over the country,
which meets next May in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   But the vote adds a powerful voice within the church in its
debate of its own policies toward gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   The action on Sunday came in response to the Aug. 4 New Jersey
Supreme Court ruling that the Boy Scouts are illegally
discriminating by excluding gays.
</P>
<P>
   Another church group, the Commission on United Methodist Men,
already has taken the opposite stance, supporting the Boy Scouts in
their appeal of the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg Shields, a Boy Scout spokesman in Irving, Texas, said of
the Methodist board's vote: ``We've got a lot of support for our
position within the United Methodist Church. It's substantial and
it's growing. We hope we can continue that relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   The Methodist Church, like other major religious denominations,
is deeply split over homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   While its Social Principles call for equal treatment of gays and
lesbians, other policies prohibit homosexuals from serving as
clergy and, as of 1996, outlaw holy unions for same-sex couples.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
