<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6776 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-FIGHTCLUB-TEX     10-14 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-FIGHTCLUB-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FIGHT CLUB' WILL LEAVE YOU REELING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The lead character might be an insomniac, but ``Fight Club'' is
wide awake, and it's going to ruffle the feathers of a lot of
people who would rather their slumber remain undisturbed. It
doesn't seem likely that a movie featuring repeated scenes of men
gthe stuffing beaten out of them could work on so many
levels, but it does: emotionally, physically, viscerally and
intellectually, while providing an interesting take on Y2K
paranoia. It's also often very funny, in the most blistering ways.
</P>
<P>
   To call the nameless narrator and protagonist (Edward Norton) an
insomniac would be putting it charitably. This guy's an automaton
by day, a zombie by night. He toils at a well-paid but dull and
morally questionable job, then goes home to his condo, which he's
stocked with as much yuppie-friendly merchandise as he can handle
(this may be the first movie in which a guy gets an erotic charge
from an IKEA catalog). Then he stays up in a state of ennui-induced
catatonia, too shellshocked even to zap the infomercials off his
blaring TV.
</P>
<P>
   Our, um, hero is so desperate for connection in his disaffected
world that he begins hanging out in a variety of support groups,
where the links come automatically, and chats up strangers on
airplanes _ ``single-serving friends'' who require only temporary
effort. It's on an airplane that he meets Tyler Durden (Brad Pitt),
a soap salesman who apparently doesn't use his own product and has
some interesting ideas about what's wrong with society. It's at a
testicular-cancer survivors' support group that the narrator meets
Marla Singer (Helena Bonham Carter), a punked-out, chain-smoking
young woman who may be his soul mate. One will bring him to the
brink, the other will keep him from jumping over.
</P>
<P>
   It's Tyler, though, who helps the narrator erase some of his
alienation by co-creating Fight Club, in which men with meaningless
and menial jobs take some control of their lives by staging
bare-knuckled bouts in which they knock one another senseless. The
object isn't so much to win as it is to feel, because pain beats
the numbness these guys experience every day. Even when they're on
the losing end, they're in control, because one of the rules of
Fight Club is that when someone says stop, you stop. One of the
problems is that Tyler, especially, doesn't know when to stop, and
the underground group starts waging a larger war on our culture.
Their enemy isn't the government; it's the corporations that
control everything.
</P>
<P>
   Judged on cinematic terms alone, ``Fight Club'' is one of the
year's best movies. Director David Fincher, who gave us the rainy
bleakness of ``Seven'' and the glitzy paranoia of ``The Game,''
continues to show his skill for creating whole other worlds that
exist inside our own. Norton, the narrator (who has given out so
many aliases that he's forgotten his own name), gives a performance
that's nothing short of amazing _ a combination of wired and
fatigued, drone and dervish, catalyst and conscience.
</P>
<P>
   As Tyler, Pitt gives his best performance in years _ maybe ever;
he's so hot-wired it's as if he stored up energy while he
sleepwalked through his roles in ``Seven Years in Tibet'' and
``Meet Joe Black.'' Carter, as Marla, finally manages to execute a
contemporary role with a tough, sad performance that might help her
escape the period-film trap she's often ensnared in. The Dust
Brothers provide a pulsing score that drives things along, and the
cinematography and editing, remnants of Fincher's music-video days,
move this lengthy film at a fast-lane clip.
</P>
<P>
   It's when your conscience enters the picture that ``Fight Club''
becomes a problem. Although I've long believed that art reflects
society's violence and not vice versa, I wondered about the movie's
copycat potential. But you'd have to be pretty nearsighted not to
see that things get worse for Norton's character as the movie goes
along. But doubtless there are people who will see the movie only
for its action and not for what it has to say. It seems destined to
inspire overreaction at the other end of the spectrum as well; it's
already being seen as an apology for fascism, although it could
just as easily be seen as a satire of it. It is interesting,
though, that the men of ``Fight Club'' are overwhelmingly white _
and not too smart _ and that one of the few guys in the movie who
doesn't fall for it is the black detective who's trying to find out
just why the narrator's condo exploded.
</P>
<P>
   Selective perception is a powerful thing, though, and people
tend to take away from movies what they want to. ``''Fight Club''''
is cannily designed to play to that; it's a movie so crammed with
ideas that it uses both sides of its mouth to express them. It's a
macho movie that becomes a male-on-male love story (it's funny to
see Pitt and Norton bicker over Pitt's driving in one scene),
that's about wusses becoming tough by beating one another up. A
movie that uses a woman to help its hero get back in touch with
himself, but all but ignores her until it needs to call her off the
bench. A movie that laughs at us for wearing Gap khakis, then
shoves its Krispy Kreme product placement in our faces so hard that
we can taste the doughnuts. An anti-consumerist movie made by a guy
who made his name with a Madonna music video, an anti-corporation
movie made for a studio owned by Rupert Murdoch.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, it gets away with it, spending more than two hours
dancing on your nerve endings and leaving your senses heightened
and your adrenalin buzzing as you leave the theater. If it takes
off _ and given its enormous potential for repeat business, its
success appears guaranteed _ it will wind up being reviewed on the
editorial pages, where pundits will ignore its style and see only
part of its content. It's a movie that makes you think, though, and
stays with you for days, a refreshing sight when so many films want
to spoon-feed you. You'll be talking about it the next morning,
after you put on your Gap khakis, buy your Starbucks coffee and
step back onto your 9-to-5 treadmill.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Fight Club''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: David Fincher
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Edward Norton, Brad Pitt, Helena Bonham Carter
</P>
<P>
   Length: 139 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ graphic violence, strong language and very loud
sexual situations
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
