<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6785 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-ROMANCE-TEX     10-14 0491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ROMANCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNROMANTIC ... PERIOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The French melodrama ``Romance'' uses sex purely for suffering.
Its heroine, Marie (Caroline Ducey), has a blank-faced sincerity
even when she cries, which is almost all the time. She sacrifices
herself on the altar of love, to her pretty-boy corpse of a
boyfriend, a male model who's utterly uninterested in having sex
with her. Instead, she submits to a series of affairs that further
dehumanize her. She wants to turn herself into an object, prove
herself to be unworthy of any male attention, because her live-in
lover won't deal with her.
</P>
<P>
   When we meet Marie and her boyfriend, he's telling her that he
always loses interest in the women he sees. And after a few months,
he has no physical need for her. As she notices him, smiling as he
reads and eats alone at a restaurant, she realizes he's actually
happier on his own.
</P>
<P>
   Their sterile apartment _ no one capable of pleasure could
choose to live in an environment so chic and pale (it looks like
one of those Evian billboards) _ mirrors the hollowness of their
existence. And her narration, an attempt to provide rich insight
into the emptiness of her existence, sounds like a series of
position papers written by someone who's seen ``Last Tango in
Paris'' way too many times.
</P>
<P>
   The title ``Romance'' itself is undergrad-ironic. There's not
much resembling romance, or even affection, in Marie's life, as she
plods from one dehumanizing liaison to the next. If the kind of
psychological degradation she puts herself through weren't so
punishing, the movie could be viewed as a parody of anti-pleasure
art-house porn like ``In the Realm of the Senses.''
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the movie is pretty laughable. She takes herself so
seriously, you're not sure if she'd recognize a good time if she
stumbled over it. (Director Catherine Breillat's previous wrestling
with female sexuality, ``36 Fillette,'' was grim going, too.)
``Romance'' mistakes glum tawdriness for existential truth. All the
poking and prodding take place as Marie's bland narration _ meant
to show that she's distant from the sexual adventures, including
prostitution and rape, that she subjects herself to _ drops morsels
of philosophy that roll across the floor like ball bearings. And
``Romance'' is about as compelling. When Ducey is seen
participating in the sordid activities, you can tell it's an art
film; she never has any fun _ you may not either.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Romance''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Catherine Breillat
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Caroline Ducey
</P>
<P>
   Length: 103 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Unrated _ contains explicit sexuality _ nudity, oral sex, rape,
bondage _ and profanity. In French, with subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   .MDNM/(Elvis Mitchell is a film critic for the Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
