<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPMUSIC-FERMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCARTNEY CELEBRATES ROOTS OF ROCK 'N' ROLL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The next century approaches, the Y2K problem is upon us (or
maybe not) and what is Paul McCartney doing?
</P>
<P>
   Strapping on his bass and bashing out protean rock 'n' roll and
R&AMP;B from the '50s.
</P>
<P>
   One take. Maybe two. Over and out. And on to the next song.
</P>
<P>
   Makes sense, if you ask me.
</P>
<P>
   This is how McCartney cut ``Run Devil Run,'' the new 15-song
tribute to the music that inspired him and the Beatles to pick up
the torch of American music way back when.
</P>
<P>
   Recorded in just seven days this past spring at, yep, Abbey Road
in London, ``Run Devil Run'' is one heck of a good old-old-school
rock 'n' roll record that harks back to the days when the Beatles
were young and hungry and absorbing all the Buddy Holly, Gene
Vincent, Larry Williams and Little Richard that they could find.
</P>
<P>
   As detailed in the CD's liner notes, McCartney simply picked an
oldie such as Carl Perkins' ``Movie Magg'' or Chuck Berry's ``Brown
Eyed Handsome Man'' and banged it down with the help of a backing
band that included Mick Green and Pink Floyd's David Gilmore on
guitar, keyboardists Pete Wingfield and Geraint Watkins and drummer
Ian Paice (Deep Purple) and Dave Mattacks (Jethro Tull). He did
well-known stuff, such as Rick Nelson's 1958 pop hit ``Lonesome
Town'' and Elvis' ``All Shook Up'' as well as obscurities such as
``Coquette,'' a Fats Domino B-side.
</P>
<P>
   There's a certain abandon and joy in working so quickly,
learning a song and recording it all within perhaps half an hour,
and McCartney and friends have captured it. Raw, and at times
rocking very hard indeed _ check his version of ``All Shook Up''
against Elvis' _ ``Run Devil Run'' has the immediacy (and the
volume) of a set in a small, packed bar.
</P>
<P>
   McCartney was and is a great rock 'n' roll singer, and the band
performs impeccably behind him, whether it's on a raver such as
Larry Williams' ``She Said Yeah,'' or the ballads _ ``Lonesome
Town'' is darned near perfect.
</P>
<P>
   The three McCartney-penned tunes _ the title track, ``Try Not To
Cry'' and his tribute to Linda, ``What It Is'' _ are all upbeat.
None is as strong as the oldies he covers here, but then again,
several of those are among the great rock 'n' roll songs of all
time. Paul McCartney has decided to bid farewell to the old year
and ring in the new by paying tribute to his youth, and ``Run Devil
Run'' is the excellent result. You could do a lot worse for a
soundtrack for your New Year's Eve party.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 1417EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
