<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6795 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CHINA-NOBEL-1015-COX     10-14 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-NOBEL-1015-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHINA WARNS NOBEL COMMITTEE AGAINST REWARDING POLITICAL
DISSIDENTS
 &HT;    500&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service (at)
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Rumors that a Chinese dissident may win the Nobel
Peace Prize Friday stirred a flurry of diplomatic warnings from
China's edgy communist government.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare governmental effort to head off a Nobel award, China
has made a series of calls to the Nobel committee in Oslo,
reportedly called in the Norwegian ambassador to complain, and
issued a stinging statement on Thursday warning against Western
aggrandizement of Chinese dissidents.
</P>
<P>
   Such a Nobel award would be ``flagrant interference'' in China's
internal affairs, said Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Zhang Qiyue.
She was responding to reports that exiled dissidents Wei Jingsheng
and Wang Dan, both of whom served time in Chinese prisons for their
political activity, might win the prestigious prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these people win the prize, that is unacceptable to the
Chinese people and the Chinese government,'' Zhang said at a
ministry briefing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wei Jingsheng and Wang Dan had been sentenced to prison terms
by the judicial departments of China because of their engagement in
activities that jeopardized national security and overthrowing the
government,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now some people in Western countries have gone so far as to
nominate these people as candidates for the Nobel Peace Prize. This
constitutes a flagrant interference in China's internal affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   China is clearly nervous that the two are among possible
favorites to win the prize, which will be announced at 11 a.m.
(Oslo time) on Friday (5 a.m. EDT) at the Norwegian Nobel
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   China is especially sensitive now to such an implied critique of
its human rights policies, since this year it is touting the range
of achievements scored in 50 years of communist rule. It doesn't
want the continuing celebration tarnished by a Western anointment
of two men it
</P>
<P>
   considers domestic saboteurs of the Chinese system.
</P>
<P>
   Reports out of Oslo quoted the Nobel committee secretary as
saying he received several worried telephone calls from Chinese
officials. And Norway's foreign ministry spokesman said Chinese
officials summoned Norway's ambassador and made other contacts to
express concern, according to the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Norwegian officials emphasize the Nobel committee is not a
government agency, but a private organization.
</P>
<P>
   China well understands the impact a Nobel peace prize can have
in generating support for a recipient's cause. After Tibet's Dalai
Lama won the Nobel prize in 1989, the crusade for Tibet's
independence from China gained new momentum with support from movie
stars and other prominent figures from Western nations, and two
movies were made about Tibet portraying China's actions there in
sinister light.
</P>
<P>
   A more formidable result came in nearby Indonesia, after East
Timorese activists Jose Ramos-Horta and Catholic Bishop Carlos Belo
won the prize in 1996. Their independence movement, not widely
known round the world, got an energy boost. Enough international
pressure was generated that Indonesia's central government called
for a self-determination vote this year. East
</P>
<P>
   Timorese overwhelmingly chose independence, and deadly violence
ensued.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The dissident Wei Jingsheng has been mentioned as a possible
peace prize recipient for each of the last six years. He spent 18
years in Chinese prisons for pro-democracy activities before being
released to exile on medical parole in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   His actions since then have been considered especially damaging
here, as he has lobbied for economic sanctions and other tough
policies that would hurt China.
</P>
<P>
   Wang Dan came to prominence as a student leader during the
Tiananmen Square protests in 1989, which led to his arrest and
three-and-half years in prison. On release he continued agitating
for political reform in foreign publications and ended up spending
another three years behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 he also was released for medical reasons, but from
America has conducted a more low-key campaign than Wei for change
in China. He has pressed for release of political prisoners and for
China to reassess its official stand on the events related to the
Tiananmen crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
