<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6816 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-PATAKI-TOBACCO-HNS &LR;      10-14 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATAKI-TOBACCO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAMBER GROUP SEES NO LINK BETWEEN PATAKI TRIP, TOBACCO MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANIELLE FURFARO and EDWARD FITZPATRICK  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The head of the Hungarian-American Chamber of
Commerce U.S.A. defended the group's sponsorship of two trips Gov.
George Pataki took to Hungary, saying she has no idea why a giant
tobacco company donated $10,000 to the chamber before each of those
visits.
</P>
<P>
   In her first extensive interview since the donations came to
light, chamber President Monika Szarka-Elling on Wednesday
dismissed questions about whether Philip Morris was trying to buy
influence with the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not privy to their strategies. We don't think about
it,'' Szarka-Elling said. ``We have a tiny chamber of commerce.
It's not up to us. Frankly, none of these issues are important to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris, which often lobbies in Albany, contributed
$10,000 to the chamber one week before the governor's first trip to
Hungary, in September 1995, plus another $10,000 a few weeks before
Pataki's second trip, in October 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Szarka-Elling said Philip Morris had never before contributed to
the chamber, which was founded in 1992. She attributed the
donations to a mass mailing the chamber sent to companies doing
business in Hungary, including the cigarette maker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hadn't targeted them before,'' she said. ``But we were
expanding our activities and we were looking to reach out to more
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Szarka-Elling declined to say how much the trips cost the
chamber or whether the money from Philip Morris was used to pay
those costs. She said the chamber paid for the governor's plane
tickets, which were discounted as part of an agreement with the
Hungarian airline, Malev, but again she declined to give the price.
</P>
<P>
   She said she cannot understand why anyone is questioning the
sponsorship of a trade delegation by a trade organization. ``To us,
it's a non-issue,'' Szarka-Elling said.
</P>
<P>
   Blair Horner, legislative director of the New York Public
Interest Research Group, said the issue is whether the donations
may have violated state ethics rules. The law prohibits state
officials from directly or indirectly accepting or receiving gifts
of $75 or more from companies with business before the state if the
gifts ``could reasonably be inferred'' as attempts to influence
those officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's that niggling concern about the law,'' Horner said.
``That's a powerful reason people should care.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Philip Morris, two other big corporations with business
before the state _ the PepsiCo soft drink company and the
pharmaceutical company Bristol-Myers Squibb _ made donations to the
chamber.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think people who have business interests before
government should be paying for top policy-makers' trips,'' Horner
said. New York Public Interest Research Group and two other
government watchdog organizations _ the League of Women Voters and
Common Cause _ have filed a complaint, asking the State Ethics
Commission to investigate the Hungary trips.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's spokesman, Michael McKeon, emphasized the trips
did not cost the taxpayers anything, and before the visits, the
State Ethics Commission ruled that the trips would not violate
ethics rules because the chamber had no business before the state.
</P>
<P>
   Horner argued that the State Ethics Commission should now look
into whether the companies were merely funneling gifts to Pataki
through a third party. ``That's the issue,'' he said. ``Was this
really just the companies' effort to give the governor a gift and
escape scrutiny of the Ethics Commission?''
</P>
<P>
   McKeon said the governor had no idea who was contributing to the
chamber and how they were paying for the trips.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether executives at Philip Morris knew about the
governor's upcoming trip when they made the donations, K. Richmond
Temple, manager of corporate communication at Philip Morris, said
Andrew Whist, former president of the tobacco giant, made the
decision to join the chamber and make the $10,000 contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no way of knowing what his intentions were,'' Temple
said.
</P>
<P>
   Whist is retired and could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Philip Morris, one of the biggest corporations in the country,
is ``very active, very vocal and very visible'' when it comes to
lobbying state officials in Albany over tobacco-related
legislation, according to Timothy Nichols, director of government
affairs for the American Lung Association of New York State.
</P>
<P>
   The donations to the chamber raise questions about how much
influence Philip Morris has had on recent tobacco legislation,
Nichols said. ``It's disturbing because so many good measures don't
become law,'' he said. ``It makes one wonder if this is all
connected.''
</P>
<P>
   McKeon said state funding for anti-tobacco initiatives has
increased by more than 400 percent since Pataki took office in
1995. That funding increased from $2 million in 1994 to $8.4
million this year. ``The governor has demonstrated an unprecedented
commitment to reducing smoking among New Yorkers,'' McKeon said.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols said, ``From our point of view, the tobacco industry has
been very successful in recent years in stopping effective
anti-smoking bills from becoming law.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example, he said, the industry has blocked measures that
would have banned self-serve cigarette displays and increased
penalties for selling cigarettes to minors.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki visited Hungary and Italy to both explore his family's
heritage and to promote business. Szarka-Elling said that while in
Hungary, Pataki made contacts that led to the opening of a glass
manufacturing plant in Geneva, N.Y. The Guardian Industries plant
now employs 300, company officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 1435EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
