<HEADLINE>
TO MANY READERS, BOSTON POST PET WAS THE CAT'S MEOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: For at least 30 years, my husband has had a picture of Hindy
the Boston Post cat. What's the history of this paper, and how did
it get this adorable cat?
</P>
<P>
   _ V.A.L., E. Templeton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A: Hindy was a feral cat who made its home in the Boston Post
building after World War I, said Herbert A. Kenny, author of
``Newspaper Row,'' an out-of-print book about early Boston papers.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny devotes a chapter of his book to Hindy. After first being
considered a nuisance, the cat was adopted by the city-room staff
and ``spoiled silly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they didn't have anything else to do, all the guys would
write fake stories about the cat,'' Kenny said. ``The readers went
nuts for Hindy.''
</P>
<P>
   When the paper offered to send a free picture of the cat to
readers, expecting a small response, it was overwhelmed by
thousands of requests. ``It was bedlam _ they had to hire a firm to
print them,'' Kenny said. ``At that moment, the Post had the
largest circulation of any standard-size newspaper in America _
over 300,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Declining circulation led to the paper's closure in 1956 after
125 years of publication.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I contact Moxie Firecracker Films, the film company
owned by Rory Kennedy and her husband, Mark Bailey?
</P>
<P>
   _ C.T., Worcester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to the company at Moxie Firecracker, 180 Varick, Suite
1302, New York, NY 10014.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 29, the Moxie documentary film ``American Hollow'' will
air on HBO as part of the ``America Undercover'' series. The film
details the extreme poverty in rural Appalachia as Kennedy and her
crew follow a local family for a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father had gone down there in the 1960s,'' Rory Kennedy
said at a March showing of the film during a Housing and Urban
Development seminar. ``His experience there had a very profound
impression on him and it was something that was talked about in my
family often.''
</P>
<P>
   Moxie also has produced ``Different Moms,'' a documentary about
mentally retarded mothers that aired on Lifetime, and the AIDS
prevention film ``Fire in Our House.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Was the woman who plays the mother on ``Second Heaven''
actually pregnant, and are the twins on the show her children?
</P>
<P>
   _ B.K., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Actress Catherine Hicks, who has a 6-year-old daughter named
Catie with director Kevin Yagher, was not pregnant last season.
</P>
<P>
   The roles of Sam and David Camden have been played by six
children so far, according to the Internet Movie Database: Bryce
and James Braxmeyer and the quadruplets Lorenzo, Myrinda, Nikolas
and Zachary Brino.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet Movie Database is on the Web at www.imdb.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
