<HEADER>
A6846 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-IVOR-MICHAEL-CRISTOFE     10-14 1444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-MICHAEL-CRISTOFER-DIRECTS-BODY-SHOTS-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATTERS OF SEX AND DEATH: PLAYWRIGHT MICHAEL CRISTOFER STEPS BEHIND
THE CAMERA 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Michael
Cristofer with Sybil Temchen, Tara Reid, Emily Proctor and Amanda
Peet on the set of ``Body Shots.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Michael Cristofer is a long way from Broadway.
 &HT;    The Pulitzer Prize-winning author of ``The Shadow Box'' (1978),
which subsequently became an award-winning television movie in
l980, directed by Paul Newman and starring Joanne Woodward, has
split his time between Hollywood and New York ever since.
 &HT;    If you don't think of him as a screenwriter, that's
understandable. He wrote ``The Witches of Eastwick'' (l987) and
co-scripted Brian De Palma's legendarily disastrous ``The Bonfire
of the Vanities'' (l990). But most of his script work, while it
earned him millions of dollars, never made it onto the screen.
 &HT;    It was frustration over a long string of abortive movies that
led Cristofer to try a new career in 1998, when he directed
Angelina Jolie in the award-winning ``Gia,'' an HBO movie about the
short, sad life of the drug-addicted supermodel.
 &HT;    Having enjoyed the experience, Cristofer is now venturing onto
the big screen, as director of ``Body Shots,'' opening on Oct. 22.
 &HT;    Not necessarily what you'd expect from a Pulitzer-winning
playwright, ``Body Shots'' is a 20-something saga about the
tormented, sex-soaked relationships of four gorgeous women and
their equally handsome male partners amid the often-tawdry world of
disco Los Angeles. It's a darker take on the same world covered by
HBO's comedic ``Sex and the City,'' with a bunch of privileged but
lonely people drowning themselves in booze in search of intimacy,
sex and maybe even love.
 &HT;    The cast includes a bunch of-up and-coming young actors, none of
them household names _ Amanda Peet, Sybil Temchen, Tara Reid and
Emily Proctor are the women, with Sean Patrick Flanery, Jerry
O'Connell, Ron Livingston and Brad Rowe as the men.
 &HT;    ``When I first read the script I turned it down _ I thought it
was a generational thing,'' the 49-year-old Cristofer says.
``Although I had strong opinions about it, I thought if they wanted
a kid movie they should get a kid to direct it.''
 &HT;    Coincidentally, however, he had been collecting interviews of
people talking about sex for an HBO special, which he'd dropped in
order to do ``Gia.''
 &HT;    ``I thought of adding elements of those interviews to the script
I'd read, and suddenly they sounded different,'' he says. ``I was
inside them a little more. I felt this sense of desperation behind
their behavior.''
 &HT;    Essentially, he says, the film depicts an end-of-the-century
emotional wasteland.
 &HT;    ``It's about people who feel they should connect sexually in a
desperate attempt to connect intimately in a period extending into
a new, post-AIDS era,'' the director says. ``This absence of
intimacy in their lives, however, is brutal.''
 &HT;    With thinning hair, slightly silvered at the edges, wearing a
gray suit, open-necked shirt and sensible brown brogues, Cristofer
sits in his suite in a Beverly Hills hotel and explains that it was
disillusionment with the New York stage that drove him back to
movies, and disillusionment with the Hollywood movie that led him
to directing.
 &HT;    Born in New Jersey, Cristofer once toyed with the idea of
becoming a priest. Instead he became an actor, and was appearing in
``The Cherry Orchard'' on Broadway opposite Meryl Streep when ``The
Shadow Box'' opened on the Great White Way.
 &HT;    ``I was very lucky,'' he says. ``It was all a bit of a fairy
tale for me. I thought it would be that way every year from then
on.''
 &HT;    It wasn't. His later plays, including the controversial ``Ice,''
have failed to find so large an audience, so he was ready for
something new when he got a call from Jack Clayton, veteran
director of ``Room at the Top'' (l959) and ``The Great Gatsby''
(l974).
 &HT;    ``Jack Clayton, one of the all-time-great directors, pulled me
out of New York and said, `Come write a screenplay for me,'''
Cristofer recalls. ``I had no idea what a screenplay was. In London
he used to sit there with a bottle of brandy in one hand and a
pistol in the other ... and get pages out of me every day. And he
taught me how to write a screenplay.''
 &HT;    The 1980s were a good time to look westward, the playwright
says.
 &HT;    ``Broadway was failing in terms of new plays,'' he explains.
``When `Shadow Box' was on Broadway, the Tony nominations were six
plays _ all of them American. You don't find that anymore. The
whole Broadway scene has faded badly. It's become commercial and
crass, like Hollywood.
 &HT;    ``So I kept bringing a new play into New York every few years
and subsidizing this filthy habit by writing screenplays,'' he
says. ``Then gradually I shifted over to films.''
 &HT;    He found, however, that he'd simply traded one set of
frustrations for another.
 &HT;    ``I was earning more money than I'd ever earned in my life,'' he
says, ``and never got a picture made. I was furious and living with
anger about that. The frustration was immense _ two or three years
on projects, with big directors like Paul Verhoeven, earning over a
million a year, but the picture was not done. Huge salaries, and
nobody's making a movie.''
 &HT;    As a result, he says, his interest as a director lies not in the
megabudget ``event picture,'' but in reasonably priced films which
have more of a chance of actually getting made.
 &HT;    ``I think the whole business is skewed,'' Cristofer says.
``You're working with all these $20 million babies we've created,
and they have far too much power and not enough intelligence to
really be in those kind of power positions. I don't want to make
movies with them, because you really just serve their egos and
their ideas about how to make a movie and what it should be about.
 &HT;    ``There are really fine actors who are in their 30s, 40s and 50s
who are not that kind of star.''
 &HT;    Next up for Cristofer is a reteaming with Jolie for ``Dancing in
the Dark,'' a period movie about sexual obsession.
 &HT;    ``It's considered risky by Hollywood,'' he says sarcastically,
``because it takes place before the '70s. That makes it a period
piece and they're terrified of those.
 &HT;    ``They don't realize that the last two Oscar-winning pictures,
`Shakespeare in Love' and `Titanic,' were period films,'' he says
with an air of resignation. ``The perception is that period
pictures means it will eliminate a good share of the movie-going
market and nobody will go see it.''
 &HT;    At his age, Cristofer says, he's not interested in most of the
things that contemporary films are usually about.
 &HT;    ``If I'd started directing when I was younger,'' he says, ``I
would have pursued a lot of different areas. From writing for the
stage and film it's come down to two subjects for me: sex and
death.''
 &HT;    He pauses.
 &HT;    ``Why does everyone laugh when I say that?'' he says with mock
irritation. ``Those are the subjects I'm most interested in
exploring.''
 &HT;    And indeed, both ``Gia'' and ``Body Shots'' reflect those
preoccupations.
 &HT;    But Cristofer had better watch his step _ exploring the subject
of sex, especially where young, attractive characters are
concerned, is a good way to end up commercial in spite of himself.
 c.1999 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Body Shots,'' consult the
official Website at www.bodyshotsmovie.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood Stars
and other features. &QL; 
