<HEADLINE>
SMALL CANCER SURGERY ON THE FACE LEADS TO BIG SHOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If I had to pick a low point, it would be Day
Two when I took off the bandages and realized I looked like one of
the horribly deformed pig people in a classic TV episode of the
``Twilight Zone.''
</P>
<P>
   (Remember the shocker where the ``abnormal'' plastic surgery
patient turns out to be gorgeous and _ whoa! _ all the
``attractive'' doctors and nurses have pig-like faces that look as
if they've been smashed by steamrollers?)
</P>
<P>
   ``Who,'' I asked myself ``would ever go through something like
this if they didn't absolutely have to?''
</P>
<P>
   ``This'' was the bruised and swollen aftermath of some
relatively minor facial surgery. No, not for wrinkles or age spots.
It was for the real epidermal bummer among an aging Baby Boom
population: skin cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 1 million Americans were diagnosed with some form of
skin cancer. The odds are that one in seven will develop the
disease, and that 90 percent of the cancers will be facial.
</P>
<P>
   Mine was a tiny basal cell carcinoma, the mildest and most
easily treated type of skin cancer. But, hey, it's still cancer,
which means some form of slash-and-burn to treat it.
</P>
<P>
   Because the little spot was just below my nose _ and because my
primary care physician asked sooo nicely _ my HMO approved a
refined form of slash-and-burn called ``Mohs.''
</P>
<P>
   Named after the University of Wisconsin surgery professor who
invented it four decades ago, Dr. Frederic Mohs, the procedure is
also known as ``microscopic controlled excision.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike run-of-the-mill skin cancer removal, which often
resembles home carpentry (measure twice, cut once), Mohs requires a
specially trained dermatologist and lots of time. With the aid of
microscopes, dyes and tissue-freezing technology, the doc goes
after the tumor in painstaking, minute fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Because Mohs is so precise, it is tedious and time-consuming.
</P>
<P>
   But it has two big things going for it: Surgeons get to minimize
the amount of mess they must make, so the patient ends up with a
kinder, gentler scar. More important, Mohs has a 97-99 percent cure
rate. In standard skin cancer removal, tumors return 30-to-50
percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   The downside: Even microscopic, precise surgery is no day at the
beach for skin that is as sensitive as facial skin. Thus, after
more than four hours of injections, slicing, dicing, cauterization
and one very careful stitch-up, I looked like a pig person.
</P>
<P>
   My response to temporary disfigurement was to hide out in my
house for five days. The physical pain was inconsequential; a
couple of regular Tylenol pills knocked it out. But I could not _
you should excuse the term _ face the merciless stares of strangers
and that predictable but irritating query from acquaintances:
``What in the world did you do to yourself?''
</P>
<P>
   An editor pal, who had Mohs done the same week on his cheek,
made me feel like a wimp. Despite a black eye and mounds of
bandages, he not only showed up at the office, he addressed a
public gathering of 800 people.
</P>
<P>
   When I mentioned this difference to another friend _ a guy who
sports more than his share of scars _ he told me not to feel bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a man isn't always the greatest thing,'' he said. ``We
die earlier and do some really stupid stuff. But there ARE two
things about beingthat are undeniably an advantage: You can
pee standing up and, the more maimed you are in public, the better
everybody thinks you look. It's not the same for women.''
</P>
<P>
   That wisdom, and a reduction in the swelling have lifted my
spirits. Besides, when I went in the other day to have the stitches
taken out, I got a look at the Polaroid they shot after the tumor
was removed but before the doc did his magic sewing.
</P>
<P>
   Although the visible part of the cancer had been just a little
bigger than the head of a pin, the hole left from excavating the
entire thing was the size of a contact lens.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Mohs, and a fine doc, the scar I'll have will be a
wisp.
</P>
<P>
   If only the pig people had been so lucky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
