A6851 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-BREAST-CANCER-HNS &LR;      10-14 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAST-CANCER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH WORKERS TRY TO CRACK CULTURAL BARRIERS TO BREAST EXAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARSHA GINSBURG  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The young Hispanic mother was stricken with
breast cancer, and although she had access to good health care, she
initially turned down treatment because her husband could not stand
the idea of his wife being examined by a male doctor.
</P>
<P>
   By the time her family angrily pressured him into letting the
woman get help, it was too late. About a month after getting
treatment, she died at age 38, leaving behind four young children.
</P>
<P>
   The anecdote points up the struggles in reaching out to
minorities of all kinds, many of whom have cultural roadblocks that
prevent them from seeking both preventive care and medical
treatment for breast cancer. The cultural divide cuts across an
array of ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   But by using creative approaches that have proved to be
successful in a medical profession still male- and white-dominated,
traditionally ignored groups are slowly responding to outreach.
</P>
<P>
   A conference at the University of California at San Francisco on
ways to prevent and treat breast cancer by integrating Western
medicine with traditional healing practices will emphasize
inclusion of underserved minorities.
</P>
<P>
   One way doctors are successfully reaching out to minorities is
by using the lay community for door-to-door programs that both
contact women directly and provide medical professionals with
sensitive approaches to cultural issues.
</P>
<P>
   One of the groups attending Saturday's conference is Companeras
En Accion, a federally funded organization that helps recruit and
train health advisers.
</P>
<P>
   The advisers tend to be of the same ethnic origin as the groups
they are targeting and often are empathetic to the cultural
differences and barriers that prevent them from getting the help
they need.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women who give education classes on breast cancer go over the
myths,'' said Claudia Sandoval, who works with the San Diego-based
Companeras, which started out targeting Hispanic women but has
since expanded to other minorities. ``A lot of (Hispanic) men say,
`I don't want my wife to be seen by another man,' that kind of
machismo thing. We're telling them you need to get away from
that.''
</P>
<P>
   From women whose culture dictates modesty, it also may be hard
to face examination, Sandoval said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell them you have to change that attitude,'' she said.
``Would you rather be embarrassed or dead?''
</P>
<P>
   Irene Lopez, who coordinates the educators, said many educators
have experienced the same cultural barriers as the women they
teach. Because of that women tend to trust them more than
establishment doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gain their trust and confidence,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said language is another ongoing barrier because although
interest is expressed in reaching out to minorities, most
information is still in English.
</P>
<P>
   To combat that, Stephen McPhee, a UC-San Francisco professor of
medicine, and his colleagues waged an all-out media campaign in
Vietnamese.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've been able to show that it just takes targeted
education and using language and role models, as well as culturally
appropriate methods. You have to respect the culture of the
women,'' McPhee said.
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Jenkins, a breast cancer survivor and outreach worker in
Southern California, found that African-American women felt fearful
of screenings and exams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fear of the unknown. What they don't know they don't want
to know,'' said Jenkins, who turns 60 in December, and was stricken
with breast cancer at age 36.
</P>
<P>
   She tells women not to be afraid, and that her early discovery
of a breast lump ultimately saved her life. She also tells them
that any relationship that's lost over breasts wasn't worth having
to begin with.
</P>
<P>
   And she tells them how glad she is that she got to raise her
three children, hoping her experience will permeate any cultural
barriers women might face.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what I wanted out of the deal: to live and raise my
children,'' Jenkins said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
