<HEADLINE>
DESPITE STAR POWER, `STORY OF US' DISAPPOINTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   That complex and high-maintenance state of mind called marriage
is comedically, often cloyingly _ and not near cynically enough _
examined in Rob Reiner's newest feel-good film, ``The Story of
Us.'' Reiner has directed equally clean-cut cinematic excursions
into the workings of the human heart in ``When Harry Met Sally''
and the much better ``The American President,'' which at least had
some subtextual depth, dimension and purpose.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's its short running time but ``The Story of Us''
doesn't delve very deeply into the emotional mayhem that reigns _
and is ruining _ the 15-year relationship between Ben (Bruce
Willis) and Katie (Michelle Pfeiffer) Jordan. They have a great
house, two perfect children, jobs to die for and the requisite
``best friends'' with whom they discuss their wedded woes.
</P>
<P>
   So why is this once-blissful world falling apart? This is the
family who plays together and each evening at the dinner table,
blurts out the highs and lows of each members' day. In ``The Story
of Us'' the culprit is the tics and quirks and personality traits
that initially brought Ben and Katie together in the first place
but which have built up over the years into a maelstrom of anger,
silence and mis-communication.
</P>
<P>
   Reiner uses the device of the actors talking to the screen (much
like Woody Allen utilized in his more abrasive story of marriage,
``Husbands and Wives'') and looks at Ben and Katie's life through
flashbacks and thoughts after they have separated. But Reiner never
strives for much more than platitudes, nifty one-liners and surface
skimming in telling us about the journey Ben and Katie have made
together _ and apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all illusions,'' remarks one friend to Ben about
marriage. And indeed, ``The Story of Us'' is mostly illusion as
well. It may be that there is humor in pathos, tragedy and sadness
after a certain amount of time has passed, but while Reiner
purports to reveal truths about relationships in general, it's
almost as if he's afraid to look at this couple's darkest interior
and their real disenchantment, disappointment and dismay.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately this ``tell me, not show me'' movie works as a
crowd-pleaser but dissipates into an easy, accessible ending sure
to make couples go home feeling happy because they've just seen
gorgeous Michelle Pfeiffer and cool Bruce Willis go through the
same carping and picking that they have. But in truth, these
star-powered actors never really strike many sparks together (and
in fairness the script doesn't really give them the opportunity)
though each is affecting in individual scenes.
</P>
<P>
   What starts as an energetic, vitriolic joust between spouses
inevitably winds up a low energy, contrived film that tidily ties
up its loose ends, makes so few waves and has so little insight
into how tough relationships are that I scratched my head in wonder
as to why this pair of one-dimensional characters couldn't find
happiness in such a shallow story.
</P>
<P>
   The Story of Us. Directed by Rob Reiner. Written by Alan
Zweibel, Jessie Nelson. Cast: Bruce Willis, Michelle Pfeiffer.
Universal Pictures. 92 minutes. Rated R for language, sexual
content.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 1507EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6856 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-MORRISON17-COX     10-14 2218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MORRISON17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WRITING ATLANTA'S NIGHTMARE
 &HT;    Morrison and Bambara's literary friendship leads to posthumous
publication of novel on child murders
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 17
 &HT;    By Valerie Boyd
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Toni Morrison had a problem. She was editing her late friend
Toni Cade Bambara's masterwork _ a challenging novel set in
Atlanta. But she was missing something.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Bambara's death in 1995, Morrison, along with
Bambara's daughter, decided to publish ``Those Bones Are Not My
Child,'' the novel Bambara had worked on for 12 years. Morrison was
delighted to find ``this huge thing of well-typed stuff,'' she
recalls in a phone interview from her home on New York's Hudson
River. No illegible paper-clipped notes to decipher. No ``penciled
sentences that curl up and down the page and wind around.'' A
former editor at Random House, Morrison wasn't even daunted by the
manuscript's 1,800 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem was, a page was missing _ the first page.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can fudge a lot as an editor,'' Morrison says, ``but you
cannot fudge the first page.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrison had always admired Bambara's ``extraordinary wit,'' she
says. ``So I just thought, `What kind of trick is she pulling on
me?'''
</P>
<P>
   Calls to Bambara's daughter, Karma Bene Bambara, and to friends
and associates yielded nothing. After about eight months of
desperately seeking the first page, Morrison recalls, she resorted
to the things that had sustained her friendship with Bambara for
nearly a quarter-century: talk and laughter. Though Bambara was no
longer physically present to answer, Morrison asked her for help:
``I said, `Toni, puuh-leeeaz, what is this about?'''
</P>
<P>
   A short while later, Morrison was rooting through old boxes and
file cabinets at her home. Though she'd lost a devastating amount
of material in a 1993 fire, Morrison was amazed to find an early
version of Bambara's book in progress. ``It was not even a
version,'' she says. ``It was just 50 pages, but it included the
first page,'' she says, her easy laughter rumbling through the
phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   With that problem solved, Morrison got down to the arduous
business of cutting the massive manuscript to a more manageable _
and more commercially sellable _ size. That task presented its own
problem: Morrison was ``seduced'' by Bambara's writing. ``I'd get
caught up in it,'' she explains, ``which is a marvelous sign of the
power a book has. But at the same time, you're not doing your work,
which is to look at it with a surgeon's eye, or to look at it
coldly and be unimpressed, unseduced. If you start loving it,
you're not gonna cut it.''
</P>
<P>
   Having sold Pantheon on the idea of publishing the book _ with
all money going to Bambara's daughter _ Morrison asked for an
in-house copy editor to read the book and to make initial
corrections and cutting suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   Then Morrison took up her red pen again. Cutting Bambara's
writing must be done ``in an elegant way,'' Morrison says, because
``she's very, very intricate, and almost cunning, in her
structure.'' One excised sentence could unravel a crucial thread in
the story. Yet Morrison, the author of seven novels of her own
(``Paradise,'' ``Beloved'' and ``Sula'' among them), managed to
edit Bambara's book rather seamlessly. The reader never gets the
sense that Morrison's distinct voice is intruding on the narrative.
Always, Bambara's voice is telling this story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say that I'm very good at that,'' says Morrison, who
teaches at Princeton. ``Editing is, I suppose, like teaching in a
way, because you really are trying to make certain that the
author's voice is clear and it's what the author wants, what the
text is demanding _ in that style, in that fashion. What would this
author say if she had her lifetime to do this? How would she say
it?''
</P>
<P>
   In editing ``Those Bones,'' Morrison carefully read the novel
more than a dozen times. ``Every time I read it,'' she says, ``I
felt better, even though I had looked into those terrible, dark
places.''
</P>
<P>
   Those places are the very ones where terror skulked in the late
1970s and early '80s, when more than 40 black children were
murdered in Atlanta, then marketing itself as ``The City Too Busy
To Hate.''
</P>
<P>
   A riveting fusion of fact and fiction, ``Those Bones'' begins on
a Sunday in July 1980, when Zala Spencer discovers that her oldest
child, Sonny, has not come home from a Boys' Club trip. At first,
she believes her 14-year-old is pulling some kind of defiant act.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played her. He depended on her fear being stronger than
anger,'' Bambara writes from inside Zala's head. ``So he could come
home when he got good and ready, saunter in, the crooked grin, that
chipped tooth in front a prize he would flash. And she, relieved,
would let him outtalk her. But she was not going for it, not
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, however, Zala and her estranged husband, Spence, a Vietnam
War veteran, are frantically searching for their son. Meanwhile,
their younger children, 9-year-old Kofi and 7-year-old Kenti,
helplessly witness their family's implosion.
</P>
<P>
   Listen as Bambara writes from the perspective of the little girl
lamenting the loss of normalcy:
</P>
<P>
   ``All week Kenti had been waiting for Sunday. She wanted her
ruffled petticoat pulled down over her head. She wanted to lean her
back against Mama's chest and step into her good dress noisy with
starch and warm from the iron. She wanted to stand up in big
people's church and give the lesson from her Sunday-school group.
... Every time they were supposed to go somewhere, Mama would pull
the stop bell before they got there. And they'd have to get off the
bus and trot after her while she tacked up Sonny's picture on a
pole.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a multilayered portrayal of black life is rare in American
literature, Morrison notes. ``There's the negative image and then
there's the positive image, and neither one holds anything that is
like a complicated, interesting black life.'' Eliciting such
complexity from her characters, however, was one of Bambara's
strong suits. ``She loathed, as I do, the sort of simplistic
reduction of black people,'' Morrison says. ``And she loathed, as I
do, that notion that all black people are good, and everybody can
eat off their grandmother's floor.''
</P>
<P>
   When you read Bambara's fiction, Morrison says, you see real
black people, in all their courage, confusion _ and complexity. As
Morrison puts it: ``You laugh, you weep, you disagree, but you
recognize.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Morrison says, ``you want to slap Zala because she's
not paying attention to her kids, but you understand this is what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Spencer family is fictional, their story, Morrison
points out, ``has got to rest on publicly verifiable information.
Otherwise, it doesn't work.'' Thus, many Atlanta landmarks _
MARTA's Five Points station, Paschal's restaurant, Bowen Homes _
are important settings in the novel. Likewise, some of the book's
supporting characters come straight from the headlines of the '80s:
Atlanta's then-Police Chief Eldrin Bell and former Mayor Maynard
Jackson even make appearances.
</P>
<P>
   And, despite its horrific subject matter, ``Those Bones'' is
rife with unexpected, often irreverent, humor. Here's how Bambara
describes Jackson, as he prepares to address a crowd of black
residents:
</P>
<P>
   ``This was Himself, the Mayor, Big M, ... the Chief, the
Silver-Tongued Emperor who knew just how to enliven dull newsprint,
telling the good ole boys of big biznis to kiss his royal yellow
behind while he ushered in the Second Reconstruction. And yeah,
sure, people reminded each other, he'd messed up on occasion, the
man's human and give me a break, like his handling of the garbage
workers' strike, yeah, yeah, but chalk that up to that diet Dick
Gregory put him on without adding the postscript that in case of
emergency brainwork to grab a fish sammich. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the novel, Bambara glides in and out of the
vernacular, the novel's language shifting subtly to suit each
character's perspective. ``Her ear is flawless, her instincts, her
observations _ she really can go there,'' Morrison says. ``And you
know it's not even a question of authenticity. It's just right.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrison, a Nobel laureate and a Pulitzer Prize winner, met Toni
Cade Bambara in the early 1970s, while Morrison was working as an
editor at Random House and actively looking to publish black female
authors. Bambara _ who had edited a groundbreaking 1970 anthology,
``The Black Woman'' _ strode into Morrison's office and engaged her
in a ``very funny, fun, interesting conversation.'' Soon, Morrison
remembers, Bambara ``turned in these stories which were amazing to
me. They were so sophisticated, so far beyond the kind of
literature that was being published at that time. It wasn't
harangue, you know. It was beautifully political without being
pedestrian.''
</P>
<P>
   With Morrison as her editor, Bambara became the critically
acclaimed author of two short-story collections, ``Gorilla, My
Love'' and ``The Seabirds Are Still Alive.'' In 1980, she published
a novel, ``The Salt Eaters,'' which Morrison calls ``a brilliant,
magical work.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrison laughingly recounts the ``editorial meetings'' she and
her friend had while conjuring ``The Salt Eaters.'' Morrison had
just moved into her home on the Hudson when Bambara came to visit _
and to write _ for several days while Morrison unpacked. ``It was
total chaos. She would go upstairs and work, then she'd run down
the stairs and say, `What about this?''' Morrison recalls. ``Then I
would sit down and go over that, then she'd run back up the stairs.
It was the most amazing _ but certainly extremely efficient _ way
to do it, because she was so clear. She could focus in immediately.
I would just have to grunt and point and she knew exactly what I
was suggesting.''
</P>
<P>
   By that time, Bambara, also a documentary filmmaker, was living
in Atlanta _ partially at the suggestion of a seer who had advised
her that Atlanta was part of her destiny, Morrison says.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I lived in Atlanta, I was a community scribe,'' Bambara
recalled in the early 1990s. ``People in the neighborhood would
knock on my door. `You the writin' lady? Listen, the telephone
company has screwed me again. Can you write a nasty letter?' Then
they would pay me with Jell-O with fruit in it,'' Bambara said in
an interview published posthumously in ``Deep Sightings and Rescue
Missions,'' a 1996 collection of Bambara's work that Morrison also
edited.
</P>
<P>
   Like that book, ``Those Bones Are Not My Child'' did not have
the benefit of a series of meetings between Bambara and Morrison.
There were ``no hilarious title struggles,'' as Morrison puts it.
No ``cloaked suggestions for ways to highlight, to foreground.'' No
``trips uptown for fried fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrison left her editing job at Random House more than a decade
ago, but she still felt it was her duty to make sure her friend's
``magnum opus'' was published. ``I know that was my work, and I
know she gave it to me, and I know she wanted me to do it. That I
know. ... I didn't really have to ask her. It was as clear as
daylight to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrison doesn't expect ``Those Bones'' to receive the same kind
of criticism that met recent posthumous publications of novels by
Ralph Ellison and Ernest Hemingway. Unlike those authors' works,
Morrison says, Bambara's novel wasn't culled from partial
manuscripts. ``Toni's book had its own shape _ its beginning, its
middle and its end. It had everything. It was just too long.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Morrison is concerned about the book finding a
substantial readership, given its difficult subject matter. ``Most
people read not to confront anything like that, but to escape,''
she points out.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, though the novel is haunting, it's ultimately not a downer.
Bambara ``did not want, and never did want, any of her work to end
in despair,'' Morrison explains. ``That was extremely important to
her. She wanted not just survival at the end of her work, but kind
of a refreshment at the same time.'' Amazingly, she manages to
achieve that, even in a book that looks unblinkingly at the Atlanta
child murders.
</P>
<P>
   That achievement is a testament to her friend's
``wide-spiritedness,'' Morrison says, and to her absolute
commitment to giving black people voice in ``stories that save our
lives,'' as Bambara herself put it.
</P>
<P>
   Says Morrison: ``Her respect and her love and her seriousness
about us is so overwhelming and is so irresistible that she brings
you up to her level. She never plays down. If the reader wants to
be played down to, he should read something else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those Bones Are Not My Child,'' Morrison says, ``is as large
as the events that took place'' in Atlanta during the
missing-and-murdered siege. ``And I thought, `If this book is not
published, that whole period would just be a little anecdote in the
history of the country.' But now it's not.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  FICTION
</P>
<P>
   Those Bones Are Not My Child. By Toni Cade
</P>
<P>
   Bambara. Pantheon. $27.50. 676 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A riveting fusion of fact and fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Boyd, a part-time editor at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, is working on a biography of Zora Neale
Hurston.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
