<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6857 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS15-COX     10-14 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Famous critic finds meaning in friend's death
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 17.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``We were getting calls from people hundreds of miles
away, people who couldn't even pronounce his name,'' Emory's
(University) Claire Nouvet said moments before he would walk
unassumingly from the wings and begin to speak. ``We even got
e-mails from New Zealand.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not every day that star power is given to a philosopher,
but this was Jacques Derrida, pied piper of literary criticism for
20 years or more, enfant terrible of the strange phenomenon known
as deconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   The name (pronounced dairy-DAH) ignites impassioned dispute and
dismissive parody. There is scarcely a corner in the humanities,
notably literary criticism, that hasn't been touched, and in some
cases redefined, by Derrida and the analytical technique known as
deconstruction. Within literary studies, deconstruction has lost
ground over the past decade, but it has found a footing in such
disparate undertakings as architecture and anthropology, law and
psychoanalysis, public education and decision-making in business.
Even everyday speech and popular culture have picked it up: Woody
Allen deconstructed Harry, a blues magazine refers to
deconstructive techniques of guitar playing, people are commonly
said to be ``marginalized'' _ echoes, in each instance, of Jacques
Derrida.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-nine years old, born and reared in French Algeria, living
now in Paris, Derrida came to Atlanta recently to give the keynote
lecture at Emory University's International Symposium on
Jean-Francois Lyotard, professor of philosophy and French at Emory
before his death in April 1998. They were old friends, and Derrida
made it a point that he had come not to be interviewed but to honor
Lyotard, a pioneer in postmodernism.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, there was no mistaking the singularity of Derrida's
presence. Tan in a way that suggested his Mediterranean origins, he
cut a striking figure, a healthy head of snow-white hair atop a
handsomely chiseled face. We tend to think of philosophers as dour
pedants, an unfortunate caricature drawn from prints of G.W.F.
Hegel or Immanuel Kant. Granted, not many resemble Billy Crystal or
Michael J. Fox. But Derrida, in a photo from half a lifetime ago,
has the cool rebellious air of James Dean in that famous
windbreaker shot.
</P>
<P>
   Derrida is nothing if not a rebel, although what precisely his
cause might be is less than clear. He was never taken seriously in
philosophy and found his flock instead in the English department,
which was ready for whatever Jim Jones came along. Derrida not only
had charisma but he wrote impenetrably, and the two could not be
resisted.
</P>
<P>
   By deconstruction, Derrida and his disciples refer to
disassembling surface features _ language, for example _ to reveal
what is below. It might be customary to write that ``deconstruction
means ...'' But that is just the point: We assume a ``text'' (the
obligatory term for literary critics) has one meaning or a
hierarchical set of meanings, which can be arrived at by reason.
But in fact, according to deconstruction, a close parsing of the
words reveals not just -- meaning but multiple meanings, some
contradicting others.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1970s and '80s, once it became clear that Marxism was
in rigor mortis, this idea had enormous appeal for intellectuals on
the political left. Since objective truth was bound up in a culture
they rejected, deconstruction offered the means of attacking it
from within. They would undermine trust in reason. Meaning, and
therefore truth, is never stable because the words in which it is
encased cannot be pinned on a slide like butterflies. They can be
shown to contradict what the author presumably intended. In such a
way does the ``text'' subvert meaning. It says many things at once,
and the reader determines what those meanings are (the schools call
a variant of this technique critical thinking). By the nature of
language itself, the author has lost control of his own words.
</P>
<P>
   Now, to most people this is sheer hokum, a perverse sophistry
masquerading as ``rigor.'' If nothing more were at stake than
literary criticism, no one would care. But the dagger concealed
within deconstruction is that words cannot be trusted, that one
standard of beauty or excellence is no better (or worse) than
another, that objective truth is unknowable. Thus the charge of
nihilism.
</P>
<P>
   It is a difficult one to refute, but less damaging than the
contradiction inherent in the entire project that Derrida wrought:
If words are suspect and meaning a mirage, then what is the point?
Life is short, and deconstruction can go on forever.
</P>
<P>
   For two hours and 15 minutes Derrida parsed a single sentence
Lyotard had written before he was found to have leukemia. The
sentence was: There Shall Be No Mourning. Derrida explicated it
this way and that, and did so with a didactic charm that had many
hanging onto every word.
</P>
<P>
   Not all, to be sure: There were a few nodding heads and a more
than a few fish-eyed expressions of vacuity. But in the end Derrida
was able to construe from his friend's words something he was
willing to settle upon, something he might even be willing to call
its meaning: In the face of genocide, in the face of death, we do
not stop to pity ourselves for those we have lost, but rather we
carry on and fight injustice with justice. Hardly a profound
thought, but an admirable one all the same, and the 900 who came to
Emory to hear it must have left with the hope that it be
deconstructed no further. It was fine, just fine, as it was.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
