<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6868 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-COLORADO17-COX     10-14 2122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLORADO17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Colorado's Black Canyon of the Gunnison presents a monumental
challenge for hikers, fly-fishers
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Oct. 17.
 &HT;    By Susan Abramson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTROSE, Colo. _ There's only one way into this canyon by car.
We shift down and go as slowly as possible. A sign tells us what we
already know: This is one steep drive. The grade is 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The last time my friend Eddie Moore drove this road, his brakes
went out halfway down. He and his fishing buddies prayed they'd be
able to stop before plunging into their destination _ the Gunnison
River. Somehow they managed. This time, Eddie suggests we take the
rental car, with its new brakes.
</P>
<P>
   No disagreement there.
</P>
<P>
   Along with our friend Kim Wessel, Eddie and I had contemplated
hiking into the Black Canyon of the Gunnison National Monument. The
brochure says to plan an hour and a half down and two or more back
up on the Gunnison Route, the path that is most used by day hikers.
It's just one mile, but it drops 1,800 feet. Calling it a path is
generous _ there are lots of loose rocks and no marked trails. The
National Park Service has thoughtfully provided an 80-foot-chain to
help ease you down.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the easiest of the hikes into the inner canyon. The
longest drops 2,660 feet. For any of them, you must get a
backcountry permit. That's so park rangers can keep track of who
goes in. A pamphlet on hiking the inner canyon offers this chipper
bit of advice: ``Hikers are expected to find their own way and be
prepared for self-rescue.''
</P>
<P>
   Self-rescue?
</P>
<P>
   Of the 220,000 people who visit the monument each year, only
about 3,000 accept the challenge to hike in, says Paul Zaenger, a
supervisory ranger at the monument. ``It's a very demanding
thing,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   After scoping out the canyon from the rim, we spy a buff-looking
young woman with a fly rod in her hand, all aglow from effort. We
ask about the hike.
</P>
<P>
   It had taken her about an hour each way. We brighten at the
news. But that was for a person in really good condition, she says,
casting doubtful glances in our direction. As if her point hadn't
been made, she adds, ``And that was for someone who lives at 9,000
feet.''
</P>
<P>
   Any way you choose to go, a descent into the Black Canyon is a
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The car ride down, while not as harrowing as Eddie's first trip,
is dizzying. Tall poles line the road _ to mark it so snowplows
won't plunge over the edge in winter. In a short time we drop
nearly 2,000 feet, in low gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several western canyons exceed the Black Canyon in overall
size,'' Wallace Hansen wrote, after surveying much of the region
for the U.S. Geological Service in the 1950s. ``But no other canyon
in North America combines the depth, narrowness, sheerness and
somber countenance of the Black Canyon of the Gunnison.''
</P>
<P>
   The Grand Canyon, the big daddy of gorges, is twice as deep as
the Black Canyon. But it is five miles wide, allowing hikers a more
gradual descent. The Black Canyon, in contrast, is far more steep _
it's only a quarter of a mile wide at its narrowest point.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this, sunlight doesn't penetrate the canyon for long.
Much of it lies in shadow for most of the day, giving it the
ominous look that inspired its name.
</P>
<P>
   The landscape was formed by the action of water and rock
scouring through hard crystalline rock. It took the river 2 million
years to carve its way through rock to an average depth of 2,000
feet in the canyon. The jagged walls of layered rock look almost
surreal against the blue, blue Colorado sky. You half expect to see
Wile E. Coyote plummeting from the top.
</P>
<P>
   We weren't the only ones a little daunted by the descent.
Archaeologists believe that prehistoric man, and later the Ute
Indians, avoided the inner canyon, choosing instead to stick close
to the rim. The first white men to see it were members of the
Hayden expedition of 1873-74. Even the group led by Capt. John W.
Gunnison, whose name the river bears, skipped the gorge itself in
its search for a river crossing. The Hayden expedition and later
surveying parties for the Denver and Rio Grande Railroad all
declared the canyon inaccessible.
</P>
<P>
   But they weren't fly-fishers.
</P>
<P>
   And they didn't have a rental car.From the rim, the ribbon of
river is bottle green. From the bottom you can see that it's also
fast. It's been running high, we are told, as many of Colorado's
rivers have after late spring snows and afternoon rains. But this
stretch of the Gunnison is classified by the state of Colorado as
Gold Medal water based on the number and size of fish it contains.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's where your best chances are to catch lots of big fish,''
says Geoff Tischbein of the Colorado Division of Wildlife. ``It's
where you go for the best fishing experience.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it's a river worth trying even in less than
perfect conditions.
</P>
<P>
   On our Colorado tour, my friends and I fish the Frying Pan River
at Basalt, the Taylor and the Rio Grande. All are stunning. But the
most dramatic, by far, is the Gunnison in the Black Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   Kim and I have been fly-fishing for about three years. Eddie was
one of our first teachers. Separately and together we have visited
beautiful rivers in many states. This is a large part of the draw
of the sport. Trout have impeccable taste in surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   The Black Canyon is no exception.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Bureau, a metro Atlanta high school biology teacher and
author of ``The Angler's Guide to the Atlanta Chattahoochee
River,'' often poses the Gunnison in sharp contrast to the Hooch
when he gives talks. The Gunnison is one of his favorite examples
of a nutrient-rich river teeming with insect life and well-fed
fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference between the rivers is, of course, the
fertility,'' he says. The Chattahoochee is basically a sterile
river, because its water is pulled from the bottom of a lake. The
Gunnison, in contrast, has a high level of dissolved calcium
carbonate, which boosts its fertility. ``It's unbelievable what
they have,'' Bureau says.
</P>
<P>
   President Herbert Hoover recognized the magnificence of the
river and gorge when he proclaimed Black Canyon a national monument
in 1933. A bill recently approved by Congress would make it a
national park, which Zaenger says would further protect it.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, for example, would provide scenic easements that would
prevent some types of development on the private land that
surrounds the park. It also would expand the park from about 21,000
acres to about 31,000 acres. The president is expected to sign the
bill this month.
</P>
<P>
   The vulnerability of surrounding private land caused park
officials to seek the designation. ``There's been so much rapid
development over much of Colorado,'' Zaenger says. ``It's of great
concern to the park service.''
</P>
<P>
   The river, too, is vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   As breathtaking as it is, with its sheer cliffs and fat trout,
it is not the fishery it once was. Its population of rainbow trout
has declined dramatically, the victim of whirling disease, a
parasite that affects a young fish's nervous system and causes it
to swim erratically when it is frightened. The parasite can kill a
fish outright or make it more vulnerable to predators.
</P>
<P>
   Many famed Western rivers have experienced the same sort of
decline. Brown trout are not seriously affected by the parasite and
have continued to thrive. Colorado plans to gradually supplement
the Gunnison's rainbows with a variety it hopes is resistant to the
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Even with its problems, the river holds one of the best
populations of trout anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Wading into the 53-degree river, I cast to the seam that
separates the fast and slow water. My expectations aren't high. I'm
too awed by my surroundings to believe that I would actually catch
a fish here, too, regardless of the river's reputation. I work the
seam and am surprised to hook a trout.
</P>
<P>
   The fish takes off into the current. I let him take the line,
knowing that if I put too much pressure on him, it will break. He
keeps going, downstream. Kim and Eddie arrive just in time to see
this. Eddie grabs his camera and starts shooting. Kim cheers me on,
but the fish keeps going. He takes every inch of my fly line,
taking me right into the backing _ the line that connects the fly
line to the reel. Clearly he is big. I start to ease him toward the
bank.
</P>
<P>
   My heart pounds. I try to remember to breathe.
</P>
<P>
   An eternity passes.
</P>
<P>
   He darts in my direction, and I gently reel in.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in an instant, the line goes slack.
</P>
<P>
   He's gone.
</P>
<P>
   I stand there for a minute, staring blankly at the spot where
the big fish once was. Then I stamp my foot like a 6-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   A little while later, I get another chance. This time I ease the
trout out of the fast current more quickly, so he can't use it
against me. A few minutes later, I hold a fat 16-inch brown trout
just long enough for Kim to take our picture. Then I return him to
the water and watch him swim away.
</P>
<P>
   The fish I didn't catch was bigger, no doubt about it. I imagine
him to be the largest trout I've ever (almost) caught. But of
course there's no way to know. Not that it really matters. Just
standing in this river, in this canyon, is enough.
</P>
<P>
   Even if we did take the car down.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: The Black Canyon of the Gunnison National
Monument is 250 miles southwest of Denver, 15 miles east of
Montrose via U.S. 50 and Colo. 347. To get to the South Rim from
Montrose, go east on U.S. 50 for eight miles; north on Colo. 347,
then six miles to the park entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Fly United and America West Airlines (via Phoenix or Las Vegas,
respectively) to Montrose for $404.50 round trip. Delta offers one
daily nonstop to Gunnison, about an hour east of Montrose, for
$498.50 round trip. Or fly United to Gunnison (via Denver) or
American (via Dallas) at $438.50. Rules for all these flights:
21-day advance purchase and two-day minimum stay required; travel
permitted to Colorado on Sundays-Wednesdays; return
Tuesdays-Fridays.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Park details: The entrance fee is $7. Be sure to stop at the
South Rim Visitor Center, 970-249-1915, Ext. 23, which offers
stunning views as well as exhibits about the park's history, flora,
fauna and geology. A video is also available for viewing.
</P>
<P>
   For those not brave enough to hike into the inner canyon, there
are plenty of short hikes from the rim that offer spectacular
sights. These hikes are rated easy, but park officials caution that
even these are at 8,000 feet, so if you haven't had time to adjust
to Colorado's higher elevations, take it slow.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to stay: The park has two campgrounds, one on each rim.
Campsites are available on a first-come, first-served basis. The
south rim campground has 102 sites and is rarely full. The north
rim campground has 15 sites. Park officials ask visitors to use
water sparingly, because it must be hauled in by truck. Each
campsite has its own fire ring or grill and a table. Wood gathering
is not permitted, so bring your own. Fee is $8 per vehicle.
Reservations are not accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Campsites are also available within the canyon. Backcountry
permits are required, and no wood fires are allowed.
</P>
<P>
   For motels, hotels, cabins or other campgrounds outside the
park, call the Montrose Visitors and Convention Bureau at
970-249-6360 or 1-800-873-0244; the Delta County Tourism Office at
1-800-436-3041; or the Gunnison Chamber of Commerce at
970-641-1501. The park's Web site is www.nps.gov/blca/.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  If you plan to fish: A valid Colorado fishing license is
required, and Gold Medal water restrictions apply: artificial lures
only, only four brown trout may be kept, and only one of those may
be 16 inches or longer. All rainbow trout must be released. To
arrange for a guided trip, call Gunnison River Outfitters in
Montrose, 1-800-297-4441. Owner Hank Hotze has been guiding people
in the canyon for 18 years. His clients have included accomplished
fly-fishers Jimmy and Rosalynn Carter. A walk and wade trip is $275
for one angler, $300 for two. Cost includes lunch. Float trips of
two to four days can be arranged. Cost is $600 per day, per raft
(each raft holds two fishermen), including lunch and camping
arrangements. The river through the gorge features class II through
IV rapids.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The park in winter: The park is open year-round, but
visitation slows after Thanksgiving. In an average fall, people can
typically expect to hike the routes down to the river until early
November. Park officials say visitation picks up again in February
and March.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Abramson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
