   BBO-LIPSYTE-COLUMN (Undated) _ Why shouldn't choosing between
the Yankees and the Mets be as easy as choosing between the Beatles
and the Stones, Apple and IBM, Lancaster and York, Good and Evil?
It's just brand equity. Two ball teams. But no. Ever since Dr.
Margaret Mead and the sports pundits who also considered themselves
anthropologists proclaimed the Yankees and Mets irrevocably rival
tribes, their fans have been made to define themselves by the
choice. When it merely leads to bar fights over who would win a
subway series, there is no harm done. But when cultural, class and
economic divisions are perpetuated, we have trouble here on River
Avenue. By Robert Lipsyte.
