<SLUG> BC-FILM-MATING-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLY AN ALIEN MIGHT ENJOY LOUSY `MATING HABITS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There has rarely been a movie about the ``mating ritual'' _ inthis case, a polite term for lots of simulated screen sex _ that's
as dumb as this one.
</P>
<P>
   It's told from the point of view of an extraterrestrial (the
voice of David Hyde Pierce of TV's ``Frasier'') who is making a
documentary about human courtship and copulation for other
galaxies. His handbook of human rituals focuses on a male and
female, following their progress from first meeting to inevitable
mating _ and more mating.
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers can dress up such silliness any way they'd like,
but they can't disguise the fact that ``The Mating Habits of the
Earthbound Human'' is a pedestrian, cliched movie that is inanely
dumb and utterly predictable. There's hardly a whit of invention in
it despite the alien point of view, which comes across instead as a
stilted reworking of ``Wild Kingdom'' or a tepid National
Geographic special.
</P>
<P>
   Billy (Mackenzie Astin) is a nice, average guy who's looking to
have sex. Jenny (Carmen Electra) is the gorgeous gal who catches
his eye. They meet at a Los Angeles disco (called a ``sacred
meeting ground'' by their ET narrator) and drink ``fermented
grain'' in order to muster up the courage to chat. Soon they're
dating, dining and doing it; meeting each other's friends and
parents and dealing with the dilemmas and complexities of safe sex.
</P>
<P>
   If this sounds ho-hum it certainly is. TV writer Jeff Abugov
(``Cheers,'' ``Roseanne,'' ``Grace Under Fire'') makes the leap
from small to big screen with this directorial debut and it's
certainly not as inspired as any of the television series he may
have helped script. In fact, following this film, he went back to
TV and began working on ``Caroline In the City.'' An even bigger
surprise is that the film's associate producer is Sam Irvin, a
filmmaker who was co-executive producer of last year's evocative
and smart ``Gods and Monsters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mating Habits of the Earthbound Human'' borrows bits from
Woody Allen's 1972 film, ``Everything You Always Wanted To Know
About Sex But Were Afraid to Ask'' (human sperms run around wildly
looking for their target egg) and desperately hopes that someone
out there will find it clever. But the actors plod almost
sheepishly through their paces and by choosing to study a couple's
sexual proclivities through the eyes of an alien, this clunker
ironically emphasizes the fact that the only creatures who might
think it creative would have be from outer space.
</P>
<P>
   The Mating Habits of the Earthbound Human. Directed and written
by Jeff Abugov. Cast: Mackenzie Astin, Carmen Electra, David Hyde
Pierce. Independent Artists. 90 minutes. Rated R for sexual
content.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 1517EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
