<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6878 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-FILM-HAPPY-SPI &LR;      10-14 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HAPPY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZAHN, MACY MAKE `HAPPY, TEXAS' A WINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a breath of fresh air to review a film that, having
received an award from the Sundance Film Festival, actually
deserves the accolade. Sundance, which was conceived by Robert
Redford 20 years ago as an antidote to the elitist, expensive
mainstream studio system, provided a safe haven for filmmakers to
show their small movies. But for the past decade, it's become known
more as a bidding war marketplace for distributors and as a forum
which hands out its prizes rather undiscerningly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Happy, Texas'' won the Special Jury Prize for Comedic
Performance for actor Steve Zahn and, thankfully, he deserves it.
An additional prize should have been given to co-star William H.
Macy as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Happy, Texas'' is a fresh, well-written comedy that doesn't
lag, casts its actors against type and has a real love for its
characters. It's tolerant and full of sweet-natured sensibilities
that allow its small-town inhabitants a great deal of dignity while
making us laugh at the folly life throws their way.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Sawyer (Jeremy Northam) and Wayne Wayne Wayne, Jr. (Zahn)
are escaped convicts. They steal a motor home to assist in their
flight, not knowing it belongs to a pair of gay, professional
beauty pageant directors who are headed toward a small town called
Happy, Texas. Happy is sad over the fact that they haven't won the
Little Miss Squeezed Pageant for at least 25 years and in
frustration, the town has hired the real thing in order to ensure
they'll qualify for the finals.
</P>
<P>
   But Wayne and Harry are hardly the type of guys who know
anything about a beauty pageant _ much less being gay. What they do
know after sizing up Happy is the sheriff (Macy) is a softie and
the bank is ineptly secured. It's a perfect setup for a pair of
imposters who need to make a quick hit and get out of town fast.
But sometimes life has other plans even for the least hardened of
criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Director and co-writer Mark Illsley may have learned a few
tricks from working as a second unit director for director Kevin
Reynolds, who reportedly barely survived collisions with his former
pal and frequent star, Kevin Costner, while making ``Robin Hood,
Prince of Thieves'' and ``Waterworld.'' Illsley opted to make a
low-budget, labor of love comedy instead of a whopper-budget movie
star vehicle. He joyously avoids many of the pitfalls his mentor
endured working within the studio/star system.
</P>
<P>
   Even better, ``Happy, Texas'' gives Macy space to steal the film
and create another memorable movie character after his
Oscar-nominated role in ``Fargo.'' He also allows Northam to break
free from his priggish English period piece persona. The end result
is a movie that revels in _ and loves _ its idiosyncrasies and
generously allows the audience to revel in them too.
</P>
<P>
   Happy, Texas. Directed by Mark Illsley. Written by Mark Illsley,
Ed Stone, Phil Reeves. Cast: Jeremy Northam, Steve Zahn, Ally
Walker, Illeana Douglas, William H. Macy. Miramax Films. 90
minutes. Rated PG-13 for language, minor sexual content.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 1517EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
