<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-NYT-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
 Attn Sports Editors:  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sports stories from The New York Times News Service for FRIDAY,
Oct. 15
</P>
<P>
   BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN (New York) _ Sports Column on David Cone,
who starts for the Yankees in Game 2 of the American League
Championship Series Thursday night at Yankee Stadium. This is
Cone's first appearance in the postseason, and it could be one of
the last appearances he makes as a Yankee, since the prevailing
wisdom is that he will not be back with the team next season. By
Dave Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-ARATON-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports column on the Yankees and
the constant physical vulnerability that makes them more attractive
than a dominating world champion might ordinarily be. Right now,
you have Paul O'Neill in right field with a fractured rib, Darryl
Strawberry, a cancer victim, as the sometimes designated hitter;
Joe Torre, cancer victim, managing in the dugout. By Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-LIPSYTE-COLUMN (Undated) _ Why shouldn't choosing between
the Yankees and the Mets be as easy as choosing between the Beatles
and the Stones, Apple and IBM, Lancaster and York, Good and Evil?
It's just brand equity. Two ball teams. But no. Ever since Dr.
Margaret Mead and the sports pundits who also considered themselves
anthropologists proclaimed the Yankees and Mets irrevocably rival
tribes, their fans have been made to define themselves by the
choice. When it merely leads to bar fights over who would win a
subway series, there is no harm done. But when cultural, class and
economic divisions are perpetuated, we have trouble here on River
Avenue. By Robert Lipsyte.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKEES-REDSOX (New York) _ Red Sox at Yanks, Game 2,
American League Championship Series, 8:17 p.m. David Cone vs. Ramon
Martinez, Pedro's older brother. By Buster Olney.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKEE-LUCK (New York) _ For the second time in four years,
the Yankees have benefited from a bad call by an umpire to win Game
1 of a playoff series on a Bernie Williams extra-inning home run.
In 1996, it was young Jeffrey Maier reaching over the right-field
wall to turn Derek Jeter's long fly ball into a home run, with
umpire Richie Garcia failing to call fan interference. Last night,
it was umpire Rick Reed ruling that Chuck Knoblauch had held onto a
throw to second base in the top of the 10th inning, when he clearly
hadn't. By Buster Olney.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-METS (Undated) _ The Mets work out at Shea Stadium,
preparing for Game 3 of their National League Championship Series
against Atlanta on Friday night and no doubt hoping that the
sellout crowd at Shea might give them the inspiration they clearly
need against the Braves. By Judy Battista.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-CHASS-COLUMN (Undated) _ The heart of the Mets' batting
order _ John Olerud, Mike Piazza and Robin Ventura _ has gone 1 for
21 in this series. But that's nothing new; the same three players
batted a combined .194 against Atlanta during the regular season.
By Murray Chass.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-BRAVES (Undated) _ Atlanta has a 2-0 lead over the Mets in
the NLCS and has beaten the Mets 11 out of 14 over all in 1999. Do
they have anything to fear in this series? Maybe raucous taunts
from Mets fans on Friday night, but even that is unlikely to affect
this polished and poised Atlanta team. By Steve Popper.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-PEREZ (Undated) _ Feature on Eddie Perez, the Atlanta
catcher who has hit key home runs in both games of the Mets-Braves
series. Perez was a backup until All-Star Javy Lopez was lost for
the season with an injury. Lopez used to kill the Mets; now Perez
is doing it. By Clifton Brown.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-MATCHUPS (Undated) _ NFL matchups. By Thomas George.
</P>
<P>
   HKN-RANGERS-PENGUINS (New York) _ Pittsburgh at Rangers, 7:30
p.m. By Jason Diamos.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other
entertainment stories from our partners: Bloomberg News The Boston
Globe, Cox News Service, Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle,
The Arizona Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram,
Los Angeles Daily News, San Francisco Chronicle and Seattle
Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
