<HEADER>
A6908 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-ANTI-ALCOHOL-AD-HNS &LR;      10-14 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTI-ALCOHOL-AD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDER-AGE DRINKING AD CAMPAIGN CAN'T GET COVETED BILLBOARD SPACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANDREA WOO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Eller Media, one of the largest billboard
companies in the world, has refused the Contra Costa County Health
Department request to display an advertisement that discourages
underaged drinking.
</P>
<P>
   After using the promotional ads in nearby Oakland, the company
declined to lease space to the Contra Costa Health Department
because the promotions poke fund at a client, Anheuser-Busch.
</P>
<P>
   The ad had a one-month contract on 20 billboards in Oakland and
depicts three frogs croaking ``Big Lose R'' with the center frog
sitting on a ``Not Wiser'' can, allusions to Anheuser-Busch's ads
for its Budweiser beer brand.
</P>
<P>
   Paul J. Meyer, president of Eller Media, said the company had a
policy not to place any billboards that offended existing clients.
</P>
<P>
   But the Marin Institute for the Prevention of Alcohol and Other
Drug Problems is calling the matter a violation of First Amendment
rights. Diana Conti, president of the Marin Institute, said it was
important to have such popular icons as the Anheuser frog or R.J.
Reynolds' Joe Camel seen in a negative light so children would not
find the real ads glamorous. And Contra Costa County has a right to
use the promotions, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can't use the images to debunk the myths, then there's
no point in the campaign,'' Conti said. ``We do consider this
censorship. Their profit-driven motives undercut the importance of
public health.''
</P>
<P>
   The Shareholders of Anheuser-Busch for Advertising Reform, a
group founded by the Marin Institute to try to make alcohol
advertising child-proof, originally had the idea for a billboard
campaign against under-aged drinking. It sponsored a contest in
April for fifth- to 12th-grade students to depict the problems of
alcohol advertising from the perspective of a young person's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The winner, Tramaine de Senna, now a freshman at the University
of California at Berkeley, drew the parody of the Budweiser frogs.
De Senna said she would see peers imitating the frogs, and knew it
was a problem.
</P>
<P>
   The ads soon caught the eye of Mildred Carlton, a Richmond
resident, who contacted the Contra Costa County Health Department
and offered to arrange similar ads in the county. She called Eller
Media. She said the company initially had agreed to display the ads
for the cut-rate price of about $1,000 per billboard. Carlton said
the company had promised to mail her information and find
appropriate sites for the ads. But she said she never heard from
Eller Media again. When she phoned to ask why, she said a
representative said the company had changed its mind.
</P>
<P>
   Carlton said Eller Media had told her that Anheuser-Busch had
complained about the ads. Furthermore, Eller Media said it wouldn't
display the signs in Oakland once the contract with the Marin
Institute was up.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, Anheuser-Busch officials said the
company had ``no role in the decision to either put this sign up or
take the sign down.'' They declined further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Residents have been working with the Marin Institute, Contra
Costa County's Substance Abuse Services and other county officials
to try to change Eller Media's position.
</P>
<P>
   County health educator Fatima Matal Sol, however, said the
billboard ad might be a dead end. Outdoor Systems, another big
billboard company, also declined to display the ads, to avoid what
they believed was copyright infringement, said Steve Shinn,
director of public affairs for Outdoor Systems.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, residents and officials are looking to place smaller
posters of the ad outside and inside county buses.
</P>
<P>
   Contra Costa County Supervisor John Gioia said he would take the
issue before the Board of Supervisors next week. Gioia said he was
not sure what measures the board might take, but it could involve
legal action or encouraging businesses to boycott the two billboard
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advertisers are targeting young people, and we need to respond
in kind,'' Gioia said. ``It's unfair for the billboard company to
deny us. It's a First Amendment issue. ... This is not an issue
we're going to let get away.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyer said he would do whatever he could to help the county's
under-aged drinking campaign, as long as the image in the ad was
changed. Meyer has offered the Marin Institute the use of his
award-winning creative staff to design new ads for free. He said
his staff could create more effective ads because they were trained
to design eye-catching billboards for passing motorists.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, he noted, Eller Media has displayed many public
service billboards, including ones for Mothers Against Drunk
Driving. And Meyer said he was not afraid to make the ad
hard-hitting, just as long as it didn't attack specific alcohol
companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
