<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIFFERENT APPROACHES MAY BE NEEDED TO MANAGE WORKERS IN WIDE AGE
RANGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For those of you who wax nostalgic over the days when several
generations were all under one roof, look no further than your
office.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, Grandpa, Mom, Sis and even grandsons are all
working there. And any one of them could be the boss.
</P>
<P>
   They may not be your relatives, but you are more likelyto
be working with a mix of generations than at any other time in
American history, three workplace consultants suggest in a new
book.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike the industrial era, when each generation was
sequestered from the others in a hierarchical organization, with
the most senior at the top and the youngest at the bottom, these
days it could be the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   ``At no previous time in our history have so many and such
different generations with such diversity been asked to work
together shoulder to shoulder, side by side, cubicle to cubicle,''
write Ron Zemke, Claire Raines and Bob Filipczak.
</P>
<P>
   Given the distinct upbringing and value system of each
generation, this meeting of minds is creating yet another potential
for conflict in the workplace, but also the chance to promote even
greater creativity, they say.
</P>
<P>
   The authors discuss the trend and how companies are dealing with
its problems and opportunities in ``Generations At Work: Managing
the Clash of Veterans, Boomers, Xers, and Nexters in Your
Workplace'' (Amacom, 280 pages, $25).
</P>
<P>
   First, the authors set about defining the four generational
groups, based on conclusions drawn from their research. They don't
always follow the traditional definitions of the generations,
instead factoring in the ``feel'' and the ``face'' of each:
</P>
<P>
   _ Veterans were born between 1922 and 1943 and number 52
million. Obviously influenced tremendously by the Great Depression
and World War II, ``their mind-set has so dominated our culture
that every other set of beliefs is weighed against theirs,'' the
authors write. They make up about 25 percent of the work force and
hold a whopping 75 percent of all the financial assets in the
United States, with a net worth of more than $7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   On teams, veterans are strong when most team members are
veterans and when the team leader takes a directive role, the
authors write. But if a younger team leader did not enforce rules,
policy, and mutual agreements consistently, such a team would come
apart, they add. Motivating a veteran can be done with traditional
perks, such as a good parking spot. Handwrite notes to them.
</P>
<P>
   _ The 73 million baby boomers were born between 1943 and 1960.
During 19 years in that time period, a new baby was being born
every 17 minutes. They are one-third of all Americans and account
for 53 percent of the work force. They advocated turning the
traditional corporate hierarchy upside down, but often are not
strong in their conviction on participatory and inclusive
management.
</P>
<P>
   The authors observe that boomers tend to be good team members,
but at times are very political, protecting their own turf and
plans for self-promotion. They will not suffer mismanagement in
silence. Show them how they can be a star and you will have their
productivity, the authors write.
</P>
<P>
   _ The 52 million Generation X'ers were born between 1960 and
1989 and suffer being in the shadow of the boomers as much as
second and third children in a family might. To X'ers the job is
``just a job,'' as opposed to the boomers, who ``saw their careers
as great melodramas and heroic endeavors that could consume their
lives,'' the authors write. Fortunately for them, the labor
shortage hit full stride in 1997, and Gen X can finally start to
cash in. Multi-tasking and technological skill are high among that
generation's abilities, but don't give them repetitive tasks;
they'll crater.
</P>
<P>
   _ Finally, the ``nexters,'' born between 1980 and 2000, have yet
another way of approaching work. They may mirror the boomers in
number, with about 72.9 million projected, and destined, like the
boomers, to be one-third of the total population. A generation
dominated by the Internet, that group is surprisingly leaning
toward the same outlook as the veterans. Managers will need to
provide structure and attention similar to the old ways, but at the
same time take on the concept of treating employees as customers,
the authors say.
</P>
<P>
   These insights and more are found in this interesting look at a
cross-section of the work force. Multi-generational work forces are
becoming a strong trend for managers to address.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Cover blurbs
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Never Be Lied To Again''
</P>
<P>
   By David J. Lieberman
</P>
<P>
   St. Martin's Griffin, $12.95
</P>
<P>
   This bestseller is now out in paperback. Written by popular
psychologist David Lieberman, a regular on television, radio and
the lecture circuit, the book describes in great detail ways to
detect lies, as well as what to do about being lied to. Lieberman
comes up with 46 clues in body language alone to determine whether
or not someone is lying to you. The book also provides ways to
attack and/or get the truth out of the person. Helpful for anyone
in business.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Action Coaching: How to Leverage Individual Performance for
Company Success''
</P>
<P>
   By David L. Dotlich and Peter C. Cairo
</P>
<P>
   Jossey-Bass, $28
</P>
<P>
   Coaching a manager may lead to a better person, but not
necessarily better performance, conclude consultants David Dotlich
and Peter Cairo. Hence, their take on the management consultant
lexicon is ``action coaching.'' They say that they can turn a
manager who is a ``pleasant but unconfident leader'' into a
``decisive, charismatic visionary.'' Their book is the blueprint
for how to create such a manager.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Book of Entrepreneurs' Wisdom: Classic Writings by
Legendary Entrepreneurs''
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Peter Krass
</P>
<P>
   John Wiley &AMP; Sons, $29.95
</P>
<P>
   From Benjamin Franklin and Henry Ford to Michael Bloomberg and
Steve Jobs, entrepreneurs have always held an interesting story.
This book provides short essays written by such classic American
business owners with more than 50 essays and speeches spanning more
than 200 years of business. Whether its Steve Case, founder of
America Online, or Debbi Fields, creator of Mrs. Fields Cookies,
each has an interesting view on the tough but fulfilling world of
the entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
