<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton blasts the
Republican-led Senate for rejecting the nuclear test ban treaty and
for not putting partisanship aside in negotiations over the federal
budget. By NANCY MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-FINANCE (Washington) _ The Senate begins a debate on
legislation to overhaul federal campaign finance laws and a ban on
so-called soft money, the donations given to the Democratic and
Republican parties for party-building purposes. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   RENO-PAROLE (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno calls for
a new system to monitor convicts paroled from state and local
prisons. The program would require involvement of local police,
businesses, churches, counselors and neighborhood organizations. By
MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-TEXAS (Washington) _ Texas has slashed the rate at which
stores sell cigarettes to minors over the past three years, making
the state one of best performing under a 1992 federal anti-tobacco
law, according to state and federal statistics. By ANDREW BROMAN.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-CONTROL (Washington) _ The House rejects the effort led by
Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Texas, to force an Oct. 23 vote on
juvenile justice legislation, which is bottled up in a House-Senate
conference committee. Jackson Lee's proposal also would have
required Republican negotiators to include gun-control measures
when the bill reaches the House floor. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-2000 (Washington) _ Vice President Al Gore, sensing
political advantage to be had over the Senate's rejection of the
nuclear test ban treaty, quickly taped commercials denouncing the
vote and plans to rush them to the air in his first media blitz.
The ads will air in Iowa, New Hampshire and nationally on CNN. By
CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AMBUSH-TEXAS (Pleasanton, Texas) _ A longtime friend of Jeremiah
Engleton, the young man who killed three law enforcement officers
near San Antonio, says he was a good person who was inconsolable at
learning his wife had had an affair. By JAMES PINKERTON.
</P>
<P>
   BLIND-WORKERS (Austin, Texas) _ The federal government's General
Services Administration has temporarily reversed a decision to
close eight supply facilities, a move that would have taken jobs
from about 1,400 blind workers in Texas. By JOHN GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-AL (New York) _ Full coverage of Game 2 of the American
League Championship Series between the New York Yankees and Boston
Red Sox. The Yankees lead the best-of-seven series 1-0. By JOSEPH
DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-NL (New York) _ The New York Mets (0-2) return home in their
best-of-seven National League Championship Series against the
Atlanta Braves, but the Mets remain confident they can turn the
series around at Shea Stadium. By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   With: BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN
</P>
<P>
   FBC-BIG12 (Houston) _ Nebraska and Kansas State appear to be the
class of the field, with Texas A&AMP;M and Texas a notch below, as the
Big 12 football season nears the halfway point. By JEROME SOLOMON.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-HALFWAY (Undated) _ Although there have been some major
upsets in college football this season, many of the same names
remain atop the polls as the season approaches the halfway point.
But there are few newcomers making some noise this year, especially
Michigan State and Virginia Tech. By BILL SULLIVAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Former Democratic House Speaker
Thomas Foley returned to the U.S. Capitol Wednesday and briefly
restored the mood of mutual respect that evaporated when Newt
Gingrich's conservative rebels captured control of the House five
years ago. Foley's official portrait was unveiled in a burst of
bipartisan good will from the present Republican speaker, Dennis
Hastert, and former GOP minority leader, Robert Michel. Too bad it
won't last. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
