<HEADER>
A6925 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BOYS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      10-14 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOYS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE BOYS': A BOY'S STRUGGLE WITH DYSFUNCTIONAL FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the lethargy that's appalling. Yes, the house that the
Spragues live in is unremittingly ugly and uncared for, from the
dirt-brown air-conditioning unit to the red-tile bathroom walls to
the empty, misshapen wire hangers.
</P>
<P>
   And the family's criminal tendencies _ the police always seem to
be dropping by to question one of them _ is hardly admirable. But
what stays with the moviegoer, after seeing the gloomy, somewhat
plodding but still arresting Australian drama, ``The Boys,'' is the
maddening inertia of its characters, their seeming inability to
take even the smallest action.
</P>
<P>
   The Spragues don't have jobs; they clearly don't read, decorate,
cook or garden a lot; they don't even seem to enjoy the bliss of
leisure. Instead, they spend their days wandering through the
house, a little dazed, or sitting on the sofa, as if waiting for
someone to arrive, for something to start. Nothing ever does.
</P>
<P>
   The protagonist of ``The Boys,'' which won a batch of awards
from the Australian Film Institute and the Film Critics' Circle of
Australia, is Brett (David Wenham), the oldest son, who has just
returned from prison.
</P>
<P>
   When he brings his mother (Lynette Curran) a Parsons table he
has made and she just stares at it, without a thank you or any
comment at all, it's clear that we are dealing with severe
emotional illiteracy.
</P>
<P>
   The dynamic at work is Brett's return and his re-establishment
as the alpha male in the household. (Dad is nowhere to be seen, and
Mom has a new live-in boyfriend whom the sons look down on because
he is half-Aboriginal.)
</P>
<P>
   One brother, Stevie (Anthony Hayes), has a pregnant live-in
girlfriend, a waif called Nola (Anna Lise), who looks as if she
could bolt at any moment. The other brother, Glenn (John Polson),
has done the unspeakable: he has taken a job, under the influence
of his wife, Jackie (Jeanette Cronin), who thinks he should stop
seeing his bad-influence brothers altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Brett's own love interest is the enthusiastically sensual
Michelle (Toni Collette, whom Americans have seen in films from
``Muriel's Wedding'' to ``The Sixth Sense''). She has waited for
him loyally but _ like his family _ never bothered to visit him.
</P>
<P>
   There is mistrust in the air, no sense of family in a positive
sense and a pervasive coldness that explains a good deal about the
characters' mentality.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Sewell, who wrote the screenplay (based on the stage
play ``The Boys'' by Gordon Graham), and Rowan Woods, the director,
have created a believable world down to the last emotional detail.
That is the film's strength. Maybe its weakness, a lack of energy
that mirrors the characters' own, was intentional. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   THE BOYS
</P>
<P>
   Rating: `The Boys' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It includes profanity and crude sexual
references, sexual situations and domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Rowan Woods; written by Stephen Sewell, based on the
play ``The Boys'' by Gordon Graham; director of photography,
Tristan Milani; edited by Nick Meyers; music by the Necks;
production designer, Luigi Pittorino; produced by Robert Connolly
and John Maynard; released by Stratosphere Entertainment. Running
time: 86 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: David Wenham (Brett), Toni Collette (Michelle), Lynette
Curran (Sandra), John Polson (Glenn), Jeanette Cronin (Jackie),
Anthony Hayes (Stevie), Anna Lise (Nola) and Pete Smith
(George/Abo). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
