A6926 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-KING-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      10-14 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JOE THE KING': NOT THE GREATEST FAMILY TO GROW UP IN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In its stronger moments, Frank Whaley's sincere but wobbly first
film, ``Joe the King,'' conveys the panic, embarrassment and
sinking despair of growing up in a poor, strife-torn household in
upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   This dour little movie, set in the 1970s at the height of the
roller disco craze, is especially good at capturing the mixture of
shame and longing that its adolescent protagonist, Joe Henry (Noah
Fleiss), feels toward his embattled parents, Bob (Val Kilmer) and
Theresa (Karen Young).
</P>
<P>
   As Joe shambles around his bleak working-class neighborhood,
with its cheap restaurants and shabby houses guarded by chain
fences, you empathize with this morose young man drifting through
life, his head hung, searching for signs of hope.
</P>
<P>
   You're also reminded that whatever feelings of well-being and
entitlement we carry around tend to originate from our parents'
sense of self-worth. But what if those parents are too
disappointed, harried and angry to provide more than cursory love
and support?
</P>
<P>
   Bob, whom Kilmer plays with a bleary-eyed pugnacity, is a
grade-school janitor who, after losing his job, floats around town
in a state of drunken belligerence.
</P>
<P>
   One of the daily humiliations Joe has to endure is being
accosted by impatient creditors asking him to remind his father
about the money he owes them.
</P>
<P>
   Theresa, whom Ms. Young plays with a curt, whiplash intensity,
is so frazzled from her day job that she has neither the time nor
the energy to feed the family properlyor explosion erupts
one evening when Bob arrives home to discover his dinner consists
of two-day-old spaghetti.
</P>
<P>
   But Theresa has a soft-hearted streak symbolized by her
attachment to the weepy Johnnie Ray hits of her youth. (``The
Little White Cloud That Cried'' emerges as the movie's theme song.)
When Bob, in a fit of rage, destroys those records, you have a
sense of a flickering inner light being extinguished.
</P>
<P>
   Amid this desolation, no wonder Joe resorts to petty thievery.
His first bold heist involves breaking into a car and stealing
jewelry, which he sells to a pawnbroker. His career in crime
culminates with the robbery of his abusive, drunken boss, who owns
the greasy spoon where he works as a dishwasher.
</P>
<P>
   As a first-time screen director, Whaley, an actor best-known for
playing Kevin Spacey's assistant in ``Swimming With Sharks,'' is
adroit at creating an atmosphere that reeks of cooking grease and
motor oil. And he has elicited performances from Kilmer (who
developed a protuberant beer belly for his role) and Ethan Hawke
(as a gawky, ill-dressed high-school guidance counselor) that strip
these actors of their glamour.
</P>
<P>
   Camyrn Manheim also appears in an early flashback as a sadistic
grade-school teacher who traumatizes Joe with a classroom spanking,
and John Leguizamo has a flashy turn as a co-worker in the diner.
</P>
<P>
   But dramatically ``Joe the King'' feels unglued, as if crucial
sequences had been left on the cutting-room floor. Joe has an elder
brother, Mike (Max Ligosh), but the movie barely begins to explore
a deep fraternal bond that has its own set of complications.
</P>
<P>
   A subplot involving Mike's running feud with a bully is
introduced, then abandoned. While individual monologues bring the
characters to life, they seem oddly disconnected. ``Joe the King''
leaves us suspended in the void of its central character's
impoverished imagination.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `JOE THE KING'
</P>
<P>
   Rating: `Joe the King' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It has some strong
language. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Frank Whaley; director of photography,
Michael Mayers; edited by Melody London and Miran Miosic; music by
Robert Whaley and Anthony Grimaldi; production designer, Dan
Ouellette; produced by Robin O'Hara, Scott Macaulay, Jennifer Dewis
and Lindsay Marx; released by Trimark Pictures. Running time: 100
minutes.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Noah Fleiss (Joe), Val Kilmer (Bob), Karen Young
(Theresa), Camryn Manheim (Mrs. Basil), Austin Pendleton (Winston),
John Leguizamo (Jorge), Ethan Hawke (Len Coles) and Max Ligosh
(Mike). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
