<SLUG> BC-TREK-GILLIAN-ANDERSON-IN-THE-X-FILES-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILLIAN ANDERSON GETS ANIMATED 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., OCT. 25, 1999) 
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Gillian
Anderson with Mitch Pileggi in a scene from ``The X-Files.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Gillian Anderson is unusually animated.
 &HT;    No, not about the seventh and presumably final season of ``The
X-Files,'' though she seems reasonably upbeat about that. But it
would take an alien invasion force to suppress her excitement about
two upcoming films, the animated feature ``Princess Mononoke'' and
the live-action drama ``The House of Mirth.''
 &HT;    ``I just loved the idea of working on a Hayao Miyazaki film,''
Anderson says, referring to the revered Japanese anime director
whose ``Mononoke'' emerged as Japan's highest-grossing home-grown
film. Miramax Films will release an English-language ``Mononoke''
on Oct. 29, featuring the voices of Claire Danes, Billy Crudup,
Minnie Driver and Billy Bob Thornton, with Anderson voicing the
formidable wolf god, Moro.
 &HT;    The complex story follows the adventures of young warrior
Ashitaka (Crudup), who _ despite a curse soon to spell his doom _
strives to restore the fragile balance that once allowed humans to
co-exist with nature and the forest gods.
 &HT;    ``The aspect of almost all of Miyazaki's films that appeals most
to me is the spiritual aspect,'' Anderson says by cellular
telephone after wrapping a day of ``X-Files'' shooting in Los
Angeles. ``Miyazaki films take the environment, nature and respect
for nature as entities in and of themselves. I think it's important
that audiences view that and see nature being so appreciated.
 &HT;    ``Miyazaki's films also have really strong messages,'' she says.
``They're messages that we see now and again, but he delivers them
in a different way, in a more complex and kind of elusive way than
you usually see. He makes you think, and it's not in an immediate
way that you react.
 &HT;    ``The messages strike you subversively and in a very powerful
way.''
 &HT;    This past summer, during her ``X-Files'' hiatus, Anderson filmed
``The House of Mirth.'' Based on Edith Wharton's novel of the same
name, Terence Davies' film stars Anderson as Lily Bart, a
turn-of-the-century woman raised solely to attract and marry a
fabulously wealthy man, and features ravishing cinematography by
Remi Adefarasin, who also shot ``Elizabeth'' (1998).
 &HT;    ``Ultimately, her morals are too high and she just can't bring
herself to commit to men purely for money and not out of love,''
Anderson says. ``Those particular morals end up causing her
downfall.
 &HT;    ``It's a film about paying attention to your instincts, about
honesty and about being true to yourself,'' the actress says. ``If
nothing else, given the way Terence Davies shoots his movies and
the work of Remi Adefarasin, the film will be visually stunning.''
 &HT;    While waiting anxiously for ``Mirth'' to find a distributor,
Anderson is back on the ``X-Files'' set. Season seven kicks off on
Nov. 7 with ``The Sixth Extinction, Part I.''
 &HT;    Written by series mastermind Chris Carter and directed by
``X-Files'' veteran Kim Manners, the episode picks up where the
sixth-season cliffhanger, ``Biogenesis,'' left off.
 &HT;    ``I'm still in Africa,'' Anderson says. ``Mulder's still crazy.
I find some more answers about what is written on the ship and
about the origins of mankind and ... alien-kind.''
 &HT;    Anderson laughs at her own cryptic description. While she's
gotten used to the show's out-there conspiracy/alien/supernatural
mumbo-jumbo and outlandish plots, sometimes she can't help doing a
double-take at herself.
 &HT;    ``You know what's very funny?'' she says. ``Every once in a
while someone will ask me something and I'll say, `I'm sorry, I
can't do that right now _ I'm just about to chase a zombie.' I'll
literally find myself in midsentence, describing something
absolutely ludicrous as if it's the most natural thing in the
world.''
 &HT;    Her conversation may get more normal before long, however.
Though her contract contains an option for an eighth season,
Anderson does not plan to return _ a bombshell which she refuses to
elaborate upon.
 &HT;    ``It's actually impossible for me, for private reasons,'' the
actress says. ``Hopefully they will end up respecting that. But
it's not something I can do.''
 &HT;    Is Anderson at least open to reprising Agent Scully in future
``X-Files'' films, should they come to pass?
 &HT;    ``Absolutely,'' she says.
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The X-Files,'' consult the
official Website at www.thex-files.com. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Inside Trek and
Sci-Fi and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
