<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX-YANKEES FIGHT IS MUCH MORE COMPELLING THAN GOP VS. DEMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ This is the time of year you're a damn fool
Philistine if you're doing anything but watching baseball.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a New Englander or a New Yorker and you're not
watching baseball, you should be forced to stand in the corner and
say ``Nomar Garciaparra'' 500 times without pronouncing any Rs.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox are playing the Yankees for the right to take their
curse to a higher level, and perhaps lose a World Series to the
Mets. That is a more compelling struggle than you'll ever see
between Republicans and Democrats or between San Francisco Mayor
Willie Brown and the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   The drama is all the greater because Red Sox fans really think
their team can win the World Series. They really do, despite all
the publicity about New Englanders' baseball fatalism.
</P>
<P>
   My dad was born three years after the Sox won their last Series
in 1918 and watched games from the roof of his father's wool
warehouse next door to Fenway Park. Optically speaking, he could
see only three-quarters of each game, but optimistically speaking
he has been a Red Sox believer all these years.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox fans such as my dad (or me, if the Sox are still playing
after the Giants' season) are like Giants fans. They always
complain and grouse, but they always believe.
</P>
<P>
   This is a glorious time for New Englanders, even we reformed
ones who never had that wicked accent. The leaves are turning back
home, and the team hasn't turned on us yet. These are the days
before we lose.
</P>
<P>
   I admit it. We're realistic optimists, or hopeful pessimists, or
whatever that son-of-a-Connecticut Yankee George W. Bush would call
it.
</P>
<P>
   But the question is why we here become mentally distant from the
San Francisco Bay area when the Yankees are playing the Red Sox in
the playoffs. We don't want to live in New England or New York.
</P>
<P>
   We go back and visit just to see how good we have it in San
Francisco, and to stay in hotel rooms cheaper than our apartments.
</P>
<P>
   It's been weird to sit in the placid, food and fitness-obsessed
bay area and watch the crowds at Jacobs Field in Cleveland and
Fenway Park in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   I've lived in both of those towns, would never live in either
again, but I have the strangest pangs for them whenever their
baseball teams are in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   People are genetically nuts about their sports teams in those
kinds of towns. The most frightening riot I ever saw in the '60s
was in Kenmore Square in 1967 when the Red Sox won the pennant.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of people were almost trampled when the word flashed
through the crowd that the police had released the dogs. It's the
dogs who should have been scared.
</P>
<P>
   There's too much to do in San Francisco and the bay area. You
can have multiple lives, and never have to live it through a team _
although many do, and good luck to them with the Niners.
</P>
<P>
   A civic life that revolves around a team can be a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   The team may be composed of high-priced mercenaries and owned by
a profiteering jerk, but the fans own them with their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   They and their parents and grandparents made the payments over
the years.
</P>
<P>
   Giants fans are like that, but all of San Francisco doesn't
revolve around the team. It's good to have lots of things to do
besides live vicariously through the adventures of men in tight
pants. But a serious American city has to shake, rattle and roll
during a World Series without an act of God or plate tectonics.
</P>
<P>
   For further evidence that San Francisco may not be an entirely
serious city (as if anyone would argue it is), consider Willie
Brown's wavering campaign to take shopping carts away from the
homeless.
</P>
<P>
   First he is. Then he isn't. The homeless advocates claim the
shopping carts are works of art, in a blatant attempt to
Giuliani-ize Brown. But Willie Brown is no Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
of New York.
</P>
<P>
   He's not nearly decisive enough. Nor is he a down-to-earth Mayor
Thomas Menino of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It's a great week to forget San Francisco's bush-league politics
and watch some major-league real life in Boston and New York.
</P>
<P>
   In other news that proves life is the toy department of sports:
Wilt Chamberlain died and what a legend. Does it matter that most
people will remember him for his achievements on the percale rather
than on the parquet?
</P>
<P>
   The basketball great claimed he slept with 20,000 women, which
works out to about more women in an year of his adult life than
there are days. Right now probably half a million women are
claiming to have slept with him. Or maybe none.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the amount of time he spent taking off and putting on
his shoes alone.
</P>
<P>
   That was a man, and maybe his physical efforts off the court
explain his inability to conquer Bill Russell of the Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   Loved that 1993 line of Chamberlain's: ``I could believe in
abstinence, but I don't know how long I could sustain it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 1624EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
