<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6940 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     10-14 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOKIE `RYAN' ANOTHER MEDIOCRE ATTEMPT BY FOX TO COLLAR YOUNG MEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A baby-faced Ryan struts through the pilot episode of ``Ryan
Caulfield: Year One'' with this cheesy grin stapled to his face, as
content as any carefree fellow with a PlayStation, a rent-free
environment and no pressure from college exams. We learn early on
what's really behind Ryan's glee: He's a cop. He's a 19-year-old as
wide-eyed and cocky as they come, until the first day, when bullets
whiz past his head and into the body of a suspect holding a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Played with charming naivete by Sean Maher, Ryan quickly learns
that this isn't like the movies, that people die, that real blood
flows.
</P>
<P>
   ``A month ago, it was PlayStation games,'' Ryan's teary-eyed
mother says to him as he poses in the mirror in full blue. ``Now
it's your nightstick.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan, turning and flashing that wide grin, utters: ``It's cool,
huh?''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not completely sold on this show's coolness, but its
demographic game plan is certainly airtight. Fox is continuing the
young audience hunt by putting a young face on an old genre. Making
it a male face and firing bullets at it is an all-out counterattack
on the female-friendly ``Providence'' racking up viewers on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   The early minutes of ``Ryan Caulfield'' _ when a gunman mows
down a half-dozen people, including a cop _ serves notice that this
is more ``NYPD Blue'' realism than ``Nash Bridges'' inanity.
</P>
<P>
   As Ryan and his partner arrive on the scene, dead people are
everywhere, and the rookie is frozen. ``It's not real unless you
smell it,'' Ryan says in a voice-over. ``It's like blood mixed with
sweat and oil. This guy's really dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, Ryan is in a tux attending his girlfriend's
sorority bash, but he can't get those dead faces out of his head.
He leaves, wondering how these people can have such a good time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know you had a bad day,'' his peeved girlfriend says when
confronting him later. ``But that was no reason to blow off the
formal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan Caulfield,'' arriving late to a Friday lineup that's off
and running, wants to show how a young cop balances two worlds: the
harsh reality of being a police officer and the often-carefree
existence of being a young adult. Friday's opening episode
introduces this premise, and next week's installment rolls it out
big time, with messy results.
</P>
<P>
   One problem is that Ryan's lifelong buddies are supposed to show
that he's got a foot in the other world, but they merely get in the
way. Vic (James Roday) is supposedly something of an academic wiz,
yet he works at a gas station, spewing intellectual whatevers about
his disdain for organized education. Vic's musings are merely
annoying, particularly next week, after he's robbed at gunpoint and
freaks out. ``H'' (Chad Lindberg) is another slacker who'd rather
be anywhere than working in his family plumbing business, where he
complains about getting hit on by lonely homemakers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Susser (Michael Rispoli) is Ryan's partner, a veteran
cop with an affinity for Donna Summer and no life whatsoever
outside the precinct.
</P>
<P>
   Where Kim Veras (Roselyn Sanchez) fits in is harder to detect.
She's also a rookie but is five years older than Ryan. At one
point, Ryan strolls into the locker room and catches Kim in bra and
underwear. She doesn't flinch, instead telling Ryan to chill, that
she grew up with brothers, that this wasn't a big deal. But the sly
grin on her face said flirtation to me; next week, she informs Ryan
that her dress for the police social ``has a slit on the side.''
</P>
<P>
   The drama series is produced and written by the same people who
gave us ``The Negotiator,'' which explains the talky, tense feel,
and that film's poster on Ryan's wall. ``The Negotiator'' director
F. Gary Gray, whose work includes the female shoot-'em-up ``Set It
Off,'' directed the pilot, which has its edgy moments but relies
too much on coming-of-age dialogue that sounds far too touchy-feely
for a hard-boiled guy like Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   ``On one of those good days,'' Ryan reflects after ending a day
frolicking in a mud puddle with his buddies, ``I can set things
right in both worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Ryan Caulfield'' opens with some gripping scenes, so
far its characters are sketchy and lack spark. In a season in which
one comedy (''The Mike O'Malley Show'') has been axed after two
episodes and another show (''Manchester Prep'') was benched even
before it aired, ``Ryan Caulfield'' simply doesn't have the luxury
of growing up on the job.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 1635EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6942 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-VIDAL-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     10-14 1207
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDAL-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GORE VIDAL, A BIOGRAPHY': LONG AND SHORT OF GORE VIDAL'S LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By RICHARD EDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Accompanying Gore Vidal and his lifelong companion Howard Austen
to the cemetery in Rock Creek Park in Washington to visit their
chosen grave sites, Fred Kaplan notes ``the irony of the biographer
being consulted about the burial circumstances.'' Earlier,
consenting to Vidal's request to write his biography, Kaplan had
observed that ``I prefer my subjects dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchange makes a whimsical, even a charming prelude, but
Kaplan, author of biographies of Dickens, Carlyle and Henry James,
was dead right in his preferring.
</P>
<P>
   True, he has avoided the obvious pitfall in treating a subject
who is still alive, who has chosen him to record his life and who
has made himself, his friends and his papers almost unstintingly
available. Vidal agreed not to interfere with the writing; he also
agreed not to read the result prior to publication _ just about
now, that is.
</P>
<P>
   The problem in ``Gore Vidal, a Biography'' is a different one.
Living accessibility seems to have substituted ``because it is
there'' for a more searching answer to the why that must underly
any biography and determine its approach, voice and dimension. As
to the last: at 850 pages with photographs and notes, the book
joins the contemporary fashion for megalography: cutting the
biographical suit too large for the subject and with cloth yards to
spare.
</P>
<P>
   Vidal is a valuable writer but a minor one: most valuable for
his trenchant and elegant essays up-ending both received and
contrarian American wisdoms; most minor in a fiction that ranges
from several skillful historical novels to others which, lacking
the crutch of fact, call for a fictional autonomy and artistry that
the writer has tried for all his life though never very
successfully.
</P>
<P>
   There can be major biographical and autobiographical writing,
long or short, about relatively minor subjects. Think of Samuel
Johnson's ``Life of Richard Savage'' (short) or Henry Adams'
``Education'' (medium long) or for that matter his letters (six
volumes). The point is not the size of the figure but the size of
the life the writer is able to find or, to put it differently, the
distance the writer travels finding it. With so much material so
easily at hand (though an unconscionable amount is social
chitchat), Kaplan settled for a short journey expounded at length.
</P>
<P>
   The facts are all there. Vidal was born to various kinds of
privilege and one horrendous deprivation. His maternal grandfather,
Thomas Gore, was a senator from Oklahoma and both a populist and a
defender of oil interests. His father was an airline pioneer, the
country's first director of civil aviation.
</P>
<P>
   Brought up in Washington, where his family had strong social and
political connections, Gore attended the posh St. Albans school and
later Phillips Exeter Academy. The deprivation _ detailed painfully
and well by Kaplan _ was his mother, Nina: beautiful, alcoholic,
promiscuous and sometimes violent. She left Gore's father for the
first of several husbands: the wealthy Hugh Auchincloss, later
stepfather to Jacqueline Bouvier Kennedy Onassis.
</P>
<P>
   From his school days he wrote assiduously. His first novel,
``Williwaw,'' received good reviews. In 1948 ``The City and the
Pillar,'' with its outspoken homosexual theme, sold well while
causing some critical dismay. Kaplan writes of these books and the
many that followed with general admiration but little effective
evocation or critical insight.
</P>
<P>
   One page about a book will be followed by six about Vidal's
travels in intersecting worlds: high and cafe society, literary and
artistic cohorts, jet-setters and expatriates, Hollywood and a gay
network extending from celebrities to processions of hired boys
(topolini) through his apartment in Rome.
</P>
<P>
   Names are dropped: the Kennedys, connected through Jackie (Jack
encouraged an unsuccessful race for Congress from Gore's Hudson
River home), Tennessee Williams (hilarious travel companion and
fellow topolino hunter), William F. Buckley and Norman Mailer
(celebrated feuds), Paul Newman and Joanne Woodward (buddies and
housemates), Princess Margaret, the Partisan Review and New York
Review of Books crowds and a slew of British and American writers.
</P>
<P>
   Residences are bought and cherished (Hudson River, Rome and
Gore's present house in Ravello, Italy). A great deal of money is
earned from television drama, screen writing, two successful
Broadway plays and the big sales of his historical books and the
sensational ``Myra Breckenridge.'' It allowed luxurious travel and
living and psychological altitude. Vidal needed to shoot his
literary darts from above. (I like the darts; the acrophilia
somewhat less).
</P>
<P>
   From his youth, Gore was torn between writing and a delusional
hope of matching the political career of his grandfather. It was
the least serious of his splits. He craved celebrity and was good
at it; at the same time he aspired to be a real artist. He divided
his writing between what he succeeded with and seemingly despised,
and what he failed with and seemingly loved. ``I want to keep the
separation distinct, as much as possible, between my hack writing,
however charming, and the serious novels, no matter how dull.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan expounds the contradictions plausibly, but it is the
plausibility of dedicated celebrity journalism and, at such length,
dismayingly flat. He can't pierce Vidal's skillful mask-making, nor
does he much try. The friends he interviews couldn't either: they
were variably fond or dazzled, and invariably puzzled.
</P>
<P>
   Vidal gives his biographer lots of surface and few openings. His
several romantic attachments to women _ Claire Bloom, Anais Nin,
the actress Diana Lynn _ were, to bowdlerize and reverse Erica
Jong, sexless zips. Sex has been almost exclusively with men, but,
Vidal insists, it has been divorced from sentiment. ``I am
depressed,'' he has an alter ego character say, ``partly at time's
passage . . . and at the glum realization that I forgot to arrange
to have sex today.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan recognizes the posturing but doesn't get past it. He
makes no attempt to sound out Gore's lifelong relationship with his
companion and domestic manager, Austen. Except at the start, there
was apparently no sex; clearly there is something deeper, but we do
not learn what it is. The biography has much more detail than
Vidal's own semimemoir, ``Palimpsest,'' and some is scandalous.
Making the facts freely available, though, Vidal keeps successful
control of the insights. His openness is pre-emptive: a tour of a
shrewdly arranged Potemkin village.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan had warning. He notes that ``Palimpsest'' is ``a
nonintrospective memoir without a center of consciousness.'' Early
in their talks Vidal told him: ``I don't know how you are going to
do this because there isn't anything there.'' It was a red flag, if
you like, but biographers _ particularly with the prospect of
unlimited access _ are bulls. It is Kaplan, though, who has been
Gored.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `GORE VIDAL: A BIOGRAPHY'
</P>
<P>
   By Fred Kaplan
</P>
<P>
   850 pages. Doubleday. $35.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
