<HEADLINE>
IT SEEMS TO BE BROSIUS' TIME OF YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRIAN MURPHY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If the Yankees' old Mr. October were a brash,
spotlight-loving superstar, consider it a twist of fate that their
new Mr. October is a soft-spoken, aw-shucks kid out of Oregon who
came to the big city by way of the sleepy Oakland A's franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Surely you remember Scott Brosius, 1998 World Series MVP. The
ex-Athletic is well on his way to stirring memories of Reggie
Jackson _ and ALCS MVP honors _ if he keeps up his 3-for-4,
two-RBI, two-runs-scored performance from Game 1's 4-3, 10-inning
win over the Red Sox on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I l postseason,'' Brosius said.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously.
</P>
<P>
   It was Brosius who lit a fire under stunned Yankee Stadium by
closing a 3-0 Boston lead to 3-2 when he pumped a Kent Mercker
changeup over the left-field wall in the second inning. And it was
Brosius who churned home from second base _ after doubling _ on
Derek Jeter's RBI single in the seventh inning, his magic aura
almost the reason why Boston catcher Jason Varitek muffed the relay
that would have rung him up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really had nowhere to go on the play,'' Brosius said, making
his safe arrival at the plate that much more vexing to the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   This postseason is especially meaningful for Brosius, who
endured the death of his father on Sept. 12 from colon cancer. He
missed five games in late August and early September to visit with
his father in Oregon, to say his goodbyes and then return to his
job playing third base for the defending champions. Many of his
teammates after Game 1 spoke of Brosius' loss, and Yankee manager
Joe Torre praised Brosius' steely focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a tough year emotionally,'' Torre said. ``Nobody else
had to live with what he did. And he was still the same guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Brosius: ``When this whole thing is said and done, I think
that is when it will really affect me. But this time of year I'm
not supposed to be away. I am out playing baseball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
