<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6944 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-EAMES-EXHIBIT-2TAKES(     10-14 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EAMES-EXHIBIT-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARLES AND RAY EAMES MOLDING   A PLYWOOD   UTOPIA  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Britain)   By HERBERT MUSCHAMP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Those who think that there is too much irony at large
in the world should hasten to see ``The Work of Charles and Ray
Eames: A Legacy of Invention,'' the major fall offering at the
Cooper-Hewitt National Design Museum. Even those of us who couldn't
make it through the day without a morning dose of paradox will find
this show restorative.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot of wit in the Eameses' work. The California-based
couple clowned around with Good Design even as they personified it.
But there is nothing doubled-edged, sardonic or arch about their
work. Toward the end of their careers, when irony did overtake
them, it was because the times had changed.
</P>
<P>
   Organized by Donald Albrecht, adjunct curator for special
projects at Cooper-Hewitt, the show offers a first-rate look at a
fantastic subject. Besides highlighting the work of two major
designers, the show examines the vision of postwar America that
they imagined. More than 500 objects, arranged on two floors,
document the tables, chairs, fabrics, environments, movies and
other artifacts produced by the Eames office from 1941 to 1984. The
show is a shrine to the belief that the world really can be changed
by good design.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition was first mounted earlier this year at the
Library of Congress, holder of the vast Eames archives. Here, as in
Washington, the show is presented within a fine installation
designed by the Los Angeles architects Craig Hodgetts and Ming
Fung. This is a happy meeting of minds.
</P>
<P>
   No one has replaced the Eameses, but Hodgetts and Ms. Fung are
the closest we have to their heirs among the rock-and-roll
generation. This husband-wife team, based in Los Angeles and
equally blessed with that city's sunny disposition, has also
distinguished itself in the field of exhibition design with
intelligence and verve.
</P>
<P>
   Husband-wife design teams are thick on the ground these days,
but the Eameses invented the type. They met in the late 1930s at
the Cranbrook Academy of Art, outside Detroit, where Charles Eames
was an instructor and Ray Kaiser a student. They married in 1941
and headed for Los Angeles that summer, settling in what was then
the country's major center of munitions production. The Eameses set
their sights on developing a utopian vision of American life after
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The vision crystallized in 1949 with the completion of their own
house in Pacific Palisades. Set in the lush, sloping landscape of a
eucalyptus woods, the two-story house was fashioned from
prefabricated industrial hardware. It was one of a group of what
were called Case Study Houses, low-cost prototypes commissioned by
John Entenza, editor of the groundbreaking Arts and Architecture
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   With its open plan and its integration of structure with
landscape, the Eames house translated into high-tech forms the
democratic ethos Frank Lloyd Wright had earlier explored in his
prairie houses. With the Eameses, as with Wright, the Japanese
influence is pronounced, evident not only in the simple, tatami
matlike rhythm of walls, floors and ceilings, but in the attempt to
displace Western ideas of art with the Eastern art of living.
Pottery, flowers, the arrangement of food on a plate, shells,
pebbles and antiques were embraced in the Eameses' effort to adapt
an Eastern esthetic for Western use.
</P>
<P>
   Albrecht was also the curator of ``Building the American
Dream,'' a show presented several years ago at the National
Building Museum in Washington. One of the most important design
exhibitions in recent years, that show analyzed the mythology of
the postwar suburban consumer society as a tool for keeping
peacetime production at wartime levels.
</P>
<P>
   At Cooper-Hewitt we see a rosier view of the same material. Out
there, on the Pacific Rim, emerged Homo California, a
hunter-gatherer species that lived in clean machines surrounded by
eucalyptus trees and posed no threat to nature, ho ho ho.
</P>
<P>
   One item was featured in both shows: a leg splint of molded
plywood designed by the Eameses for military use in 1942. The
following year Ray Eames turned one of the splints into a se
of Noguchi-like contour. This fusion of can-do resourcefulness with
sensuous appeal is quintessentially Eamsian. Come on now, shake a
leg! They do, in a selection of the plywood, fiberglass and
metal-wire chairs with which the Eameses furnished America at
mid-century.
</P>
<P>
   Neurasthenic types will head for La Chaise, a molded fiberglass
chair designed in 1948. With its Arp-like biomorphic shell, its
asymmetrical curves, this is the modern equivalent of a Victorian
fainting couch. Pass the lavender salts, please.
</P>
<P>
   Those not ashamed to settle into shopworn cliche will want the
leather and molded rosewood lounge chair, paired with a matching
ottoman, that the team designed for Herman Miller in 1956. Albrecht
says this was not the Eameses' own favorite among their works. The
chair is wildly comfortable but has never freed itself from the
Junior Executive status it acquired in the 1960's.
</P>
<P>
   Albrecht describes the well-known plywood side chair as a
brilliant failure. Starting in 1941, the couple had tried to
develop a chair from a single piece of molded plywood, but they
never found a form that gave sufficient strength to the curving
section between seat and back. What they lost in simplicity they
gained in figurative charm. These are like domesticated animals,
four-legged creatures with smooth coats.
</P>
<P>
   The wire chairs are incomplete Saul Steinberg cartoons, needing
only an overweight adult to deliver the punch line.
Three-dimensional objects made from precisely shaped black lines,
they come as close as furniture gets to drawing in space. Combining
voluptuousness and austerity, they are a statement of moral faith
in American power. Since they don't block light, views or
reflections, these chairs are ideal for people who live in glass
houses.
</P>
<P>
   The chairs are presented amid a background of molds, prototypes
and photographs depicting the manufacturing process. The effect is
to make the process equal in importance to the product. Like
conceptual artists, the Eameses gained hold of the tools of modern
industry and proceeded to play them like instruments.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) &QL; 
</P>
<P>
   Peter Smithson, the British architect and planner, observed that
the Eameses had the sensibility of an ad man. Since Smithson was a
fan, I assume the comparison was kindly intended. Two displays in
the show suggest that the Eameses were indeed Renaissance
cut-and-paste people. On the ground floor Hodgetts and Ms. Fung
have recreated bulletin boards from the designers' studios.
Christmas cards, photographs, art show invitations and other
ephemera convey the wide-ranging curiosity of these designers and
their talent for drawing the world around them into their work.
</P>
<P>
   On the second floor a light table presents a selection of images
from the Eameses' slides, pictures gathered on travels, in the
street, the backyard, the kitchen. The table is an Information Age
mosaic, an altar to the everyday.
</P>
<P>
   The second floor traces the Eameses' transition from industrial
production to information management, a field that dominates design
today. Working with the U.S. government, and with major corporate
clients like IBM and Polaroid, they sent their work on the road
with elaborate, multimedia promotional shows.
</P>
<P>
   The 1959 Moscow Fair is best remembered as the site of the
``Kitchen Debate'' between Richard M. Nixon and Nikita S.
Khrushchev. But the fair was also distinguished by ``Glimpses of
the USA,'' a startling piece of cinematic propaganda created by the
Eames office. The film was projected on seven screens mounted
inside a dome designed by Buckminster Fuller. In the Cooper-Hewitt
show, a photograph of Charles Eames' head inside a model of the
dome suggests a Western version of Big Brother.
</P>
<P>
   To an extent the Eameses were Cold War casualties. ``The World
of Washington and Jefferson,'' presented at the Metropolitan Museum
of Art in 1976, turned out to be their Waterloo. This elaborate,
mixed-media salute to the Founding Fathers, underwritten by IBM,
was the work of two smart cookies who had fallen conspicuously out
of touch. By the Bicentennial year the liberal consensus culture
had been dead for nearly a decade; Vietnam, ``Silent Spring'' and
Watergate had intervened, and the collaboration between art and
industry no longer seemed so benign.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not in the Eameses' nature to walk away from the
optimistic frame of mind they had helped to construct. Problems
would always arise in democracy, and they could always be solved,
by design.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   By chance the Eames show coincides with the Whitney Museum of
American Art's presentation of the second in its two-part survey of
20th-century American art. A comparison is instructive. At the
Whitney a wall plaque informs us that the leading theme of the art
on view is the desire to bring art into closer proximity with life.
While the Whitney show doesn't begin to prove its case, the Eames
show conveys this idea with precision and depth.
</P>
<P>
   In the process it suggests that the Eameses' work prefigures the
art movements that came later. Ideas from Pop, Minimalist,
Conceptual, Process, Povera and Media Art are all present in the
1949 house, even as the building's strong, rectangular lines
mirrored the geometric abstraction of the designers' own
generation.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Apart from irony, the New York art movements of the 1960s, '70s
and '80s could add little to what the Eameses had already achieved
by 1950. Artists could only subtract, isolating this or that facet
of the whole: popular culture, industrial process, media power.
This isolation had its uses, but bringing art into closer proximity
with life was not one of them. In fact the reverse was true.
Relocating a soup can from a supermarket to a gallery only
reinforced art's privileged place outside life.
</P>
<P>
   The Eameses' nomadic esthetic worked for them because they
worked for it. They were artists and designers. The spaces, objects
and images they created had nothing to do with consumption. Rather,
the esthetic resulted from an ongoing, humanist process of
self-creation. Their work was all action, perhaps especially when
it demanded contemplation. Their power was the power to be moved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
