<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE DVD OUTLETS; `SHOAH' RETURNS; NEW RELEASES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Big Increase In DVD Outlets
</P>
<P>
   It's taken a while, but Blockbuster has opened its doors _ all
of them _ to DVD. Since the digital videodisc was introduced in
1997, the country's largest video chain has been gradually giving
DVD a try, increasing the number of stores carrying the format to
900 of 4,500 wholly owned and franchised outlets. By the end of the
year nearly all of the stores will carry about 200 titles for rent
and an additional 50 for sale.
</P>
<P>
   About 4 million households are expected to have DVD players by
the new year, and Blockbuster cites industry projections that the
number will grow to 40 to 50 million by 2007. ``We've been
following consumer demand,'' a company spokeswoman said. For the
last two years, DVD supporters have called on Blockbuster to help
create demand, not follow it, but with VCR sales continuing to be
very strong, the big chains have taken their time with the disc.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason is that, DVD or cassette, Blockbuster stresses
movie rental over sales while the studios favor selling the discs
to consumers. Nevertheless, the DVD tide has begun to flow in the
big rental establishments. ``It's the medium of the future,'' said
Joe Malugen, chairman of Movie Gallery, the country's third largest
video chain, with about 1,000 stores. ``Probably in five years
we'll be about 50-50 DVDs and VCRs.''
</P>
<P>
   Malugen sees a gradual transition. ``Our stores tend to be in
more rural and suburban settings, so the rollout for DVD will be a
little slower than it would be in New York City,'' he said. As with
Blockbuster, there is no inclination to push matters. ``We'll be
providing it as the demand is there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, how long will the cassette or DVD go before there is
significant competition from cable, satellite and other methods of
delivery? ``Ten years from now I can't tell you what the technology
will be for watching movies, but over the next five years, home
video will be a very strong medium,'' Malugen said.
</P>
<P>
   `Shoah' Returns  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``La fin du voyage'' reads the caption as the railway tracks
lead into the concentration camp at Auschwitz. After seven years
out of circulation, ``Shoah'' (in Hebrew, ``Annihilation''), Claude
Lanzmann's monumental 9-hour, 22-minute documentary about the
Holocaust has returned to video in a new four-cassette edition from
New Yorker, to be released Oct. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Not a documentary in the conventional sense, the film puts
together eyewitness accounts of survivors and perpetrators and all
manner of individuals caught in between. ``The unspeakable is
spoken,'' Vincent Canby wrote in The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorker bought the rights to ``Shoah'' in 1985 and sold them
to Paramount which released the film on video until it was
discontinued. A New Yorker spokesman said that increased interest
in the Holocaust warranted a reissue. For now the set is priced as
a rental title at $299.98, though it can be bought from Amazon.com
and various stores. After about a year, he added, there could be a
reduction. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Election
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the nation's most ambitious politician, Tracy Flick
(Reese Witherspoon, left) drives hard for the student government
presidency at George Washington Carver High School. Tracy stamps
out her own campaign buttons, throws tantrums when her banners get
mussed up and proves lethal to the careers of teachers. Uneasy with
her ambition, faculty adviser Jim McAllister (Matthew Broderick)
seeks a rival candidate to derail the Flick express. But for all
his ethics, McAllister has his own skeletons and, Janet Maslin
wrote in The New York Times, ``for all its nicely malevolent humor
this is a story that ultimately leads to disillusionment.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. Paramount. $104.16. 103 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
Release date: Oct. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Existenz
</P>
<P>
   After a bizarre attempt on her life, Allegra Geller (Jennifer
Jason Leigh), designer of the world's most challenging
virtual-reality game, escapes into her own creation. Melding ideas
about an artist and her creation with stomach-turning psychological
horror, David Cronenberg's film has all the throbbing, ghoulish
hallmarks of his other fever dreams. For company in hiding, Allegra
has her prototype meta-flesh game pod, a lump with several nipples.
Eating something ghastly in a Chinese restaurant, an admirer (Jude
Law) says he finds it disgusting but he can't help himself. ``The
best-case scenario of being caught up in `Existenz' goes something
like that'' (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1999. Dimension. $104.16. 97 minutes. Closed captioned. Release
date: Oct. 19.
</P>
<P>
   A Walk on the Moon
</P>
<P>
   As she does every summer, Pearl Kantrowitz (Diane Lane) goes off
to a Jewish bungalow colony in the Catskills with her children
while her husband (Liev Schreiber) works in New York City. But this
is 1969, the year of her liberation with a handsome, itinerant
hippie (Viggo Mortensen), whom she meets at the colony. As a woman
caught in a sexual dilemma, Ms. Lane movingly captures the problem
of someone married at 17 yearning for freedom. Even when it turns
turbulent, Tony Goldwyn's film ``sustains its warm summer glow, and
makes itself a conversation piece about the moral issues it means
to raise'' (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1999. Miramax. $104.16. 107 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
Release date: Oct. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Metroland
</P>
<P>
   A male counterpart to Pearl in ``A Walk on the Moon,'' Chris
(Christian Bale) wonders why he settled down so early. ``You're not
original enough not to,'' says his wife, Marion (Emily Watson).
Chris did try the artist's life in Paris in 1968, but now it's
London in the '70s and he can only envy his friend Toni (Lee Ross),
who writes poetry and roams the world. Philip Saville's film is
plausible as a cri de coeur from a trapped young husband, but ``its
affectations are more galling than Gallic most of the time''
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   1999. Universal. $99.36. 105 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
Release date: Oct. 19.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   THE MCCOURTS OF NEW YORK. Rounded up once more by Malachy
McCourt's son Conor, who also produced the earlier documentary
``The McCourts of Limerick'' on HBO, the four brothers _ Frank
(``Angela's Ashes''), Malachy, Mike and Alphie _ dredge up even
more reminiscences, this time about their early days in New York.
``There was blarney this and killarney that and O'That and
McThis,'' Malachy says of the Third Avenue bars. 1999. Winstar. 74
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   PIRATES OF SILICON VALLEY. ``It's better to be a pirate than to
run the navy,'' says Steve Jobs (Noah Wyle), the founder of Apple
and the hare to the plodding Bill Gates' tortoise as the founder of
Microsoft. Parallel developments in rival camps have their own
narrators, but the complex Jobs, the more interesting of the two,
is never fully explored, especially his bizarre transformation from
hippie to a Captain Queeg who drove his employees through 90-hour
weeks. Nor, for that matter, is Gates (Anthony Michael Hall) in a
film that has, Caryn James wrote in the New York Times, ``a script
with the daring of a scared rabbit.'' 1999. Warner. $72.11. 95
minutes. Closed captioned.
</P>
<P>
   SLAM NATION. Saul Williams, Mums da Schemer, Beau Sia, Taylor
Mali, Daniel Ferri, Jessica Care Moore and Patricia Smith are some
of the performance poets featured in Paul Devlin's film, which
follows the New York City Slam Team as it journeys to the National
Poetry Slam in Portland, Ore. 1999. Cinema Guild. $59.95. 91
minutes. Information: (800) 723-5522.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
