<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6966 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-TRENTON-REBIRTH-ART-3     10-14 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRENTON-REBIRTH-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRENTON RECLAIMS ITS CULTURAL PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl)  
 By PAULA DEITZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the late 1940s, right after World War II, there was a
rich cultural life in Trenton, N.J., including opera, ballet and
symphony, that centered on the theater in the War Memorial
building, completed in 1932 to commemorate local citizens who died
in World War I. Unlike the sprawling performing arts centers that
succeeded this compact genre, War Memorial buildings were designed
to house numerous civic events. Half town meeting house, half
theater, the civic auditorium as a civilizing force in the
community had an architectural presence akin to museums, banks,
courthouses and city halls.
</P>
<P>
   Trenton's War Memorial building exuded a sophisticated opulence
and grandeur that made the audience dress up to attend
performances, but like many civic structures during the great
catastrophe of urban renewal that obliterated downtowns, the War
Memorial, despite its proximity to the State Capitol, slipped into
dowdiness as the downtown area shifted away. Gov. Tom Kean took
notice in 1988 (it has been the site of all gubernatorial
inaugurations since its opening) and announced that the building
would be renovated. Earlier this year, after going dark for five
years, the War Memorial reopened and is more splendid than ever.
But best of all, it once again has a full program of performances.
</P>
<P>
   The reborn Trenton War Memorial Theater is only one of several
cultural and historic places in Trenton to visit for special
reasons this fall, all in what is known as the Capitol Complex, the
buildings clustered around the State House along the Delaware
River. In addition to attending a matinee or evening performance in
the theater, one can visit the New Jersey State Museum; the
restored 19th-century rotunda under the Capitol dome; the Old
Barracks Museum, reconfigured to its 18th-century military period,
and the 1719 Queen Anne-style mansion of William Trent, after we city is named.
</P>
<P>
   Trenton's limestone and granite War Memorial is a blend of
neo-Italian Renaissance and Art Deco styles with a high parapet and
an Ionic colonnade leading to the Memorial Court, the main
entrance, with its blue, green and gold terra-cotta ceiling and
dedication plaques.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946 and 1947 the Ballet Russe de Monte Carlo performed
dances there choreographed by George Balanchine before he helped
found the New York City Ballet. Among the works were ``Concerto
Barocco,'' the first ``Mozartiana'' and ``The Night Shadow'' (now
``La Sonnambula''), the latter with Alexandra Danilova and Maria
Tallchief, who had danced at its premiere in New York in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1948, before starring in ``South Pacific'' on Broadway,
Ezio Pinza sang Mephistopheles in Gounod's ``Faust,'' and his
daughter, Claudia, sang Marguerite in the Trenton Opera
Association's production. In addition to being performed by invited
stars, the opera repertory was presented by local singers in the
minor roles and the Trenton Opera Chorus.
</P>
<P>
   Trenton at that period had a cultural life unto itself, not
necessarily dependent on Philadelphia or New York. What's more, the
theater would hold a graduating class of more than 1,000 from
Trenton Central High School. Dance teachers held their student
recitals in the ballroom. And when John F. Kennedy ran for
president, he stood between the Ionic columns during an autumn
twilight and spoke to thousands standing in the plaza below.
</P>
<P>
   While the War Memorial's interior remained intact during the
renovation, every marble and painted surface and all the bronze
light fixtures and railings had to be revitalized to restore their
gleam and glitter. The Vitetta Group, architects and engineers
based in Cherry Hill, N.J., and Philadelphia who undertook the
renovation, had the advantage of the original drawings by the
building's architect, Louis Kaplan. Kaplan had been the chief
draftsman for William Klemann, the architect for the preliminary
plan, who died during the process. An analysis by Matthew Mosca, a
historical paint consultant, revealed the bright colors that gave
the theater its fantasy environment.
</P>
<P>
   Hyman Myers, the director of historic preservation for Vitetta,
sees the 1,800-seat theater, in its new raiment, fulfilling its
role as ``a spaceship to an imaginary dream world,'' with updating
to enhance the acoustics and improve the stage machinery.
</P>
<P>
   Architecture Grand as Opera
</P>
<P>
   What delights the eye are the decorative surfaces of rose and
saffron further embellished with gilded plaster; the newly polished
marble walls and terrazzo floors of the corridors, and bronze
classical motifs like the image of Terpsichore, the muse of the
dance in her diaphanous garb. An immense ceiling medallion
festooned with garlands and smaller medallions in the same warm
palette glows in soft illumination. Even the rust-colored stage
curtain was reproduced down to the last gold tassel from a
photograph in the archives of the Greater Trenton Symphony
Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   A performance last spring of ``Rigoletto'' by the War Memorial's
resident company, Boheme Opera N.J., took full advantage of the
broad stage with one architectural set that seemed to turn inside
out depending on the scene. The hall was filled, and those with
years in the know found the balcony seats the best for a complete
overview of the theater, the stage and the recent addition of
supertitles.
</P>
<P>
   The company's artistic director and conductor, Trenton-born
Joseph Pucciatti, founded Boheme Opera 11 years ago with his wife,
Sandra Milstein-Pucciatti, a concert pianist who is managing
director and assistant conductor. One hour before the ``Rigoletto''
performance, the couple gave their customary cogent and amusing
precurtain talk in the War Memorial's blue, mauve and silver Art
Deco ballroom. These talks are usually packed, and as in earlier
times, it was heartening to see many children in attendance. While
Pucciatti gave the background of the characters, describing the
real Duke of Mantua, and of Victor Hugo's 1832 play ``Le Roi
S'Amuse,'' on which the opera is based, his wife played the
relevant themes on the piano.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A Link to Russia
</P>
<P>
   Since 1986 Trenton has been a sister city to the Central
District of Moscow. Out of this relationship and under the
sponsorship of the American-Russian Cultural Cooperation
Foundation, Trenton was selected as the only East Coast site for a
major international touring exhibition: ``Unseen Treasures:
Imperial Russia and the New World,'' which includes 300 art objects
and artifacts from the Russian State Historical Museum and the
State Archive of the Russian Federation in Moscow. Its opening,
which had been scheduled for this weekend, has been postponed
because of delays in shipping the works from Russia; it is now
expected to open in November.
</P>
<P>
   Commemorating the founding in 1799 of the Russian-American
Company, the exhibition will document the little-known story of the
Russian colonization of what is now northern California and Alaska,
an effort motivated by the fur trade.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Pfeifer Swezey, the guest curator of ``Unseen
Treasures,'' describes the exhibition as ``a trip from imperial
Russia across Siberia to the New World, and back for the coronation
of Alexander II in 1855.'' This unusual and sumptuous display
combines objects from the imperial courts, including paintings,
costumes, jewelry and furniture, with those of the world of
Siberian merchants and voyages to the New World. An important
segment of cultural history incorporating the role of the Orthodox
Church is being shown in the United States for the first time, Ms.
Swezey said.
</P>
<P>
   A Restored Rotunda
</P>
<P>
   While the museum is in a 1960s building, the State House is the
second oldest state capitol in continuous use. Completed in 1792,
four years behind the one in Annapolis, Md., there were several
additions and demolitions due to fire over the years. The present
north wing and rotunda, reflecting the French style of the Italian
Renaissance, was built in 1889 and is the work of a Jersey City
architect, Lewis Broome. Recently regilded with Florentine gold
leaf, the dome, which symbolizes representative government in the
United States, has once again become a gleaming beacon over the
city.
</P>
<P>
   Under the dome, the 105-foot-high, three-tiered rotunda has also
been restored. Completed this summer, it equals the War Memorial's
in its richness of decor, as Mosca was on board again to discover
the original paint pigments. Venetian-red walls and a salmon
ceiling from the 1895 period once again offset the marble
wainscoting trimmed in bronze and the gleaming balcony railings
supported by cast-iron brackets in the form of fire-breathing
dragons. On walls between stained-glass windows hang the portraits
of New Jersey's governors, beginning with its first, William
Livingston. It is a dignified and exhilarating space.
</P>
<P>
   Historic Barracks
</P>
<P>
   Around the corner, going back even earlier to the Colonial
period, is the Old Barracks. It has also seen many transitions
since it first quartered British soldiers in 1758, when the local
residents no longer wished to house them. When it was built, it was
the largest building in Trenton. It probably housed Tory
sympathizers and Hessian military scouts before Gen. George
Washington routed them out in the Battle of Trenton, the day after
Christmas in 1776.
</P>
<P>
   For many years in this century the Old Barracks was a museum of
Colonial curios. Since 1985, archaeologists, architects and
historians have put the fieldstone building back into its original
configuration, trimmed with cantilevered wooden balconies and
staircases. The Georgian-style officers' house at one end shows
clearly that the upper ranks lived in more genteel conditions than
the soldiers, who slept four to a two-tiered bunk in the barracks.
The parade ground in front reinforces the military air.
</P>
<P>
   But the man who truly set a stylish tone for the early township
was William Trent. His brick house built in 1719, the oldest
surviving dwelling in Trenton, is surrounded by a little park and
once again has a view of the river now that the surrounding streets
have been cleared away during urban renewal. A merchant and ship
owner from Scotland who was a partner with William Penn in
Philadelphia, Trent settled at his country estate on 800 acres
along the Delaware in New Jersey and became the state's chief
justice.
</P>
<P>
   The house, mostly intact from the period and furnished with
paneling and William andurniture described in a 1726
inventory taken two years after his death, resembles on a smaller
scale a fine Baroque mansion in England. It not only demonstrates
that early Colonial leaders were in touch with current English
taste, but also represents the high standard that Trent set for
Trenton.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being the state capital, Trenton gained
prominence as an industrial town in the 19th century from the
production of Roebling wire cable for suspension bridges and from
the manufacture of ceramics and fine china. And with this
prominence came a motto emblazoned across one of the bridges over
the Delaware River that can be seen from trains running between
Philadelphia and New York. Now, as the city makes a comeback with
its reputation for cultural life, the motto still applies:
``Trenton Makes, the World Takes.''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS IN 3rd TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   TRAVELS IN TRENTON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By PAULA DEITZ
</P>
<P>
   Trenton is about 53 miles south of New York City. The Trenton
Convention and Visitors Bureau is on Lafayette Street at Barrack
Street, (609) 777-1770. Here is a sampling of attractions, along
with travel information:
</P>
<P>
   Attractions
</P>
<P>
   TRENTON WAR MEMORIAL THEATER, West Lafayette Street at Barrack
Street. General box office: (609) 984-8400. Boheme Opera NJ: ``Sang
Sista' Sang,'' a musical tribute to the singers Bessie Smith,
Billie Holliday, Dinah Washington, Dorothy Dandridge, Josephine
Baker and Mahalia Jackson, featuring an ensemble of six singers,
Oct. 26-28; tickets, $18.50 to $25. ``L'Elisir d'Amore'' by
Donizetti with Lorraine Ernest, soprano; Barton Green, tenor; David
Arnold, baritone; William Walker, bass-baritone. Performances on
Nov. 5 at 8 p.m. (precurtain talk at 7 p.m.) and Nov. 7 at 3 p.m.
(precurtain talk at 1:45 p.m.) Opera box office: (609) 581-7200.
Tickets: $20 to $50. The New Jersey Symphony Orchestra: Dvorak's
``Requiem,'' conducted by Zdenek Macal, with the Westminster
Symphonic Choir; Oksana Krovytska, soprano; John Aler, tenor; Wendy
Hoffman, mezzo; Gutav Belacek, bass. Tomorrow, 8 p.m. Tickets: $15
to $58. All-Haydn program. Conductor and violinist: Pinchas
Zukerman; Dec. 10, 8 p.m. Tickets: $14 to $46. Symphony box office:
(800) 255-3476. Tickets: $10 to $58.
</P>
<P>
   NEW JERSEY STATE MUSEUM, 205 W. State St., (609) 984-5687.
``Unseen Treasures: Imperial Russia and the New World,'' whose
opening this weekend was postponed because of shipping delays in
Russia, is now expected to open in November and run through Jan.
16. Hours: Tuesdays through Saturdays, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.; Sundays,
11 a.m. to 6 p.m. Admission to the museum is free. Special
admission for ``Unseen Treasures,'' $10; $8.50, students, the
elderly and groups of 10 or more; $6, children under 12. Free
parking in the Capitol Complex parking garage.
</P>
<P>
   NEW JERSEY STATE HOUSE, 125 W. State St., (609) 633-2709. Tour
includes newly renovated rotunda, Senate and General Assembly
chambers, Senate Majority Conference Room and Governor's Reception
Room: hourly on Tuesdays, Wednesdays and Fridays, 10 a.m. to 3
p.m., and on Saturdays, noon to 3 p.m. Free.
</P>
<P>
   OLD BARRACKS MUSEUM, Barrack Street, (609) 396-1776. Hours:
Daily, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Closed Thanksgiving, Dec. 24 and 25, Jan.
1 and Easter. Admission: $6; $3, children six to 18, students and
the elderly; under 5, free. A re-enactment of the first and second
Battles of Trenton, on Jan. 2, 11 a.m. to noon and 1 to 3 p.m.
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   WILLIAM TRENT HOUSE, 15 Market St., (609) 989-3027. Hours:
Daily, 12:30 p.m. to 4 p.m. Admission: $2.50; $2, students and the
elderly; $1, children under 12. A Fall Family Festival will be held
Saturday from noon to 5 p.m.; $1 admission includes a tour.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   PETE LORENZO'S CAFE, 66 S. Clinton Ave., (609) 695-6868. Across
from the railroad station. Long frequented by local politicians and
business people. Italian food, steaks, chops, lobster and other
seafood. Hours: Mondays through Fridays, 11:30 a.m. to 11 p.m.;
Saturdays, 5 to 11 p.m. Lunch, $7 to $34; dinner, $12 to $40.
</P>
<P>
   MAXINE'S, 120 S. Warren St., (609) 392-0022. A block from the
War Memorial Theater. International food. Hours: Mondays through
Thursdays, 11:30 a.m. to 2:30 p.m. and 5:30 P.M to 10 p.m.;
Fridays, 11:30 a.m. to 2.30 p.m. and 5:30 p.m. to midnight;
Saturdays, noon to 3 p.m. and 5:30 p.m. to midnight; Sundays,
brunch from 11:30 a.m. to 3:30 p.m.; dinner, 5 to 9 p.m.; Lunch, $7
to $9; dinner, $15 to $25; Sunday brunch, $15.
</P>
<P>
   CAFE OLE!, 126 S. Warren St., (609) 396-2233. A family
restaurant near the War Memorial Theater that also provides the
theater's food concession. Mondays through Fridays, breakfast and
lunch only, 7 a.m. to 4 p.m. Breakfast, $2 to $4; lunch, $1.50 to
$6.
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUM CAFE, New Jersey State Museum, 205 W. State St., (609)
292-6464. Hours: Tuesdays through Saturdays, 9 a.m. to 4 p.m.;
Sunday, noon to 5 p.m. Assorted sandwiches, salads, soups and baked
goods; $2.50 to $5.50.
</P>
<P>
   MARSILIO'S, 541 Roebling Ave., (609) 695-1916. In the
Chambersburg area, Trenton's Little Italy, a five-minute drive from
the Capitol Complex. Traditional southern Italian restaurant.
Hours: Mondays through Thursdays, 11:30 a.m. to 2 p.m. and 5 to 10
p.m.; Fridays, 11:30 a.m. to 2 p.m. and 5 to 11 p.m.; Saturdays, 5
to 11 p.m. Lunch, $7.49 to $22; dinner, $13 to $24.
</P>
