<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, Oct. 15, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday afternoon, Hurricane Irene, armed with maximum
sustained winds of 75 miles per hour, jogged to the northeast over
the Isle of Youth south of Cuba. Such a jog, if it were to persist,
would put southern Florida at risk. However, steering winds over
the western Caribbean and the eastern Gulf of Mexico will continue
to be weak and capricious Friday, placing uncertainty on the timing
and eventual path of Irene.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, heavy rains will invade southern and central parts
of the Florida peninsula as tropical moisture streams northeastward
into the region. Rains may be enhanced by additional moisture
carried inland by winds off the Atlantic circulating around a broad
expanse of high pressure over the Eastern seaboard. Rainfalls in
excess of two inches or more will douse some areas. Street and
flash flooding will occur in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, another southward surge of chilly Canadian air will
follow on the heels of a cold front across the upper Middle West.
Showers will be limited along and ahead of the cold front over the
upper Mississippi Valley, given the slow return of moisture from
the south. However, splotches of chilly rain will develop behind
the front across the northern Plains. Father west, snow will fall
on high ground in parts of Wyoming and Montana as moist cold, winds
from the east glide up the sloping terrain.
</P>
<P>
   The Northeast will be very chilly to start, but the afternoon
will be milder. Saturday will be warmer, with afternoon
temperatures cresting near or slightly above seasonal levels.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Restricted Air Force &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thursday morning, the Hurricane Hunter Aircraft was unable to
determine the precise center of Hurricane Irene because Air Force
regulations prevent any flight near the coast of Cuba. As a matter
of policy, reconnaissance aircraft do not fly into tropical systems
over land. Turbulence in thunderstorms around the centers of
tropical storms and hurricanes often is more intense over land.
Winds blowing over island mountains also generate turbulence.
Moreover, reconnaissance aircraft do not fly over land so as not to
jeopardize people on the ground in the event of a crash landing. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
