<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-ART </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANNING   BOSTON STYLE,   CIRCA 1720 
</HEADLINE>
 - NYT  
 (ATTN: Mass., Vt., Calif., Del.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the colonists of Boston in the 1700s, the height
of high style was japanning, a Western technique invented in the
17th century to imitate ancient Oriental lacquer.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most dazzling examples of American japanning is a
William and Mary high chest that Sotheby's is selling Friday. Made
in Boston between 1712 and 1725, the black chest, Lot 107, sits on
a tablelike base fitted with drawers.
</P>
<P>
   The base has turned baluster legs and curved stretchers. The
tapered conical legs and bun feet are characteristic of the William
and Mary style, named for the English monarchs of the late 17th
century.
</P>
<P>
   While the chest has painted birds and flowers on its legs and
sides, what makes it remarkable is the silver and gold chinoiserie
decoration on the drawer fronts. Borrowing from Chinese porcelains
and silks, the japanners employed such Oriental motifs as Chinese
figures arranging flowers, showing off pet birds, sailing sampans
and flying kites. There are poetical arched bridges, bamboo-garden
pavilions and soaring butterflies. In one charming vignette, a
crouching dog teases a rooster.
</P>
<P>
   The figures are made of gesso, a gypsum composition, that has
been colored with paint pigments and particles of gold, silver,
bronze and copper. The glittering figures have silver faces and
golden gowns accented in vermilion red and royal blue. The black
moldings are sprinkled with golden flecks.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, visitors gravitated to the glamorous high chest the
moment Sotheby's opened its doors for the preview of its American
furniture sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``William and Mary high chests are very scarce,'' said Albert
Sack, the dean of American furniture dealers in New York. ``Boston
seems to have been the only place japanning was so popular.''
</P>
<P>
   Sack sold a similar high chest to the Virginia Museum of Fine
Arts in 1991 for $1.5 million, according to the museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``This piece is rare,'' he said. ``It's a good one. Anyone would
be lucky to have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Trace, a dealer from Cortlandt Manor, N.Y., was
similarly smitten. ``It has a nice verticality,'' he said. ``It has
such a lift to it.'' A friend, Paige Inslee, added, ``All the
decoration is there, and the colors are still vibrant.''
</P>
<P>
   Other visitors pulled out the drawers and looked inside with
flashlights. The backs of some drawers are signed ``Park,'' the
name of the cabinetmaker.
</P>
<P>
   While the piece has pleasing proportions and elegant decoration,
it is important for other reasons as well. It has been handed down
through the family of President John Adams. In 1788, before he
became president, John Adams apparently owned two japanned Boston
high chests.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's has not learned how or when Adams obtained them, but
he would have been familiar with japanned furniture from his years
of diplomatic service in France and Britain in the 1770s and '80s,
when it was in fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's reports that Adams' wife, Abigail, was close to her
sister, Mary Smith Cranch, and it is thought that the Adamses gave
the chest to Mary Cranch to thank her for looking after their home
when the Adamses were abroad. Both families lived in Quincy, Mass.,
and Mary's husband, Richard, was a financial backer of the future
president. It is Mary Cranch's California descendants who are now
selling the chest.
</P>
<P>
   That the chest has remained in one family for 200 years probably
accounts for its excellent condition. ``It is remarkably
untouched,'' said Deborah Anne Federhen, a furniture scholar based
in Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Federhen, a former curator at the Winterthur museum, pointed
out that although the chest does not have its original drawer
pulls, it does have its original imported escutcheons, the
expensive, shield-shaped brass plates that protect the keyholes.
</P>
<P>
   The chest was actually made during the reign of Queen Anne; it
took years for new British furniture styles to reach the American
colonies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston was the closest port to London, and Boston set the pace
for style in the first half of the 18th century,'' Leslie Keno,
director of American furniture at Sotheby's, said. ``The chest is
one of the earliest examples of the William and Mary style in the
Colonies. It would have been one of the most elaborate and
costliest things you could have bought. It would have been
cutting-edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Keno said that the chest, which is made of pine and maple
instead of oak, was much lighter than most Pilgrim furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Federhen said that there are only six known examples of
William and Mary flat-top japanned high chests made in Boston. Five
are in museums, including the Metropolitan Museum of Art, Historic
Deerfield, Winterthur, the Virginia Museum of Fine Arts and the
Adams house in Quincy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sotheby's chest is the only one I know in private hands,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Japanning should not be confused with ebonizing, which is
staining wood black to look like ebony or lacquer.
</P>
<P>
   As Judith Miller spelled out in the 1999 Antiques Encyclopedia,
lacquering is a technique used on furniture produced in the East,
whereas japanning refers to the attempt to copy that technique in
the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one in the West could make lacquer,'' Ms. Federhen said.
``It is formed from the sap of a tree that doesn't grow in Europe
or North America.''
</P>
<P>
   She explained that japanners painted furniture ``lamp black,''
then decorated it with gesso. The powdered pigments and metals were
laid on the wet black paint or glued to the gesso figures. The
pieces are vulnerable to changes in temperature.
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. Federhen put it, ``Gesso is an immovable material, which
is then put on wood, which is always moving.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the chest was made specifically to be japanned,'' she
said, ``because the drawer fronts are American maple, a
hard-grained wood that is more stable and less porous than pine,
the wood used on the sides and top.''
</P>
<P>
   The estimate, $700,000 to $900,000, is based on condition,
rarity, provenance and its being American.
</P>
<P>
   Less patriotic browsers might consider a rare and equally
show-stopping pair of 17th-century William and Mary japanned
writing tables from London that will be in Sotheby's English
furniture sale next Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The estimate for the pair is $40,000 to $60,000.
</P>
<P>
   Regency Silver Gilt
</P>
<P>
   Silver enthusiasts should note that Alan and Simon Hartman,
private dealers in New York, are selling their private collection
of exceptional Regency silver-gilt candelabra, chargers, salt
cellars and wine coolers at Christie's on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The 210 lots, which go on view Friday, include examples from the
workshops of Paul Storr, Digby Scott and Benjamin Smith II, and
Robert Garrard II, most of them made during the Regency
(1811-1820).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
