<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN A BELOVED BLANKET MEANS MORE THAN SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE ADVENTURES OF ELMO IN GROUCHLAND &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vanessa Williams, Mandy Patinkin; voices of Kevin Clash, Carroll
Spinney, Martin P. Robinson, Frank Oz, Fran Brill, Steve Whitmire &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Gary Halvorson &QL;
</P>
<P>
   G 90 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like Linus of ``Peanuts,'' Elmo of ``Sesame Street'' is grafted
to his blanket, which one day gets away from him and goes down a
pipe into Oscar's home territory in Grouchland. Sliding after it,
Elmo finds himself amid a mob of assorted grouches (not bad folks
actually) and a world of gleeful dirtiness.
</P>
<P>
   From there the blanket has proceeded into the hands of Huxley (
Patinkin) of Huxley Castle, a kind of Bela Lugosi of consumerism
who prances about a lair full of possessions, many of them other
people's, that he wouldn't surrender or share with others on pain
of death.
</P>
<P>
   Huxley is evil. Take a weed whacker to those eyebrows, someone
suggests. ``All I see I give to me,'' he sings with relish.
</P>
<P>
   Relieving him of the blanket seems impossible, but Elmo is
encouraged by the vampy Queen of Trash (Ms. Williams), who
teasingly tests his mettle by making him perform 100 raspberries in
30 seconds. Thus armed with a new can-do attitude, he marches on
Huxley. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-7 Amazingly small moviegoers are having an uproariously
good time at this film, which is fine because there are no pitfalls
whatever. This is a completely sweet little tale with familiar,
unfailingly cheerful and resilient characters extolling such
virtues as sharing and being nice to people. (Don't worry about
Huxley.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THREE KINGS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   George Clooney, Mark Wahlberg, Ice Cube, Spike Jonze, Nora Dunn &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by David O. Russell &QL;
</P>
<P>
   R 105 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Conditions are bizarre immediately after Operation Desert Storm
in Iraq. ``Are we shooting people or not?'' an American soldier
asks. Iraqi troops have turned their attention to rounding up
dissidents and terrorizing their own population, virtually ignoring
the invaders.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the sands in vast reinforced bunkers lie fleets of
luxury automobiles and oceans of other goods plundered from Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing around terms like ``clear moral imperative'' and
invoking ``orders from President Bush,'' three American musketeers
and their little D'Artagnan, a slightly crazed and appealing Texan
named Conrad ( Jonze), commandeer a Humvee and jump into the local
Iraqi political imbroglio in an effort to steal gold bars worth $23
million stashed amid the other swag in the subterranean maze.
</P>
<P>
   At first two of them, Sgt. Troy Barlow ( Wahlberg), a new
father, and Staff Sgt. Chief (Ice Cube), a reservist on a
``four-month paid vacation from Detroit,'' are reluctant. Perhaps
they prefer their day jobs, says their fast-talking leader, the
special forces officer Archie Gates ( Clooney).
</P>
<P>
   An airport baggage handler by trade, Chief knows that 200 pounds
of gold will tear the bottom out of an ordinary suitcase. Efforts
to remove the bars get increasingly complicated as do the
Americans' relations with the Iraqi rebels living directly above
the loot.
</P>
<P>
   Offered an opportunity to help these people escape Saddam
Hussein, Gates and the others find themselves acting on their own
moral imperatives. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE Graphic and extreme. At one point a man's head is blown
off in startling detail; at others, wounds are examined
anatomically to demonstrate what bullets do to internal organs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX Gates has rambunctious sex with a television reporter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Much. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 11 Many children will be attracted to a big action
film, but considering the nature of the violence, it's not the best
idea. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 12-14 Russell's film makes an interesting case since it has
all the action elements _ stars, explosions, wisecracking repartee
_ but also an innovative look and an unusually fey style to project
a sharp and strong point of view about the events it depicts.
</P>
<P>
   For these reasons, the gore may seem unreasonable, but it may
make it harder to rule the film out on those grounds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 15 AND UP They'll go if they want to, of course, and as
action films go, there are far worse. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DRIVE ME CRAZY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Joan Hart, Adrian Grenier, Mark Webber, Gabriel
Carpenter, Ali Lartner &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by John Schultz &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 93 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to another high school movie, where the romantic
maneuvers more or less jibe with those in the last high school
movie. Nicole (Ms. Hart, star of the television series ``Sabrina,
the Teen-Age Witch'') and Chase ( Grenier) are next-door neighbors
who used to be pals until about junior high school, when she turned
scrubbed achiever and he began riding around in supermarket
shopping carts and calling pep rallies fascist.
</P>
<P>
   Now she's the head of the centennial dance committee and is
angling for a date with a basketball star named Brad. Chase stands
up for animal rights, hangs out in scuzzy clubs and holds steamy
trysts with Dulcie (Ms. Lartner) in vacant classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   But Nicole and Chase are bright and mature for their ilk and,
with liaisons in their own circles falling short of expectations,
it's not long before they decide to give each other a whirl.
</P>
<P>
   That calls for a makeover on Chase's part. ``You can't wear
anything you own,'' Nicole tells him. Escorted through the Gap, he
emerges looking the part of high school star, and with a fluid line
of patter he's soon working the upper social reaches.
</P>
<P>
   It should not be altogether surprising, however, that there are
many second thoughts by both parties, which, along with treacheries
by jealous so-called friends, prolong total surrender to the
relationship until the final fade-out. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX There is some teen-age necking and groping, but outright sex
is implied rather than performed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Just enough to avoid a G rating, which would turn off
teen-agers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-9 Pretty much a dud with the youngest viewers, who
wouldn't be all that interested. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 10-11 Parents should be aware that sexual activity lurks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 12 AND UP They're the audience, and there really are no
problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
