u e BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT     10-14 0220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBUM-OF-THE-WEEK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPOTLIGHTING A NEW ALBUM 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By JON PARELES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STEREOLAB: ``Cobra and Phases Group Play Voltage in the Milky
Night'' (Elektra).
</P>
<P>
   Stereolab has built its music on unexpected affinities: Steve
Reich's Minimalism and 1960s French ye-ye pop, serene female voices
and goofy analog synthesizer sounds, lounge exotica and art-rock,
funk drumbeats and odd-meter 1950s jazz, dialectical musings and
nonsense syllables.
</P>
<P>
   All of it resolves, sooner or later, into patterns that are both
insouciant and orderly, creating a bustling stasis with a clarity
that's reassuring. ``Out of chaos a creation binding into one
form,'' a new song explains.
</P>
<P>
   On its 11th album, Stereolab throws still more sources into its
mesh. Perking up after its last album, the languid ``Dots and
Loops,'' Stereolab starts the album with a swing beat out of Gene
Krupa and what sounds like a big band cracking up before the voices
arrive.
</P>
<P>
   Other songs gaze toward the gently undulating ballads of Brian
Wilson, placing brass and string sections alongside the
synthesizers while trading his expansive melodies for ones that
circle back on themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Stereolab's sound world is still a meticulous refuge from
disorder, but it keeps letting in new possibilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
