<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-MAYOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERVISOR DECLARES WRITE-IN CANDIDACY FOR MAYOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Board of Supervisors President Tom Ammiano
announced he is running for mayor as a write-in candidate, a move
that livens up the campaign and raises the question how, or even
if, his candidacy will affect the outcome of the race.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano is the most liberal elected leader in San Francisco,
with strong ties to the gay community, tenant activists and labor
unions.
</P>
<P>
   He decided in early August not to run. On Wednesday he changed
his mind after what he described as a strong push from supporters
to jump into the race.
</P>
<P>
   A recent San Francisco Examiner poll showed that the three
leading candidates in the race _ Mayor Willie Brown, former Mayor
Frank Jordan and former political consultant Clint Reilly _ all
have higher unfavorable ratings than favorable ones and may be
vulnerable to a high-profile challenger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to run for mayor for two reasons,'' Ammiano said
in explaining his initial decision to stay out. ``I didn't relish
entering a race that promised to become truly negative, and I was
concerned about having enough time, as of August, to raise the
money to compete against extremely well-financed opponents.''
</P>
<P>
   He reconsidered because ``the tone of the campaign and the
record-setting spending to date have surpassed my worst
expectations,'' he said. ``The result is a strong feeling of
disaffection among voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano believes that voters are hungry for an alternative.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Reilly, Jordan and Brown, 11 others, considered
dark-horse contenders, are on the ballot for the Nov. 2 election.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano has to settle for being a write-in candidate because the
deadline to get his name on the ballot passed two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   However, city rules require that he has to officially declare he
is a candidate if his votes are to be counted.
</P>
<P>
   He said he does not plan to actively campaign or raise money
``at this time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 1734EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7013 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-AIRDELAYS15-COX     10-14 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRDELAYS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EFFORTS TO IMPROVE AIR TRAFFIC CONTROL SYSTEMS BLAMED FOR DALAYS
 &HT;    Moving in Washington and Financial categories
 &HT;    BY SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington _ Necessary updates in air traffic control systems
may have played a role in delaying airline passengers earlier this
year, FAA Administrator Jane Garvey told federal lawmakers on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Airline delays reached record highs during the summer. The FAA
reports that delays in April alone were up 51 percent from 1998. In
July, the FAA estimates that on average more than 100,000
passengers were delayed every day, and that an average delay was
nearly 45 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Garvey told the House subcommittee on aviation that some of the
delays were caused by improvements made to the federal government's
air traffic control system designed to better display air traffic
information at control centers throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FAA is willing to do whatever is within our power to
improve the efficiency of the air traffic system, so long as safety
is not compromised,'' Garvey said.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA's technological improvements were not the only culprit
in the recent delays, Garvey said. She added that bad weather, as
well as airports and airlines, should share responsibility for
delays.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Hallett, president and chief executive officer of the Air
Transport Association of America, disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``These delays are insignificant in comparison with the numerous
instances this summer where aircraft were delayed over six hours by
the FAA and an inadequately managed air traffic control system,''
Hallett told the panel.
</P>
<P>
   Hallett added that the transition to the new equipment this
summer sparked the delays when the FAA slowed the air traffic in
its Cleveland Center airspace to give air traffic controllers time
to learn the new system. Hallett added that these transitions
followed in New York and Chicago, creating more delays.
</P>
<P>
   Also, in a report released by the Air Transport Association on
Thursday, the FAA's systems of weather management was also blamed
for contributing to the delays. According to the report, the FAA
restricted many flights because of early weather forecasts, then
delayed the flights even when bad weather didn't follow.
</P>
<P>
   The report called for an ``immediate and extensive'' overhaul of
the FAA air traffic control system and warned that unless the air
traffic control system was fixed, passengers could expect to see an
increasing rise in the number of delays.
</P>
<P>
   In early July, the FAA met representatives from the Air
Transport Association and the National Air Traffic Controllers
Association to evaluate 33 of the FAA's air traffic control
facilities and its command center in Herndon, Va. As a result the
FAA introduced several reforms aimed at reducing the number of air
traffic delays.
</P>
<P>
   Garvey said that the federal government's air traffic control
command center will now have a greater role in air traffic
management. Garvey added that the FAA is also currently working on
updating aging equipment to combat delays and develop more
efficient air traffic routes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
