u k BC-EDIT-NUKE15-COX     10-14 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NUKE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Politics imperils security
 &HT;    (EDs: This is an editorial from Friday's Atlanta Constitution.)
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Clintonphobes in the U.S. Senate couldn't bring down
the president by convicting him on impeachment charges, so they
decided to pursue the next most satisfying course _ to humiliate
him.
</P>
<P>
   What better way to do that than to defeat him on a treaty he had
signed with great fanfare and promised the world he could deliver
with Senate ratification?
</P>
<P>
   Never mind his GOP opponents' protestations that the nuclear
test-ban treaty would have played fast and loose with U.S.
security. The opposite is true. Once the treaty went into effect,
with all nuclear powers signed on, it would have reinforced
America's vast strategic superiority.
</P>
<P>
   To those who worried the U.S. nuclear arsenal might degrade
without any testing to assure its warheads were in working order,
the fact is America is much better equipped to check its weapons
stockpile _ by computer modeling _ than any potential foe. No other
power in the world would be able to match the reliability of our
deterrent.
</P>
<P>
   Those who sounded alarms about secret underground nuclear tests
by hostile nations had an even weaker leg to stand on. True, the
CIA says it can't tell a 1-kiloton blast or less from a seismic
event, but military analysts consider tests that small to be
strategically unimportant.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the treaty provided for the establishment of a
comprehensive worldwide network of seismic and other sensors that
would have greatly enhanced U.S. ability to detect cheaters.
</P>
<P>
   By their near-perfect party-line vote, Senate Republicans
stripped the U.S. government of any moral authority it might have
had to pressure India and Pakistan not to resume nuclear testing.
It was almost as if this week's Pakistan coup by a military high
command of murky motives went totally unnoticed by Trent Lott &AMP; Co.
An oversight like that is really playing fast and loose with U.S.
security.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if Majority Leader Lott and his cohorts in the GOP's
isolationist wing had to vote on the treaty this week. They could
have put it off, as Clinton requested. But, no, they demanded that
he pledge not to bring the treaty up for a vote, under any
circumstance, during the balance of his term _ an unconditional
surrender that would have weakened the presidency. Correctly, he
refused, and GOP senators played out their game of political
chicken to its illogical end.
</P>
<P>
   The treaty may look moribund, but it is not dead. Technically,
it goes back to the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, from where
it can be recalled for another vote, but certainly not in this
GOP-led Congress. Democrats are right to vow that the treaty,
supported by a large majority of Americans in national surveys,
will be a major issue in next year's election campaign and a
priority for them should they regain control of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Time was when Republicans and Democrats gave lip-service to the
ideal that politics stopped at the water's edge, that they strived
for consensus on foreign policy. It never was quite true, but at
least they tried. Democrats ought to mark well the record of this
deeply partisan congressional leadership _ its attempts to confound
Clinton at every nearly every turn on foreign policy _ and swear
not to behave as the GOP has the next time a Republican is elected
president.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 1741EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
