A7019 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EDIT-RAMSEY15-COX     10-14 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-RAMSEY15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grand jury did the best it could
 &HT;    (EDs: This is an editorial from Friday's Atlanta Constitution.)
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Justice may not have triumphed in the JonBenet Ramsey
case, but neither did it err. Despite political and public pressure
to solve this brutal 3-year-old crime, the eight-woman, four-man
grand jury found the evidence insufficient to indict anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Over 13 months, the grand jurors weighed the facts and ignored
the emotions. In the end, they exited their deliberations
empty-handed and a killer went unpunished. For the millions of
people who felt passionate about this tragedy, that's a distressing
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   But citizens ought to be equally passionate about protecting
against injustice. When reasonable doubt exists, it remains the far
better course for the guilty to go free than for the innocent to be
wrongly punished.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Constitution understood the gravity of wrongly
convicting someone, which is why its authors built in protections
for defendants. The nation's high courts have followed suit,
setting standards of evidence to safeguard against unsubstantiated
prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   The Ramsey case suffered from too much speculation and too
little hard evidence. The unexplained DNA and unidentified
footprints never pointed directly at a suspect, and the
circumstantial evidence was so vague that two lead investigators
came up with opposite conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury should not be criticized for its performance. It
did its job well under uncommon strain. The same can't be said of
Boulder authorities. Police bungled the crime scene by allowing
family and friends to run amok on the day of the murder.
</P>
<P>
   As the investigation dragged on, petty squabbling broke out
between police and prosecutors. The chief police investigator
resigned after accusing the district attorney of mishandling the
case and trying to protect JonBenet's parents.
</P>
<P>
   No one can declare that JonBenet's killer got what he or she
deserved. Nevertheless, justice was not trampled in this case, and
sometimes that's the best an imperfect system can do.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 1741EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7020 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-LATINO-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      10-14 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LATINO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: FROM THE POLITICAL TO THE PERSONAL: A PAN-AMERICAN
FEAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The recent blast of popular enthusiasm for Latino
music and culture has yet to find serious resonance in the
mainstream New York art world. People of Hispanic descent now make
up nearly 30 percent of the city's population, but most of its
high-profile museums seem to have slept through that development,
and only a handful of galleries regularly show Latino artists.
</P>
<P>
   This situation automatically makes El Museo del Barrio an
indispensable public resource. But the museum goes way beyond just
meeting the demands of a statistic. Now in its 30th year, it
consistently offers exhibitions of contemporary and historical art
as stimulating to look at as to think about, by artists who live
hundreds of miles away or just a few blocks east of the museum
itself.
</P>
<P>
   El Museo was established in 1969 in an East Harlem storefront by
artists, teachers and political activists (the categories often
overlapped) as a cultural center for the local Puerto Rican
community.
</P>
<P>
   It has since moved to grander headquarters on Fifth Avenue and
has _ controversially for those who feel it should focus on its
original constituency _ embraced Latino art as a Pan-American
phenomenon, in line with shifts in the city's population.
</P>
<P>
   `Pressing the Point'
</P>
<P>
   This broader perspective is evident in the four exhibitions,
large and small, which fill every inch of floor space for the
museum's 30th birthday fete this fall. But the emphasis falls
squarely on the activist impulses that first brought this and many
other ``alternative spaces'' into being.
</P>
<P>
   Unsurprisingly, the two main shows are devoted to prints.
Inexpensive to produce and distribute, available (ideally) to rich
and poor alike, and suited to combining didactic content with
graphic innovation, they have long been the polemical medium par
excellence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pressing the Point: Parallel Expressions in the Graphic Arts
of the Chicano and Puerto Rican Movements'' brings together dozens
of works produced more or less simultaneously on the East and West
coasts in the agitated 1960s and '70s as various liberation and
protests movements were moving into high gear.
</P>
<P>
   Organized by Yasmin Ramirez and Henry Estrada, and selected from
the holdings of El Museo and from the Gilberto Cardenas collection
of Latino art at the Jack S. Blanton Museum of Art at the
University of Texas at Austin, the show is given historical
grounding with the presence of some older figures, beginning with
the seminal Mexican printmaker Jose Guadalupe Posada (1852-1913).
</P>
<P>
   His sardonic riffs on sensationalist news items and popular
religion had a big impact on the art of the Mexican Revolution. And
the cooperative production mode favored by that movement set a
model for future collectives, among them the Taller de Grafica
Popular in Mexico City in the 1930s and '40s (several of its
members, including Luis Arenal, Pablo O'Higgins and Leopoldo
Mendez, are in the show) and workshops in Puerto Rico led by, among
others, Lorenzo Homar, Antonio Maldonado, Rafael Rivera Rosa and
Rafael Tufino (who was born in New York and now lives in Puerto
Rico).
</P>
<P>
   These artists made themselves felt in North America. Tufino,
whose Social Realist linocuts were inspired by Mexican art, was
part of the community that founded El Museo del Barrio. And
Chicago-based Carlos A. Cortez Koyokuikatl served as a hard-hitting
role model for Chicano, or Mexican-American, artists largely
concentrated in California.
</P>
<P>
   The story grows ever more complicated in the 1960s and '70s, or
at least that's the way it feels in the show's sometimes
hard-to-follow arrangement, as political action intensified.
Workshops across the country turned out posters, flyers,
newsletters and journals in response to causes like the Vietnam
War, Puerto Rican independence and the farmworkers' strikes.
</P>
<P>
   La Raza Graphic Center was formed in San Francisco in 1971 (one
of its co-founders, Linda Lucero, is in the show). And Self-Help
Graphics started in Los Angeles in 1972 with such outstanding
participants as Yreina D. Cervantez (represented by some fabulous
work here), Gronk, Daniel J. Martinez and Patssi Valdez.
</P>
<P>
   Among the snazziest images were those turned out by Ricardo
Favela and the collective called the Royal Chicano Air Force,
including a witty, Pop-colored silk-screen poster titled
``Strike!'' in which three guys in guerrilla gear pose outside a
boycotted Safeway supermarket. And individual artists came through
with some great things. Ester Hernandez's ``Sun Mad Raisins,'' with
its skeletal grape picker, and Yolanda M. Lopez's Aztec warrior
holding immigration papers and demanding ``Who's the illegal alien,
Pilgrim?'' are agitprop classics.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, meanwhile, the Taller Boricua, or Puerto Rican
Workshop, was founded in 1969 in East Harlem by members of the Art
Workers Coalition who were trying to crack the color-and-ethnicity
barrier at New York museums and bring art into the community. Pop
Art, indigenous culture and Social Realism came together in their
work.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Warhol lies behind a cool, beautiful silk-screen portrait
of the poet Julia de Burgos by Fernando Salicrup and one of Lolita
Lebron, an icon of Puerto Rican independence, by Marcos Dimas. (
Dimas and Salicrup are the current directors of Taller Boricua,
which is still flourishing in East Harlem.) Symbols associated with
the Taino, the original inhabitants of the Caribbean, crop up in
work by Sandra Maria Estevez, Gilberto Hernandez and Nitza Tufino,
the daughter of Rafael Tufino.
</P>
<P>
   Tufino's expressive linocut style was carried forward by Antonio
Martorell, who divides his time between Puerto Rico and New York.
Martorell's superb prints, bold and delicate, often combine figures
and texts on a monumental scale, as is evident in his two-room
installation on view (only through Saturday, unfortunately) at the
Taller Boricua Gallery, a quick walk east from the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Sanchez
</P>
<P>
   ``Pressing the Point'' confirms that Puerto Rican and Chicano
artists have produced one of the major bodies of American printwork
in the postwar years. And many of its key themes and sentiments are
distilled in the museum's other large fall show, ``Juan Sanchez:
Printed Convictions,'' a survey of prints by Sanchez organized by
Alejandro Anreus, curator of the Jersey City Museum, with Julia P.
Herzberg.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez, best known as a painter, was born in 1954 in Brooklyn
of Puerto Rican parents. He is a political artist to the core, and
in his hands activism assumes distinctly religious overtones. In
fact, the complex, multilayered vision of Puerto Rico embodied in
his prints amounts to a kind of sacred history, populated by
saints, living and dead.
</P>
<P>
   In a tribute to the nationalist hero Pedro Albizu Campos
(1891-1965), Sanchez alternates photographs of the man, elderly,
just out of prison and slumped in a wheelchair, with a popular
print of Jesus crowned with thorns. In a 1990 monotype, he presents
snapshot images of his mother and aunt in a diptych-shaped monotype
resembling a portable altarpiece.
</P>
<P>
   And in one of his largest pieces, he enshrined a photograph of
his daughter, dressed for her First Communion, in a mixed-media
print shaped like an arched church window. Here, along with
Christian symbols, the girl is surrounded by spiral-shaped Taino
emblems emphasizing the other, recessive culture that is part of
her spiritual heritage. As in so much of Sanchez's art, the
political, the social and the personal are inseparable and deeply
felt.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Santos and `Transboricua'
</P>
<P>
   The spiritual cast to his prints finds a counterpart in ``Puerto
Rican Santos de Palo: Sculptures Between Heaven and Earth,'' a
selection from the museum's splendid collection of santos, or
wooden saints and madonnas, many of them carved by self-taught
rural artists for home altars. Accompanying the display, organized
by Fatima Bercht, are photographs by Hector Mendez Caratini
documenting Puerto Rican religious practices.
</P>
<P>
   And Sanchez's commitment to the ideal of community is shared by
the artist Pepon Osorio, represented here by his remarkable
installation ``Transboricua,'' which made its debut last summer
under the museum's auspices in a children's department store in the
barrio. An iconic and atmospheric assemblage, it addresses the
changing complexion of a neighborhood in which various Latino
populations now mix, with Mexicans among the most recent arrivals.
</P>
<P>
   `Viva la Muerte'
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Mexican culture is honored in ``Viva la Muerte,'' a
small sampling of contemporary work inspired by the festival known
as the Day of the Dead. An exuberant blend of Christian and
Mesoamerican traditions, the holiday, which falls on Nov. 1 and 2,
is widely celebrated in Mexico itself and was adopted as an emblem
of cultural identity by the Chicano movement.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the work in the show, organized by Deborah Lawrence and
Eduardo Pineda of the San Franciscan Museum of Modern Art and
Miriam de Uriarte of El Museo, is slight, but it includes a fine
Posada-esque drawing of grinning skeletons by Enrique Chagoya,
hallucinatory computer-generated images by Rupert Garcia and a
flavorful installation by Raul E. Aquilar.
</P>
<P>
   A full-size Day of the Dead altar will be built at the museum on
Oct. 31, and the public is invited to join in by contributing small
offerings. The result last fall was a fantastic array of religious
images, toys, food, candles, marzipan skulls, flowers, personal
mementos and photos of family and friends. The whole idea of this
bountiful, ceremonial gesture, honoring vital spirits past and
those still to come, seems very much in the spirit of El Museo del
Barrio itself in its anniversary year.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 1741EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
