<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0238 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7023 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-BILINGUAL-BABIES15-CO     10-14 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILINGUAL-BABIES15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kidspeak program promotes infant biligual educationBy Dan
Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Hey kids, it's time to play ``Simon dice''!
</P>
<P>
   A game which is even more fun than ``Simon Says'' because, in
the hands of Spanish teacher Estela Flores-Moreno, it's muy loco.
</P>
<P>
   And a good thing it's nutty, too. Because of the dozen
preschoolers sitting in a semicircle around Estela, in the Cross
and Crown Child Care Center in Dunwoody (Ga.), none has yet reached
his or her third birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simon dice: arriba!'' cries Estela, who has the
larger-than-life personality of a standup comedian, jumping up and
throwing her hands over her head. All the kids follow suit,
grinning. They continue to imitate the cherubic, foghorn-voiced
teacher as she shakes her hands (``las manos!''), and collapses on
the floor to simulate sleep (``dormir!'') with a rumbling snore.
Not all the kids repeat the words back _ some of the 2-year-olds
can barely speak, after all _ but they follow and obviously
understand Estela's every move because she herself is no snore.
</P>
<P>
   The class is clearly more fun than work for the tykes _ even
though Estela speaks nothing but Spanish for the full 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the get-'em-young campaign of Kidspeak International.
Based in Atlanta, the 4-year-old program dispatches 20 instructors
of French and Spanish to teach about 900 students in schools and
preschools around metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started this organization because I was impressed by the
scientific evidence that your mind is most flexible before you're
7,'' says Kidspeak president Robert Goldberg. The 39-year-old
ex-Army officer explains, ``There are millions of connections
between brain cells that can only form before age 7. It's a
use-it-or-lose-it situation; at Kidspeak, we use it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a national trend that might be called smarting down, parents
are striving to give their preschoolers, even infants, a structured
educational experience in language, math, arts _ even computers _
for a competitive edge in education and life. Scientific evidence
often, but not always, supports the trend. For instance, the theory
that listening to classical music from the crib could cultivate a
smarter child was recently challenged by new research that claims
it makes no difference.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the studies of infant brain development that Goldberg
referred to, widely publicized in 1997, have lowered the age
threshhold for teaching a second language. The Atlanta-based
Primrose Schools Franchising Company, with 70 schools in seven
states, includes Spanish in its core curiculum for 4- and
5-year-olds. The Language Workshop for Children in New York starts
infants at six months.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every city we go into, there are parents clamoring for more
preschool education,'' says Primrose president Jo Kirchner. ``We
provide that structure, but structure doesn't mean pressure. There
has to be a part of the day when the kids participate only because
they choose to, otherwise you create unhealthy stress.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed there are parents who worry that a carefree, workfree
childhood is, like the rainforest, a precious vanishing resource.
Goldberg's response is, ``If you make learning fun enough, it's not
an either-or situation. You can have the freedom of play with the
kinds of structure that will enhance learning later in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg regrets learning Spanish so late _ when he was a cadet
at West Point. ``When I finally went to Spain, I was petrified of
carrying on a conversation,'' he says. ``It got me thinking about
the importance of an early start.''
</P>
<P>
   After stewing in an unfulfilling law practice in Michigan, he
headed for Atlanta in 1996 with a hunch that the Olympics would
raise demand for more languages. He and his wife, Kimberley
Goldberg _ whom he met while both were teaching Spanish in Atlanta
that year _ founded Kidspeak, partly on the model of a British
program they had studied.
</P>
<P>
   They have built a healthy roster of clients. Occasionally they
contract with an institution _ for instance, Cross and Crown, which
pays Kidspeak to teach seven classes at various age levels _ but
more often they sell the course directly to parents, typically for
$140-$185 for about 16 weekly sessions.
</P>
<P>
   The 2- and 3-year-old starts may not be right for every child.
At Cross and Crown, one of the 2-year-olds was so unresponsive to
Estela that he was eventually allowed to wander across the room and
investigate an inflatable pumpkin.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, one of the advantages of starting at a younger age
became clear when Estela hurried down the hall to her 3-year-old
class. When she held up an animal picture and pronounced, ``leon,''
one boy protested, ``That's a lion!'' Later on he insisted on
``fox'' for the picture of ``El Lobo!'' that Estella brought to
hilarious, snarling life in her Spanish version of ``Little Red
Riding Hood.'' The 2-year-olds, on the other hand, often mimicked
Estela's Spanish words perfectly and never countered with English
ones.
</P>
<P>
   Which raises the question: how low can they go?
</P>
<P>
   ``I once started teaching Spanish to an infant six weeks old,''
Estela says, ''And by two-and-a-half he was fully bilingual.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
