<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7024 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SOCCER-JUNKIE-ART-NYT     10-14 1257
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCCER-JUNKIE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE JOYS AND PAINS OF PURSUING PICKUP SOCCER GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By CHRIS BALLARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ My introduction to soccer came when I was 8 and my
family moved to Oxford for two years. Homesick for America, my
brother and I would head to a local field with our baseball gloves
only to find it consistently occupied by kids kicking around a
volleyball. Or at least that's what it looked like to me.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually realizing that our only other option was cricket, a
game that makes baseball look like nonstop action, we began playing
soccer. By the time I returned stateside, I had not only picked up
the type of English accent that gets one beat up by large fourth
graders, but had also acquired a love of the game. The free-flowing
play, intricate teamwork and athleticism all appealed to me. I
played competitively through high school, but with the exception of
kicking around in the backyard I hadn't played since.
</P>
<P>
   Intent on changing that, I set out recently in search of pickup
soccer games. In many cities this would have been a foolish quest.
Most players drift away from the game after school, choosing to
pursue more practical sports.
</P>
<P>
   But in the great melting pot of New York City, where immigrants
arrive harboring a love of the game, you can always find people
playing. They set up garbage cans and play in the street or throw
down their shirts to create impromptu goals on any grassy surface.
The games in each neighborhood reflect the population: Irish
players at Van Cortlandt Park in the Bronx, a Caribbean influence
at Prospect Park in Brooklyn and a Hispanic flavor at Flushing
Meadows Park in Queens. I knew they had to be playing in Manhattan,
I just had to find them.
</P>
<P>
   After a few dead ends, I met a couple of players at Chelsea
Piers (which has indoor leagues and occasional open play) who told
me about regular pickup games on a field at 101st Street and
Riverside Drive. I headed up there with my cleats, soccer shorts
and a fair amount of apprehension. It turns out I needed only the
latter two; open grass fields in Manhattan are about as common as
taxi drivers in the rain. As a result, most games are played on
asphalt, dirt or, as in this case, artificial turf. The ``field''
at 101st Street and Riverside Drive is actually an expanse of
tan-colored turf about 60 yards long ringed by trees and a running
track. Two small netted goals about four feet high stand at
opposite ends.
</P>
<P>
   When I arrived in the late afternoon, there was already an
eight-on-eight game under way. I warmed up on the sideline, kicking
around with a local teen-ager and trying to get the hang of playing
in running shoes. Six more players arrived, and the eight of us
took the field to challenge the winning team. All but one of my
teammates were speaking Spanish, a language I once studied but had
not used in years.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, one of my opponents, a regular (and the only woman
playing that day) named Wendy Hollender filled me in. ``We play
first to score or until 15 minutes,'' she said. ``There are no
corner kicks or throw-ins, and the goalie can't use his hands.''
Perhaps noticing my butterflies _ it had been more than eight years
since I'd played game _ she added: ``Don't worry. If you don't mess
up too bad the first time, they'll pass it to you again.''
</P>
<P>
   Pass they did. Because of the short field (regulation soccer
fields are 100 to 130 yards long), artificial turf and minuscule
goals, there were no booming free kicks, slide tackles,
crossbar-scraping shots on goal or diving headers. The name of the
game was ball control, with an emphasis on numerous quick passes,
fancy footwork and close-range shots. Success depended on
understanding the angles and nuances. In one sense, it was the
sport distilled to its essence. In another less poetic sense, it
was really frustrating. I felt like the long-hitting golfer John
Daly trapped on a miniature-golf course.
</P>
<P>
   After growing up playing on expansive suburban fields, I was
accustomed to lots of space, long passes and physical tackles: the
traditional American style of play. Forced to play a more refined
finesse game, I found my athletic advantage taken away, and I felt
clumsy and confined, especially against quicker, more lithe
opponents. I made erratic passes, overran the ball and almost
leveled my teammates numerous times.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of our 15 minutes, we were still tied, so they
flipped a coin to decide the winner. We won the toss, and in our
second game a skilled midfielder on our squad nicknamed Maradona
made like his namesake _ the forward from Argentina's World Cup
teams _ and punched in an early goal to give us the victory. My
play improved _ I made a couple of good passes and almost scored on
a header _ but I was still basically a nonfactor.
</P>
<P>
   Our run ended in the third game and I retired to the sideline,
where I sat down beside Richard, a compact man with white hair and
a mustache. Richard is the unofficial commissioner of this field.
He settles disputes, jokes with the children and barks strategy
from his position as goalie. At 49, he has spent more than 20 years
playing soccer on the streets of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until they opened this park last year, we used to play on any
flat space we could find,'' he said. ``We'd head out between
baseball games, play on blacktops, whatever it took.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing about soccer in the city is that you play with
everyone from busboys to doctors, whoever loves the game,'' he
continued. ``Out here, the ages range from 15 to 50, and because
there are so many immigrants in New York we get all nations and
races.''
</P>
<P>
   Within an hour or so, the park had filled up with about 60
people, mostly Hispanic men in their 20s and 30s. Along the
sidelines, the waiting players gave impromptu color commentary or
analyzed their previous loss. Behind one net a group of people had
set up a short field using garbage cans for goals. In the distance,
I could see a couple of games starting up on deserted baseball
diamonds north of the park. It was an amazing collection of skilled
soccer players to find in the heart of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   I left the park energized but still itched to play on a big
field. The next weekend I got my chance. A friend and fellow
athletic enthusiast, Istvan Seri, invited me to play a game with
his league team. I packed my cleats and followed him to a local
suburban high school.
</P>
<P>
   We started out strong, attacking well and keeping the
opposition's fast forwards at bay. Seri, who almost played
professionally in his native Hungary (his father told him ``better
to be a mediocre doctor than a mediocre soccer player''),
controlled the midfield. His son Adam, a nationally ranked tennis
player at the University of Georgia, made acrobatic saves in goal.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't enough though; we couldn't generate much offense and
lost 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, I felt my skills returning as I charged up and down the
grass field. With every pass, header or dribble, my muscle memory
slowly creaked back to life.
</P>
<P>
   After the match, I headed home and flopped onto my sofa,
clinging to a 32-ounce bottle of Gatorade. My hamstrings were
tighter than the strings on a concerto violin, my quadriceps
throbbed like twin stereo speakers and my neck felt as if I had
just subjected it to a double feature from the front row of the
movie theater. In other words, I felt great. I was back in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
