<HEADLINE>
RIGHTS AGENCY DIRECTOR UNDER REVIEW FOR ALLEGED MISMANAGEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JULIE CHAO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The 11 commissioners of the Human Rights
Commission are conducting a closed-door evaluation of the agency's
director amid accusations of mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
   The HRC, which is responsible for administering the affirmative
action and domestic partner benefits programs in San Francisco, has
logged far more complaints than any other city agency, a union
representative said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had contact with a great deal of employees representing
departments all around the city,'' said Harry Baker, president of
the Golden Gate Chapter of Service Employees International Union
Local 790, which represents 1,200 municipal employees. ``I've never
seen a management team as abusive of its employees as that one, and
petty.''
</P>
<P>
   The commissioners have focused their evaluation on the executive
director, Marivic Bamba, who was appointed by Mayor Willie Brown in
1996. She was formerly the director of contract compliance for the
city of Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically if you're the head coach, if you're the CEO, you're
the person where the buck stops,'' said Harry Low, a retired judge
who is the chairman of the commission. ``We're doing that
evaluation.''
</P>
<P>
   The volume of complaints _ more than 30 in 2 1/2 years from a
staff of about 40, according to Baker _ led last year to a review
of the agency by the Department of Human Resources, which is
responsible for personnel matters in city departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It showed a need for improvement in management style,
returning phone calls, open communication,'' Low said.
</P>
<P>
   The confidential report recommended management training and
better people skills, said Low, who is also one of three people
appointed by the mayor to serve on a panel to assess the HRC's
minority contracting program.
</P>
<P>
   Baker said he has filed four grievances on behalf of employees
who have been dismissed or demoted in the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   All worked in contract compliance at the airport. Other staff
complaints were more informal and mostly involved perceived
mistreatment.
</P>
<P>
   Bamba responded to a list of specific questions with a statemenng she has increased the department's staffing and budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``HRC staff continue to work diligently as a team of committed
professionals who firmly believe in the daunting task of
eradicating discrimination,'' she said in the statement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 1746EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
