<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFL-MATCHUPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL MATCHUPS FOR WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAME OF THE WEEK (4:05 P.M. SUNDAY)
</P>
<P>
   Seattle (3-1) vs. San Diego (3-1)
</P>
<P>
   This game was not originally considered a matchup that would
determine the early American Football Conference West lead, but the
Seahawks and Chargers are picking up this division's pieces left by
Denver's early swoon. Seattle has won without its holdout receiver,
Joey Galloway, and San Diego has won despite injuries at
quarterback, where Jim Harbaugh recovers from banged ribs and
watches Erik Kramer excel. Kramer is especially good late in games,
having completed 9 of 11 fourth-quarter passes for 77 yards. It
will be a see-saw, entertaining game dripping with drama, one in
which San Diego wins it in the fourth quarter with a stout
defensive stand. Chargers, 23-19.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY, 1 P.M. GAMES
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland (0-5) vs. Jacksonville (4-1)
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland lost its first two games by an average of 30 points
and then lost its last three by a an average of only 6.7 points.
Improvement, yes, but hollow compared with the bottom line of
winning games. Of course, the Browns are excused, as they gain
experience as an expansion franchise while competing against teams
that view them as a sure victory. Jacksonville sees the same, and
the Jaguars will use this game as a chance to tune an offense that
has toiled while its defense roars. Jacksonville reaches a 5-1
record for the third straight year. Jaguars, 38-16.
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis (2-2) vs. Jets (1-4)
</P>
<P>
   The Jets have problems running, passing, catching and scoring.
Their offense has slumped, and they face a team that leads the AFC
in scoring. Peyton Manning has thrown at least a touchdown pass in
his last 17 consecutive starts (best in the league) and has tossed
a scoring pass to receiver Marvin Harrison in 14 of the Colts' last
16 games. The Jets must figure a way to pressure Manning, who has
only been sacked twice. They hope quarterback Rick Mirer (3
touchdown passes, 7 interceptions) can elevate his play.
Indianapolis has won more games (34) against the Jets than it has
against any opponent and it has won seven of the last nine in this
series. That trend continues. Colts, 20-17.
</P>
<P>
   Miami (3-1) vs. New England (4-1)
</P>
<P>
   Miami makes its second straight divisional road trip, having
tripped Indianapolis, 34-31. This time, the test is tougher. It is
a smart matchup _ the Dolphins' flexible and fast defense against
the Patriots' deep-strike offense. Quarterback Drew Bledsoe has
four 300-yard passing games against Miami, the most he has compiled
against any team, and receiver Terry Glenn has gained at least 92
receiving yards in each game this season. Glenn owns league-bests
in receiving yards (636) and in average yards per catch (17.2).
Bledsoe-to-Glenn and New England's ability to convert third downs
wins it. Watch Dan Marino become the first NFL passer to reach
60,000 yards. Patriots, 24-17.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota (2-3) vs. Detroit (2-2)
</P>
<P>
   Both teams lost at home last week _ Minnesota to Chicago and
Detroit to San Diego _ but it is the Vikings who are reeling most.
They are finding it impossible to duplicate the traits, primarily a
circus-like offense, that made them a 15-1 team a year ago. Fewer
points, fewer big plays for the Vikings and a defense that is
allowing an average of 374 yards a game spell trouble. Detroit
needs more big plays, too, especially in the passing game. It is
often not a good sign when a team's leading receiver is its running
back, and that back happens to be Ron Rivers _ not Barry Sanders _
with only 17 catches. Help is on the way for Detroit. Receiver
Herman Moore is expected to return from injury, and Detroit will
benefit. Lions, 17-16.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland (2-3) vs. Buffalo (4-1)
</P>
<P>
   A meeting of two quarterbacks who like to run with the ball and
are as good at it as they are passing it. Rich Gannon and Doug
Flutie have thrown six touchdown passes apiece, but Buffalo has
been more successful as a team because of a better defense. It
features the league's best run defense (62.4 yards allowed per
game). It is allowing 54 fewer overall yards per game than Oakland
and is allowing only a 30.8 percent conversion on third-down plays.
Buffalo shoots for continuation of some nifty streaks _ its fifth
5-1 start of the '90s, its 10th victory in its last 11 home games
and its seventh consecutive victory in October. It gets them.
Bills, 16-10.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia (1-4) vs. Chicago (3-2)
</P>
<P>
   ``The most disgusting thing was when the stretcher came out and
they started cheering again,'' said Eagles receiver Charles Johnson
about his team's fans when Dallas receiver Michael Irvin was
injured in Philadelphia last week. ``It was embarrassing to be on
the sideline. He's lying out there with a restraint on his neck and
you don't even know if he's conscious, and your heart really goes
out to the guy. Not all of our fans were booing, but for the ones
who did, it just wasn't tasteful. Our fans pride themselves on
being tough, but that wasn't tough. That was ignorant.'' OK. Even
with the Eagles on the road, their fans will boo THEM this time.
Bears, 19-12.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh (2-3) vs. Cincinnati (1-4)
</P>
<P>
   Akili Smith passed for 221 yards, 2 touchdowns and led the late,
game-winning drive in his first NFL start in the Bengals' victory
over Cleveland. He is supported by Corey Dillon, the league's
leading rusher, and if Dillion finishes the season that way, he
will become the first Bengal to do so since Paul Robinson 31 years
ago. Of course, the Bengals usually have a rough time stopping
Pittsburgh's Jerome Bettis; he has gained 615 rushing yards in his
last 6 games against them. Bettis is a bruiser, Dillon is a
slasher. Bettis vs. Dillon? This time, go with Bettis. Steelers,
23-21.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis (4-0) vs. Atlanta (1-4)
</P>
<P>
   The Rams are amazing. Curt Warner has 14 touchdown passes and is
the first since Don Meredith in 1966 to throw that many in his
first four games. The Rams threw only 12 touchdown passes all of
last year. Warner has three 300-yard passing games and has thrown
at least three touchdowns in each of his four games. Warner throws
to dynamic receivers, chief among them Isaac Bruce (22 catches for
446 yards and a 20.3 average yards per catch along with 6 touchdown
grabs, 4 last week against San Francisco). The Rams finally ended
their losing hex against the 49ers and they will not slip. They
remain hungry, reaching a 5-0 record for the first time since 1989.
Rams, 25-20.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee (4-1) vs. New Orleans (1-3)
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee has not reached a 5-1 record in eight years and this
game is dangerous. The Saints may not be so terrible. They are plus
5 in turnover differential. Their six turnovers committed rank
second-fewest in the NFC. Their seven fumble recoveries rank second
in the conference. They have allowed the fewest passing first downs
(33) in the league. They rank second in sacks in the conference.
Those numbers sound like a 3-1 team, not a 1-3 team. Much of it
boils down to timing, not making consistent or big plays in the
game's most excruciating moments. Tennessee slips by. Titans, 10-9.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 1747EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7027 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-MATCHUPS-2NDTAKE-     10-14 0431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MATCHUPS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: 10-9.  

</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNDAY, 4 P.M. GAMES
</P>
<P>
   Carolina (1-3) vs. San Francisco (3-2)
</P>
<P>
   This is George Seifert's first game against his old team, and he
catches them at a low point. The 49ers are nursing deep wounds
after their whipping at the Rams. They still don't have Steve Young
back at quarterback and, more and more, it looks as if Young's
concussion might keep him out longer. Their pass defense was porous
against the Rams and oftentimes embarrassing. Look for the 49ers to
rebound. But watch Carolina and back Tim Biakabutuka chew them up.
Look for a big game from Beuerlein and his receivers. This is a
victory that Seifert desperately wants. He will cherrish it.
Panthers, 31-28.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay (3-1) vs. Denver (1-4)
</P>
<P>
   A rematch of Super Bowl XXXII but both teams have different
looks. Green Bay is turning games over to Brett Favre, letting him
work his magic in a variety of ways. Denver is still trying to
solve its problems at quarterback, running back and on defense.
Winning at the Raiders was a start. But the Broncos meet a team
that has jelled much faster than them. One with more talent, too,
especially at the skill positions. Denver offers a fight but Green
Bay's Dorsey Levens (4.4 average yards per carry) runs out the
clock at the end. Packers, 24-20.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Washington (3-1) vs. Arizona (2-3)
</P>
<P>
   Washington enjoyed a bye and an extra week to prepare for
Arizona. That should serve them well, especially quarterback Brad
Johnson. He has thrown for 1,191 yards in four games and leads an
offense that averages 412.5 yards per game. In 122 pass attempts
this season, Johnson has not thrown an interception. Stephen Davis
anchors the ground game with 400 rushing yards; his career high in
a season is 567. Arizona has won six of the last seven at home
against Washington and its defense is capable; it has the
top-ranked pass defense in the NFC. But look for Johnson to solve
them. Redskins, 21-16.
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Dallas (3-1) vs. Giants (2-3)
</P>
<P>
   Dallas is 6-0 against the Giants on Monday nights and last year
in a Monday night game spanked them, 31-7. It was a game where
Deion Sanders ran circles around them, scoring on punt and
interception returns. Dallas swept the Giants last year. The
Cowboys recover from the emotional loss of the injured Michael
Irvin and play confidently against a team they think they can
dominate. They find the Giants offense simple, the Giants defense
tougher, but, overall, believe they are simply a better team. Maybe
so. Cowboys, 23-17.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
