<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Contact,'' Susan Stroman and John Weidman's musical
meditation on dance and love, is prompting the type of sales that
make even producers get misty.
</P>
<P>
   The show, which opened last Thursday at Lincoln Center's Mitzi
E. Newhouse Theater, sold $298,000 in tickets the next day, an
exceptional showing for an off-Broadway-size theater. (Top tickets,
it should be noted, are $65, higher than most off-Broadway shows.)
By midday Saturday, it had sold out its entire run, including a
five-week extension through Jan. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Scenarios for moving the show downtown to a Broadway theater
cropped up almost instantly. But in the end, ``Contact'' will stay
close to home, moving from the downstairs Newhouse to the upstairs
Vivian Beaumont, a Broadway-size venue, where the show will be
eligible for Tony nominations.
</P>
<P>
   Performances at the Beaumont begin on March 9. That date allows
a four-week cushion for a possible extension of the new musical
``Marie Christine,'' which opens on Dec. 2 at the Beaumont and has
an official closing date of Jan. 9. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Debut in `Wild Party'
</P>
<P>
   Confirming widespread speculation, the Public Theater said this
week that Toni Collette, the comely Australian actress currently
starring in the film ``The Sixth Sense,'' has been cast in the role
of Queenie in next spring's Broadway production of ``The Wild
Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Queenie, you'll remember, was the part played by Vanessa
Williams in an early workshop of the show. Ms. Williams bowed out
of the show in late September just before a surprise wedding
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Collette, 26, has been acting professionally since her
teens, making her breakthrough in 1995 as the Abba-loving,
nuptial-obsessed title character in ``Muriel's Wedding,'' a role
she had to gain weight to play. She's had a steady stream of parts
since, but ``The Wild Party'' will be her Broadway debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done no theater since 1993, so I'm going to be absolutely
petrified,'' said Ms. Collette, who is from Sydney. ``But it's
going to be nice to actually unpack my bags.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Ragtime' Suit
</P>
<P>
   Wilner Advertising, a Broadway advertising agency, has filed a
$500,000 lawsuit against the Pace Theatrical Group, the producer of
``Ragtime,'' claiming that Pace stole an advertising slogan for the
show.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, which alleges copyright infringement, concerns an
advertisement that appeared in The New York Times and several other
newspapers on Sept. 19. The ad portrays three beaming children
standing beneath a millennial slogan: ``Before the century ends,
see how it all began.'' Similar ads are also running on television
and radio.
</P>
<P>
   In a complaint filed in U.S. District Court on Oct. 1, lawyers
for the Wilner agency said that the slogan and image had been
lifted from a pitch for the ``Ragtime'' account, which John Wilner,
the agency's founder, presented to Scott Zeiger, Pace's president,
in a meeting in late August.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Wilner showed Pace its storyboards, and the next thing
you know, he saw his line in the paper,'' said Eve Rachel
Markewich, a lawyer for Tenzer Greenblatt, which is representing
Wilner.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Pace said it believed the lawsuit was ``without
merit,'' and objected to the naming of Zeiger as an individual
defendant.
</P>
<P>
   The Broadway advertising community is a small but highly
competitive one. In the mid-1990s, Wilner and his former partner,
Peter LeDonne, handled a series of major shows, including ``Show
Boat'' and ``Kiss of the Spider Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently, however, the company has lost ground to Serino-Coyne,
the industry leader, and to companies like Spotco and Grey
Entertainment. It is currently handling only one Broadway show,
``Saturday Night Fever.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `Aida' Without Pyramid
</P>
<P>
   The lighting was austere, the costumes were basic black, and
there wasn't a giant, mobile pyramid in sight.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday afternoon at the New Amsterdam Theater, Disney staged
its first major group-sales presentation of the new ``Aida,'' a
musical written by Sir Elton John and Tim Rice.
</P>
<P>
   The audience was a select crowd of 3,600 close friends and
potential bulk-ticket buyers. The show, which begins a tryout in
Chicago on Nov. 12, opens at the Palace Theater in New York in
March.
</P>
<P>
   The presentation was a first look at how the $15 million show
has evolved from its first incarnation, which stalled in Atlanta
last year _ as did its oft-maligned set centerpiece, a giant
rotating pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   Early indications are that the new creative team, headed by the
director Robert Falls (``Death of a Salesman'') and the designer
Bob Crowley (``The Iceman Cometh''), has revamped the show from
head to toe.
</P>
<P>
   Falls outlined a new beginning, which involves a modern couple
pre-incarnated as the princess Aida (played by Heather Headley) and
her lover Radames (Adam Pascal). He also offered quips about Disney
and Sir Elton _ and himself. ``I did everything I could to slip
musical numbers in `Death of a Salesman,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Crowley, meanwhile, showed more than a half-dozen designs, from
a prison scene, with stark black cells in front of a deep blue
backdrop, to his vision of the Nile valley, all yellow and orange,
with palm trees reflected in silhouette. As for that infamous set
piece, it has been replaced by a more minimalist _ and less finicky
_ triangular laser beam.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the nearest thing you are going to get to a pyramid,''
Crowley said.
</P>
<P>
   Along the Way
</P>
<P>
   _ George Wendt, known on television for ``Cheers'' and on
Broadway for ``Art,'' will return to a New York stage in ``An Empty
Plate at the Cafe du Grand Boeuf.'' It will open in March at
Primary Stages.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Another American: Asking and Telling,'' a play by Marc Wolf
about gays in the military, will be the second show in the New
Group's season. Produced in association with David Marshall Grant,
it will begin performances on Dec. 7 at the Theater at St. Clements
. The company's season opener, ``Cranes,'' opens there on
Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
