<SLUG> BC-TV-RYAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW COP DRAMA WORTH CARING ABOUT ON FOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ryan Caulfield: Year One'' is a cop drama, but Dewey-decimal
devotees may want to categorize it with all the new shows exploring
class polarization. For when 19-year-old Philadelphia police
officer Ryan Caulfield straps on his 9-millimeter, he is as
different from his pals in teen mufti as high school is from
college.
</P>
<P>
   Caulfield, whose dirty-cop father is in prison, eschewed a
college scholarship to attend the police academy. Now on the beat
and eager to do right, he is tormented by his father's legacy, his
mother's mothering, his own insecurity and the allure of the road
not taken.
</P>
<P>
   That's more carry-on baggage than the FAA recommends, but
Caulfield is willing to face the pressure of his fears, his peers
and his seers. He cares enough to make a difference and, despite a
second episode that's overwrought by a sob or two, ``Ryan
Caulfield: Year One'' looks like a cop drama worth caring about.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's premiere, the telegenic Sean Maher establishes
Caulfield as the enthusiastic rookie cop teamed with a seasoned
veteran in one of Philadelphia's most blighted neighborhoods. In
his first day on the job, Caulfield sees more dead bodies than the
average cop probably sees in a career, but, hey, this is prime-time
TV. Caulfield's reaction to it is also fairly standard _ first the
stiff upper lip, then the crumbling facade later on.
</P>
<P>
   But by letting viewers see Caulfield off the job as well as on,
creators James DeMonaco and Kevin Fox (``The Negotiator'') have put
a fresh face on yet another show about big-city cops. The story
lines are equally divided between Caulfield's time behind the badge
and his time behind the scenes, that is, in the privacy of
relationships with his mother, his girlfriend and his two best
buddies.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, given to overexaggeration, calls it the most original
police drama in years. It's an easy claim to dismiss: CBS's
``Turks'' plowed some of the same ground as recently as last
season. Still, ``Ryan Caulfield: Year One'' is better than its
gestation period might have suggested. Originally titled ``Ryan
Caulfield,'' which sounds like an Aaron Spelling soaper, the show
had the gifted Mary McDonnell in the role of Caulfield's mother.
McDonnell departed after the pilot was shot, ostensibly because the
show was going to be less mom-centric and the producers had renamed
it ``The Badland,'' after a downtrodden district in Philadelphia.
That title was also somewhat misleading, so it was finally changed
to ``Ryan Caulfield: Year One,'' which at least suggests some sort
of story arc involving a fledgling endeavor.
</P>
<P>
   Maher brings credibility to the principal role. But, as is
usually the case in a good show, the strength of the supporting
cast is its keystone. Familiar players such as Michael Rispoli and
Richard Portnow help fill out the police ranks with something more
than station-house cliches, while James Roday and Chad Lindberg
play Caulfield's best friends with a liveliness that makes it
possible to see police officers as regular people.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to embrace another police drama, but if there's still
room on your dance card this late in the new season, it might be
worth giving ``Ryan Caulfield: Year One'' a spin.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Caulfield: Year One. Hourlong drama series about a
19-year-old police officer in Philadelphia. Starring Sean Maher,
Michael Rispoli, Roselyn Sanchez, James Roday, Chad Lindberg,
Richard Portnow, Clifton Powell and Brenda Bakke. Series premiere
Friday night on Fox. Parental guideline rating: TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 1749EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
