<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0245 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7030 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-JAZZ-DRUMMERS-2TAKES-     10-14 1413
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAZZ-DRUMMERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPELLED BY DIFFERENT DRUMMERS: SETTING JAZZ'S COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By BEN RATLIFF    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ About three years ago I started to notice that I no
longer knew what to expect at a jazz club. The music started
changing. The clunkily drawn opposing territories _ traditional vs.
avant-garde, or swing-centric jazz vs. jazz free with a steady
pulse _ became irrelevant. Lots of bands were coming up with ways
to create spontaneous form onstage.
</P>
<P>
   A huge hybrid area, a kind of adventurous mainstream, began to
assert itself. The music sounded different. And as is always the
case when jazz evolves, rhythm seemed to be at the root of the
change.
</P>
<P>
   I began to notice a rash of young drummers I'd never heard of,
all of them loaded with technique and with at least the seeds of
originality. They were opening up the idea of strict time, making
lots of tempo changes, playing slowly behind a fast solo or vice
versa.
</P>
<P>
   They were stretching the music's formal elements while keeping
bounce and swing in it, and their playing often seemed to define
the shape of the band's sound. These young drummers were obviously
learning rhythms from other cultures; not just glancing at them but
really learning them.
</P>
<P>
   Marvelous drummers came along in the 1980s, and they're still
playing superbly, refining their craft and wielding influence. They
include Jeff ``Tain'' Watts, Ralph Peterson and Lewis Nash. And in
the early and mid-1990s they were joined by Greg Hutchinson, Matt
Wilson, Jim Black, Brian Blade, Clarence Penn and Leon Parker.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is another new crop, setting the rhythm for jazz's
future. It's a good time to pay attention to the back of the
bandstand.
</P>
<P>
   NASHEET WAITS
</P>
<P>
   Nasheet Waits plays with band leaders like the vibraphonist
Stefon Harris and the saxophonist Antonio Hart, musicians who use
hard swing and come more or less out of the mainstream jazz idiom.
But in each tune, Waits performs as if he's taking a never-ending
solo.
</P>
<P>
   The pulse is always there, yet he moves accents around it,
making rhythm contract and expand, changing his focus for stretches
at a time from cymbals to toms to bass drum and snare. Waits is the
son of Freddie Waits, one of jazz's recent unsung heroes, a drummer
who played all over the aesthetic map, with Kenny Barron and Sonny
Rollins and Cecil Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Nasheet Waits only grew serious about playing after his father's
death in 1989, and he studied with Michael Carvin as well as Max
Roach, whose tendency to break rhythms down to their essence and
slowly build them up again have leaked into Waits' playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did a gig with Hamiet Bluiett at the Vision Festival,'' he
said recently, referring to his appearance with the baritone
saxophone player at a free-jazz festival in May. ``That was nice,
because it let me see that the way that I feel music is valid. You
don't always have to be snapping your fingers, one, two, three,
four.''
</P>
<P>
   He recalled seeing the saxophonist David S. Ware play. ``The
audience was swaying,'' he said, ``more like an infinity sign, that
kind of movement. And I said, `Yeah, that's the way I feel when I
play.' I feel it in a circle. You start from a point in the center
and circle around, kind of swirl, like the ocean, the water, that
kind of movement.''
</P>
<P>
   When he's playing, Waits said, he's not just thinking about jazz
drumming, but he proceeds as if he were using an imaginary
instrument of infinite capability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Max told me that he used to ride the train and try to deal
with the rhythm of the train,'' he said. ``There are all these
sounds out there that you can incorporate into your flow.''
</P>
<P>
   Waits was talking in a cafe, and outside a bus released its air
brakes and took off. ``You can use that,'' Waits said, gesturing
behind him, ``get that sound like ssss and then rruuuurrr, an
acceleration kind of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But even here Waits sets rules. ``You can sound like you're
accelerating without actually speeding anything up,'' he said.
``You want to be able to manipulate energy.''
</P>
<P>
   RODNEY GREEN
</P>
<P>
   Two winters ago, when Greg Osby's quartet played a week at Sweet
Basil, musicians came down in droves. The band was particularly
hot, and word had been spreading about its new drummer, Rodney
Green, a teen-ager from Camden, N.J. Some of the music that week
turned into a live album, ``Banned in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I had just turned 18,'' he said, ``and I didn't even have all
my stuff moved to New York yet. I'd graduated from high school in
June, and that was December. I was scared to death. People were
coming down to the club, and I'm just now starting to realize who
they were.'' Then, awe-struck, he recited a roll call of drummers:
``Lenny White. Billy Hart. Brian Blade. Victor Lewis.''
</P>
<P>
   You get a sense of just how young Green is when he speaks of
having ``had the good fortune'' to see, say, Blade, once or twice.
(Blade plays in New York regularly.) But Green is a fearsome
drummer.
</P>
<P>
   From the age of 6 he played drums in church, accompanying his
parents, who are both preachers. He mastered the most recent
incarnation of gospel-funk rhythms, playing behind tremendous drum
sets with racks of tom-toms and a lot of cymbals.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 15, a friend showed him an album-cover photo of
Elvin Jones, whom he'd never heard of, and then played him the
record, which was John Coltrane's ``Transition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Elvin had this little 18-inch bass drum, toms that looked
really small, and two cymbals, and he was playing all this stuff,''
Green said, looking shattered. The experience challenged him to
find his own sound on a drum kit, rather than letting the kit
define him.
</P>
<P>
   Before he left high school, he was playing with the pop singer
Patti LaBelle, but jazz won out. Now he's a regular member of the
band led by the pianist Eric Reed. Like a lot of young drummers,
he's thrilling at fast tempos, but his grooves are ornate, full of
tone color from the tiny additions of cymbals and toms that he
positions around each beat.
</P>
<P>
   He has been studying with Carvin for about a year and a half.
``He made one of the strangest requests I've ever heard,'' Green
said of his teacher. ``He told me to stop listening to jazz. Listen
to the Nat King Cole trio without the drums, the one with bass,
drums and guitar. Listen to classical music. And then listen to
yourself. Now I can't listen to my favorite drummer and copy all
his ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   JOHN HOLLENBECK
</P>
<P>
   I first heard John Hollenbeck at alt.coffee, a small East
Village cafe that booked music on Monday nights. His bands, the
Claudia Quintet and the Lucy Quartet, are set up for his
compositions, which are slightly academic: he likes to write tone
rows based on telephone numbers and melodies based on the rhythms
of poems. But his light, swinging drumming gives them a feeling of
security and purpose.
</P>
<P>
   The air that night was sticky, and street noises flooded through
the open street-level window. But Hollenbeck responded with even
more noises, subtle ones that were difficult to discern. He'd use
metal bowls, a child's plastic toy, a small box activated by heat
that made cricket sounds, and he'd deftly add them into his
improvisations.
</P>
<P>
   Here was a drummer with marvelous technique. He studied
classical percussion and jazz at the Eastman School of Music, he
has spent time learning Brazilian and Indian drumming, and he
substitutes in the Village Vanguard Monday night big band, reading
the complex music of Thad Jones and Mel Lewis on the bandstand. For
such a player to be performing oddball music in the East Village is
rare enough. But what won me over was his seriousness about it.
</P>
<P>
   Hollenbeck said that his father, who is a mail-order antiques
dealer in Binghamton, N.Y., would pick up anything that had sound
and bring it home for his older brother, who is now a percussionist
in the Boston Pops.
</P>
<P>
   ``So when I started playing at alt.coffee,'' Hollenbeck said,
``I had an outlet all of a sudden to try to make some of them legal
instruments.''
</P>
<P>
   Ostentation isn't the point, and Hollenbeck is not looking for
cheap humor. ``I like to take something with a funny context, that
you think of as a toy, but to make something beautiful out of it.
People laugh if they've never seen it before. But I have a really
dry sense of humor, and for me it's not funny. It's part of the
music. It's just there, and nobody has to know what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ERIC HARLAND
</P>
<P>
   ``The new thing is about freer time,'' said Eric Harland, who's
a member of Terence Blanchard's band and has recorded with Jason
Moran, Stefon Harris and Rodney Jones. ``You keep the time, but you
hear different rhythmic elements in the midst of it and play them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take our discussion right now. We're talking, and if you were
to place time in the midst of how we're talking, each word and each
breath forms a rhythmic concept, some type of rhythm. I've
incorporated that into the way I play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like speaking. If I was talking when I was
playing, what would I say? So I wrap that around a pulse, and find
the different rhythmic values of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Harland, in his mid-20s, is from Houston, and he, too, had a
religious background, with parents who sang and played the organ in
church. He studied at the Manhattan School of Music, left to return
to Houston and become a minister, then came back to New York when
Greg Osby hired him for a tour. Apart from the funk rhythms in
gospel music, he was working out jazz technique and questioning it
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned to play complex before I learned simplicity,'' he
said. ``I love meter shifting. I was heavily influenced by Tain and
Jack DeJohnette, and also Elvin Jones and Tony Williams and Max
Roach. Back then they couldn't really get away with it as much as
we can now.''
</P>
<P>
   The refinement of his playing came slowly. ``I used to approach
the drums in an angry way,'' he admitted. ``I used them to let out
my frustrations. My practice technique was that I would get on the
drums, put on a John Coltrane CD and play wild. Little did I know
how much that was helping me, because it was conditioning my body
to be able to get around the drums. Eventually I heard a metronome.
I started hearing a pulse in the midst of the wild beats.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty Carter, the great singer and trainer of young jazz
musicians who died last year, hired Harland for her last band. He
lived in her basement during some of that time, improving his piano
skills and generally increasing his musicality.
</P>
<P>
   ``She got us to write our own tunes,'' he said. ``She told us:
`Learn who you are. Don't sit around and wait for things to come to
you.' It started showing me a softer side of myself, which
surprised me. She taught me the polite side of music, too, how to
just `tip''' _ drummers' parlance for minimal accompaniment _ ``and
get into the groove of the song and enjoy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never could say I enjoyed sitting there tipping on the
cymbal, just catching the groove. But Betty made it fun, to the
point where now, doing it with other people, I have fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't always have to play a lot of chops. I think jazz is
totally free. You have the establishment of the groove, but it's
about the freedom of improvisation. You can put anything into it.''
</P>
<P>
   DANIEL FREEDMAN
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I go to Israel,'' said the 25-year-old drummer
Daniel Freedman, ``I go to the Sinai desert. It's possible there to
study with the Bedouins and the Sudanese. You can get a vibe, being
in the mountains with these people.''
</P>
<P>
   Like more and more jazz musicians, Freedman is in search of an
honest understanding of foreign rhythms. He has taken advantage of
the proliferation of foreign music on CD, and he leaves the country
whenever he can. In Israel he travels with his friend the Israeli
bassist Omer Avital, who has been a part of the New York jazz scene
for five years now. They go in search of musicians: not as
musicologists, but as vibe seekers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know musicians, but there are certain places where
there are Sudanese who play every night,'' Freedman said. ``They
might be working in the kitchen. Even if you sit with a 13-year-old
kid, the way he would feel a rhythm is the real thing. You don't
have to sit with a master drummer to learn the phrasing. That's
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Freedman attended La Guardia High School of Music and Art and
the Performing Arts in Manhattan, along with a lot of other
musicians who are now part of the scene at the West Village jazz
club Smalls, including the drummer Eric McPherson, the saxophonist
Myron Walden and the pianist Jason Lindner.
</P>
<P>
   At Mannes College of Music he often rehearsed in the basement
with Juan Rodriguez, a rumba expert, who worked at the school as a
custodian. And Freedman started performing Latin-influenced jazz
before he knew much about it, when Lindner landed a gig at a
midtown Cuban restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Freedman has since spent a few months in Cuba, where he studied
with the percussion group Yoruba Andabo, and in Mali. But even in
New York he can indulge a lot of his interest in Afro-Cuban
percussion by playing on weekends with rumba groups in Tompkins
Square Park in the East Village.
</P>
<P>
   The point, as he describes it, is not to play music from other
cultures directly, which he says is inappropriate and disrespectful
to its source. Rather, as new knowledge seeps into him, he can
summon different impulses from himself and the bands he plays with.
</P>
<P>
   And the musicians in his circle, including the members of
Lindner's big band, as well as the drummer Jeff Ballard, the
bassist Avishai Cohen and the oud player Amos Hoffman, are
searching, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all learning together, developing a language,'' Freedman
said. ``Sometimes we'll be playing a groove that might be somewhere
between Latin and Arabic. For a long time, if there was a `Latin'
section of a piece, jazz musicians would play a kind of
stereotypical jazz-Latin groove, and the bass player might play a
samba groove. They didn't really know how the parts fit together. I
feel that it's time to learn what those people are doing. Brazilian
music is totally different from Cuban music.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all looking for something besides straight-ahead jazz.
It doesn't necessarily express everything we have to say. I'm from
New York City, so in my ear is already Latin and Arabic and Jewish
music. What a lot of jazz drummers play sounds like jazz drums,
which is amazing. But I would like to make the drum set not sound
like a drum set.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I'm going for. And sometimes I get there, just for
a minute.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 1754EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7036 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      10-14 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MR. ROCK 'N' ROLL: THE ALAN FREED STORY'  
 `RYAN CAULFIELD: YEAR ONE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes for `Freed' movie at end of review) 
(bl) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   J. Edgar Hoover always gets the silliest lines. ``Let's get
everything we can on him,'' Hoover (Aron Tager) says to an FBI
employee in his one scene in ``Mr. Rock 'n' Roll: The Alan Freed
Story.'' ``This rock 'n' roll scourge may turn out to be more
dangerous than communism.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Mr. Rock 'n' Roll,'' an NBC movie to be shown Sunday night,
people are always making pronouncements like that. They don't have
conversations; they sum up the situation with the closest cliche at
hand. And just about every word spoken has one purpose: to sanctify
Freed as an advocate and promoter of racial harmony and justice
second only to the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. and as the founding
father of rock music.
</P>
<P>
   Freed (played by Judd Nelson, who looks a little startled
throughout the two hours), announces at various points: ``This
music can change the world,'' ``Didn't I tell you? This music has
the power,'' and ``Man, what a show!''
</P>
<P>
   If just once in a while Matt Dorff's script (based on John A.
Jackson's book ``Big Beat Heat: Alan Freed and the Early Years of
Rock-and-Roll'') let the action or normal dialogue make his points,
instead of repeatedly stating the obvious, ``Mr. Rock 'n' Roll''
might not be so insipid.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it will probably have no problem attracting
viewers, if only because of the original recordings used. When
Buddy Holly bursts into ``Peggy Sue'' in an office reception room,
the singing voice and the music are Holly and the Crickets.
</P>
<P>
   The same is true of a dozen or so other numbers, including
Jackie Wilson's ``Lonely Teardrops,'' Little Richard's ``Tutti
Frutti'' and Jerry Lee Lewis' ``Whole Lot of Shakin' Goin' On,''
and these performances are potent reminders of just how thrilling
early rock 'n' roll could be. When the actor playing Bo Diddley
sings, a man at the television station naturally says, ``This stuff
sounds like jungle music.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC is also promoting cameo appearances by Fabian, as an
outraged parent, and Bobby Rydell as a narrow-minded network
executive. Both are pretty much unrecognizable. Paula Abdul also
has a small role, as a songwriter who becomes Freed's mistress.
</P>
<P>
   Freed, who died in obscurity in 1965 at 43, was not necessarily
such a great guy. His contention that he invented the term rock 'n'
roll, which is pretty much the basis for his being celebrated in
this film, is challenged by more than a few people. His career went
downhill after the payola scandal, which is given short shrift
toward the end of ``Mr. Rock 'n' Roll.''
</P>
<P>
   The film also leaves out a couple of Freed's wives and children,
keeping him married to a former dance instructor (Madchen Amick,
who looks very pretty in ponytails and angora sweaters) until the
last scenes. And her unhappiness with the marriage seems to stem
from nothing more than his being out of town a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise the story is straightforward. As a radio disk jockey
in Cleveland in his early 30s, he learns from a store owner that
white teen-agers are buying rhythm-and-blues records. So Freed
stops playing mainstream music like Patti Page's ``Old Cape Cod''
and starts playing R-and-B on his show instead. Soon he's the host
of huge concerts and dance parties, and New York calls. He becomes
famous as a New York DJ, gets his own television show (``The Big
Beat'') and makes some movies. Then it all falls apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Rock 'n' Roll'' doesn't seem to be bothered by verbal
anachronisms either. After Freed has had a car accident, his doctor
warns him that he needs to give up smoking, drinking and partying.
``In order to fully recover,'' the young doctor says solemnly,
``you're going to have to make some lifestyle changes.'' People may
have had life styles in the 1950s, but nobody called them that.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MR. ROCK 'N' ROLL: THE ALAN FREED STORY'  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NBC, Sunday night at 9  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Written by Matt Dorff, based on the book ``Big Beat Heat: Alan
Freed and the Early Years of Rock-and-Roll'' by John A. Jackson.
Frank von Zerneck, Robert Sertner, Andy Wolk and Dorff, executive
producers; Randy Sutter and Rick Arredondo, producers; Wolk,
director; Derick Underschultz, director of photography.
</P>
<P>
   With: Judd Nelson (Alan Freed), Madchen Amick (Jackie Freed),
Leon (Jackie Wilson), Bobby Rydell (country club parent), Fabian
(head parent), Paula Abdul (Denise Walton) and Aron Tager (J. Edgar
Hoover). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `RYAN CAULFIELD: YEAR ONE'
</P>
<P>
   Fox, Friday night at 8
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan Caulfield'' is about a 19-year-old police rookie who
lives at home with his mom and gets introduced to the mean streets
in ways that shock his delicate sensibilities. And if you think
that's ridiculous, wait until you see the show itself, which was
briefly going to be called ``The Badland,'' a nickname for the
tough neighborhood he's assigned. The premier episode, in which
during his first hour on the job the title character is sent to a
crime scene where a cop has been fatally shot, has not a moment of
believability. Ryan has to shoot and kill someone before he has
even found out where his locker is. Sean Maher, who plays Ryan, is
very good looking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 1755EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
