<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-EURO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAIR LEADS CAMPAIGN SUPPORTING BRITISH ECONOMIC INTEGRATION WITH
EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Saying it would be ``madness'' to rule out joining the
European common currency, Prime Minister Tony Blair kicked off a
rare multiparty campaign Thursday aimed at combating widespread
antipathy in Britain to further integration with Europe.
</P>
<P>
   With high-profile figures from the opposition Conservatives and
the third party, the Liberal Democrats, by his side on a stage in a
futuristic movie theater, Blair, who leads the Labor Party, said:
``Europe is not marginal to the British economy. It is fundamental
to it and each day becomes more so.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To quit Europe,'' he declared, ``would be an act of economic
mutilation.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair's appearance, his most overt demonstration to date of
enthusiasm for a British role in monetary union, occurred as the
decadelong battle over Europe has intensified, with British
politicians going on combat alert. The Conservative leader, William
Hague, stiffened his party's stance last week, and his predecessor,
John Major, labeled Blair's policy ``absurd and crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   The two most important members of Major's former Cabinet, Deputy
Prime Minister Michael Heseltine and Chancellor of the Exchequer
Kenneth Clarke, along with the new leader of the Liberal Democrats,
Charles Kennedy, joined in the presentation Thursday in what Blair
called ``a patriotic alliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said the founding of the group was the start of a
``long-term campaign to change the way Britain thinks about
Europe.'' Clarke warned that his party's tough position was
dangerously isolationist, and Heseltine said, ``Whether we like it
or not, what happens in Europe is inseparable from what happens to
our own trade, employment, investment and industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Clarke and Heseltine hit back at claims that they were
``traitors,'' and Heseltine added a warning about quitting Europe
that singled out former Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, a
particularly belligerent opponent. ``You cannot wield a handbag
from an empty chair,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's presentation was to have occurred months ago, but
Blair postponed it, wary of becoming too closely identified with
the euro at a time when the new currency was underperforming and
doubts about it were deepening in the already distrustful British
public. It was only allowed to go forward when promoters agreed to
dilute its pro-euro message into a broader pro-Europe one.
</P>
<P>
   Blair, his' position unchanged by anything said Thursday, backs
a ``plan and decide'' policy whereby Britain encourages the public
and business to prepare for the possibility of adopting the euro
some years from now, but holds off the promised public referendum
on whether to go into monetary union until there is a sounder
economic basis for participation.
</P>
<P>
   There is virtually no lobby for Britain's immediate entry,
because by every standard the British economy is outperforming
those on the Continent and would have to stunt its growth to
achieve compatibility. But an individual's identification with a
particular attitude on Europe is so key in British politics these
days that the terms Euroskeptic, Europhobe and Europhile regularly
accompany mentions of public figures in news accounts.
</P>
<P>
   When Hague took the Conservative leadership two years ago, the
party abandoned Major's tolerant ``wait and see'' approach, and
adopted an absolute view that ruled out any consideration of
joining monetary union until at least the end of the next
Parliament, seven years from now.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show the British public resolutely against swapping their
currency for the euro, and the issue is one on which the Tories
hope to contest the next election and work their way back into
power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 1803EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7055 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKE     10-14 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPSULE REVIEWS OF MOVIES AND SERIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The Times of new or
noteworthy movies and film series playing this weekend in New York
City. (Star) denotes a highly recommended film or series. Ratings
and running times are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``AMERICAN BEAUTY,'' starring Kevin Spacey, Annette
Bening, Chris Cooper, Wes Bentley and Thora Birch. Written by Alan
Ball. Directed by Sam Mendes (R, 116 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   With heavenly finesse, Spacey plays a buttoned-down 42-year-old
suburbanite who flips his lid for a teen-age cheerleader. And he
never gets it back on. The midlife crisis motif is familiar, but
the stage director Sam Mendes brings terrific visual flair and dry
humor to this barbecuing of the bourgeoisie.
</P>
<P>
   All the actors display coolly expert timing, especially Ms.
Bening as the antihero's grasping wife. Although the story spreads
itself thin among many characters, the film coalesces for a
devastating finale (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``BOYS DON'T CRY,'' starring Hillary Swank and Chloe
Sevigny. Directed by Kimberley Pierce (R, 114 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   This stunning debut feature tells the strange and resonant story
of Brandon Teena, who despite being born Teena Brandon went on to
create a charismatic identity as a young man. Brandon's ultimately
wrenching tale may sound tabloid-ready, but on screen it turns into
Theodore Dreiser's idea of American tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   The film makes it hauntingly real and even tenderly romantic,
with the astonishing acting needed to make it work. One of the
year's best (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``DOUBLE JEOPARDY,'' starring Ashley Judd, Tommy Lee Jones and
Bruce Greenwood. Directed by Bruce Beresford (R, 106 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   In a touristy thriller that roams from the coastline of
Washington State to New Orleans' French Quarter, Ms. Judd plays a
woman who is free to kill her husband because she has already gone
to prison for the crime (see title). Not even she is beautiful
enough to get away with rote acting and a far-fetched plot, but she
perks up as her character becomes less of a victim.
</P>
<P>
   In this coed homage to ``The Fugitive,'' Jones is on hand as
another weathered sourpuss with a knack for barking orders.
Beresford directs so unremarkably that it takes a line like ``I
feel like I've grown in the last six years'' to signal the passage
of time (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``EARTH,'' starring Aamir Khan, Nandita Das, Rahul Khanna
and Maia Sethna. Directed by Deepa Mehta (not rated, 99 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   It is 1947, and India is about to explode into ethnic violence
as British colonial rule ends and the country is partitioned into
two nations, mostly Hindu India and mostly Muslim Pakistan. These
momentous changes are observed by Lenny (Ms. Sethna), the
8-year-old daughter of a well-to-do Parsi family in Lahore. As
Hindus, Muslims and Sikhs slaughter one another in the streets, old
friends become deadly enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Caught in the middle is Shanta (Ms. Das), Lenny's beautiful
Hindu nanny, who has two Muslim suitors. The movie's child's-eye
view somewhat mutes its dramatic sweep (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   ``GUINEVERE,'' starring Sarah Polley and Stephen Rea. Written
and directed by Audrey Wells (R, 104 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Polley shines as a shy, rebellious 21-year-old involved in
an affair with an older man. Escaping her chilly family, she moves
into the well-populated space beneath the wing of a bohemian
photographer, played with great charm by Rea.
</P>
<P>
   This coming-of-age film takes a knowing, intimate view of the
dynamics of such a relationship and watches its heroine blossom. So
does Ms. Polley, as a luminous, mysterious young actress capable of
exceptionally subtle shadings (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``HAPPY, TEXAS,'' starring Jeremy Northam, Steve Zahn and
William H. Macy. Directed by Mark Illsley (R, 96 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   The zany comedy follows two escaped convicts (Northam and Zahn)
who pose as a pair of gay pageant producers in a small Texas town
that is grooming its little girls for the Little Miss Squeezed
Pageant. Macy is poignant as the discreetly gay, doe-eyed sheriff
who shyly pursues Northam (who is only posing as gay). Zahn has his
amusing moments as an oaf improvising ludicrous dance routines.
</P>
<P>
   But the movie is so desperate to be liked that its satire is
risk-free and toothless, and its laughs widely scattered (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``JAKOB THE LIAR,'' starring Robin Williams, Alan Arkin, Liev
Schreiber and Armin Mueller-Stahl. Directed by Peter Kassovitz
(PG-13, 114 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   In a Holocaust story to make Roberto Benigni look like Primo
Levi, Williams plays a man who brightens life in a Polish ghetto
with imaginary good news about the imminent end of the war.
Surrounded by a strong supporting cast (with Arkin giving the
film's only genuinely funny performance), he again indulges that
unfortunate yen to play the clown who cried.
</P>
<P>
   The direction is sincere but sloppy. Watch the microphone make
repeated, unwelcome entrances from the top of the frame (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``JULIEN DONKEY-BOY,'' starring Ewen Bremner, Chloe Sevigny and
Werner Herzog. Directed by Harmony Korine (R, 94 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Working in accordance with the Danish set of directorial
strictures known as Dogma '95, the enfant-terrible director of
``Gummo'' finds creative ways to bend the rules. Inventively and
kinetically shot, this film about a schizophrenic is vastly more
interesting on its visual merits than for its hazy, indulgent
drama.
</P>
<P>
   As the ranting father of the title character, Herzog goes
enthusiastically over the top. The luminous Ms. Sevigny remains
Korine's secret weapon (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``THE LIMEY,'' starring Terence Stamp and Peter Fonda.
Directed by Steven Soderbergh (R, 89 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   From a director for whom the quirky stylistic exercise is
standard style, this is a handsome throwback to the salad days of
its two iconic stars. Stamp, in a stony, magnetic performance
punctuated by flashbacks to his early career, plays an ex-con
seeking revenge for the death of his daughter. He becomes the
nemesis of Fonda's slick Hollywood hipster, in another role that's
piquantly tailor-made.
</P>
<P>
   Soderbergh resurrects the lean, hard-boiled look of John
Boorman's ``Point Blank'' as he dissects and considers these two
tough customers from every conceivable perspective (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``LUCIE AUBRAC,'' starring Carole Bouquet and Daniel
Auteuil. Produced, written and directed by Claude Berri (R, 116
minutes).
</P>
<P>
   What lifts this taut World War II thriller based on a true story
above the ordinary are the impassioned performances of Ms. Bouquet
and Auteuil as Lucie and Raymond, a married couple who are fighters
in the French Resistance.
</P>
<P>
   When Raymond is arrested by the Nazis and convicted of war
crimes, Lucie conceives an outrageously audacious plan for his
escape. Ms. Bouquet and Auteuil are as romantically intense as
Bogey and Bergman in ``Casablanca,'' but here the woman is the one
who ends up doing the thinking for both of them (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``MUMFORD,'' starring Loren Dean, Hope Davis, Jason Lee,
Alfre Woodard, David Paymer and Mary McDonnell. Written and
directed by Lawrence Kasdan (R, 115 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   An immensely likable semi-screwball comedy from the director of
``The Big Chill,'' ``Mumford'' follows the adventures of an
engaging charlatan psychotherapist (Dean) fleeing a sleazy former
life, who names himself after the town (Mumford) in which he
settles and helps a lot of troubled people, even though he is
without credentials.
</P>
<P>
   His most endearing client ( Lee) is a warm, fuzzy billionaire
computer nerd who loves to skateboard but finds it's lonely at the
top. Mumford's moral ambiguity (he's both a hero and a fraud) keeps
this delightful Frank Capraesque fable of self-invention from
becoming too sappy (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   ``MYSTERY, ALASKA,'' starring Russell Crowe, Hank Azaria, Ryan
Northcott, Mary McCormack and Burt Reynolds. Directed by Jay Roach
(R, 119 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   The king of television drama, David E. Kelley, helped produce
and write the satirically edged meat-and-potatoes story of a
legendary ice hockey team in the small town of Mystery, Alaska,
that is persuaded to play the New York Rangers in a televised
exhibition match. With its skillfully interwoven personal dramas of
assorted townspeople, the movie is a convincingly likable portrait
of a modern pioneer community under siege from the media.
</P>
<P>
   But it begins to lose its punch when the story settles into the
all-too-familiar ``Rocky'' formula. It includes strong performances
by Crowe (as the town sheriff) and Reynolds (as an imperious local
judge) (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Star) ``RANDOM HEARTS,'' starring Harrison Ford and Kristin
Scott Thomas. Directed by Sydney Pollack (R, 131 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Pollack's characteristically solid, incisive direction has
become a throwback to the days of subtler movie storytelling. But
it still rivets attention during the first half of this
star-crossed romance, which tells of two people who meet after
their spouses die in the same plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   The plot becomes very thick indeed when it develops that the
dead spouses were having an affair, and the survivors fall into a
bittersweet relationship of their own. Ford is taciturnly forceful,
Ms. Scott Thomas a shade too familiar, as credulity-stretching
complications ensue (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``ROMANCE,'' starring Caroline Ducey, Sagamore Stevenin,
Francois Berleand and Rocco Siffredi. Written and directed by
Catherine Breillat (not rated, 93 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   A solemn, sexually graphic exploration of the nature of a
woman's need for male attention and erotic love, even if its
insights are already familiar to readers of Cosmopolitan and the
Marquis de Sade. And it's doubtful that the film's intellectual
aspects would command the same attention if its camera did not make
the actors' genitals as familiar as their faces.
</P>
<P>
   The carnal and cerebral erotica here have already achieved the
considerable feat of shocking France, but the film is often stilted
and methodical to the point of tediousness. It hovers between
passion and philosophical argument without often achieving Ms.
Breillat's ambition to fuse the two (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``THE SIXTH SENSE,'' starring Bruce Willis and Haley Joel
Osment. Written and directed by M. Night Shyamalan (PG-13, 107
minutes).
</P>
<P>
   What starts out as a horror movie about a troubled 8-year-old
boy (Osment) who claims to see dead people, and the child
psychologist (Willis) determined to cure him, eventually turns into
New Age mush (think ``What Dreams May Come'' and ``Simon Birch'').
</P>
<P>
   When you trace the plot backward after its big secret is
revealed, the story doesn't begin to add up. Willis gives his usual
smirking one-note performance. What empathy the movie generates
comes from Osment's intense portrayal of the tormented child
(Holden).
</P>
<P>
   ``STIR OF ECHOES,'' starring Kevin Bacon and Kathryn Erbe.
Directed by David Koepp (R, 99 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Another little boy talks to a ghost at the start of this
thriller, but it isn't an instant ``Sixth Sense'' sequel. Instead
it shows what happens when the boy's closed-minded father lets
himself be hypnotized and awakens to find himself receiving
otherworldly stimuli.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon gives a grippingly intense performance as a man terrified
by his new extrasensory powers. And Koepp conveys a potent sense of
what it means to unravel. Despite its strong, spooky start and
early momentum, the film winds up with too earthbound an
explanation for the havoc it unleashes (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   ``THREE KINGS,'' starring George Clooney, Mark Wahlberg and Ice
Cube. Written and directed by David O. Russell (R, 105 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   The prodigiously talented writer-director of ``Spanking the
Monkey'' and ``Flirting With Disaster'' has made a much more
ambitious film, with mixed results. His gimlet-eyed Persian Gulf
War film has a ``Catch-22'' absurdist edge, but it also has an
oversupply of visual affectations.
</P>
<P>
   Vertiginous music-video camera tricks jazz up the otherwise
straightforward story of American soldiers who have larcenous
designs on Saddam Hussein's captured gold and then develop
conscience pangs about their own roles in Iraq. There are many
clever peripheral touches, but there's something tamely
conventional at the film's core (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Film Series
</P>
<P>
   ``DREYER.'' In a career that spanned the 45 years from 1919 to
1964, Carl Theodor Dreyer made relatively few films. His fierce
artistic pride was legendary, and his conflicts with producers,
which led to prolonged inactivity, were frequent. Nor did he often
enjoy the favor of contemporary critics.
</P>
<P>
   But today Dreyer (1889-1968) ranks as a giant of cinema and the
foremost talent in the history of Danish filmmaking. This week, he
is the subject of a retrospective at the Film Forum, and 8 p.m.
Friday, 7 p.m. Saturday and 2 p.m. Sunday bring screenings of one
of his masterpieces.
</P>
<P>
   It is ``The Passion of Joan of Arc'' (1928), with a splendid
performance by the Corsican-born stage actress Renee Falconetti in
her only screen role. Filmed over a year and a half at enormous
cost, this intense drama, presented with a live piano
accompaniment, is drawn from the transcripts of the heresy trial of
the Maid of Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dreyer'' continues through Tuesday at Film Forum in Manhattan.
Tickets: $8.50; $4.50 for members. Screening schedule and
information: (212) 727-8110 (Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
