<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-PAROLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO CALLS FOR NEW APPROACH TO PAROLEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno on Thursday called for
a new system for monitoring convicts paroled from state and local
prisons that would require the involvement of local law
enforcement, businesses, churches, counselors and neighborhood
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too often, offenders leave prison and return to the community
without supervision, without jobs, without housing,'' Reno said at
her weekly news conference.
</P>
<P>
   She said most of the nearly 500,000 people paroled each year
``quickly fall back into their old patterns'' of drug use and gang
activity.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent this from happening, Reno said the Department of
Justice is working with local and state authorities to set up
so-called ``re-entry courts'' that would supervise parolees who
return to their communities.
</P>
<P>
   She said the re-entry courts could be integrated into
already-existing courts. In this scenario, parolees would report on
a monthly basis to the judges who originally sentenced them to
prison. The judges, with help from local law enforcement officials
and community organizations, would construct a plan to reintegrate
the offenders back into the community and then present the plan to
the parolees to follow.
</P>
<P>
   If state judges were too busy to handle the added burden, the
re-entry courts could be headed by such substitutes as retired
judges, magistrates or administrative judges. The substitute judges
would still have the authority to punish or reward the parolees,
the Justice Department said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Work with us, stay clean, stay out of trouble, get a job, and
we will help you in that effort,'' Reno said. ``But if you come
back testing positive for drugs, if you commit further crime, if
you violate the conditions of your release, you're going to face a
more serious punishment every step of the way.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the punishment could be spending a night in jail,
performing community service or, in extreme cases, being sent back
to prison.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general said the re-entry courts would not be used
with federal parolees because state courts would be in a better
position to work with local organizations and law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said the re-entry court proposal was presented to thousands
of state and local officials last week to review. She said the
Justice Department would chose a dozen cities over the next year to
develop ways to implement and fund the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crime has been dropping for years, but if we can find a way to
keep people from returning to prison again and again, you'll see
America's crime rate drop like never before,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
