<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT EASY BEING A SCHMERD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes it can get lonely being a schmerd.
</P>
<P>
   And that makes it really gratifying when you meet another
schmerd who doesn't mind showing his or her tendencies to the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where'd you find that?'' asked the cashier at one of the
larger southwest Fort Worth supermarkets. She was a small,
beyond-middle-aged woman with grayish-blond hair and sky-blue eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over near the lawn stuff,'' I said. ``I guess some of my
neighbors will really think I'm a schmerd if they see me sprinkling
it on my lawn.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's a schmerd?''
</P>
<P>
   I explained to her that it was a word I had coined for people
like me who take offense at some of the things that a lot of other
people think quite all right, and even neighborly correct, to do.
</P>
<P>
   The stuff she was asking about was pet repellent in powdered
form.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one of those strange folks who detests having dog walkers
bring their four-legged friends around to discharge on my lawn,'' I
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me, too,'' she said. ``Nothing makes me madder than to have to
step in or step around dog droppings when I'm trying to cut my
grass.''
</P>
<P>
   She said it loudly, as though she wanted everyone in the store
to hear her.
</P>
<P>
   The woman in the next line with the huge bag of dry canine
morsels stared daggers at us. Of course, that could been just my
imagination. Being a schmerd can make you borderline paranoid.
</P>
<P>
   You feel kind of guilty because you know that if a dog's got to
go, it's got to go. It's just doing what comes naturally.
</P>
<P>
   And it bothers you some to realize that the dog walkers think
you're unreasonable for objecting to it. And they wonder why you
don't like dogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do like dogs,'' I told the cashier. ``Over the years some of
my best friends have been border collies and Irish setters, truly
noble beasts. I have a plaque on my wall from the humane society
for my work on behalf of animals.''
</P>
<P>
   But I explained to her that when I owned dogs, I either lived
somewhere with ample open space to allow them to heed nature's call
without decorating someone else's lawn, or I confined their bowel
movements to my own property and cleaned up after them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't own a dog now because I don't have the time or the
inclination anymore to handle the refuse disposal problems they
create. I'm pro-pet; I'm just anti-poo,'' I told the cashier.
</P>
<P>
   She agreed wholeheartedly and said she thought ``it ought to be
against the law, if it isn't,'' for people to take their dogs
around to defecate in other people's yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make them do their business in their own yards,'' she said.
And she pointed out that she has made her feelings on the subject
known to several of the regular dog walkers on her street, up close
and personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them now carry little plastic bags and scoops for the
poop with them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   I left the supermarket feeling a little less lonely, knowing
that there must be other schmerds out there fighting the same
lonely battle.
</P>
<P>
   And if there are more schmerds like that around, I reasoned,
there must also be some who share my other pet peeve: visits by
Halloween trick-or-treaters.
</P>
<P>
   There is no lonelier time of the year for this schmerd than
Allhallows Eve, when the little spooks, witches and goblins gambol
from door to door demanding unhealthful booty.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I'm not anti-child. I used to have one. And some of my best
friends over the years have been children. I was once one myself,
for heaven's sake. I'm just anti-Halloween _ both the commercial
vulgarity of it and what I see as its more sinister implications.
</P>
<P>
   It may astonish some to hear thaton like me, of the
fiendish liberal persuasion, harbors serious religious reservations
about something so seemingly innocent, nonthreatening and enjoyable
as Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, I do. And I am aware that I risk ruining my
reputation as a sober cynic by admitting that I believe in the
existence of pervasive and infectious evil in this realm of being.
</P>
<P>
   It is my view that parents who glorify Halloween are exposing
their children to that evil and providing gateways for the
intrusion of demonic influences into human affairs.
</P>
<P>
   But that's just this schmerd's take on it. I'm not calling for
the abolishment of Halloween. I could be wrong. Maybe Halloween is
just harmless fun, and not (as I see it) satanic revelry.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, I'll keep my lights out as usual until the dark
and shadowy figures stop passing and the living dead return to
their graves.
</P>
<P>
   Then I'll go outside with my flashlight and see if any of them
brought their dogs to poop on my lawn.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can contact him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
