NYT-10-14-99 1811EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7070 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FIGHTCLUB-MEN-TEX     10-14 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIGHTCLUB-MEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FIGHT CLUB' IS ANOTHER IN A RECENT CROP OF WHITE-MALE ANGST
MOVIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I haven't read ``Stiffed,'' Susan Faludi's new book about ``the
betrayal of the American male.'' I suspect that I'm too busy being
betrayed to plow through her 608-page book, although judging from a
Newsweek excerpt, I'm not the type of guy Faludi's talking about.
She's talking about guys set adrift by corporate culture and lack
of control in their jobs. And yeah, I feel a little of that, but as
someone who writes about entertainment for a living, I have a job
that many people would envy. No, Faludi is writing about guys like
Lester Burnham and Tyler Durden.
</P>
<P>
   Lester is the hero of the celebrated movie ``American Beauty,''
a guy stuck in his beautiful suburban house with a shrill wife, an
alienated daughter and a well-paid but desensitizing job. His
sudden crush on a teen-ager leads him to re-evaluate his life and
take matters into his own hands. Tyler is a key figure in ``Fight
Club;'' he's an influence on the nameless narrator, who, like
Lester, lives well but without meaning and has a desensitizing job.
The narrator's so desensitized that he and Tyler form Fight Club,
in which men beat one another to bloody pulps just so that they can
feel something, even if it's abject pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty'' and ``Fight Club'' _ and an earlier 1999
movie, ``Office Space,'' recently released on video _ share a scene
in which the protagonist finally decides that he's had it with the
job that's making him feel adrift. In each movie, the guy unloads
on his boss, telling him what he really thinks. These scenes are
cathartic for the men _ and the women _ in the audience, because
haven't most of us wanted to speak our minds to a supervisor,
putting our jobs at risk, at least once in our lives? They're
cathartic because we're too smart to do that; most of us value our
paychecks too much to make such a dumb move. By watching somebody
else do it, we can take some vicarious pleasure and say, ``I've
always wanted to say that.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all the fuss that these movies are causing _ and
``American Beauty'' and ``Fight Club'' are certainly fuss-worthy
movies _ they take an easy way out when it comes to giving the boss
what for. ``Fight Club's'' hero and ``Beauty's'' Lester, portrayed
respectively by Edward Norton and Kevin Spacey in performances that
should fill the first two spots on this year's Oscar ballot, both
have something on their bosses, a bit of blackmail material that
allows them to pull off their stunts without suffering the
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beauty'' and ``Fight Club'' are both beautifully written,
excellently directed and wonderfully acted, but as with with so
many movies, their originality comes not in their content but in
their execution. In their white-male angst, they echo dozens of
movies over the years, most notably ``Happiness'' (in the case of
``Beauty'') and 1992's underrated ``Falling Down'' (in ``Fight
Club's'' case). In ``Falling Down,'' Michael Douglas plays a
defense contractor who exits his car during a traffic jam and
begins attacking head-on the things that bother him; he doesn't
even confront his boss, much less blackmail him, but simply makes a
snap decision to change his life. At the end of the movie, he makes
a white-guy complaint that Faludi must love, plaintively asking a
cop who's tracked him down, ``I'm the bad guy?''
</P>
<P>
   But ``Falling'' wasn't original, either; like ``American
Beauty'' and ``Fight Club,'' it's a more mature, darker, serious
take on that staple of the late '70s and early '80s, the slob
comedy. The difference between the '90s characters and slob
characters played by Bill Murray and John Belushi is that the new
guys are rebelling against jobs that at least provide a chance at
affluence; in a way, they're the guys whom Murray and Rodney
Dangerfield irritated so well in ``Caddyshack.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody ever quit a job better than Murray did in ``Stripes,'' in
which he began the movie as a cabdriver who deals with an annoying
passenger by simply stranding the car on a bridge, getting out and
tossing his keys in the river. No boss, no blackmail, not even a
two-week notice. Murray has played both ends of the spectrum; in
this year's ``Rushmore,'' he's an industrialist who rebels against
a life he hates by getting into a romantic rivalry with a
particularly obnoxious teen-ager. He grew into a guy his younger
characters never wanted to be.
</P>
<P>
   In the Newsweek excerpt, Faludi talks a lot about how men in the
World War II generation and before had more control, how their
masculinity was more appreciated. But she discusses her theory of a
'90s lack of direction as if it were a new thing, as if we were
responding to consumer culture and a corporation-ruled world.
``American Beauty'' and ``Fight Club'' argue that we can fight
back, but that even if we do, the victories will be small.
</P>
<P>
   Let's not forget that ``American Beauty'' comes from a
subsidiary of Disney, a corporation so ubiquitous that it's hard to
go through a day without somehow encountering it, and that ``Fight
Club'' comes from 20th Century Fox, a studio owned by Rupert
Murdoch, who can afford to laugh at the movie's anarchy. We'll make
these movies hits, and we'll respond to other movies in which
someone flips the bird at authority. And then, the next day, we'll
amiably talk about 'em with our bosses.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7278, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
