<HEADER>
A7071 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-HOUSTON-ART-2ndTake-T     10-14 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSTON-ART-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
HOUSTON: reflects that.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a result, the arts lover visiting Houston has perhaps a wider
range of things to choose from than does a visitor to any other
city in the Southwest. On a recent weekend visit, for instance, it
was possible to spend the morning seeing the works of Mexican
superstar artist Diego Rivera (in a touring exhibit at the fine
arts museum), to walk a few blocks to take in the devastating
depiction of Nazi terrorism at the Holocaust Museum of Houston,
then to detour south of downtown to marvel at the Orange Show, a
multilevel folk-art sculpture festooned with tiles, flags and
bright paint, where every visit can be capped off with a glass of
orange juice in the gift shop. That evening, choices included the
ballet's presentation of ``The Merry Widow'' or the Alley's
production of Arthur Miller's ``A View From the Bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Both of those were playing in the downtown theater district, a
17-block area that houses several theaters encompassing 10,000
seats _ the most in a single area outside Manhattan. And although
Houston has long had a thriving performing arts community _ its
opera is noted for mounting such avant-garde, and acclaimed,
productions as ``Nixon in China'' and ``Harvey Milk,'' and the
Alley regularly produces world premieres such as last season's
``The Civil War'' by Frank Wildhorn _ it has boomed over the past
decade or so.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that stems from the recent downtown building spree. The
Wortham Center, home to the ballet and the opera, came first, in
1987, joining the 1969-era Alley Theatre across the street and the
nearby Jesse H. Jones Hall, where the symphony performs. This year,
ground was broken on the Hobby Center for the Performing Arts,
which will be built on the site of the old Music Hall and will host
musical theater and other performances. (It's scheduled to open in
2002.)
</P>
<P>
   Barry Mandel, who left a career in business to become the
director of the Theater District Association six months ago, and
his colleagues have more plans. They're embarking on a promotional
campaign tying theater productions to deals at area hotels and
restaurants, for instance. And this winter, Mandel wants to build
an outdoor ice rink on the plaza outside the Wortham Center,
perhaps even staging an ice-skating version of ``The Nutcracker''
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm making it my own version of Rockefeller Center,'' Mandel
says. ``I want to raise the profile of the theater district and let
people know the arts are not just this rich person's thing _
they're accessible to everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   If Houston has a patron saint of arts accessibility, it would be
the late Dominique de Menil, who, with husband John, was the
namesake for the Menil Collection.
</P>
<P>
   Dominique de Menil opened the museum in 1987 to share with the
public the couple's exhaustive collection of surrealist art
(masterpieces by Salvador Dali and Max Ernst, among others) and
antiquities such as African masks, wooden seal clubs intricately
carved by Canada's indigenous tribes, and hand-woven textiles from
the Oceanic region. The campus also includes a gallery devoted to
American artist Cy Twombly and the de Menil-sponsored Rothko
Chapel, with abstract paintings by Mark Rothko. Admission to all is
free.
</P>
<P>
   The last addition to the de Menil legacy has one of the most
interesting stories: The Byzantine Fresco Chapel Museum houses
13th-century frescoes that Dominique de Menil literally ransomed
from thieves who had removed them from a Cyprus church and chopped
them into pieces. After she negotiated their purchase, she had them
painstakingly restored in London (it took two years) and then had
her architect son design an understated chapel in which to display
them.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like the plot line from a movie-of-the-week. But then
again, true to her adopted hometown, Dominique de Menil loved art
in all its forms. She was one of the first financial backers of
another acclaimed Houston institution _ the Orange Show.
</P>
<P>
   (Patricia Rodriguez is travel editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7571, or e-mail:
prodriguez(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
