<HEADLINE>
THE ART LOVERS' GUIDE TO HOUSTON
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by HOUSTON-ART-SKED and HOUSTON-ART-HOW) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ ``You can take your shoes off if you want,'' the
white-haired volunteer called after us graciously as we sat in the
lobby at the Menil Collection, studying the map she'd just handed
us, trying to figure out which gallery to head to first.
</P>
<P>
   We looked up, sure she was being sarcastic. I mean, it wasn't as
if we were entering the jumpy tent at a Discovery Zone. We were in
the Menil, one of the premier art destinations of not just Houston
but the entire Southwest, a priceless repository of works by
Picasso and Warhol and Dali, and of antiquities from all over the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``People do it all the time,'' she continued, nodding and
smiling. ``Go ahead, make yourself comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Um, thanks, we think we'll wear our shoes (sensible walking
ones, of course). But we liked the message: Houston may be a city
with Serious Art, but it doesn't take itself all that seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the Museum of Fine Arts, Houston will unveil a
192,000-square-foot, $83 million addition in March that will make
it the sixth-largest museum in the nation. But this is also a town
that counts as one of its beloved art attractions the Orange Show,
a bizarre folk-art salute to the orange, built more than 25 years
by a postal carrier out of odds and ends largely picked up on his
route.
</P>
<P>
   And the downtown theater district likes to call itself the
biggest such district outside Manhattan, and to tout its world
premieres and its Tony-Award-winning Alley Theatre. But the city is
equally proud of what's probably its biggest annual production, the
Art Car parade, where 200,000 people show up every spring to watch
cars decorated like giant bunnies and cows and red high-heeled
pumps roll down the streets.
</P>
<P>
   As Bryan Taylor, education curator at the 2-year-old Art Car
Museum, puts it: ``There's something that's not quite right about
this city.''
</P>
<P>
   He is only partly joking. And that is a big part of Houston's
charm.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   To those who don't know any different, both from within Texas
and from elsewhere, Houston is often lumped in with Dallas _ just
another big, sprawling Sun Belt city built from oil money and
corporate interests. And the two do have their similarities, from
shiny skyscraper-filled downtowns to obsessions with big hair and
big sports.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, however, has been a different kind of place from the
beginning. In 1836, to lure prospective settlers, a pair of
scheming brothers ran a newspaper ad touting the business district
and busy port. Unfortunately, these things did not exist. People
showed up anyway, and the city started growing _ fast and in all
directions. (To this day, Houston has no zoning laws.)
</P>
<P>
   The people who built Houston wanted it to be a world-class city,
and its arts scene has developed accordingly. Houston is one of the
few U.S. cities with full-season resident companies in all the
major performing disciplines: ballet, opera, symphony and theater.
It is home to dozens of museums, including the fine arts museum and
the Menil, which houses perhaps the world's finest collection of
surrealist art, and more than 50 galleries.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because the city grew out of a giant con game, though,
its arts scene has always had its lighter side. Take, for instance,
the atmosphere at the Contemporary Arts Museum during the '70s,
when the hippie artists' commune known as The Ant Farm set up shop
in the parking lot, and one notorious exhibit involving the Kilgore
Rangerettes and many loaves of painted bread supposedly devolved
into a bread-throwing riot.
</P>
<P>
   To put it in a North Texas perspective: If someone in Dallas
covered a house in beer cans, the neighbors would make sure it got
torn down. In Houston, the Convention and Visitors Bureau touts it
as a tourist destination. (The so-called Beer Can House, an
aluminum-covered marvel at 222 Malone, is even included on some
tour companies' itineraries.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The folk art tradition here is so strong; it's kind of a part
of the city's identity, and people were doing it for years, before
there was a recognition of folk art,'' explains Dr. Peter Marzio,
the director of the Museum of Fine Arts, Houston, an encyclopedic
museum that includes respected collections of photography and
American decorative arts, plus pre-Columbian, African and
20th-century art.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all just part of the individual character of the city.
Houston is the freest and most individualistic society I've ever
lived in, and I think the art here reflects that.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
