<SLUG> BC-HOUSTON-ART-HOW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE TO STAY, EAT
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies HOUSTON-ART) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOTELS:
</P>
<P>
   Houston has the standard hotel chains, but these might be
especially suited to the arts tourist:
</P>
<P>
   The Lancaster: Perfect for theater buffs, this luxurious
downtown hotel is steps away from the Alley Theatre, the Wortham
Center and the Bayou Bend, a newish, multilevel urban mall that
features a sushi bar, Italian restaurant and six-screen multiplex.
Weekend rates, $130-$275. 701 Texas St., (713) 228-9500
</P>
<P>
   The Warwick: Though less than 80 years old, it's Houston's most
historic hotel, as downtown's Rice Hotel was turned into lofts and
the Shamrock got the wrecking ball. Finishing touches are being put
on a multimillion-dollar renovation that retained the hotel's
European character but lightened and modernized the interior. Right
across the street from the Museum of Fine Arts, Houston. Weekend
rates, $119-194. 5701 S. Main St., (713) 526-1991
</P>
<P>
   La Colombe d'Or: An ultra-small (just six suites),
ultraluxurious hotel housed in a former oil baron's mansion on
trendy Montrose, close to museums and nightlife. Weekend rates,
$195-$575. 3401 Montrose Blvd., (713) 524-7999
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   DINING:
</P>
<P>
   If you're doing the museums, there are plenty of breakfast and
lunch spots nearby, especially on Montrose, Westheimer and Kirby.
</P>
<P>
   For breakfast, we tried a friend's recommendation, Empire Cafe,
1732 Westheimer Road, (713) 528-5282; try the frittatas or the
huge, gooey cinnamon rolls. We liked the fish tacos and the fresh
salsas at casual-but-hip Taco Milagro, 2555 Kirby Drive at
Westheimer Road, (713) 522-1999; it's also a reasonably priced way
to sample the food of Houston's premier chef Robert del Grande, of
the justifiably acclaimed Cafe Annie. Urbana, 3407 Montrose Blvd.,
(713) 521-1086, has a sleek patio on which to enjoy its
Southwestern-flavored dishes, such as potato-and-poblano flautas
and barbecued Gulf shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's downtown has boomed with restaurants in the past five
years, but many theater patrons still head straight for Clive's,
517 Louisiana St., (713) 224-4438, for steaks, seafood and a great
wine list. For Mediterranean fare and live jazz, try the local
incarnation of a Dallas favorite, Sambuca, 909 Texas St., (713)
224-5299. For Spanish-style tapas and paella, there's Solero, 910
Prairie St., (713) 227-2665.
</P>
<P>
   After-theater choices downtown include Cabo, the mothership for
downtown Fort Worth's bar/restaurant of the same name. The original
one here is a raucous hangout with a lively second-story patio;
it's at 419 Travis St., (713) 225-2060. The new hip spot is The
Mercury Room, a sleek club with live music at 1008 Prairie St.;
(713) 225-6372), but others prefer the more established Spy (112
Travis St., (713) 228-0007).
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
