<HEADER>
A7074 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOK-NOTES15-COX     10-14 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Waiting' is worthwhile for award finalist Jin
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whenever a new group of writing students enrolls in his class,
Ha Jin tells them that being a writer ``has nothing to do with
glory or fame.''
</P>
<P>
   He may want to reconsider those words. Two years after winning
two prestigious literary prizes, the Emory professor has been named
a National Book Award finalist for his new novel, ``Waiting''
(Pantheon Books, $24), the story of a married doctor who falls in
love with a nurse during China's Cultural Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased,'' Jin said after hearing the news. ``There's
a lot of anxiety in writing a book. You don't know how well it will
do. Now at least it will have a longer life.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the 43-year-old native of China won the Ernest
Hemingway Foundation/PEN Award for his debut story collection,
``Ocean of Words: Army Stories,'' and the Flannery O'Connor Award
for ``Under the Red Flag.'' The first book deals with Jin's stint
in the People's Army; the second describes life during the Cultural
Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Other fiction finalists are Andrew Dubus III (``House of Sand
and Fog''); Kent Haruf (``Plainsong''); Patricia Henley
(``Hummingbird House''); and Jean Thompson (``Who Do You Love?'').
</P>
<P>
   Nonfiction finalists are Natalie Angier (``Woman: An Intimate
Geography''); Mark Bowden (``Black Hawk Down: A Story of Modern
War''); John W. Dower (``Embracing Defeat: Japan in the Wake of
World War II''); John Phillip Santos (``Places Left Unfinished at
the Time of Creation''); and Judith Thurman (``Secrets of the
Flesh: A Life of Colette'').
</P>
<P>
   Finalists in the Young People's Literature category are Laurie
Halse Anderson (``Speak''); Louise Erdrich (``The Birchbark
House''); Kimberly Willis Holt (``When Zachary Beaver Came to
Town''); Polly Horvath (``The Trolls''); and Walter Dean Myers
(``Monster'').
</P>
<P>
   Poetry finalists are Ai (``Vice: New and Selected Poems'');
Louise Gluck (``Vita Nova: Poems''); Clarence Major
(``Configurations: New &AMP; Selected Poems 1958-1998''); Sherod Santos
(``The Pilot Star Elegies''); and C.K. Williams (``Repair'').
</P>
<P>
   Winners will be announced Nov. 17 in New York at a ceremony in
which Oprah Winfrey will receive an award for her contribution to
reading and books. Steve Martin will act as emcee.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  They've got mail: Long before the Internet and e-mail, people
lamented the decline of correspondence. In a note to his son in
1900, Joel Chandler Harris wrote: ``People no longer write letters.
Lacking the leisure, and, for the most part, the ability, they
dictate dispatches, and scribble messages. When you are in the
humor, you should take a peep at some of the letters written by
people who lived long ago.''
</P>
<P>
   To paraphrase Mark Twain, rumors of the death of letter writing
are greatly exaggerated. Just ask Lisa Grunwald and Stephen J.
Adler. In their new book, ``Letters of the Century'' (Dial Press,
$35), the husband-and-wife team sifted through more than half a
million letters to find 412 that reflect the events and trends of
the past 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a real treasure hunt,'' Grunwald said in a telephone
interview from New York. ``We spent a lot of time on the Internet
and in libraries. We didn't want to do a book about letters; we
wanted to do a book about the 20th century. Letters are what
history sounds like when it is still part of everyday life.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all the letters are historically significant. Some are
simply fun to read, such as Groucho Marx's letters to lawyers at
Warner Bros. who threatened to sue him over the use of the word
``Casablanca'' in ``A Night in Casablanca.'' In one response Marx
writes, ``I am sure the average movie fan could learn in time to
distinguish between Ingrid Bergman and Harpo. I don't know whether
I could, but I certainly would like to try.''
</P>
<P>
   Others include bank robber Clyde Barrow's letter to Henry Ford
telling him ``what a dandy car you make. For sustained speed and
freedom from trouble the Ford has got every other car skinned.''
</P>
<P>
   Letters in general have diminished in number and eloquence, but
Grunwald predicts that the Internet will save the art of letter
writing. ``When I write an e-mail, it's the real thing. And one of
my friends writes such eloquent e-mails, I print them out and save
them. I don't think the Internet has hurt letter writing. It's
taken away from telephoning, and that's just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More award winners: ``A Clashing of the Soul'' by Emory
professor Leroy Davis and ``Colorblind Injustice'' by Caltech
professor J. Morgan Kousser are the 1999 winners of the Lillian
Smith Book Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' book traces the life of John Hope, the first
African-American president of Morehouse College and Atlanta
University, and the problems of black higher education in the early
20th century. Kousser's study examines minority voting rights.
</P>
<P>
   Presented by the Southern Regional Council, the awards honor the
late Georgia writer Lillian Smith, author of ``Strange Fruit'' and
other books that dealt with race and sex before they were generally
permissible topics in the South.
</P>
<P>
   The awards will be presented at a noon luncheon Nov. 6 at the
Sheraton Colony Square, 14th and Peachtree streets in Midtown.
Information: 404-522-8764, Ext. 24.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
