<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-GLYNN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Book recalls WWII scare on Ga. coast
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Long before Tom Brokaw's best seller ``The Greatest
Generation'' recorded memories of Americans during World War II,
Sonja Kinard set out with her sister, Thora Kimsey, to record the
same kind of slice of life, focusing on what then was the tiny port
town of Brunswick in South Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   They found that, for many residents of coastal Georgia, World
War II really started on April 8, 1942. The 66-year-old Kinard
herself remembers: Shivering survivors of two U.S. merchant ships
sunk just off the Georgia coast early that morning were huddled on
a St. Simons Island boat dock. Some were burned. All were
oil-blackened. St. Simons and nearby Brunswick were in shock,
afraid that the Germans who had torpedoed the ships would invade at
any moment.
</P>
<P>
   The sisters, both originally from the Brunswick area, share
recollections in a new book, ``Memories From The Marshes of Glynn:
World War II,'' published with the support of Atlanta's Callanwolde
Fine Arts Center. Kinard and Kimsey, who died several months ago,
contacted many friends and coastal residents, whose memories paint
a vivid picture of small-town Georgia in crisis.
</P>
<P>
   For example, their brother, Olaf H. Olsen Jr., recalls that
their father, Olaf Olsen, was the first to reach survivors who had
manned lifeboats, bringing 54 ashore. The senior Olsen, the skipper
of a yacht owned by Coca-Cola magnate Asa Candler, was alerted to
the sinkings when a small private plane whose pilot had spotted the
burning ships dropped a note, attached to a wrench, into his yard.
</P>
<P>
   The book contains dozens of poignant accounts of Glynn County
residents who recount their memories of those days when America
seemed on the verge of losing the war. It even contains an account
of an interview with Kapitan Reinhard Hardegan, the skipper of the
submarine that sank the two ships, and many others, along the
coast.
</P>
<P>
   Kinard and many of those whose memories fill the book will be on
hand at 2 p.m. Sunday at Callanwolde, when the book will be
unveiled amid displays of World War II memorabilia, a life-size
model of a USO canteen and 1940s music. The event is open to the
public. The book should be available soon at local bookstores, as
well as at Callanwolde, for $36.50.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hendrick writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
