<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern festivals
 &HT;    By Helen Holzer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Highlands, N.C. _ Highlands Own Craft Show offers a wide
assortment of crafts and specialty foods. The free event on
Saturday is at Highlands Recreation Park. 828-526-5246.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dallas, Ga. _ The Pickett's Mill Battlefield State Historic
Site provides the backdrop Friday and Saturday for a re-enactment
of the Battle of Pickett's Mill. 770-443-7850.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  High Shoals, Ga. _ ``The Real Tara'' at the Casulon Plantation
Antebellum Festival offers Southern belles giving guided home and
garden tours, wagon rides, country cooking, country music, Native
American crafts, a classic car show, children's activities and
environmental displays. Saturday's festival is off Ga. 186 between
High Shoals and Good Hope. 706-769-2599.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Calhoun, Ga. _ New Echota State Historic Site hosts Frontier
Day on Saturday. A celebration of early Cherokee culture, the event
offers demonstrations such as basketmaking, hide tanning,
blacksmithing and weaving. 706-624-1321.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Live Oak, Fla. _ The third annual MagnoliaFest Friday-Sunday
at the Spirit of the Suwannee Music Park features more than 20
folk-rock, jam-rock and bluegrass acts. Among the scheduled
performers: String Cheese Incident, Donna the Buffalo, Peter Rowan
and Vassar Clements, It's a Beautiful Day and Atlanta-based groups
Blueground Undergrass and Day by the River. Children's
entertainment, too. 904-249-7990 or www.magmusic.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Euharlee, Ga. _ A Civil War encampment, arts and crafts,
museum and historic town tours, entertainment and children's
activities are featured at the Covered Bridge Festival,
Friday-Sunday, 8 miles southwest of Cartersville. 770-386-1542.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Georgetown, S.C. _ The Georgetown Wooden Boat Exhibit on
Saturday features displays of more than 60 vessels, from kayaks to
60-foot yachts. Visitors can talk to wooden boat craftsmen,
manufacturers and owners about building techniques and materials.
Events include the International Wooden Boat Challenge, with teams
competing in boating and building categories. 1-877-285-3888.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dahlonega, Ga. _ Pan for gold, take gold mine tours and watch
a liar's contest at the annual Gold Rush Days Saturday-Sunday. And
there will be more than 300 arts and crafts booths, clogging,
bluegrass music and country cooking. 706-864-3711.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Clearwater, Fla. _ Appearing Thursday-Sunday at the 20th
annual Clearwater Jazz Holiday, a free event at Coachman Park, are
Tito Puente, Nnenna Freelon, Jason Marsalis, Etta Jones and Spyro
Gyra. 1-877-352-8224 or www.FloridasBeach
</P>
<P>
   .com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Perry, Ga. _ At the Mossy Creek Barnyard Festival,
Saturday-Sunday, craftsmen will demonstrate how to build and play
dulcimers, weave hammocks, build homemade fishing rods and split
oak for baskets. Performers include the Foxfire Boys Band. Also,
hayrides, storytelling and country cuisine. 912-922-8265.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rome, Ga. _ Guided bus tours of the northwest Georgia city's
downtown area Saturday-Sunday. Besides touring the 25-acre Myrtle
Hill Cemetery, guests will see historic sites such as the Masonic
Temple and the DeSoto Theatre. Rome also hosts the Chiaha Harvest
Fair in Heritage Park Saturday-Sunday. 1-800-444-1834.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Whitwell, Tenn. _ Ketner's Mill Country Fair, Saturday-Sunday
on the grounds of Ketner's Mill in the Sequatchie Valley, features
displays and demonstrations by more than 170 craftsmen. Regional
dishes and a petting zoo, too. 423-821-3238.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bell Buckle, Tenn. _ The 23rd annual Webb School Craft &AMP; Art
Show Saturday-Sunday, features works by 100 artists and craftsmen.
Visitors can nosh on German sausages, fried pies, hamburgers and
international favorites. 615-377-9535.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gatlinburg, Tenn. _ The Gatlinburg Craftsmen's Fair through
Oct. 24 features works by 150 craftsmen working in such traditional
art forms as quilting, woodcarving, pottery, broom and dulcimer
making, candle dipping and metal work. 423-436-7479 or
www.craftsmenfair.com.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Holzer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
