<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    At Black Rock Mountain park, forget miniature golf and enjoy the
grandeur
 &HT;    By Clint Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNTAIN CITY, Ga. _ Black Rock Mountain State Park is one of
the first places in Georgia that autumn visits. Located north of
Clayton not far from the North Carolina border, the 1,800-acre
parcel of mountaintops is Georgia's highest state park. The summit
of Black Rock Mountain is 3,640 feet above sea level, and most
overnight visitors who camp out or rent a cabin sleep above 3,000
feet.
</P>
<P>
   Even with autumn just under way, hints of the fall colors to
come can be seen across the park. As the trees begin to lose their
leaves, towering oaks drop acorns by the thousands. They fall like
dark brown hailstones, bouncing off the picnic table, the roof of
our tent and, once or twice, my head. This rain of acorns is good,
though: They provide food for a variety of wildlife, including
squirrels, deer and black bears.
</P>
<P>
   During a fathers-and-sons expedition, the acorn caps provide
amusement for two boys, ages 8 and 9. If you hold the tan top
between your thumbs just so and blow, the boys learn, it makes a
loud, shrill whistle. So much for a tranquil wilderness experience.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the park is big enough that the whistling doesn't
disturb anyone but me. Our walk-in campsite _ one of 11 tents-only
spots _ is a fair piece from another site. We can see the light
from their campfire and little else. The 10 miles of trail that
wind through the highlands also provide some solitude, although the
trailhead parking lot is usually jammed.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular trail, and the one most suitable for whistling
8- and 9-year-olds, is the Tennessee Rock Trail, a 2.2-mile loop.
</P>
<P>
   The James Edmonds Trail, a strenuous 7.2-mile route, provides
access to four back-country campsites designed for backpackers. The
back-country sites, says Anthony Lampros, the park superintendent,
``are real popular and becoming more and more so.''
</P>
<P>
   The sites, two of which opened last spring, include fire rings,
benches ``and a whole lot of real estate between you and your
neighbor,'' Lampros says.
</P>
<P>
   The back-country sites fit well with the management philosophy
of the park. Just 5 percent of the property is developed and,
unlike some state parks, there is no beach, no miniature golf
course. While there's a 17-acre fishing lake, it isn't the
centerpiece. In fact, you must drive out of the main park entrance
to get to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't entertain you,'' Lampros says. ``The big attraction
here is nature and scenery.''
</P>
<P>
   And the views. Bring your binoculars, because this mountaintop
park offers dozens of stunning vistas across the southern
Appalachians. Ridge lines running through North Carolina and South
Carolina are always part of the skyline here. Haze-free days mean
views of Mount LaConte and Clingman's Dome, landmarks of Great
Smoky Mountains National Park, more than 50 miles away in
Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can see tall buildings in Greenville, S.C. (58 miles away),
when it is real clear,'' Lampros says.
</P>
<P>
   Wooden deck overlooks along the roads and trails winding through
the park capitalize on the vistas. Park literature rates the view
from each of the 10 cabins _ cabins numbered 3, 4 and 6 are rated
excellent. Each cabin has cable television and a fireplace or wood
stove. Everything is provided expect food and firewood.
</P>
<P>
   The park, sadly, is also a good place to see the effects of the
drought gripping northeast Georgia, where rainfall for the year is
running about 20 inches below normal. Ferns covering the dark
forest floor are brown and brittle. Black leaves on the massive
rhododendrons are evidence of stress from the dry spell. Ada-Hi
Falls, the payoff at the end of a steep, quarter-mile trail, is
little more than a trickle. The drought has dried up springs and
slowed the flow of wells that provide water for the park. Two of
the three comfort stations that offer flush toilets and showers for
campers have been closed.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend will offer visitors something for the ears as well
as the eyes. The Georgia Mountain Fall Festival is under way at the
Georgia Mountains Fairgrounds in nearby Hiawassee, with the State
Fiddler's Convention coming up Friday and Saturday. Members of the
bluegrass gospel band Never Fade camp at the state park when
they're in the area for concerts and contests, and they usually
make their way to the porch of the campground trading post after
supper to make a little music.
</P>
<P>
   Find yourself an acorn cap and join in.
</P>
<P>
   If You Go
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Black Rock Mountain State Park is just off U.S.
441 and is less than a two-hour drive from most of metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rates: Campsites with water, electrical and cable TV hookups
are $15 to $17 per night. Walk-in tent campsites are $8 per night.
Cottages are $70 to $85 per night during the week and $80-$95 on
weekends, with a two-night minimum for cottage rentals.
Reservations are essential.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Reservations: In metro Atlanta, call 770-389-7275. Elsewhere,
call 1-800-864-7275. Or go online to www.georgianet.org/dnr/parks.
</P>
<P>
   Clint Williams writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
