<SLUG> BC-HIGHPOINT15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Furnishings take cue from global view
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   High Point, N.C. _ Ready or not, here comes the much-hyped year
2000, when stores were expected to roll out Space Age furnishings
designed for ``homes of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's La-Z-Boy, known for its ever-more-inventive recliners,
pitching for next spring?
</P>
<P>
   Try a wooden folding chair.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the electric coolers, the massage mechanisms, the
built-in phones of its newest recliners. Thursday, as the world's
largest furniture market opened in High Point with a preview of the
newest designs, this chair represents bare-bones comfort. It's the
only kind manufacturers knew back in 1928 when the company
introduced its original wood-slatted recliner, limited
reproductions of which are being offered for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very first chair was not even upholstered,'' company
spokeswoman Kay Degenhardt said. ``But it's still beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   The chair, expected to retail for about $400, is just one of the
new offerings that will be shown by 2,500 manufacturers during the
weeklong event, expected to draw 75,000 retail buyers, interior
designers and media from 106 countries. Furnishings sold here
should arrive in stores early next year, and already several themes
are emerging _ none even close to the mid-century predictions that
had our homes looking much like George and Jane Jetson's.
</P>
<P>
   Trend watchers say they believe the next century's interiors
will become more eclectic than ever, reflecting the collectibles
homeowners pick up in their travels. At the same time, while
comfort will dominate choices, young consumers will seek something
elegant for making a statement among the mass produced.
</P>
<P>
   Trends aside, the buzz at this market are the celebrities _
authors, artists, fashion designers and even a publishing magnate _
lending their names to new collections.
</P>
<P>
   Even members of the cast of ``Ally McBeal'' will be on hand
Saturday to help Lane Furniture kick off new lines.
</P>
<P>
   Take supermodel, actress Kathy Ireland, who's created a line for
Vanguard Furniture. ``When I was 8, my family took a trip to
England, and we visited Windsor Castle. I was just awestruck by the
elegance and beauty of it all, but it wasn't family-friendly,''
said the mother of a 5- and 1-year-old from her southern California
home.
</P>
<P>
   So Ireland came up with a eclectic collection of living room,
dining room, bedroom and accent pieces, priced from $500 to $2,200,
that can be used in formal as well as casual rooms. The pieces can
be interchanged much like the women's ensembles she creates for
Kmart.
</P>
<P>
   Another big name tapping into the world-traveler theme is
Forbes. Harden Furniture and six other manufacturers have created
the Forbes Collection of traditional furnishings inspired by the
publishing family's famed estates in London and Normandy. Marquetry
inlay and fabrics feature scenes of ballooning and Faberge eggs _
two longstanding family passions, said Christopher Forbes, son of
the late publisher Malcolm Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Other celebrity brands include trends guru and ``cocooning''
queen Faith Popcorn, with a home office collection for Hooker
Furniture; costume designer Bob Mackie of Cher and Carol Burnett
fame, with additional pieces for Clayton Marcus; and fashion
designer Alexander Julian, with new upholstery groups produced by
BenchCraft. Even members of the cast of ``Ally McBeal'' will be on
hand Saturday to help Lane Furniture kick off new lines.
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
