<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-EARNHARDT-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THE MAN IN BLACK REALLY BACK? 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., Ala., N.C.)  By PATRICK ZIER   The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's not on a winning roll like Jeff Gordon. And he's not making
a championship run like Dale Jarrett.
</P>
<P>
   But if you're looking for the Dale Earnhardt of old, who hasn't
really been showing up a lot lately, you can still find him at
Daytona, Fla., and Talladega, Ala.
</P>
<P>
   While the Intimidator, as he's called, may be just a memory at a
lot of other tracks, he definitely remains larger than life at
NASCAR's two biggest ovals.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, Earnhardt won the first Talladega race April 25. He
backed that with seconds in the Daytona 500 in February and July's
Pepsi 400, also at Daytona International Speedway. This weekend
he'll be back in Talladega for the Winston 500.
</P>
<P>
   The superspeedway surge has enabled Earnhardt to stop a dramatic
skid that has seen him in a downward slide since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   While that, by itself, is no guarantee that Earnhardt can again
become competitive on a weekly basis, it is a start, and something
for the legions of Earnhardt fans, and Earnhardt's team, to hold.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps part of the reason for Earnhardt's success at Daytona
and Talladega is that even with all the technology that goes into
today's race cars, Talladega in particular and Daytona to a lesser
extent suit Earnhardt's foot-to-the-floor driving style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy racing on the big tracks,'' Earnhardt said. ``It used
to be more fun than it is now, because we could run wide open with
no restrictor plates. You would carry so much speed going into the
corners that you had to lift to make it around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' Earnhardt said, ``it's straight leg, foot to the floor
all the way around the track, and the first one who lifts goes back
to the end of the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt's performance at Daytona and Talladega, plus another
win at Bristol, Tenn., have made him the most competitive he's been
since 1996, when he started to fall off.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, there has been a lot of turnover on his team, major
changes in the cars and increased competition. When those points
are factored in with Earnhardt's many outside interests, which pull
him away from the car, some wonder if the team can ever again
achieve the cohesiveness needed to perform at a championship level.
</P>
<P>
   While Earnhardt admits it is difficult to find time to spend at
the shop, he doesn't believe that puts him at a disadvantage. He
says he still remains in close contact with his team, even if he
isn't around as much physically as he used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to jump on a helicopter and get there and try to get
everything done that we have to do,'' Earnhardt said.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt's home and his shop are both in North Carolina but he
lives in the Charlotte metro area, while his team works near
Winston-Salem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you don't have to change anything on the race car, you
go up there and go through the shop and visit and make sure
everybody is excited about what's going on and what's happening and
let them know that you're interested in what's going on,''
Earnhardt said. That's a big part of it. It makes a difference when
I go to the shop. It's always good to go up there and catch up on
things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dale comes to the shop maybe once a month or more if needed,''
crew chief Kevin Hamlin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have plenty of capable people,'' Hamlin said. ``If he
communicates with me and tells me he would like something or wants
something different, then we can work on it without him.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as him being at the shop, it's not a necessity,''
Hamlin said. ``He likes to stop by and say hey to all of the guys
and tell them they're doing a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt that helps, but Earnhardt still isn't what he used to
be. This week though, returning to Talladega, it should be like old
times.
</P>
<P>
   For one race at least, the man in black is back.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla. is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
