<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7090 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CREDIT-NYT &LR;      10-14 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOND YIELDS CLIMB FOR 3RD STRAIGHT DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Driven by some investors' concern that strong
economic growth will prompt the Federal Reserve to raise short-term
interest rates, bond yields climbed higher Thursday for a third
consecutive day.
</P>
<P>
   Prices of Treasury securities, which move in the opposite
direction from yields, fell again on fresh evidence that consumers
are buying more and paying more for imported goods. By late in the
day, the price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond was down
20/32, to 97 13/32. Its yield rose to 6.32 percent from 6.27
percent on Wednesday, the highest level since Oct. 22, 1997, when
it reached 6.41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department reported Thursday that retail sales were
up last month, but not as much as expected, while the Labor
Department stirred market fears with a report saying that prices of
imported goods kept rising last month.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts argued that Thursday's figures had proved
counterproductive for the bond market because they did not really
suggest that the trend of strong consumer spending had changed.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the rate-setting Federal Open Market Committee,
Donald Fine, chief market analyst for Chase Asset Management, said,
``The bond market has been in a heightened state of alert for signs
of inflation now that the FOMC is officially biased toward
tightening, particularly in light of upcoming data that are not
expected to be market-friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``While the Fed specifically stated that it is not
committed to any near-term action, a firming of its policy stance
at the next FOMC meeting on Nov. 16 is a distinct possibility, and
in fact is now expected by market participants, judging from the
spread between the two-year Treasury note and the federal funds
rate. At this juncture, it would appear that only a sudden,
significant deterioration in the economy's performance or imminent
sharp contraction in the stock market could quickly alleviate
inflation concerns and keep the Fed at bay.''
</P>
<P>
   But consumer spending, the key to the economic outlook, still
appears to be healthy. September retail sales rose just 0.1
percent, less than the 0.2 percent expected. This does not seem
indicative of a slowdown since it came on the heels of outsized
increases of 1.5 percent and 1.0 percent in August and July
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Sherry Cooper, chief economist at Nesbitt Burns Securities,
said Thursday's retail sales report was masking powerful
third-quarter growth for the economy. ``U.S. consumers paused for
breath in September, but the underlying trend remains undeniably
strong. Even with the September lull, sales are still up a towering
10.5 percent from year-ago levels and they expanded at a healthy
9.5 percent annual pace in the third quarter.'' Dr. Cooper said
that even Hurricane Floyd could not put a meaningful dent in
consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the market is bracing for Friday's producer price
numbers, which are expected to come in well above the recent trend.
Analyst are forecasting the core and overall number to be up 0.4 to
0.5 percent. ``Each new piece of strong data is adding to fears
that the Fed is falling behind,'' said Stanley Shepard, a market
analyst with Standard &AMP; Poor's MMS, a research and analysis firm
based in San Francisco. ``This is causing players to mark prices
ever lower.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, investors are opting to buy corporate debt to give
them a bigger yield cushion if inflation accelerates.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pugliese, senior vice president and director of fixed
income at J.W. Genesis Financial Corp., in Boca Raton, Fla., sees a
lack of conviction in the market at this point, with not many
people willing to make buying bets. ``If the PPI number takes an
inflationary turn, I see the long bond yield gravitating toward 6.5
percent. If it proves benign, do not expect a major rally either.
The current bias is toward lower prices, with any rally a selling
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much lower do prices have to go?'' Pugliese asked. `` I
think we're nearing a short-term bottom as the market sets for a
Fed tightening.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
