<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7091 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     10-14 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APOLOGIZING FOR A JOB DONE RIGHT
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Friday, Oct. 15)  
(mk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It seems that companies have become so accustomed to irritating
their customers that they now feel a need to apologize when they do
something right.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of months ago, British train passenger Stevan Walton
wrote to a railway company to express his appreciation for a
pleasant journey. The company, Virgin Trains VA.CN, was so
discombobulated it sent him not one, but two, letters of apology.
</P>
<P>
   According to the London Daily Telegraph, the first letter
offered an apology and a ticket refund. The second apologized that
Walton's ``complaint'' had not been dealt with quickly enough.
</P>
<P>
   Red-faced train-company officials admitted later that the whole
matter had been an ``administrative mistake'' and that the letters
were a ``completely inappropriate response.''
</P>
<P>
   That could well be, but I think Virgin Trains VA.CN may have
inadvertently discovered a way for major corporations to trim
customer-service costs. Instead of going to all the trouble and
expense of creating a complaint department _ or, more likely, a
labyrinthine voice-mail system that routes the calls of
dissatisfied customers from machine to machine until the caller
hangs up, is disconnected or dies of old age, whichever comes first
_ why not simply bring someone in for an hour or two a year to
apologize for what has been done right?
</P>
<P>
   Customers do not like change and need to be assured that the
positive experience they had with a store, business or service
provider will never be repeated again. Eventually, after repeated
apologies, the concept of ``good service'' will become so blurred
in the customer's mind that they will stop bothering company
officials with appreciative calls and letters and the company can
devote more of its energies to raising prices and lowering quality.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers, which are inundated with complaints on a daily
basis, would enjoy the benefits of this new approach more than
most. Newspapers are forever publishing corrections,
clarifications, retractions, apologies, reversals, recantations,
set-the-record-straighters, oopsies, never-minds and general
obsequious boot-lickings, and neither the papers nor the readers
seem to feel any better for it.
</P>
<P>
   It would certainly save a lot of time and effort, not to mention
trees, if papers would simply apologize, right off the bat, for
anything that might be accurate, truthful or otherwise correct in
the day's edition.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the editorial department might issue this
disclaimer: ``Dear Readers: Due to circumstances beyond our
control, it turned out we were right about the state lottery. None
of the money has been used to enhance education or, if it has, no
one has been able to tell the difference. We apologize for being
right about this and intend to make it up to you in the near future
by writing an editorial urging the legislature to make it easier
for convicted felons to purchase automatic weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   The person who delivers your paper could send out a form letter
once a year _ perhaps enclosed in the annual Christmas card _
apologizing for all the times the paper did not arrive late or was
not thrown on the roof or in a puddle. It's gestures like this that
make people open their hearts, and checkbooks, at Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Personal computer companies certainly stand to gain a lot from
this new approach to customer relations. The present system
basically consists of frustrated computer-users sitting on ``hold''
for hours at a time while a tech-service representative makes a few
personal calls and does his or her homework. For this you pay them
$7 an hour so they can go out and buy more nose rings and tongue
studs? Wouldn't it make more (economic and fashion) sense to fire
all these people and simply record a brief message apologizing for
whatever the computer managed to do right?
</P>
<P>
   ``Dear customer,'' the apology might begin. ``We wish to
apologize for the fact that your computer has not crashed in
(Choose one: 1, 2, 3 days) and/or has not flushed an irreplaceable
file that took you (1, 2, 3) weeks to create straight down the
silicone-lined commode to Gigabit Hell in less time than it will
take Bill Gates to earn his next (1, 2, 3) million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, we are sorry that we have failed to develop any
mandatory and expensive `upgrades' to your system in the past (1,
2, 3) minutes, or forced you to install some of our slow and balky
software that will cause your computer, and perhaps every
electrical appliance in your house, to start sparking and smoking
the instant you try to use it.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a token of our remorse, please note that we have raised
your monthly user fee by $10. Have a nice day.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
