<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-ROUSH-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACK ROUSH LOOKING AHEAD TO 2000  (DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ala., Calif., Mich., Ky.)  By PATRICK ZIER   The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Jack Roush talks, he comes across as the kind of guy who
could probably tell you where every single nut and bolt is on every
one of his race cars.
</P>
<P>
   In Winston Cup alone, Roush owns five entries, the largest
multi-car team in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   During Sunday's Winston 500 in Talladega, Ala., three of Roush's
car, driven by Jeff Burton, Mark Martin and Kevin Lepage, will vie
for a $1 million bonus.
</P>
<P>
   They are eligible for the money by virtue of having finished in
the top five at the last bonus race, Darlington's Southern 500,
which Burton won.
</P>
<P>
   Should Burton win again Sunday, it would be his third victory in
a bonus race this year. In addition to Darlington, he also won at
Las Vegas, so he could wind up pocketing $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   All of which is interesting to Roush, but not his main focus.
</P>
<P>
   With a bachelor of arts degree in mathematics and physics from
Berea (Ky.) College and a masters in scientific mathematics from
Eastern Michigan, Roush's main concern is trying to make his cars
run faster.
</P>
<P>
   He is always looking ahead, and right now, that means trying to
narrow the gap between Martin and Burton, by far the best cars in
his team, and Lepage, Chad Little and Johnny Benson, who are
essentially non-competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Benson lost his sponsor and that operation will be shut down.
</P>
<P>
   But Roush is adding Matt Kenseth, perhaps the best young driver
in the Busch Series, to his stable in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the Winston Cup Series is concerned, we've had a
great year,'' Roush said. ``Mark has had some mechanical problems
at times when it hurt a lot. We've been caught in a wreck or two
that has hurt us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff Burton and his crew chief Frankie Stoddard have come of
age and placed themselves well in the top 10 and served notice that
they'll be contenders for championships and winning races into the
next millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those I take great pride in,'' Roush said. ``Johnny Benson's
program is a huge disappointment to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin Lepage is about on track with what it takes to be able
to establish the chemistry and build a group around a driver that
can get him what he needs. That's working about the way it should.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chad Little and the John Deere program have been up and
down,'' Roush said. ``We certainly didn't start the year on the
note we finished on last year, but this has been a solid year of
building.''
</P>
<P>
   For Roush, the goal is a title in 2000. Despite having the
talent and equipment to run with anybody, Roush Racing has not been
able to take the final step.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody will say they can't make it, though, and with a new car
and a new year, they will be ready. Roush will see to that.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
