A7094 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-STAMP-TEXAS15-COX     10-14 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAMP-TEXAS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    TEXAS WAR HERO-ACTOR AUDIE MURPHY HONORED WITH POSTAGE STAMP
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In what some consider postage overdue, the boyish,
freckled face of a Texas war hero will join the profiles of Elvis
Presley and Marilyn Monroe next year, with the debut of the 33-cent
Audie Murphy commemorative stamp.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy, the son of Hunt County sharecroppers, gained national
fame as the most decorated U.S. combat soldier of World War II and
became a Hollywood star, making 44 feature films.
</P>
<P>
   Texas legislators, including Rep. Ralph Hall, D-Rockwall,
unveiled the stamp at a Capitol Hill press conference Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Audie Murphy was indeed a legend in his own time _ and a hero
for all times,'' said Hall, who counted the Texan among his
personal friends, until Murphy's death in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Hall recalled one of Murphy's favorite sayings about the Lone
Star state: ``He always said never to ask people if they're from
Texas, because if they were, they'd tell you, and if they weren't,
there wasn't any reason to embarrass them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, also praised Murphy, whom he called a
``country boy, baby-faced young man'' who turned out to be the
greatest hero of World War II and a major spokesman for the rights
of veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're awfully proud that he is a Texan, and we think that he
is a symbol of what is best in our state and in our country,''
Gramm said.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy received the Congressional Medal of Honor for saving the
troops in his company and single-handedly breaking up a German
attack toward the end of World War II. His young looks and modest
frame did not exactly fit the typical visual of a Hollywood war
hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was small _ 5 feet 5 inches, 112 pounds and the Marines
turned him down,'' said Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas. ``But
he wanted to serve his country, and we all know the end of that
story.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy received 33 military awards and decorations and is
credited with killing more than 240 enemy soldiers and wounding and
capturing many others.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a 120-pound, blue-eyed killer during the war. He
answered the call and carried it out well,'' Hall said. ``But to
know him and be with him, he was very mild _ a very quiet guy.''
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Murphy was invited to Hollywood by actor James
Cagney, who saw his picture on the cover of Life magazine. Among
his many films _ most of them Westerns _ the best known is ``To
Hell and Back,'' in which
</P>
<P>
   Murphy starred as himself. The motion picture, based on his
best-selling autobiography, was Universal's highest grossing film
until 1975, when it was surpassed by ``Jaws.''
</P>
<P>
   His legend extended to other areas, including gambling _ where
he was known to have won and lost fortunes. He also raised horses
and wrote dozens of songs that were recorded by artists including
Dean Martin and Roy Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Three other soldiers will be featured on new U.S. postal stamps
next year: Gen. John L. Hines, a highly decorated WWII veteran who
later became Army Chief of Staff; Sgt. Alvin C. York, who received
the Medal of Honor for his single-handed capture of German soldiers
during World War I; and Gen. Omar N. Bradley, who commanded the1st
Army during the 1944 Allied landing in Normandy and became the
first chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   The stamps feature black and white photographs of the soldiers
in uniform with boxes in the corner that indicate the
shoulder-sleeve insignia of the units in which they served.
</P>
<P>
   At the press conference, Hutchison quoted several letters
supporting the Audie Murphy stamp, including one from a veteran in
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hard to believe that Bugs Bunny, Marilyn Monroe and Bela
Lugosi have stamps but not Audie Murphy. Somebody has got to get
their priorities straight,'' the letter read.
</P>
<P>
   After his death in a 1971 plane crash, Murphy was buried with
full military honors in Arlington National Cemetery. His gravesite
is the second most-visited in the historic park, after the eternal
flame of President John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
