<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7099 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-MATCHUPS-2NDTAKE-     10-14 0431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MATCHUPS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: 10-9.  

</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNDAY, 4 P.M. GAMES
</P>
<P>
   Carolina (1-3) vs. San Francisco (3-2)
</P>
<P>
   This is George Seifert's first game against his old team, and he
catches them at a low point. The 49ers are nursing deep wounds
after their whipping at the Rams. They still don't have Steve Young
back at quarterback and, more and more, it looks as if Young's
concussion might keep him out longer. Their pass defense was porous
against the Rams and oftentimes embarrassing. Look for the 49ers to
rebound. But watch Carolina and back Tim Biakabutuka chew them up.
Look for a big game from Beuerlein and his receivers. This is a
victory that Seifert desperately wants. He will cherrish it.
Panthers, 31-28.
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay (3-1) vs. Denver (1-4)
</P>
<P>
   A rematch of Super Bowl XXXII but both teams have different
looks. Green Bay is turning games over to Brett Favre, letting him
work his magic in a variety of ways. Denver is still trying to
solve its problems at quarterback, running back and on defense.
Winning at the Raiders was a start. But the Broncos meet a team
that has jelled much faster than them. One with more talent, too,
especially at the skill positions. Denver offers a fight but Green
Bay's Dorsey Levens (4.4 average yards per carry) runs out the
clock at the end. Packers, 24-20.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDAY NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Washington (3-1) vs. Arizona (2-3)
</P>
<P>
   Washington enjoyed a bye and an extra week to prepare for
Arizona. That should serve them well, especially quarterback Brad
Johnson. He has thrown for 1,191 yards in four games and leads an
offense that averages 412.5 yards per game. In 122 pass attempts
this season, Johnson has not thrown an interception. Stephen Davis
anchors the ground game with 400 rushing yards; his career high in
a season is 567. Arizona has won six of the last seven at home
against Washington and its defense is capable; it has the
top-ranked pass defense in the NFC. But look for Johnson to solve
them. Redskins, 21-16.
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   Dallas (3-1) vs. Giants (2-3)
</P>
<P>
   Dallas is 6-0 against the Giants on Monday nights and last year
in a Monday night game spanked them, 31-7. It was a game where
Deion Sanders ran circles around them, scoring on punt and
interception returns. Dallas swept the Giants last year. The
Cowboys recover from the emotional loss of the injured Michael
Irvin and play confidently against a team they think they can
dominate. They find the Giants offense simple, the Giants defense
tougher, but, overall, believe they are simply a better team. Maybe
so. Cowboys, 23-17.
</P>
</TEXT>
