<HEADER>
A7112 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CLINTON-VIEQUES-HNS &LR;      10-14 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VIEQUES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS SAY CLINTON SEEKS COMPROMISE ON PUERTO RICAN BOMB RANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, meeting with Hispanic lawmakers
from six states, appealed for Puerto Rico's political leaders to
negotiate the Navy's future use of a bombing range on the island of
Vieques, Rep. Carlos Romero-Barcelo, D-Puerto Rico, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But the lawmaker, a non-voting member of Congress who represents
the 3.8 million U.S. citizens in Puerto Rico, said the government
of Puerto Rico would not negotiate resumption of Navy target
practice on an island that is home to almost 9,400 civilians.
</P>
<P>
   The president is ``looking for a solution to a very difficult
problem and he doesn't have an answer at this point in time,''
Romero-Barcelo said, adding: ``The president thinks there must be a
meeting of the minds, that we have to sit down and discuss the
situation with the Navy.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jose Serrano, D-N.Y., said Clinton appealed for continued
efforts to find a compromise to a five-month stalemate that would
satisfy Navy needs for combat training and Puerto Ricans'
insistence that the Navy withdraw from Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ``understood that for the Navy to stay in Vieques and
resume bombings would be an affront to the Puerto Ricans both on
the island and in the states,'' Serrano said. ``I was pleasantly
surprised and somewhat shocked to hear an American president speak
the way he spoke about the situation in Vieques.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers' comments followed a meeting Wednesday night at
the White House with the president and members of the Congressional
Hispanic Caucus that includes representatives from Arizona,
California, Illinois, New Jersey, New York and Texas, as well as
Guam and Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials had no comment on the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lucille Roybal-Allard, D-Calif., chairwoman of the
17-member caucus, said lawmakers had a ``productive, working
meeting'' with the president that ``will keep the lines of
communication open.'' But neither the congresswoman nor her aides
would discuss what the president said at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Romero-Barcelo said he told the president that the government of
Puerto Rico will not discuss resumption of live-fire combat
training on the bombing range that has been used by Atlantic-based
Navy and Marine Corps forces since 1941.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our position is that the bombing must cease permanently and
the Navy must withdraw from Vieques,'' Romero-Barcelo said.
</P>
<P>
   Romero-Barcelo said the lawmakers who took part in the meeting
with the president on behalf of the Hispanic Congressional Caucus
were unified in their appeal for the president to order the Navy to
cease using Vieques for bombing practice and military maneuvers and
to return Navy-owned land to Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   Romero-Barcelo said he warned the president against undertaking
any effort by U.S. Marshals or other federal law enforcement
authorities to clear several dozen protesters from the 899-acre
area where they have camped since April in a bid to prevent
resumption of target practice with bombs, rockets, naval gunfire
and artillery.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people are arrested there, there will be others who go in
to replace them, including some members of the Hispanic
Congressional Caucus,'' the lawmaker said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is grappling with a politically sensitive decision that
has repercussions for the New York Senate campaign of First Lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton and the presidential ambitions of Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rican voters are an influential constituency in New York,
representing about 60 percent of the 2.6 million Hispanics in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanic voters also have growing political influence in
electorally important states that are represented in Congress by
members of the Hispanic Congressional Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has not taken a public position. But New York state Sen.
Olga Mendez, a Democrat from Manhattan, said Gore told her during a
private meeting on Oct. 5 that he favored closing the target range.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy's bombing range on Vieques has been closed since April
19 when a Marine Corps pilot mistakenly bombed a range observation
post located about 10 miles from the nearest civilians. Two 500
pound bombs killed a Puerto Rican security guard employed by the
Navy and wounded four other civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Romero-Barcelo said Puerto Rico's political leaders, led by Gov.
Pedro Rossello, will only consider discussions with the Navy after
a Pentagon review panel appointed at the request of the president
publicly delivers its recommendations for future use of the target
range.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has sought a compromise in the dispute from the outset,
sounding sympathetic to both sides. The president, in a
hand-written note on July 21, told national security adviser Samuel
``Sandy'' Berger that ``the Navy can find a way to work around''
local opposition to the live-fire training.
</P>
<P>
   But in a letter to Senate Armed Services Committee Chairman John
Warner, R-Va., released on Sept. 23, Clinton endorsed the
``rigorous, realistic'' combat training sought by the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
