<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSIDE ART: COLLECTING CEZANNE; URBAN SCULPTURES; RENAMING THE
TATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Auguste Pellerin is a name that keeps cropping up at
auctions. The French industrialist, who died in 1929, was one of
the world's greatest collectors of Impressionist and
post-Impressionist art. He bought his first Cezanne in 1895 and by
his death had amassed about 150 works by Cezanne, almost a sixth of
his entire surviving oeuvre.
</P>
<P>
   But Pellerin didn't stop there. He also collected paintings,
drawings and sculptures by masters like Manet, Monet, Rodin and
Renoir.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Pellerin's heirs have been slowly selling off
the parts of the collection that had not found their way to
museums. Both Sotheby's and Christie's have sold works from the
Pellerin collection.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Christie's will auction 10 paintings by Cezanne as
well as a sculpture by Rodin and a painting by Manet. They will be
included in Christie's sale of Impressionist and post-Impressionist
art on Nov. 8.
</P>
<P>
   While the current crop of Pellerin works are by big-ticket
artists, they tend to be serious and early, the kind of things that
appeal more to scholars, serious connoisseurs and museums than to
the art buyer looking for a pretty image to put in a living room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have already had museums sniffing around `The Orgy,' ''
said Nicholas Maclean, who runs Christie's department of
Impressionist and 19th-century art, referring to the 1867 Cezanne
painting. Partly inspired by Veronese's masterpiece ``The Marriage
of Cana,'' which is in the Louvre, it depicts a drunken banquet and
is estimated to sell for $7 million to $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eve,'' a sculpture by Rodin, is the first bronze cast by the
Rudier Foundry. Dating from 1897, it was initially conceived as
part of an Adam and Eve group to flank Rodin's ``Gates of Hell,''
one cast of which is in the Rodin Museum in Paris. Pellerin
purchased the Rodin directly from the artist in 1898. Christie's
estimates it will sell for $3 million to $4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the Christie's sale is Manet's ``Polichinelle,' an 1873
full-length portrait of Punch, from the Italian medieval comic
couple Punch and Judy. Punch was a central figure in the artist's
work in 1873 and '74. The painting is estimated to bring $2.5
million to $3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Art in Urban Landscape
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Metrotech, the complex of corporate offices in
downtown Brooklyn that includes Chase Manhattan Bank, Bear Stearns
and Brooklyn Union Gas, has just installed a show of special
commissions by five young artists.
</P>
<P>
   Since its inception eight years ago, Metrotech has been known
for its public art _ both permanent installations and temporary
exhibitions _ and for giving younger sculptors a chance to work in
a public place.
</P>
<P>
   The Public Art Fund, a nonprofit group that installs art around
the city, has been responsible for Metrotech's program. This
season, it placed all but one of its new commissions in the
Metrotech commons. Visitors are greeted by ``Grand Entrance at the
Commons'' by Jason Middlebrook, a Brooklyn-based installation
artist. He created a false entrance outside the complex, the kind
one might find in an upscale suburban housing cluster, made from
Styrofoam, wood and paint.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the Australian artist James Angus' ``Basketball
Dropped from 35,000 Feet at Moment of Impact.'' Using
three-dimensional computer-aided design technology, the artist
simulated the impact of a basketball that has fallen from an
aircraft onto a New York sidewalk. Kirsten Mosher, a Manhattan
installation artist, made ``Local Park Express,'' an interactive
sculpture where benches and planters travel along train tracks. In
the trees, Sharon Louden, a Manhattan artist known primarily for
her drawings, created ``Tangled Tips,'' webs of luminescent pale
blue wires.
</P>
<P>
   In the lobby of MetroTech 1, the Canadian artist James Carl has
made ``Dupes,'' life-size, finely detailed recreations of an ATM, a
Federal Express box and a metal detector like those used at
airports.
</P>
<P>
   Each artist was given $10,000 toward the fabrication of the
works, which will be on view at least a year. Some works installed
last year, like Tony Matelli's ``Stray Dog'' and Do-Ho Suh's
``Public Figures,'' are so popular that they are staying a second
year.
</P>
<P>
   Tate Who?
</P>
<P>
   It's not only Americans who like sound bites. The Tate Gallery
in London conducted marketing studies to determine a suitable way
of distinguishing its 102-year-old Millbank building from its new
museum under construction in the renovated Bankside power station
in Southwark. Popular opinion voted overwhelmingly for short,
punchy names.
</P>
<P>
   When the Bankside project was begun seven years ago, Sir
Nicholas Serota, the Tate's director, announced that the Millbank
site would house only British art and that the new museum would be
devoted to modern art from all over the world. Back then, the
museum called the two branches the Tate Gallery of British Art and
the Tate Gallery of Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were two big mouthfuls,'' Sir Nicholas said. ``We
realized that the public wanted snappy names that were connected
with the subjects.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting March 24, the original museum building will be called
simply Tate Britain. And when the transformed power station opens
on May 12, it will be known as Tate Modern.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of hanging art chronologically, both museums will use a
theme approach _ ``hanging historic and modern works together in
challenging juxtaposition,'' Serota said.
</P>
<P>
   To insure that the Tate's original home doesn't seem outdated,
it is getting a $51.6 million facelift and its collection of
British art, from the 16th century to the present, will be rehung.
</P>
<P>
   The London architects John Miller and Partners are working on
upgrading the building to create new galleries, increasing the
display space by 35 percent. The museum will also get a second
entrance, in Atterbury Street, to reduce overcrowding at the main
entrance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 1906EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
