<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7130 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-R-AUTOCREDIT-NORRIS-C     10-14 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-AUTOCREDIT-NORRIS-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: BIZARRE FIGHT FOR CONTROL AT NATIONAL AUTO CREDIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add art note)  
 (ATTN: Ohio)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The subpoenas arrived this week, and the president of the
company being investigated by the Securities and Exchange
Commission sounded downright exultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope the authorities will continue to move quickly,'' said
Allen Rice of National Auto Credit Inc. ``This investigation by the
SEC appears to be consistent with the agency's well-publicized
crackdown on individuals who are suspected of manipulating
corporate earnings.''
</P>
<P>
   Your average chief executive wouldn't be thrilled to have
gumshoes from Washington going over his books, but this is not a
normal situation. The investigation, and a related one by the
Justice Department, probably represents Rice's best chance of
keeping his job. For National Auto Credit of Solon, Ohio, a company
that specializes in auto loans to people with dubious credit, is
the target of one of the more bizarre fights for control ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   On one side is Rice, who joined the company in May. On the other
side is the company's majority shareholder, Sam Frankino, who was
not consulted on Rice's employment. Frankino is now battling in
Delaware courts to take control of the board, with a ruling
expected soon. The losers so far are the public shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   A little background is in order. Early last year, when Frankino
was running National Auto Credit and its shares were traded on the
New York Stock Exchange, the company's auditors resigned, saying
that they did not trust management's representations. A special
committee of the board concluded that the auditors had a point.
Frankino forced those directors off the board, and appointed
replacements more to his liking. The stock cratered.
</P>
<P>
   But since then, things have gone against Frankino. After he
stepped down as chairman in March 1998, his hand-picked board
turned against him and now says it may sue him. Restated financial
results showed about $100 million in losses that, the company says,
``should have been reported when Frankino was at the helm.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankino denies wrongdoing. ``They've spent millions of dollars
on an alleged witch-hunt, and Mr. Frankino is tired of it,'' says
William Lafferty, a lawyer for Frankino. ``They've come up with
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice says they certainly have come up with something. ``The
forensic auditors completed their report in late July,'' he said in
an interview. ``It is quite a substantial report. There is a lot of
information therein that is very damning to the former
management.'' But he says he can't release the report, which was
provided to the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   In his arguments in Delaware, Frankino maintains that the past
is irrelevant. He has a majority of the stock, he says, and
majority rules.
</P>
<P>
   Where does all this leave the company? In limbo. It avoided
bankruptcy and has positive cash flow, but it can't borrow money
while the battle is on. Its stock, kicked off the Big Board, trades
for 76 cents on the over-the-counter bulletin board, far below book
value of about $3 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the SEC investigation goes on. Even if he loses in
Delaware, Frankino can probably take control at next year's annual
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   If minority shareholders don't like it, there does not appear to
be much they can do. They have tried suing, but on Wednesday, a
federal magistrate judge in Cleveland recommended dismissal of the
suit against the company and its former officials. She reasoned
that there was no proof that the company knew its books were wrong
before the auditors quit, and therefore there was no case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
