<HEADER>
A7131 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VW-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-14 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VW-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOLKSWAGEN CHOSEN FOR FIRST CLIENT EXHIBIT AT PRESTIGIOUS
ADVERTISING CLUB  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Del., South Africa, Germany, Britain, France)   By STUART ELLIOTT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Volkswagen may have once implored consumers to
``Think small,'' but now a prestigious advertising organization is
thinking big about the auto maker's campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The One Club for Art and Copy in New York, which encourages
creativity in advertising through efforts like the annual One Show
awards, will devote an exhibit to a single advertiser: Volkswagen
AG. The exhibit, which is to open to the public Friday at the One
Club Gallery here at 32 E. 21st St., offers a retrospective of VW
campaigns around the world from the 1940s through the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to presenting television commercials, print
advertisements and posters, the show, which is scheduled to run
through Nov. 30, also looks at how Volkswagen has earned a place in
popular culture, primarily through the venerable Beetle and its
contemporary successor, the New Beetle. There will be reproductions
of cartoons from magazines like The New Yorker, excerpts from films
like ``The Love Bug'' and video clips of quips from late-night
comics like Jay Leno and Dennis Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time we've done an exhibition for just one
client,'' said Mary Warlick, executive director of the One Club.
``But what a client.''
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen has gained a reputation as a marketer that encourages
creativity among its agencies, which have won innumerable awards
from the One Club and other organizations for campaigns for the
Beetle, New Beetle, Golf, Polo and other models. The company's
Volkswagen of America unit has agreed to sponsor the exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   The original Beetle ads, by Doyle Dane Bernbach in New York _
now part of the DDB Worldwide Communications Group, owned by
Omnicom Group _ have been widely deemed the best campaign of all
time. The ads for the New Beetle by Arnold Communications in
Boston, a unit of Snyder Communications, pay tribute to their
predecessors with a look and attitude evocative of the understated,
humorous Doyle Dane style.
</P>
<P>
   ``The '90s are similar to the '60s,'' said Ann Cooper, an
advertising journalist who is the curator of the exhibition, ``with
the right people and the right car coming together and able to
create great buzz again.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition also features work from DDB agencies that still
work for Volkswagen, including BMP DDB in London and DDB Paris, as
well as other Volkswagen shops like the Cape Town, South Africa,
office of Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide, part of WPP Group PLC. In
addition, online advertising for Volkswagen created by BBDO
Interactive in Dusseldorf, Germany _ part of the BBDO Worldwide
unit of Omnicom _ will be available on computers.
</P>
<P>
   Vintage Beetle ads will be displayed as they appeared in
magazines of the era like Life and Look. Those ads are being
borrowed from Raymond Nichols, coordinator of the Visual
Communications Group in the Department of Art at the University of
Delaware. Nichols also conducted interviews with some of the
creators of the ads.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition coincides with three anniversaries. Doyle Dane
opened for business in 1949, when the first two Beetles were sold
in the United States. (That modest beginning was the inspiration
for a classic Beetle TV spot, ``1949 Auto Show,'' that is part of
the exhibition.) The Doyle Dane relationship with Volkswagen
started in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   As for other clients that may merit similar salutes, Ms. Warlick
suggested Absolut vodka, Apple Computer, Levi Strauss and Polaroid.
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
