<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, Oct. 15. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TREATY-CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton charges that the
Republicans who defeated a treaty banning all underground nuclear
testing are leading the United States into a ``new isolationism,''
and he vows to abide by the treaty's provisions even though it was
overwhelmingly rejected by the Senate. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   With photos.
</P>
<P>
   TREATY-CANDIDATES (Undated) _ The contrasting responses by
presidential candidates underscores how Republicans and Democrats
see the vote from decidedly opposite vantage points. By Richard L.
Berke.
</P>
<P>
   TREATY-REACT (United Nations) _ Around the world, government
leaders and arms experts react with dismay and even anger after the
U.S. Senate defeated, without much debate, a nuclear test ban
treaty that had been decades in the making. For many, there was a
sense that the treaty may now be dead. By Barbara Crossette. 1,200
words.
</P>
<P>
   NAZI-GOLD-TRAIN (Washington) _ In the last weeks of World War
II, as Soviet troops advanced from the east, Nazi officials in
Hungary ordered that a train be sent west toward Germany with the
collected wealth of Hungary's decimated Jews. Their wedding bands
alone filled crate after crate. American troops intercepted the
train in Austria in May 1945, and moved its contents _ gold,
silver, paintings and furs _ to a guarded warehouse near Salzburg.
But according to a report Thursday by U.S. investigators, the
Americans were not the most selfless of custodians. U.S. officials
deemed the valuables ``unidentifiable'' and refused to let the
Hungarians inspect them for their possible return to rightful
owners. In the meantime, however, some of the American troops in
Austria helped themselves. By Tim Golden.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-MILITARY (New Delhi, India) _ Soldiers seal off
Pakistan's Parliament and round up more ministers who had served in
the elected government that was toppled Tuesday in a military coup,
but the chief spokesman for the country's armed forces declares,
``Yes, democracy is intact.'' As the nation waits for the military
to announce who will govern the country now that Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif has been dismissed and put under house arrest, the
military's efforts to put a friendly face on their takeover does
not end signs of nervousness. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   LEAD-LAWYERS (Undated) _ A growing wave of lawsuits by cities
and states against makers of tobacco, guns _ and now lead paint _
has reignited a fierce debate over the role of lawyers and the
enormous fees they can earn in legal actions brought by public
officials. By Barry Meier and Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-LIFE-COURSES (Southampton, N.Y.) _ There is a
proliferation of life-skills seminars nationwide, with more than 70
percent of colleges and universities offering some sort of academic
classes designed to help students adjust to adulthood and
institutional life. The trend has exploded over the last decade, as
budget-strapped and consumer-oriented colleges battled high dropout
rates and searched for strategies to boost student success. By Jodi
Wilgoren. 2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRAIN (Undated) _ In a new challenge to the longstanding
belief that adults never generate new brain cells, biologists at
Princeton University have found that thousands of freshly born
neurons arrive each day in the cerebral cortex, the brain's outer
rind, where higher intellectual functions and personality are
centered. Though based on research in monkeys, the finding is
likely to prove true of people too and if so, several experts said.
By Nicholas Wade. 1,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-NYERERE (Undated) _ Julius K. Nyerere, the idealistic,
principled and some would say naively misguided founding father of
Tanzania, died Thursday. The man who led his country into
independence and guided it for nearly three decades was about 77
years old. By Michael T. Kaufman. 3,400 words.
</P>
<P>
   (MOVED; also OBIT-NYERERE-ABRIDGED, 940 words)
</P>
