<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 19:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7137 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WHISTLEBLOWER-MOVIE-A     10-14 1245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHISTLEBLOWER-MOVIE-ART-825&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOBACCO WHISTLE-BLOWER'S LIFE BECOMES PUBLIC WITH `THE INSIDER' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky., S.C.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) (th) 
 By RICK LYMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, S.C. _ It was not the first time it had happened.
Sitting with some friends in a restaurant, still energized from
accepting his first honorary doctorate, Jeffrey S. Wigand noticed a
man approaching from the bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``He started shouting at me in a very abusive way,'' Wigand
said.
</P>
<P>
   A colleague who was seated with Wigand said it was all very
sudden and threatening.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man just went off on Jeff,'' she said. ``He started
screaming: `How does it feel not to be making big money any more?
Look at your cheap shoes.' He said to me, `What's a nice-looking
woman like you doing with a loser like this?'''
</P>
<P>
   The man pointed to a tobacco company logo on his shirt and
pulled a wad of bills from his pocket, thrusting it under Wigand's
nose. Big tobacco money! Remember what this looks like?
</P>
<P>
   Only several years ago, few people had heard of Jeffrey S.
Wigand, then a high-salaried senior executive at Brown &AMP; Williamson
tobacco company in Louisville, Ky., owned by British American
Tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1993 Wigand was dismissed, which he said was because he
resisted the company's use of a potentially dangerous pipe tobacco
additive. And he was warned, he said, to abide by the company's
confidentiality agreement or face lawsuits and the potential loss
of his family's medical benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, despite increasing pressure from the company and
anonymous death threats, he said, he decided to cooperate with
federal regulators and anti-tobacco investigators, becoming among
the most famous corporate whistle-blowers in America, the man who
told a grand jury and ``60 Minutes'' the inside secrets of Big
Tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Wigand's disclosures played a crucial role in the case brought
by the states' attorneys general against the major tobacco
companies, which resulted in a $246 billion settlement last year
for health claims paid by the states for tobacco related illnesses,
and in the decision last month by the Justice Department to seek
billions of dollars in additional damages from the tobacco makers.
</P>
<P>
   But being a whistle-blower has not been easy. Indeed, Wigand
said he has never become comfortable with the term whistle-blower.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even like the word,'' he said. ``To me, it has a
negative connotation. And I struggle with what I did with what I
knew, I really do.''
</P>
<P>
   Wigand has drawn his share of critics. He has been cast as a
turncoat for spilling company secrets and blasted as someone driven
to anti-tobacco zealotry by what has happened to him. But he said
he does not embrace the martyr's cloak, and is not dedicating his
life to an anti-tobacco crusade to do penance for his years earning
big dollars from tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's penance, I've paid it already,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When he worked for Brown &AMP; Williamson, he lived in an
8,300-square-foot house in one of Louisville's fanciest
neighborhoods, sent his daughters to the best schools, drove a
company-bought Mercedes, played golf at the country club and
brought his wife with him on business trips, everything first
class.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had all the trappings of a successful corporate executive,''
Wigand said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he lives and works in an apartment on the outskirts of
Charleston _ ``two-and-a-half miles from downtown and
two-and-a-half miles from the beach'' _ running a foundation he
formed to teach children about the dangers of tobacco. The
foundation, Smoke-Free Kids, has a staff of one, he said. Him.
There are no more country clubs or first-class living.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went from making $300,000 a year _ plus stock options, plus,
plus, plus _ to making $30,000,'' Wigand said. ``Yes, there is a
price I've paid. Anybody who got near me paid a price.''
</P>
<P>
   So, the inevitable question, the one he said everyone eventually
asks him: Would he do it again?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he said. ``There is no stuttering here. There is no
hesitation. I am at peace with myself. I have a good name now. It's
a very good name and I protect it very much. My name stands for
integrity. I can't describe to you what it is like to have that
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   His story is the subject of a new movie, ``The Insider,'' to be
released by Disney on Nov. 5, directed by Michael Mann and starring
Al Pacino as Lowell Bergman, the ``60 Minutes'' producer who
prodded Wigand to go public and then fought to have the interview
broadcast, and Russell Crowe as Wigand.
</P>
<P>
   He has seen the movie and loves it _ ``it was 100 percent on
target, at least for me'' _ and acknowledges that he feels more
than a tiny bit of vindication. He looks forward to taking his
daughters, ages 11 and 13, to the star-studded premieres.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want my children to see it with me,'' he said. ``I mean,
they're proud. Terribly proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Wigand said he has received and will receive no money from the
film. ``My pay is psychological.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the future, Wigand said: ``Basically, I would like to have
some private life again. I don't want the people around me to feel
there is always an impending situation about to happen.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After he was dismissed by Brown &AMP; Williamson, Wigand taught at
du Pont Manual High School in a diverse, urban neighborhood in
central Louisville. His marriage fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really want to go there,'' he said. ``It was very
passionate and very bitter, on both sides. It was not an amicable
divorce.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he decided to stay in Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   ``My kids were there, and there was a part of me that did not
want to run out of the lion's den with my tail between my legs,''
Wigand said.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't all bad, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some days were good, some were ugly,'' he said. ``Sometimes
people would come up and defend me when someone attacked me.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, his ex-wife remarried and moved to Texas. And there
continued to be the occasional nasty incident in Louisville. In
1998, when the states' attorneys-general settled with the tobacco
companies, part of the settlement was an agreement that the
companies would drop all of their legal actions against Wigand. He
decided it was time to leave Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   He picked Charleston, he said, because one of his lawyers had
his offices there, and because it was near his father and the
ocean. His daughters remain close to him and visit regularly. But
he lives alone, save for a dog that one of his lawyers bought him,
``you know, for some company.'' He said he hasn't felt, until very
recently, that he was ready to embark on a new relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed to be able to go around anonymously for awhile, to
heal,'' Wigand said. ``Now, I can relax a little bit. I would like
to have a relationship. I'm going through rebuilding my life when
I'm 56 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Some days, he said, he hardly thinks about his former life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fear is gone now,'' he said. ``I think I've been seasoned
a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   That made it all the more disheartening when the man verbally
assaulted him. It reminded him, Wigand said, that passions about
tobacco are high and that the release of the new movie may stir
them up again in some people.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get the truth out has been such an effort,'' he said.
``It's still an effort.''
</P>
</TEXT>
