<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-KIDNAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN WITH ATTENTION ON WAR, KIDNAPPINGS CONTINUE IN CHECHNYA  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GROZNY, Russia _ Bursts of automatic gunfire rang out in central
Grozny on Wednesday, followed by an ear-splitting volley from a
heavy machine gun. People were running on the street, while
fighters and armed men rushed toward the gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   In broad daylight, on a main street in the center of town, an
armed gang was trying to kidnap a local journalist. With a burst of
machine-gun fire, government commandos shot out the wheels of the
gunmen's jeep and wounded the driver, just as the gunmen were
forcing their hostage into the car.
</P>
<P>
   Kidnapping, the scourge of the Chechen republic since the last
war with Russia ended in 1996, has not ceased, even when attentions
are turning to a renewed war. The Chechen government has fought a
losing battle against the kidnapping gangs that have targeted
foreign journalists and aid workers, as well as ordinary Chechens.
</P>
<P>
   The Chechen leadership has long been criticized for failing to
stop the increase in crime, and this incident illustrated the
brazenness of the kidnappers and their disdain for the government
forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I immediately felt so mad,'' said Ruslan Suleymanov, one of
the commandos who arrested the men, hitting one of them on the head
and disarming him quickly. ``At such a time, when a war is going
on, they are kidnapping people.''
</P>
<P>
   Roman Savin, a computer technician from the Chechenpress
government news agency, escaped the kidnapping attempt with just a
blow to the head. A Chechenpress correspondent with him, Marina
Abubakarova, was unhurt.
</P>
<P>
   One kidnapper shouted ``Allahu-Akbar!'' as he was marched to the
commando headquarters, and one of his guards thumped him between
the shoulders with a rifle butt.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later they were taken off in cars by the government
security services to be interrogated, their jackets pulled over
their heads. If they are found guilty of attempted kidnapping, they
could face a death sentence, said Abu Movsayev, chief of Chechnya's
Special Department Responsible for Internal Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not just criminals,'' he said. ``This is a group sent
with an aim. It is calculated to frighten foreign journalists from
coming here.''
</P>
<P>
   The hostage trade grew out of the last war, when prisoners taken
in fighting, even the bodies of dead fighters or soldiers, were
handed over only for a price. Almost every commander was thought to
be involved in trading hostages.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, kidnapping began to become widespread, with every
small-time criminal joining in. Criminal gangs elsewhere in the
Caucasus also took part, often selling their hostages to people in
Chechnya, or claiming to be holding them there.
</P>
<P>
   The government, with its economy destroyed by the war, has been
unable to pay its law enforcement agencies and is ill-equipped to
fight such powerful and well-armed groups. But it does claim to
have captured, tried and executed some of the culprits, including
Abbas Murtazalayev, the leader of a criminal gang responsible for
the beheading of four employees of a British telecommunications
company.
</P>
<P>
   Movsayev says he is convinced that Russian secret services are
behind much of the kidnapping that has made Chechnya one of the
most dangerous places in the world for foreigners, and created an
image of the Chechens as bandits, and even terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   It touches civilians too. Khadizhat Gatayeva, who runs a home
for war orphans in Grozny, received a visit from two Dagestani
women who said they had two of her children, who disappeared at the
border between Chechnya and Dagestan last month. They demanded
either $10,000 for the teen-age boys or the return of two Dagestani
hostages seized by Chechens in recent fighting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
