<HEADER>
A7147 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BOOKS-MCCAIN15-COX     10-14 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MCCAIN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McCain tells his Vietnam War story in new book
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _
</P>
<P>
   Faith of My Fathers, By John McCain. Random House; 349 pages;
$25.
</P>
<P>
   First the politics. John McCain is touting his book in the usual
cities _ New York, Los Angeles, Boston, Chicago and Manchester,
N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Manchester?
</P>
<P>
   Note that New Hampshire is home to the first presidential
primary _ which the third-term senator would love to win in his bid
to become the Republican nominee.
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be more than coincidence at work in this book's
timing, which is bringing the Arizona Republican a lot of
attention.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a new ploy. Biographies or weighty missives on
social and international issues have long been a part of campaign
strategy. That said, ``Faith of My Fathers'' does much more than
accomplish its political goal of helping a candidate win attention.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's story about his father and grandfather, both Navy
admirals, and the strength he took from them as he struggled to
stay alive for more than five years as a prisoner of war in
Vietnam, is compelling.
</P>
<P>
   A family of warriors, the McCains distinguished themselves in
battle. Father and grandfather were heroes in World War II. Both
would become four-star admirals, a first for a father and son. Both
were hellraisers who loved the Navy and saw it as a calling but
struggled through the Naval Academy. Both were revered by the
enlisted men they commanded.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain entered the Naval Academy and turned out to be a
dismal student who couldn't avoid getting into mischief. He did so
poorly that he was nearly kicked out and finished fifth from the
bottom of the class of 1958.
</P>
<P>
   Things didn't get much better after he left Annapolis. He went
to Pensacola, Fla., for flight training and became a Navy pilot. In
between flights, McCain played hard, often too hard. Even in play
he was following the McCain family legend. His father smoked, drank
and loved to gamble.
</P>
<P>
   Life's first big jolt hit McCain shortly before 11 a.m., July
29, 1967, while he was sitting in his A-4 fighter plane on the deck
of the USS Forrestal, preparing for his sixth bombing run over
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Just before takeoff, a missile from a nearby jet accidentally
fired, hitting McCain's plane. Fleeing through the fireball, McCain
managed to put out the flames on his flight suit. Seconds later, he
was hit in the legs and chest by bits of shrapnel from exploding
bombs.
</P>
<P>
   The fire burned for 24 hours, killing 134 men, wounding many
more. Worried he would be forced to return to the States, McCain
volunteered to go to another ship and continue combat duty. He
would be hit by one more missile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I was hit. My A-4, traveling at about 550 miles an
hour, was violently spiraling to earth. In this predicament, a
pilot's training takes over. ... I reacted automatically the moment
I took the hit and saw that my wing was gone. I radioed, `I'm hit,'
reached up, and pulled the ejection seat handle.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain broke both arms and his right knee. He landed in a lake
near Hanoi.
</P>
<P>
   After pulling him from the water, one of his captors broke
McCain's shoulder with a rifle butt. He was stabbed in the leg and
groin with a bayonet. Then he was taken to what POWs derisively
called the ``Hanoi Hilton.'' It was Oct. 26, 1967.
</P>
<P>
   During the next 5 1/2 years, McCain and the other POWs would
endure torture, solitary confinement, sleep deprivation, demands
for confessions and the constant threat of execution.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a year after his capture, McCain's father was named
commander in chief in the Pacific _ in charge of all ground, sea
and air forces in the Pacific, including those in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Believing they could get some propaganda value out of releasing
the admiral's son, McCain's captors offered to let him go. He
refused, saying that those captured before him should be released
first. He understood that his release would be used to torment the
other prisoners, who would be told that their country cared only
about the children of admirals.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the book is devoted to the bravery of the POWs, who did
all they could to torment and resist their guards. It is a grim
reminder of the real cost of the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   McCain ends his book shortly after the prisoners were released
in 1972. He writes that his Vietnam experiences have strengthened
him and his country. ``America has a long, accomplished and
honorable history. We should never have let this one mistake,
terrible though it was, color our perceptions forever of our
country's purpose. We were a good country before Vietnam, and we
are a good country after Vietnam. In all history, you cannot find a
better one.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that McCain really believes that. And if that
belief helps him in New Hampshire, McCain's not going to complain.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
