<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 19:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7148 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BOOKS-RIDLEY15-COX     10-14 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-RIDLEY15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ridley jabs, weaves in gritty, sin-filled 'Smokes'
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Now that James Ellroy has been taken
seriously as a writer and _ worse _ slowed down, the mantle of the
hot and hungry master of neo-noir has passed to John Ridley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody Smokes in Hell'' is a title that promises a lot,
and, by God, Ridley delivers. The book is more fun than a box full
of scorpions at a wedding, a convoluted but never-confusing story
of greed, lust, and all the other deadly sins that keep life from
being dull.
</P>
<P>
   The setup: Paris Scott, would-be writer, would-be actor,
would-be director, actual failure, works at a convenience store
where he's picked up by a famous rock star named Ian who's doing a
Howard Hughes/Melvin Dummar number. Ian takes Paris back to his
mansion, plays him a tape with his latest and greatest music on it,
then passes out.
</P>
<P>
   Paris steals the tape. Ian wakes up and, not knowing the tape is
gone, accidentally kills himself in a way even Sonny Bono would
find hilarious.
</P>
<P>
   Unbeknownst to Paris, his equally feckless roommate has
liberated a quantity of fine cocaine from a particularly vicious
drug lord, who sets two thugs to catch and kill the man who stole
his drugs. Then, just in case they fail, he sets an even scarier
psychopath named Brice to back them up.
</P>
<P>
   Brice happens to be a beautiful woman who likes to dance to hard
rock while she tortures her victims, usually with cigarette butts.
Paris hits the road for Las Vegas, with all manner of viciousness
following in his wake.
</P>
<P>
   What sets Ridley apart is his uncompromising grimness matched
with a high energy. Jim Thompson had a similar outlook but wrote
through a dolorous fog; Ridley writes like the keys are tapped into
a Sears Die-Hard.
</P>
<P>
   The conventional tactic for most writers who deal with
antiheroes is to make their heavies much worse than their heroes,
so the audience has no choice but to root for the half-bad man.
</P>
<P>
   But Paris is not just a mope and a loser; he's a faithless mope
and loser, betraying the trust of the only sympathetic character in
the book.
</P>
<P>
   Ridley's people are empty souls on the fast track to perdition:
``The girl behind the counter was nineteen and white trash
distilled to its purest form: uncontaminated, unaffected,
undetrashified by the many and various, the endless variety of
ethnicities in the city she'd migrated to ... The girl was white
trash by virtue of the pumps she wore with her Levis and the halter
top that drooped from her shoulders, exposing creamy pink
afraid-of-the-sun flesh. She was white trash because of her hair _
dirty blonde despite its bleaching _ which had been tossed and
permed, blown out and curled ... everything except properly
introduced to a comb ... The girl filled her time thumbing through
a Hollywood fluff rag, not bothering with the simple-worded
articles, but lingering in rapture over the pictures of beautiful
movie-star people hanging out in beautiful movie-star places doing
nothing more significant than looking good. Manufactured glamour
shots were just about as heavy-duty a concept as this chick could
handle.''
</P>
<P>
   This luscious bit of character setting is not for a major player
but a walk-on; a more literary style would make it a couple of
wasted paragraphs, but Ridley's energy makes it an extended jazz
riff before returning to the central melody of the plot.
</P>
<P>
   The central gimmick could be played for farce as well as thrills
_ Paris thinks the people chasing him are homicidal record
executives who want Ian's tape. He doesn't even know about the
cocaine in his bag and has no idea some serious blood-and-guts
types want a heart-to-heart.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the cross-purposes, Ridley bobs and weaves, moving
fast, crosscutting between short, punchy scenes _ ``Everybody
Smokes in Hell'' has all the marks of a busted screenplay, but it's
subtler and more surprising than most screenplays ever dare to be.
Ridley even references ``The Treasure of the Sierra Madre,'' which,
these days, is grad-school esoteric _ and pulls off a tingling
lady-or-the-tiger ending.
</P>
<P>
   The book is for those with a taste for hard-core crime writing.
``I don't believe in love,'' a character says. ``I think people get
together with someone because they lust after them. I think people
stay together because they're afraid of being alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Thompson never said it better. Or Charles Willeford. Or even
Dashiell Hammett.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
