A7149 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS15-COX     10-14 0463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EYMAN-ON-BOOKS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oxford Press reissues classics in paperback
 &HT;    By Scott Eyman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Oxford University Press is reissuing
their legendary World Classics in a new paperback format. There are
nearly 700 titles in print in the series, and the paperbacks have
been around since 1980, but the books have been reformatted and, in
some cases, reset. The results are quite attractive and readable,
and the versions offered by Oxford also come with annotations,
chronologies, glossaries and new introductions.
</P>
<P>
   The joy of the Oxford collection is its range. There are the
expected titles _ 46 novels by Trollope, 15 by Dickens, 14 Conrads,
11 Conan Doyles, nine Eliots, eight Dostoevskys, five Melvilles and
a partridge in a pear tree.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also a profusion of 19th-century Gothics (``The
Mysteries of Udolpho,'' etc.) and other titles from deep left field
_ two volumes of James M. Barrie, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   I'm particularly interested in catching up on some gaps in my
19th-century British reading: the once-popular Jerome K. Jerome's
``Three Men in a Boat,'' as well as Philip Taylor's ``Confessions
of a Thug,'' a famous early (1839) novel about India. Prices range
from $8.95 for ``Riders of the Purple Sage'' up to $12.95. Also
from Oxford is a delightful reissue of Somerset Maugham's
``Princess September and the Nightingale'' ($16.95). Written in
1922, Oxford first issued the book in 1939, with stunning, densely
colored illustrations by Richard Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Maugham's story is a light, charming tale of a Thai princess who
owns a gifted nightingale who cannot sing unless it is free, and
cannot live if it cannot sing. By itself, it's a sweet footnote to
Maugham's sardonic, realistic career, but the illustrations take it
to another level.
</P>
<P>
   Highly recommended.
</P>
<P>
   LEX LUTHOR LIVES ...
</P>
<P>
   Those with a bent towards Superman won't do better than
``Superman: The Complete History'' ($29.95), a very nice
coffee-table book from Chronicle Books. The text takes you through
all of the character's permutations, from the imaginations of Jerry
Siegel and Joe Shuster, two Cleveland high school kids, through
comics, radio, serials, television and features. And yes, Siegel
and Shuster named Clark Kent's home base of Metropolis after Fritz
Lang's great 1926 film.
</P>
<P>
   The art is, of course, the main selling point, with everything
from cels from the Fleischer animated shorts of the war years, to
reprints of classic ``Superman'' comics of the postwar era.
</P>
<P>
   Seriously nostalgic fun.
</P>
<P>
   QUOTE UNQUOTE ...
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't given to us to know what is good, only what is
popular.''
</P>
<P>
   _ James Salter
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
