<HEADER>
A7150 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOVIE-FANATIC15-COX     10-14 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-FANATIC15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `My Son the Fanatic' a unique cross-cultural drama
 &HT;    By Jim Luksic
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The meshing of different cultures is given a
fresh perspective in ``My Son the Fanatic,'' director Udayan
Prasad's second big-screen feature. The filmmaker, an India native
who immigrated to Great Britain, stays objective in his treatment
of Hanif Kureishi's script, first published as a New Yorker short
story.
</P>
<P>
   This uncommonly poignant tale unfolds through the eyes of Parvez
(Om Pui), a Pakistani who has spent his quarter-century in England
as a cab driver. While wife Minoo (Gopi Desai) and son Farid (Akbar
Kurtha) _ who broke up with his fiance to pursue religion _ remain
home, Parvez seems content tooling around in his taxi at night.
</P>
<P>
   He will introduce his favorite passenger, a hooker named Bettina
(Rachel Griffiths), to debauched German businessman Mr. Schitz
(Stellan Skarsgard of ``Breaking the Waves''). Parvez becomes
disgusted by their activities, but soon finds his affection for
Bettina is reciprocated. That revelation widens the chasm between
him and his dutiful spouse, and further strains relations with
Farid, whom Parvez suspects is taking drugs. Longtime friend and
restaurant owner Fizzy (Harish Patel) comes forth as a
fence-straddling devil's advocate.
</P>
<P>
   The inherently disturbing narrative examines the confusion and
contradictions Middle Easterners face in foreign lands.
Screenwriter Kureishi traversed similar turf in 1986 with ``My
Beautiful Laundrette,'' but here implements an intriguing notion: a
middle-aged married man acting less responsibly, and having less
trouble assimilating, than his devout son.
</P>
<P>
   Prasad's treatment of the material is unobtrusive; he doesn't
take sides, nor does he patronize the characters. Each individual
is given distinct values, ideals, dreams. One touching moment shows
the father grasping for explanation when asked why he hasn't
pursued a desire to write. (``It's been so long since I thought
about anything.'')
</P>
<P>
   Loose strands have been drawn together into a tiny knot. A
potentially explosive, overwrought scene wherein fundamentalists
converge upon a whorehouse isn't framed distortingly or
ostentatiously with heavy-handed angles and slow motion. In the
same instant, our hero gets revenge on his two male antagonists in
a sharp, economically shot clip.
</P>
<P>
   An Indian native with more than 100 movies under his belt, Puri
fills the screen with presence and emotional range subtly
demonstrated by his careworn face. Griffiths, the brunette in
``Hilary &AMP; Jackie,'' here sports blond locks, perhaps to augment
her trick-turning persona _ but the coif belies pain and
tenderness. The pair's pleasant conversation over coffee at dusk
speaks volumes, a credit to the actors. Kurtha and Patel,
conversely, emote too intensely; both could learn from the reserved
Skarsgard.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Son the Fanatic'' overcomes a jumbled, misleading prologue
and settles down into a provocative, deceivingly witty drama about
tolerance, integrity, love and family. Rarely has the generational
gap between a parent and child been outlined within such an unusual
framework.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
