<HEADER>
A7153 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-TV-RYAN-REVIEW-SFCHRO     10-14 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-RYAN-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RYAN CAULFIELD': IN NEED OF A HIT, FOX CALLS A ROOKIE COP 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the morning of his first day as a Philadelphia street cop,
Ryan Caulfield (Sean Maher) admires himself in his bedroom mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Sharing his thoughts with viewers in one of those overused
interior monologues, he notes the heft of the handcuffs and the
badge.
</P>
<P>
   ``And finally,'' he says, ``the gun. A standard-issue
nine-millimeter semiautomatic weighs about two pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all heavy,'' he continues, presumably speaking now about
the whole uniform regalia, ``and very cool.''
</P>
<P>
   The scene conveys the character's boyishness and the seriousness
of the job as ``Ryan Caulfield: Year One'' premieres Friday on Fox.
</P>
<P>
   He's 19 years old, recently out of high school. He's too young
to buy a legal drink, and he's about to shoulder a big load.
</P>
<P>
   So is the show, because Fox is off to a splatter start to its TV
season. Fox desperately needs a new hit, and everything's going
(set ital)kerplop.(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   ``Action,'' pre-empted the past few weeks, has practically sunk
to Pax-land in the Nielsen ratings, and Fox decided this week to
pull it from the November sweeps.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get Real'' hasn't made a dent. ``Harsh Realm'' premiered to
poor numbers. Viewers are sniffing the fraud in ``Ally,'' the
foreshortened ``Ally McBeal'' that's also known as David E.
Kelley's Christmas Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's ``Manchester Prep.'' In a severe act of pre-emptive
criticism, Fox saved time and trouble by murdering that clinker
before it even aired.
</P>
<P>
   These are not happy times in Fox's chicken coop.
</P>
<P>
   So, under the circumstances, ``Ryan Caulfield: Year One'' might
seem presumptuously named. ``Week One'' might be more appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   By any name _ it originally was ``Ryan Caulfield,'' without the
``Year One,'' and later ``The Badland'' _ this show won't be a
smash hit. But it has survival potential, which is good enough.
With its careful insistence on tracing the emotions and tracking
the senses of a rookie cop, ``Ryan Caulfield: Year One'' has a feel
that's all its own.
</P>
<P>
   You sense his awkwardness at his on-the-run introduction to his
partner, a veteran named Susser (Michael Rispoli). Caulfield
doesn't even make roll call before Susser swoops him into a squad
car and off to the scene of a shooting.
</P>
<P>
   And Caulfield is embarrassed when duty brings him into the
bedroom of a tenement apartment, where a corpulent man lies nude in
a deep alcoholic doze.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't tell you how strange you feel when you're in
someone's home,'' he tells us in voice-over. ``Even though you're a
cop, you feel like you're an intruder invading their privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   The device is a narrative crutch that's suddenly all the rage on
TV this fall _ I blame HBO's ``Sex and the City.'' But a limited
amount of it works for ``Ryan Caulfield.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night's episode seems complete, but it's full of loose
threads and dangling story lines. I'm not sure there are many sides
to Ryan Caulfield the character. But there are to ``Ryan
Caulfield'' the show.
</P>
<P>
   We're introduced to his retinue of buddies, headed by his best
friend, Vic (James Roday), an acid-tongued slacker. To Ryan's
college freshman girlfriend, though she's destined to be written
out of the show. To Ryan's mother (Brenda Bakke). To the notion
that Ryan's father was a crooked cop, now in prison. And to the
precinct house, where the regulars include the Puerto Rican rookie
Kim Veras (Roselyn Sanchez).
</P>
<P>
   (As if Sanchez weren't singeing the screen enough by her very
presence, she's given a bra-and-panty scene in the precinct locker
room.)
</P>
<P>
   The sizable supporting cast also includes Clifton Powell as a
lieutenant at the precinct, Richard Portnow as a tough sergeant and
Chad Lindberg as yet another Ryan bud, a young plumber called
``H.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``Ryan Caulfield'' will rise or fall, with millions of
dollars at stake, on one of those great television risks: its
unknown star. Maher hasn't had a regular role in any previous TV
series. In fact, there's no sign he's ever been on TV before, in
any capacity. Or in a movie. Regional theater roles are the
entirety of his career credits.
</P>
<P>
   He's got those daytime soap-opera looks, though, that would make
him stand out anywhere _ except TV, of course, where everybody's
beautiful. Imagine Ray Liotta's face imposed on a younger George
Clooney's head, and you're close to Maher. That's the look. As for
ability, those theater boards are no liability; Maher has an
appealing presence for a young actor, with just the right mix of
shyness and self-assurance.
</P>
<P>
   I'm often, if not customarily, wrong about these things. But
this show could be a quiet success en route to ``Ryan Caulfield:
Year Two.'' That's not exactly an answered prayer for Fox. But it
would be sustenance at the moment it's needed most.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
