<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7157 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CANCER-DNA-BOS &LR;      10-14 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-DNA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENETIC FINGERPRINTS YIELD CLUES ON CANCER CELLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scientists have proven that identical-looking cancer cells can
be distinguished just by their genetic fingerprints, and they say
that this method _ a spinoff of the Human Genome Project _ could
greatly improve cancer diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the Whitehead Institute in Cambridge, Mass., and
the Dana-Farber Cancer Institute in Boston used powerful, miniature
``laboratories-on-a-chip'' to scan two types of cancer cells for
genetic differences.
</P>
<P>
   These DNA chips, as they are called, can scan thousands of genes
at once and determine whether each is active or switched off. In
the test results, the chips showed that two distinct types of
cancer cells (acute myeloid leukemia, or AML, and acute
lymphoblastic leukemia, or ALL) showed activity differences in more
than 50 of their several thousand genes.
</P>
<P>
   The differing gene signatures alone told which cells were which,
said the scientists. When genes are active, they make proteins;
when genes are off, no protein is made. A combination of the wrong
proteins being made or the right ones not being made cause cells to
become malignant.
</P>
<P>
   The results show that what scientists had predicted was in fact
feasible, said Dr. Todd Golub, a physician and scientist at the
Whitehead Institute and Dana-Farber.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are two types of leukemias that appear to be a single
disease under the microscope,'' said Golub, adding that it requires
experienced pathologists using highly specialized equipment to
distinguish them in clinical practice. But the diagnosis is
crucial, he said, because the two types of leukemia have different
prognoses and need to be treated differently.
</P>
<P>
   The report in journal Science, authored by Golub, Eric S.
Lander, also of the Whitehead, and a number of other scientists, is
the first success in what cancer scientists believe will be a new
approach to diagnosing and treating cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a window into the future in terms of getting at the
fundamental genetic abnormalities (in cancer cells) and also being
able to intelligently classify cancers,'' said Dr. Jerome Groopman,
chief of experimental medicine at Beth-Israel Deaconess Medical
Center.
</P>
<P>
   In traditional cancer diagnoses, specialists take samples of a
tumor from the patient and study them under the microscope, looking
for characteristic abnormalities in the way cells look or the way
they absorb chemical stains. Sometimes the differences are hard to
identify and the pathologist is required to make a judgment call.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the research was to find out if cancer cells could
be differentiated entirely by genetic differences, which would be
an objective, systematic approach in which the gene chips and
computer analyses would give an answer that didn't depend on human
judgment. Moreover, said Golub, the technique could also be used to
make distinctions that haven't yet been found between some types of
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Once the differences in gene activity have been discovered,
Golub said, a DNA chip that looks just for those differences can be
used as a test for varying cancer types.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at the National Cancer Institute, using techniques
devised in the Human Genome Project for mapping and deciphering all
the 100,000 or human genes, have discovered thousands of genes that
are expressed _ that is, are active _ in cancer cells. Dr. Richard
Klausner, director of the NCI, spoke recently about the value of
classifying cancers by their genetic patterns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Classifying them is incredibly important,'' he said. ``You
need to have a meaningful diagnostic classification to have
meaningful therapy.'' For example, said Klausner, a cancer known as
diffuse large-cell lymphoma is currently being studied to determine
whether it is one, two, or more different diseases. Genetic
patterns, it is hoped, will help find the answer, making it
possible to say which patients will respond well to which drugs,
which patients will go into remission and be cured, and which will
relapse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
