u f BC-STATES-SPACE-NAT     10-14 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-SPACE-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        TEXAS SPACEPORT FACES LEGISLATIVE HURDLES
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Alex Canizares  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Oct. 14 -- The Texas congressional delegation sent a
letter Thursday urging a space launch company to choose south Texas
as a site for a spaceport. But obstacles remain before the Texans'
dream of being the home of spaceport for reusable launch vehicles
becomes a reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Texas delegation wishes to express to you our desire that
the site for the Spaceport be in Texas,'' read a letter to Steve
Wurst, president of Space Access, a space launch company that is
narrowing its decision of where to construct a runway and hangar
for its shuttles to two sites in South Texas, at least one in
Florida, and one in California.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Solomon Ortiz, D-Corpus Christi, was one of the 23
lawmakers to sign the letter.
</P>
<P>
   Valley officials hope the site will boost the Valley's economy
by hiring employees and bringing in tourists.
</P>
<P>
   But hurdles remain before Space Access makes a decision about
where -- or whether at all -- to build a spaceport.
</P>
<P>
   One obstacle involves federal paperwork, which entails
environmental inspections of the two Texas sites, one in Brazoria
County and the other between Corpus Christi and the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to ensure that the [Federal Aviation Administration]
licenses aren't a problem, `` said Tom Moser, spokesman for the
Texas Aerospace Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Texas plans to use the site for reusable launch vehicles, which
would go to space and return needing only refueling. Since there
has never been a reusable launch, FAA must establish rules to
license their launch. The FAA is finalizing the rules, which will
then need approval by the Office of Management and Budget.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Aerospace commission has not submitted an application
for a licence, but has made a ``compelling enough'' business offer
to the FAA, Moser said, by claiming it has adequate weather,
infrastructure, and a location near water.
</P>
<P>
   Another obstacle to a port being built at all is that launch
companies may not be able to afford it unless Congress approves
space launch legislation that offers loan gaurantees to the private
sector.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, introduced by Sen. John Breaux, D-La., would offer
$500 million of govnernment-backed loans to the commercial space
launch industry. Because space launches are risky, investors are
wary of giving money to launch companies. The bill would provide
government backing that could trigger $5 billion in loans,
according to Breaux.
</P>
<P>
   Without government backing, the companies may struggle to raise
enough capital to build the site, Moser said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Breaux bill sends a signal to the private sector that the
government wants them to do this,'' Moser said. If the bill fails,
``companies won't be able to get financing to build the vehicle, so
we wouldn't need the spaceport.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, to keep [the site] on the timeline that these
companies have created, this bill is very important,'' said Shirley
Clowers of the Harlingen Chamber of Commerce, which has been trying
to garner support for the project for two years.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's fate is unclear. Although some Senators have voiced
support for it, the measure failed to gain support in Congress last
year, and some small companies have opposed it on the grounds that
it will only help larger companies who don't need loan gaurantees.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Space Access, along with other launch vehicle companies,
asked Congress this week to approve the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Space Access has yet to build its resuable, 747-size space
shuttle, which it wants to launch from the spaceport.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
