<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ACCUSES GOP OF `RECKLESS PARTISANSHIP' IN WAKE OF TREATY'S
DEFEAT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton denounced congressional
Republicans on Thursday for ``reckless partisanship'' after the
Senate rejected a nuclear test ban treaty and as the House attempts
to force him to sign budget bills he opposes.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between the Republican-led Congress and the Democratic
White House appear at a new low just as another deadline looms for
a government shutdown next Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton held an hourlong news conference in the East Room just a
day after the Senate handed him the biggest foreign policy defeat
of his presidency _ and amid some signs that political retribution
has been simmering since Clinton's impeachment played a role.
</P>
<P>
   ``In recent days, members of the congressional majority have
displayed a reckless partisanship. It threatens America's economic
well-being and now our national security,'' Clinton said in his
opening statement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton accused ``hard-line Republicans'' of acting
``irresponsibly'' in forcing a vote on the Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty rather than allowing it to be withdrawn. And, he accused
Republicans of turning to isolationism at a time when the United
States is the lone superpower.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was partisan politics of the worst kind because it was so
blatant and because of the risks it poses to the safety of the
American people and the world,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., denied politics was
afoot. ``I reject any suggestion of reckless partisanship. If there
is any partisanship, it's on the other side,'' he said. Lott said
he was proud of the vote to defeat the treaty, which he called a
danger to the nation's security.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton refused to accept any responsibility for the treaty's
defeat, even though the White House and Democrats demanded Senate
action at a time they lacked the votes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he assumed there would be hearings that would allow
him to address opponents concerns for a verifiable test ban.
Instead, Lott gave Democrats eight days to make their case and
allowed the administration no chance to offer safeguards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have reached an all-time low in relations between the
executive and legislative branches. You'd probably have to go back
to 1974 in the dark hours of the Nixon administration to find
something comparable,'' said Marshall Whitman, a government expert
with the conservative Heritage Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   A House Republican leadership aide said GOP members find Clinton
untrustworthy, a fallout not just of the impeachment of Clinton
sparked by accusations of perjury stemming from his affair with
Monica Lewinsky but from years of double-talk from the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will look you in the face and lie and that hinders any sort
of true negotiations,'' the aide said. ``There's no trust there.''
</P>
<P>
   But references to the sex scandal came from Sen. Jesse Helms,
R-N.C., chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee and
leader of the treaty opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Dismissing a letter supporting the treaty from British Prime
Minister Tony Blair, Helms said he could just imagine Clinton
asking Blair for the letter and, ``I know Tony said `oh yes, I'll
do that; I'll do that and give Monica my regards.''' Helms edited
that remark out of the Congressional Record.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in debate, Helms answered a question by saying, ``It
depends on what your definition of `is,' is,'' a reference to
Clinton's infamous equivocation before the grand jury. The Senate,
along a largely party line vote in February, acquitted Clinton of
impeachment charges brought by the House.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who never mentioned Helms by name, said personal
attacks against him only were an indication of the weakness of the
treaty opponents arguments. ``They think that maybe they can
deflect the analysis of their vote and their argument by attacking
their opponent,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   In a tit-for-tat response, Lott accused Clinton of making
partisan remarks because the president had a weak argument in favor
of the treaty. Sen. Joe Lieberman, a Connecticut Democrat hoping to
fashion a bipartisan resurrection of the treaty, said, ``There is
plenty of blame to go around.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also looked toward next Thursday when a temporary
spending measure expires at midnight, chastising the House
Republicans for ``lurching from one unworkable idea to the next''
while time runs out.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would veto any measure that cuts spending
across-the-board by 1 percent to 3 percent as House Republicans now
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be unconscionable to think that America at its moment
of greatest prosperity, when we've got our first surplus in 30
years, is out there cutting education and several other areas. So
yes, I would (veto the bill),'' Clinton said. He also blasted
Congress for failing to provide money for U.S. obligations in the
Middle East peace process or to help dismantle Russian nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are legitimate differences of opinion, but we can put an
end to the reckless partisanship, to gimmicks and gamesmanship,''
Clinton said. ``We can work for a season of progress, not a winter
of politics. And I am committed to do just that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee, said, ``For a president who took office hoping to bring
America together to tackle our country's toughest problems, it's
sad that his (Clinton's) final chapter has been reduced to tax
hikes and partisan attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans, where conservatives hold a stronger sway,
have often been at odds with Clinton, especially over budget
issues.
</P>
<P>
   They intend to vote next week on the tax hike package that
Clinton proposed in January as part of his budget to pay for
spending increases in education and other areas. The stand-alone
tax hike measure will fail and Democrats contend it is an attempt
to embarrass them and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like another stunt, another gimmick, another effort
at political advantage rather than trying to sit down and figure
out a budget that people can agree to,'' said House Minority Leader
Richard Gephardt, D-Mo. ``We're sitting here wasting time.''
</P>
<P>
   The president chided House Republicans for not wanting to raise
taxes on tobacco companies as a way to curtail teen smoking. ``You
know, they don't have to agree to raise it as much as I proposed,
but it would help to sit down and negotiate that,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   But negotiations any time soon seem unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
