<HEADER>
A7167 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDONESIA-POLITICS-71     10-14 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-POLITICS-710(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA ENTERS FINAL DAYS BEFORE ASSEMBLY SELECTS A PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Indonesia entered the final and most
intense days of its political transition Thursday with
demonstrators and security forces battling in the streets as
President B.J. Habibie pleaded with an electoral assembly to choose
him for a full five-year term.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion was the president's ``accountability speech'' in
which Habibie described what he saw as his accomplishments _ civil
rights and openness, a degree of economic stability and the
political transition itself _ since the forced resignation of his
autocratic predecessor, Suharto, 17 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   What was a ceremonial routine during Suharto's 32 years in power
is now a crucial moment for Habibie, whose political stature has
been slipping. For the first time, there is the possibility that,
in the next two days, the electoral assembly could reject an
accountability speech, dooming Habibie's hopes for election.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Wednesday the 700-member assembly is to choose the next
president in what has become an electoral cliffhanger between
Habibie, his chief challenger, Megawati Sukarnoputri, and a third
candidate, Abdurrahman Wahid, a popular Muslim leader.
</P>
<P>
   At stake, in the minds of most Indonesians, is something more
than personalities or even policies: it is the future of the
movement for reforms in the post-Suharto era.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the candidates may say or do, Habibie, a protege of
Suharto, is seen as representing the old order and Mrs. Megawati,
the daughter of Indonesia's founding president, Sukarno, carries
the nation's hopes for change.
</P>
<P>
   Resting quietly at home after a recent stroke, Suharto remains
the nation's political touchstone. Mrs. Megawati's popularity grows
out of her opposition to him. Habibie's greatest liability is his
personal and political closeness to him.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday the president defied one of the main demands of
reformers, refusing to proceed with an investigation into charges
of corruption by Suharto. That action drew angry chants at protests
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, in the first corruption case brought against
Suharto or his family, a judge acquitted one of his sons, Hutomo
Mandala Putra, who had been accused of bilking the government in a
land deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the witnesses could prove the accused had directly or
indirectly caused a loss to the country,'' said the judge,
Soenarto.
</P>
<P>
   As Habibie spoke Thursday evening, all the forces that came
together in May 1998 to force the resignation of Suharto were
gathered once again at the nation's political center, the
Parliament Building. It was here that the spectacle of thousands of
student demonstrators and the defection of key political supporters
helped force Suharto's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, the student demonstrators chanted and waved
banners opposing Habibie as an apostle of Suharto's discredited
regime. They threw rocks and gasoline bombs and charged at massed
ranks of soldiers and riot policemen with their samurai-style
helmets and tall plastic shields.
</P>
<P>
   The security forces fired tear gas, water cannon and plastic
bullets in a replay of scenes that have become as integral a part
of Indonesia's political process as the assembly meeting that
continued at its measured pace inside the Parliament Building.
</P>
<P>
   The crowds represented Mrs. Megawati's political strength: a
personal popularity that no other candidate comes close to
rivaling. The tumult in the streets outside was a reminder to the
parliamentary delegates of the broad unrest that many people here
warn will erupt if Mrs. Megawati is denied the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``A re-election of Habibie is not going to be definitive; people
are not going to take this lying down,'' said James C. Clad, a
professor of Southeast Asian Studies at Georgetown University. ``It
could move us into a new period of really endemic civil
disobedience.''
</P>
<P>
   In the general election in June, Mrs. Megawati's party won
nearly 34 percent of the votes in a raucous field crowded with
dozens of newly formed parties. Habibie's party, which had been the
vehicle for Suharto's repeated and manipulated re-elections,
finished second with 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The June election involved just 462 of the 700 seats in the
partly appointed electoral assembly that is now meeting. Mrs.
Megawati's victory gave her just 153 of these seats.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the months of power plays and payoffs that have intensified
since the assembly convened at the start of this month, Habibie's
party has the advantage of long political experience and huge sums
of money.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, many foreign and Indonesian analysts have been
aghast at the passivity and sense of entitlement of Mrs. Megawati
and her party in this period of hard bargaining. Accounts abound of
her refusing to meet with political rivals or canceling meetings at
the last moment.
</P>
<P>
   After her plurality in the first contested election in Indonesia
since the mid-1950s, the presidency seemed to be hers to lose. And
indeed, she has been losing ground since then, refusing to make
deals as the political ground shifts rapidly around her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's so aloof! She's not a politician,'' exclaimed Jusuf
Wanandi, who heads a private policy institute, the Center for
Strategic and International Studies. ``It's a good thing that she's
now scared and her people are now scared. Finally they are willing
to compromise, willing to entertain anybody that could help her.''
</P>
<P>
   As the presidential vote approaches, alignments have become
increasingly fragmented and fluid. The electoral process today is
as chaotic and unpredictable as it was packaged and stultifying for
decades under Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   A key bloc of 38 votes or more is held by the military, and its
chief, Gen. Wiranto, is being courted by Habibie with an invitation
this week to be his vice president. A number of analysts say that
the military would feel comfortable with either Habibie or Mrs.
Megawati and that it is likely to wait to align itself with
whichever party seems likely to win.
</P>
<P>
   Abdurrahman Wahid, the Muslim leader, whose party finished third
in the June vote, was originally aligned with Mrs. Megawati, then
broke away to pursue his own candidacy. He is not seen as a strong
candidate on his own, but his endorsement and the votes of his
supporters are considered crucial for Mrs. Megawati to gain a
majority.
</P>
<P>
   Another Muslim leader, Amien Rais, did poorly in June but
remains a key political figure and was chosen last week to head the
electoral assembly. Even more than Mrs. Megawati, he is a reformer
at heart. In the vacuum of her inactivity he has formed a loose
coalition that could also be crucial to her if he chooses to
support her.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a faction of Habibie's party has vigorously
opposed his candidacy for months and could throw its support to
Mrs. Megawati. One indication of the fluidity of this moment, less
than a week before the vote, is that even in this well-defined bloc
the estimates of delegates who might break away range from 20 to 40
to 60.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
