<HEADLINE>
SMALL SCHOOL   CLOSES IN ON A BIG RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The numbers indicate greatness: eight undefeated seasons, four
national championships, and a 145-16-3 record in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Critics argue that the level of competition (Division 3)
mitigates those impressive numbers to some extent.
</P>
<P>
   Horsefeathers.
</P>
<P>
   Winning is winning, and when you have 47 consecutive victories,
as tiny Mount Union has over the past four seasons, you deserve all
the accolades you receive.
</P>
<P>
   The feel-good story to date of this college football season
should be in Alliance, Ohio, Saturday afternoon as the Purple
Raiders go after a record 48 consecutive victories when they meet
Otterbein.
</P>
<P>
   By winning _ and Mount Union is an overwhelming favorite _ the
Purple Raiders would break a tie with Oklahoma, which set the
current NCAA record for consecutive wins in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Mount Union coach Larry Kehres, who holds the all-time mark for
winning percentage (.811) among college football coaches (ahead of
No. 2 Knute Rockne and No. 3 Frank Leahy), understands the apples
and oranges theory concerning the streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mount Union can't break Oklahoma's winning streak because they
are Divison 1 and we're Division 3,'' says Kehres. ``If you were a
longtime Oklahoma person and heard some little school called Mount
Union is breaking your record, you'd go, `What are you talking
about?' I respect that.''
</P>
<P>
   As well he should. But what Mount Union has accomplished also
deserves recognition and respect.
</P>
<P>
   Mount Union has not lost a game since a 20-17 defeat to
Wisconsin-LaCrosse in the semifinals of the 1995 Divison 3
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Which means: no bad games, no let downs, no flat games. The team
has not lost a game in almost four seasons, not four weeks or four
months.
</P>
<P>
   And Kehres has done this going through a couple of recruiting
classes. It wasn't like he brought in a superstar class that kicked
butt for a few years and moved on.
</P>
<P>
   Those classes are gone, and Mount Union is still winning, still
adding to the streak.
</P>
<P>
   At times, the Purple Raiders have been lucky _ they survived a
57-51 triple-overtime battle against John Carroll two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma may have run up its winning streak from 1954 to '56
against tougher competition, but that competition is relative.
Divison 3 football is not Division 1. There are no athletic
scholarships and the athletes are less-skilled, but Mount Union has
done it on a level playing field.
</P>
<P>
   You can argue the merits of the achievement all you want and
talk about how Oklahoma had to beat tougher competition. And that
may all be true.
</P>
<P>
   But the feat of winning 48 games in succession should not, must
not, be denied.
</P>
<P>
   In this era, when negative stories get more attention than
positive ones, Mount Union deserves the 15 minutes of national fame
it has received this week and will receive Saturday if it breaks
the record.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mum's the word in Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State coach Joe Paterno has shut down the media's access to
his players this week in preparation for the Ohio State game,
barring all but three players from speaking.
</P>
<P>
   His argument is that the players are overwhelmed, not just by
the media, but by fans and autograph hounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they need a little time to themselves,'' said Paterno.
``I think this thing has gotten a little bit ridiculous, the amount
of time they have to give up to it. Someone complained to me that
they can't get things done, that there are a lot of things going
on. You keep forgetting that they are college students. You're the
first people that would crucify them if they don't go to class or
they flunk out of school or something happens to them. I've got to
protect them.''
</P>
<P>
   Fine, Joe. Have it your way. But life is not just games on
Saturday afternoon. It's dealing with adversity, it's dealing with
pressures. It's what going to college is all about.
</P>
<P>
   By shutting down access, Paterno is making the game more
important than it is, saying this is a different week than any
other. If the routine is broken, the players might be more uptight
than normal.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State coach John Cooper has made that mistake numerous
times before Buckeye games with Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State-Penn State is a big game, but there will be bigger
ones. There will be bigger things in the players' lives in the
future, far more than a simple game Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Talking to the media doesn't require a lot of time or effort. An
hour a week is enough in most instances. A few innocuous quotes,
and life goes on.
</P>
<P>
   It's part of life. Paterno, as much as anyone, should know that.
</P>
<P>
   Deal with it and move on. Don't make it bigger or more important
than it should be by breaking the routine.
</P>
<P>
   Paterno has chosen not to do that. If Penn State loses to Ohio
State, the finger will be pointed in a lot of directions, but not
at the media.
</P>
<P>
   A Pitt-fall for BC?
</P>
<P>
   The loss to Temple last Saturday exposed Boston College's
weaknesses and magnified the challenge the team now faces. At 4-1
(instead of 5-0), the Eagles will have to pull off a few upsets to
become bowl-eligible with six wins.
</P>
<P>
   The game against Pittsburgh Saturday looks like a tossup, with
the Eagles holding the home-field edge.
</P>
<P>
   After that, there are no guarantees. The Eagles could very well
lose all their remaining games, which would put another dark cloud
over the program at The Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the uncertainty is the health of starting quarterback
Tim Hasselbeck, who injured his right shoulder in the 24-14 loss to
Temple.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Tom O'Brien's dilemma is clear. Hasselbeck might be
healthy enough to play, but also fragile enough that one hit could
sideline him for several weeks or the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   What should O'Brien do?
</P>
<P>
   He could sit Hasselbeck for a week to get him healthy and play
Brian St. Pierre instead. If he does that and St. Pierre has a
strong game to help beat Pittsburgh, O'Brien's got a quarterback
dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   All of that makes Saturday's game the biggest of the season for
BC, one that could determine the course of the season and the
program.
</P>
<P>
   Either the Eagles move on and build, or they fall back into what
could be another deadly 4-7 season.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Big East feast
</P>
<P>
   The Big East finally has a national marquee game. Syracuse at
Virginia Tech has drawn the ESPN Game Day traveling set to
Blacksburg, Va. It will be the first time a Big East game has been
covered by the network's top crew . . . With Florida State's Peter
Warrick sitting out another game because of legal problems, the
quest for the Heisman Trophy for the wide receiver becomes more
difficult. The character issue involved in committing what was a
petty crime (paying less than 10 percent for more than $400 worth
of merchandise) is not as important to many voters as simply not
playing in games . . . The first BCS ratings, which will determine
the teams in the Sugar Bowl Jan. 4, come out next week. Right now,
Florida State and Nebraska are 1-2, which could be a problem for
undefeated Virginia Tech and Penn State if everyone runs the table.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
