<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON THREATENS TO VETO ACROSS-THE-BUDGET CUTS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., Texas)   By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Thursday that if Republicans
in Congress pressed ahead with their latest plan for meeting budget
targets _ an across-the-board cut in spending on all government
programs _ he would veto the measure.
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference, the president accused Republicans of
``lurching from one unworkable idea to the next'' and urged them to
``put an end to reckless partisanship, to gimmicks and
gamesmanship.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the Republican leader, called
his own news conference immediately following the president's and
responded, ``If there is any partisanship, it's on the other
side.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott insisted that he and his allies in the House of
Representatives had not made a final decision on whether to seek
spending reductions in all programs, but he said: ``If the choice
comes down to protecting Social Security or cutting across the
board just a little nick off of every program, I believe the
American people would support that. I would.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now if he wants to veto it because of that reason, I guess he
can, but I don't think that would be the responsible thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   On the budget, the president and the Republican leaders in
Congress are like two feral animals circling each other, working
for a position that will be advantageous when the inevitable clash
occurs.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the spending bills to finance the various Departments
and agencies in the fiscal year that began Oct. 1 have still not
been enacted. Government offices have remained open under temporary
legislation extending their spending authority, but that measure
expires Oct. 21.
</P>
<P>
   The president and Congress will almost certainly agree next week
to another extension, but sooner or later concessions will have to
be made by one side, the other or both. Clinton has generally
prevailed politically in such battles in recent years, and
Republicans are determined not to let that happen this year.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the Senate gave final legislative approval to the
Defense Department's spending bill, and the House approved a final
version of a measure for veterans, housing and other programs. With
most of the controversies bypassed, the president is likely to sign
them.
</P>
<P>
   But the House also passed a funding measure for the District of
Columbia that is so similar to one the president vetoed last month
that it is clearly ripe for another veto.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said Clinton would probably veto the Interior
Department's spending bill on the ground that provisions to help
oil and mining companies would be detrimental to the environment.
In a speech on Wednesday, Clinton said: ``If the Interior bill
lands on my desk looking like it does now, I will give it a good
environmental response. I will send it straight back to the
recycling bin.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest stumbling block is the largest of all spending
bills, the one for the Departments of Labor, Education and Health
and Human Services. Republican leaders have not yet assembled a
measure that can attain a majority in Congress, much less pass
Presidential muster.
</P>
<P>
   To meet their self-imposed goals of not raising taxes and not
spending any money raised by Social Security taxes above what is
needed for Social Security benefits, Republicans have floated and
then discarded several options.
</P>
<P>
   One would have made bookkeeping adjustments so that a good deal
of spending was shuffled into the next fiscal year. Another would
have delayed payments of tax credits to low-income workers.
</P>
<P>
   The latest idea is the across-the-board spending reduction in
all government programs. Estimates of how large the cuts would be
have ranged from 0.5 percent to 2.5 percent. Lott Thursday called
the plan ``a work in progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was asked at his news conference whether he would veto
such a measure. He replied: ``I would have no choice. It would be
unconscionable to think that America at its moment of greatest
prosperity, when we've got our first surplus in 30 years, is out
there cutting education and several other areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton then renewed his proposal for meeting the spending needs
by raising the tax on cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Armey of Texas, the House majority leader, accused the
president of wanting to raise taxes on the poor. He cited studies
showing that 55 percent of tobacco taxes are paid by people making
less than $30,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said Thursday they might try to embarrass the
president and Democrats in the House by calling for an up or down
vote next week on the entire $90 billion in tax increases in the
president's budget, including the tobacco tax. The taxes are sure
to be rejected.
</P>
</TEXT>
