<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AIRS ADS CRITICAL OF SENATE'S REJECTION TO RATIFY TREATY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore, sensing a political
opportunity in the Senate's rejection of the nuclear test ban
treaty, quickly taped campaign commercials denouncing the vote and
rushed them on to the air Thursday as the first television ads of
his White House bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in my heart this vote does not speak for the
American people,'' Gore says in the 60-second ad. He called on
voters for ``your mandate'' to resubmit the treaty if he is elected
president.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic vice president said he had worked on arms control
for 20 years and would send the pact back to the Senate, ``because
unless we get this one right nothing else matters.'' In other
appearances, Gore said that resubmission would be the first act of
his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Gore described the commercials, paid for by the Gore 2000
campaign, as he flew back to Washington from a three-day campaign
tour in the West. He had made criticism of the Senate action a key
piece of public appearances as soon as the vote occurred Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The quick move by Gore to seize on the Senate vote was also
intended to show that the vice president had taken personal charge
of his troubled political operation. Gore said that after the
Senate vote he called his political team and announced his
intention to tape the ads. Media adviser Carter Eskew, working from
Washington, assembled a video team that completed taping the
commercial near midnight Wednesday in a hotel suite in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Gore stressed that the ad was a largely personal effort and gave
reporters aboard Air Force Two a copy of the final script with his
heavy editing. Gore said he told President Clinton about the ads in
a telephone call early Thursday and that the response was
``positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Senate action allows Gore to campaign on arms
control, an issue he knows well, he expressed sorrow that the
matter had become available for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tragedy for the country that has to be rectified,''
Gore said on Air Force Two. ``Nothing would make me happier than to
not have this issue on the table by virtue of the Senate having
ratified the treaty.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the commercials would run nationally but with a
concentration of airings in early-voting Iowa and New Hampshire.
Beyond those states, an aide said, the heaviest purchase of
broadcast time was apparently on CNN nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's ads are the first in the Democratic race.
</P>
<P>
   In the Republican race, magazine publisher Steve Forbes, whose
campaign is largely self-financed, has been on and off the air
several times with ads about himself and his position on several
issues. Forbes is expected soon to launch ads aimed at Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas, the GOP front-runner, and Bush's campaign is
apparently ready to respond in kind.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore ad came as a new poll showed Gore lagging farther
behind Bradley in New Hampshire, site of the first presidential
primary. A Zogby International survey found that among likely
Democratic voters in the Granite State, Bradley led Gore 45 percent
to 36.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, taken Friday through Sunday, found that in
general-election matchups among all New Hampshire voters, Bradley
led Bush 47.6 percent to 40.8 percent, while Gore trailed Bush 49.8
percent to 39.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's rhetorical tone in the ad is less heated than his initial
reaction to the Senate vote.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement just minutes after the Senate acted, Gore called
rejection of the treaty ``breathtakingly irresponsible'' and ``one
of the most dangerous votes ever cast in the Senate. ... I'm angry
about it.'' He repeated similar sentiments later Wednesday to a
machinists union rally and a fund-raising dinner in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The ad also does not mention, as Gore did in the speeches, that
Gov. Bush had voiced opposition to the pact, formally known as the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Bush issued a statement early Thursday that said: ``The
president failed to make the case that this treaty was in America's
best interests. I support a continued moratorium on nuclear testing
and oppose the treaty.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the treaty was not verifiable. He said it would have
weakened the United States while allowing ``rogue'' nations, such
as Iraq and North Korea, to test nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``If elected president, I will be committed to stopping
proliferation, but this flawed treaty was not the way to further
the cause of peace in the world,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to Gore's statements, Bush spokesman Mindy Tucker said,
``This issue should not be a political question. It's a matter of
national security. Governor Bush's position on this is based on his
view of this as an issue of national security.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore does point out in the ad that ``the last Republican
president'' _ Bush's father _ ``stopped all U.S. testing'' and that
the treaty was supported by chairmen of the military Joint Chiefs
of Staff from the Bush administration as well as those of
Presidents Clinton, Reagan and Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since President Kennedy began the effort almost 40 years ago,
Democrats and Republicans have made nuclear arms control a national
priority,'' Clinton says in the ad. ``But now the Republican Senate
has rejected the nuclear test ban treaty signed by 154 nations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in my heart this vote does not speak for the
American people. So why don't we do something about it?'' Gore
says. ``I believe campaigns should be about the future, and there's
no more important challenge than stopping the spread of nuclear
weapons. I ask for your support and your mandate, if elected
president, to send this treaty back to the Senate with your demand
that they ratify it. ... If you agree, we can change this mistake
and once again lead the world toward peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore delivered a similar message after arriving in the capital
to the Democratic Leadership Council, a group of party centrists
which he helped form in the mid-1980s and whose support is critical
to his White House campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
