<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GE-POWER15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Officials to mark GE unit's opening
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A fast-growing General Electric Co. business today
officially opens a high-tech customer service center in Cobb County
that will monitor a global network of electric power plants.
</P>
<P>
   The center moved last year from Schenectady, N.Y., to Wildwood
Office Park. It has grown from 450 employees to 1,000 to keep pace
with the booming demand for natural gas-fired turbines used at such
plants.
</P>
<P>
   The facility is operated by GE Energy Services, a $3.5
billion-a-year GE unit based in Atlanta. The offices first opened
in June 1998, but the company is staging a ceremonial headquarters
opening today with top executives attending. Gov. Roy Barnes is
also scheduled to appear.
</P>
<P>
   About 650 employees have been recruited locally, said GE
spokeswoman Jan Smith. The rest were relocated from upstate New
York and other GE locations.
</P>
<P>
   GE Energy Services has contracts for various services with more
than 120 power plants in 22 countries. The Atlanta customer service
center is staffed 24 hours a day and monitors operations of
GE-manufactured turbines at 50 plants around the world.
</P>
<P>
   GE Energy Services is part of Schenectady-based GE Power
Systems, a $9.5 billion-a-year unit that builds power plants and
equipment. The parent General Electric Co. earlier this month
reported that the Power Systems unit posted a 51 percent increase
in operating profit for the third quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Power Systems is benefiting from strong global demand for
natural gas-fired turbines, which are much cheaper to build than
other technologies and burn a relatively clean fuel.
</P>
<P>
   The unit in July signed contracts valued at $210 million to
design and maintain power plants for Gulf Power Co. and Alabama
Power Co., both subsidiaries of Atlanta-based Southern Co.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Power Systems has also announced deals with
utility companies in Venezuela and Chile, and the largest oil and
gas companies in Mexico and Brazil. The division announced this
week that it will build a $1.9 billion power plant for Entergy, the
New Orleans-based utility.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Nardelli, president and chief executive of Power Systems,
has had such success that he is reported to be in contention to
succeed GE Chairman Jack Welch, who is scheduled to retire at the
end of the year. Nardelli is scheduled to attend today's Atlanta
grand opening.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
