<HEADER>
A7185 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS &LR;      10-14 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERVIS ELLISON IS MAKING STRIDES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WALTHAM _ The moment went relatively unnoticed Wednesday at the
FleetCenter, given the time (4:38 left in the first quarter), score
(15-8, Charlotte), and overall situation (bored fans waiting for
the Red Sox-Yankees to start).
</P>
<P>
   Onto a basketball court, in any kind of quasi-meaningful
situation for the first time since March 11, 1998, strode Pervis
Ellison. He had that familiar, loping gait and the now-familiar
dredlocks in a ponytail. It was a moment more than a few Celtic
fans wondered if they'd ever see again: Ellison as a Celtic.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't dazzle anyone. He didn't embarrass anyone. He played
12 minutes and had 4 points, 3 rebounds, and 1 assist. It's not all
that different a line from the submission of March 11 against
Atlanta (2 points, 2 rebounds, 9 minutes).
</P>
<P>
   But there was one big difference: After the Hawks game, Ellison
went on the injured list for the remainder of the season because he
wasn't in shape. This year, he still isn't in the kind of shape
coach Rick Pitino would like, but he's apparently getting there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to get my timing back,'' Ellison said after
the game Wednesday. ``It felt great to be out there. It would have
felt even better if I had done anything.''
</P>
<P>
   That last sentence demonstrates Ellison's value to the Celtics,
maybe even more than whatever he can deliver on the court. He's
enormously popular among his teammates, as much for his humor as
for his even-keel demeanor. He wants to be a leader. He wants to be
a locker room presence.
</P>
<P>
   But for that to happen, he has to play. And for that to happen,
he has to spit in the face of his personal history and avoid
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're out there in the heat of battle, you don't think
about injuries,'' said Ellison, who has seen little heat the last
three years. ``It's the farthest thing from my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's go back and revisit some of the maladies that have
afflicted Ellison in his five years with the Celtics:
</P>
<P>
   Year 1: He missed 27 games mostly because of knee
rehabilitation. Yet the promise was there in two huge outings: a
19-point, 10-rebound effort against Denver in his Boston debut, and
a big performance in Game 2 of their playoff series with Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Year 2: His Ripken-esque year in Boston. He totaled 69 games,
led the Celtics in blocked shots, and even had 29 starts. Of the 13
missed games, one was a suspension for fighting with Miami's Kurt
Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Year 3: The slide begins. He played six games and was out for
the year after, according to the Celtics, he dropped a coffee table
on his foot while helping Greg Minor move furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Year 4: Pitino arrives and, to everyone's surprise, is smitten
with Ellison's personality. He names him a captain. But Ellison
appears in only 33 games and is placed on the IL for the final 20
games because he's out of shape.
</P>
<P>
   Year 5: Season-DNP. He underwent ankle surgery in November
during the lockout and never made it back.
</P>
<P>
   Year 6: Who knows?
</P>
<P>
   Ellison could be the test case for ``What Is Wrong With
Guaranteed Contracts.'' He could be the test case for ``How To Make
The System Work For You'' or ``Skating, NBA Style.'' He has
collected a lot of money in Boston for not a lot of work, which has
made him the subject of a lot of ridicule.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino, always talking positive, figures Ellison may actually be
involved this season, if for no other reason than it's the last
year of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to be a UMass grad to figure that out,'' the
UMass alum said. ``If he continually misses games, no one is going
to take him seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was counting on Ellison, Pitino said, ``If he
totally dedicates himself, he is our best big man. He would be a
starter. But he'd have to totally dedicate himself and totally turn
himself over. I am not counting on him, based on his history. If he
can give us something, that's great.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Pitino said Ellison is not in shape and is unfamiliar
with the offense.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison didn't look too out of whack against the Hornets. Two of
his three rebounds were off the offensive glass, a team weakness
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt a little awkward,'' he said. ``But that's why you have
an exhibition season.''
</P>
<P>
   He then said he was simply happy to be playing basketball again,
which, given his history, is understandable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 1947EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
