<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-FLOODS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN VILLAGES REMAIN CUT OFF AFTER FLOODS AND MUDSLIDES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZACAPOAXTLA, Mexico _ They walked 16 hours through fog and
drizzle, but when the Indian men in mud-spattered sandals arrived
safely at this mountain town in search of food for their devastated
hamlet, they broke into a murmured chant, thanking the Virgin for
small blessings amid vast misfortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost everything,'' said Francisco Santiago Rodriguez,
whispering in broken Spanish as he and his 37 Totonaco-speaking
neighbors lined up for bean broth at a sidewalk soup kitchen.
Later, at a municipal warehouse, the men shouldered bags of corn
meal and sugar to bear back to their village, Olintla, where homes,
cattle and crops were swept away last week by flash floods and
mudslides.
</P>
<P>
   Olintla, like hundreds of other settlements across four states
in eastern Mexico, remained cut off Thursday from outside help, 10
days after one of Mexico's worst natural disasters. Virtually all
country roads in the region have been washed out, and a vengeful
fog had grounded helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   The men of Olintla were part of a tide of thousands of storm
victims who have converged on Zacapoaxtla, a county seat of 27,000
bedraggled souls that straddles a hillside shoulder in northern
Puebla state 95 miles east of Mexico City. Hundreds of Zacapoaxtla
residents have themselves lost homes and businesses, but those who
still have a roof and floor space have opened their doors to the
arriving refugees. The government is distributing free food and
medical supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never dreamed that rain could hit so hard,'' Gildardo
Castaneda Dominguez, Zacapoaxtla's mayor, said to a visitor as he
helped form a clamorous crowd of peasants seeking foodstuffs into a
line snaking along the front edge of the tile-roofed town hall.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican government said Thursday that the death toll had
risen to 360 from the tropical rains that deluged Puebla, Veracruz,
Hidalgo and Tabasco states on Oct. 4 and 5 and have continued as a
drizzle since. Estimates by the Catholic church and other private
groups have put the toll above 500.
</P>
<P>
   The rains were like one of those summer downpours that drops
buckets of water for a few minutes, then clears. But this deluge
did not clear. Fueled by a tropical depression hanging over the
Gulf of Mexico, it dumped 30 inches of rain in three days,
according to Mexico's National Water Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The roiling currents of two rivers flowing past Zacapoaxtla
swept away scores of riverside shanties, drowning eight people. As
hillsides began to give way, seven others, including a local
policeman, were crushed by sliding mud. Other villages and towns
along a 600-mile stretch of the Gulf Coast suffered even more
tragic consequences.
</P>
<P>
   In Teziutlan, 20 miles east of Zacapoaxtla, a cliff-top cemetery
tore down a hillside, sweeping away dozens of homes. The death toll
there reached 102 on Thursday, officials said. In Gutierrez Zamora,
a coastal town in Veracruz, a 12-foot wave at the front edge of a
flash flood swept away an entire riverside neighborhood, killing
dozens.
</P>
<P>
   Those dramatic tragedies have attracted news coverage, but parts
of hundreds of other settlements across the Gulf Coast region were
swept away in the same hours by rampaging waters and sliding mud.
Many villages that suffered tremendous damage have received little
or no help because authorities cannot get to them except on foot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tapayula doesn't exist anymore,'' said Zeferino Ramos Peralta,
a schoolteacher who arrived here Wednesday night, speaking of a
village nestled in a valley 10 miles north of Zacapoaxtla.
Mudslides hit Tapayula from two sides.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Amador Manzanero, a radio repairman and volunteer
ambulance driver, said peasants who had passed Tapayula on their
trek to Zacapoaxtla had reported that only the bell tower of the
church was visible above the mud.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only catastrophe in all my villages,'' said the Rev.
Jose Margarito Robles, a priest based in Zacapoaxtla who tends to
several dozen settlements in the surrounding mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Early Wednesday, during a brief break in the fog, army pilots
flew a helicopter from Zacapoaxtla to a nearby town cut off from
outside help, carrying a doctor and foodstuffs and hoping to rescue
a few of dozens of tourists stranded there. But the fog closed in
and the helicopter could not leave, said Valdivieso Suastegui, an
Interior Ministry official working here.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, how Mexico should face the disaster became a
national issue when President Ernesto Zedillo was confronted by a
throng of victims in Veracruz state imploring him to ask the United
States for aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, we Mexicans can handle this ourselves,'' Zedillo
responded.
</P>
<P>
   That comment provoked outcry from opposition lawmakers, who
criticized it as a display of stubborn nationalism, and the
government has since softened its stance. Cash donations from
foreign friends are welcome, and will be donated to the Mexican Red
Cross, the government says. But since hundreds of communities are
cut off from truck traffic, the government still will not accept
shipments of food or medicine.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said on Wednesday that Americans ``as a people
and as a government stand ready to help in any way we can,''
according to a statement by the American Embassy. The United States
has offered $100,000 in immediate cash aid, the statement said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 1948EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0332 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7188 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      10-14 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREW, MEET BEN. BEN, MEET DREW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Five games are gone, and the starting tight
end has only 11 catches, so we feel it's time to re-introduce Drew
Bledsoe to Ben Coates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drew . . . Ben. Ben . . . Drew.''
</P>
<P>
   With those formalities out of the way, let's make sure that a
little selective amnesia hasn't taken place by going over Coates's
resume. He is a five-time Pro Bowler who has caught 50 touchdown
passes in his career. Only two other tight ends have caught more TD
passes in NFL history _ Jerry Smith and Dave Casper, who leads
Coates by only two. Coates is sixth all-time among tight ends in
receptions (468).
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1994, Drew, Ben Coates set a record for most receptions
by a tight end with 96. Remember? It was you who threw him those
balls. The following year, Coates caught 84 passes. He has caught
50 or more passes in six consecutive seasons. That's second best
all-time. Only quasi-tight end Shannon Sharpe has more consecutive
50-catch seasons (seven), and Coates has done it more consecutive
times than Kellen Winslow, a Hall of Famer who was coached by none
other than Ernie Zampese, the Patriots' offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   On his current pace, Coates won't even break 35 receptions,
which is fine for, say, Lovett Purnell, but for Ben Coates?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always gonna be frustrating when you're used to catching
50 or 60 balls at the end of the season and you only have 11 right
now,'' said Coates. ``You make goals as a player. A lot of players
do that. If you catch 60 balls this year, you try to do that every
year so you can make a contribution to the team.''
</P>
<P>
   We've heard many explanations as to why the number of passes to
Coates has decreased. The popular theory is that Terry Glenn is
healthy, therefore he will be the go-to guy. Understandable. Of
course, back in '96, the Super Bowl season when Glenn caught 90
balls as a rookie, Coates caught 62 and nine touchdown passes.
</P>
<P>
   Now you hear Bledsoe say, ``Teams are taking Ben out of our
offense.'' This leads to the old ``you say `to-may-to,' I say
`to-mah-to' '' bit, as Coates doesn't appear to share that thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think teams are trying to take me away at all,'' said
Coates. ``I'm seeing a lot more man-to-man coverage than I've seen
at any time in my career. Like I said before, they're going with
the hot guy, and `T' (Glenn) is still the hot guy. I don't see that
changing, so I think my role is going to be the same unless
something happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously that ``something'' could be injuries. Troy Brown
(ankle sprain) likely won't play Sunday against Miami. There's a
theory that Coates will see a lot of Brown's third-down
opportunities. Maybe. Because there's been such attention paid to
this situation around the league, perhaps Bledsoe will be more
conscious of his once-favorite receiver and get him the ball. One
need only harken back to the Patriots' 21-16 win over the Colts
Nov. 1, when Coates caught 10 passes for 109 yards and one
touchdown. That week, both Glenn and Brown were out of the lineup.
Coates had Colts draped all over him, but Bledsoe kept forcing the
ball into him, and Coates kept catching it in a brilliant
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Last week in Kansas City, Bledsoe tried to force one in and it
was intercepted. He tried to force another in and Coates couldn't
hold it in double-coverage.
</P>
<P>
   As long as the Patriots were winning, it didn't matter how they
won or who got the ball. But after a loss, issues do arise. And one
of them is ``Where's Ben?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know, to be honest,'' said Coates, who has
caught 61 career passes, including nine for touchdowns, against
Miami. ``Everybody's healthy, and they're just using other guys to
throw it to. Maybe it'll change, maybe it won't. Right now, it's
just not coming my way, period.''
</P>
<P>
   Coates has had to listen to all sorts of wild speculation about
himself because of this situation. One idea is that he is slowing
down. A second is that he is injured. And a third is that perhaps
the Patriots are phasing him out of the offense so they won't have
to deal with re-signing him when his contract expires after next
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt, I feel great,'' Coates said. ``I've had no
injuries. My body feels good. No problems. Nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Pete Carroll insisted this week, ``This has nothing to do with
Ben.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A game ago, I think the explanation was clear the ball went
outside all day long for obvious reasons,'' Carroll said. ``This
last week, we had a normal mix of what we are doing, although we
were trying to get the ball downfield against their corners. But we
went to Ben three, four, five times, something like that. He caught
one that was called back. It's just the way it's happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anything to this at all. We would rather
have Ben catching passes three to five times a game to make sure
that people have to pay attention to him. I'm not real pleased with
the fact that hasn't happened, because it doesn't give us the
balance that we would like. One game doesn't matter, but when you
take it over two or three games, then we need to get him back
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Coates was thrown the possibility that it will all balance out
in the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it will,'' said Coates. ``I'm not saying it will. I
hope I can contribute to the team in some kind of way. I'm just
used to being in here and being a guy who's involved in what's
going on. It's strange not to be contributing to the team in that
area.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Patriots have proven anything over the years, it's that
when times are tough and the Patriots are having trouble moving the
offense, Coates has always been there. Over the last two weeks, the
Patriots have scored 19 and 14 points respectively. In that time,
Coates has caught a total of one pass.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Coates caught only one ball over a two-game span
was in the dark, dank pre-Bledsoe era. It can most assuredly be
written that Bledsoe's career took off because he had Coates to
throw to, and Coates's career became what it was because of
Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   But now this long-standing relationship has grown distant, and
it needs a re-introduction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drew . . . .Ben. Ben . . . Drew.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
