<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Oct. 14 and thereafter. For questions about stories, please contact
Elizabeth Ferry Slocum at the Daily News at (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   McCARTHY-SEEING (Los Angeles) _ Turnabout's only fair play. On
any given day in Los Angeles County, an estimated 10,000 guide dogs
help blind people make it through the perils of daily life. So, how
about a guide person helping a blind golden retriever puppy get
around? A school teacher with a husband, two kids, one horse and
four dogs has adopted a blind pup and named it after one of the
kids in her kindergarten class. By Dennis McCarthy. (Will run on
the ``a'' national and ``n'' state news files.)
</P>
<P>
   LOTTO-WINNER (Los Angeles) _ A 66-year-old Calabasas attorney
who says he rarely plays the lottery is now $14 million richer. He
said he plans to continue practicing law and perhaps buy a new car
with his winnings, which he took as cash value. By Jesse Hiestand.
(Will run on the ``n'' state news files.)
</P>
<P>
   CANCER-SCHOOLS (Los Angeles) _ State and county officials vowed
to find money to conduct cancer studies following the Los Angeles
Daily News' disclosure that Los Angeles County was balking at a
state-ordered study at Polytechnic High and Towne Avenue Elementary
schools. County supervisors are under pressure to allocate funds
for the county study. By Terry Hardy. (Will run on the ``n'' state
news files.)
</P>
<P>
   FEES-CHECKING (Los Angeles) _ Consumers in California this year
paid on average $202 to maintain a regular checking account, less
than the national average but still a double-digit percentage
increase from 1997, according to a survey released Thursday. By
Chris Sieroty. (Will run on the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TITLE-FINE (Los Angeles) _ First American Title Company was
fined $2.5 million and suspended for one day for giving kickbacks
to real estate agents who referred title or escrow business to the
company, California Insurance Commissioner Chuck Quackenbush
announced Thursday.The company also agreed that starting Monday, it
will not market its title services in Los Angeles County for five
days. By Gregory Wilcox. (Will run on the ``f'' financial news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   MAILBOX-ADDRESS (Los Angeles) _ The U.S. Postal Service diffused
a controversial ruling when it announced late Thursday a change in
yet-to-be-enacted rules governing private mailboxes. The USPS will
allow owners of those mailboxes to use the (no.) designation for
their mailbox address, instead of the hugely unpopular PMB it tried
to force the industry to change to. Originally, the Postal Service
said the PMB would thwart fraud by helping consumers differentiate
between large businesses and those hiding behind post office boxes.
But legitimate owners of those boxes complained bitterly, saying
their business would be hurt. By Dave McNary. (Will run on the
``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SUPERIOR-PARTS (Los Angeles) _ Superior Industries Inc., the Van
Nuys-based manufacturer of automotive wheel parts, is expected to
release strong quarterly earnings Friday. By Gregory Wilcox. (Will
run on the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KSWISS-EARNINGS (Los Angeles) _ K-Swiss Inc. reported strong
quarterly earnings after the markets closed Thursday, a week after
the company had warned that a slowdown in orders would hurt
earnings in six months. By Dave McNary. (Will run on the ``f''
financial news file.)
</P>
