<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7200 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIE-TRENDS15-COX     10-14 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-TRENDS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Heaven knocks on Hollywood's door
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Today isn't just another opening weekend at the
movies.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood's $65 million ``Fight Club,'' with previous Oscar
nominees Brad Pitt and Ed Norton trading jawbreaking uppercuts in a
bloody tale of anti-establishment pugilism, is expected to ignite
the most controversy at the box office. But a smaller, far less
publicized film with a distinct religious connection _ the $8.5
million ``The Omega Code'' _ is boldly challenging Hollywood at its
own game.
</P>
<P>
   As with a cry from the wilderness, Trinity Broadcasting Network,
the world's largest Christian television network, has been
unabashedly promoting ``Omega Code'' across the country, urging
viewers to buy advance tickets en mass. And many are.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 ``Omega Code'' tickets, for instance, have been
pre-sold for this weekend's showings at the Regal megaplex at the
Mall of Georgia in metro Atlanta. And two people representing
separate groups walked up to Regal box offices this week in
Portland, Ore., and Oklahoma City and bought 1,000-seat blocks of
tickets for showings in those cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is huge,'' says Phil Zacheretti, Regal's senior vice
president of marketing and advertising. ``Other than with something
major like 'Star Wars,' you just don't sell advance tickets to
movies. Even with blockbusters, moviegoers usually decide to buy
the day they go.''
</P>
<P>
   Financed in part by TBN and produced by Matt Crouch, son of TBN
founder Paul Crouch, ``The Omega Code'' stars veteran actor Michael
York (``Cabaret'' and the ``Austin Powers'' flicks) and Casper Van
Dien (``Stormship Troopers'') in a story somewhat reminiscent of
the biblical book of Revelation: A prominent entrepreneur seeks
world domination. The title relates to real-life claims of a
scriptural code that supposedly deciphers hidden messages in the
Old Testament.
</P>
<P>
   The Motion Picture Association of America has rated ``Omega
Code'' PG-13, for several scenes involving shootings. ``Fight
Club'' is rated R, for disturbing and graphic depictions of violent
antisocial behavior, sexuality and profanity.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Omega Code'' does involve Hollywood talent and a healthy
special-effects budget, it is not connected with any of the major
studios or widely known distributors that normally handle a movie
of this size. The film is aimed squarely at the nation's
evangelical Christians, which some experts estimate to number about
75 million.
</P>
<P>
   Today ``is our chance,'' Matt Crouch says. ``It's a way to show
Hollywood there is a market out there for (this kind of)
entertainment. We have the ability to make a film and we have a
core audience out there who want to buy our stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   TBN's only previous movie experience has been 1991's little-seen
``China Cry.''
</P>
<P>
   To drum up support for ``Omega Code,'' TBN, which airs locally
on WHSG, has been occasionally running a crawl detailing the 300
theaters nationwide (15 in metro Atlanta) where the movie will be
playing. On Wednesday, the network broadcast live from the movie's
world premiere in Los Angeles. In addition to York and Van Dien,
stars attending included Clifton Davis, Smokey Robinson and Kim
Fields. TBN also is touting a website devoted to the film
(www.omegacode.com).
</P>
<P>
   Though 300 theaters is a much smaller release pattern than what
most major Hollywood films attain (``Fight Club'' will debut at
approximately 2,000 theaters), ``Omega Code'' will get wider
exposure than many specialty films which debut at a limited number
of theaters in select markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe somebody's going to find out how many Christians there
are in this country,'' says actress Jane Russell, who touted the
film at the L.A. premiere. ``This is the way to get the word out.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Family Christian Store in Gainesville, manager Judy
Herndon says she and all of her 10-member staff are planning to go
see ``Omega Code.'' ``I've had a lot of calls from people asking
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Herndon, 55, of Gillsville, says she hasn't heard of ``Fight
Club'' and hasn't seen a movie at a theater since last year's ``ThePrince of Egypt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I normally don't care to go see (Hollywood movies),'' she
says. ``I don't care to hear the language and a lot of times
they're full of bedroom scenes.'' But she'll go to ``Omega Code.''
``I'm excited. I want to help make a statement. And that's that
Christians will get behind good movies if Hollywood will do this
kind of quality movie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Prince of Egypt'' is also the last movie Larry Pitts saw at a
theater. But Pitts, manager of Kennesaw's Family Christian Store,
which is promoting ``Omega Code'' with posters and Bible study
materials at his store, plans to see ``Omega Code'' with his wife
next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a movie's not going to be beneficial to our lives, we're
not going to spend two hours (insheater),'' says Pitts, 49,
of Nelson. ``We even elected to take cable TV out of our home. Why?
Because the content is not the truth. They perpetuate the theory
that life is not eternal and that you better enjoy what's here at
the expense of everyone. Of course, the Bible teaches the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where this movie fits right in.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
