<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0339 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7201 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-TREATY-LOTT-NYT &LR;      10-14 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREATY-LOTT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTT'S ROLE IN TEST BAN TREATY'S DEFEAT SHAPED BY 1997 VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Miss., S.D., Pa., Ariz., Okla., N.C., Ga., Ark.)  (With TREATY-CLINTON, TREATY-REACT) 
(th) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One day shortly after Sen. Trent Lott of
Mississippi became the Republican leader in 1996, he got an urgent
phone call from Secretary of State Warren Christopher.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate was to begin debating a treaty that banned the
production, storage and use of poison gas, and Christopher pleaded
with Lott to cancel the vote _ likely to be a rejection _ for
national security reasons. Lott readily agreed, and over the next
seven months worked closely with the White House and Senate
Democrats to address objections to the Chemical Weapons Convention.
</P>
<P>
   On April 24, 1997, when the Senate approved the revised treaty
with a 74-26 vote, Lott voted yes. His cautious support was sealed
by a last-minute letter from President Clinton, who promised to
withdraw from the accord if it compromised the country's military
capacities or led to the spread of poison gas. ``He is the
president and his assurances in foreign policy must make a
difference,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   The contrasts between Lott's accommodation on the poison gas
treaty and the decisions he made this week that helped spell defeat
for another landmark pact, the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, can
be explained, in part, by the wrath he drew from Senate
conservatives on that first treaty vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been paying the price for that vote ever since,'' Lott
said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republican hard-liners have always grumbled that Lott is
more comfortable cutting deals and keeping comity than sticking to
core conservative principles. They complain that Lott backed a GATT
trade accord that challenged U.S. sovereignty, and that he sold out
the House Republican managers during Clinton's impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   As Sen. James Inhofe, an Oklahoma Republican, said in an
interview last week, ``As much as I like and love Trent Lott, I've
said he'd rather make a bad deal than no deal at all.''
</P>
<P>
   So when Democrats goaded Lott into calling up the test ban
treaty this month on short notice, and then quickly realized the
accord lacked the two-thirds majority to pass, the scene was set
for another political rescue.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Clinton and his aides appealed to Lott to defer
action, and near-certain defeat, citing national security reasons.
This time, however, the Republican dynamics had changed. Four
conservatives, including Inhofe, blocked an easy escape by
declaring that they would object to breaking a prearranged
agreement, endorsed by all 100 senators, to debate and vote on the
treaty.
</P>
<P>
   A new hurdle had risen since 1996. ``Some of my colleagues are
philosophically opposed to arms control,'' explained Sen. Arlen
Specter of Pennsylvania, one of four Republicans to vote for the
test ban treaty. ``There are some who just want to have Fortress
America.''
</P>
<P>
   A tentative deal that Lott and the Democratic leader, Sen. Tom
Daschle of South Dakota, worked out _ to delay Senate action on the
treaty until Clinton left office _ collapsed in the face of
opposition from conservatives like Sens. Jesse Helms of North
Carolina, Jon Kyl of Arizona and Paul Coverdell of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   As majority leader with supreme control over the Senate's
schedule, Lott alone could still have honored Clinton's pleas,
including a last-minute phone call before the final vote, by not
moving the Senate from its regular legislative business to what is
called the executive calendar, where treaties reside. But he pushed
ahead, buoyed by a pep talk on Wednesday from Dick Cheney, a former
Defense secretary, who opposes the pact.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue had been elevated to the level where it was seen as
such a bad treaty, that it'd have been very hard to shift gears
with our conservative base and not vote on it,'' one top Republican
aide said. ``They wanted us in the end zone, spiking the ball on
something that belonged to Bill Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Lott denied that partisan politics had factored into
the test ban vote. Approving the poison gas treaty, he said, ``was
the right thing to do.'' The test ban agreement, he said, was
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   He agreed to delay action on the poison gas treaty because
Democrats ``had not been playing with this politically'' as they
had with the test ban treaty. Yet in his floor speech two years
ago, Lott recalled two filibusters that the Democrats held in 1995
and 1996 to force Republicans to take up the chemical weapons pact.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said Thursday that Christopher's request had come ``early
enough in the process'' but that Clinton's written plea had come
``very late.'' In fact, Lott received both requests before floor
debate began.
</P>
<P>
   As for deferring to presidential assurances on matters of state,
as he did three years ago, Lott insisted Thursday, ``We are not a
rubber stamp for the president of the United States on a treaty we
think is flawed. We have a co-equal role.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, conservatives cheered Lott and savored their victory.
Sen. Tim Hutchinson of Arkansas, one of the four unyielding
conservatives, said, ``Lott took a difficult decision and showed
leadership.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
