<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7203 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-SURVIVOR-COMMENTAR     10-14 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURVIVOR-COMMENTARY15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Survivor!' takes TV game shows to the extreme
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With its new show ``Survivor!,'' already generating buzz though
it won't air until next summer, CBS has managed to merge two TV
megatrends _ the resurgence of game shows and Extreme TV.
</P>
<P>
   Part ``Lord of the Flies,'' part MTV's ``Real World'' and, who
knows, maybe part ``Gilligan's Island,'' ``Survivor!'' will deposit
16 prescreened applicants _ normal Americans from all walks of life
_ on a deserted island near Borneo with no shelter, the only food
what they can catch or kill. Every three days, they take a secret
vote to exile one of their own. When it's down to two survivors,
everyone comes back and votes on one winner, who gets $1 million.
Everything they do will be filmed, then edited for viewing.
</P>
<P>
   Will ``Survivor!'' be degrading, voyeuristic, appealing to our
darker impulses? Quite likely. Will people watch? Like it was O.J.
confessing.
</P>
<P>
   High anxiety
</P>
<P>
   Ever since ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'' lured millions of
viewers in August, the networks have been slobbering over
high-stakes, high-anxiety game shows. CBS is working on a new
``$64,000 Question'' (presumably adjusted for inflation) and NBC on
a revved-up (presumably scandal-free) ``Twenty-One.'' Fox, always
the class act, is trying to launch ``Greed'' for November sweeps, a
show described as like ``Famly Feud,'' only the family members have
to betray each other to win. ABC will also bring back
``Millionaire'' for a two-week run in November.
</P>
<P>
   Cross that with Extreme TV, the catch-all genre that includes
pro wrestling (the most popular show on cable), the rebirth of
Roller Derby, the still popular (but fading somewhat)
confrontational talk shows and Fox's ``World's Most
Shocking/Amazing . . . '' shows. Fox has been trying to get
government permission to crash an unmanned jumbo jet into the
desert on live TV for November sweeps, which makes ``Survivor!''
seem relatively tame.
</P>
<P>
   Producer Mark Burnett says he wants to get a diverse mix of
castaways for ``Survivor!'' ``We may have a 60-year-old priest. We
may have a 22-year-old from the inner city, or a fortysomething
mother of three from the Midwest,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Who does Burnett think will win? Somebody with strong survival
skills whom the group needs, and who also gets along well with
everyone. The guy with attitude will be gone real fast.
</P>
<P>
   Safely dangerous
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the camera crews who will tape the proceedings,
there will be medical teams standing by. Not a bad idea, since
CBS's official announcement claims that PulauTiga is home to ``the
world's most venomous snake,'' the sea krait. Burnett, trying to
downplay the krait, says it's very small, lives in the ocean and
``is not known to bite people.''
</P>
<P>
   This have-it-both-ways hype is typical for TV: It's really
dangerous! But it's really safe!
</P>
<P>
   What's most surprising about ``Survivor!'' is that it's taken
America this long to get it. The show comes from Sweden, where it's
huge, like the cast of ``ER'' vs. the cast of ``Ally McBeal'' in
the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the American Century, our pop culture is one of
our most widespread exports, but the rest of the world has its own
ideas about TV game shows. In Italy and other European countries,
contestants strip as they play. Japanese game shows border on S&AMP;M,
with participants humiliated and literally tortured: Women are
fondled by strangers, and men stand barefoot on blocks of ice or
have the hot sun focused on their bare skin by large magnifying
glasses.
</P>
<P>
   We've already been borrowing the tame: ``Whose Line Is It
Anyway?'' and ``Millionaire'' both originated in England. Now we're
on to the next level of imports, and don't think it will stop with
``Survivor.'' It's only starting.
</P>
<P>
   Applications to compete on ``Survivor'' are available only at:
www.cbs.com
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
