<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PEREZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDDIE PEREZ STEPS UP IN THE POST-SEASON  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After hitting his second home run in two days against the Mets _
this one to win the game _ Eddie Perez, former backup catcher,
continued to play down his talents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand why they're pitching to me,'' said Perez, the
Atlanta Braves' most-potent offensive force in the first two games
of the National League Championship Series. ``I'm not a good
hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   But Perez has been very good lately. Against the Mets in this
series, Perez is 4 for 7, with the two home runs, a double and
three runs batted in. His sixth-inning homer in Game 1 on Tuesday
night gave the Braves some breathing room, turning a 2-1 lead into
a 3-1 margin. His two-run, sixth-inning homer in Game 2 on
Wednesday afternoon broke a 2-2 tie and sealed the Mets' fate.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta entered the bottom of that inning, trailing, 2-0, but
Brian Jordan tied the game with a two-run homer to the opposite
field. Andruw Jones followed with a hard single to left that
brought Perez to the plate. The Mets' starter, Kenny Rogers, was
obviously losing his effectiveness, and Mets Manager Bobby
Valentine weighed whether to yank Rogers from the game.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Valentine decided to let Rogers pitch to Perez. That
was a mistake. One pitch later, Perez's home run was sailing into
the left-field seats, and the Braves were in front for good.
</P>
<P>
   Perez admitted he was surprised, and pleased, by Valentine's
decision not to pull Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was coming out of the game, but I didn't want him
to,'' Perez said of Rogers. ``I didn't want to face a fresh arm
from the bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez got his wish, then he made the most of it. With his home
run, Perez continued his uncanny penchant for becoming a dangerous
hitter during the post-season. A career .259 hitter, Perez is 7 for
his last 11 in NLCS play. In last year's NLCS against the San Diego
Padres, Perez was 3 for 4 in a backup role, and while some players
become more tense in pressure situations, Perez seems to have the
kind of self-deprecating humor that allows him to relax. For
instance, when asked about Rogers' pickoff move to first base,
which caught both Gerald Williams and Andruw Jones in Game 2, Perez
had to laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the best pickoff move I've ever seen,'' Perez
said. ``When he threw Andruw out, I swung the bat and he threw to
first base.''
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old Perez became Atlanta's starting catcher when
Javy Lopez suffered a season-ending knee injury on July 24.
Catching 104 games, Perez hit .249 with 7 home runs and 30 rbi, but
his main value was behind the plate, where he provided solid
defense and did a strong job handling Atlanta's fine pitching
staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Javy went down, Eddie stepped right in and did the job,''
John Schuerholz, Atlanta's general manager, said. ``What he has
done is even more impressive because he's banged up, with two sore
knees. He's done a great job. Believe me, he'd be the No. 1 catcher
on a lot of teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the series began, Perez thought he might play a key role.
He knew the Mets would pitch carefully to Atlanta's dangerous No. 3
and No. 4 hitters _ Chipper Jones and Jordan _ and walk them on
occasion. That left Andruw Jones, batting fifth, and Perez, batting
sixth, with a chance to make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want to pitch to Chipper and Brian,'' Perez said.
``I told Andruw before the series to be ready, because we're going
to see somebody on base every time we're up.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see how Perez and his teammates react
Friday night, when the series shifts to Shea Stadium for Game 3,
and the atmosphere becomes more hostile. Still, during the regular
season, all seven of Perez's homers were on the road, a statistic
the Mets' pitching staff would be wise to note.
</P>
<P>
   If Perez continues to hit, it will greatly improve Atlanta's
chances. His performance has raised questions about who will be the
No. 1 catcher next season, when Lopez, a two-time All-Star, is
expected to return. For his part, Perez, who has been the backup
since Lopez became a regular in 1996, would rather not worry about
that issue until next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what's going to happen, but I don't want to go
anywhere,'' Perez said. ``I want to stay in Atlanta. This is where
I want to be, with a team that has a chance to make the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only are the Braves in the playoffs, but Perez has also been
one of their heroes. Maybe the Mets are surprised. But the Braves
are not.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great defensive catcher and he can hit,'' Braves
Manager Bobby Cox said. ``I've seen him in the playoffs before, and
it's not unusual for Eddie to hit a home run or drive in a big run.
He has done a fantastic job.''
</P>
<P>
   There could be more to come. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
