<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7206 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AUTO-CHRYSLER-MUSEUMS     10-14 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-CHRYSLER-MUSEUMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRYSLER MAKES ITS PLACE IN HISTORY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.C., Pa., Minn., Ky., N.J., Calif., Wis., Germany)   By MICHELLE KREBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ This city, whose name is synonymous with the American
auto industry, is strengthening that identification at several
museums dedicated to the business.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Ford Motor Co. opened a museum in its nearby
hometown of Dearborn, Mich., and only a few Thunderbird-lengths
from the Henry Ford Museum and the Automotive Hall of Fame. Early
in the next century, General Motors plans to open a downtown
museum.
</P>
<P>
   And this month, DaimlerChrysler opened the Walter P. Chrysler
Museum at its North American headquarters in the suburb of Auburn
Hills.
</P>
<P>
   The cars are the stars of the Chrysler museum, which is named
for the company's founder. It displays 75 vehicles from a
collection of about 140, and they were chosen to showcase
milestones for Chrysler and the auto industry. Many of the displays
are intended to give visitors a sense of Chrysler's place in
history and American culture as the century draws to a close. A
World War II Jeep, for example, appears to emerge from the rubble
of a French village, and a 1924 Chrysler Six, the first car to bear
the Chrysler name, is seen through the window of a replica of the
founder's office.
</P>
<P>
   A two-story revolving display shows off a half-dozen vehicles,
including a 1963 Chrysler experimental turbine car, the original
1989 Dodge Viper show car, the Chrysler Thunderbolt and the
twin-cockpit Chrysler Newport Phaeton, both from 1941.
</P>
<P>
   The prewar vehicles include a 1929 DeSoto, which had been walled
up in a Chrysler plant; &UR;  &LR; a 1934 DeSoto Airflow, considered by many
to be the first modern car because it foreshadowed the aerodynamic
design of cars built decades later, and a 1929 Nash that never left
the factory in Kenosha, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   About 35 high-performance cars line a track in the lower level
known as Boss Chrysler's garage. A lounge resembles a 1930s
showroom and there is a replica of Chrysler's Room 13, the
birthplace of legendary high-performance engines, including the
Chrysler Hemi V8.
</P>
<P>
   The new Spirit of Ford &UR;  &LR; museum is near the Henry Ford Museum in
Dearborn, as well as the recently opened Automotive Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the Henry Ford Museum, which contains a wide
collection of historic cars, including Ford's original quadricycle,
the Spirit of Ford focuses on current vehicles and future concepts.
It also stresses the design and manufacturing process more than the
Chrysler museum does.
</P>
<P>
   In 2002, GM plans to open its museum, focusing on the company's
heritage, in the Renaissance Center in downtown Detroit, which
General Motors bought for its headquarters two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Dressel, director of the Chrysler museum, said travel
industry surveys found that about half of Americans plan museum
visits during vacations, with corporate museums accounting for an
increasing share. For example, he said, Crayola Crayon's visitor
and creative center in Easton, Pa., &UR;  &LR; attracts more than 300,000
people a year, and Spam Town in Austin, Minn., draws 60,000.
DaimlerChrysler's Mercedes-Benz museum in Stuttgart, Germany, pulls
in an average of 35,000. BMW has a museum in Munich and has opened
a smaller one at its plant in Spartanburg, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of museums nationwide contain collections of cars or car
artifacts. Chevrolet's Corvette museum in Bowling Green, Ky., has
become one of the state's top tourist attractions. Jaguar plans to
build a museum at its North American headquarters in Mahwah, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the nation's finest automobile museums, which are not
affiliated with an auto manufacturer, are in California. The
Blackhawk Automotive Museum in Danville is filled with beautiful
rare cars _ some once owned by Hollywood stars _ with nameplates
like Bugatti, Mercer and Hispano-Suiza. A relatively new wing of
the museum is devoted exclusively to automotive art from fine
paintings to hood ornaments.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The Petersen Automotive Museum in Los Angeles exhibits
important cars in historical displays. Dioramas, including a 1930s
Hollywood street scene, a 1960s garage and a 1931 showroom, depict
the history of the automobile and its impact on Amlife.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
