<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0344 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7207 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CLINTON15-COX     10-14 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON BLASTS REPUBLICANS FOR TREATY REJECTION
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Venting frustration a day after suffering a
bruising foreign policy defeat, President Clinton accused Senate
Republicans on Thursday of listing toward ``a new isolationism''
that threatens the country's global leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think we ought to go it alone,'' Clinton said,
summarizing the GOP message to the closest U.S. allies as, ``Go
take a hike.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are saying America does not need to lead, either by
effort or by example. They are saying we don't need our friends or
allies ... that, at the height of our power and prosperity, we
should bury our heads in the sand, behind a wall.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not where I stand,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's fourth animated broadside against the GOP-controlled
Congress in less than two weeks came at a White House news
conference dominated by the Senate's rejection Wednesday of an
international nuclear test ban treaty at the heart of the
president's nonproliferation agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., called his own news
conference to rebut the charges.
</P>
<P>
   He said Clinton had gotten his ``feelings hurt a little bit''
over the defeat, denied that his party was drifting toward
isolationism, and said the president was using that charge to mask
substantive objections to the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be international cowboys,'' Lott told
reporters at the Capitol. ``Nobody can be an isolationist in this
world. It's physically impossible, it's irrational, and we are
not.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Lott added, ``we are not a rubber stamp for the president
of the United States on a treaty we think is flawed.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in his hour-long East Room press conference, touched on
a handful of subjects:
</P>
<P>
   _ He threatened to veto a spending bill Congress is scheduled to
sent to his desk within the week unless it contains sufficient
funding for his plans to hire additional teachers, boost
after-school programs and add computers to classrooms. Republicans
have proposed lumping most of that funding into block grants that
would let local school boards decide how the money is spent.
</P>
<P>
   _ He tiptoed around a question about this week's military coup
in Pakistan, declining to condemn the overthrow of that country's
democratically elected government and saying instead, ``We don't
like it when military leaders forcibly displace elected governments
... and I would hope that the military government will soon
transition to a civilian one.''
</P>
<P>
   _ And he declined to comment on an Arkansas court ruling that he
had committed perjury in connection with a civil suit filed by
Paula Jones, who later reached an out-of-court settlement with
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I am out of office, I will have a lot to say about
this,'' said Clinton. ``As I understand it now, all this is
finished and I don't have to comment on it; and unless there is
some reason I legally have to, I'm not going to say anything else
that doesn't relate to my responsibilities as president.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Time and again, though, Clinton returned to the test ban treaty,
the topic with which he kicked off his press conference.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to portray Wednesday's Senate action as a central
moment in a far larger debate. At issue, he said, is whether
conservative Senate voices would be able to steer the country away
from five decades of diplomacy aimed at putting in place arms
control agreements and economic treaties meant to strengthen global
security and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine the world we will live in if they prevail,'' Clinton
said. ``I think it will be a bleak, poor, less secure world. I
don't want my children and my grandchildren, or your children or
your grandchildren to live in it. ... I will do everything I can to
stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond this country's shores, Clinton said, the Senate's
rejection of the test ban treaty ``was also an amazing rebuke to
our allies.''
</P>
<P>
   The British, French and German heads of state had pleaded in a
joint op-ed article for the Senate not to kill the treaty. Those
countries are the United States' core NATO allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We say, 'Okay, you guys are with us every time we need you,
the Gulf War, the Balkans, always in NATO, you're there, but you
ask us to do something for your common safety, go take a hike,'''
said Clinton. ``I think that's a very tenuous position.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's blistering critique added to a season of mounting
contention between the White House and the GOP-controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Clinton assailed Senate Republicans for shooting
down his nomination to the federal court in Missouri of Ronnie
White, the first African-American to sit on the bench of the
Missouri Supreme Court. Clinton statement that White's rejection
lent credence to the view that the Senate confirmation process
discriminated against minorities and women infuriated Lott.
</P>
<P>
   He later accused House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R- Ill., of
selling out to the interests of the health insurance industry in
his efforts to kill new consumer protections. Hastert denied the
charge, and the protections passed the House.
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton last Friday accused Senate Republicans of placing
politics ahead of national security as it became clear that the
nuclear test ban treaty was headed toward defeat, again raising the
ire of Lott.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not about politics,'' Lott said Thursday, ``it was
about the substance of the treaty.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott suggested that Clinton's remarks reflected an emotional
reaction to Wednesday's vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he's disappointed and maybe his, you know, feelings
hurt a little bit here,'' said Lott. ``But, you know, let's move
on. You don't win them all, Mr. President. Sometimes you're
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
