<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NORTH BEACH PAINTING COMES HOME
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Musician, radio man and jazz connoisseur  &UR; Mal Sharpe &LR;  found a
bit of bohemian San Francisco in Berkeley at the Trout Farm antique
store. It's a 1964 mural from the now-defunct Old Spaghetti
Factory, which includes images of 25 or 30 North Beach regulars of
the era.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpe, who paid $3,000 for the painting, his wife,  &UR; Sandra &LR; ,
and filmmaker  &UR; Bill Farley &LR;  have been able to identify many of the
faces, including Factory owner  &UR; Freddie Kuh &LR; ; model  &UR; Flo Allen &LR; ;
poet  &UR; Thom Gunn &LR; ;  &UR; Millie &LR; , who still sells flowers and takes
tourists's &LR;  pictures in North Beach;  &UR; Mike Kitay &LR; ;  &UR; Joe St. &LR; 
 &UR; Alban &LR; ;  &UR; Joan Oaktree &LR; ; and the muralist,  &UR; Kaffe Fassett &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The painter, whose name will be recognized by textile
connoisseurs, left San Francisco for England, where he became a
renowned designer of knitwear and knitting patterns.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing the mural back to its home turf, Sharpe is leasing it
to Enrico's, which is celebrating its return the afternoon of
October 30.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. North Beach regulars weren't shy about celebrating
themselves. The Black Cat's &UR; Cornelius Sampson  &LR; painting, made in
1938, pictures 78 cafe regulars.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the 'hood, Tommaso's in North Beach has been
selected as one of the first ``inductees'' into the Select 16, a
Pizza Hall of Fame honoring 16 pizzerias across the country, at the
soon-to-open Metro Pizza in Las Vegas. And  &UR; Jeannette &LR; 
 &UR; Etheredge  &LR; is marking the 80th anniversary of her Tosca Cafe on
November 20.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RUSHDIE ESSAY ANGERS ANNAN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Secretary-General  &UR; Kofi Annan &LR; , who had agreed to provide
the preface to the forthcoming book ``Letters to the Six Billionth
Citizen,'' dropped out, reports the Times of London, because the
book included  &UR; Salman Rushdie &LR; 's assertion that religion is to
blame for overpopulation.
</P>
<P>
   Rushdie's assertion that ``the overpopulation of the planet is
the fault of the lies of religious leaders'' was so upsetting to
Annan that he demanded it be removed. When the publisher wouldn't
agree, Annan ``couldn't believe that Rushdie's views would take
precedence over his,'' a U.N. staff member told the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Upon learning of the decision, Annan withdrew his introductory
essay.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ The  &UR; Duchess of York &LR; , who turns 40 O &LR; ctober 15 &LR; , told People
magazine, ``I quite like the person I am. I'd like her as a
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Ira Epstein &LR;  noticed while watching ``Robin Hood, Men in
Tights,'' on TBS last weekend that the Yiddish word faygele, which
literally means small bird and idiomatically means gay, was blipped
out, but schmuck, which is Yiddish slang for the male member, was
uttered loud and clear.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Mario Cuomo  &LR; told the New York Daily News'  &UR; Mitchell Fink &LR; 
that  &UR; Bill Bradley  &LR; is a ``charming underdog'' who can't win, but
``if Bradley agrees to be  &UR; Al Gore &LR; 's vice presidential running
mate, they can beat  &UR; George W. Bush &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHAT MAKES WOMEN HAPPY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Reporting on international polls about happiness levels for
various generations of women, the Economist finds that nostalgia
has a warm and fuzzy effect.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, an Angus Reid poll found, only 29 percent of modern
women feel they are happier than their grandmothers were. In the
United States, 28 percent of modern women think they are happier
than their grandmothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``So 71 percent of German women think their grandmothers living
under Hitler were happier,'' writes  &UR; Robert Kunze &LR; , ``and 72
percent of Americans think the Depression was a lot of laughs.''
Japan was the only country where a rousing majority of respondents,
82 percent, recognized that they were happier than their
grandmothers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to have this dream where everyone was using my
toothbrush and I'd come in and either someone I didn't know was in
the process of using my toothbrush or someone I knew let someone
use my toothbrush. And then a couple of years ago I started having
a dream that someone used my toothbrush _ this is such a, who's
that guy, Richard Bach, dream _ but that I had all these other
toothbrushes at my disposal and I didn't know I had them. Dissect
that one.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Brad Pitt to interviewer Charles Heath in Rolling Stone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
