NYT-10-14-99 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0346 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7209 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AUTO-FORD-BUILDINGS-N     10-14 0450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-FORD-BUILDINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GHOSTS OF DETROIT PAST IN OLD FORD BUILDINGS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JIM McCRAW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. _ Henry Ford was so intent on preserving pieces
of the nation's past that he had dozens of buildings shipped here
to Greenfield Village, a historical park where visitors can wander
through Thomas Edison's laboratory and the Wright Brothers' bicycle
shop. Yet as Ford's greatest legacy, the Ford Motor Co., looks to
its centennial in 2003, several of the most important buildings
from its past have disappeared or are in disrepair.
</P>
<P>
   The company's original Mack Avenue plant in Detroit was
destroyed by fire decades ago, though it has been recreated in
Greenfield Village. The company's former headquarters at 3000
Schaefer Road in Dearborn, which was later the home of
Lincoln-Mercury and then the Ford parts and service division, was
leveled in 1998. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two historic structures remain, but their future is in doubt. An
enormous complex that built 15 million Model Ts in Highland Park _
a city encircled by Detroit _ has been empty for decades. There is
a historical marker in front on Woodward Avenue, but the complex is
much too large to restore. Most of its thousands of windows _ it
was nicknamed the Crystal Palace _ are broken, and weeds and trash
are everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The administrative offices may soon be converted into a charter
school for 540 students from kindergarten to fifth grade. The
school would be operated by Advantage Schools of Boston under a
10-year lease, but the building would need at least $2 million in
renovations, Advantage said.
</P>
<P>
   The other building is at 411 Piquette Street in Detroit, a few
miles south of the Highland Park complex. Ford quickly outgrew its
original Mack Avenue site and moved to the three-story Piquette
Street building. Between 1903 and 1909, Ford built thousands of
cars there, said Mike Skinner, a Ford historian. In an office on
the northeast corner of the third floor of this building, Henry
Ford and his research staff designed and developed the Model T.
</P>
<P>
   The building is currently owned by Heritage Investments, but is
being sold to the Henry Ford Heritage Association, a group of about
1,000 Ford history buffs.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Wickins of Heritage Investments said the sale was
complicated because Studebaker bought the building from Ford and
added an extension that now makes it a blocklong building with a
single title. Heritage wants to sell the entire building, currently
worth about $3 million, to the group. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Henry Ford Hospital uses most of the Studebaker extension to
store records, and the original Ford building is used by multiple
tenants, mostly for storage. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 2001EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
