<HEADER>
A7227 &Cx1f; tic-z
u v BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR &LR;      10-14 0376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Friday, Oct. 15. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
DRUGCASH (Phoenix) - A billboard that just went up in Phoenix
offers drug addicts $200 cash if they get implanted with Norplant
or take other birth control. All kinds of folks are upset about
this, including those who say the addicts need drug counseling, not
cash. The billboard is part of a national campaign, Arizona is one
of the first states to get one. By BEVERLY FORD. Story will move in
the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MCCAIN (Washington) - In a blistering debate on the floor of the
U.S. Senate Thursday, John McCain's enemies tried to fit him for a
political pine box, insisting on a adding an amendment that would
require any senator who made a general charge of corruption or
improper influence to back it up with specifics or pay a penalty.
More than a few GOP senators expressed outrage over McCain's
citations of `pork` on his website, forcing the Arizona senator and
his Wisconsin co-sponsor to backpedal, explaining they were talking
about `the appearance of corruption.` This spectacle of a GOP
presidential candidate being flayed by members of his own party
even as Democrats kneeled down to nurse his wounds is so
extraordinary that it raises the question: Even in the unlikely
event McCain could be elected president, would he be able to govern
when so many powerful senators of his own party are willing to
display their contempt for him in public? By KRIS MAYES. Story will
move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
FLIMFLAM (Phoenix) - A Carefree, Ariz., man accused of bilking $30
million to $50 million from investors in Arizona, California &AMP;
Texas is on the lam after a federal judge declared him in contempt
for threatening the judge and a witness in the fraud case. He
probably got away in the one airplane the SEC didn't seize when it
shut down his business, Dennel Finance, in March. By PAT FLANNERY.
Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
PASTA-FOOD (Phoenix) - How to make pasta. With recipes. By JONATHAN
SIDENER. Story will move in the ``D'' category.
</P>
</TEXT>
