NYT-10-14-99 2003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0348 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7223 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SC-VIDEOPOKER15-COX     10-14 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-VIDEOPOKER15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    S.C. high court rules against video gaming referendum
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel and Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MILL, S.C. _ The South Carolina Supreme Court on Thursday
shoved the state's embattled video poker industry halfway into its
grave. As it stands, the lid will slam shut July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Whether there's any breathing room for the controversial $2.8
billion industry is up to state legislators who convene in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got eight months till the deadline goes into effect,''
said Michael Gunn, a South Carolina video poker lobbyist. ``A lot
can happen between now and then. What that is I don't know, but a
lot can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   However, both Gov. Jim Hodges, a Democrat, and state House
speaker David Wilkins, a Republican, said Thursday there aren't
enough votes to reverse next year's ban.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's deader than Elvis,'' said Larry Huff, a spokesman for the
anti-gambling group Legacy Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Voters had been scheduled to decide the fate of video poker in a
statewide referendum Nov. 2. But the state Supreme Court ruled 5-0
Thursday that the measure unconstitutionally granted voters the
option to decide statewide policy themselves. The court kept intact
the part of the law, passed last session, that outlawed video poker
payoffs starting July 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although we may view the task with disfavor, and may have
varying personal views on the merits of the controversy that
surrounds video gaming, we cannot ignore precedent and our duty to
interpret the constitution,'' said the unsigned South Carolina
Supreme Court decision.
</P>
<P>
   Greenville attorney Frank Eppes, who filed the suit on behalf of
Joytime Amusement Co., said he hasn't decided what to do, though he
doubts the U.S. Supreme Court would take up a state's rights issue.
Eppes has until Tuesday to request a reconsideration by the state's
highest court.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the referendum had taken place and there was a `yes' vote,
opponents of gaming would have challenged the outcome and the court
would have ruled the same way,'' Eppes said. ``It was a case of
taking your medicine now or later.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen colorful, neon-lit game parlors sit jammed
between here and the North Carolina state line. Erin Delehant, 38,
owns one of them, State Line Video.
</P>
<P>
   ``When are they going to stop telling people how to live their
lives?'' Delehant asked.
</P>
<P>
   Delehant projects the Legislature ``will continue to juggle and
bounce around'' the issue, delaying or rescinding the July 1 ban.
He reasoned the machines contribute too much to state and local
taxes, payroll and legal fees to be eliminated by legislators.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that is most important in this country is the
dollar,'' said Delehant, sitting outside his 15-machine parlor
within sight of the North Carolina state line.
</P>
<P>
   When he was governor, David Beasley vowed to shut down video
poker, calling it a ``cancer'' on South Carolina. Outraged, video
poker operators shoveled $3 million into Hodges' campaign. Hodges
said he would let voters decide the fate of video gambling. The
issue turned Beasley into an unlikely upset victim _ a conservative
Christian elected by a core of Southern Baptists in the Deep South.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some degree of vindication,'' Beasley said Thursday
from a conference of former governors in Nevada. ``But I would have
done it again. It was worth risking everything to see this day.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoing other video gambling opponents, Beasley said the battle
is far from over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Video poker bought one branch of government, and they'll try
and influence another, whether ethically or unethically,'' Beasley
said. ``It's a very corrupt industry, and they'll do anything they
can to keep it going. It's going to be an all-out battle in the
Legislature. It's not over. They will try and do everything they
can.''
</P>
<P>
   The South Carolina court decision came two days after Alabama
voters rejected a constitutional amendment that would have
authorized a Georgia-style education lottery.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest anti-gambling week in American history,''
said gambling expert Bill Thompson, a public administration
professor at the University of Nevada-Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   During next year's general election, South Carolina voters will
vote on their own lottery proposal, which would fund HOPE
scholarships like Georgia's.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia lottery players from South Carolina represent the
highest group of out-of-state winners. Last year, South Carolinians
bought an estimated $112 million of Georgia lottery tickets _ 5.52
percent of the lottery's $2 billion in sales. However, if video
poker dies in South Carolina, Thompson and other gambling
researchers doubt those players would add much revenue to the
Georgia lottery.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're close to Georgia they might buy a ticket,'' said
Thompson, in Columbia today for a forum on gambling. ``But they're
not going to drive 100 miles to play. It won't be a major shift.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 2003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
