<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7225 &Cx1f; tic-z
r d BC-PASTA-FOOD-AZR &LR;      10-14 2491
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PASTA-FOOD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING CAN TOP HOMEMADE NOODLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN SIDENER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Many Thanksgivings ago, my cousins and I took their
German shorthaired pointer for a post-feast walk through a nearby
field in the New Jersey suburbs. I mentioned whatever dish their
paternal grandmother had whipped up and said she was a good cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' my cousin Kenny said, ``She's never eaten pasta
that came out of a box.''
</P>
<P>
   Their very Italian grandmother had clearly eaten her share of
pasta over the years. She made the staple several times a week,
Kenny said, but never from a box.
</P>
<P>
   As someone whose genes had been routed from northern Europe and
the British Isles, via a couple of generations in the Midwest, the
idea that pasta could originate from anywhere other than a box was
startling.
</P>
<P>
   I filed the concept of homemade pasta away in the
Isn't-That-Quaint section of my pre-adolescent brain. It would be
several years before the idea would resurface in the form of a menu
item, homemade fettuccine with veal.
</P>
<P>
   I ordered it. I tasted it. I was hooked.
</P>
<P>
   There is something wonderful about a simple starch elevated to
near perfection. I have a Chinese cookbook that recommends
carefully prepared rice as a meal and encourages diners to
appreciate the steamed grains in and of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   If you have ever had sweet corn cooked within minutes of being
picked, you know that no other corn can compare.
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for homemade pasta. The fresh pasta in the grocery
refrigerator is not a bad compromise, but it's still a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   After eating homemade pasta for the first time, I refiled the
concept in my brain's Order-It-If-You-See-It-on-the-Menu folder.
</P>
<P>
   That lasted until a few years ago, when a friend had a yard sale
to jettison excess household goods before getting married. He
wanted to get rid of a shiny, imported, hand-cranked pasta machine.
I decided to take a stab at making my own, so I bought it.
</P>
<P>
   There are two types of pasta machines. Owners of either type
will tell you that theirs is the best. I love my hand-powered
machine. I think it's the best. And there's no disputing that it's
the more traditional.
</P>
<P>
   The hand-cranked machines are a little harder to find, but are
available in some department-store kitchen departments, mall
specialty kitchen-supply stores and Italian delis.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, it consists of two rollers. A ball of dough is pulled
through the rollers, making a thick, flat strip. The rollers are
moved progressively closer together and the dough is run through,
making it progressively wider. When it's been through the roller,
it's called sheet, as in a sheet of pasta. Different end products
get rolled into sheets of varying thicknesses, but spaghetti,
linguine, angel hair, fettuccine and ravioli all start out as
sheet.
</P>
<P>
   On the East Coast, there are commercial pastamakers that sell
sheets, which cuts the work by half or more. However, I don't know
of any in the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   The machine also includes hand-turned blades that cut the pasta
into various-size strips.
</P>
<P>
   The other type of machine is an all-American electronic kitchen
appliance. Its advantage is that it simplifies the process down to
dumping the ingredients into one end and waiting for the pasta to
come out the other. As a shortcut, the machine does an end run
around the sheet process. Instead, the pasta is extruded into
various shapes. This extrusion method is the way to go for tube
shapes such as ziti and rigatoni.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think the extruded fettuccine or other long noodles are
the equal of those made from sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Making pasta is an acquired skill, which means it gets easier
the more you do it. The first time you try it, give yourself lots
of time. The first time I cranked up my pasta machine, I served
dinner around 11:30 p.m. and my blood pressure was about 390 over
185. The second time, it took half as long. Now, it takes about an
hour, including 30 minutes for the dough to rest before rolling it
into sheets.
</P>
<P>
   The first time I made pasta, I used plain old American white
all-purpose flour. The results came out more like Pennsylvania
Dutch egg noodles than pasta.
</P>
<P>
   The first rule of pastamaking is to use semolina flour. Right
off the bat, this gives you an advantage over many grocery-store
products. Some Valley grocery stores carry it, including AJ's.
</P>
<P>
   The second rule is to never add salt, no matter what the recipe
says. It will only detract from the texture of the dough. If you
want salt, add it to the water when you cook the pasta.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the pasta batch is in proportion to the number of
eggs you add. A one-egg batch serves two or three. A two-egg batch
serves four or five.
</P>
<P>
   I use a mixer to blend and knead the dough, which simplifies the
process. Both steps can be done by hand if you don't have a dough
hook on your mixer.
</P>
<P>
   Start with the flour, oil and egg(s.) Mix on low speed until
everything is blended together. It should have a course, crumbly
look like cornmeal. Add the water, a half tablespoon at a time, to
the dough until it begins to change from a crumbly mixture into a
dough. You want only enough water to hold it together, not enough
to make it spongy or batterlike.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, switch to a dough hook and knead the dough for 10
minutes. The dough should not be crumbling into separate pieces,
but it should not be sticky, either. If it's too dry, add a few
drops of water. If it's too moist, you can sprinkle in a tablespoon
of flour.
</P>
<P>
   Cover it with plastic wrap care fully, because dough exposed to
the air will dry quickly and be ruined. Let it sit for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This gives you time to have a glass of wine and get the sauce
simmering on a back burner.
</P>
<P>
   After the dough finishes its nap, tear or cut it into pieces
slightly bigger than golf balls. Cover everything back up except
the one you're working on.
</P>
<P>
   Set the pasta machine rollers for the widest opening.
</P>
<P>
   Turn the handle and run the ball through to make a thick, flat
oblong. Fold it in half and run it through again. Do this several
times. You'll see the dough become softer and more flexible.
</P>
<P>
   Then, adjust the rollers one notch to the second-widest opening
and run the oblong through again. My machine has five settings. I
never use the smallest opening because I generally make ravioli,
fettuccine and lasagna, which are thicker noodles.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to have a sheet almost exactly as wide as the
rollers by the time you're at the last step. The blades are the
same width, so this is the most efficient way to do it. Don't worry
if the sheet is a little short or not wide enough when you start
out. It'll be easier next time.
</P>
<P>
   Cover the piece of sheet. Reset the rollers to the widest
setting and get out another ball of dough. Repeat the above steps
until you have rolled all the dough into sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Gaze proudly at your handiwork for a second, then place the
blade attachment on the machine and get ready to cut the pasta.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly flour the sheet to keep the cut pieces from sticking to
each other. Move the handle to the blade and turn the blades while
feeding the sheet in with your other hand. When two-thirds of the
sheet has been cut, let the machine pull the remainder through.
This frees up your other hand to catch the pasta and keep it from
clumping together. Hang the strips on a pasta rack or spread them
on a floured surface. The idea is to keep them separated from each
other, because they will try to turn themselves back into a lump of
dough when you're not looking.
</P>
<P>
   I'm told that sheet can be rolled out by hand and rolling pin if
you don't have a machine. The theory is that you roll the ball a
little, turn it 45 degrees. Roll it. Turn it. Repeat until you have
a thin sheet of pasta. Then you lightly flour the sheet and roll it
up into a cylinder. Slice the noodles off the end of the cylinder.
</P>
<P>
   Boil the water (always boil the water before you add the pasta).
Cut the remaining sheets. And get ready to eat.
</P>
<P>
   When cooking homemade pasta, always remember Henry Blake's
recipe for cooking a steak: ``Just show it the fire, Radar.'' Just
show it the water.
</P>
<P>
   A thin homemade pasta such as angel hair is done almost as fast
as you can put it in the water. Have your strainer ready in the
sink before you put the pasta in the boiling water. Pasta should
come to the top when it is done. A fettuccine or lasagna may take
up to 90 seconds to cook. Don't plan on a break while it cooks.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the pasta and water through the strainer. Don't rinse. The
pasta will continue to cook even after it's out of the pot, so it's
important to not boil it too long.
</P>
<P>
   Add a little olive oil or sauce and the pasta to the serving
bowl and lightly toss to coat the pasta and keep it from sticking
together. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jon Sidener's Marinara Sauce &QL; 
(From ``The Arizona Republic's`` Cooking 101) &QL; 
3 cloves garlic, crushed
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons parsley, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 or 3 fresh basil leaves, chopped, or 1 teaspoon dried basil
</P>
<P>
   1 can (15 to 16 ounces) crushed tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of oregano
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Saute garlic in olive oil over medium-low heat until it begins
to turn brown. Add parsley and basil leaves. Stir for another
minute, then add tomatoes, oregano, salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 2 cups or 4 servings. &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 123 calories, 11 g fat, 7 g
carbohydrates, 2 g fiber, 2 g protein, 198 mg sodium, 73 percent
calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jon Sidener's Pesto Sauce &QL; 
(From ``The Arizona Republic's'' Cooking 101) &QL; 
4 cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped basil
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons grated Parmesan or Romano cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup hot water
</P>
<P>
   Cut garlic into chunks. Coarsely chop fresh basil.
</P>
<P>
   Pour olive oil into a blender. Add garlic and blend thoroughly.
Add some basil and blend again. You may have to stop the blender
once or twice so you can push the basil down into the oil. Add
butter at room temperature, but not melted, and grated Parmesan or
Romano cheese. Blend again. Just before serving, add hot water and
blend slightly one last time. Toss with your favorite pasta. Makes
enough pesto to cover 4 servings of pasta. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 246 calories, 24 g fat, 15 mg
cholesterol, 7 g carbohydrates, 2 g fiber, 4 g protein, 140 mg
sodium, 84 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Saffron Lasagna Rolls With Shrimp &QL; 
One Egg Pasta (see recipe below)
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of saffron (optional)
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 small or { medium yellow onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds raw shrimp, deveined and chopped
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper and ground New Mexico or cayenne pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon basil, or to taste (chopped if fresh or crumbled if
dried)
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces mozzarella, shredded
</P>
<P>
   Freshly grated Parmesan, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Prepare Marinara Sauce and keep warm. Make pasta, mixing a
healthy pinch of saffron (optional) into the flour before adding
the wet ingredients. Cut sheet into 2-inch wide strips about 10
inches long.
</P>
<P>
   In a large pan filled with boiling water, cook the strips three
or four at a time until al dente (still resistant to the tooth).
Place a strainer in a second large pan. Pour water and pasta into
strainer. Return second pan to stove and return water to boil for
next batch of lasagna.
</P>
<P>
   Heat olive oil in large skillet. Add onion and saute over medium
heat until onion starts to turn translucent. Add shrimp and cook
until it turns pink and meat is no longer translucent. Add a pinch
of salt and peppers to taste. Turn heat to medium low and add
garlic.
</P>
<P>
   Saute for one minute and then add a tablespoon of basil, either
dried or fresh, chopped. After another minute, remove from heat.
</P>
<P>
   Coat a shallow baking pan (such as a 9- by 13-inch one) with
non-stick spray. Coat bottom with a layer of marinara.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 325 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Place one of the lasagna noodles flat on a work surface, and
spread about three tablespoons of shrimp mixture from one end to
the other. Sprinkle with a layer of shredded cheese. Carefully roll
into a spiral.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat with remaining noodles.
</P>
<P>
   Set lasagna rolls in pan and then cover with remaining marinara.
Cover pan with aluminum foil and bake for 25 to 30 minutes,
removing foil for final 5 to 10 minutes. After cooking, let lasagna
sit for a few minutes before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Garnish with grated Parmesan cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 to 6 servings. &QL; 
Approximate values per one-fifth serving: 576 calories, 32 g fat,
284 mg cholesterol, 27 g carbohydrates, 2 g fiber, 43 g protein,
550 mg sodium, 51 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
One Egg Pasta and Variations &QL; 
(From Jon Sidener) &QL; 
One Egg Pasta: Makes 2 servings.
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup semolina flour
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1/2 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 or 2 teaspoons lukewarm water or milk
</P>
<P>
   Two Egg Pasta: Makes 3 to 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups semolina flour
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   3/4 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 or 3 teaspoons lukewarm water or milk
</P>
<P>
   Three Egg Pasta: Makes 5 to 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   2 1/4 cups semolina flour
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 or 4 teaspoons lukewarm water or milk
</P>
<P>
   Mix flour, eggs and oil on low speed in a heavy-duty mixer until
mixture has a coarse, crumbly look, like corn meal. Add water or
milk a half tablespoon at a time until the mixture starts to hold
together.
</P>
<P>
   Switch to the dough hook on the mixer, or knead by hand. Knead
in mixer 7 to 10 minutes. Dough should not be sticky or in separate
pieces. Add a little more liquid if needed, or a little more flour
if sticky.
</P>
<P>
   If kneading by hand, turn out onto lightly floured board and
knead well for 7 to 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Cover with plastic wrap and let dough rest 15 to 30 minutes. Set
pasta machine to widest opening. Roll out ball of dough just a
little larger than golf balls, then run through machine to make a
thick, fat oblong shape. Fold in half and run through again. Repeat
three or four times, then roll to desired thickness.
</P>
<P>
   Repeat until all balls of dough are rolled into sheets, keeping
all extras and finished sheets covered. Then put blade attachment
on pasta machine. Lightly flour the sheets of pasta to keep them
from sticking to each other. Run through the machine, using one
hand to crank and the other to hold the strips as they come out.
</P>
<P>
   Hang the strips on a pasta rack or a floured surface to dry.
</P>
<P>
   To cook, be sure water is at a full boil. Fresh pasta cooks very
quickly and will rise to the top of the water when done. Drain in a
colander; do not rinse. Because pasta will continue to cook after
it's done, be careful not to overcook. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Approximate values per serving: 287 calories, 6 g fat, 90 mg
cholesterol, 46 g carbohydrates, 2 g fiber, 11 g protein, 27 mg
sodium, 20 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Jonathan Sidener can be reached at (602) 444-8169 or at
jon.sidener(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
