<HEADER>
A7229 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      10-14 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WAY THEY WERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was almost like the good old days before Newt
Gingrich spoiled the fun.
</P>
<P>
   Former Democratic House Speaker Thomas Foley returned to the
U.S. Capitol Wednesday and for a brief moment restored the mood of
mutual respect that evaporated when Gingrich's right-wing troops
seized control of the House five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Foley's official portrait was unveiled amidst a burst of
bipartisan good will that included the present Republican speaker,
Dennis Hastert, and former Minority Leader Robert Michel. Big-name
Democrats, natch, turned out in droves to honor one of their best _
still a political role model to be admired.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad the mood won't last. How nice if it would spread like a
permanent balm through the marble halls of our overrated,
overheated chief deliberative body.
</P>
<P>
   Foley's six years as speaker were recalled as a golden era of
legislative battle in which the vindictiveness and name-calling
that are now routine in Congress were rare. Michel observed, ``We
were political adversaries, but there was never an ill word spoken
between us ... and that's the way it ought to be.''
</P>
<P>
   But Foley lost his longtime seat from Washington state and his
job as speaker in the 1994 Gingrich revolution. Civility and comity
in Washington, always a delicate business more honored in concept
than practice, went totally out of fashion. Tough, uncompromising
talk was in. Personal insults became the basic coin of exchange.
</P>
<P>
   As Foley's successor, Gingrich viewed the speaker's role as a
partisan hammer with which to beat up Democrats, not work with
them. He and his Democratic counterpart, Minority Leader Richard
Gephardt, barely spoke during the four years they shared the House
leadership. Foley and Michel actually liked each other and called
each other ``friend,'' but Gingrich and Gephardt are creatures
apart.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert has restored a kindly face to the speaker's role. With
only a six-vote margin of control, he has little choice but to be
more conciliatory than Gingrich, although this makes the GOP
hotheads call him weak. He stressed his respect for Foley and
praised him for ``dignity and purpose, always with fair and honest
treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt, a longtime Foley protege, never mentioned Gingrich's
name but managed to draw an unflattering contrast between the two
speakers with practically every sentence. Gephardt recalled Foley
was so honorable that ``when our members were clamoring to vote the
political way, Foley always brought us back to the right thing to
do, for country and for the Constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   He also praised Foley's sense of bipartisanship, noting that
when the speaker was about to disagree with someone he invariably
began by saying, ``With respect, I ... '' That was what it was all
about, Gephardt said. Mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
   Disagreeing without being disagreeable. It reinforces the most
important function of politics _ serving as a substitute for
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Foley himself, now U.S. ambassador to Japan, was in fine fettle.
He recalled that when he was first elected to Congress in 1964, a
powerful House committee chairman warned the freshman class members
that the most dangerous thing they could do would be to ``think for
yourself.'' He told the newcomers that instead they should follow
the advice of their elders, their subcommittee chairmen, their
chairmen, their party leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Foley was outraged. ``I was not about to subcontract out my vote
to others,'' he remembered.
</P>
<P>
   But times change, for us all. ``When I was sworn in as
speaker,'' he smiled, ``the wise words of that chairman came
favorably back to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress is torn today, as it was then, between the demands of
party leaders that members fall into line and the independent
spirit that helped get the members elected in the first place. As
Foley noted, where you stand depends on where you sit, which makes
the joint pretty confusing.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
