<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, Oct. 17,
1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ELIMINATE; TSCHUMI-ARCH.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE story &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DISCO-MUSIC (subslug) (New York) _ When the Broadway musical
version of ``Saturday Night Fever'' opens on at the Thursday
Minskoff Theater, it should, by rights, look as quaint as the 1950s
of ``Grease'' did in the 1970s. ``Saturday Night Fever,'' the movie
released in 1977, marked the apogee of disco, a lucrative moment in
pop that quickly generated a backlash, a record-business crash and
a widespread repudiation. Twenty years is the usual nostalgia gap,
the time it takes for fond memory to replace the embarrassment of
succumbing to a long-gone trend; hence the Broadway-bound
``Saturday Night Fever,'' despite disparaging reviews of its London
production. By Jon Pareles. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAME-OLD-SONG-FILM (Paris) _ Alain Resnais seemed quite amused
by the idea that it took him 35 years to have his first genuine box
office hit. Of course, at 77, he could well afford to display
nonchalance, what with his place in the history of modern cinema
having long been assured by his remarkable first two feature films,
``Hiroshima Mon Amour'' and ``Last Year at Marienbad.'' Even so,
the success of his latest movie, ``On Connait La Chanson,'' or
``Same Old Song,'' surprised him. Much of the charm of ``Same Old
Song,'' which opened in New York on Friday, derives from the way
its six main characters lip-synch popular French songs. By Alan
Riding. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   JOE-THE-KING-FILM (Undated) _ In ``Joe the King,'' which opened
on Friday, Frank Whaley has made an intensely affecting yet
unsentimental movie about a lost child. That the film contains a
large dollop of autobiography _ it is dedicated to his parents _
only makes this 36-year-old actor's achievement more striking.
``Joe the King'' is Whaley's first outing as a writer and director,
and if this is what's considered a small film, it's an
exceptionally rich one. The movie won the screenwriting award at
this year's Sundance Festival. By Karen Durbin. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN-BALLET (Ne _ More than most dance companies,
American Ballet Theater prides itself on its versatility. And
rightly so. Last spring it presented ``Giselle'' and other Old
World heirlooms. For the fall season, which opens on Tuesday and
runs for two weeks at the City Center, the troupe will flaunt its
progressive side, taking on the macabre expressionism of Agnes de
Mille, the wry populism of Twyla Tharp and the quicksilver
partnering of Nacho Duato. By Christopher Reardon. (Moved). Photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ST.-FRANCIS-OPERA (Undated) _ As it becomes clear that Gerard
Mortier will be replaced as director of the Salzburg Festival when
his contract expires in 2002, a new release of Olivier Messiaen's
lone, immense opera ``St. Francois d'Assise,'' which was present on
the program of his first year at the festival, is especially
timely. The new release (Deutsche Grammophon 445 176-2; four CDs),
was recorded at a revival last year. By Paul Griffiths. (Moved).
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRANSPOSED-MUSIC (New York) _ Transposition is in the news at
the Metropolitan Opera. Sir Charles Mackerras has just opened a run
of ``Lucia di Lammermoor'' with three large chunks of the score
restored to the higher keys in which the composer originally wrote
them, and at the same time Placido Domingo is reprising two of his
most celebrated roles, the tragic clown of ``Pagliacci'' and the
tormented Moor of ``Otello,'' with adjustments in the other
direction to accommodate the autumnal range of his tenor voice.
Both circumstances are being discussed extensively _ even heatedly
_ and both are being a bit misunderstood as often as not. By Will
Crutchfield. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POP MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LOMAX-DELTA-BLUES (Undated) _ In 1941 and 1942, the folklorist
Alan Lomax visited the Mississippi Delta to document its
African-American folk music. One of his major objectives was to
record the Delta's most famous cultural product, the blues.
``Mississippi the Blues Lineage'' (Rounder 11661-1825), whose
contents Lomax selected before a stroke incapacitated him several
years ago, represents his early-40s Delta blues fieldwork. By Tony
Scherman. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-ART (Bogota, Colombia) _ Gloria Zea, director of the
Museum of Modern Art here, in an effort to provoke what she calls
``a profound and unhurried meditation'' that can ``help change
behaviors and habits that impede civil discourse,'' her museum, the
capital's most prestigious, has organized the first systematic
examination of ``the scourge that has bled the country dry,'' as
she puts it, in an unsettling exhibition entitled ``Art and
Violence in Colombia Since 1948.'' Each of the show's dozen
sections, spread over four floors, addresses one specific
manifestation of the violence that afflicts this nation of 40
million people. By Larry Rohter. (Moved).
</P>
<P>
   ARTISTS-RETREATS (Undated) _ In a late 20th-century version of
J.M.W. Turner's search for the untrammeled landscape, a small band
of contemporary artists is spending this month trekking in the
Himalayas, seeking fresh vision as well as fresh scenery. This is
part of new versions of the artist residency program in which
traditionally, artists retreat for sabbaticals in bucolic,
cloistered settings like Yaddo or the MacDowell Colony. Now artists
may convene in gritty urban environments, participate in group
living experiments or join far-flung adventures resembling Outward
Bound. By Ann Wilson Lloyd. (Moved).
</P>
