<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7233 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-HNS &LR;      10-14 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE AGAIN DEBATES CAMPAIGN FINANCE REFORM 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate began another long debate on campaign
finance reform Thursday, taking up a streamlined version of a
bipartisan bill introduced by Sens. John McCain, R-Ariz., and
Russell Feingold, D-Wis., that would ban unregulated ``soft money''
donations to political parties.
</P>
<P>
   But as the debate opened, the senators were still far short of
the 60 votes they need to stop a Republican-led filibuster against
the legislation, which is designed to curb the massive
contributions from special interests groups, corporations and
wealthy individuals that McCain says are ``corrupting'' the
nation's political system.
</P>
<P>
   The two sponsors remained hopeful that their decision to drop a
controversial provision of their measure that would have imposed
restrictions on so-called ``issue'' advertisements in campaigns
will persuade some opponents to change their minds. The two also
agreed to a five-daylong debate on the issue, during which members
would be allowed to offer amendments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goal is to break this open,'' Feingold told reporters
earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   The House has already passed a much stronger version of campaign
finance legislation, and if enough senators end up supporting
``McCain-Feingold lite,'' as it's now being called, a compromise
bill would have to be worked out between House and Senate
conferees.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain, who has made campaign finance reform the centerpiece
of his run for the 2000 Republican presidential nomination,
acknowledged that the outcome this year is likely to be the same as
in previous years when he has tried to get his bill through a
Senate controlled by his own party.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., the leading opponent of the
measure, showed McCain just how hard he intends to fight it by
peppering his colleague with questions about what constitutes the
``corruption of government.''
</P>
<P>
   McConnell hammered away at his Arizona colleague for nearly two
hours, and at one point challenged him to name lawmakers who had
engaged in corrupt practices on behalf of special interest
contributors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no corruption, none whatsoever,'' McConnell told
McCain, who has spoken bluntly for years _ and now in his campaign
for the presidency _ about ``the corrupting influence'' of money on
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Special interests have the right to participate in the
political process,'' said McConnell, who as director of the
Republican Senate Campaign Committee is in charge of raising
millions for the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell added that he is ``extremely grateful'' that special
interest groups give their money to support get-out-the-vote
drives, advertising and other campaign-related efforts.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, McCain continued to insist that ``soft money
distorts the legislative process'' by putting pressure on lawmakers
to back legislation and causes favored by big contributors.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a head-in-the-sand pretense ... to say that soft
money does not affect the legislative process,'' McCain said,
adding that the flow of unlimited and unregulated cash into
campaigns ``is impairing our integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   The McCain-Feingold measure would ban the use in federal
campaigns of unlimited and unregulated soft money donations that
the Democratic and Republican parties have come to rely on to get
around federal limitations on contributions to individual
candidates. The money, which pours in from unions, business
interests, wealthy individuals and special interest groups with
their own agendas, is used to finance everything from voter drives
to negative commercials in the closing days of a campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, the bill would force the parties and candidates to
adhere to strict spending and donation limitations imposed by
current federal law.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to win more support, McCain and Feingold dropped
the most controversial provision of their bill, which would have
dictated how and when so-called issue ads could be used in the
closing weeks of a campaign. The ads, often aired by anonymous
groups, are used to promote a negative image of a particular
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   As the debate started, President Clinton signaled his support
for the measure by sending a letter to Senate leaders urging its
adoption.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who is challenging Texas Gov. George W. Bush for the
Republican nomination, has staked his presidential candidacy on
convincing Americans that the nation's campaign finance system is
preventing other vital government reforms from taking place.
</P>
<P>
   Recent public opinion polls in New Hampshire and other early
primary states indicate that McCain, who is now considered the
primary challenger to Bush for the nomination, is beginning to
strike a chord with voters. In New Hampshire, he has climbed to 21
percent in the polls as the favored GOP candidate, second only to
Bush who is still about 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
