<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7235 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GORE15-COX     10-14 0505
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE'S FIRST TV AD SUPPORTS TEST BAN TREATY
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore moved Thursday to make the
2000 presidential campaign a referendum on nuclear weapons with the
broadcast of the first TV commercial of his White House bid _ a
60-second ad he wrote himself and filmed in a Seattle hotel room in
the wee morning hours after the Senate rejected a treaty banning
nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
   And at a conference on global trade with pro-business Democrats
later Thursday, Gore said the actions of the Republican majority of
the Senate, in voting down the treaty Wednesday, was ``breathlessly
reckless'' and ``goes against'' the national security advice of
military advisers in the Clinton, Bush, Reagan and Carter
administrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did they do this? I think there was undeniably for some of
those who voted as they did an element of what feels like political
spitefulness,'' he told an audience of several hundred at the
Democratic Leadership Council's trade conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'm wrong about that,'' he added. ``But there has never
been a time in my memory when issues of war and peace, issues of
nuclear security have been handled on a party-line vote in a
partisan atmosphere with personal invectives directed at the
commander in chief.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore makes similar points in the TV ad, which was to run
nationally on CNN Thursday night. ``This vote goes against the tide
of history,'' the vice president says, according to a copy of the
script provided by campaign officials. ``Why don't we do something
about it?''
</P>
<P>
   In the ad, Gore promises that, if elected president, he will
send the treaty back to the Senate ``with your demand that they
ratify it.'' He adds: ``We can change this mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president wrote the script on hotel stationery in
Seattle late Wednesday, then summoned a local TV production crew to
his hotel room to shoot the ad. He telephoned President Clinton
Thursday morning to notify him of his plans to make the treaty a
campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   Gore had originally planned a biographical ad for his first TV
spot later in the campaign. But he told reporters on the flight
from Seattle to Washington that he felt so strongly about the
Senate's actions that he chose to make the treaty the subject of
his first ad instead.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign policy is rarely a big factor in presidential politics
and treaties even less so. But Gore became an expert on strategic
arms during his 16 years in Congress. And his TV ad indirectly
points up the lack of foreign policy experience on the part of
Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the front-runner for the Republican
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, like most of the Republican members of the Senate, opposes
the treaty. But a poll conducted last summer by Democrat Mark
Mellman and Republican Richard Wirthlin found that 80 percent of
Americans are against nuclear testing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
