<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0357 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7237 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BRADLEYNET15-COX     10-14 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEYNET15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bradley's Internet irregulars helping boost support
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHERRY HILL, N.J. _ Bill Bradley doesn't know it, but the secret
weapon of his presidential campaign lives in the basement of a
split-level house in this leafy suburb of Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   His name is Greg Laynor. He is 14 years old. He studies world
civilization and Latin at the local high school, where he just
started as a freshman. He doesn't drive and he won't cast his first
vote for president until 2004.
</P>
<P>
   But this gawky teen-ager, who began using computers at the age
of 5, is at the forefront of how the Internet is changing political
dialogue in America and giving voice to a new class of political
activist.
</P>
<P>
   Four months ago, Laynor started a Web site supporting Bradley,
whom he has always admired, from his basement computer. Soon,
Laynor was corresponding via e-mail with other Internet users
around the country who liked Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Noah Heller, a sophomore at Ohio's Oberlin College, suggested
they move the site to a larger Internet server, one that would
support more information and more traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Web site (www.netizensforbradley.org) serves as the
unofficial Bill Bradley for president Web site, using some of the
Web's latest technology to link together about 500 hard-core
supporters and thousands of visitors.
</P>
<P>
   It hosts live chat sessions about Bradley and features
electronic bulletin boards, one for each state, where supporters
can post messages about organizing for Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim'' of New York is looking for volunteers to circulate
petitions to get Bradley on the primary ballot there. ``Steve'' of
Florida is urging Bradley supporters to attend the state Democratic
convention in December.
</P>
<P>
   The site has spawned BostonForBradley.org and
studentsforbradley, an off-shoot of that site. Supporters in
Austin, Texas, are launching their own site soon.
</P>
<P>
   This week, users bombarded AFL-CIO President John Sweeney with
e-mails urging him to withhold labor's endorsement of Vice
President Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just organizing,'' said Laynor, a slender teen who wears
braces. ``I don't think there is anything like this for any other
candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Activists such as Laynor, even those younger than voting age,
also are creating new headaches for regulators at the Federal
Election Commission. The FEC is considering whether such
computer-driven organizing is an independent expenditure subject to
FEC disclosure requirements, a finding that Internet users would
vigorously oppose.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you try to regulate a medium that is unregulatable,
global and ubiquitous?'' said Phil Noble, president of
PoliticsOnline. ``You can have a `Bill Bradley is a jerk' Web site
that is hosted in the Ukraine, developed by programmers in Fiji and
funded by credit card contributions all over the world. How is the
FEC going to deal with it? It's almost impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush's campaign, which asked the FEC to clarify
its rules with regard to the Internet, wants answers to difficult
questions. What is the value of e-mail? What about volunteers who
use the Internet to raise money?
</P>
<P>
   ``The way the rules are written now forces campaigns into the
position of almost discouraging the free voices of the Internet,''
said Ben Ginsberg, a lawyer for Bush's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   When Bradley's campaign found out about Laynor, the campaign's
lawyer directed campaign staff to avoid having any contact with the
Web site or its creators, advising them that they might run afoul
of FEC regulations prohibiting coordination with outside groups.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign modified its disclosure statement on its own Web
site, www.billbradley.com, to spell out that it was Bradley's one,
only and official campaign Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Bradley doesn't appreciate what Laynor is doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great,'' said Lynn Reed, Bradley's Internet consultant.
``We've got to have lots of Greg Laynors out there if we are going
to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Every candidate for president, of course, has a Web site,
offering visitors campaign information. Most also allow visitors to
make a credit card contribution.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, Gore and Elizabeth Dole also are using their sites to
develop e-mail lists of supporters. The Bradley database, for
example, is up to about 40,000. When Bradley visits a state, the
campaign alerts supporters so they can turn out to support him.
</P>
<P>
   But what the official sites aren't doing, and what Laynor and
his fellow ``netizens'' are, is creating a medium where supporters
can talk to each other, via e-mail, weekly on-line chats and
postings on electronic bulletin boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's supporters talking to supporters,'' said Laynor, who
convinced his father to drive with him to New Hampshire to canvass
for Bradley this summer. ``People feel like they are a part of the
campaign _ that they are making a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Laynor is a child of the Internet age. His mother
is a librarian. His father is a college text book salesman. Both
use computers in their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Greg grew up with computers _ the family now has five. And he
has grown up with the rapid explosion of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Laynor's mother said her son spent about ``a zillion hours''
this summer hunched over his computer in the basement developing
his netizens site. ``We couldn't get him to do anything else,''
Barbara Laynor said.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 people scattered around the country, from Texas to New
Jersey, maintain the site, which just added a new feature that
tells users how to write letters to the editor on behalf of
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Laynor reads and answers scores of e-mails every day. He has
never spoken to, or even met, Heller, the Ohio college student.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I should call him one of these days,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now that school has started, Laynor's parents are encouraging
their son to spend less time on the computer and more time on his
other school work, such as a pesky geography map he had to draw
recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting, what he's doing,'' said his father, Dennis
Laynor. ``I just don't want it to interfere with his Latin exam or
geometry.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
