<HEADER>
A7253 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-COLLEGE-LIFE-COURSES-     10-14 1305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-LIFE-COURSES-1,200(2TAKES)-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE 101: COLLEGE STUDENTS GET CREDIT FOR LEARNING PRACTICAL
SKILLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., S.C., Wis., Calif., N.C., Ky., Md., Colo., Ind., N.J.,
Conn.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTHAMPTON, N.Y. _ These are the lessons from Tuesday's class
at Southampton College:
</P>
<P>
   _ A smart budget has more money coming in than going out.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do not make the password for your ATM card something obvious,
like your birthday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pay the full balance on credit cards, if possible, but
definitely more than the minimum.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in college, I had a roommate who thought as long as
she had a checkbook with checks in it, she could write checks,''
Suzette Carlow, a guest lecturer from European American Bank, told
the students. ``That's not the way it works.''
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly macroeconomics. Rather, it is College 101, a
one-credit seminar required of all new students. Highlights of the
syllabus: ``Values _ What Matters to You?'' and ``Home for the
Holidays: Readjusting.''
</P>
<P>
   The course at Southampton, a campus of Long Island University,
is part of a proliferation of life-skills seminars nationwide, with
more than 70 percent of colleges and universities offering some
sort of academic class designed to help students adjust to
adulthood and campus life. The trend has exploded over the last
decade, as budget-strapped and consumer-oriented colleges have
battled high dropout rates, and have searched for strategies to
increase student success.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with large groups of immigrants and first-generation
college students pushing enrollments to record numbers,
administrators say the courses are critical. Besides teaching
skills like how to balance a checkbook and deal with the opposite
sex, the classes also create a comfortable environment of
small-group discussions in a world often dominated by droning
lectures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us who went to college 20 or 30 years ago managed to
handle this on our own,'' said Betsy foot, until recently
the co-director of the National Resource Center for the Freshman
Year Experience at the University of South Carolina in Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barefoot acknowledged that the courses, ``to many people,
seem like hand-holding and coddling,'' but she and John Gardner,
the University of South Carolina historian who is considered the
father of the modern life-skills movement, said they are a
necessary adjustment to the changes in higher education.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kind of people who are going to college now are not those
for whom colleges were historically designed,'' Gardner said.
``It's really very subversive. It's about changing the structures
and policies of college to make it more realistic for the people we
serve.''
</P>
<P>
   The goals range from improved note-taking to better self-esteem
and a deeper connection to the college community. The lesson plans
can be as unconventional as the subject matter.
</P>
<P>
   At the University of Wisconsin-Eau Claire, students must attend
a campus event _ a lecture, a basketball game, even a house party _
and write a paper about it.
</P>
<P>
   At California State University at Chico, a class reads the
town's alternative newspaper one week and embarks on a quest for
the best hamburgers in the neighborhood the next. At the Carolinas
College of Health Sciences in Charlotte, N.C., one instructor has
each student draw ``a negative self-picture'' and then she burns
them.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the courses include an orientation workshop with the
campus e-mail system _ often followed by mandatory e-mail journals
submitted weekly _ and a field trip to the library.
</P>
<P>
   ``A college library today?'' Ms. Barefoot said. ``Even I need
help.''
</P>
<P>
   Those involved in what they call the ``first-year experience
movement'' say the first life-skills course dates from 1882, at a
community college in Kentucky. The modern version started at the
University of South Carolina in 1972, in an era of student protest,
as administrators tried to cultivate a sense of citizenship within
the university.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Students were, and still are, taught ``The Carolinian Creed,''
six principles that form a code of honor for the school. The course
started as pass/fail, but now is letter-graded, with midterm and
final exams.
</P>
<P>
   Word spread. And spread. In 1981, about one in five colleges had
such classes; now, it is more like three out of four, the resource
center said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Becoming a Master Student,'' a textbook that includes ``The
seven-day anti-procrastination plan'' and an article headlined
``Crazed Glazed Donut Runs Amok,'' has sold 3 million copies, and
is just one of about 50 such handbooks on the market.
</P>
<P>
   There is a Freshman Year Experience newsletter, an academic
journal (articles include ``New Student Disorientation: Becoming a
Member of an Academic Community'' and ``Is There Life After the
Freshman Seminar''), annual conferences and an e-mail discussion
group with 1,500 members.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Experts estimate that about 85 percent of the classes are for
credit, but typically one credit instead of three, the standard
amount for an academic course. The majority are graded, and taught
by a mix of faculty and staff members.
</P>
<P>
   A few colleges, particularly elite ones, just try to integrate
life lessons into a freshman seminar on an academic subject, but
most make orientation the centerpiece of the life-skills
curriculum, mixing tutorials on how to take proper notes with
sessions urging students to join campus clubs. The trend stretches
from community colleges to selective liberal arts campuses to large
research universities, every place from Ithaca College to the
University of Maryland to the Air Force Academy.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the curriculum, including substance abuse, sexual
harassment and multicultural relations, used to be covered over
pizza in the dorm lounge during orientation. Taking these topics
into the classroom, instructors say, lends more seriousness and
reflects a belief that social problems are linked to grade-point
averages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our overall goal here is promoting academic success,'' Gardner
said. ``If a student has a propensity for acquiring a sexually
transmitted disease, that's very likely to deter academic success.
Drinking certainly affects academic success. It affects class
attendance, it affects your concentration ability, it affects your
dietary habits, your sleep habits. All of that relates to academic
success.''
</P>
<P>
   But some say the courses should be more narrowly focused on
skills crucial to the classroom, like note-taking, close reading
and time management.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without sounding too much like a snob, we are in the business
of higher education,'' said B. Thomas Lowe, a dean for first-year
students at Ball State University in Muncie, Ind., scoffing at the
notion of giving students course credit for learning the names of
campus buildings or discussing roommate problems, common items on
life-skills syllabuses. ``While checkbook balancing and the like
are important, they must be learned elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Research suggests that the introduction of life-skills courses
has helped increase retention rates at open-enrollment schools by
about 10 percentage points, and that students who take the courses
earn higher grades in academic courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one credit,'' said Christopher Lynch, director of
the Freshman Seminar at Kean University in Union, N.J., one of many
schools where a life-skills course is required. ``But it's the most
important credit, because this is the course that motivates
students for success.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Many campuses also offer specialized seminars for specific
groups of students, for example future teachers, business majors,
older students, the disabled, or athletes, and include career
planning in the curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   At a session of ``Life Skills for Athletes'' at the University
of Connecticut in Storrs this fall, a panel of upperclassmen gave
the new students advice on everything from homesickness to handling
criticism from coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go to class as much as possible,'' Erin Layton, a softball
player now in graduate school, said to a room in which several
heads lay on tables. ``Yes, you're going to be tired. If the
professor sees you every day, then if you have to leave early to
catch a bus, or miss class, they might understand.''
</P>
<P>
   When absent, she added, get several classmates' notes. ``One
person can be unreliable,'' Ms. Layton said. ``They may be
sleeping.''
</P>
<P>
   Sleep _ How much is enough? Are catnaps worthwhile? _ is a hot
subject in the required freshman seminar at the University of New
Haven, where a homework assignment asked students to keep an
hour-by-hour time sheet for a week.
</P>
<P>
   Nick D'Amato, a baseball recruit from Mystic, Conn., had ample
sections blocked off for sleep, and several marked ``chill with
friends.'' Monday from 11 p.m. to 1 a.m. was filled with S-E-X,
while Friday from 7:30 p.m. to 1 a.m. was simply, ``party.'' The
calendar did not have room for the 24 hours per week of study time
the instructor said was suggested for a 12-credit course load.
</P>
<P>
   Students in the University of New Haven classes said the
lectures and videos on study skills were often boring review, but
that they liked having a place where they could talk about their
problems, and form a kind of community with classmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my favorite class, for one reason: We actually get to
interact with each other,'' said Branden Morgan, 18, of Newport
Beach, Calif. ``My other classes, the teacher just sits up there
and blah, blah, blah.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan's comments came after a heated discussion of drinking and
date rape, where students raised different colored pieces of paper
to indicate whether they agreed (green) or disagreed (pink) with a
set of controversial statements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes women invite sexual assault by their actions,
appearances or behavior,'' the instructor said, and all of a sudden
Lyn Fockler, clutching pink, founded herself alone in a classroom
crowded with green.
</P>
<P>
   Plaintively yet forcefully, Ms. Fockler, a 17-year-old forensic
science major from San Francisco, complained that if she wore a
tube top rather than her bulky sweatshirt, she would be more likely
to be harassed, or even attacked, than a man strolling shirtless
down the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's because you're a woman,'' Morgan said from across the
room. ``It's been that way since the beginning of time. It's always
going to be,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're just going to have to accept that,'' added Brett
Ortola, 20, of Berlin, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to accept that,'' insisted Ms. Fockler, a petite
woman who wears a buzz cut and several hoops in her ears. ``You
don't deserve to be harassed. It doesn't matter what you wear. It
doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Freshman seminar teachers at several campuses said the
discussions of sex and drugs, diversity and homosexuality, are
typically the most volatile, but that students often also praise
the more practical sessions, like the library visit.
</P>
<P>
   At Southampton, a serene 1,200-student campus whose rolling
hills resemble the Shinnecock Hills Golf Club across the street,
students asked few questions during the banking lecture, but
listened attentively. Several even took notes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I'd had this workshop when I was a freshman,'' said
Lisa McCluskey, 21, a senior who was a teaching assistant for the
class. ``I wouldn't be $1,500 in debt right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
