<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Friday, Oct.
15, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call Bob
Schenet at (206) 448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   KENNEWICK-MAN (Seattle) _ Kennewick Man isn't European or Native
American, a court-appointed scientific panel reported Thursday, but
southeast Asian. The bones that came to be known as Kennewick Man
washed out of the Columbia River in July 1996 and immediately
became the focal point of a dispute between local tribes and a
group of scientists.
</P>
<P>
   By Tom Paulson. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FAST-JUBILEE (Washington) _ His cheeks are sunken, his ankles
swollen. A week ago, he started using a cane. By next week he
expects to need a walker, and a week later a wheelchair. David
Duncombe is starving. Deliberately. The retired minister from White
Salmon, Wash., has been fasting for 39 days now in an effort to
call attention to the starving people of the world. In a city
swarming with lobbyists and protesters of all sorts, Duncombe is
trying a personal approach. He is trying to persuade members of
Congress, one by one, to cancel the debt owed the United States by
about 40 impoverished countries.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael Paulson. (Story will move in the ``w'' category).
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-EARNS (Seattle) _ Boeing delivers a knock-out earnings
report, with commercial production improvements mostly responsible.
</P>
<P>
   By James Wallace. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-FIGHT (Undated) _ ``Fight Club'' is a dangerously
seductive, subversive and seditious movie that is smart in idea and
individuality. The film is visually dark and beautifully dirty and
the performances by Brad Pitt, Helena Bonham Carter and especially
Edward Norton, are first rate. Through its brutality it's wildly
anarchic and bruisingly funny.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-MATING (Undated) _ ``The Mating Habits of the Earthbound
Human'' is one dumb movie. A couple's sexual courtship is viewed
and documented through the eyes of an alien who is making a movie
for other extraterrestrials perplexed by human nature. Carmen
Electra and Mackenzie Astin are the people picked for study from
first meeting to ultimate mating.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-US (Undated) _ Its got Michelle Pfeiffer and Bruce Willis
but their considerable star power can't quite save``The Story of
Us,'' Rob Reiner's tepid comedy about the mayhem of marriage. Ben
and Katie have been wed 15 years and the things that brought them
together are tearing them apart. In flashbacks we glimpse the
fights and fury and fun of their union and by the end, the
one-dimensional couple (thanks to the script) seem so perfectly
suited that we wonder why they bothered to separate in the first
place.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-HAPPY (Undated) _ ``Happy, Texas'' is a contagiously funny,
touching comedy about a pair of escaped prisoners who steal a
Winnebago belonging to two gay, professional beauty pageant
directors and wind up having to impersonate the pair. William H.
Macy walks off with the film in a sweet, gruff portrayal of a cop
who ``finds'' himself when the cons hit town.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-RYAN (Undated) _ ``Ryan Caulfield: Year One,'' premiering
tonight on Fox, looks like a cop drama worth caring about.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN (New York) _ Column from Game 2 of the
American League Championship Series, Boston Red Sox vs. New York
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   By Laura Vecsey. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-THIEL-COLUMN (Seattle) _ Since Alex Rodriguez and his agent
have shown virtually no desire to sign a contract extension with
any team until he becomes a free agent after the 2000 season, the
corner that the Mariners find themselves in this off-season just
became excruciatingly tight.
</P>
<P>
   By Art Thiel. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
</TEXT>
