<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMBUSH-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS KILLER APPARENTLY BECAME ENRAGED BY WIFE'S INFIDELITY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLEASANTON, Texas _ Friends of the young gunman who killed three
law enforcement officers in an ambush described him Thursday as a
likable, hard-working man who was distraught over marital problems.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Vodochodsky, 19, his wife and two children lived with
Jeremiah Engleton and his wife and 15-month-old daughter for the
last six or seven months in their double-wide mobile home.
</P>
<P>
   Vodochodsky, a friend from San Antonio who had known Engleton
for 11 years, said the two of them worked together on a
construction job in nearby Pearsall. Engleton, 21, was deeply upset
and depressed about an affair his wife had had months earlier,
Vodochodsky said, and often cried and talked to Vodochodsky's wife
about the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was stressed out read bad, depressed ... He found out about
it, and they've been trying to work it out, but it wasn't worked
out,'' he said. ``So that's mainly why they argued so much. He was
too hurt to even look at her every day. That's why they'd fight so
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Engleton's anger, his friend said, ``I didn't think that
he'd do this.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, about six hours after his release from jail for
beating his wife, Violet, Engleton made a phony 911 call from his
home and lay in wait for officers to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   He systematically killed Atascosa County Sheriff's deputies
Thomas Monse, 31, who had arrested him earlier that day, Mark
Stephenson, 31, and state trooper Terry Miller, 37. He wounded two
others and held 75 officers and state troopers off for two more
hours before shooting himself in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Tommy Williams could only speculate that Engleton may
have been angry at officers for jailing him after he beat his wife.
When he got out of jail, she wasn't home because a county family
violence counselor had convinced her to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Police found photographs of Violet Engleton in the trash after
her husband's shooting rampage.
</P>
<P>
   Engleton also had been arrested in April for hitting his wife,
but not as violently, the sheriff said, as the episode that caused
his arrest early Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Engleton's mother, Renita, agreed with Vodochodsky's assessment
of her son and his claims that his wife had had an affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``She loved Jeremiah very much and he loved her,'' Renita
Engleton said. ``But he just was not willing to forgive her for
what had happened. It hurt him too deeply.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that her daughter-in-law had spent much of Thursday
with her. But Violet Engleton could not be located for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Most neighbors of the Engletons _ who had moved to the
subdivision of mesquite- and cactus-dotted, five-acre lots less
than a year ago _ knew of nothing amiss.
</P>
<P>
   Resident Wayne Thomas, 44, plant manager for a peanut company,
said Engleton was a polite neighbor who was always ready to help.
``He wasn't at all sullen. ... He would always wave. I told my wife
he would be a good addition (to the neighborhood).''
</P>
<P>
   Other neighbors gave similar assessments, although some said
they were troubled that he often liked to shoot guns at night.
Engleton's firearms collection included the Chinese-made SKS
semiautomatic rifle he used to shoot the officers, plus three
pistols and a shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   Renita Engleton said her son had wanted to live in the country
for a long time, and had ``scraped and saved'' to buy the land and
mobile home in the San Antonio bedroom community best known for
ranching and deer hunting.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors said Engleton worked relentlessly to clear the land
and put in a septic tank.
</P>
<P>
   `` He just had too much stress, too much pressure, and somebody
did something to make him snap,'' his mother said.
</P>
<P>
   She believes her son's rage was triggered by an undisclosed
``culprit'' and she wondered if something might have happened in
jail that made him snap.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff said nothing out of the ordinary happened during
Engleton's arrest or the nearly 12 hours that he was in the county
jail in Jourdanton.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from his arrests for domestic violence, Engleton did not
appear to have a criminal record as an adult. However, a scuffle
with San Antonio police in 1991 over an argument over bus fare
resulted in his suing the police. The suit was dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Vodochodsky said that the final fight between
Engleton and his wife was over a trivial event: The family dog, a
Rottweiler named Chaos, chased their lone milk cow away. Engleton
wanted his wife to track down the cow, Vodochodsky said, and she
refused.
</P>
<P>
   But that minor episode was not at the heart of their problems,
he said. It was always the affair.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
