<SLUG> BC-WORCESTER-NEWSPAPER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. TIMES AGREES TO BUY WORCESTER, MASS., NEWSPAPER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times Co. said Thursday that it has agreed to buy
the third-largest daily newspaper in Massachusetts, the Worcester
Telegram &AMP; Gazette, for about $295 million from The Chronicle
Publishing Co. of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The long-expected purchase would let the Times, which also owns
The Boston Globe, pursue a ``cluster strategy'' in Eastern and
Central Massachusetts. The strategy is one of the latest trends in
the newspaper industry, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   By owning papers in neighboring markets, companies can gain
efficiencies by combining some back-office operations and
potentially boost revenues by offering national advertisers
one-stop shopping for buying ads in a geographic region.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strategically, the Telegram &AMP; Gazette supports a clustering
strategy of managing complementary markets,'' Russell T. Lewis,
president and chief executive officer of the Times Co., said in a
statement. ``The company's ownership of The Boston Globe and the
Telegram &AMP; Gazette will enable us to better serve readers and
advertisers in the eastern half of Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   In one sense, the proposed purchase of the Telegram &AMP; Gazette,
Worcester's only newspaper, is also a bet on the future of central
Massachusetts and the high-technology and biotechnology companies
that are rapidly growing there.
</P>
<P>
   These companies are likely to employ affluent, well-educated
consumers that newspapers and their advertisers want to reach.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Times, the T&AMP;G has a daily circulation of about
107,000, and the Globe has a daily circulation of 463,600.
</P>
<P>
   The T&AMP;G sale is subject to regulatory approval, and until the
purchase is completed, Times spokeswoman Nancy Nielsen said it
would be ``premature'' to discuss specific plans that the company
has for the T&AMP;G's future.
</P>
<P>
   Along with television and radio stations and magazines, The New
York Times Co. publishes 23 newspapers, including the Globe, which
it bought in 1993. The Times had 1998 revenue of $2.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   At Credit Suisse First Boston, analyst Steven N. Barlow said
that the clustering theories behind the proposed purchase of the
T&AMP;G have the ``potential for achieving revenue gains.''
</P>
<P>
   Clustering strategies have grown increasingly popular among
newspaper companies in recent years, added David Cole, publisher of
News Inc., a newsletter that tracks the newspaper industry.
</P>
<P>
   By owning newspapers in neighboring markets, companies have the
opportunity to combine many operations. Taken to its extreme,
clustering could some day have different papers sharing a single
centralized printing facility; what's more, neighboring newspaper
could share stories _ or even whole sections of the newspaper such
as business, features, and sports sections.
</P>
<P>
   Many US newspaper chains are pursuing modified versions of this
strategy, said media analyst John Morton.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the T&AMP;G's strong cash-flow margin, Nielsen said the $295
million purchase price made the T&AMP;G ``an excellent value.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a full price but not extravagant,'' Morton said.
</P>
<P>
   Given that there was a ``bidding war'' for the T&AMP;G, Cole said of
the price, ``It's not totally outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, shares of the Times dropped 9/16
to close at 40-7/16 on a day when it also released quarterly
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   For the past few months, the Chronicle had been looking for a
buyer, and because newspapers of the T&AMP;G's size rarely go on sale,
many newspaper companies had expressed interest.
</P>
<P>
   Identified in news reports as potential T&AMP;G suitors were
Community Newspapers Co., the Needham-based company owned by
Fidelity Investments; Pulitzer Inc.; and Gannett Co.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, the T&AMP;G reported in its business pages that the
front-runners in the bidding war were the Times, Media NewsGroup
Inc. of Denver, and Journal Register Co. of Trenton, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps intent on pursuing cluster strategies of their own, some
of those companies have reputations as rigorous cost cutters. As a
result, some T&AMP;G employees said they were relieved that the Times
had submitted the winning bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is the best possible deal we could have,'' said
reporter Kathleen A. Shaw, who also heads the newsroom union, a
unit of the Providence Newspaper Guild.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody was pleased that it was the Times over some of the
alternatives,'' said reporter Chris Pope. ``But there was some
trepidation over whether there will cutbacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Many questions about the future remain unanswered, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he would remain as publisher, Bruce S. Bennett
replied, ``I have made no assumptions.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added that the paper's management and staff were part of
what had made the Telegram &AMP; Gazette attractive to the Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal is good for everyone,'' said Chronicle chairman and
chief executive John B. Sias in a statement. ``The employees will
benefit and the community served will benefit from the new
ownership.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chronicle has been embroiled in a dispute among the heirs of
its founding family and is selling off its media empire piece by
piece as heirs look to cash out, Cole said.
</P>
<P>
   According to a timeline on the T&AMP;G's Web site, the Worcester
Evening Gazette was founded by a Rhode Island dentist and a Boston
reporter in 1866, and the Worcester Sunday Telegram began
publishing in 1884. The papers were owned by a series of families.
In 1925, the Stoddard and Booth families bought the Telegram and
Gazette. The papers were sold to the Chronicle in 1986 and merged
into the Telegram &AMP; Gazette in 1989.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
