<HEADLINE>
SHARES HALT TWO-DAY SLIDE, BUT INFLATION FEARS PERSIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks arrested their sharp two-day decline Thursday
but regained little ground as investors digested another strong
report on the economy and braced for another round of possibly
unsettling inflation news.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, after retreating nearly 100
points and slipping more than 10 percent from its Aug. 25 record,
recovered and closed with a gain of 54.45, or 0.53 percent, at
10,286.61. The Nasdaq had a smaller gain, but the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 index declined for the fourth straight session.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interest rate fright,'' said David G. Dietze, president
of Point View Financial Services, one of many analysts who cited
rising yields on Treasury bonds and other high-quality debt as the
market's chief depressant. ``When you get up over 6.30 percent,
fixed-income starts looking attractive relative to stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 30-year Treasury fell enough to raise its yield to
6.32 percent, another two-year high, from 6.27 percent on
Wednesday, after the government reported that retail sales,
excluding the automotive sector, were stronger than expected last
month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sentiment is poor,'' added Kathleen M. Camilli, director of
economic research at Tucker Anthony. ``The bond market is telling
us that it smells inflation, not just fears inflation.''
</P>
<P>
   Offsetting some of the gloom about rising rates, however, was
continued optimism about corporate profits, which are beginning to
be reported for the summer quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, for example, jumped 3[, to 43|, accounting for nearly a
third of the rise in the Dow blue-chip average after announcing a
sharp earnings increase. And Apple Computer, which issued a
surprisingly favorable report after the close on Wednesday, soared
9 5/32, or 14 percent, to 73 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   But the market continued to batter companies announcing bad
news, like Unisys, which warned of lower revenue in coming
quarters. Its stock fell 15 11/16, or 37 percent, to 26 9/16 as 23
million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
   And Tyco International, plunged 10, to 87, after losing 7] on
Wednesday after questions were raised about its accounting
practices.
</P>
<P>
   But the recent general weakness has served to create bargains,
some strategists suggested, noting that whole sectors, such as
military goods, have been battered as a result of problems at
individual companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``You start to wonder if we're setting up a pretty good
opportunity to do better,'' said Andrew M. Brooks, chief stock
trader at T. Rowe Price. ``There are some pretty good valuations,
some pretty good entry points.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, including Elizabeth J. Mackay, chief strategist at Bear
Stearns, said the rate rise might be approaching its peak. The risk
of deflation is gone, she said, but there is no risk of serious
inflation despite jumps in the price of some commodities, including
oil and coffee.
</P>
<P>
   The markets will be closely examining a government report on
inflation at the producer level Friday, with the Consumer Price
Index for September to be published next week.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq market, which hit a record on Monday before tumbling,
finished with a gain of 5.57 points, or two-tenths of 1 percent, to
2,806.84.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500, which had 237 components moving up
and 236 down, fell 2.13 points, or 0.17 percent, to 1,283.42, close
to 10 percent below its mid-July peak.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, volume rose to 892.3 million
shares from 821.5 million on Wednesday, with 1,841 issues closing
lower against 1,157 that rose. A whopping 371 stocks made new
52-week lows compared with just 24 reaching new highs.
</P>
</TEXT>
