<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINORITY15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Leaders rally against plan to redefine minority-owned companies
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A proposal that would relax the definition of what
constitutes a minority company came under fire Thursday from
African-American and Hispanic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians, business executives and civil rights leaders
rallied against a proposal by the National Minority Supplier
Development Council to grant waivers to its own rule that companies
must be 51 percent owned by minority groups in order to receive
minority certification.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is controversial because it would allow a company,
on a case-by-case basis, to retain the council's highly coveted
certification even if that company sells stock that reduces
minority ownership to as little as 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call on them to slow down, to push back, to cease and to
desist any and all efforts to redefine what is or is not a
minority-owned business,'' said Kweisi Mfume, president of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People. ``If it
ain't broke, don't fix it, and if it is broke, let's learn to fix
it together.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell said if the proposal is adopted by
the council at its Oct. 26 meeting in Phoenix, it could open the
door to ``front companies'' that hire minorities, but are
controlled by whites.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will stunt the growth of real minority-owned businesses
that have been deliberately left out of the nation's economic
mainstream for hundreds of years,'' said Campbell, who was not at
the news conference but is working with protesters to draw
attention to the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The group _ which included Ray Arvizu, chairman of the United
States Hispanic Chamber of Commerce; Earl Graves, publisher of
Black Enterprise magazine and one of the founders of the council;
and African-American and Hispanic members of Congress _ is asking
the council to postpone voting on the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   But Harriet Michel, president of the New York-based council,
said the proposal is vitally important to help minority businesses
expand their capital. That expansion, she said, is critical if
minority companies are going to compete against larger and better
financed white-owned companies.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to what critics say, Michel said, the council is not
proposing to change its overall definition of a minority company.
Companies would still be required to meet the 51-percent ownership
rule.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed change would allow companies already designated as
minority-owned to apply for a waiver from the rule if they have
brokered a stock deal with a venture capitalist for money.
</P>
<P>
   Michel noted that companies that apply for an exemption of the
ownership rule would be required to keep minorities in control of
the voting stock and board of directors _ a fact not mentioned by
the opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Much of the criticism came before the proposal was released,''
Michel said. ``In the heat of the discussion, it is hard to lower
the decibel level of the opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   The council, started in 1972 to increase business opportunities
for minorities, has the potent power of certifying whether a
company is actually owned by minority entrepreneurs. Large Fortune
500 corporations regularly depend on that certification before
doing business with minority contractors.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed change is supported by big companies, which say
they want to do more business with minority companies but are
limited by the small size of many minority firms.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
