<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7277 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-TREATY-CLINTON-ART-1     10-14 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREATY-CLINTON-ART-1,100&AMP;ADD(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ACCUSES GOP OF ISOLATIONISM; SAYS U.S. WILL ABIDE BY TEST
BAN TREATY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-REPUBLICANS, TREATY-REACT, TREATY-ASSESS,
TREATY-LOTT) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT 10, 11, 12 and 13 have been sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Thursday accused the
Republicans who defeated a treaty that would ban underground
nuclear testing of retreating into a ``new isolationism'' that
threatens national security.
</P>
<P>
   He pledged to abide by the treaty's provisions and warned
countries with nuclear ambitions like China, India and Pakistan not
interpret the defeat as a signal that they are free to resume
testing.
</P>
<P>
   In an hourlong news conference, Clinton tried to make the best
of what his aides conceded on Thursday was a humiliating setback,
one that some White House officials fear could lead other foreign
leaders to wait until the end of Clinton's term before seeking to
strike any deals with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   With a series of attacks on Congress for what he called
``reckless partisanship,'' Clinton made it clear that he hoped
Democrats would turn the defeat of the Comprehensive Nuclear Test
Ban Treaty into a campaign issue. He said that the Senate's
rejection of the treaty effectively sent a four-word message to
America's allies: ``Go take a hike.''
</P>
<P>
   And he added, ``By this vote, the Senate majority has turned its
back on 50 years of American leadership against the spread of
weapons of mass destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Without a hint of the usual Washington bipartisan niceties
toward the Republican leaders who organized the defeat of what was
supposed to be the crowning achievement of his foreign policy,
Clinton used the vote to launch a sweeping denunciation of the
Republicans on the full range of domestic issues: the budget
surplus, Social Security, education, the environment, Head Start,
taxes, Medicare, medical research and air traffic safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``I say to the congressional majority, enough is enough,''
Clinton. said ``We've got a job to do for the American people. It
is not that difficult. Let's just do it.''
</P>
<P>
   And by announcing his resolve to abide by the provisions of the
first major treaty rejected by the Senate since 1920, Clinton was
essentially challenging the Republican aspirants for president to
say whether they would resume underground explosions in the Nevada
desert _ a change of policy that would invite other nuclear powers
to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, if we ever get a president that's against the Test Ban
Treaty, which we may get,'' the president said, the world should
know that ``all bets are off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have Russia testing, we'll have China testing, we'll
have India testing, we'll have Pakistan testing,'' he said. ``We'll
have countries abandoning the Nonproliferation Treaty.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential candidates were careful to focus their
criticism on specifics flaws in the treaty and not to dismiss the
notion of banning nuclear weapons testing altogether. Republicans
in Congress were quick to reject the isolationist label. They shot
back that the Senate simply voted against the treaty because it
could never be confident that China, Russia, North Korea or others
had truly abandoned testing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the substance, the facts were not with the president or
with the supporters of this treaty, they are saying, `Oh, well, it
was politics,' '' Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said on
Thursday. ``That was absolutely not the case.''
</P>
<P>
   While the treaty's rejection and its impact dominated Thursday's
news conference, Clinton also used it to press his case against the
budget that Republicans are assembling, and to lay out America's
agenda for what is likely to be a noisy, protest-filled meeting of
the world's top trade officials in Seattle next month.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that he would veto any spending bill that
eliminated his plans to increase funding for education,
specifically for more teachers and computers in classrooms around
the country. The current Republican plan for across-the-board
spending cuts would eliminate many of those initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that he was willing to negotiate on an increased
tobacco tax, a tax most Republicans oppose.
</P>
<P>
   Only once in the press conference did Clinton begin to sound
defensive _ and it was when a reporter questioned whether the White
House, by inattention or ineptitude, was partly responsible for the
treaty's defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Though he insisted that he had spoken ``30 times'' about the
need to pass the treaty, his aides have acknowledged that Clinton
made little effort to build support for the treaty until
Republicans caught the administration off guard by suddenly putting
it on the agenda for a speedy vote. Only then, as one adviser to
Clinton said on Thursday, ``did everyone discover that there was a
wildly wrong estimate of where we were on this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Clinton faces a delicate dance: He must convince his
domestic audience that the Senate has made a terrible mistake, and
convince other nations not to take his defeat as an invitation to
abandon the treaty themselves or challenge Clinton's authority.
</P>
<P>
   A delay in the vote would have made that two-step a lot simpler.
On Tuesday, when it appeared possible that Democrats and
Republicans would strike an agreement that would delay a vote until
after the next president takes office, Clinton's national security
adviser, Sandy Berger, said that ``there is an enormous difference
between a postponement and a defeat.'' An outright defeat, he said,
could vitiate American credibility and ``give other countries a
pretext'' to resume testing.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton acknowledged that prospect on Thursday, and he
specifically warned India and Pakistan, neither of which have yet
signed the treaty, against interpreting the Senate vote as a green
light to proceed with their nuclear weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me say to India and Pakistan, do not take yesterday's vote
as a sign that America doesn't care whether you resume nuclear
testing and build up your nuclear arsenals,'' Clinton said. Such a
move, he told them, ``will hurt your economy and your future.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same moment, he acknowledged that the message the vote
sent would be a confused one. He said that he told three
ambassadors that he saw on Wednesday night, hours after the vote,
that they should tell their governments that he remained ``in a
battle with the new isolationists in the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   But he expressed confidence, he said, that ``we are not going to
reverse 40 years of commitment on non-proliferation,'' and he
insisted that the treaty remains on the Senate calendar _ even
though there is no interest, in either party, of reviving it.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It is far from clear whether the treaty vote will become a
potent election issue over the next year; without a clear threat
from the likes of the former Soviet Union or China, nuclear
politics do not have the kind of resonance they did when Lyndon
Johnson ran a campaign advertisement in 1964 of a giant mushroom
cloud.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton made a run on Thursday at reviving that strategy.
``Imagine the world we will live in if they prevail,'' he said of
the Republicans whom he charged _ three times _ with isolationism.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that the ultimate goal of the Republicans was to
wipe out all arms control accords, and leave the United States free
to expand on its huge lead. ``They think we ought to go it alone,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a lengthy aside, he said that if the nuclear arms and
chemical weapons conventions were swept aside, defense budgets
would soar, not only in the United States but elsewhere around the
world. He painted a picture of countries diverting money from
education and health care to the military, and raised the specter
that Japan _ which has vowed never to possess nuclear arms _ might
be forced to reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and some nuclear experts questioned on Thursday
whether Clinton was stretching to make his point: Japan has never
seriously been tempted to build its own nuclear weapons, despite
years of tests by Russia and China, and India and Pakistan have
been living under mutual nuclear threat for years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
