<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7279 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-NIXON-TAPES-BOS &LR;      10-14 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIXON-TAPES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAPES REVEAL NIXON BLASTING SENATOR KENNEDY, O'NEILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ALOYSIUS FARRELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The anti-war stance struck by prominent
Massachusetts Democrats triggered fury and resentment from
President Richard Nixon during the Vietnam era, newly released
White House tapes reveal.
</P>
<P>
   In the private confines of the Oval Office, Nixon called
then-House whip Thomas P. ``Tip'' O'Neill Jr. an ``all-out dove and
a vicious bastard.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Edward M. Kennedy was a ``goddamn lily-livered
mealy-mouth,'' the president told his aides.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon had mixed feelings about young John F. Kerry, who was then
a prominent spokesman for a group of Vietnam veterans who opposed
the war. The tapes show that Nixon and his staff respected Kerry's
political gifts, but they saw him as a threat and disparaged him as
a hypocrite.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a Navy lieutenant, on a gunboat, and he used to run his
gunboat up and shoot babies out of womens' arms,'' said a bitter
White House chief of staff, H.R. Haldeman, after Kerry gave
compelling testimony before the Senate Foreign Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, stop that,'' Nixon said, in mock reproach. ``People in the
Navy don't do those things.''
</P>
<P>
   The tape recordings were made by Nixon's secret taping system,
which he had installed to document his role in history. They are
now available to the public for listening at the National Archives,
the latest in a series of tapes to be released.
</P>
<P>
   The tapes show Nixon the strategist, huddling with national
security adviser Henry Kissinger and others to bring the war in
Vietnam to an end and discussing his daring diplomatic
breakthroughs with the Soviet Union and China. They also reveal
Nixon's dark side, as the president rants against his political
enemies and makes cutting remarks about women, African-Americans,
Hispanics, gays and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame these things stay hidden when they matter,''
Kerry said Thursday. ``Yet its always better to have history
written properly.''
</P>
<P>
   When Kerry returned home from Vietnam, he took a leadership
position in the Vietnam Veterans Against The War. The veterans,
many of them disabled by their wounds, camped out in Washington and
lobbied Congress to end the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently this fellow that they put in the front row is one
of the real stars ... Kerry ... he was extremely effective,'' Nixon
said to Haldeman and Kissinger on April 23, 1971.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kerry. He did a hell of a great job ... a superb job,'' said
Haldeman. ``A Kennedy-type guy. He looks like a Kennedy and he
talks exactly like a Kennedy.'' Nixon predicted that Kerry would be
a formidable Democratic candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon's preoccupation with the Kennedys turned up on the tapes
as well. In one phone conversation with the Rev. Billy Graham,
Nixon expressed his opinion that John F. Kennedy had conspired with
former Massachusetts Senator Henry Cabot Lodge, then the ambassador
in Saigon, in the assassination of South Vietnamese President Ngo
Dinh Diem. Diem lost his life in a US-backed coup in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy ``started the damn thing. He killed Diem and he sent the
first 16,000 combat people there himself,'' Nixon told Graham.
``Diem had been murdered. The key thing here, Billy, is Kennedy's _
and I must say our friend Lodge's _ agreement to murder Diem ....
That's what threatened the whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   When the May Day demonstrations were staged by antiwar
protesters in Washington in 1971, Nixon hoped the televised scenes
of violent long-haired ``hippos'' wild on hallucinogenic ``LSC''
would play poorly in middle America. He hoped to tie Senator Edward
Kennedy to the rioters.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's Kennedy doing about all of this?'' Nixon asked his
aides.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's out of town, conveniently ...,'' said aide Charles
Colson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smart as hell,'' Nixon said.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon urged Colson to ``charge up our guys'' and kick the
``goddamn lily-livered mealy mouths'' like Kennedy ``in the
balls.''
</P>
<P>
   When Nixon discovered that Kerry was not camped out with his
fellow veterans but was staying with a friend, Nixon put him down
as a phony. ``He wasn't living down there with those guys ... He's
living in a posh pad in Georgetown,'' Nixon told his secretary,
Rose Mary Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry said jokingly Thursday, after hearing of the taped
material, ``They really liked me. They thought a lot of me.'' Then
he said proudly, ``I was a real thorn in their side.''
</P>
<P>
   In January 1971, after Nixon had addressed the nation on Vietnam
and announced new US troop withdrawals, he talked about O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly bamboozled the goddamn Congress,'' Nixon told
Kissinger. ``O'Neill, who is an all-out dove and a vicious bastard,
didn't know what the hell to say.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; At another point in the tapes, Nixon is heard laughing about
cutting defense contracts in O'Neill's district.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
