<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0377 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7282 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ABOUT-CARS-ECLIPSE-$A     10-14 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABOUT-CARS-ECLIPSE-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2000 MITSUBISHI ECLIPSE GT: SPORTS COUPE FOR MATURE AUDIENCES 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 17) 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By DAN NEIL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Car buyers can be a fickle and cranky constituency. Consider
Mitsubishi's Eclipse sport coupe, which is new for the 2000 model
year. The design wonks and focus-groupies on the company payroll
endorsed the idea that the redesigned Eclipse should be a kinder,
gentler sports coupe rather than the earthy, turbo-zinging
me-machine of years past.
</P>
<P>
   So Mitsubishi traded away a degree of hard-edged performance _
in the form of the car's optional turbo-charged four-cylinder and
all-wheel drive _ for greater civility and more sophisticated
styling.
</P>
<P>
   And an excellent trade it was, too. The top-line Eclipse, the
GT, which is powered by the Galant sedan's 3-liter V6 engine _ has
been transformed into a smooth and suave sports tourer, with
fistfuls of around-town torque, a firm but well-dampened ride and
composed handling.
</P>
<P>
   Many Eclipse loyalists, however, feel more than a bit betrayed.
The new GT is some 200 pounds heavier than the front-drive,
turbo-charged Eclipse GS-T it replaces and a step slower. The GS-T
could make it to 60 miles an hour in about 6.5 seconds; the new car
needs almost a second more.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt some of the carping is because the new Japanese-built
car cannot be as easily ``slammed'' as the older model. Slamming is
modifying imported cars with performance add-ons; it is easier when
a bigger turbo and a wilder computer chip can simply be installed
to raise turbo pressure.
</P>
<P>
   But the complainers should be thankful; Mitsubishi could have
easily pulled out of the sport coupe market, which has dwindled
drastically the last decade from about 800,000 in 1989 to about
half that level last year because of the appeal of those suddenly
sexy sport utility vehicles. So what if the Eclipse has matured
with its prospective market.
</P>
<P>
   Having said all that, the Eclipse GT is no slouch. The 205
horsepower and 205 foot-pounds of torque, or pulling power, coming
from the 24-valve dual-overhead cam V6 is more accessible than in
the older car (torque in normally aspirated V6 engines resides at
lower rpm than in four-cylinder turbos).
</P>
<P>
   Also, the GS-T had a fair amount of turbo lag, the slack period
of acceleration before the turbo kicked in, and when it did, the
car would often surge ungainfully, spinning the front tires and
washing out the steering.
</P>
<P>
   The new car is just as capable of smoking the tires, but the
power is more progressive and easier to modulate. The older model
also required constant nursing of the gears to keep it revving at
peak power. The new car pulls longer and harder at lower rpm, and
that makes for less busywork at stoplights.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the throaty contralto exhaust note is an utter joy to
the ear as you work your way up and down the gears. The test mos equipped with a notchy and quick five-speed shifter with a
nifty baseball-stitch leather cover.
</P>
<P>
   The rich, purring exhaust note, which was fairly pronounced at
higher speeds, made me long for a sixth gear.
</P>
<P>
   The GT is also available with Sportronic, an automatic that can
be shifted manually without a clutch. The lower-end RS and GS
Eclipse models, powered by 2.4-liter, 140-horsepower, in-line
four-cylinder engines, can be bought with Sportronic or manual
transmissions.
</P>
<P>
   The slightly larger, substantially stiffer body helps the new
Eclipse deliver a supple and settled ride, well isolated and quiet
without being numb. The front suspension uses MacPherson struts
while the rear suspension uses multilink connectors.
</P>
<P>
   The car handles very well, answering to steering with crispness
and without sordid body motions. The standard 17-inch Goodyear RS-A
tires, however, lack serious grip, limiting the car's agility when
you want to put the hammer down. Likewise, the four-wheel antilock
disk brakes fail to hang on when pushed hard. Mitsubishi has
obviously left itself some room to build a performance variant in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   Visually and tactually, the new Eclipse speaks a very different
vernacular than the older car. Strake-sided, jeweled with
crystalline headlights and limned in edges and accent lines
(Mitsubishi calls the styling geomechanical, though at Ford Motor
similar styling is called new edge), the Eclipse GT is smartly
current, where the earlier version's organic curves seemed cliched.
</P>
<P>
   This is a handsome car. But as an indication of just how fast
things move in the car business, the Eclipse, which went on sale
this fall, has already been trumped by Toyota's new, crisply
futuristic Celica.
</P>
<P>
   On the inside, the GT holds more than its own. The dash layout
comprises densely rubberized dual cowls divided by the center
console, with simple and well-organized audio and climate controls.
The controls have a pleasant heft and precise action.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath a deep binnacle, the instrument panel displays speed and
rpm with black-on-while dials with orange backlighting. Everything
in the cabin has a taut, rock-solid feel. By contrast, the earlier
GT-S had a nagging flimsiness to the doors and interior fittings.
</P>
<P>
   Among its keen features is an optional in-dash CD changer; two
armrest-mounted cup holders for coffee mugs, and an liquid crystal
display atop the dash, providing either time or radio station data
to the commuter who dares not take her eyes off the bumper ahead.
</P>
<P>
   In a pinch, you can even carpool. The Eclipse's rear seats have
been enlarged to seat full-size adults without undue cruelty. The
rear seatbacks fold down to reveal the trunk cargo area. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE TRACK: Aging, gracefully.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
