<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 17) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., N.Y.)  (af) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An Accounting Gap In Financial Software &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sure, personal financial software allows checkbook balancers to
track every penny. And, certainly, it can lead to gleeful moments
when consumers, after finding a bank miscalculation, say to the
branch manager: ``Oh yeah? Well, my computer says your computer is
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   But the problem is what to do next. Until the bank issues a
refund, the checkbook won't balance. The popular personal financial
software _ Quicken from Intuit, and Money from Microsoft _ have no
built-in way to correct bank errors. That can mean a delay of one
to three months before the statement can be reconciled _ the sort
of thing that can drive diligent bookkeepers to distraction.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly O'Neil, a spokeswoman for Quicken, says she just makes a
note in the note field and enters the right amount of money to
correct the balance.
</P>
<P>
   Accountants have a term for money that is missing but on its
way: ``in transit funds.'' Gerald Lean, a principal in Naden Lean,
an accounting firm in Timonium, Md., suggests entering a deduction
if the mistake is in your favor, or a deposit if the mistake is
against you, then marking it ``in transit.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't waste time over pennies, advised Damian Gallina, a
financial planner at Horan &AMP; Associates in Towson, Md. ``Just write
it off,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _Roy Furchgott &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Philanthropy Food Chain &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Philanthropy is about to show up on some high-definition radar
screens.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, have
invited 150 leading donors, as well as young people and leaders of
foundations and other nonprofit groups, to the East Room this
Friday for what is believed to be the first White House conference
on philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   The group will ``take a look at the tradition of philanthropy
and giving in this country and new ways of looking at it,'' said
Marsha Berry, Mrs. Clinton's director of communication.
</P>
<P>
   Also, America Online's AOL Foundation is about to introduce a
philanthropic Web portal, which will connect donors and volunteers
to nonprofit groups, and link those groups to resources on topics
like management and fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   A second philanthropic Web portal is also in the works. The
Surdna Foundation in New York has awarded $150,000 to Compumentor,
a nonprofit group in San Francisco, to create a technology portal
that will include links to help nonprofit groups find technical
assistance, donated and discounted software and information about
hardware.
</P>
<P>
   _Todd Cohen
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
