<SLUG> BC-MANDELA-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANDELA TO SPEAK AT RICE UNIVERSITY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LYDIA LUM 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Former South African President Nelson Mandela,
considered one of the most intriguing political figures of this
century, will appear Oct. 26 at Rice University.
</P>
<P>
   A 1993 Nobel Peace Prize winner, Mandela was the first black
president of South Africa in 1994, stepping down in June. He
emerged in 1990 after 27 years in an apartheid prison to oversee a
peaceful transfer of power from South Africa's white-minority
regime.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela's speech at the James A. Baker III Institute for Public
Policy will coincide with his receiving the Enron Prize for
Distinguished Public Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is truly a signal event for Rice and for Houston,'' said
Rice President Malcolm Gillis. ``If there's anyone in this century
who qualifies for sainthood, he's at the top of the list.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandela will speak at Autry Court, which can seat up to 5,000.
University officials are inviting students from Houston public
schools and other colleges to attend the event.
</P>
<P>
   He will be joined by His Royal Highness Prince Bandar bin
Sultan, the Saudi Arabian ambassador to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela, 81, was raised in a tribal culture. As a student and
law clerk in Johannesburg, he grew aware of the racial oppression
resulting from apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of the founding members of the African National
Congress Youth League and then opened the first black legal firm in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, Mandela helped lead a sabotage campaign against the
government. Charged with treason, he was sentenced to five years in
prison but that was later expanded to life imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   Although retired from public office, Mandela has assumed the
role of elder statesman in international affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Mandela helped convince Libyan leader Moammar
Gadhafi to turn over two men wanted for trial on charges of blowing
up a Pan Am jet over Lockerbie, Scotland, in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
