<SLUG> BC-RAMSEY-NEIGHBORS15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Friends, family support new inquiry in Ramsey case
 &HT;    By Craig Schneider
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The move to appoint a special prosecutor to
investigate the JonBenet Ramsey slaying is a popular one with
family and friends of the Ramseys.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Ramsey, brother of John Ramsey, who lives in metro Atlanta,
said John and Patsy Ramsey are innocent and the case should
continue to be investigated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just grateful that the grand jury found there was no case
against them _ because they're innocent,'' Jeff Ramsey said. ``Now
we can get on with finding out who did this. Our intention is to
find that out.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Ramseys, he said: ``They feel this was just terrible
from all directions. They were innocent but they had to go through
all this. I just hope this opens people's minds to the fact that
(the police) were going down the wrong direction. I hope law
enforcement now puts some serious attention to finding the
killer.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Sanders, 56, of Sun Lake, Ariz., became close to Patsy
Ramsey when they were both suffering from cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, they never bothered to investigate anybody but
the Ramseys. I have a lot of frustration. There were a lot of
sloppy police procedures. Now, how are they ever going to find out
who killed their (the Ramseys') baby.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the Ramseys ``are always changing their phone
numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Patsy Ramsey could have never killed JonBenet, Sanders said.
``When she had cancer, she worked too hard to stay alive, so she
could take care of her children.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty Smith, a longtime friend of the Ramseys and a chaperone
for Patsy Ramsey when she was West Virginia's entry in the Miss
America pageant, said the Ramseys had been in Boulder, Colo., for
Wednesday's announcement. Smith was happy when she heard the news
that her friends were not being indicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thrilled with the verdict,'' she said. ``I tried to call
them (Wednesday night) and (Thursday) but I don't know if they're
back in town yet. I know they were in Boulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said all along they weren't guilty. I'm sure the family is
relieved they're out from under suspicion, but they have to be
quite upset that someone else wasn't indicted.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who said she spoke with the Ramseys last month, held out
little hope a special prosecutor would help. ``I guess I'm in favor
of it. But I'm afraid it would likely be a waste of money.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Steven Bacon, head of staff at Peachtree Presbyterian
Church in Atlanta, where the Ramseys worship, said the relationship
between ministers and the Ramseys falls into the realm of pastoral
care, and they have determined not to speak publicly about the
couple or the case.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
