u a BC-RAMSEY-GRAVESITE15-CO     10-14 0385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMSEY-GRAVESITE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Visitors reflect on sad injustice at Ramsey burial site
 &HT;    By Joshua B. Good and Fran Gilpin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Betty Broom and Roslyn Lambert had shopping on the
brain Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   But bargain hunting in Marietta, Ga., could wait, as the two
strolled over to the corner of Winn and Polk streets for a more
somber, reflective moment _ a peak at JonBenet Ramsey's grave.
</P>
<P>
   The burial site has become a bit of a tourist stop _ not the
maddening, constant attraction, but a place often visited by folks
who'd never met any of the Ramseys. Thursday wasn't all that
different. A handful of visitors _ most like Broom and Lambert _
passed through.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first visit for Lambert, a 57-year-old Orlando, Fla.,
mother of three who had followed the coverage of the girl's slaying
by watching CNN and reading on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second visit for Broom, 58, of Atlanta. She showed
Lambert the dangling angel ornaments hanging from the tree
branches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't this precious, these little angels?'' Broom asked,
cradling one in her hand.
</P>
<P>
   As Broom knelt next to the grave marker and lightly brushed her
hand across the stone, Lambert stood with her arms across her
chest, reciting her opinion of the unsolved homicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just baffles my mind, our justice system,'' Lambert said.
``In all the pictures of JonBenet, she was smiling. But if you look
at the eyes, just the eyes, she was so sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Broom stood, dusted herself off and smiled as she announced her
next destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're off to the (Marietta) Square to shop,'' Broom said.
</P>
<P>
   The next visitor was Kristen Valentine. She works across the
street at Marietta High School.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine, 25, walked to the grave during her lunch break and
stopped to look for a few short moments as a TV camera recorded her
visit. Her two students ignored the grave and stared at the TV
camera.
</P>
<P>
   As Valentine turned to leave, she commented: ``It's quiet and
peaceful,'' referring to JonBenet's cemetery plot. But the visit
reminded Valentine that someone who killed a child is still free.
</P>
<P>
   ``The person or persons who did this have not been brought to
justice,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
