<SLUG> BC-NYTIMES-WORCESTER-725&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES BUYS MASSACHUSETTS NEWSPAPER FOR $295 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds note slug change: budgeted earlier as TIMES-ACQUIRE) 
(th) 
 By FELICITY BARRINGER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Times Co. bought The Worcester Telegram
&AMP; Gazette on Thursday for $295 million, expanding its reach in
Massachusetts, where it already owns The Boston Globe, and making a
major investment in the newspaper industry, which is currently
buoyed by record advertising.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's boom was reflected Thursday in the Times Co.'s
earnings report, which showed net income for the third-quarter
rising 9.2 percent, to $60 million, on revenue of $729.7 million.
The revenue total was 6.9 percent above the 1998 third-quarter
total of $682.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company's operating profit, excluding such specia
such as the cost of work force reductions at The Boston Globe, rose
11.2 percent, to $112.8 million from $101.4 million, an increase
spurred by a 9.9 percent increase in newspaper advertising revenue,
which rose to $460.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding the special items, the company earned 36 cents a
diluted share, one cent above the consensus estimate reported by
First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   The company's purchase of the Worcester newspaper, with a daily
circulation of 107,000 and a Sunday circulation of 134,000 in
central Massachusetts, ended a lively competition among at least
seven newspaper companies bidding for the remaining newspaper
properties of Chronicle Publishing Co., which sold its flagship,
The San Francisco Chronicle, this summer to Hearst Corp.
</P>
<P>
   One rival bidder, according to those who participated in the
negotiations, was Community Newspaper Co., which is based in
Needham, Mass., and publishes dailies in Framingham and Milford,
Mass., as well as more than 100 nondaily newspapers around the
state. Another was the Denver-based Media News Group Inc., which
owns five dailies in northern and central Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The competition among bidders reflects the desire of newspaper
companies to consolidate, or cluster, their holdings in one
geographic area, to gain efficiencies in everything from printing
and distribution to advertising sales.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Nielsen, a spokeswoman for the Times Co., said that the
company forecast economies in joint advertising sales between the
Globe and the Telegram &AMP; Gazette as well as centralizing newsprint
buying, accounting and record-keeping.
</P>
<P>
   According to one person who has inspected the paper's financial
statements, the $295 million price was about 13.5 times the 1998
cash flow of the Telegram &AMP; Gazette _ a multiple well below that
paid by Pulitzer Inc. to Chronicle Publishing for The Pantagraph, a
newspaper in Bloomington, Ill., that has a circulation of 49,600.
</P>
<P>
   Eight days ago, Pulitzer announced its acquisition of The
Pantagraph for a purchase price of $180 million, representing a
multiple of roughly 19 times 1998 cash flow, according to one
newspaper company adviser who had seen the financial information
circulated by Chronicle Publishing.
</P>
<P>
   But the $295 million price for the Worcester paper was still a
strong reminder of the prices newspapers can command these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Worcester price is just reflective of the very strong
state of the newspaper marketplace,'' said Owen Van Essen, the
president of the newspaper brokerage firm of Dirks, Van Essen. He
added that newspapers the size of the Telegram &AMP; Gazette that
dominate their markets _ the newspaper reaches 43 percent of the
homes in Worcester County _ do not come on the market often.
</P>
<P>
   Van Essen added, ``There is bullishness in newspaper companies''
_ a comment bolstered by recent increases in the share price of
some newspaper companies. The Times Co., Knight Ridder, Dow Jones &AMP;
Co. and Times Mirror Co. all hit 52-week highs within the last
week.
</P>
<P>
   The Worcester purchase, however, had little effect on analysts'
views of the activities of the Times Co., particularly since the
$295 million cash outlay for the newspaper is dwarfed by the $376
million the company has spent to repurchase its stock this year.
</P>
<P>
   Two analysts, Lauren Rich Fine of Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. and Kevin
R. Gruneich of Bear, Stearns, used the same word _ ``nonevent'' _
to describe the Worcester newspaper purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Both analysts focused instead on the resurgence of advertising
revenue at The Boston Globe, which took in $114.4 million in ad
revenue in the third quarter, a 9.8 percent increase over the
corresponding period in 1998. The New York Times newspaper took in
$260.5 million in the period, an increase of 10.9 percent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The most pleasant surprise was the upward pivot in Boston
Globe advertising,'' Gruneich said. He added that he also saw
``some awfully good momentum at Times Company Digital'' _ the
division of the company that includes Web sites like nytimes.com
and boston.com.
</P>
<P>
   The number of registered users of The New York Times on the Web
rose to 8.7 million, an increase of 900,000 over the June 30
figure.
</P>
<P>
   Times Co. shares closed Thursday at $40.4375, down 56.25 cents
and off more than $2 from the all-time high of $43 reached on
Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 2052EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
