<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7290 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-S.C.-GAMBLING-(TRIMS)     10-14 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-S.C.-GAMBLING-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH CAROLINA COURT ENDS VIDEO-POKER GAMBLING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.C., Ala.)  (Eds note slug change: story was budgeted previously as
SCAR-GAMBLING) 
(DW) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The country's largest video gambling industry faced
extinction Thursday when the South Carolina Supreme Court ruled
that the state's 34,000 video poker machines must be unplugged by
midnight June 30.
</P>
<P>
   In a swift stroke, the court put an end to the most rancorous
issue now confronting South Carolina, with all five justices voting
to silence the poker machines that have taken root in virtually
every convenience store and gas station in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The poker machines were at the core of the state's gubernatorial
election last year, and public anger against them had produced a
feverish campaign in recent weeks leading up to a Nov. 2 referendum
on whether the machines should remain legal. That referendum was
declared unconstitutional Thursday by the Supreme Court, triggering
a legal provision requiring the machines to be banned after June
30.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise decision, the result of a legal miscalculation by
one video poker operator, is the second major defeat this week for
organized gambling in the South. On Tuesday, with the encouragement
of religious leaders, voters in Alabama rejected a plan to create a
state lottery for the benefit of education.
</P>
<P>
   Church groups had also been extremely active in South Carolina
in campaigning against the video machines, which were called the
``crack cocaine'' of gambling in a recent national study because of
their addictive nature. Joined by most of the state's business
community and many of its politicians, the anti-poker effort had
appeared likely to suffocate the state's $2.8-billion-a-year
gambling industry at the ballot box, with polls showing that 61
percent of expected voters planned to vote against the machines.
</P>
<P>
   The court's ruling, however, said the referendum was
unconstitutional because it improperly gave the voters the ability
to legislate, a right reserved solely for the state Legislature.
The South Carolina Constitution, unlike those of some states, does
not contain a provision allowing referendums on legislative
matters.
</P>
<P>
   The court then went a step further and said that under the law
authorizing the referendum, video poker could continue only if the
voters approved. Because the referendum was i the court
said, the machines would have to be prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of video poker had helped write the law with this
possibility in mind, because it was never clear that the public had
a legitimate right to vote on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The video industry wanted the law to say that poker would stay
alive unless it was killed by the voters, but legislators decided
that poker would die unless it was kept alive by the voters. The
law explicitly said that if the referendum should be declared
illegal, then the provision outlawing video poker would stay in
effect. The high court upheld that section of the law in its
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Gambling opponents were overjoyed by the decision, even though
some had hoped for a definitive vote of the people next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were watching on TV when it was announced, and there was a
lot of shouting, high-fives, tears of disbelief, and joy,'' said
the Rev. Steve Hogg, pastor of the First Baptist Church of Rock
Hill and a leader of Change South Carolina, a prominent anti-poker
group. ``It looks the gambling industry knew they were going to
lose at the ballot box, and one of them went to court to stop the
vote. Boy, did that backfire on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the industry, fearing just such a ruling, had declined
to challenge the referendum in court. But one small operator,
Joytime Distributors and Amusements in Greenville, filed suit
against the referendum law, hoping the entire law would be thrown
out and the machines could stay.
</P>
<P>
   Other operators filed briefs to get the lawsuit thrown out. But
to the industry's chagrin, the court ruled that only the referendum
was illegal, while the rest of the law banning poker was upheld.
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, the industry could persuade the Legislature to
change the law, but legislative leaders said it was highly unlikely
they would revive the issue. Gov. Jim Hodges, who accepted $3
million from poker interests last year, half his campaign treasury,
but later announced that he would vote against gambling, said
Thursday that the industry did not have the votes to revive itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, as of June 30, the net result of this will be that
video gaming will no longer exist in South Carolina,'' Hodges said.
``We will move on and talk about other important issues on the
agenda in South Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   One issue will be a state lottery, which will be on the South
Carolina ballot in November 2000. Although Hodges built much of his
campaign on support for a lottery, anti-gambling forces are hoping
the momentum from the effort against video poker will carry over
into a defeat for a state numbers game, much like the vote in
Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Video poker has far more opponents than the lottery. Business
leaders have said poker is destroying South Carolina's image, and
many people have been galvanized by the sight of impoverished poker
players feeding money into the machines.
</P>
<P>
   The poker industry, which had held out hopes that a statewide
advertising blitz might persuade voters to keep it alive, was
stunned by the ruling. Mike Fletcher, a spokesman for the South
Carolina Coin Operators Association, said the state's 650 operators
were so focused on the referendum that they barely knew how to
respond to the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the highest court in the state, so I don't know how you
change that,'' Fletcher said. ``We're all kind of shocked and
saddened, but I guess we'll take some time to study the order and
figure out where we go next. Fortunately, we're not out of business
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   He said there might be some way to convert the machines to
nongambling amusements, like pinball, but he admitted that would
make them far less popular.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Gambling supporters had warned that 28,000 employees of the
industry faced layoffs if poker was outlawed, from repairers to
store clerks to the attendants that were required by law to
supervise every five machines. Even if that number was an
exaggeration, it was clear that many people whose livelihoods came
from the machines faced an uncertain future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unemployment line is going to be out the door, and I'm
going to be in it,'' said Chris Moskovic, assistant manager of the
Slots of Fun video parlor in West Columbia, which has 10 machines.
``This is like the state is telling me I have no rights, taking
food from my family's table. It's pretty close to being
Communist.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Francis Rice, a cashier at Cherokee Games in Fort Mill, one of
the casino-like parlors that cluster on the border with North
Carolina, said she would miss the friends she had made among the
parlor's regulars.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was one of the nice places,'' Ms. Rice said. ``It was
nicely decorated and they even paid benefits. But I guess I could
always go back to waitressing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
