<SLUG> BC-MA-DOCTORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRACTICE DROPS PLAN TO FINE DOCTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hit by sharp criticisms, the Mount Auburn Cambridge Independent
Practice Association Inc. Thursday made a hasty retreat from plans
to impose a $250-a-day fine on doctors whose hospital admissions
are deemed ``not medically necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Physicians both in and outside the 350-doctor Cambridge, Mass.,
practice have expressed outrage at the penalty, which would have
been effective Nov. 1, according to an internal memo obtained by
the Globe. Critics argued that the fine would lead to denials of
necessary hospital care.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charging $250 is quite mean spirited, frankly,'' said Dr.
Susan Bennett, an internist in Brookline, Mass. ``It's a financial
incentive to withhold care.''
</P>
<P>
   While the physician practice vigorously defended the fine as a
way to keep physicians accountable for wasteful medical practices,
it said it would review the policy before making any final decision
on whether to implement the fines.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point we are delaying the implementation of the policy
to give us more time for further discussion and education of our
members,'' said a statement from the Cambridge practice. ``We will
seek additional reviews of the policy with the various ethics
committees with which we work.''
</P>
<P>
   Managed care insurance companies have long deployed financial
rewards and penalties to prod doctors to practice efficiently, but
much of the incentives were shared by groups of doctors, rather
than individual physicians. The Cambridge practice's proposed
penalty departs from that model by taking direct aim at individual
physician's compensation, ethicists point out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having physicians be cost-conscious is certainly something we
all want,'' said Dr. Steven Pearson, associate director of the
Center for Ethics in Managed Care at Harvard Medical School and
Harvard Pilgrim Health Care. ``But when you get down to individual
physicians and individual patients, there would have to be an awful
lot of safeguards to prevent this from'' appearing to have a
conflict of interest.
</P>
<P>
   That managed care tactics are being adopted by physician groups
presents a twist in the story. Health maintenance organizations
commonly have been villified for their cost-containment strategies.
But increasingly, HMOs have passed on the financial risk to large
hospitals and physician groups such as the Mount Auburn practice,
in essence turning the practices into little insurance companies
that receive a fixed payment to care for patients. If the medical
costs exceed the payment, the group has to make up the difference
out of their own pockets. If costs come under budget, the group
gets to keep the amount and distribute the profits among its
doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Managed care companies have gotten out of the business of
being the bad cop by sharing the risk with physician groups who are
left trying to figure out how to live within a budget,'' said
Pearson.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over the Cambridge practice's penalty grows from a
long history of tensions between cost and access to health care. As
administrators struggle to keep a lid on the soaring price of
health care, physicians and patient advocates bristle under the
financial constraints. Managing those tensions has been a high-wire
exercise for many health care administrators, who are constantly
searching for new ways to cut costs without provoking too much
outcry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The managed care environment in which we operate is extremely
complicated,'' said the statement issued by the Cambridge practice.
``Our intent remains the same _ to try to improve the quality of
care we deliver to patients. We believe that the practice of good
medicine requires us to be mindful of our limited resources.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
