<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7292 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-TREATY-CANDIDATES-NYT     10-14 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREATY-CANDIDATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE OPENS FIRE ON REPUBLICANS, BUT DRAWS LITTLE FIRE IN RETURN 
</HEADLINE>
  (With TREATY-CLINTON, CLINTON-REPUBLICANS) 
(sw) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE with KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Immediately after the Senate rejected the treaty
banning all underground nuclear testing on Wednesday night, Vice
President Al Gore personally _ and furiously _ dashed off the first
television commercial of his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe this campaign is about the future,'' Gore declares
in the advertisement, which hit the airwaves on Thursday night in
an attempt to carry President Clinton's assault on the
congressional Republicans into the presidential race. ``And there
is no more important challenge that stopping the spread of nuclear
weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   But the front-runner for the Republican nomination, Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas, and the other Republican contenders did little to
respond to Gore's challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Ensconced on Thursday at his ranch northwest of Waco, Bush
issued a written statement accusing the president of backing a
treaty riddled with shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   ``No American, Republican or Democrat, supports the spread of
nuclear weapons,'' he said. ``And if elected president I will be
committed to stopping proliferation. But this flawed treaty was not
the way to further the cause of peace in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush, who declined requests to discuss the nuclear testing
issue with reporters on Thursday, offered no alternative
anti-nuclear prescription of his own and left it to his aides to
fill in what his objections were to the document rejected by the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The central objection, Bush's advisers said, is that the treaty
would commit the United States to the ban in perpetuity, an
argument that supporters of the treaty reject. But they also
complained that the pact did not contain adequate provisions to
insure it was verifiable and would not adequately dissuade
countries like North Korea and Iraq from halting their arms
buildups.
</P>
<P>
   Of the other Republican candidates, Sen. John McCain of Arizona
and Elizabeth Dole complained that the treaty lacked adequate
verification measures but did not commit themselves to offering a
better version if they were elected president. The publisher Steve
Forbes said he supported underground nuclear testing.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Bill Bradley, Gore's rival for the Democratic
nomination, issued a statement saying he would ask the Senate to
reconsider its vote if he is elected. The treaty, he said, was ``of
strategic importance'' and ``will strengthen the international
consensus for non-proliferation.''
</P>
<P>
   The contrasting responses by the leading presidential candidates
offered a clear preview of how Republicans and Democrats intend to
portray the outcome of the Senate vote as evidence of their
superior approaches to foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   As is often the case, their responses were tempered by tactical
political considerations. The statements by Bush and his chief
rivals seemed intended to cement their credentials with
conservatives who are important in the primaries. But because polls
suggest that that voters in general usually favor such agreements,
they tried to draw a distinction between the particular document
rejected on Wednesday and the worthy goal of limiting the spread of
nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also sought to make President Clinton a foil,
arguing that the outcome demonstrated that he had lost credibility
_ and that it was time for an administration that commanded more
respect on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   While Democrats did not argue that the treaty itself could be
turned into a powerful campaign issue, they tried to present the
vote as emblematic of reckless decisions by Republicans in
Congress. More specifically, Democrats said the vote was an ideal
vehicle to raise questions about Bush's lack of foreign policy
credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who was particularly swift and aggressive in his response,
does not cite Bush specifically in his new commercial. But, talking
with reporters on Air Force II as he flew on Thursday from Seattle
to Washington, Gore drew an unstated comparison by speaking at
length about the history of arms control. He vowed to make the vote
a fundamental issue in his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``My world view is pretty well developed,'' he said. ``And this
plays a major role in it.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice president said he felt so passionately about the issue
that when he checked into his hotel after two fund-raising events
in Seattle on Wednesday night, he pulled out a pen and a sheet of
white hotel stationery and wrote a script for the commercial. After
the script was typed, and then edited by Gore, his campaign
advisers dispatched a camera crew and filmed the commercial early
on Thursday in a conference room of the hotel. It will be broadcast
nationwide on CNN and on stations in the early-voting states of
Iowa and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Hart, a Democratic pollster, said his party would argue
that the vote ``isolates the Republicans into a position outside
the broad mainstream.'' He said: ``And the more questions about war
and peace the more skittish the public becomes about Governor Bush.
He becomes the untested, the unknown, the person we feel less
certain about.''
</P>
<P>
   But Condoleeza Rice, Bush's top foreign policy adviser, bristled
at those who questioned the intentions of Senate Republicans. ``I
don't know why anyone would say to the Senate that their
constitutional responsibility to assess treaties is any less
important than the president's responsibility,'' she said. ``That's
not partisan. That's not political. That's a national security
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview here before the Senate vote on Wednesday, Bush
suggested that a defeat for Clinton might come from a lack of
credibility on Capitol Hill. Asked if another president would
encounter such resistance, he said: ``It depends on whether or not
the next president can earn the trust of the Congress. It's just a
matter of relationships that need to be strong.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush hastened to add: ``The reason the test ban treaty, in
my judgment, is not going forward is because a lot of senators
think it's a bad idea. Hopefully, this isn't a personality contest.
A lot of senators, thoughtful people, feel that we shouldn't have a
test-ban treaty.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Mrs. Dole said the agreement was ``ineffective, non
verifiable and will not contribute to non-proliferation or our
national security.'' She added that it was ``nebulous in its
terminology and different countries will interpret it
differently.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain agreed that the treaty was not verifiable. ``The only
safe course, was to do what President Reagan did at Reykjavik: take
no deal rather than a bad one.'' At the Soviet-American summit in
Reykjavik, Iceland, in 1986, Reagan came close to a sweeping
arms-reduction deal with President Mikhail S. Gorbachev but backed
away.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes said his main objection was that he believes there should
be underground nuclear tests on a periodic basis. ``It is not
enough to rely upon computer models,'' he said. ``The experts tell
us we need real-world tests and I agree.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
