<SLUG> BC-NURSING-HOME-BANKRUPTCY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NURSING HOME CHAIN SEEKS BANKRUPTCY PROTECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sun Healthcare Group Inc., one of the largest nursing home
chains in America, Thursday filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy court
protection, becoming the fourth nursing home company with major
operations in the state to seek court protection against its
creditors in as many months.
</P>
<P>
   Sun, based in Albuquerque, has over 4,500 patients in
Massachusetts in 36 facilities, called SunBridge homes, that are
scattered throughout the state. Nationally, Sun has 369 facilities
with roughly 40,200 beds.
</P>
<P>
   Sun officials Thursday reassured state nursing home regulators
that it fully intends to keep its homes open and workers employed.
</P>
<P>
   Sun has not been alone in its financial woes. Vencor Inc., based
in Louisville, Ky., filed for Chapter 11 court protection last
month. In late June, it was NewCare Health Corp. of Atlanta, which
owns four nursing homes in Western Massachusetts. In July, the
Frontier Group, a Boston chain with 700 beds in Massachusetts,
sought protection from its creditors.
</P>
<P>
   Combined, the four companies represent 17 percent of all nursing
homes in Massachusetts, according to Scott Plumb, senior vice
president of the Massachusetts Extended Care Federation, which
represents over 500 nursing homes and assisted living facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many more facilities will it take for Medicare and
Medicaid to realize how grossly underfunded our industry is,''
Plumb said.
</P>
<P>
   Sun, like other financially troubled nursing home companies
preceding it in federal bankruptcy court, pleaded shortfalls in
government reimbursements from such programs as Medicare and
Medicaid, both of which make up the vast majority of payments to
the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep cuts in Medicare reimbursement exceeded all industry
expectations and severely impacted the ability to service its
current capital structure,'' Sun's Chief Executive Andrew L. Turner
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say that Sun's relentless acquisition strategy over
the years led to an unsustainable debt load. Earlier this year, it
defaulted on more than $1.57 billion in loans and bonds, leading in
June to the delisting of its shares on the New York Stock Exchange.
Company executives in August began to reassure state regulators
that it would continue to operate its 369 nursing homes in the
event it sought court protection to reorganize its finances.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a company that was extended to begin with,'' said
Charles W. Lynch, an analyst with Schroder &AMP; Co. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, we are specifically instructing the states to monitor
Sun's homes to ensure that residents continue to receive quality
care. (T)he reports that we have received to date suggest that
residents remain safe,'' said Michael Hash, deputy administrator of
the US Health Care Financing Administration, which regulates
nursing homes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
