<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No letting up for Braves
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For this the Mets can thank their favorite team from
the Bronx: the Braves are anything but secure in their 2-0 lead in
this National League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   That's because they had an even better one not too long ago _
2-0 on the Yankees in the 1996 World Series in New York _ and lost.
So they don't need anyone to remind them before tonight's Game 3 at
Shea Stadium that no lead is safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two-0 means very little when you're playing a good team,''
Chipper Jones said. ``The momentum of a series can shift with one
swing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahem. Like Jim Leyritz's home run off Mark Wohlers in the eighth
inning of Game 4 of the '96 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were talking about who was going to have post-World Series
parties,'' Jones said. ``Just goes to show you overlook a team, you
take something for granted, all of a sudden you relax and the team
is on your heels again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Humility, for us now having been there, is an incredible
thing,'' John Smoltz said. ``You learn a lot from it.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Braves plan to go about their stay this weekend in New
York the way they did the better part of September _ sniffing out
the jugular.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves used that attitude to take the Mets out of the NL
East with six consecutive wins, including a three-game sweep of the
Mets. Then after beating Mike Hampton and the Astros in the pivotal
Game 3 of the Division Series, the Braves finished them off the
following day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chemistry we have in the clubhouse, it builds emotion,''
said Brian Jordan, who drove in all five runs in that Game 3. ``We
know it's not going to be a cake-walk. We also know if we can win
the first game here off Al Leiter, that's going to be the straw to
break the camel's back, and that's what we're looking to do. I
don't want to go back to Atlanta. I want to win this weekend. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to take anything for granted,'' Jordan said. ``I
want to kick you while you're down, and I don't want it to be
close. I've had enough heart attacks for one season.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan wasn't with the Braves in 1996, but he knows how they
feel because he was playing for the Cardinals when they collapsed
to the Braves in the 1996 NLCS despite having a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like this team is in a situation to expect the
unexpected,'' Smoltz said. ``I think this team has been through
enough. We're not really feeling anything right now. ... Pressure
is what you create for the other team.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
