<SLUG> BC-FAA-DELAYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAA CHIEF SAYS AIRLINES MUST DO MORE TO EASE DELAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal Aviation Administrator Jane Garvey said Thursday that
while her agency is working hard to reduce the number of delays
that cost airlines more than $1 billion this year and frustrate
passengers, only so much can be done in the air and airlines and
airports must also do more.
</P>
<P>
   Garvey, in testimony in Washington before the House Committee on
Transportation and Infrastructure subcommittee on aviation,
acknowledged that the FAA ``clearly has an important role to play
in the reduction of airline delays'' but said only so much can be
done in the air to correct existing problems.
</P>
<P>
   She said the burden of reducing delays also must be shared by
airlines in terms of scheduling, and by airports which must deal
with what she called the ``very politically sensitive issue'' of
capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Garvey's remarks come at a time when she is being asked to
decide whether the Massachusetts Port Authority should be allowed
to proceed with plans for a controversial new runway at Boston's
Logan Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hard choices will have to be made at all levels of government
with communities across the country to ensure that we have the
infrastructure in place to accommodate anticipated demand,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether local communities are discussing new runways, new
terminals, or new airports, the debate is always heartfelt and
emotional. While the FAA will continue to make those improvements
to the NAS (national airspace system) that are within our control,
improving how the aircraft are controlled in the air does not
necessarily ensure them a place to land on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   An FAA official said Garvey's remarks were not meant to address
specific airports but deal broadly with the complex issue of
delays, both from capacity problems in terminals and at curbside
and on runways.
</P>
<P>
   A Massachusetts native and a protege of several high-profile Bay
State politicians who are opposed to the runway, Garvey has not
disclosed her position on the proposed Logan runway, but sources
say she has been spending much of her free time on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Even proponents of the proposed runway have said it would not
make Boston's airport free of delays, only reduce them.
</P>
<P>
   The number of delays at airports nationally increased
dramatically this year and Carol Hallett, president and chief
executive of the Air Transport Association, placed blame squarely
on the FAA. Hallett, whose trade association represents the major
passenger and cargo airlines, said in her testimony that the delays
``were the worst in history'' and caused $825 million in lost
productivity to passengers and more than $1 billion in losses to
the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Hallett said the FAA fails to use real-time tracking to reduce
delays caused by bad weather, which forces airplanes to be
temporarily held at airports or to be rerouted. Using last July 31
as an example, Hallett said real-time tracking did not occur as
thunderstorms were forecast in a line between Buffalo and Kansas
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consequently, numerous opportunities for relief from the
punishing ground stops that FAA had imposed, which assumed total
coverage by storms, were not taken advantage of, even though there
were large holes in the line of thunderstorms,'' she said. Some 700
flights were delayed that day, many needlessly, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Schwitz, executive vice president of the National Air
Traffic Controllers Association, however, testified that much of
the blame belongs with airlines because their schedules _ which
they set _ are ``intentionally overloading the system.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Schedules are blindly made to reduce operating costs and
maximize revenue without regard for other airlines, terminal
airspace or airport capacity,'' he said. ``Airline over-scheduling
during peak hours guarantees delays at busy airports even in good
weather. It is like trying to cram 10 pounds of sand into a five
pound bag.''
</P>
<P>
   Garvey and Schwitz both said the FAA is moving to improve air
traffic management by centralizing issuance and coordination of any
extensive ground-stop orders at its command center in Virginia. The
FAA has also pledged to reduce the maximum separation between
planes flying in the same direction from 90 to 30 miles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 2100EDT &QL; 
