<HEADER>
A7300 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-PAKISTAN-MILITARY-770     10-14 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-MILITARY-770(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILITARY LEADER DECLARES HIMSELF PAKISTAN'S CHIEF EXECUTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER with RAJA ZULFIKAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ In the middle of the night, just two days
after the armed forces toppled the country's elected government,
the army chief declared martial law, suspended the constitution and
Parliament and named himself the country's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   The officer, Gen. Pervaiz Musharraf, who had clashed with Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif over control of the powerful armed forces,
also dissolved the provincial legislatures and decreed that the
prime minister, Cabinet ministers and provincial governors would
cease to hold office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole of Pakistan will come under the control of the armed
forces of Pakistan,'' according to a statement released early
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The general's decision to rule Pakistan himself will come as a
rude shock to many lawyers, scholars and journalists who were
convinced he was about to name a civilian government of technocrats
to run the country, while keeping the constitution largely in
place. The armed forces launched the coup Tuesday, just an hour or
so after Sharif had fired the general.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday Brig. Rashid Qureshi, the chief spokesman for the
armed forces, had assured the state news agency, ``Yes, democracy
is intact.'' And a spokesman for President Muhammad Rafiq Tarar
said Musharraf wanted to restore civilian authority. ``The
rehabilitation of the democratic process as soon as possible is a
goal shared by both men,'' Qureshi said.
</P>
<P>
   But as it turned out, the army's decision to empty the
Parliament building on Thursday and seal it turned out to be a
truer foreshadowing of its intent. Pakistan has been governed by
generals for 25 of its 52 years as an independent nation, though it
has sustained a shaky, imperfect democracy for the last 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   The military's latest takeover may have serious repercussions
for Pakistan's economy. The International Monetary Fund may cut off
loans unless democracy is restored. The reserves of foreign
exchange that Pakistan needs to import food are already quite low.
</P>
<P>
   Even before this morning's announcement, there were signs of
nervousness. Prices on the jittery Karachi Stock Exchange plunged
more than 7 percent on Thursday. The state bank ordered
moneychangers to close for business until Wednesday to stop a
flight of foreign capital out of the country. The army prohibited
nearly 400 leaders of the Muslim League, Sharif's party, from
traveling abroad. And in Karachi on Thursday, the police broke up a
demonstration against the coup, shoving more than a dozen people
into vans.
</P>
<P>
   International calls for a return to democracy continued to
mount. In his news conference on Thursday, President Clinton
addressed the coup's leaders: ```You should not do it. It's not
necessary, it will hurt your economy and endanger your future.'
That is our message to Pakistan, and we hope they will move to a
civilian government as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   But in Pakistan, some in the intelligensia said Sharif's
autocratic, incompetent rule and his failure to deliver economic
progress or law and order justified the takeover. The News, an
English-language daily, said in an editorial, ``The undemocratic
ways of Pakistan's elected civilian government created conditions
which left the army, the most powerful and professional institution
in the country, with no other option but to intervene.''
</P>
<P>
   In the bazaars of Rawalpindi and the government offices of
Islamabad, people seemed fascinated by the unfolding melodrama and
its main players. Hungry for information and distrustful of the
state-run television and radio stations, they snapped up
newspapers; one hawker, Mohammad Khalil, said the stacks of papers
that used to take him most of the day to sell are gone by 8 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The general himself is a favorite subject. Jaggo, a vegetable
seller who only gave one name, said he stayed up until 3 a.m.
Wednesday to watch Musharraf explain why the military had
overthrown the government. ``I couldn't understand a word he said
because he spoke English,'' Jaggo said. ``But he looked good and
he's got a voice full of grandeur.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanif Khan, a sugar mill worker, thought Sharif, who is thought
to be under house arrest in Lahore, had been guilty of the sin of
pride. Sharif had tried to dismiss two army chiefs in one year,
tempting the fates in a country where the military sees itself as
the sole honest institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``One must always be god-fearing,'' said Khan. ``He was like a
king, but today he's a prisoner.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Musharraf had been Sharif's hand-picked choice for army chief a
year ago. But the two men have been at loggerheads over Sharif's
decision to withdraw the Pakistan-backed forces that occupied a
section of Indian-held Kashmir over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   The military felt that Sharif had bowed to pressure from
President Clinton by agreeing to the pull out, and then tried to
blame the military for the failed military adventure. India and
Pakistan, both new nuclear powers, have fought three wars in the
past 52 years and were on the verge of a fourth until the
withdrawal in July.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the military justified its seizure of power as a
spontaneous effort to protect Musharraf. Sharif had made the
surprise announcement that he was firing the general at 5 p.m.
Tuesday, while the general was airborne, returning from an official
visit to Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
   As the general's commercial flight approached the airport in
Karachi, the pilot was instructed not to land, though the jet was
short of fuel and carrying 240 passengers, 20 of them children,
Qureshi said, and army commanders made a decision on the spot to
take over the airport.
</P>
<P>
   The coup proceeded so effectively and swiftly that many think
the armed forces must have developed a contingency plan that was to
go into effect if Sharif tried to get rid of the army chief.
</P>
<P>
   Under Pakistan's Constitution, those who organize the overthrow
of an elected government can be charged with treason and sentenced
to death, though there is precedent for the courts' validating the
imposition of martial law, as in the case of Gen. Mohammad
Zia-ul-Haq's overthrow of Prime Minister Zulfikar Ali Bhutto in
1977.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, nobody has been tried under this article of the
constitution,'' said Shabbar Rizvi, a constitutional lawyer in
Lahore. ``The courts have always given legitimacy to such acts
because of some mitigating factor.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the two-page notice the military released
overnight, the courts will be irrelevant, at least unless and until
the general decides to return the power he has taken. The notice
declares that the courts will continue to function but will have no
power to make any decision against Musharraf in his capacity as the
new chief executive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
