<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 21:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7305 &Cx1f; tth-z
u w BC-FAST-JUBILEE-SPI &LR;      10-14 1496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAST-JUBILEE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MOST PERSONAL CRUSADE TO AID THE WORLD'S HUNGRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 (Eds.-- 39 days in graph 4 is as of 10-15-99)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ His cheeks are sunken, his ankles swollen.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, he started using a cane. By next week he expects to
need a walker, and a week later a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   David Duncombe is starving. Deliberately.
</P>
<P>
   The retired minister from White Salmon, Wash., has been fasting
for 39 days now in an effort to call attention to the starving
people of the world.
</P>
<P>
   In a city swarming with lobbyists and protesters of all sorts,
Duncombe is trying a personal approach. He is trying to persuade
members of Congress, one by one, to cancel the debt owed the United
States by about 40 impoverished countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want them (lawmakers) to look at the face of starvation, to
hear my voice, to touch my hand,'' he says. ``I'm becoming one of
the starving millions of people in the world, one of the 10,000 a
day who could be saved by passage of this bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Sept. 7, Duncombe has consumed no food. A gallon of water
a day, potassium pills, and faith are keeping him alive. Each day,
by his own account, he stops by several dozen congressional
offices, trying to talk with staffers or, on rare occasions,
members of Congress, to make his pitch.
</P>
<P>
   His fast is a most personal expression of a worldwide religious
movement to make the year 2000 a year of Jubilee, a concept
described in the Bible according to which, every 50 years, all
debts should be forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   The debts are large. During the 1970s and '80s, in part as a
byproduct of an energy crisis and the Cold War, numerous poor
countries accumulated an estimated $200 billion in debt to a
variety of wealthy countries and international organizations. About
$7 billion is owed to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Now, according to debt relief advocates, money that poor
countries could spend on food or medicine is instead going to debt
service.
</P>
<P>
   So a worldwide coalition of religious and political leaders is
pushing for debt forgiveness as a way to reduce world hunger and
poverty. There are a variety of proposals that differ in terms of
who gives the relief, who gets it, and under what condition, but
they share a common goal _ forgiving loans.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of Jubilee debt forgiveness has been endorsed by a
number of world religions and religious leaders, including Pope
John Paul II and the Revs. Billy Graham, Jesse Jackson and Pat
Robertson, as well as an eclectic collection of organizations and
individuals, including the rock stars Bono and Sting. Political
supporters of some form of debt relief include President Clinton
and the major industrialized nations.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, the 129 co-sponsors of the main debt relief bill
include Washington state Republican Jack Metcalf and Democrats
Brian Baird, Norm Dicks, Jim McDermott and Adam Smith; in the
Senate the 11 co-sponsors include Washington state Democrat Patty
Murray.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals face an uncertain future in a Congress generally
unenthusiastic about foreign aid, apprehensive about whether
impoverished countries would really use forgiven loan money to feed
the poor, and, at the moment, focused on the task of finishing up
work on budget bills and heading home for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Duncombe says he doesn't want to die, but he recognizes an irony
of his particular form of protest _ the more damage he does to
himself, the more effective he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more I represent the actual starvation of millions of
people through my body, letting my body talk for me, the more
chance the spirit of the Lord has to act in these people to inform
their conscience and to give them another perspective,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His body temperature has dropped far enough that he must seek
out the sun for warmth, which he does at least twice a day, sitting
on the steps of the Capitol, hoping lawmakers will stop him to ask
about his cause.
</P>
<P>
   The wooden cross that hangs around his neck bounces freely in
the space created by his suddenly roomy sportcoat.
</P>
<P>
   His briefcase doubles as a seat cushion. Stuffed with a pillow,
it helps him endure the fact that his pelvic bones are now the most
pronounced feature of his backside.
</P>
<P>
   He has met mostly with congressional aides, and a handful of
their bosses. For more than a month he has been showing up every
Wednesday morning at a coffee held for constituents by Sen. Murray.
At first she didn't know what to make of this unusual participant
in a group dominated by tourists looking for a picture with a
senator and a ticket to see Congress in action.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first thought was to dismiss him as somebody with a crazy
cause I didn't know too much about, but he kept coming, and I
started listening to him, and there was something in him that
struck me,'' Murray said. ``It struck me that someone would give up
so much of themselves to make a U.S. senator aware that other
people were suffering, and I was very struck when he said he came
back here to meet senators and representatives and I was the only
one he'd been able to meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Since his initial visit, Murray has been trying to help Duncombe
meet with other lawmakers, and has signed on as a co-sponsor to the
Senate debt relief bill.
</P>
<P>
   Among the lawmakers Duncombe has seen is Rep. Tony Hall, D-Ohio,
who has gone on hunger strikes himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is making a tremendous commitment,'' Hall said. ``Apart
from the fact that it brings attention to the issue, it brings a
spiritual element to it, because you're doing it under God. It's
much more powerful than most people realize.''
</P>
<P>
   Interest groups pushing for debt relief welcome the help,
although they don't know what will happen this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a time when the U.S. Congress is debating what to do with a
multibillion dollar budget surplus, here's someone who is putting
his life on the line, saying that we can spare some pocket change
to help countries heavily burdened by debt,'' said David Bryden of
Jubilee 2000/USA, which is offering Duncombe a variety of
logistical support. ``When he shakes the hands of a legislator, the
legislator picks up on the fact that this man is starving. This is
a town where we all get wrapped up in policy debates, and here's a
guy who's making a simple moral appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncombe is clearly hampered by his informality. He hasn't met
with Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., a fellow Dartmouth alum, in part
because he keeps showing up without an appointment. Other lawmakers
have met him only briefly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that David's interest is in seeing that he makes a
statement to members of Congress and their staffs,'' said Barbara
Howell, director of government relations for Bread for the World, a
Christian lobbying group. ``As to its effectiveness, I don't know,
but he is absolutely a sincere person not wanting to make a
spectacle but to make as vivid as possible the suffering of
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Duncombe is a native New Yorker and an Army veteran who has
spent much of his life in academia. He did his undergraduate work
at Dartmouth, was ordained by the United Church of Christ while
teaching prep school, got four graduate degrees from Yale and then
worked as a chaplain at Yale and at a health ministry associated
with the University of California at San Francisco before retiring
with his wife to White Salmon in 1993. There, he does plumbing work
for non-profit organizations, trying to help them save money.
</P>
<P>
   Duncombe has a long history of protest, and claims to have been
arrested more than 100 times. He joined Martin Luther King Jr.'s
voter registration drive in Selma, Ala. in 1965. He led a group of
picketers demanding a building permit for a women's shelter in the
tiny town of Bingen, Wash., in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Most famously, in 1987 he was one of three men who tried to
block a train they believed was carrying arms shipments destined
for Central America from the Concord Naval Weapons Station in
California. When it became apparent that the train was not going to
stop, Duncombe and another man leapt to safety; Brian Willson was
hit and lost both his legs.
</P>
<P>
   The Concord protest was the first time Duncombe had gone on an
extended fast _ he stopped eating for 40 days after Wilson got hit.
In 1991, after he was jailed in another protest, he again stopped
eating for 40 days.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that he has fasted before makes this one easier to
handle. After seven days, he said, he stopped feeling much hunger.
He uses meditation to control any pain. He says he'll stop if he
gets some indication that Congress plans to pass debt relief, or if
he becomes so incapacitated that he's no longer effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not anxious to be a martyr,'' he said. ``I love my wife
and my kids, and I'm really happy. But I'm risking my health, and
even my life, in hopes that I can reduce the loss of life for
millions of people round the world. This is the way I can make my
life count.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
