<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUNAWAY-PIZZA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE RUNAWAY ... TO GO: PIZZA DELIVERY GAVE AWAY TEEN'S HIDEOUT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trim) 
 
By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Pizza was Jose Gamez's downfall.
</P>
<P>
   For three months, the 14-year-old runaway had lived the high
life, ensconced in a vacant-but-furnished house just doors away
from his parents' own northwest Harris County home.
</P>
<P>
   While hundreds desperately searched the brushy banks of a bayou
near the family's home, the youth dined on venison steaks, drank
rum, trashed several rooms and _ some contend _ used binoculars to
monitor the excitement from a bedroom window.
</P>
<P>
   The deal began to unravel last Sunday when Gamez ordered out for
pizza. When the delivery van arrived at the supposedly empty house,
and a youth answered the door, suspicious neighbors called the law.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff's officers failed to catch the seventh-grader on their
initial visit. But they were called again Monday morning after
homeowner Wayne Heinke _ who lives in nearby Baytown but had come
to investigate the previous night's activity _ heard footsteps in
the attic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard him running across the attic,'' Heinke said Thursday
as he supervised efforts to salvage his wrecked property. ``The
(deputies) were yelling at him a lot to stand still. They found him
hiding under the insulation. When they handed him down, he was
handcuffed. He curled up into a fetal position and cried.''
</P>
<P>
   After being examined at a nearby hospital, the youth was turned
over to Harris County juvenile authorities. By Thursday, he had
been returned to his parents, Manuela Troncoso and Jose Luis Gamez,
and again was attending school.
</P>
<P>
   The young runaway's half-brother, Jose Mondragon, 23, said the
youth vanished July 9 as he was helping his mother clean the
garage.
</P>
<P>
   ``She left him in the garage, and when she returned an hour
later, he had just disappeared,'' Mondragon said. ``He was only
wearing shorts. Dressed like that, we knew he either was nearby or
had been abducted.''
</P>
<P>
   Within days, hundreds of searchers scoured the neighborhood. The
search included helicopters, police dogs and officers on horseback.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of fliers bearing the black-haired, dark-eyed youth's
photo and announcing a $4,000 reward for his location were
distributed.
</P>
<P>
   All the efforts came to naught.
</P>
<P>
   ``They even had a door-to-door search,'' said sheriff's
Detective Robert Tonry,an officer assigned to the case. ``They went
out knocking on doors, but of course, if there's no answer, they
wouldn't force their way inside.''
</P>
<P>
   The youth's parents were decimated by his disappearance, the
second time in recent years he had mysteriously left home.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother prayed every night,'' Mondragon said. ``We had a
priest here to pray and talk with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time we caught him, the police told him not to run
away again or they'd have to take him to jail,'' Mondragon said.
``This time, Jose told me he had gotten angry and just left. By the
time he realized that he had wandered away, he turned back to our
house and saw all the police cars. He decided to just keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   Though a lively member of the family circle, young Gamez was shy
around strangers, his brother said. Mondragon described the
5-foot-tall, 90-pound teen as a ``slow learner.'' Authorities
described him as possessing the mental faculties of a 9- or
10-year-old child.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was smart enough to break a window to get in,'' Heinke
complained. ``He was smart enough to cover the windows with
blankets. He was smart enough to order pizza. ... ''
</P>
<P>
   Heinke said the youth apparently paid for the pizza with money
from a large jug of change the owner kept in the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``He rolled the change up with homemade paper rollers,'' Heinke
said. ``I found piles of pennies around the house.''
</P>
<P>
   During his three-month stay, Gamez apparently raided the
refrigerator and pantry. He even used the stove to cook a freezer
full of venison.
</P>
<P>
   ``He ate everything in the house,'' Heinke said. ``He used all
the paper plates, then started on the dishes. ... He even wore my
clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Although the house had electricity during the youth's stay, it had
no running water.
</P>
<P>
   Heinke found his house a virtual disaster area, with the kitchen
floors and counters buried in dirty dishes and partially eaten
food. Carpeting in every room was crusted with filth, including
feces, and the contents of drawers and closets were dumped on the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   In one room, the youth apparently built a fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they pulled him from the attic,'' Heinke said, ``he was
covered head to toe in soot. The fire had to have been fairly
recent.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heinke, whose primary residence is in nearby Baytown, often is
out of town on business and had not entered the house all summer.
``I'd go by occasionally to see that the yard was being kept up,
but that's about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondragon said authorities have not yet told the family what
charges Gamez might face. Now that the youth has been returned to
his family, Mondragon said his wife, Nancy, will quit her job to
help keep an eye on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first reaction,'' Heinke said, ``was to wring his neck. But
when they dropped him out of that attic, I just couldn't help but
feel sorry for him. He was crying. He was scared.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
