<SLUG> BC-BIZ-PRELUDES-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MATERIAL GIRL'S SECRET WISH  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 17) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Wis.)   (af)  
 By ABBY ELLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After years of hard work and deep soul-searching, I
have finally embraced my inner princess. Oh, I guess I always knew
she was there, but I had never fully acknowledged her, thinking it
was wrong to crave the material.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, however, I have found myself lingering in department
stores and poring over furniture catalogs. I have begun to realize
that I like to consume. A lot.
</P>
<P>
   Under different circumstances, this wouldn't be a problem. The
trouble is that I, a freelance writer, have less money than the
court jester, so I've had to control my urges. For the most part,
I've been successful _ no $500 Anna Sui frocks, thank you _ but it
has taken every ounce of restraint not to throw caution to the wind
and pretend that my last name is Paltrow or Bezos.
</P>
<P>
   The hard truth is this: The princess is envious of people in her
age range who, by some stroke of luck, talent or, yes, hard work,
have acquired many more dollars than she has or probably ever will.
And of people who don't tug on both ends to make them meet. And of
people who can stumble into Bergdorf's, see something they like and
plunk down their credit cards without a second thought.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Hart, 30, who lives on the Upper East Side of Manhattan,
worked for five years at Intel and took advantage of its
stock-purchase plan. The stock split and split again. ``Now I have
on the order of a quarter of a million dollars,'' he said, ``and
I'm sort of loafing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hart is typical of many young people who have prospered mightily
in the last decade. Some work on Wall Street, some in Silicon
Valley, some in show business, Some have married into a wealthy
family; others were born to it.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not complaining, just observing. I know I'm much better off
than many other people. I have great friends and family. I love my
work and my apartment. I have my health. All of these are
infinitely more important than a Central Park West address.
</P>
<P>
   I chose to live in Manhattan; I chose my occupation. In short, I
made my bed, so who am I to protest the peas?
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's nice to know I'm not the only person of my
generation who envies people in higher tax brackets. ``I have a lot
of friends who have a lot of money,'' said Nichole DiBenedetto, 26,
an account executive at Laura Davidson Public Relations in
Manhattan. ``It's frustrating to see people who don't have to go
out to earn a living, who don't have any responsibilities and can
do what they please.''
</P>
<P>
   For help, I called Jessie H. O'Neill, founder and director of
the Affluenza Project, a counseling and education group in
Milwaukee, and author of ``The Golden Ghetto: The Psychology of
Affluence'' (Hazelden, 1996). She helps people achieve healthy
relationships with their money, or lack thereof.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. O'Neill knows about wealth: her grandfather was Charles E.
Wilson, former president of General Motors. She freely concedes
that she doesn't have to work, but says she has a message to
spread.
</P>
<P>
   Our entire culture, she posits, suffers from ``affluenza'' _
with symptoms including workaholism or addiction to the
accumulation of money, and an inability to delay gratification.
</P>
<P>
   She even has a checklist to measure the affliction. Do you work
late every night to achieve a standard of living that someone has
set for you? Is this level of material success what you really want
and need? Have you lost your family and friends trying to get
ahead? More important, have you lost yourself? If you answered yes
to any question, she said, you should examine your relationship to
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be an individual kind of turning within,
finding out what's enough to feel safe and secure,'' she said from
her horse farm in Milwaukee. ``Many people confuse security with a
lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   Valid points, but how do you reconcile yourself to the fact that
no matter how hard you work you may never earn big bucks?
</P>
<P>
   ``Money can't buy happiness,'' Ms. O'Neill continued. ``It can
buy freedom from hunger or bills, yes, but freedom can be
overwhelming. Getting up and going to work builds strength,
confidence and character.''
</P>
<P>
   I agree 100 percent. Material possessions are ephemeral. Instant
gratification ends instantly. But the princess, alas, still wants
to shop. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Abby Ellin is a Manhattan writer. Her column on starting out in
the world of money appears the third Sunday of each month. E-mail:
preludes(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
