<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7314 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-STATE-FARM-2TAKES     10-14 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-STATE-FARM-2TAKES-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A VERDICT ON AUTO PARTS, THE CONSUMER MAY LOSE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 17) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Mich.)  (af) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Now that a court in Marion, Ill., has imposed a
record $1.2 billion judgment against State Farm for ordering some
collision damage to be repaired with generic car parts, three
groups that consumers rank with the proverbial used-car salesman _
insurers, auto body shops and trial lawyers _ are arguing over what
it means.
</P>
<P>
   Its ultimate effect may be rising insurance rates, not a triumph
for consumers. State Farm, the nation's largest auto insurer, and
some other insurers say that if they have to stop buying generic
sheet-metal parts _ generally knock-offs from Taiwan _ and rely
only on the auto makers, policyholders could pay additional
billions of dollars (although State Farm says it can cover the
direct costs of the verdict without raising rates).
</P>
<P>
   It is not only that Ford charges $400 for the hood on a 1995
Taurus while the generic part costs $202, or that Pontiac wants
$216 for the fender on a 1995 Grand Am that a Taiwanese
manufacturer will sell for $59. If the generic parts disappear,
insurers say, the car makers will have a monopoly, abandoning all
restraint.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance industry's poster car is the 1997 Taurus GL, which
sold for $19,000 new, but would cost $72,000 if assembled from
spare Ford parts today, a trade group estimated. And that is with
the restraining influence of competition from generic parts.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers who brought the suit against State Farm dismiss the
insurers' arguments and say the decision will give policyholders
what they were promised in their policies: replacement parts of
``like kind and quality.'' Nobody can make a bumper or a headlight
assembly for a Toyota that is as good as Toyota's, and sell it for
less than Toyota does, the lawyers contend, pointing to economies
of scale and competitors' need to reverse-engineer. Imitation parts
cannot ``transcend their destiny,'' one lawyer said, and become
genuine.
</P>
<P>
   The auto body shops say that not having to deal with generic
parts means that their work will go faster and easier, leaving
fewer grounds for consumer complaints.
</P>
<P>
   But the shops, the insurers say, have a history of billing for
genuine parts, installing the generic ones and pocketing the
difference _ sometimes to satisfy customers who want the shop to
absorb the deductible.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over repair parts applies only to sheet metal, since
other parts are not generally seen as threats to automotive purity.
``There is a whole world of after- market parts that people are
very accustomed to using,'' said Michael J. Donoghue, vice
president of claims at Allstate, the second-largest auto insurer.
</P>
<P>
   He cited Midas mufflers, Monroe shock absorbers and NAPA parts.
``People don't seem to question those things,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many consumers, however, have learned that they can end up with
poor repairs no matter the source of the parts. Good body work,
like good house painting, can require an assertive consumer,
willing to reject shoddy jobs. In auto body repairs, the paint, the
most visible part of the project, is applied by the body shop,
regardless of where the parts are made.
</P>
<P>
   Disputes over collision damage probably go back to the creation
of the second car, providing a target for the first one to collide
with. After an accident, many people feel dissatisfied with their
insurance companies. In their defense, the insurers point out that
drivers deal with them mostly during times of trauma, hardly the
best circumstances for getting to like someone with power over you.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate stakes in the current dispute are highest for the
State Farm customers who filed 4.7 million accident claims in the
last 12 years, and whose cars were repaired with generic parts.
Those customers are in line for payments averaging $250, unless an
appeals court intervenes.
</P>
<P>
   State Farm says that if its appeal fails and it must pay the
$1.2 billion, the verdict will cost customers nothing. The lawyers
who brought the class-action suit earnestly agree and say the
decision is not anti-consumer.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear how the verdict will make any of the parties
happier. The sum is huge by historical standards but perhaps not
for State Farm, which has $16 billion salted away for catastrophes.
Spread among the 37 million policies issued by the company, the
cost of the judgment comes to about $32 a car.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In an economic sense, it is a transfer between overlapping
groups of policyholders: those who have had a collision claim or
two among the 4.7 million, and those who have not.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees. ``Your check will be, maybe, for $1, and
you will end up paying higher premiums,'' predicted Robert J.
Hurns, an auto insurance specialist with the National Association
of Independent Insurers, which represents 620 companies.
</P>
<P>
   But Elizabeth J. Cabraser, a lawyer for the plaintiffs, pointed
out that a State Farm actuary had testified that a judgment would
not affect rates. As a nonrecurring expense, the company said, the
bill cannot be built into premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the verdict's impact on future rates, the cost of auto
insurance has been declining recently. State Farm says it has
returned more than $1.5 billion, including dividends, to
policyholders in the last two years, in part because claims have
been lower than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Use of after-market parts was another reason, the company says,
saving policyholders $234 million in 1997 alone. (But in an
internal document entered as evidence in the case, executives
worried that the high cost of generic-parts was eating that up.
</P>
<P>
   Across the industry, auto insurance prices are declining by a
projected 4.5 percent this year, according to the Insurance
Information Institute, primarily because of a declining accident
rate and safer cars. In addition, new car prices, drunken driving
and car theft are all down. And the insurers, which invest their
customers' premiums, are making money in the bull market.
</P>
<P>
   But to borrow a phrase about gasoline mileage, when it comes to
your own rates, your actual results may vary. Because the car
population is rising far faster than the number of households, and
because many of those households have been buying expensive sport
utility vehicles, many families are paying more for insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance premiums include costs for theft, liability and
injury; collision damage and related costs are about 38 percent of
the total. But that cost is rising relatively rapidly, more than 3
percent last year, about half again as fast as the Consumer Price
Index, according to the Insurance Information Institute.
</P>
<P>
   State Farm, for now, has given up generic parts. Some companies,
like Chubb, are crowing that they never used them. Chubb also
boasts that it puts no ceiling on the rate it will pay for body
shop labor. It is not insurance for people who want to minimize
transportation costs; most of its customers have cars that are
three years old or less.
</P>
<P>
   But Allstate uses after-market body parts in about 20 percent of
its repairs. As an incentive, it guarantees those parts, but not
auto company parts, for as long as the customer owns the car. Only
a few car owners refuse the after-market parts, the company says.
</P>
<P>
   Allstate says it sets standards. ``As a general rule, we won't
use after-market parts on a new car,'' Donoghue said, adding that
exactly when they should be used was up to the adjuster.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
