<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TESTBAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ASSAILS GOP ON TEST-BAN STANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Stung by the Senate's defeat of a treaty banning
nuclear underground testing, a visibly angry President Clinton
Thursday accused Republicans of ``reckless partisanship'' and of
embracing a ``new isolationism'' that threatens America's national
and economic security.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton linked the Republican majority's refusal to delay a vote
on the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty to the budget battle brewing
on Capitol Hill, where lawmakers have been unable to agree on a
federal budget with only a week to go before a stopgap spending
measure, which is financing much of the government, expires.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are legitimate differences of opinion, but we can put an
end to reckless partisanship, to gimmicks and gamesmanship,''
Clinton said at a White House news conference. ``We can put people
first and make a principled, honorable compromise. We can work for
a season of progress, not a winter of politics. And I am committed
to do just that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's hour-long meeting with reporters was dominated by
questions about the treaty vote, although he was also asked about
the contest for the Democratic presidential nomination and his
reaction to a federal judge's decision that he lied under oath in
Paula Jones's sexual harassment lawsuit, which triggered the Monica
Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I am out of office, I will have a lot to say about
this,'' Clinton said about the judge's decision. He also said he
thought Vice President Al Gore would win the Democratic nomination
over former New Jersey senator Bill Bradley, whom he refused to
criticize.
</P>
<P>
   But the president was animated and verbose, often gesturing with
his hands, when discussing the test ban vote. He said he did not
think Senate Republicans were reacting out of dislike for him by
voting down the treaty. ``The idea that, you know, we would put the
future of our children in peril and the leadership of America for a
safer world in peril for some personal pique I think is
unthinkable,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Senate majority leader Trent Lott, shortly after Clinton spoke,
said the Senate's action ``was not a vote involving personalities.
It was not about politics; it was about the substance of the
treaty, and that's all it was.'' He added, ``This was a flawed
treaty.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Clinton seized the chance to make political hay, saying
he now believes it will become a campaign issue next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Wednesday voted 51-48, far short of the required
67 votes needed to ratify the treaty. Only four Republicans voted
for it. Republican presidential front-runner George W. Bush opposes
the treaty, as do other GOP presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Although the treaty was signed by 154 nations, including the
United States, it has been ratified by only 26 of the 44
nuclear-capable states that must approve it to put it into force.
</P>
<P>
   Republican National Committee chairman Jim Nicholson called it
an insult for Clinton to accuse Republican senators of a ``new
isolationism.'' ``The president can't excuse his own failure to
negotiate an enforceable, verifiable treaty _ or to make the case
for ratification,'' Nicholson said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference, Clinton said Republicans had offered no
alternatives to the ban, brushed aside public sentiment in support
of it and ``betrayed the vision'' of President Dwight D.
Eisenhower, who first proposed it in 1958 and other presidents who
have endorsed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even more troubling are the signs of a new isolationism among
some of the opponents of the treaty,'' Clinton said. ``You see it
in the refusal to pay our UN dues. You see it in the woefully
inadequate budget for foreign affairs that includes meeting our
obligations to the Middle East peace process, and to the continuing
efforts to destroy and safeguard Russian nuclear materials. You see
it in the refusal to adopt our proposals to do our part to stem the
tide of global warming, even though these proposals plainly would
create American jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Ratcheting up the rhetoric, Clinton said, ``By this vote, the
Senate majority has turned its back on 50 years of American
leadership against the spread of weapons of mass destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he will proceed according to the terms of the
treaty despite the Senate action. He noted that the treaty could be
brought up again, and vowed to ``not let yesterday's partisanship
stand as the final word.''
</P>
<P>
   That partisanship, Clinton said, also threatens America's
economic security. He said when he signed the stopgap spending
measure two weeks ago to keep the government running, ``I said they
should stop playing politics, stop playing games, start making the
necessary touch choices. Instead, we have the Republicans lurching
from one workable idea to the next.''
</P>
</TEXT>
