<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7328 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-WORLD-MEXICO-$ADV     10-14 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-WORLD-MEXICO-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DOWNSIZED LUNCH UNSETTLES A MEXICAN RITE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 17) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)   (Eds: The name Ffrench in story is correct)  
(af) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Around 4 p.m. these days, an odd calm falls over
the tables at Prendes restaurant, which for more than a century has
been a prime luncheon spot for mighty decision makers in Mexico's
government.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as March, this restaurant would have been clamorous
at that hour, filled with politicians, bureaucrats and business
people celebrating one of the great rituals of life in the Mexican
capital: the three-hour lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Tequila shot glasses would have been intermingled with plates of
sea bass, Veracruz style, and chili-laced stews. Near the end of
their feast, some diners would have been savoring cigars.
</P>
<P>
   But then, in April, the federal government put new regulations
into effect that brought a cultural revolution to Mexico City. Most
public employees, from lowly clerks to lofty cabinet ministers, are
now supposed to start work at 9 a.m. and leave at 6 p.m. They have
one hour _ just one _ for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   With the state playing so large a role in the economy here,
private businesses in the capital have been more or less obliged to
follow suit, also curtailing long lunches and late evenings in the
office.
</P>
<P>
   The midafternoon quiet at Prendes and other downtown luncheon
shrines is a sign that the new schedule really is taking effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Government people don't come here to do business anymore,''
said Carlos Velazquez, the head waiter at Prendes, surveying the
vacant floor before him. ``They have a little soup, their main
dish, and adios! They're back to work. Not so much as a beer with
lunch!''
</P>
<P>
   The new schedule has changed Mexico City's workday. Previously,
lunch was the centerpiece, the forum where political relations were
nurtured and major conclusions reached. The busiest part of the day
came after 6 p.m., when top officials returned from the big meal.
Final details of the day's deals were generally nailed down just
before the close of business, around 10.
</P>
<P>
   The revised schedule was imposed by President Ernesto Zedillo as
part of the austerity measures that have had an impact across his
government. The ministries enforce the schedule by turning off
lights and air-conditioning at 6 p.m. sharp. And to make the rules
stick, senior administrative officials in some ministries have
taken personal charge: Under secretaries patrol hallways after
lights-out to make sure offices are empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to leave at 8 p.m. with a guilty feeling,'' said Marco
Provencio, the spokesman for the Finance Ministry. ``Now I can feel
proud of myself when I leave that late, and I know that no one will
be talking about me behind my back.''
</P>
<P>
   Provencio even ventured a theory _ that improved efficiency
under the new order is contributing to the overall health of the
economy. ``Is it just a coincidence?'' he wondered aloud. ``Since
April, all the indicators have been improving: the exchange rate,
inflation ....''
</P>
<P>
   One side effect is that throughout the government, people are
finding that much work now gets done before noon _ rarely the case
before the new schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our people are much more productive in the morning,'' said
Juan de Villafranca, the top official for administration at the
Foreign Ministry. ``They are motivated because they want to get
everything done before 6 p.m. so they can go home.''
</P>
<P>
   Decisions tend to be made in the afternoon instead of the
evening, now that people are no longer slowed by the grogginess
that followed the banquet that used to be lunch. Even the nature of
decision-making has changed: More agreements are now struck by
telephone or e-mail, and officials are getting used to dispensing
with the abrazo, or bear hug, that ritually sealed a political
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``A huge city like this one has forced us to settle for less
face-to-face communication,'' said Antonio Ocaranza, head of the
Mexico City offices of Public Strategies Inc., a consulting firm
based in Austin, Texas. Before switching to the private sector a
year ago, Ocaranza worked marathon hours as a press officer for
Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The changes in communications have allowed people to be
selective and say, this is not something I absolutely have to
discuss personally,'' Ocaranza said.
</P>
<P>
   In changing its workday, Mexico City is catching up with
Monterrey, the northern city that rivals the capital as the
country's financial and industrial center. For years, Monterrey
business people have taken a more efficiency-minded approach to the
workday, lunch included.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mexican political folklore, part of the logic of
the long lunch was to give politicians _ almost invariably men _
time to visit their mistresses in the middle of the day. But a
series of jarring economic crises, and the frugal federal budgets
enacted to cope with them, have reduced the purchasing power of
public employees' pay and placed an extramarital affair beyond the
means of most officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I wanted to take a lover, I would have to have a much
higher salary than I do now,'' sighed one mid-level married
official, who, not surprisingly, spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs that Mexicans in government have begun to enjoy
the experience of a new-found after-hours private life. Attendance
at 8 p.m. movies is climbing, and government employees are signing
up for language and computer courses.
</P>
<P>
   But business people who deal regularly with the government say
that more fundamental change is coming slowly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still far away from the Swiss bureaucracy,'' said
Damian Fraser, an analyst here for Warburg Dillon Read. ``They've
changed the reason you can't get hold of them. Now they say they
are in a meeting. They can't say they are out at lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   Many officials acknowledge that the hardest part of the new
routine is the short lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Leonardo Ffrench, a top official in the Foreign Ministry, who
said he felt that the old way was more in tune with a Mexican's
natural rhythms. ``I like to have my main meal as God willed it,''
Ffrench said. ``But we understand that we have to become a lot more
rational and pragmatic. It's a sign of the times we are living
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Another sign is the crowded 2 p.m. scene in the Foreign
Ministry's cafeteria. Previously, its buffet was shunned in favor
of more relaxing corner bars nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Many doubts remain about the new schedule's survival after
Zedillo leaves office in December 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wait,'' said Velazquez, the waiter at Prendes. ``Eighteen
months from now it will all be back to the way it was before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
