<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GM REPORTS TURNAROUND ON EARNINGS FOR 3RD QUARTER
</P>
<P>
   Demand for pickup trucks, sport utility vehicles and minivans
helped General Motors earn $877 million in the third quarter, a
significant turnaround from a strike-related $309 million loss in
the quarter a year earlier. Excluding the effect of the strike,
GM's net income rose 34 percent, to $1.33 a share, beating
forecasts of $1.24 a share. Analysts said GM had earned high
profits because buyers were snapping up record numbers of new
models from all auto makers.
</P>
<P>
   TYCO STOCK FALLS DESPITE DEFENSE
</P>
<P>
   Investors brushed aside Tyco International's aggressive defense
of its accounting practices, pushing its stock down $10 more, to
$87, amid fears about the company's three-year acquisition spree.
The selloff has dropped shares of Tyco, one of the highfliers of
the bull market, by 18 percent since the start of the week, when an
investment manager wrote a detailed critique of the company.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS END SLIDE BUT GAIN LITTLE
</P>
<P>
   Stocks halted their sharp, two-day decline. The Dow Jones
industrial average gained 54.45 points, to 10,286.61. The Nasdaq
composite index rose 5.57 points, to 2,806.84, and the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index declined 2.13 points, to 1,283.42.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the 30-year bond rose to 6.32 percent from 6.27
percent on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   UNISYS MISSES REVENUE FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Unisys fell $15.6875, or 37 percent, to $26.5625 after
the technology company said revenue in the third quarter increased
by 4 percent, below investors' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ALL-STAR LIST OF ANALYSTS COMES OUT
</P>
<P>
   Institutional Investor published its annual popularity contest
for Wall Street analysts.
</P>
<P>
   EARNINGS INCREASE 37 PERCENT AT BOEING
</P>
<P>
   Continuing its financial rebound, Boeing said its third-quarter
profit grew 37 percent as its formerly ailing passenger jet
business improved its efficiency. The results beat Wall Street
estimates for the third consecutive quarter. Philip M. Condit, the
chief executive of Boeing, said that he was not worried by recent
gains by Airbus Industrie, the European consortium, which has
received orders for 329 jets this year, compared with 138 for
Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   JAPANESE BANKS PLAN MERGER
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that a proposed combination of Sumitomo Bank and
Sakura Bank would be a strong force in Japanese retail banking and
much better equipped to invest in information technology to reduce
costs and provide on-line banking and other services.
</P>
<P>
   SEPTEMBER RETAIL SALES ROSE 0.1 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Retail sales rose one-tenth of a percent in September as
furniture and department stores reported their best months since
early this year, Government figures showed. In a separate report,
the Labor Department said first-time claims for unemployment
benefits unexpectedly fell below 300,000 last week.
</P>
<P>
   SUN MICROSYSTEMS POSTS SOLID GAIN
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems, the maker of workstations and servers,
reported first-quarter earnings that exceeded analysts' estimates
as the company continued to gain market share.
</P>
<P>
   THE ART OF VOLKSWAGEN ADVERTISING
</P>
<P>
   The One Club for Art and Copy in New York, which encourages
creativity in advertising, will devote an exhibit to a single
advertiser: Volkswagen.
</P>
</TEXT>
