<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7338 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      10-14 0737
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: FINANCE 101 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm beginning to take an interest in the congressional budget
debate. After all, I live in a state that has not passed an
appropriations bill on time since the Erie Canal was built. I have
considerable expertise in legislatures that cannot repair a
collapsed bridge without throwing in extra money for a football
stadium or Recreational Vehicle Theme Park. So when the federal
government started a new fiscal year sans budget, I felt at home.
As a public service, I've prepared a cheat sheet on what's going
on.
</P>
<P>
   STANDARDS. In 1997 a reform-minded Congress decided to give
itself extra-tough, super-challenging spending restraints _ for
1999. This heroic effort was part of a rash of demanding new
standards being set by brave policy makers around the country, all
of whom hoped to be retired before the bill came due. Most members
of the current Congress find the budget caps ridiculous, given the
size of the federal surplus. But the Republican majority is not
allowed to admit it. Its leaders are very concerned about public
perception, as we have seen recently from their skilled maneuvering
to define themselves as the party of HMO bureaucracies and nuclear
proliferation.
</P>
<P>
   THE SOLUTION. Emergencies! Until now, emergency spending bills
have been reserved for crises like floods, wars or the discovery by
Sen. Ted Stevens of Alaska that his local reindeer farmers needed
$3 million RIGHT AWAY. But since emergency spending does not count
toward those pesky caps, the current Congress is getting more
creative. As a result, the following items are being declared to be
unforeseeable emergencies: the year 2000 census, winter heating
bills and operation of the Pentagon. The House Appropriations
Committee is rumored to be putting all budget items relating to
continents whose names begin with ``A'' in the emergency category,
as well as spending during daylight saving time and Tuesdays.
</P>
<P>
   THE TWILIGHT ZONE. For years now, President Clinton and the
Republican Congress have been fighting to prove who is the more
vigilant protector of the Social Security Trust Fund. This trust
fund is a metaphysical concept, sort of like eternity.
Contemplating it for too long will produce feelings of anxiety that
can only be relieved by a stiff drink or appropriating money for a
Soybean Hall of Fame in your district. Right now, Congress needs to
cut billions from the budget to avoid dipping into this imaginary
vault.
</P>
<P>
   THE SOLUTION. Directed scoring. (Impress your friends by
dropping this term at your next dinner party, and watch them head
for the door!) The Republican leaders have not believed a word
Clinton has said about anything in nearly seven years. Directed
scoring means that they have decided to trust him implicitly
whenever White House cost estimates come in lower than those of
congressional accountants.
</P>
<P>
   THE BIG BANG. Still, the numbers don't add up. One reason is
that Congress and the president were both determined that there
should be a whopping increase in the defense budget. This was
needed for priorities like a military pay raise and construction of
a $1.5 billion aircraft carrier the Navy doesn't want, in the home
district of Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott.
</P>
<P>
   THE SOLUTION. The Clinton administration proposed raising the
tobacco tax, an unfair tactic given Congress' principled commitment
to protecting our national right to inhale large quantities of
nicotine. (Who could forget Sen. Phil Gramm's moving revelation
that he feared the ``excruciating, bone-crushing'' cigarette tax
could send his chain-smoking mother to the poorhouse?) For its
part, the Republican leadership keeps eyeing the Earned Income Tax
Credit refunds for the working poor, which House Majority Leader
Dick Armey refers to as ``my money.'' This is his little joke, an
attempt to define tax breaks for minimum-wage laborers as
government giveaways, as opposed to legitimate tax deductions for
business investments in meals at the Four Seasons.
</P>
<P>
   THE ULTIMATE SOLUTION. When all else fails, the budget-makers
will simply slide bills due at the end of this fiscal year into the
next one. By then Congress will be on the brink of an election in
which the presidency and control over both the House and Senate are
on the line, and in a much better mood for bipartisan cooperation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
