<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTONS-HOUSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTONS SECURE NEW FINANCING ON WESTCHESTER HOUSE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton have
secured new financing on the house they are buying in Chappaqua,
N.Y., the White House said Thursday, enabling them to drop an
earlier loan arrangement that had come under sharp criticism.
</P>
<P>
   The new loan, for $1.36 million, is in the form of a 30-year
adjustable-rate mortgage with an annual interest rate of 7.5
percent for the first three years, said Jim Kennedy, a White House
spokesman. After the first three years, the rate will be set at the
one-year Treasury bill rate plus 2.75 percentage points, he said.
The current Treasury bill rate is just under 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the Clintons obtained new financing so they could
cancel a much-criticized arrangement they had with a prominent
Democratic Party fund-raiser, Kennedy said: ``I'm aware of that
speculation. Once they had the initial contract, a number of
different mortgage companies came forward with different options.
This one made the most sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said the loan is from PNC Mortgage, a subsidiary of the
PNC Bank Corp. of Pittsburgh. The Clintons are to make a down
payment of $340,000, or 20 percent of the purchase price of $1.7
million, and are to close on the deal on Nov. 1, Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the party fund-raiser, Terry McAuliffe, has no role in
the loan from PNC Mortgage. When the Clintons decided to buy the
white-shingled, five-bedroom Chappaqua house in September,
McAuliffe agreed to guarantee a mortgage with $1.35 million of his
money as collateral. That mortgage was to have been with Bankers
Trust Private Banking, a unit of Deutsche Bank, and its initial
interest was calculated at just over 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe is a good friend of the Clintons and is raising
millions of dollars for their legal defense fund and for a
presidential library to be built in Little Rock, Ark. The Clinton's
eagerness to accept his help brought criticism from Republicans and
public-interest groups who said the arrangement smacked of special
treatment and might constitute an illegal gift.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons' move to Westchester County will clear the way for
Mrs. Clinton to run for the Senate from New York state, which she
seems likely to do. Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani, who has been widely
mentioned as her probable Republican opponent, had questioned the
propriety of the arrangement with McAuliffe, signaling that the
issue would be a hot one in a campaign against Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy said that when the Clintons decided they wanted the
house in Chappaqua, their situation was like that of other couples
who fall in love with a house and know they must make a solid offer
quickly or risk losing out. ``They had a very short time to put
together the financing,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   But in other ways, the Clintons' situation is hard to compare
with those of other people their age. While they list slightly more
than $1 million in assets, they have about $5 million in legal
bills, a debt that might make it hard for other couples in their
50s to qualify for a mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, former presidents of the United States have
been able to command lucrative speaking fees and big book advances.
Both Clintons are lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Before McAuliffe offered his help, the Clintons sought financial
aid from former Treasury Secretary Robert E. Rubin and two former
White House chiefs of staff, Erskine B. Bowles and Thomas F.
McLarty III, who declined to help, according to several people
familiar with the couple's house-hunting.
</P>
<P>
   Principal and interest payments on a 30-year mortgage at 7.5
percent are just over $9,500 a month, exclusive of taxes and
insurance. The taxes on the Chappaqua house are estimated at
$26,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The PNC Bank Corp. advertises itself as one of the biggest
financial-services organizations in the country. It says that PNC
Mortgage provided more than $6 billion to more than 43,000
borrowers in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
