<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- Oct. 14, 1999 -- BBA-YANKS-REDSOX-1, 10-14
-- Paul O'Neill of the New York Yankees stretching before Game 2 of
the American League Championship Series against the Boston Red Sex
on Thursday. O'Neill has been playing with a broken rib. (Chang W.
Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 14, 1999 -- CLINTON-3, 10-14 --
President Clinton during his news conference in the East Room of
the White House on Thursday. Looking on at left is National
Security Advisory Sandy Berger. Clinton charged that the
Republicans, who defeated a treaty banning all underground nuclear
testing on Wednesday, were leading the United States into a ``new
isolationism,'' and vowed to abide by the treaty's provisions even
though it was rejected by the Senate. (Shana Raab/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) CHRISTCHURCH, New Zealand -- Oct. 14, 1999 --
ARTIC-RESCUE-2, 10-14 -- An LC-130 with the New York Air National
Guard's 109th Airlift Wing, takes off from Christchurch on
Wednesday en route to McMurdo Station in Antartica. Two LC-130's,
equipped with special landing gear for landing on snow and ice, are
waiting at McMurdo for favorable weather to fly the final 744 miles
to the South Pole and rescue an American doctor with suspected
breast cancer. (U.S. Air Force Photo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) CHRISTCHURCH, New Zealand -- Oct. 14, 1999 --
ARTIC-RESCUE-1, 10-14 -- Maintenance personnel check the modified
landing gear of an LC-130 with the New York Air National
Guard's109th Airlift Wing on Wednesday before the military
transport aircraft took off for McMurdo Station in Antartica. Two
LC-130's, equipped with special landing gear for landing on snow
and ice, are waiting at McMurdo for favorable weather to fly the
final 744 miles to the South Pole and rescue an American doctor
with suspected breast cancer. (U.S. Air Force Photo/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) MONTROSE, Colo. -- Oct. 14, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT.
17 -- TRAVEL-COLORADO-3-COX, 10-14 -- Intrepid fly-fisher Susan
Abramson shows off a brown trout from the Gunnison River.
Colorado's Black Canyon of the Gunnison presents a monumental
challenge for hikers and fly-fishers. At the foot of steep cliffs
is the Gunnison River, whose waters teem with trout. The Grand
Canyon, the big daddy of gorges, is twice as deep as the Black
Canyon. But it is five miles wide, allowing hikers a more gradual
descent. The Black Canyon, in contrast, is far more steep - it's
only a quarter of a mile wide at its narrowest point. (Eddie
Moore/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) MONTROSE, Colo. -- Oct. 14, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT.
17 -- TRAVEL-COLORADO-2-COX, 10-14 -- Colorado's Black Canyon of
the Gunnison presents a monumental challenge for hikers and
fly-fishers. Below is the Gunnison River, whose waters teem with
trout. The Grand Canyon, the big daddy of gorges, is twice as deep
as the Black Canyon. But it is five miles wide, allowing hikers a
more gradual descent. The Black Canyon, in contrast, is far more
steep - it's only a quarter of a mile wide at its narrowest point.
(Eddie Moore/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) MONTROSE, Colo. -- Oct. 14, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT.
17 -- TRAVEL-COLORADO-1-COX, 10-14 -- From a vertigo-inducing
overlook below the South Rim, visitors to the Black Canyon can look
thousands of feet down to the Gunnison River, whose waters teem
with trout. The Grand Canyon, the big daddy of gorges, is twice as
deep as the Black Canyon. But it is five miles wide, allowing
hikers a more gradual descent. The Black Canyon, in contrast, is
far more steep _ it's only a quarter of a mile wide at its
narrowest point. (Eddie Moore/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 14, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 17 --
GAF-ASBESTOS, 10-14 -- Samuel J. Heyman, center, during recent
testimony before the Senate Judiciary Subcommittee on
Administrative Oversight and the Courts; his wife, Ronnie, is
seated to his left. Heyman, the chairman of the GAF Corp., wants
Congress to pass a bill that gets his company off the hook for a
huge chunk of its asbestos liability exposure. (Paul Hosefros/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) UNDATED -- Oct. 14, 1999 -- JEWS-GOLD-3-B&AMP;W, 10-14 --
U.S. soldiers escort a train intercepted in Austria in 1945 which
was carrying valuables stolen from Jews by the Nazis and was bound
to Germany from Hungary. According to a report issued by the
Presidential Advisory Commission on Holocaust Assets in the United
States, some members of the American military handling Jewish
property seized by the Nazis, including valuables aboard this
train, were not always as careful accounting for it as had been
believed. (National Archives/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) UNDATED -- Oct. 14, 1999 -- JEWS-GOLD-2-B&AMP;W, 10-14 -- A
soldier holds gold wedding bands that were inside a train
intercepted by U.S. troops in Austria in 1945. Rebuffing insistent
pleas from the Hungarian Government and surviving Hungarian Jews,
United States officials deemed the valuables ``unidentifiable.'' In
the meantime, however, some of the American troops in Austria
helped themselves to the gold. (National Archives/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- Oct. 14, 1999 -- JEWS-GOLD-1-B&AMP;W, 10-14 --
Gen. Harry J. Collins , commander of the U.S. Army's 42nd Infantry
Division, known as ``Rainbow Division,'' in 1945. Collins allegedly
requisitioned silver and china from a warehouse where a train
intercepted from Hungary, carrying gold and valuables stolen from
Jews by the Nazis, was kept. According to a report issued by the
Presidential Advisory Commission on Holocaust Assets in the United
States, some members of the American military handling Jewish
property seized by the Nazis were not always as careful accounting
for it as had been believed. (National Archives/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- Oct. 14, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 17 --
ABOUT-CARS-ECLIPSE-2, 10-14 -- Mitsubishi made the interior of the
new Eclipse GT sturdy, elegant and efficient. In its redesign, the
company traded away a degree of hard-edged performance - in the
form of the car's optional turbo-charged four-cylinder and
all-wheel-drive - for greater civility and more sophisticated
styling. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) UNDATED -- Oct. 14, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., OCT. 17 --
ABOUT-CARS-ECLIPSE-1, 10-14 -- The Eclipse's styling, which
Mitsubishi calls ``geomechanical,'' features exterior accents and
crystal-like headlights. In its redesign, the company traded away a
degree of hard-edged performance - in the form of the car's
optional turbo-charged four-cylinder and all-wheel-drive - for
greater civility and more sophisticated styling. (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 14, 1999 -- TREATY-BLAME-2, 10-14 --
Sen. Joe Biden, D-Del., watches President Clinton's press
conference on Thursday outside the Senate television studio on
Capitol Hill prior to the speaking to reporters. During his news
conference, Clinton charged that Senate Republicans, who defeated a
treaty banning all underground nuclear testing, were leading the
United States into a ``new isolationism,'' and he vowed to abide by
the treaty's provisions even though it was rejected by the Senate
on Wednesday. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 14, 1999 -- TREATY-BLAME, 10-14 --
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., talks about President
Clinton's comments on Thursday on the Senate's refusal to pass the
nuclear test band treaty on Capitol Hill. Lott, speaking
immediately after Clinton's news conference, defended the Senate's
action and said ``no senator was pressured to vote any way but his
or her conscience'' and accused Clinton of ``revisionist history.''
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 14, 1999 -- CLINTON-2, 10-14 --
President Clinton during his news conference in the East Room of
the White House on Thursday. Clinton charged that the Republicans,
who defeated a treaty banning all underground nuclear testing, were
leading the United States into a ``new isolationism,'' and he vowed
to abide by the treaty's provisions even though it was rejected by
the Senate. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 14, 1999 -- CLINTON, 10-14 --
President Clinton during his news conference in the East Room of
the White House on Thursday. Clinton charged that the Republicans,
who defeated a treaty banning all underground nuclear testing, were
leading the United States into a ``new isolationism,'' and he vowed
to abide by the treaty's provisions even though it was rejected by
the Senate. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) TRENTON, N.J. -- Oct. 14, 1999 -- TRENTON-REBIRTH, 10-14
-- A tour group in the restored rotunda of the New Jersey State
House. There are several cultural and historic places in Trenton to
visit for special reasons this fall, all in what is known as the
Capitol Complex, the buildings clustered around the State House
along the Delaware River. (Laura Pedrick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- Oct. 14, 1999 -- ANTIQUES-COLUMN, 10-14 -- A
William and Mary high chest with japanned finish is to be sold at
auction Friday. Made in Boston between 1712 and 1725, the black
chest, Lot 107, sits on a tablelike base fitted with drawers.
(Sotheby's/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Oct. 14, 1999 -- SOCCER-JUNKIE, 10-14 --
Pickup soccer enthusiasts playing on the artificial turf in
Riverside Park. ``In the great melting pot of New York City, where
immigrants arrive harboring a love of the game, you can always find
people playing,'' writes Chris Ballard. ``They set up garbage cans
and play in the street or throw down their shirts to create
impromptu goals on any grassy surface.'' (Chris Ballard/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) LOS ANGELES-- Oct. 14, 1999 -- LABOR-POLITICS, 10-14 --
Firefighters, members of the AFL-CIO, during the organization's
national convention on Wednesday where Vice President Al Gore was
endorsed. Now that Gore has the endorsement of the labor
organition, AFL-CIO leaders say he has to win over the rank and
file. The leaders plan to hold Gore's feet to the fire over trade
and on the loss of manufacturing jobs. (Monica Almeida/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEVE EREZ, West Bank -- Oct. 14, 1999 -- ISRAEL-WESTBANK,
10-14 -- Amy Abels, sitting on a washing machine, with Erez Maman,
center, and Alain Jachiet after being ordered to evacuate from
their settlement on Thursday. Settlers backed down from threats of
confrontation and agreed not to stand in the way of the evacuation
of 12 West Bank outposts the Israeli government has deemed illegal.
(Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) BOSTON -- Oct. 14, 1999 -- AUTHOR-DOYLE-BOS, 10-14 --
Roddy Doyle, a popular Irish writer who has just written ``A Star
Called Henry.'' The novel is the first installment of an ambitious,
unconventional trilogy that will sum up the tumultuous history of
20th-century Ireland through the life and voice of one character.
(Bill Brett/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) QUINCY, Mass. - Oct. 14, 1999 --
FILM-INDIA-PAKISTAN-2-BOS, 10-14 -- Musadik Malik, 37, a Pakistani,
is part of a group of Pakistanis and Indians who recently wove
together their personal tales of horror after getting an early look
at the new film ``Earth.'' The movie explores how partition
shattered friendships between Hindus, Muslims, and Sikhs in Lahore.
(Dominic Chavez/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- Oct. 14, 1999 -- FILM-INDIA-PAKISTAN-1-BOS,
10-14 -- Anita Raj-Silverman, a 28-year-old American-born woman of
Indian descent, is part of a group of Pakistanis and Indians who
recently wove together their personal tales of horror after getting
an early look at the new film ``Earth.'' The movie explores how
partition shattered friendships between Hindus, Muslims, and Sikhs
in Lahore. (Wendy Maeda/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNDATED -- Oct. 14, 1999 -- OBIT-GRAINGER, 10-13 -- Isaac
B. (Ike) Grainger, former president of the U.S. Golf Association
who was one of the country's leading authorities on the rules of
golf, died on Tuesday at his home in Wilmington. He was 104.
Grainger is seen in an undated photo (Wilmington Star-News/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
