John-David, 4, after a swimming lesson. ``Value investors have to
traffic in unpopular areas of the market,'' she says. (Ed Quinn/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) RYE BROOK, N.Y. -- Oct. 14, 1999 --
SUB-WALLSTREET-SEERS-2, 10-14 -- Robert J. Barbera, chief economist
at Honeig &AMP; Co., is constantly scrambling to get the attention of
money managers. ``You cast a wide net,'' he says. ``But you never
catch it all.'' (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) NEW YORK -- Oct. 14, 1999 -- SUB-WALLSTREET-SEERS-1,
10-14 -- ``Nobody really expects there is anyone who can forecast
details accurately over the long-term,'' says John Lipsky, the
chief economist at Chase Manhattan Bank. Lipsky, who spends a third
of his time seeing clients, has to regularly contend with the
economists at the Wall Street leaders in a bid to get the attention
of money managers. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
