<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7345 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-TREATY-ASSESS-ART-NYT     10-14 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREATY-ASSESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE VOTE: RAW PARTISANSHIP ONCE UNCOMMON TO FOREIGN AFFAIRS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also TREATY-CLINTON) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate's defeat of the test ban treaty
Wednesday left many senators troubled about a level of partisanship
usually reserved for the House, and wondering about the
institution's ability to manage a complicated issue that affects
the world.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that politics ``stops at the water's edge'' has always
been an exaggeration, though with some truth to it. But these days,
as the Senate succumbs to the sound-bite culture, debates there are
increasingly rancorous and party-line votes occur with great
frequency.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of recognizing that a treaty, requiring a two-thirds
vote, cannot pass without extensive bipartisan support, Democrats
last month offered a legislative taunt to Sen. Trent Lott, the
majority leader, threatening to tie up the Senate if he did not
force hearings on the matter. Lott, always prickly about his
responsibility for the Senate agenda, took up their challenge and
beat them at their own partisan game.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Sen. Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., who said a more thorough
examination might have persuaded him to vote yes, said, ``I think
we have to find a way to come back at this in a responsible manner
where we can continue to educate ourselves and the American
public.''
</P>
<P>
   Hagel said his concerns extended beyond the details of the
treaty. ``It's a question of whether we want to continue to lead
the world,'' he said. ``There's a heavy burden associated with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., who voted to ratify, criticized
the brief time spent on the measure in committee. If the treaty was
flawed, he said, ``We could fix things; that's what you have
hearings for.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., who voted no, scoffed at the treaty
supporters for not realizing that ``anyone who has any interest in
this treaty has to get together with Senator Lott.'' Instead, he
said, supporters seemed to have the ``naive assumption that if the
president visited with a few people, then hearts would melt.''
</P>
<P>
   Lugar, who has been a leader in bipartisan arms control efforts
in the past and ranks second to Sen. Jesse Helms on the Foreign
Relations Committee, sounded frustrated that no one from the
administration had worked effectively with Lott _ a step that Lugar
said would have given him room to maneuver. Lugar said that he did
not believe the treaty would succeed in barring all tests or that
the American stockpile could be maintained with testing excluded.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the minority leader, obliquely
agreed. He said on Thursday it had been a ``blunder'' to push ahead
with the treaty in the expectation that many Republicans could be
swayed. ``We assumed that we could negotiate, but they were adamant
and dug in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the bipartisanship Lugar urged is easier to prescribe than
to accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate justly patted itself on the back in the winter for
handling the impeachment trial of President Clinton without the
rancor of the House. But good will has worn thin. As Democrats
succeed in forcing items on their agenda to be considered by the
Senate despite Lott, he gets increasingly prickly about his
authority.
</P>
<P>
   Lott relishes rare opportunities to get even. That is what
happened last month when he offered the Democrats a treaty vote.
They agreed _ even though they knew they lacked the votes to win,
or even come close. The Democrats were worried about seeming
inconsistent if they filibustered a vote on a treaty they had said
the world needed now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
