<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORCESTER-WORCESTER </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Chronicle Publishing Sells Newspaper for $295 Million  &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Chronicle Publishing Co. announced yesterday that it has agreed to
sell the Worcester Telegram &AMP; Gazette to New York Times Co. for
$295 million.
<P>
   Russell Lewis, chief executive of Times Co., which publishes the
New York Times and which bought the Boston Globe in 1993 for $1.1
billion, said the Worcester paper ``is a good fit with our other
long-term growth properties.''
</P>
<P>
   With 107,000 daily circulation and 134,000 on Sunday, the
Worcester Telegram &AMP; Gazette will be the fourth-largest of the
Times Company's 24 U.S. newspapers. Next in size is the Press
Democrat in Santa Rosa, which the Times Co. bought in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of the Worcester paper is subject to Department of
Justice review and Chronicle chief executive John Sias said he
expects the deal to close ``after the first of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Worcester deal marks the third major asset sale by the
privately owned Chronicle Publishing Co. since its board of
directors decided in June to sell some or all of its properties.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Hearst Corp., publisher of the afternoon Examiner,
agreed to buy The Chronicle morning newspaper for a reported $660
million. Last week, Pulitzer Inc. agreed to buy the Pantagraph and
seven community newspapers in Illinois for $180 million.
</P>
<P>
   Still on the block are KRON, San Francisco's NBC affiliate, two
television properties in Omaha, Neb., and Wichita, Kan., and two
book publishers _ Chronicle Books and MBI (Motorbooks
International).
</P>
<P>
   Bids were due this week for San Francisco's Chronicle Books.
Bidders reportedly include Nion McEvoy, editor in chief of the book
company and an owner of Chronicle Publishing; and Leo Hindery,
former chief finance and planning officer for Chronicle Publishing
from 1985 to 1987 who went on to become president of
Tele-Communications Inc. and, until last week, head of AT&AMP;T Corp.'s
cable television operations.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 2138EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7358 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-SCHWAB-SCHWAB_SFCHRON     10-14 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHWAB-SCHWAB </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Schwab Profit Swells 27% In 3rd Quarter  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Charles Schwab Corp., the nation's largest online and discount
broker, said its third-quarter profit jumped 27 percent from a year
ago as customers shifted assets to the firm at a rapid clip.
<P>
   San Francisco's Schwab reported net income of $124.5 million (15
cents a diluted share), compared with $97.8 million (12 cents) for
the three months ended September 1998. The firm posted revenue of
$883.7 million in the latest period, up 25 percent from a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab's earnings met Wall Street expectations but fell sharply
from the previous period as stock trading slowed.
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by a frenzied surge in Internet-based trading activity,
Schwab posted record profit and revenue of $151 million and $982.1
million, respectively, in the 1999 second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab's stock rose $1.88, to $29.94, yesterday on volume of 6.6
million shares after it announced earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion of Web-based trading during the first and second
quarter ``was clearly an aberration,'' said Hambrecht &AMP; Quist
analyst Greg Smith. Schwab's third quarter probably was more
representative of the level of activity the firm can sustain, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, Schwab did well, but not great, given market
conditions,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   The best news for Schwab was its ability to draw in assets.
Customers added $25 billion in net new assets in the past quarter,
an amount almost as large as the total assets of Menlo Park's
E-Trade Group, the No.2 online broker. That raised Schwab's total
customer assets to $595 billion and topped the firm's $23 billion
of net new assets in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The asset flow increased even though Schwab opened 282,000
accounts in the September quarter, fewer than the 422,000 it opened
in the previous period.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not worrying about that,'' Schwab Chief Financial
Officer Chris Dodds said in an interview. ``We've made a conscious
decision to focus on asset aggregation more than new accounts.``
</P>
<P>
   Average trades dropped to 175,400 per day in the quarter, from
203,700 in the previous period, as the online stock-trading mania
cooled. As a result, Schwab's revenue from commissions and
wholesale brokerage dropped, partly offset by increases in mutual
fund service fees and net interest income.
</P>
<P>
   More than two-thirds of Schwab's trades in the most recent
period occurred online.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's results contrasted sharply with that of E-Trade,
announced Wednesday, which signed up more new customers than Schwab
but added assets at a relatively sluggish pace.
</P>
<P>
   The divergence points to a growing segmentation of the online
brokerage market, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Edgier, hipper firms like E-Trade are attracting Generation X
customers comfortable on the Internet but without the wealth of
older investors. Schwab, which raised its minimum account-balance
requirement to $5,000 from $2,500 earlier this year, is attracting
well-heeled clients who traditionally used full-service brokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schwab is moving upstream and going against firms like Merrill
Lynch,'' said Smith. ``Schwab clearly has a higher-caliber level of
customer'' than other online brokers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
