<SLUG> BC-DAIMLERCHRYSLER-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERGER WILL CREATE AEROSPACE BEHEMOTH IN EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany, France, Great Britain)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STRASBOURG, France _ Overcoming national jealousies and
ideological obstacles, DaimlerChrysler AG of Germany and
Aerospatiale Matra SA of France agreed Thursday to merge their
aerospace businesses into a European behemoth with about $22
billion in annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   The new company, to be called European Aeronautic, Defense and
Space Co., would be the world's third-largest aerospace company
after Boeing Co. and Lockheed-Martin Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, it would essentially control Airbus
Industrie, Boeing's bitter rival in commercial aircraft production,
as well as Arianespace SA, currently the world's biggest commercial
rocket-launch company.
</P>
<P>
   But the deal is at least as important for political and military
as for business reasons. It marks the first major cross-border
merger within Europe's balkanized military industry and
demonstrates the galvanizing effect of the Kosovo war on European
military thinking.
</P>
<P>
   In sharp contrast to the relentless pace with which American
military contractors have merged in recent years, the European
players have remained fragmented along national lines.
</P>
<P>
   The price of that fragmentation was painfully apparent to
European leaders during NATO's war in Kosovo this summer, when
American military technology and aircraft utterly dominated the
multinational force.
</P>
<P>
   Highlighting the political significance of Thursday's deal,
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder of Germany and Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin of France took part in a signing ceremony here in this city
on the French-German border.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has become necessary to combine European forces,'' Jospin
said. ``Today's success underlines the outstanding success of the
French-German alliance as a motor of European integration.''
</P>
<P>
   That marks a huge turnaround from earlier this year. As recently
as last March, disputes between the big European aerospace
companies and their sponsoring governments had become so intense
that the Germans had begun sounding out American companies like
Northrop Grumman Corp. about possible alliances.
</P>
<P>
   Juergen Schrempp, the chairman of DaimlerChrysler, bluntly
declared in March that ``the dream of a European defense company is
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   One symbol of the enduring differences Thursday was language.
Even though the partners here were respectively French and German,
the name of the new company and indeed its official language of
business will be English.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement reached Thursday was only possible after both the
Germans and the French made big political compromises. Until
recently, Daimler executives refused to team up with Aerospatiale
as long as the French government still owned a big stake. The
French government was equally vehement in demanding continued
control over big decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The result Thursday was a complicated compromise that diminishes
the French government stake but leaves it with a veto on major
issues. In a twist, however, DaimlerChrysler has the right to sell
its 50 percent stake back to the French after three years if it is
unhappy with the results.
</P>
<P>
   If the merger is successful, it could create new competitive
pressure for Boeing, Lockheed and the remaining American military
contractors. But Pentagon officials have been quietly encouraging
European mergers, in the hope of standardizing the military
industry on both sides of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   European leaders, as well as executives at both DaimlerChrysler
and Aerospatiale, hope several other European players will join the
group. Casa, the Spanish aerospace company, is already in merger
talks with DaimlerChrysler's aerospace unit, and is expected to
join in quickly.
</P>
<P>
   But executives here are also hoping to recruit companies like
Thomson CSF of France, which produces military electronics, as well
as Italian partners.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest question now concerns the British aerospace
industry, which broke ranks with the Continental players last year.
In a stinging rebuke to the French and Germans, British Aerospace
PLC negotiated a merger with GEC Marconi, a unit of General
Electric of Britain.
</P>
<P>
   That deal derailed painstaking efforts by European political
leaders to arrange a Continent-wide merger.
</P>
<P>
   Now British Aerospace, which remains a minority shareholder in
the Airbus consortium, appears isolated.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Luc Lagadere, the chairman of Aerospatiale, made it clear
Thursday that he was hoping to lure partners from Spain and Italy
but most importantly from Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am talking about all those countries in Western Europe, and
I am of course talking about our British friends,'' said Lagadere.
</P>
<P>
   Ranked by annual sales, the French-German conglomerate would
still be less than half as big as Boeing, with $53.5 billion, and
slightly smaller than Lockheed-Martin, with $25 billion.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Its biggest component by far would be its 75 percent stake in
Airbus, the European consortium that produces commercial airliners
and has revenue of about $8.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is to convert Airbus from its current unwieldy
structure as a multinational consortium to a conventional company
that would be a subsidiary of the French-German conglomerate.
</P>
<P>
   The new company will also control Arianespace, which is the
world's biggest commercial rocket launch company. It will also
control Eurocopter, which claims to be the world's largest
helicopter producer.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the new company would remain far behind the
American rivals as a producer of jet fighters, a field where it
commands only 5.8 percent of the world market.
</P>
<P>
   To resolve the disputes over political control, the new company
would have a complicated structure. On the surface, the structure
appears to create a merger of equals that would leave the French
government with a decisive role. But the deal may well leave
DaimlerChrysler in command.
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan, DaimlerChrysler would turn over its entire
aerospace subsidiary except for a division that makes aircraft
engines. Because the aerospace subsidiary is much larger than
Aerospatiale, DaimlerChrysler would also get 3.4 billion euros in
cash, or about $3.7 billion, in exchange for accepting only 50
percent of a new holding company.
</P>
<P>
   The French government, which currently owns 48 percent of
Aerospatiale, would sell shares to its stake in the new company to
just 15 percent. But the government would still have a veto over
decisions on mergers, strategic alliances or additional stock
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, the French government control runs counter to
DaimlerChrysler's long-held refusal to team up with a
state-controlled company.
</P>
<P>
   But a provision that was not publicly disclosed Thursday
provides Daimler with a piece of insurance: the right to sell its
shares to the other shareholders _ after three years if it is
unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   Manfred Bischoff, chief executive of DaimlerChrysler Aerospace,
defended the compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to make a choice _ either we gave more importance to
being a competitive entity or we gave more importance to reducing
government ownership,'' he said Thursday. ``As we would say in
German, it was a small frog to swallow.''
</P>
<P>
   Company executives close to the deal said Schrempp approached
Lagadere informally in April but negotiations did not become
serious until June. At that point, according to one executive, he
set a deadline of July 14 for reaching an agreement at the
corporate level. If they failed, Schrempp vowed to scrap talks and
seek an American partner instead _ namely Northrop Grumman.
</P>
<P>
   The executives apparently did reach a deal in July, but they
still needed to negotiate an agreement with the French government.
Those talks began in September and did not conclude until last
week.
</P>
<P>
   American reaction to Thursday's deal was muted. ``I don't think
that fundamentally at this point changes anything,'' said Philip
Condit, Boeing's chairman and chief executive. ``It gives them both
an opportunity and a challenge to bring those together. And in the
meantime we are going to be getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon, officials are hoping to entice European
military contractors into trans-Atlantic deals. Though pleased to
see the European industry consolidating around a few big players,
officials remain wary that American rivals may be squeezed out of
European markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We favor an evolution toward a competitive trans-Atlantic
model of defense industries,'' said Cheryl Irwin, a Pentagon
spokesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
