<SLUG> BC-EGOV-EGOV </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 S.F. Turns Its Red Tape Into Digital Form  &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Moving to replace red tape with mouse clicks, the city of San
Francisco has launched a Web site that will enable local
proprietors to do business with the city directly from their
computer desktops.
<P>
   The city's 70,000 businesses now can renew their annual business
tax registration, which is due by November 1, at the new San
Francisco CityBusiness site (citybusiness.sfgov.org). Instead of
filling out paper forms, they simply punch in a couple of
identification numbers; rather than writing a check, they can enter
a credit card number to pay the associated fees, which range from
$25 to $500.
</P>
<P>
   Business owners have to wait a week to 10 days to get their
registration certificates, but they get a confirmation number as
soon as they complete the online process, plus follow-up e-mail
later.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, the city plans to expand the site with a variety of
other interactive functions, such as paying water bills, ordering
copies of birth and death certificates and eventually paying taxes
and parking tickets.
</P>
<P>
   City Treasurer Susan Leal, whose office initiated the project,
presided over the launch ceremony yesterday at City Hall.
Supervisors Gavin Newsom and Mark Leno were on hand to demonstrate
the system by renewing the registrations of their small businesses
on an IBM laptop computer.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstration got off to a rocky start when Newsom, trying
to renew the registration of his Plump Jack wine store, was greeted
with an error message (``error: failure-hard''). It turned out that
Newsom, ignoring onscreen instructions to select either Visa or
MasterCard, had tried to pay his $150 fee with an American Express
card.
</P>
<P>
   Leno's renewal for his Budget Signs company, however, went
smoothly. Newsom, after finding a Visa card in another pocket, then
tried again, this time successfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one more example of the most wired city wiring itself
even more,'' Leno said.
</P>
<P>
   The site was developed by KPMG Consulting in cooperation with
the city's Department of Telecommunications and Information
Services, with additional help from Microsoft. It runs on equipment
donated by Hewlett-Packard and hosted at Qwest Cyber.Solutions, a
joint venture of KPMG and Qwest Communications International, in
San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
