<SLUG> BC-INTEL-INTEL </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Intel Plans to Acquire DSP for $1.6 Billion  &HT;     By Henry Norr 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
A billion dollars here, a billion dollars there, pretty soon you're
a giant in the burgeoning communications-chip industry.
<P>
   That, at least, seems to be Intel's battle plan. The company
yesterday said it is shelling out $1.6 billion in cash to acquire
DSP Communications, a leading supplier of digital signal processors
and other chips for cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
   The buyout is the latest in a series of moves through which
Intel chief executive Craig Barrett is attempting to make his
company a key supplier of chips for networking and communications
products. The company has spent more than $5 billion this year to
acquire companies in this market.
</P>
<P>
   ``This acquisition is an important element of Intel's plan to
become the leading building-block supplier to the Internet,''
according to the company's press release.
</P>
<P>
   Intel still derives the bulk of its revenues from its Pentium
family of microprocessors for PCs, but growth in that market is
slowing and price pressures have squeezed profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's revenues and earnings for the quarter ended September 25
fell slightly short of analysts' expectations, just as they have
done for the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
   DSP Communications is headquartered in Cupertino, but as of Dec.
31, 1998, 80 percent of its 230 employees were in Israel, according
to Securities and Exchange Commission filings. The company
specializes in the design of digital signal processors and
companion chips for cellular phones.
</P>
<P>
   DSPC's customers include many of the giants in the cellular
world, among them Lucent Technologies, Motorola, NEC, Philips,
Sanyo and Sharp.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bier, president and general manager of Berkeley Design
Technology Inc., a Berkeley consulting company that specializes in
digital signal processing, said DSPC's products are not unique,
``but they've certainly been successful.''
</P>
<P>
   He also noted that the other leading players in the cell-phone
chipset market, including Texas Instruments, LSI Logic and Philips,
are larger companies that would have been more expensive for Intel
to acquire and more difficult to digest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may have been unique in being the only pure-play company in
this field,'' he said. ``And the $1.6 billion price looks very
reasonable when you consider that much smaller, less-established
companies in the embedded telecommunications space have recently
been selling for hundreds of millions of dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   In its SEC filing, DSPC reported that it had 52 patents allowed
or pending in the United States, Japan and Israel. The company has
expertise in several cellular technologies used by different
companies and in different countries. Some of its products are
designed for phones that let users connect wirelessly to the
Internet, a market expected to boom in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   Intel CEO Barrett focused on that theme in comments included in
Intel's announcement: ``Cellular technology is emerging as a new
high-speed method of connecting to the Internet and we believe over
time it will become increasingly important for connecting PCs to
the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The $1.6 billion purchase price values DSPC's shares at $36
each, a premium of almost 29 percent over Wednesday's closing price
of $28.
</P>
<P>
   News of the deal was well received on Wall Street. Intel shares
rose $1.22 to close at $73.43, while DSP's stock soared $6.94, to
$34.94.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
