</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIDGE-FRIDGE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Office Fridge Fright  &HT;     By Sam McManis 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Co-workers at Samuel Merritt College in Oakland always
good-naturedly kidded associate registrar Anne Scher about her
healthy eating habits, such as her affinity for all things bran and
a steadfast refusal to let refined sugar pass between her lips.
<P>
   But it was Scher's ominous-looking natural food drink, the color
and texture of which she acknowledged looked like ``pond scum,''
that made colleagues warily move their casserole dishes and roast
beef sandwiches to another shelf.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks went by, and still the drink remained untouched _ even by
Scher herself. No one mentioned it; apparently, they didn't want to
get near this presumably toxic substance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It finally exploded inside the refrigerator, completely
covering the ceiling, walls and everyone's food with bright green
pond scum,'' said Scher, who spent two hours on her hands and knees
with a sponge cleaning up the mess. ``My co-workers found this very
amusing.''
</P>
<P>
   At least Scher's office-mates had a sense of humor. Discarded
horrors lurking in office fridges are the bane of many a workplace
environment.
</P>
<P>
   Be it pungent chicken chow mein in Styrofoam boxes left over
from Reagan's first term, carrot juice that dripped to the bottom
shelf and became as indestructible as titanium or an unrecognizable
entree that has grown blue hair and seems to be moving, a messy,
malodorous fridge can chip away at a worker's well-being.
</P>
<P>
   Long considered a workplace perk, office fridges provide
employees a chance to save money and eat something to their liking.
</P>
<P>
   Several surveys also point out that American workers have
chosen, for the sake of productivity, to eat lunch at their desks
rather than eat out.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reasons, the office refrigerator has led to abuses
that have turned it into a battleground among grousing employees
and a breeding ground for bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   That has caused many companies to assign workers _ usually
administrative staff _ to regularly clean the mess. Kathie Dills,
president of the Berkeley-Vallejo chapter of the International
Association of Administrative Professionals, said her large
corporation in San Francisco now has specific cleanliness rules
after a big fridge fallout a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's worked pretty well, but generally, it's still the women
who clean up,'' Dills said. ``Although I have seen some of our
partners wipe things down occasionally.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, though, refrigerator wars remain a relatively harmless
workplace irritant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bosses who are psychotic and people being laid off _ those are
the big traumatic events in the workplace,'' said Bob Rosner, who
hosts a Web site ( &LR; www.workingwounded.com &LR; ) &LR;   &LR; that provides an
outlet for workers to vent and get advice. ``But I'd say, on a
day-to-day basis, I get more mail on pebble-in-the-shoe stuff like
office refrigerators than the important stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow, when you're sitting there for eight hours a day,
workers pump these little things like a bad fridge smell into major
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Take it from a veteran office temp in San Francisco, who didn't
want to give her name for fear of reprisal _ nearly every company
she has done time with has had a fridge fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've come across that refrigerators that, you know, the food
must have been there a million years,'' she said. ``It's, like,
growing hair. You open the Tupperware container, and you go, `Oooh,
that's terrible.' I've found that, in the offices I've worked in,
the bigger the company, the worse the fridge. There's always a sign
on the front that says, `Take out by Friday,' but they always
forget to put what year.''
</P>
<P>
   Some employees say they don't understand how co-workers can
leave leftovers in the refrigerator for so long that they start to
resemble science experiments in food preservation gone awry.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is, few will cop to ownership of the
bacteria-spawning wedges of decaying lunch leftovers. Fewer still
will volunteer to clean this repository of once-edible rubbish.
</P>
<P>
   Even professionals shy away from such unenviable tasks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reminds me of college kids' fridges,'' says a manager of
High Marks Janitorial Service, which cleans many office buildings
in San Francisco. ``Food will sit there a month before somebody
says, `What is this?' As a general rule, janitorial services won't
go in a fridge to clean unless specifically asked to do it for an
additional charge. We charge about 30 bucks extra. But it's not
something we like to do.''
</P>
<P>
   But somebody, someday, must do it. Usually, it is one fastidious
person disgusted with slovenly colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Diane Orr, a vice president at Tsantes &AMP; Associates, a Campbell
public relations firm, embarrassed her co-workers last year by
complaining about their office fridge in the Wall Street Journal.
It seems Orr was tired of being the office nag and cleaning up
after everyone else, so she went public with the firm's dirty
little secret.
</P>
<P>
   The public flogging apparently had the desired effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am happy to report that our fridge has been clean and
odor-free for quite some time,'' Orr said. ``We still get the
occasional yogurt left in there with the expiration dates older
than my car, but for the most part, everyone is pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   For some, the cleanup is therapy itself. Cheryl, a marketing
executive from the East Bay who declined to give her last name,
used to volunteer to clean the office fridge. ``Sometimes, people
would ask me why if they happened by while I was at it,'' Cheryl
said. ``The same curious people would just stuff whatever into the
fridge and leave dirty dishes in the sink and just move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosner says the top office complaint to his Web site involves
brown-bag criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``One woman told me about a psychotic co-worker who opened a
sealed box of chicken, ate six of the seven pieces, put the bones
back and re-sealed it,'' Rosner said.
</P>
<P>
   Debra Ebling, an East Bay lawyer, has a similar tale of woe.
``Someone finally put a Post-it note that read, `I spit in this
jar' on a jar of food, obviously hoping this would stop anyone from
taking it,'' she said. ``A friend of mine ... saw this and couldn't
resist putting his own note that read, `So did I.'''
</P>
<P>
   In drastic cases, the leftover problem has made the fridge so
hideous that the only viable option is to toss it and buy a new
one.
</P>
<P>
   This happened in a Philadelphia law firm a few years ago, when a
lawyer, an avid hunter, brought a decapitated fox head in a box and
stored it there until he could get his secretary to make
arrangements with a testing laboratory to determine whether the fox
was rabid. Employees who opened the fridge were horrified.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one went near (the fridge) for weeks after that,'' she
said, noting that the company bought a new refrigerator shortly
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
