u s BC-BBA-YANKEES-BRIEFS-NY     10-14 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIRARDI MOVES TO FRONT; BROSIUS SHORT ONE DOUBLE: NIELSEN RATINGS
UP  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jorge Posada is the catcher of the future, but as far as Yankees
Manager Joe Torre is concerned, Joe Girardi is the catcher of the
present.
</P>
<P>
   Girardi was scheduled to start Game 2 of the American League
Championship Series against the Boston Red Sox last night, and team
with David Cone _ a departure from the way Girardi and Posada
shared responsibilities during the regular season. Posada made
about 60 percent of the starts behind the plate, teaming with
Orlando Hernandez, Cone and Hideki Irabu.
</P>
<P>
   But now that the Yankees are in the midst of the playoffs, Torre
is going with the catcher with whom the pitchers have been the most
comfortable, and in Cone's case, that has always been Girardi.
Cone's earned run average is more than a run lower with Girardi
behind the plate than it is when Posada catches him and, of course,
Girardi was the catcher on the day this season when Cone pitched
his perfect game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough in relation to Jorge, but I'm trying to give David
every benefit _ even though David has never expressed a preference,
one way or the other,'' Torre said. ``Since Cone hasn't pitched for
a while, I wanted to put Joe back there.''
</P>
<P>
   Posada went into the 1998 season as the primary catcher, and at
that time, the Yankees were committed to his developing into an
everyday catcher for the 1999 season. But when the season was over,
the Yankees surprised Girardi by exercising his $3.4 million option
for this season _ at Torre's suggestion _ and Posada has not played
as much as he would have liked.
</P>
<P>
   Girardi is also expected to catch Games 3 and 4 in Boston, where
Roger Clemens and then Pettitte will pitch. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BROSIUS' BID COMES UP SHORT
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius hammered a two-run homer in his first at-bat in
Game 1 on Wednesday night, to keep the Yankees close at 3-2, then
added a triple in his next plate appearance when his blooper fell
out of the grasp of the diving Trot Nixon in right field and rolled
into the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius hit a single in the seventh inning, leaving him only a
double away from becoming the first player in major league history
to hit for the cycle _ a single, a double, a triple and a home run
_ in a post-season game. ``I knew that if I had a chance, it would
probably be tonight because I got that triple out of the way
early,'' Brosius said.
</P>
<P>
   Brosius, however, struck out in his last at-bat, which hardly
diminished his impact on the game.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RATINGS ARE UP &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By RICHARD SANDOMIR &QC;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Game 1 of the ALCS on Wednesday night produced a 10.8 national
Nielsen rating for Fox, an increase of 74 percent from the league
championship game the network showed on the same night last year,
between Atlanta and San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, on Channel 5, the game generated a 24.4 rating.
</P>
<P>
   The game started with an 8.4 rating from 8:14 to 8:30 p.m. and
peaked at an 11.5 from 9:30 to 10. When Bernie Williams hit the
game-winning home run in the bottom of the 10th inning, the rating
stood at 11.3.
</P>
<P>
   On NBC, Game 2 of the Mets-Braves NLCS posted a 7.3 preliminary
overnight rating, down from a 9.8 for a Cleveland-Yankees ALCS game
last year. For Game 1 of the Mets-Braves series, NBC posted a 10.8
rating, up from a 9.2 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
