<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7377 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT &LR;      10-14 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Wis., Ky., Minn., Kan., Utah, Wash.)  
 REPUBLICANS PILLORY McCAIN IN DEBATE OVER SOFT MONEY  
(th) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the Senate opened five days of debate on the
campaign finance bill, Republicans bitterly turned on one of their
own Thursday, demanding that Sen. John McCain of Arizona prove his
contentions that special-interest contributions to political
parties are corrupting Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The unusually personal exchanges consumed most of the morning
and illustrated how high passions run on an issue that affects
lawmakers quite personally.
</P>
<P>
   The rancor also showcased the difficulties faced by McCain and
Sen. Russ Feingold, a Wisconsin Democrat, in their effort to ban
the unlimited and unregulated six-figure donations to the political
parties known as soft money.
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary dialogue in a chamber that usually strives for
comity began when Sen. Mitch McConnell, the Kentucky Republican who
has been a steady opponent of the bipartisan legislation, began
reading statement after statement made by McCain, who has made his
stand against special-interest money a foundation of his bid for
the Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone must be corrupt for there to be corruption,''
McConnell said, and he challenged McCain to come forth with
specific charges against individual senators.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can there be corruption if no one is corrupt?'' McConnell
asked, ``That's like saying the gang is corrupt but none of the
gangsters are.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain instead read passages about the culture of money in
Washington from a new book by Elizabeth Drew, ``The Corruption of
American Politics.'' But he refused to name names, saying, ``I am
not in the business of identifying individuals or attacking
individuals. I am attacking a system. I am attacking a system that
has to be fixed.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, several Republicans refused to relent, pressing for
precise examples of corruption from McCain, a maverick who has
irritated many in his party with his stands against pork-barrel
spending, for overhaul of the campaign finance law and for
antismoking legislation. The few Democrats on the floor watched for
the most part in fascinated silence as Republicans tore into one of
their own presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Sen. Paul Wellstone, Democrat of Minnesota,
inquired of McConnell how long he planned to ``continue with this
attack on Senator McCain on the floor?''
</P>
<P>
   Although the House passed comprehensive legislation to overhaul
the campaign finance law by a 252-177 vote last month, McCain and
Feingold have repeatedly fallen at least eight votes short of the
60 they need to steer their companion bill past a Senate
filibuster.
</P>
<P>
   So this year, in an effort to change the dynamics, they scaled
back their bill to focus mainly on the soft-money ban and dropped
efforts to regulate issue advocacy advertisements by outside
groups, which are often thinly disguised campaign commercials.
During the next five days of debate and amendment efforts that
McCain has described as a ``dynamic process'' the two senators hope
to craft a bill that can pick up additional votes to overcome a
filibuster.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, the new bill has won only one additional supporter,
Sen. Sam Brownback, Republican of Kansas. And the new strategy
could just as easily risk losing votes for the bill as gaining
them. The League of Women Voters, for example, has already
withdrawn its previous support for the legislation, saying it is no
longer comprehensive enough.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of the kind of pitfalls that could be ahead, the
Senate by voice vote Thursday approved a seemingly innocuous
amendment offered by McConnell to change Senate rules to require
senators to report any ``credible information'' of corruption.
</P>
<P>
   But the amendment had a little-noticed second effect: through a
parliamentary tactic it created a nearly insurmountable threshold
for McCain and Feingold to meet to overcome an expected filibuster
against their legislation by McConnell.
</P>
<P>
   To stop a filibuster against a change in Senate rules requires
67 votes instead of the usual 60 votes. But aides to McCain said he
had enough votes to overturn McConnell's amendment and replace it
with a slightly different one. And McConnell, having demonstrated
just how wily a master he is of Senate rules, told reporters later
that he would not insist that his opponents come up with 67 votes
to fight his filibuster.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate also approved an amendment requiring quick disclosure
of campaign contributions on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   As senators argued across a long day over whether the current
system of campaign financing was by its very nature corrupting, one
of the sharpest exchanges came between Sen. Robert F. Bennett,
Republican of Utah, and McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett noted that a $2.2 million sewer project for the 2002
Winter Olympics that he had sponsored was mentioned on the Web page
of McCain's presidential campaign as an example of the kind of pork
barrel spending that results from the contributions of special
interests. He demanded that McCain identify the contributions that
he believed had made Bennett propose the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who gave the soft money?'' Bennett asked. ``How much was it
and where did it go?''
</P>
<P>
   McCain replied that he had said only that campaign contributions
were a main ingredient in pork barrel spending. And he read a
dictionary definition of corruption as ``the impairment of
integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   More specifically, he took on Bennett over the practice, common
in Congress, of inserting money for special projects into spending
bills. McCain said he had written to Bennett in 1997 about the Utah
senator's efforts to insert money for the 2002 Winter Olympics into
spending bills without congressional hearings.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said that when he never received a response he personally
gave Bennett a copy of the letter a year later. ``The people of
Arizona would at least like to have a hearing before their tax
dollars go to the state of Utah,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Then another Republican senator with a project listed on
McCain's Web site _ Slade Gorton of Washington _ began a similar
wrangle.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of the day, the debate covered more familiar
ground.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell, who heads the Senate Republicans' campaign committee,
argued that the McCain-Feingold legislation even in the scaled-back
form he derided as ``McCain-Feingold lite'' contains contribution
limits that violate constitutional guarantees of free speech.
McConnell called it ``one of the tragedies of our time'' that the
bill ``is allowed to be advanced as reform.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure's supporters said that large campaign contributions
were causing pervasive cynicism about politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not only a crucial issue to the health and future of
Congress, but also for democracy itself,'' Feingold said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that if he had his way, the Senate would pass
public financing of campaigns.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
