<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7378 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV17-NY     10-14 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV17-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSPERITY AS REDEMPTION FOR A BOOMER GENERATION  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 17) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)   (af)  
 By TOM REDBURN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everybody knows that journalism thrives on bad news: natural
disasters, wars, financial crashes. Where would newspapers be
without them?
</P>
<P>
   So when a book comes along titled ``The Long Boom: A Vision For
the Coming Age of Prosperity,'' the natural reaction of any
self-respecting economics reporter or editor is to examine it with
a jaundiced eye.
</P>
<P>
   For what if its message _ that the world stands on the edge of a
``global economic expansion on a scale never before experienced'' _
turns out to be true? In that case, the job of covering the economy
in the future, I have to confess, would probably be a lot less
engaging than it has been in the thrilling upheavals of the two
decades I've been writing or editing articles about economics and
business affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Who wants to write an unending series of upbeat stories? Who
wants to read them? People pay a lot more attention to the economy,
after all, when things are going badly than when they are going
well. Even the current obsession with getting rich in the stock
market is built on the fear that it may all fall apart at any
moment.
</P>
<P>
   Despite my clear interest in finding fault, ``The Long Boom''
(Perseus Books, October 1999), is not so easy to dismiss.
</P>
<P>
   The book's central thesis, first propounded in an exceptionally
long article written by Peter Schwartz and Pete Leyden in Wired
magazine in 1997, is by now quite familiar. ``We have gone from an
economy driven by the production of tangible things to one driven
by intangible ideas,'' they argue. The global economy is in the
midst of a ``40-year period from 1980 to 2020 encompassing a
critical shift from an Industrial Age economy to an Information Age
economy, or a Knowledge Economy, or what we simply call the New
Economy.''
</P>
<P>
   While still controversial among economists, this kind of
thinking has been accepted for years in the technology centers on
the West Coast. It is reflected in the writings of everyone from
Peter Drucker to Paul Hawken, whose seminal 1983 book, ``The Next
Economy,'' grew out of futurism scenarios developed at the Stanford
Research Institute. Even Alan Greenspan is a convert.
</P>
<P>
   And it turned out to be more prescient than the fashionably
pessimistic East Coast views of the 1980s, expressed in critically
acclaimed books like ``The Rise and Fall of the Great Powers,'' by
Paul Kennedy, a professor at Yale. He predicted the decline of the
United States as a world power only a few years before America's
chief strategic rival, the Soviet Union, fell apart and its chief
economic challenger, Japan, entered decade-long stagnation.
</P>
<P>
   But the pessimists have been swept from the field, and American
optimism about the nation's technological and economic superiority
is running rampant. So what now? ``If we do it right, it's an
opportunity to build a vastly better world,'' said Schwartz,
visiting New York the other day with Leyden, in a wide-ranging
conversation. ``This is the reverse of World War II. This is about
more than simply protecting what we've got against the sea of
darkness.''
</P>
<P>
   The allusion to World War II is revealing. Millions of baby
boomers harbor a not-so-hidden envy of their parents' great
crusade. ``Saving Private Ryan'' and Tom Brokaw's paean to ``The
Greatest Generation'' have touched a chord: Making money doesn't
compare to ridding the world of Nazism.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing wrong, of course, with recognizing the nobility
of that heroic struggle. Self-sacrifice is morally superior to
self-indulgence. But sometimes that wisdom slops over into a
yearning for another war to fight, a hankering simply to risk death
for a greater cause.
</P>
<P>
   And that's where ``The Long Boom'' gets interesting. For what
the authors are really doing is trying to infuse that hoariest of
cliches _ the moral equivalent of war _ with real meaning for
generations who, one hopes, will never experience a real war.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, they offer an ideology for college-educated
knowledge workers, who will soon be the largest class in America.
They advocate globalization and open markets, and while not
particularly anti-government, they are vaguely libertarian in
outlook.
</P>
<P>
   They see rapid growth built on technologies like fuel cells and
genetic engineering as capable of improving the environment rather
than degrading it. ``It's an anti-Blade Runner vision of the
future,'' Leyden said.
</P>
<P>
   The payoff from all this in 25 years or so, they argue, will be
to pull perhaps half the world's population out of subsistence
living into a vast, well-educated global middle class. The average
life span would lengthen tremendously. The risk of global warming
would disappear.
</P>
<P>
   I've got my doubts. They underestimate the threat of deep
cultural conflict and a backlash against technology that would
result from fast growth. They tend to congratulate the high-tech
centimillionaires of Silicon Valley simply for doing what they do
best: getting rich. And their vision is too New Agey for my taste.
</P>
<P>
   Still, their dream looks superior to the likely alternatives.
Growth is indeed better than stagnation. Peace beats war. If that's
not so good for reporters, so be it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 2147EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
