<HEADER>
A7380 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GEN-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN     10-14 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET REPORTING GAINS CREDIBILITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (ital)This is the latest in a series on the Internet and sports
media:(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Catch the story the other day about the possible involvement of
five University of Tennessee football players, a baseball player
and a female athlete in academic irregularities involving four
tutors going back to 1995? The school recently held four football
players out of a game, then reinstated them a week later after its
own investigation found them to be clean.
</P>
<P>
   But the crux of the tale _ that some at the school knew about
these allegations but didn't act on it for a long while _ has yet
to be addressed publicly by Tennessee officials.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was a startling revelation that two top instructors
in the Dodgers' minor-league system were accused by more than one
person of physically and verbally abusing players.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone denied it.
</P>
<P>
   Then this week he hired a new director of minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you missed these news items because they broke on the
Internet, where the concept of sports journalism continues to be
regarded by the mainstream as one of the great oxymorons of the day
_ basically because any moron who has access to a computer can make
his own Web site, shovel information out there and claim to be a
journalist.
</P>
<P>
   As this communication renaissance has taken off on the Internet
over the last five years, we've been told that sports sites are one
of the strongest driving forces of the Web. Yet, in one way, the
Internet model of reporting is perceived to have been set by
scavenger Matt Drudge, who built the Monica Lewinsky-President
Clinton scandal into something that led to a governmental
shakedown.
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee story, first reported on ESPN.com, and the Dodgers
story, broken by KFWB-AM (980) sports anchor and former longtime
radio-sports-talk host Joe McDonnell on his site
(www.la-sports.com), have rattled some cages in high places as
well. Although these examples are seen almost as aberrations in
this medium, they could set the tone nationally and locally for
what original Internet sports reporting will be about.
</P>
<P>
   Each has one thing other start-up wanna-be sites can not attain
so easily this early in the game _ a track record of credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to look at where the information is coming from,''
said John Marvel, the executive editor of ESPN.com, who comes from
years of newspaper writing. ``How you set yourself apart is by your
journalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like we're pioneering a great medium, probably like
the guys who started in TV in the mid-'40s. We know everyone can
put up a site, but we play by the same rules of journalism here.
We're not Matt Drudge throwing up stuff and hoping it sticks. We
never want to embarrass ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is good journalism on the Web. When people start
understanding that, the credibility factor goes up. We're proud of
what we do and you'll probably see a lot more original reporting as
other sites start to understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee announced last week that there would be no NCAA
investigation into academic fraud after an internal probe found no
rules violation. University president J. Wade Gilley was quoted in
the local press as calling the original story ``speculation and
rumor'' and that ``ESPN.com is not the judge, jury and
executioner.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee did, however, interview a former academic counselor
who was a key source in the ESPN.com story.
</P>
<P>
   Marvel's man on the Tennessee story was Tom Farrey, a former
Seattle Times reporter who once did a story in 1992 about a
University of Washington quarterback who took a $50,000 loan. That
led to the school, which had just won the national championship,
going on probation and the resignation of coach Don James.
</P>
<P>
   Farrey was tipped off to the Tennessee story by an e-mail from a
student-athlete at the school.
</P>
<P>
   With the backing of ESPN, one of the first all-sports sites that
the Net users embraced, ESPN.com has become a news force in itself.
In fact, ESPN ``SportsCenter'' didn't report the story until
!ital!after!off! ESPN.com broke it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a great advantage in those four letters,'' Marvel
agrees. ``People know who we are, even though we go independently
of the TV. We've also built a reputation on our own. It's not as if
we're just `Joe's Website.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Although, in this instance, it's not that different from a real
Joe's site.
</P>
<P>
   McDonnell started his two years ago with a URL (thebignasty.com)
that was more an extension of his sports-talk show persona. When he
started at KFWB earlier this year, he revamped his site, included
links to many of the Internet newspaper sites and put up an
interactive poll. But what he found is that it not only gave him an
outlet to express his opinions on what was going on, but to become
a breaking-news site.
</P>
<P>
   When McDonnell posted his Dodgers story earlier this month, it
included Malone's quote that ``there's no validity to it'' and
``from what you're telling me, it seems like there are some people
around here with axes to grind. What really upsets me is they don't
have the guts to come directly to me with their complaints. Why
they would go (to the media) instead of me is mind-boggling.''
</P>
<P>
   The mainstream media _ including this newspaper _ checked out
these allegations but has not advanced the story. The Dodgers,
meanwhile, announced Wednesday that they promoted Jerry Weinstein
from minor-league catching coordinator to director of player
development. He will oversee all aspects of the Dodgers'
minor-league system.
</P>
<P>
   McDonnell compares Net sports reporting to what he had to go
through with radio in the '70s when he was one of the first to
cover a team on a full-time basis as a reporter. Media credentials
to events weren't easy to come by, and it was difficult to
establish credibility right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate that phrase that you've got to pay your dues, but
unless people know where the information is coming from, it's not
credible,'' said McDonnell, who has also had many Lakers
player-transactions on his site before the local newspapers, radio
and TV get wind of it. ``The bad reputation (of the Internet) is
from people who don't want to admit it's a force. People have a
fear of the truth sometimes, and I don't think a lot of the sports
journalists out there have the guts to go with the same
information. I'm not intimidated.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor will he slow down. McDonnell's site has increased traffic to
his site from about 1,200 visitors a day to about 6,000. He says
eventually he could see himself dedicated full-time to the site
(which will soon change its name to lasports2000.com). But without
a corporate backer such as ESPN.com has, McDonnell has managed only
to break even with his daily operation of the site, which includes
hiring a Web master.
</P>
<P>
   Since few individuals have figured out how to make their Web
sites financially viable without strong advertisements, it's
difficult to maintain the stature of a full-time reporter and gain
the recognition that comes with that.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't deter McDonnell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evolution of this will come much quicker than many
think,'' said McDonnell. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 2148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
