</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CONE'S INVISIBLE CLIFF  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When David Cone strode to the mound at Yankee Stadium
for the first inning last night, he knew there was an invisible
cliff there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I relish this opportunity; I've been in this position a lot,''
he had said, alluding to a 5-2 record in nine other post-season
starts since he joined the Yankees in 1995. ``But who knows what's
going to happen on down the line?''
</P>
<P>
   On down the line.
</P>
<P>
   For David Cone, that's a euphemism for the invisible cliff. For
what's going to happen when it's time for George Steinbrenner to
decide if an aging right-hander who will be 37 years old next
season should be pushed over the cliff of the Yankee payroll. If
the principal owner hasn't already decided.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year,'' Cone said last weekend in Texas, ``I can honestly
say that this may be my last chance to pitch in the playoffs for
the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   Cone didn't mean just his chance to pitch last night's second
game of the American League Championship Series with the Boston Red
Sox, he meant for whenever the Yankees need him to pitch if they
get to the World Series for the third time in four years.
</P>
<P>
   But after that, the cliff that is invisible now might be all too
visible. To everybody, not just Cone.
</P>
<P>
   If Cone were elsewhere next season, he would be a victim of what
might be called the Curse of the Perfecto.
</P>
<P>
   David Wells pitched a perfect game against the Minnesota Twins
in 1998, then was traded to the Toronto Blue Jays for Roger
Clemens. Cone pitched a perfect game against the Montreal Expos on
July 18 and now he could be in his last days as a Yankee, but he
knows why.
</P>
<P>
   ``I let a big year get away from me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of Cone's perfect game, his record was a snappy 10-4
with a 2.65 earned run average. Since then he was 2-5 with a 4.28
ERA; in his last five starts, he was 1-2 with a 6.00 ERA. Over all,
he was 12-9 with a 3.44 ERA. (second best in the AL behind Pedro
Martinez, the Red Sox ace).
</P>
<P>
   Not bad, but not what it might have been with a stronger finish.
</P>
<P>
   Not enough to keep the Yankees from slotting Cone as their
fourth starter in the division series with Texas. When the Yankees
swept, he was inserted as the Game 2 starter against the Red Sox
behind Orlando (El Duque) Hernandez, the Game 1 starter. He is also
expected to start Game 6 at the Stadium next Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand,'' Cone said, ``that post-season is a whole
different animal, and I'm well rested.''
</P>
<P>
   His arm has been under the Yankee microscope ever since he had
surgery to remove an aneurysm in 1996. The next season tendinitis
in his right elbow put him on the disabled list. In 1998 he had a
20-7 record but needed extensive medical treatments to get through
the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The invisible cliff now in Cone's future, of course, is what
baseball free agency is all about now.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time a franchise stockpiled its best players with
one eye on the payroll. But now, no matter how successful a
franchise is, both eyes are on the payroll. All those multimillion
dollar contracts in free agency can be a double-edged sword.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Cone has earned in excess of $50 million over the last
decade with the Mets, the Blue Jays, the Royals, the Blue Jays
again and the Yankees, suddenly he might no longer be worth the $8
million he earned this season.
</P>
<P>
   At least Cone might no longer be worth $8 million to
Steinbrenner, who next season will need to ante up fresh millions
for Derek Jeter, Mariano Rivera, Andy Pettitte and Jorge Posada as
the Yankees' payroll soars higher than this season's record $85
million.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those millions for Jeter, Rivera, Pettitte and Posada
are likely to come from the millions that the principal owner
probably will not want to pay Cone.
</P>
<P>
   Just because Cone might not be worth $8 million to the Yankees
doesn't mean he won't be worth $8 million, if not more, to the Mets
or the Orioles next season. Remember how the Orioles jumped to sign
Jimmy Key when the Yankees decided his left arm wouldn't endure a
three-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   But for David Cone, the Mets would be ideal: a return to the
other New York franchise for a year-round New Yorker with an upper
East Side apartment.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't take him any longer to get to Shea Stadium than it
does to get to Yankee Stadium for all those post-season games the
last five years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
