<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: PAPON DISAPPEARS
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Papon, 89, convicted last year of complicity in Nazi
crimes against humanity for his role in ordering the deportation of
Jews from Bordeaux, has disappeared from his home near Paris on the
eve of an appeals hearing. A Bordeaux court ruled he would have to
start serving his 10-year prison sentence before the appeal could
be heard next Thursday. Papon's lawyer said he knew where his
client was but would not say whether he would surrender.
</P>
<P>
   IRELAND: EX-PREMIER INDICTED
</P>
<P>
   Former Prime Minister Charles Haughey, 73, has been indicted on
charges of obstructing an investigation two years ago into payments
to politicians. Arraignment was set for Oct. 28 in Dublin's Circuit
Criminal Court. Haughey, whose finances are under study by a High
Court justice, faces two years' imprisonment and a fine of $16,000
if convicted of the new charges.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: RETIREMENT AT 60
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder and Labor Minister Walter Riester
supported a plan made by the powerful IG Metall trade union to
lower the effective retirement age from 65 to 60. IG Metall says
allowing early retirement would make it possible for up to 1.5
million young people to get work. Employers say the plan would
increase costs and cut net wages.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CHILE: THREATS FORCE OUT BRITON
</P>
<P>
   Britain's honorary consul in Valparaiso, Chile's largest port,
quit after receiving death threats in letters written to local
newspapers protesting the arrest in London of the former dictator
Gen. Augusto Pinochet. The resignation came as Chile warned it
would act strongly against any violent acts committed on Saturday,
the first anniversary of Pinochet's arrest.
</P>
<P>
   PERU: CABINET SHUFFLE
</P>
<P>
   President Alberto Fujimori shuffled his Cabinet, naming former
Foreign Minister Efrain Goldenberg as economy minister. The move
came after Prime Minister Victor Joy Way, who also served as
economy minister, resigned to run in congressional elections next
year.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: JUDGE FIRED
</P>
<P>
   A judge who freed one of Mexico's most powerful drug traffickers
was fired by a judicial review board and barred from the bench for
10 years. Last year Judge Nicandro Martinez Lopez used legal
technicalities to overturn two indictments against Adan Amezcua,
whose extradition is being sought by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAN: NEW SENTENCE FOR GERMAN
</P>
<P>
   A 57-year-old German businessman jailed for nearly two years on
charges of having a sexual relationship with an Iranian woman had
hopes of an early release dashed when he was taken to court on a
new charge of insulting a security policeman. Helmut Hofer told the
judge, ``I don't speak Farsi, and they don't speak German, so how
could I have insulted anyone?'' Hofer was twice sentenced to death
on charges of having sex with a 26-year-old student, but a judge
later found him guilty of having had ``illicit relations'' that did
not involve sex.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA: SWISS FREEZE ABACHA ACCOUNTS
</P>
<P>
   Swiss officials, acting at Nigeria's request, have ordered five
banks to freeze accounts held by the late Nigerian dictator Gen.
Sani Abacha, his relatives and associates, who are accused of
having ``systematically plundered'' the country's central bank. No
figure was disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA: ABACHA SON CHARGED
</P>
<P>
   A son of Gen. Sani Abacha and the late dictator's personal
security chief were charged with the 1996 murder of Kudirat Abiola,
who campaigned against the military government for imprisoning her
husband, Moshood K.O. Abiola. Mohammed Abacha and the former
security chief did not enter pleas. Abiola, whose apparent victory
in the 1993 presidential elections was annulled by the military,
died in prison in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
