<HEADER>
A7385 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-IRENE15-COX     10-14 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRENE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida expecting Irene to make landfall as tropical storm
 &HT;    By A. Scharnhorst
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Hurricane Irene changed paths Thursday
as easily as a cross-country driver abandons the homogenous
interstate for a more aesthetic highway. But Irene's scenic route
now stands to traverse Palm Beach County and the Treasure Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Through most of the day Thursday _ while feeder bands of rain
doused much of South Florida _ Irene seemed to be headed north
across Cuba and into the eastern waters of the Gulf of Mexico. But
by early afternoon, the Category 1 hurricane had taken a jog to the
east as if lured by billboards advertising the glories of the
Sunshine State.
</P>
<P>
   Experts now expect Irene to head over the heart of the
peninsula, across Key West, the Everglades and Lake Okeechobee,
past Disney World and the Space Coast before sailing out to sea
over Daytona Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the ones in her path, Irene should grow tired as
the journey continues. Within about 12 hours of making Florida
landfall _which is expected today _ it should be a tropical storm,
said National Hurricane Center meteorologist Chris Robbins. That
means shredding winds will be few, but there's no protection from
the water.
</P>
<P>
   By noon Saturday, much of Palm Beach County stands to get 10 to
20 inches of rain _ falling with little respite in sustained
sheets, experts said _ on top of the more than 6 inches that
saturated some portions of the county Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The worst weather for South Florida and the Treasure Coast
should occur between midnight tonight and early Saturday evening,
meteorologists said. Total rainfall could be equal to the rain from
Hurricane Floyd that devastated parts of the Carolinas, Gross said.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``the soil is different down here so we can handle
the rain much better than North Carolina can. But when you're
talking 15 inches of rain, particularly in urban areas, you're
looking at a lot of water.''
</P>
<P>
   The precipitation won't end there, National Weather Service
meteorologist Jack Gross predicts, although there's no accurate way
to estimate how bad it will be after that.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency management officials planned to open hurricane
shelters to help those who need refuge from the storm.
</P>
<P>
   In Palm Beach County, shelters at the South Florida Fairgrounds
could hold up to 800 people, said Assistant County Administrator
Vince Bonvento. The shelters are operated by the American Red
Cross.
</P>
<P>
   The county's traffic and road and bridge department also expects
a busy weekend dealing with flooding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're already responding to some reports of localized
flooding,'' Bonvento said. ``That's our biggest concern right now,
and should be for the next four days.''
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday afternoon, the National Weather Service had issued a
flood watch, tropical storm warning and hurricane watch for Palm
Beach County. Irene was expected to cause local flooding in
low-lying neighborhoods, possibly as far north as Kissimmee, South
Florida Water Management District officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricanes draw energy from warm water _ and much of the
southern third of Florida is covered with the warm waters of the
Everglades and Lake Okeechobee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't really matter how deep that water source is,''
Robbins said. ``It could be a foot of water but it's still a source
of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   It's doubtful that Irene could intensify over South Florida, he
said, but the warmth will certainly keep the storm from dissipating
as quickly.
</P>
<P>
   That will likely worsen the drowning of the already waterlogged
</P>
<P>
   Everglades and Lake Okeechobee's marshes, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The flooding also could hamper the $495 million restoration that
the district and the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers is carrying out
on the Kissimmee River, and is already affecting some farms in the
Glades, said Water Management District operations manager Tommy
Strowd.
</P>
<P>
   The Everglades is waterlogged from years of unusually high
water, causing trees on its myriad, teardrop-shaped islands to wilt
while bobcats and deer seek refuge atop levees and boat ramps,
Strowd said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rain we're getting is going to make that situation much,
much worse,'' Strowd said.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Trebor Banstetter, Robert P. King and Eliot
Kleinberg contributed to this story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
