<HEADER>
A7391 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FED-TREASURY-NYT &LR;      10-14 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-TREASURY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURY AND FED REACH COMPROMISE ON BANKING OVERHAUL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After decades of bickering over control of the
nation's banking system, the Treasury Department and the Federal
Reserve announced on Thursday that they had reached an agreement,
resolving one of the last outstanding issues in the fight to
overhaul the nation's financial system.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise, brokered in the early morning by Lawrence
Summers, Treasury secretary, and Alan Greenspan, chairman of the
Fed, was disclosed shortly before lawmakers met to reconcile the
few remaining differences between competing measures that had
already passed in the Senate and the House.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation still has privacy and lending provisions that
the White House says fail to adequately protect consumers and the
disadvantaged, but the compromise significantly increased the odds
of passage of a sweeping financial services bill that President
Clinton may ultimately agree to sign. The legislation would repeal
laws like the Glass-Steagall Act, fashioned by the banking crisis
of the 1930s, that had sharply limited the ability of banks,
securities firms and insurance companies from expanding into each
other's businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Treasury-Fed agreement puts us closer than ever before to
writing financial-services-modernization legislation,'' said Rep.
Jim Leach, R-Iowa, who is chairman of the conference committee.
``Let's finish the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyists said the deal was certain to put pressure on the
lawmakers to change the legislation in a way that the president
would be able to sign it. Still, by Thursday evening, the measure
under discussion still had provisions, objectionable to the White
House, that watered down the Community Reinvestment Act. That act
requires banks to make loans to minorities, residents of inner
cities, farmers and others who have historically had trouble
getting credit.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said on Thursday night that the president
still intended to veto the legislation unless major changes were
made on the provisions in the Community Reinvestment Act.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those provisions, there was broad optimism on Thursday
that Congress was nearing completion on legislation that would
significantly reshape the nation's financial services industry.
</P>
<P>
   For years, a central stumbling block to overhauling the system
has been an arcane regulatory turf fight between the Treasury
Department's Comptroller of the Currency, which supervises
nationally chartered banks, and the Fed, which oversees bank
holding companies. By allowing insurers, bankers and investment
bankers to enter each other's business, any new legislation would
have to prescribe a corporate structure for the new financial
conglomerates, and as such, would ultimately dictate which agency
had primacy.
</P>
<P>
   The debate traces its roots to the establishment of the Federal
Reserve in 1913, and the tension that followed between the Fed and
the executive branch over both of the banks and the carrying out of
economic policy.
</P>
<P>
   The issue now has no practical significance for either consumers
or most banks. But it has been an enduring struggle between two of
Washington's power centers. The squabbling between a long line of
Treasury secretaries and Fed chairmen had inevitably stalled any
efforts at trying to eliminate the legislation adopted during the
Great Depression and later that has limited the cross-ownership of
banks, insurers and investment banks.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed wanted financial service conglomerates to keep their
banking, insurance and securities functions separate and under the
umbrella of a holding company. The Treasury proposed giving banking
companies the option of organizing financial service companies as
operating subsidiaries of the parent company.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury maintained that it needed to play a big role in
bank oversight so that the executive branch could carry out
economic policy. But over the years officials at the Fed had two
replies.
</P>
<P>
   One was that the central bank would be unable to carry out
monetary policy without some control over a large portion of the
banks. Greenspan also maintained that financial conglomerates
should organize under a holding company so as to prevent the banks
from using certain government subsidies to their advantage as they
expand into new areas like investment banking and insurance. Those
subsidies include deposit insurance backed by the federal
government, access to credit through the discount window and a
Federal clearinghouse.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement brokered a few hours after midnight on Thursday
morning by Summers and Greenspan is as complex as you would expect
to get from the two economic engineers and Ph.D.'s.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said that under the compromise, both
agencies would continue to play significant roles in overseeing the
nation's banks and emerging financial conglomerates. The deal
provides for operating subsidiaries of banks to underwrite
securities. After five years, a subsidiary could also engage in
merchant banking activities if jointly approved by the Federal
Reserve and the Treasury. Banks interested in insurance
underwriting and real estate development would have to set up
separate affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also imposes certain other financial safeguards
intended to protect the banking components of a financial
conglomerate because those units have insured deposits ultimately
backed by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement requires, for instance, that the aggregate asset
value of the financial subsidiaries of a bank not be greater than
80 percent of the bank's assets. And the equity capital in the
subsidiaries cannot be greater than 20 percent of the bank's equity
capital. Finally, the assets of all the financial subsidiaries of a
bank would not be able to exceed $50 billion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
