<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 21:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7392 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     10-14 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: YANKEES FEEL THE PAIN AND GO ON  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The glare was direct and distinct, Clint Eastwood in a
pinstriped baseball suit, though it was obviously unrehearsed.
After one question, Paul O'Neill had heard enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to feel it once in a while,'' he said, ``but the
story is Boston and New York. I'm getting tired of talking about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't really have to. The sight of O'Neill earlier in the
night sliding on his back and turning over on his side told the
story about a fractured rib and a player who had talked his way
into Game 1 of the American League Championship Series Wednesday
night. O'Neill made the catch on Troy O'Leary's sinking,
sixth-inning liner in the Yankees' 4-3 victory, turned over on his
side, his rugged face a contorted mask.
</P>
<P>
   He picked himself up, stiffly and slowly. A stadium full of
Yankee fans let him know they appreciated the effort, felt his
pain. Later, both he and Derek Jeter made a point of saying we
shouldn't make too much of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he wasn't going to play hard,'' Jeter rationalized, ``he
wouldn't have put himself in the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   There is the rare subject in sports that doesn't require too
much talk. We can see for ourselves that some athletes play when
their bodies say don't. Some athletes don't. Some make an attempt
when they're not feeling well and proceed to not run fast enough to
suit the critics. But those who make millions of dollars are never
more publicly hailed than when they drag their aching bodies across
the big-game landscape, and when they win.
</P>
<P>
   We have seen Paul O'Neill's sixth-inning grimace on other faces
and remembered them with a fondness unmatched. However long he
waited to test his bad back, Pedro Martinez pitched himself into
Red Sox lore in Cleveland Monday night. A wincing Kirk Gibson
struck the supreme World Series pose hitting his mind-bending home
run in 1988. Michael Jordan a couple of years ago, sick to his
stomach during the finals in Salt Lake City, was never more
unearthly and human at the same time. Pete Sampras serving an ace
in a U.S. Open match when he appeared more likely to faint was
never more appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   As a kid, I remember reading in the newspaper that Mickey Mantle
had bled right through his uniform during the 1961 World Series. It
is an image, a young boy's sense of true heroism, that has endured
for 38 years and more than a few less flattering Mantle tales.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill didn't bleed, didn't hit a home run, didn't get the ball
out of the infield in five at-bats. Had the Yankees lost, one of
the post-game questions Joe Torre would surely have heard was why
he let O'Neill convince him he could play at all.
</P>
<P>
   Torre could have talked himself into a healthier outfield
situation, but he is loyal to the veterans who have helped him win
here and he also seems to sense that vulnerability has been and
remains a most appealing and effective staple of his Yankee teams.
They have a payroll escalating toward $100 million. They won more
overall games than any team in history last year. They are owned by
a man who considers failure to be everything but the ultimate goal.
Yet, the impression is that rooting for these Yankees is not like
rooting for U.S. Steel.
</P>
<P>
   You start with the manager, a cancer patient last spring, and
his 68-year-old bench coach, Don Zimmer, limping through the season
and bouncing up from the recent dugout shot he took to the ear. Go
through the lineup, and there is Scott Brosius dealing with the
trauma of burying his father, while Chuck Knoblauch's father
battles Alzheimer's and the second baseman struggles with his own
throwing dysfunction.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Pettitte's father had open-heart surgery and the pitcher
feared he would be traded out of New York in the middle of the
summer. Roger Clemens was one confused future Hall of Famer for
much of the season. Monday night's designated hitter, Chili Davis,
is contemplating his last season after 19 in the major leagues.
Thursday night's designated hitter, Darryl Strawberry, took another
wrong turn in his life following his own cancer scare. Thursday
night's starting pitcher, David Cone, was trying to nurse his
well-worn right shoulder through one more post-season night.
</P>
<P>
   The franchise has had a long tradition of greatness mixed with
tragedy, but this Yankee team has carved its own niche for public
professionalism amid personal pain.
</P>
<P>
   So Paul O'Neill, without another word, picked up his glove again
Wednesday night and trotted out to right field for Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kid gives everything he's got out there,'' Red Sox
Manager Jimy Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Some kid, at the advanced baseball age of 36. But that's the way
he made people feel. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
