<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN AGAINST ALL ODDS, THE METS STILL BELIEVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BBN-BRAVES, BBN-CHASS-COLUMN) 
(mk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York Mets owner Fred Wilpon accompanied manager
Bobby Valentine on the field for Thursday's workout at Shea Stadium
and then made his way around the diamond, shaking hands and patting
backs in a conspicuous show of support for his team.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, with the Mets down by 0-2 to the Atlanta Braves in
the National League Championship Series, the players probably wish
Wilpon had a tank or two he could lend them so they could try to
make some sort of dent in the Braves' machine that is threatening
to flatten the Mets. The Mets' charter flight from Atlanta got in
so early Thursday morning that Valentine slept in his office rather
than drive home to Connecticut. Valentine said he slept just fine,
but you have to wonder.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have lost 11 of 14 games against the Braves this
season, and it says something about how dire their predicament is.
Even with Games 3 and 4 and a potential Game 5 at home, the players
use the recent debacle that nearly short-circuited their run to the
playoffs _ the bleakest moment of the season _ as a reason to
believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last bit of the season will help us because we went
through a tough stretch and we were able to turn it around,'' John
Olerud said. ``We know we can persevere even when things don't look
good.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are some glaring differences between now and then,
then being three weeks ago. When the Mets had lost eight of nine _
including five to the Braves _ to nearly scuttle their playoff
chances, they had the opportunity to pull out of their offensive
tailspin and begin a five-game winning streak against the Pirates,
who were essentially sporting a Class AAA lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Mets will have to pull out of their slide and win four
of the next five games against a team they have not beaten twice in
a row all season and against an all-star pitching rotation that, in
eight face-to-face meetings over the last three weeks, has held the
heart of the Mets' lineup _ Olerud, Mike Piazza and Robin Ventura _
to an astonishing 14 for 93 (.150) at the plate. Piazza admitted
Thursday that the Mets may be guilty of trying to get everything
back with one swing and thus overswinging, a symptom of pressing
that was also on display during the regular-season free fall.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, contrary to all rational thought, the Mets insist there
is hope. Wilpon gleefully recalled that the Mets were down by 0-2
to the Red Sox in the 1986 World Series before prevailing with a
few miraculous moments _ anyone remember Bill Buckner? _ that might
still make anything the Mets could pull off this weekend look
pedestrian. More recently, the Mets beat up on Greg Maddux and
Randy Johnson within the last two weeks and Arizona had beaten the
Mets seven of nine times in the regular season, but could manage
just one victory in the three-of-five-game division series.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you looked at it based on past performance, the
Diamondbacks should have won that series,'' Olerud said. ``The same
is true of this series. Based on past performance, the Braves
should win this series. It's not like we've gotten blown out. We've
played them well. It's discouraging to keep coming up just short.
Everybody believes we can get it turned around and we're that close
to beating these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in looking for the bright side as the losses to the
Braves keep piling up, it is this: With the exception of one 16-0
loss in July, no Mets' loss to the Braves was by more than six runs
and eight of the 11 losses were by three or fewer runs. And on
Friday night, the Mets have Al Leiter, who has pitched superbly in
four of the biggest and most pressure-packed games of the season: a
victory at Yankee Stadium to snap an eight-game losing streak the
day after three coaches were fired; the victory over Atlanta on
Sept. 29 to break the seven-game losing streak; the one-game
playoff victory over Cincinnati to clinch the wild card and,
finally, the victory over the Diamondbacks that sent the Mets to
the NLCS.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like every inning we've played we've had a chance,''
Valentine said of the Braves. ``I think things eventually even out.
Balls that hit the foul pole miss the foul pole. Against the
Diamondbacks we had the bases loaded and hit it over the fence and
it turned. We haven't had that turn in this series yet. It's not
like there's a defeatist attitude and we're up against an immovable
object. We've been pushing a long time and it's moving slowly. When
it starts moving, then sometimes it's an unstoppable motion.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Mets' clubhouse opened to reporters Thursday, Piazza
was slouched as comfortably on a sofa as if he were in his own
living room, watching a baseball highlight show that spent plenty
of time spotlighting the Mets' improbable and fairy-tale surge into
the postseason and then their destruction of Arizona. There was the
wild pitch that allowed Melvin Mora to score to beat Pittsburgh and
the domination of the Reds and Edgardo Alfonzo's grand slam and
Todd Pratt's home run.
</P>
<P>
   As various Mets arrived and hooted at their favorite moments, it
was a warm reminder that the Mets have been in much worse
predicaments before and, like a still-beloved New York team that
waited until next year season after season, they somehow prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take our team over their team every day,'' Piazza said of
the Braves. ``I think a lot of people would agree with me. I look
back to when the Dodgers finally beat the Yankees in 1955 after,
what, 10 times trying? People say that's no comparison _ there's
more money in the game now, the guys are different. The Braves are
that sort of monkey you have to get off your back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 2202EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0454 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7411 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-RAMSEY-PERSPECTIVE15-     10-14 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMSEY-PERSPECTIVE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Why Ramsey slaying rivets America
 &HT;    By Jay Croft and Craig Schneider
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ More than 600 American children younger than 9 were
murdered in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Only one is familiar to the whole nation.
</P>
<P>
   The slaying of JonBenet Ramsey was a rock-solid sensation from
the start and elevated the 6-year-old beauty to the realm of
iconic, one-name celebrities such as Cher or Madonna, Jackie or
Diana.
</P>
<P>
   Tiny-tot pageant winner found brutally murdered in her family's
mansion the day after Christmas. Millionaire businessman and former
beauty queen for parents. Perversely compelling videotape of the
perky little girl cavorting in makeup and costumes like a
20-year-old showgirl. A suggestion of sexual abuse. Police
suspicion clouding the parents. The couple's nationally televised
plea for help finding the killer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The facts were absolutely the stuff of which high drama is
made, and high tragedy,'' said Christopher Mueller, a law professor
at the University of Colorado in Boulder. ``It has all the
ingredients of a media story. It was destined to be just as big as
the O.J. Simpson case.''
</P>
<P>
   Even now, after the district attorney sent a grand jury home and
said no one has been charged in JonBenet's death, the mystery
remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to know why,'' said Bruce Howell, 57, of
Raleigh, N.C., among the audience watching the taping of a CNN show
on the subject Thursday in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants justice,'' said his friend Faye Perry, 50, of
Zebulon, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado Gov. Bill Owens, as he considers appointing a special
prosecutor to investigate, recognizes the magnitude of this mystery
_ as a criminal case and a national story. ``It has all the makings
of a mystery,'' Owens said. ``And I just wish it was fiction, but
it's true.''
</P>
<P>
   Even friends of John and Patsy Ramsey _ who now live in Atlanta,
where JonBenet was born and buried _ understand what makes the
horrible event enduring news, piquing reporters from the tabloids
as well as The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone (from the national media) who wasn't there (in Boulder
this week) would be a fool,'' said Barbara Sanders, 56, of Sun
Lake, Ariz., who became close to Patsy Ramsey when they shared the
trauma of ovarian cancer. Standing across from more than 100
reporters and a cluster of TV satellite trucks Thursday, Phil
Robertson expressed his disgust that the case remains such a draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's absurd,'' said the 65-year-old Boulder resident.
``I wonder how many journalists are over in Pakistan. That's a real
story.''
</P>
<P>
   But as many Americans remained gripped by the bizarre chain of
events and speculation, with countless Internet postings and Web
sites as evidence of the near-obsession with the case, the
possibility of an indictment was clearly big news.
</P>
<P>
   Among the dimensions that have fueled the story for so long are
questions about the competence of police and prosecutors, said Bob
Steele of the Poynter Institute, a national center for media
studies in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Journalism has an obligation to report that meaningfully and
fairly,'' he said. ``You will find cases of children who die at
home, and a good number of them are unsolved. There is that kind of
continuing interest in that by the public. We should not be ashamed
to have an interest in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Ermini of the the National Center for Missing and Exploited
Children agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see that as exploitation, but I can see where interest
is generated,'' Ermini said. ``I'm not disturbed by (the focus on
this case) at all. It's important that the general public knows
that these types of incidents occur.''
</P>
<P>
   National reporters in Boulder said the TV-friendly nature of
JonBenet's videotaped life gave the story impact. The video images
of the girl dancing and singing, dolled up for the various
competitions she entered during her brief life, stayed in our
minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came into everybody's home,'' said the Chicago Tribune's
Maurice Possley. ``Now, even if you're in Chicago, people follow
this case, and there was a feeling that if there was any
resolution, we should be here.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN field producer Betty Anderson, who also worked the O.J.
Simpson trial, said, ``When you mix all that together, the prurient
interest is what draws the American audience, and nobody wants to
admit it.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times' Michael Janofsky added race to the litany.
``Mainstream media tends to put a minority face on crime,'' he
said. ``But when the face of crime is white, we always seem to be
surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   People magazine writer Vickie Bane said the story was catapulted
to national prominence only after the Ramseys gave an interview to
CNN on Jan. 1, 1997, a week after their daughter was found
strangled in the basement of their home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Ramseys helped create, early on, some of their own
media,'' Bane said. ``They might have spoken to the police first''
if they wanted to keep a lower profile.
</P>
<P>
   In death, JonBenet found fame ``bigger than her mother ever
dreamed,'' Bane said. ``It's very sad when you consider that this
little child has been on the cover of People magazine four times.
Can you imagine the celebrities who would covet that?
</P>
<P>
   ``And what we've lost in all of this is that she was just a
little girl. I think in all this, she has become a character, and
she was a real, live, breathing little girl who's not here
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
