<SLUG> BC-BABBITT-INQUIRY-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BABBITT, A WEARYING EXONERATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Wis.)  (th) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By the standards of some recent independent counsel
investigations, the 19-month inquiry of Interior Secretary Bruce
Babbitt was relatively quick, leak-free and legally painless _
ending as it did with the prosecutor's announcement on Wednesday
that no charges would be brought against Babbitt or anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel, Carol Elder Bruce, said in an interview
Thursday that she had handled the case like the dozens of
corruption cases she handled as a federal prosecutor for the U.S.
attorney's office in the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I treated it as I believe the Justice Department would handle
any significant corruption case,'' she said. ``The guiding rule of
the office was that we were focusing on the events and the
allegations.''
</P>
<P>
   While her approach might seem swift when measured against that
of other independent counsels, for Babbitt the road to exoneration
was long and rocky. And, to his supporters, exoneration came only
after an investigation that never would have even reached a grand
jury _ before which Babbitt testified for two days _ if it had not
been for the independent counsel law.
</P>
<P>
   That law died unceremoniously in June after two decades of
controversial inquiries involving high-ranking officials from both
parties.
</P>
<P>
   Since Ms. Bruce's announcement that she had uncovered
insufficient evidence to warrant charges against Babbitt in his
handling of an Indian gambling project, the secretary has not
commented on the decision except for a brief statement from his
office expressing ``gratitude'' but not surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and associates said Thursday, however, that Babbitt, a
former two-term Arizona governor who began his tenure at the
Interior Department as one of the most accomplished members of the
Cabinet, had been wearied and wounded by the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   More broadly, Babbitt's case seemed to raise the question of
whether he was a victim of a phenomenon that he described in an
interview last month as the ``permanent culture of the
criminalization of political differences.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bruce's inquiry centered on the question of whether Babbitt
committed perjury in congressional testimony in 1997 about an
Interior Department decision to reject an application by three
Indian tribes that wanted to operate a gambling casino in Hudson,
Wis.
</P>
<P>
   The perjury issues were coupled with allegations of possible
political influence-buying, in large measure because several tribes
that opposed the gambling permit, and benefited from the Interior
Department's denial of it, later contributed $230,000 to the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Before deciding that those allegations were unsupported by the
evidence, Ms. Bruce and her staff interviewed 450 witnesses and
examined more than 630,000 pages of documents. Investigators also
evaluated issues like the relationship between the Interior
Department and the White House and how the Democratic Party sought
soft-money contributions for party-building purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bruce would not discuss the details of the Babbitt case, or
her views of the evidence, or even whether her appointment was
necessary. Despite Babbitt's discomfort, however, her handling of
the case contrasted sharply with the seemingly endless inquiries by
some other independent counsels.
</P>
<P>
   For example, at last count, Ms. Bruce, who was appointed in
March 1998, had spent only $3.9 million as of last March 31,
according to most recent figures compiled by the Congressional
Research Service. That is much less than some other independent
prosecutors have spent while investigating other Clinton Cabinet
officers with mixed results.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Smaltz, who was appointed in March 1994, had spent $21
million by March 31 in an inquiry into the activities of former
Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy, the research service said. That
inquiry ended last December with the acquittal of Espy on
corruption charges.
</P>
<P>
   David M. Barrett, who was appointed in May 1995, spent $10
million in his inquiry into former Housing Secretary Henry
Cisneros. The investigation ended last month when Cisneros pleaded
guilty to a single misdemeanor of lying to federal agents about the
extent of payments to a former mistress.
</P>
<P>
   In part, Ms. Bruce's focus was built in by the narrow charter
for her inquiry that was drafted by the Justice Department.
Republican critics complained that Attorney General Janet Reno had
kept the focus narrow to prevent Ms. Bruce from turning her case
into a wider investigation of campaign finance issues.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bruce said Thursday that her charter from the Justice
Department allowed her to adequately investigate the Babbitt case.
``From our perspective, if we felt it was necessary to get a
broader mandate to get to the bottom of our case we would have
sought that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Sept. 8 with Diane Rehm, whose program is
broadcast on public radio stations around the country, Babbitt said
that, in light of his experience, he now advised students that ``if
you're going to be in a high-profile position, the first thing
you'd better do is have some lawyer's insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   The secretary added: ``The worst moments were when I got hauled
up before a Senate investigating committee, then a House
investigating committee, then the Justice Department, then the FBI,
then a special prosecutor. And there's kind of a lynch mob
mentality in the press, to be frank. There wasn't any kind of a
presumption of innocence; it was a presumption of guilt. But the
system ultimately does work. The justice system does work. But it
wasn't pleasant.''
</P>
</TEXT>
