<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL COLUMN: METS' BIG THREE ARE SCARY PUSHOVERS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Maybe no one should be surprised that John Olerud,
Mike Piazza and Robin Ventura are not hitting Atlanta Braves
pitchers in the National League Championship Series. The men who
make up the middle of the New York Mets' lineup did not hit the
Braves' pitchers during the season, either.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud, Piazza and Ventura have a grand total of 1 hit in 21
times at bat as the Mets have lost the first two games in the NL
series, which resumes with Game 3 Friday night at Shea Stadium.
That embarrassing achievement has reduced their collective 1999
batting average against the Braves to .173 from .194. They hit .309
against everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   As an indication of their paucity of productivity, they have a
slugging percentage of .220 against the Braves. Against the rest of
the league? It's .541.
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder that the Mets have lost 11 of the 14 games the
teams have played this year? Is there any reason to think the
outcome of the next two games, or more, if the Braves need more,
will be any different? Can the Mets win without the middle of their
lineup hitting?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think for long,'' Piazza said. ``We've done it before.
You just have to completely minimize your mistakes and we haven't
been doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mistakes like the manager's admittedly leaving his starting
pitcher in the game a batter or two too long, batters' bunting when
they are not supposed to be bunting, pinch-hitters' being used or
not used at questionable times. A few hits from the middle third of
the batting order could negate such mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to try to sugarcoat it,'' Piazza said Thursday
after working on his problems in batting practice. ``We're just not
swinging the bat well. There's nothing else you can say. Maybe it's
poor pitch selection, maybe some mechanical flaws, which we've been
working on today.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, who missed the last two games of the division series
with a stiff, swollen left thumb, has no hits in seven times at bat
in this series. Three times he batted with runners on base, twice
with runners in scoring position. In losses by scores of 4-2 and
4-3, a hit here or there could have made a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe we can turn it around,'' the catcher said. ``A
couple key hits. We've been getting guys in scoring position. We
just haven't been able to push them across. They've been getting
timely hitting from everybody on that ball club. When you have guys
on first and third and nobody out, you have to push a run across.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventura has failed to hit in six at-bats while Olerud has a
single in eight at-bats. His single moved a runner to third, from
where he scored on a Piazza groundout, but Olerud failed to hit
with three other runners in scoring position. Collectively, the
three have one hit in nine at-bats with runners on base and one in
seven with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura suffered a strained right shoulder when he was picked
off at second base in a division series game, but he said the
shoulder was not affecting his hitting. What is? ``Poor swings,''
he said. ``Give credit to their pitching,'' the third baseman
added. ``You'd like to have better swings, but sometimes that's the
result of good pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta manager Bobby Cox said of his pitchers: ``We're hitting
good spots and they're pitching their game, that's all. No magic.''
</P>
<P>
   Olerud said he thought he had had some good at-bats in spite of
appearances. ``I just haven't gotten hits on them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, who did not hit well in his previous two postseason
series with Los Angeles, said he believed he was aware of what his
recent problems have been and worked on them Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's bad mechanics that creates bad swings which
doesn't translate into base hits,'' he said. ``I think I've been
pulling off the ball. That's the first sign that you don't trust
yourself. I'm trying to cover both sides of the plate. I've been
thinking about too many pitches. Instead of just picking out a
pitch out overthe plate where I know I can get it and put a good
swing on it, I'm thinking pitch away, pitch down, pitch in, pitch
up. I've always been a zone hitter. If a pitch is in my zone, it
doesn't matter what it is; I know I can hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza related a story he heard about Sparky Anderson making out
his lineup for a game in the 1984 World Series. ``A friend
suggested he should put this guy in because he was due,'' Piazza
said. ``Sparky said, `The World Series is for people who are doing,
not for people who are due.''' Piazza paused for a moment, then
said: ``I believe eventually I'm going to be doing. But for now I'm
due, as are a few guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The test of the trio's timeliness will come Friday night when
they face Tom Glavine, the left-hander in the Braves' rotation. In
their careers, they all have hit Glavine better than they have the
other Braves starters: Piazza .372, Olerud .364, Ventura .333.
Piazza, in fact, hit a two-run home run against Glavine three weeks
ago, and eighth-inning singles by Piazza and Ventura knocked him
out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   But Olerud cautioned that past performance does not guarantee
anything. ``I think Glavine can be a real tough pitcher and is a
tough pitcher,'' the first baseman said. ``I don't think the past
has a whole lot to do with this game tomorrow. It's a new game. We
have to take advantage of the at-bats we have.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
