<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-ALLSTARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYZE THIS: INSTITUTIONAL INVESTOR NAMES ITS ALL-STARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Exultant cries of ``We're No. 2'' and ``I'm No. 3''
rang out on Wall Street Thursday as hundreds of people who would
never be confused with competitive athletes learned that they had
been deemed ``all-Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Institutional Investor magazine published the results of its
annual popularity contest for stock analysts, instantly inducing
daydreams about even bigger bonuses among those who made the list
and grumbles from those left off it. In the research departments of
securities firms, no other event creates as much tension as the
release of the ``I.I. rankings'' for one simple reason: money.
</P>
<P>
   It is the Kentucky Derby of the analysts' year, and just as in
the Derby, you can cash in if you win, place or show.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this market, an I.I. ranking will vault an analyst into the
million-plus category,'' said Joan Zimmerman, executive vice
president at G.Z. Stephens, a Wall Street recruiting firm. ``If his
incumbent employer doesn't pay him at least $1 million, someone
else will come along and snatch him away for that amount.''
</P>
<P>
   For each of the last 28 years, Institutional Investor has polled
managers of mutual funds and pension funds to find out which
analysts they considered the best at their jobs. Then, in its
November issue, the magazine publishes its All-America Research
Team, a ranking of the top three analysts and some runners-up in
each industry sector and a tally of the totals for each firm.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. claimed the most spots on the
list, with 56, its fifth year on top. Merrill nosed out a
hard-charging Salomon Smith Barney, which had 55 spots on the list,
up from 46 and fourth place in 1998. Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP;
Co. and Goldman Sachs Group, which tied for second place last year,
wound up third and fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The poll's importance has definitely increased in the last
three to five years,'' said Kevin McCaffrey, director of United
States equity research at Salomon Smith Barney, part of Citigroup.
``That's because corporate America is paying executives more in
stock and stock-related incentives, and they are more interested in
what the top analysts have to say.''
</P>
<P>
   But many people in the stock research business say they think
entirely too much weight has been placed on the poll, leading
analysts and their firms to resort to tricks to improve their
standings.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts have been caught cheating, filling out ballots for
themselves. Others have been caught in tugs-of-war over their
allegiances.
</P>
<P>
   For example, consider what happened to Alex Cena last year.
Cena, an analyst of wireless-phone companies, left Bear Stearns to
join Salomon Smith Barney last summer, several weeks before
Institutional Investor published its 1998 survey.
</P>
<P>
   But Bear Stearns tried to claim credit for Cena's No. 1 ranking
anyway, contending that he left the firm after the magazine's
cutoff for publication, according to people who were involved in
the dispute. To settle the issue, Cena produced a dated receipt for
the movement of his belongings from Bear Stearns' office to
Salomon's, these people said, and the magazine credited Cena to his
new employer.
</P>
<P>
   The big role the poll plays has not gone unnoticed outside the
industry. The Wall Street Journal has been compiling its own
ranking of analysts for several years, measuring them by the
accuracy of their picks.
</P>
<P>
   Now another competitor looms: TheStreet.com, the online
information site. In the summer, it hired away Laurie Meisler, who
had long overseen Institutional Investor's poll. Ms. Meisler, who
has lured some of her former co-workers from the magazine, plans to
start publishing competing rankings early next year.
</P>
<P>
   The research director at one investment bank, weary of the
emotions the annual publication of the poll arouses, said, ``We
need another poll like we need a hole in the head.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
