<HEADER>
A7420 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-RAMSEY15-COX     10-14 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMSEY15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Authorities say they won't give up on Ramsey case
 &HT;    By Craig Schneider
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOULDER, Colo. _ Boulder District Attorney Alex Hunter vowed to
continue investigating the JonBenet murder case Thursday, and noted
that the girl's parents have not been removed from investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to quit on this case,'' said Hunter during an
afternoon news conference. He added that John and Patsy Ramsey
``have not been eliminated from the investigation ... They're not
excluded.''
</P>
<P>
   Boulder Police Chief Mark Beckner acknowledged that John and
Patsy Ramsey remained under the ``umbrella of suspicion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The status of this investigation has not changed so
significantly as to change that characterization,'' Beckner said.
</P>
<P>
   The remark infuriated John Ramsey's brother, Jeff Ramsey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's absolutely ridiculous,'' said Jeff Ramsey, who
lives in metro Atlanta. ``John and Patsy Ramsey have been
investigated for three years. What's it going to take to get
Boulder authorities to see they are barking up the wrong tree?''
</P>
<P>
   He said he hopes Colorado Gov. Bill Owens, who is mulling the
appointment of a special prosecutor, does so. ``That would be fine,
if he helps us solve this crime,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Owens, who got only a mild show of support from Hunter, expects
to decide in a week or so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to second-guess the governor,'' he said. ``We are
interested in the pursuit of truth. If he can assist in that, we
won't stand in the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter, speaking to 100 reporters gathered at the Boulder
Justice Center, said Thursday he has an ``aching heart'' regarding
the lack of an indictment, but that he felt no sense of failure.
``We find no reason to give up heart,'' said Hunter. ``We may never
get there, but we're not going to stop trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckner took a more subdued tone on the future of the
investigation, stressing that while the case will remain an open,
ongoing probe, ``There's not all that much to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Police will probably not be working on the case daily, he said,
and the ``Ramsey Room,'' established for the case, probably will be
assigned to another use.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Hunter nor Beckner would say whether the grand jury of
12 Boulder residents ever voted on any indictments, or whether they
had written a report on its findings.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Hunter announced only that the grand jury had
completed its work, adding, ``Yet I must report to you that I and
my prosecution task force believe we do not have sufficient
evidence to warrant the filing of charges against anyone who has
been investigated at the present time.''
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury was convened 13 months ago when the investigation
became bogged down in disputes between the police and district
attorney's office. At Thursday's 40-minute news conference, Hunter
referred to those kinds of problems, saying, ``We're all human
beings, and I've certainly made mistakes in this case. We've had
some people in this case who got off track, lost objectivity, and
forgot that their charge is to follow the evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   JonBenet, a 6-year-old star of child beauty pageants, was found
beaten and strangled the day after Christmas in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Her father said he discovered the body in the basement of the
family's Boulder home in the afternoon, about seven hours after his
wife said she found a ransom note demanding $118,000 for the girl's
safe return.
</P>
<P>
   Beckner discounted critics who say the case was ruined when
police allowed John Ramsey to search the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say that mistakes have made this an unsolvable case is not
accurate,'' the police chief said. ``Circumstances and evidence
that raise questions for us today are not the result of a
contaminated crime scene. Yes there are things we should have done
differently.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the grand jury process helped police advance the
case. ``But all the pieces have to come together, and we do not
have a puzzle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Beckner would not say whether he thought the evidence
warranted any indictments.
</P>
<P>
   While the two law enforcement figures insist the case will
continue, William Pizzi, a Colorado University law professor and
former federal prosecutor, said a grand jury coming up empty-handed
most often spells the death knell on a case. ``Sure the case will
remain open, but I don't expect much to come forward,'' he said.
``After all, what else could they have. This is the end of the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on the two officials' comments Thursday, Christopher
Mueller, also a Colorado University law professor, commented:
``It's very hard for a public official to say they are giving up.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of his news conference, Beckner was asked by a
reporter whether the case required new evidence to be solved.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got some, we'll certainly take it,'' responded the
police chief.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
