<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-NOTES15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bad-call fallout: Umps must work as `a team'
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Umpire Rick Reed's midnight confession early Thursday
that he blew a critical call in Game 1 raised two questions. First,
why aren't all umpires similarly frank in the face of a blown call?
And how often is Reed going to hear about it from Red Sox fans
Saturday in Boston, when he calls the plate in Game 3?
</P>
<P>
   Jimy Williams had another question: Why didn't Reed ask for help
on what might have been the most critical play of the game?
</P>
<P>
   ``They (the umpires) are a team,'' said the Boston manager.
``They work together. I don't know a lot about umpiring but I do
know the closer you are to a play, the tougher it is to see
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Reed who called Boston's Jose Offerman out at second base
in the top of the 10th when it was clear both before and after the
replay that New York second baseman Chuck Knoblauch dropped Scott
Brosius' throw. Instead of two men on and no out, the Red Sox had
one out with a man on first, which changed quickly on a double-play
ball by Brian Daubach.
</P>
<P>
   Late after the game, Reed said, ``I thought he had possession
before he dropped the ball. After we went in and looked at the
tape, we decided that wasn't the case. As an umpire, it was my job
to get it right. I didn't. You feel bad about it. I feel awful.''
</P>
<P>
   A day later, Williams gave a five-minute address on the issue,
blaming his own ``brain lapse'' for not asking Reed to check with
his fellow umpires on the call. During the League Divisional
Series, Williams watched Cleveland's Travis Fryman awarded a
disputed home run in the second inning of Game 5 after the crew
conferred.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not mad and I'm not saying we would have scored,''
Williams said. ``But when I think about what (ump) Jimmy Joyce told
me in Cleveland, `We just want to get it right,' whether it's in a
playoff game or the 85th game of the season, it shouldn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was some kind of process,'' New York manager Joe
Torre said, ``that would allow the umpires to help each other in a
lot of different plays, I have no objection to that. I've seen that
in a lot of instances.''
</P>
<P>
   Just not in Wednesday night's game. And before anyone started
talking about instant replay, Williams said this: ``I think the
human element is beautiful. Maybe the game is a lot like life, so
why put something like (replay) in there?''
</P>
<P>
   MINDING MARIANO
</P>
<P>
   Torre doesn't like to use closer Mariano Rivera on a two-inning
basis as he did in Game 1, but the Yankees have been able to twice
this postseason, thanks to the stretched playoff schedule that
features off-days three times a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think once he realized that he didn't have to strike people
out,'' Torre said, ``and (pitching coach) Mel (Stottlemyre) worked
with him on the different type of fastballs he throws, he has been
a lot easier to go to consistently because he doesn't use many
pitches. To me, 22 or 23 (Wednesday) for two innings was pretty
damn good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Again, I never got out there thinking two innings but with an
off-day (Friday) and what happened in the Division Series with the
every-other-day scenario, it's easier to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivera went into Game 2 with five scoreless postseason innings,
which, when added to the last 28 regular season appearances, ran
his scoreless streak to 35 2/3 innings without allowing a run. His
career postseason ERA dropped further to 0.45, the lowest by anyone
with a minimum of 30 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ETC.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch had precautionary X-rays taken of his left instep
after being struck by a foul ball while hitting in the ninth in
Game 1. X-rays were negative. ... Red Sox health report: Pedro
Martinez has reported no stiffness after pitching Monday and is on
schedule to start Saturday. Reliever Rich Garces was not available
Thursday due to a muscle discomfort under his right arm pit. ...
Brosius finished one double shy Wednesday night of becoming the
first place to hit for the cycle in the postseason. He led off the
ninth needing to double off Boston's Derek Lowe and struck out ...
One of the most unlikely Red Sox fans is rooting for Boston. ``I'm
pulling for the Red Sox,'' Babe Ruth's daughter, Julia Ruth
Stevens, 82, said from her winter home in Sun City, Ariz. ``It's
the end of the century, and I think it is high time (they won).''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
