<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK'S NEMESIS, ROCKER, HAS SOME NICE THINGS TO SAY ABOUT THE
METS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By STEVE POPPER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A few of the Atlanta Braves players were already
scattered around the field at Shea Stadium for Thursday night's
workout when one player rushed out of the tunnel and onto the
field. The jersey was familiar, the number 49 on the back with
Rocker emblazoned above the number. But the Fu Manchu on the face
did not match.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Klesko, the Braves hard-hitting left fielder, had swapped
jerseys with reliever John Rocker, a move that was funny Thursday
night, but might be a little risky Friday when the Mets and Braves
take the field for Game 3 of the National League Championship
Series. With the Mets limping back home facing a 2-0 deficit in the
four-of-seven-game series, Rocker has provided more fire for the
fans than the play of the hometown team has.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him I wouldn't do it tomorrow,'' Klesko said. ``I told
him if I survived for a few minutes, it would be safer for him to
come out. Do they check for guns and ammunition here?
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him I'd go out there for him to see how it was. I'm
actually protecting our save guy. We've got a couple of first
basemen. It was just to have some fun, stay loose. I just think
going out and having fun, there is so much pressure anyway, keeping
these guys loose is the main thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker, who has engaged in a back-and-forth dialogue that has
made him a target, not only of the fans, but also of Mets Manager
Bobby Valentine, was not so lighthearted about the debate. He has
been an object of scorn by the fans, particularly in the three-game
series at Shea during the final week of the regular season. But he
has managed to overcome it by dominating the New York batters.
</P>
<P>
   When reporters surrounded his locker after the workout, Rocker
did not want to continue any of the commentary on New York fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we get started, if you don't have any constructive
questions about the series, which is the only important thing, then
I've got nothing to say,'' he said. ``I'll talk about the series
and that's it. I know a good many out there think I'm just kidding,
and they'll ask me some questions about the fans anyway. If you do,
I'll cuss you out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to defuse the situation. I think it's funny.
This is the first time the Mets have made the playoffs in 11 years
and all you care about is comments we say about the fans. I don't
know, it seems to me there's a bigger story there, two very good
teams on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   And Rocker did stick to his word throughout most of the
interview, expressing respect for a Mets team that he believes is
not out of this series yet, and he even had kind words for hitters
like Mets third baseman Robin Ventura, whom Rocker has struck out
the five times he has faced him. He did manage to stick in a dig at
the fans he knows will be waiting to boo him if he gets the call
from the bullpen on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be the same situation it was last time when I got
booed and then I struck out the side on 14 pitches,'' he said. ``I
find it more fun, more enjoyable for myself, to pitch in front of a
hostile crowd that's jeering me as opposed to one that's cheering
me. I get a lot more fired up when the situation is like that. It's
just the kind of personality I've got.''
</P>
<P>
   With the emotional reliever expected to serve as a lightning rod
for the Mets fans, the rest of the Braves were actually excited
about the prospect of playing in front of a sold-out stadium that
they expected to be loud, for better or worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be wild and crazy,'' said Chipper Jones, who is
probably second only to Rocker in the hearts and minds of the fans.
``It was wild and crazy up here the last week of the season and it
wasn't even the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to hear things we haven't heard before and hopefully
the guys will wear their earplugs and concentrate on the game,'' he
said. ``It can act as a motivational factor. I think most of the
guys are going to tune it out as much as they can.
</P>
<P>
   ``John is going to get booed before I do when they call the
players out, so hopefully they'll get all booed out by the time
they get to me. Somehow I doubt that though.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
