<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7434 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NY     10-14 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES AND METS ARE IN, AND THAT BRINGS OUT THE POLAR PEOPLE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I am in conflict, too.
</P>
<P>
   Why shouldn't choosing between the Yankees and the Mets be as
easy as choosing between the Beatles and the Stones, Apple and IBM,
Lancaster and York, Good and Evil? It's just brand equity. Two ball
teams.
</P>
<P>
   But no. Ever since Dr. Margaret Mead and the sports pundits who
also considered themselves anthropologists proclaimed the Yankees
and the Mets rival tribes, their fans have been made to define
themselves by the choice. When it merely leads to bar fights over
who would win a Subway Series, there is no harm done. But when
cultural, class and economic divisions are perpetuated, we have
trouble here on River Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   The anthro pop quizzes drive me nuts. Do you like opera? You're
a Yankees fan. Do you shop at Kmart? You're a Mets fan. And this is
supposed to be whether your seat is behind the dugout or behind the
right fielder. Do you call them drapes or curtains, a couch or a
sofa? From that answer, someone will be able to tell you that the
rich man you admire is either Fred Wilpon or George Steinbrenner.
Do you perceive cancer or mental illness as the frontier of health
care discussion? From that answer we know you identify with either
Joe Torre (recovering from prostate treatment) or Bobby Valentine
(reveling in mood swings). This is sick.
</P>
<P>
   And the lunch-pail versus humidor construct, polyester versus
linen, Figaro versus Count Almaviva, is basically lame. The Mets of
the '80s personified the stinking cigars of Wall Street, while
Yankee Stadium has for years been overrun with low-rent slobs.
</P>
<P>
   And not only is this lame, it also leads to the easy, dangerous
thinking that there are only two kinds of people in the world, and
the twain will never meet or merge or morph. Yea and behold, we
call these polar people, Yankees or Mets.
</P>
<P>
   So where does that leave me? I love them both. Differently.
</P>
<P>
   I was born in the Bronx, as were my father and mother, and so my
diapers were pinstripes (chalk stripes, actually, but that just
leads us back to drapes and couches). My father wasn't impressed by
Joe DiMaggio because he had grown up with the Babe.
</P>
<P>
   During my childhood in Queens, there were three major league
teams and no regional pressure. I always felt that Giant fans were
arrogant front-runners and Dodger fans were sweatily righteous, but
I did not make my choice based on rooting for the equivalent of
U.S. Steel. I always thought the Yankees were the true
outsider-immigrant-striver team. They were the best because of
merit, not because swells trooped up to the Polo Grounds or poets
found Elysium in Ebbets Field.
</P>
<P>
   And then I met the Mets on my first important out-of-town
assignment. I brought my glove to their opening spring training in
1962, which was also the first time I tried to hit major league
pitching _ actually, it was a sore-armed coach throwing batting
practice. For me, it might as well have been Whitey Ford. I have
never lost respect.
</P>
<P>
   That day, I just went to the bar and let Mets manager Casey
Stengel talk and drink me under the table. He had also been manager
of the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, three of the most interesting New York ballplayers of
my times have been both Mets and the Yankees. David Cone as a young
wise guy was one of those rich, victorious, out-of-control '80s
Mets. He was accused of flashing in the bullpen. He was an outlaw
hero of the tell-all tomes. Perfect David Cone is now an elder
statesman of the Yankees locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Strawberry, brought up before his time by the greedy
Mets, never quite fulfilled his promise (Mets' management billed
him as ``the next DiMaggio'') but he enjoyed and destroyed himself
in the garden of earthly delights. Who resurrected him? The Boss.
</P>
<P>
   And Marvelous Marv Throneberry, promoted as the quintessential
Met when the team was lionized as the worst in baseball (it was the
rebirth of irony), had come up as a Yankees bonus baby. He roamed
the outfield with the Mick, pinch-hit in the 1958 World Series.
Years later, he said: ``I kind of think of myself as a former
Yankee, not a Met. A man is always sentimental about his first
team.''
</P>
<P>
   So, you see my problem and I see yours.
</P>
<P>
   Let's leave it at this: There are only two kinds of people in
the world; those who duck foul balls and those who stand up to
catch them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
