<SLUG> BC-BBN-NOTES15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chipper Jones struggling in field, at plate
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chipper Jones is on the defensive and it has nothing
to do with Mets fans. It's his bad case of the bobbles.
</P>
<P>
   He had a late-inning error in each of the first two games of the
NLCS to put men on base in the worst of times. He has three errors
in six postseason games. When he failed to field what looked to be
a simple grounder to third by Melvin Mora in the eighth, the Mets
drew to within one run 4-3 after Edgardo Alfonzo doubled Mora in.
It took heroics by John Rocker and John Smoltz to save the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was lucky to make only one error in the first game,'' said
Jones, who had a rough time getting a grip on several balls his
way, including one on a double-play chance that cost Greg Maddux a
run. ``(Wednesday's) could have really cost us the game. I want to
prepare myself so it doesn't happen tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Hence, Thursday afternoon's digging in the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Jones took, as he described it, more groundballs during the
Braves' workout at Shea Stadium than he's taken in three years,
trying to get himself back on track defensively before Game 3
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit of inconsistent hops, little bit of bad play
on my part,'' Jones said. ``Fielding is as much a feel thing as
hitting and when you don't feel comfortable out there, you get
yourself in trouble. ... Hopefully I'll get some better hops and
have better concentration.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as his hitting is concerned, Jones has struggled to find
a balance between how to be patient and still not miss the
occasional good pitch to hit he sees. It would seem to get even
harder with a pack of angry Mets fans ready to make his weekend
long. But hitting coach Don Baylor thinks Jones is in the perfect
setting to break out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes the arena here,'' Baylor said. ``Over there in
Yankeee Stadium, he was as locked in as I've ever seen him, even
more so than the Mets series (in Atlanta).''
</P>
<P>
   Jones was 3-for-9 in three games at Yankee Stadium with a
double, a homer, two runs scored, six walks and zero strikeouts.
That set him off on his way to a second half that made him the best
candidate for the National League MVP.
</P>
<P>
   MORE TALK
</P>
<P>
   Upon hearing about Rocker's comments after the Braves' win in
Game 2, when he said ``To hell with New York fans, they're stupid
anyway. We beat them 20 out of 26 times and they still say we
(stink),'' Mets manager Bobby Valentine said this:
</P>
<P>
   ``How many Mets fans has he met? That's kind of interesting. I
don't know (if it will come back to haunt him). He's another one
with really good ability. When you can throw 96 and throw it where
you want it and have a hook like he has, I guess it's easy to make
any comment you want to make.''
</P>
<P>
   LINEUP WATCH
</P>
<P>
   Mets left fielder Rickey Henderson, who left Game 2 with
light-headedness, was feeling well enough on Thursday to take
batting practice and had Valentine predicting he'd be OK for
tonight's game.
</P>
<P>
   That may be good news for the Braves after Henderson's
replacement, Mora, homered, reached on an error and scored two
runs. Henderson, meanwhile, is 0-for-6 in the first two games.
PRICE OF FAME
</P>
<P>
   After he hit the first of two NLCS home runs in the Braves' 4-2
win in Game 1 on Tuesday night, Eddie Perez was asked to do an
interview with ESPN on the field a while after the game.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he finished, the Braves clubhouse doors had been
locked and Perez couldn't get back in. He called his friend and the
Braves usual catcher in the limelight, Javy Lopez, on his cell
phone to see if he could let him back in the Braves' clubhouse, and
Lopez was on his way home, laughing at Perez's predicament.
Eventually, Perez called Braves security and they let him back in
the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
