<SLUG> BC-AUTO-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM REPORTS TURNAROUND ON EARNINGS IN THIRD QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Demand for pickup trucks, sport utility vehicles and
minivans helped the General Motors Corp. earn $877 million in the
third quarter, a significant turnaround from a $309 million loss in
the period a year eariler.
</P>
<P>
   The loss was caused by an expensive strike in the summer of
1998. Excluding the impact of the strike, GM's net income rose 34
percent in the third quarter compared with the period a year
earlier, on revenue of $42.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   All figures have been adjusted to reflect GM's spinoff in May of
its giant auto-parts division, Delphi Automotive Systems Inc.
</P>
<P>
   While GM has operations around the world, the largest share of
its profits came from its home market, where buyers have been
trading in their cars for hefty trucks that carry high profit
margins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly one of the big contributors here in North America
would be full-sized trucks,'' J. Michael Losh, GM's chief financial
officer, said in an interview. ``We've been running at high rates
of production and sales all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts said GM had earned high profits because
buyers were snapping up record numbers of new models from all auto
makers. ``It was good,'' said David B. Healy, an auto analyst at
Burnham Securities, of GM's third quarter. ``But it was all due to
volume increases for the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The third-quarter profit of $1.33 a diluted share, contrasting
to a loss of 52 cents a share in the period a year earlier, was on
the high end of the range of analysts' estimates. The consensus
among analysts was that GM would earn $1.24 a share, with some
expecting earnings as low as $1.15 a share and some expecting
profits as high as $1.35 a share, according to First Call, a
Boston-based investment research firm. GM shares fell 12.5 cents
Thursday, to $65.
</P>
<P>
   The company surprised analysts by piling up even more cash than
expected during the quarter. GM ended the quarter with $16.7
billion in its rainy-day fund, even after it spent $386 million
between July 1 and Wednesday buying back its stock. The company has
now bought back 63 percent of the $4 billion in stock it promised
to buy back in March 1998. Since January 1997, GM has bought back
stock worth $7.5 billion, or about 15.6 percent of its outstanding
shares.
</P>
<P>
   GM's North American automotive sales business contributed $671
million to the company's profits this quarter. Its financing and
insurance arm, the General Motors Acceptance Corp., came in
stronger than expected, adding $393 million, up from $313 million
in the corresponding period last year.
</P>
<P>
   GM's European automotive business contributed $32 million, and
together, those three units offset losses elsewhere for the
company. ``The overall results show the strength of operating as
one globally integrated company,'' said John F. Smith Jr., GM's
chairman and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   While the third-quarter automotive net margin was 1.7 percent
companywide, it was 2.3 percent in North America, still short of
the company's 5 percent goal. GM's third-quarter market share in
the United States was 28.9 percent, well up from the 24.1 percent
during the period a year earlier, when GM sales plunged because of
a strike that shuttered nearly all the company's factories for two
months. The market share remains well below the 31.7 percent GM
held just two years ago, in the third quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Even those sales are coming at a price, as GM, like most of its
competitors, offers generous rebates, discounted leases and other
incentives that crimp profits. In the third quarter, those
incentives averaged about $1,610 a vehicle, down from the $1,732 in
the third quarter last year but well up from the $992 average in
the third quarter of 1997 and more than double the $764 average in
the third quarter of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   A strike last year at two auto-parts factories cost GM $965
million after taxes in the third quarter, or $1.48 a share.
</P>
<P>
   The Hughes Electronics division lost $30 million in the third
quarter, in contrast to a $43 million profit a year earlier. The
losses came as revenue increased to $2 billion from $1.5 billion,
primarily because of the growing number of subscribers to its
DirecTV unit. While GM owns Hughes, it is traded as a separate
tracking stock. GM is evaluating whether to sell or spin off the
unit.
</P>
<P>
   GM was the first auto maker to report third-quarter results.
Other auto makers are expected to announce strong third-quarter
profits later this month. The Ford Motor Co. is scheduled to
announce its results on Monday, and the consensus among analysts is
that it will earn 85 cents a share, up from 80 cents in the third
quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler is scheduled to announce its results during the
last week of October, and analysts are expecting earnings of $1.25
a share. The company was formed in November when Daimler-Benz of
Germany bought the Chrysler Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Ford increased its dividend by 9 percent. Ford's
fourth-quarter dividend will rise 4 cents, to 50 cents a share.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
