<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-ORGERON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC'S ORGERON GETS HIS POINT ACROSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Each Monday, millions of wrestling fans watch
``The Rock'' strut before a television camera, and sooner or later,
yell his trademark slogan: ``Know your role, and shut the hell
up.''
</P>
<P>
   If USC assistant football coach Ed Orgeron could get residuals
from that comment, he might not need to work anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The Rock, aka Rocky Maivia, is really Dwayne Johnson, a former
University of Miami defensive lineman coached by Orgeron before
becoming a famous wrestler. And somewhere along the line, Johnson
borrowed Orgeron's coaching mantra.
</P>
<P>
   It's the most-visible example of the influence Orgeron has on
players. On the practice field, his loud comments, intense nature
and hard-driving manner are impossible to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   An outsider might think he's crazy, listening to him yell during
practice. Free safety David Gibson remembers the first time he saw
Orgeron.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was completely nuts,'' Gibson said. ``I didn't
know his background. I thought, `I'm going to have to deal with
this guy?' You can't ignore him if you had earplugs.''
</P>
<P>
   But first impressions of Orgeron are usually far from the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the heart of the defense,'' Gibson said. ``He wants to
win more than we do. He's an old-school type of coach. He's
positive. He's not negative.''
</P>
<P>
   Orgeron's coaching tactics are hard to dispute. He has molded
USC's defensive line into the most impressive unit on the team, and
done it with only one certain NFL prospect _ defensive tackle Ennis
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Orgeron has developed a group of linemen that were somewhat of a
mystery and turned them into consistent playmakers. Defensive
linemen Ryan Nielsen, Matt Childers, Lonnie Ford and Shamsud-Din
Abdul-Shaheed are all exceeding expectations this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want them to feel like pro material. I want them to feel
like national champions,'' Orgeron said. ``When they walk out of
the tunnel, I want them to feel that way.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see why his players perform. They might fear
Orgeron in a first meeting, but are quickly won over and fiercely
loyal. He's the most popular assistant on the coaching staff
because of his fairness with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no favoritism. Everybody is equal,'' defensive end
Ford said. ``He talks to Ennis just like he talks to
third-stringers. You know your role every week. He just flat out
tells you.
</P>
<P>
   ``He treats us like men. If you have something to talk about,
you can come up to his office. I respect that.''
</P>
<P>
   Orgeron said his coaching style comes primarily from working at
Miami under former coach Jimmy Johnson. He stayed with the
Hurricanes when Dennis Erickson was hired and coached star linemen
Cortez Kennedy, Russell Maryland and Warren Sapp.
</P>
<P>
   One of Orgeron's favorite pictures hanging in his house shows
him standing on the sideline during a game against Florida State.
It's a fourth-and-1 situation, and Orgeron has Sapp standing behind
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine having a line like that, with Warren Sapp on
the sideline?'' Orgeron said.
</P>
<P>
   It was an amazing coaching ascent for Orgeron. He was young and
successful and his future was limitless at Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on the fast track at 29. We were winning national
championships,'' Orgeron said. ``We went two years without losing a
game. We went five years without losing a home game. You get a
false sense of reality.''
</P>
<P>
   It all changed in 1992. According to police records, Orgeron was
arrested after a fight in a Baton Rouge, La., bar in which he
head-butted the bar manager. He was charged with second-degree
battery _ a felony _ and police said he was ``highly intoxicated''
when he was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Orgeron was also charged with failure to leave the premises and
misrepresentation during booking. The charges were eventually
dropped at the request of the bar manager.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Orgeron resigned from Miami and took a year off from
coaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I had a major setback,'' Orgeron said. ``That's been
seven years ago, and I'm still very cautious in everything I do.
I've slowed down. My priorities have changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Orgeron made the slow climb back into coaching, with one year at
Nicholls State in Louisiana before being hired at Syracuse in 1995.
He came to USC when coach Paul Hackett hired him in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   His personal life has also changed dramatically since Miami.
Three years ago, Orgeron went on a blind date while Syracuse was
playing in the Liberty Bowl. Two months later, he was married.
</P>
<P>
   ``I normally don't go on blind dates, but when I met Ed, it was
all over,'' Kelly Orgeron said. ``It was one of those, `Oh oh. He's
the one.' Everybody was shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Orgeron was as surprised as everyone else the first time
she saw her husband's aggressive coaching style, but she also saw
the side unknown to casual observers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always ask me how he acts at home or after a game,''
she said. ``Curiosity gets the best of them. He is very
intimidating to most people, but once they get to know him, he's a
big Teddy Bear. Once he comes home, he's Mr. Dad.''
</P>
<P>
   Orgeron's lifestyle has changed so much that most of his spare
time is spent around his 7-year-old stepson, Tyler, and 19-month
twin sons, Parker and Cody.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I met Kelly, I was set to stay single and coach,''
Orgeron said. ``It's nice to have a home and not carouse. Very
rarely do I go out. I'm home changing diapers.''
</P>
<P>
   But he hasn't lost his intensity when football is concerned. He
dismantled a chair last year before the Stanford game to prove a
point to his linemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always riled up with somebody, but he says everybody gets
in fights with their brothers and sisters,'' defensive tackle
Bernard Riley said. ``We're a family. He's there to protect us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
