<SLUG> BC-TITLE-FINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST AMERICAN TO PAY $2.5 MILLION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the largest penalty of its kind to date,
California's biggest title insurance company will pay $2.5 million
to settle charges it made illegal kickbacks to real estate agents,
State Insurance Commissioner Chuck Quackenbush said.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Ana-based First American Title Co. will pay $1.25 million
in fines and penalties and $1.25 million to fund a consumer
awareness program.
</P>
<P>
   The most egregious violations occurred in the company's Los
Angeles office, which was not allowed to take any new orders on
Monday as part of the penalty. It still was able to service
existing orders and customers.
</P>
<P>
   That office also will be forced to halt its marketing activities
for five business days at a later date, the state said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   First American, with revenues of about $2.06 billion nationally,
has 125 office throughout the state and a 22 percent market share.
In Los Angeles County, the company has a main office in Glendale
and three other customer service offices.
</P>
<P>
   State investigators determined that First American solicited
business from real estate agents by providing a variety of
inducements, including trips to Las Vegas, ski trips to Utah and
tickets to concerts and sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   The state maintains consumers were harmed because real estate
agents are supposed to find the best possible price for a title
search, not one offering them a kickback.
</P>
<P>
   Rates for title services in California vary from company to
company and are filed with the state.
</P>
<P>
   The company issued a statement saying it was taking the matter
seriously and has been implementing programs to ensure the
questionable marketing practices outlined by the insurance
department do not reoccur.
</P>
<P>
   This is the eighth and by far the largest penalty levied upon a
title company since the state began an aggressive policing of the
industry in 1996. Earlier this year, Chicago Title Co. was fined
$235,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's because of the egregious inducements,'' insurance
department spokeswoman Dana Spurrier said of the harsh penalty.
``It's almost as if they were flagrant and were hoping to get
caught, because they certainly did hide it once our investigators
started looking.''
</P>
<P>
   She called the marketing ban a death sentence for the company's
Los Angeles office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only will they lose customers, they will probably lose
some of their staff,'' Spurrier said. ``We're sending a very strong
message to the title insurance industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Jo Etta Bandy, First American spokesman, said she would not
speculate on how the marketing ban would hurt the company and noted
existing orders could still be serviced during the five-day
blackout.
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
