<SLUG> BC-SUNMICRO-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUN MICROSYSTEMS SAYS PROFIT ROSE AND OUTLOOK IS STRONG 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Sun Microsystems Inc. reported earnings for its
first fiscal quarter that exceeded analysts' estimates by a couple
of cents, as the maker of work stations and servers continued to
gain market share. Revenues were well above estimates as well, and
Sun executives predicted more strong growth for this quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Sun reported its results after the close of the market. Its
shares had closed at $89.40625, up 0.03125 cent.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended Sept. 15, Sun reported earnings of $271.1
million, or 33 cents a diluted share, more than twice the $113.9
million, or 14 cents a share, in the period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue rose 25 percent, to $3.12 billion from $2.49 billion in
the first quarter of fiscal 1999. First-quarter 2000 earnings
reflected a charge of $3.5 million incurred in the acquisition of
Star Division Corp. and a related increase of $1.3 million to Sun's
income tax provision.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected Sun to earn 31 cents a share, according to
First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Sun executives said the company's success came at the expense of
its traditional competitors, particularly Hewlett-Packard Co.,
which warned earlier this month that its fourth-quarter revenue
growth would fall at the low end of estimates, primarily because of
slow sales of its Unix servers. They said Sun had also taken market
share from IBM and had benefited from the delayed delivery of
Microsoft Corp.'s Windows 2000 operating system, the successor to
Windows NT.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really seems like we're distancing ourselves from the
pack,'' Michael E. Lehman, Sun's vice president for corporate
resources and chief financial officer, said in a telephone
interview. ``HP's out there forecasting a low-ball number, while
our results are almost blown away.'' For the December quarter,
``we've got a strong backlog, and people should probably think
about revenue growth in the low 20s,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   During the quarter, Sun acquired Star Division and certain
assets and liabilities of Star Division Software-Entwicklung und
Vertriebs GmbH, a German producer of office productivity
applications that compete directly with Microsoft's offerings but
run on Sun's Solaris operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Scott McNeely, Sun's chairman and chief executive, said in a
conference call with analysts that more than one million people had
downloaded these applications from Sun's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of being NT road kill, Solaris has widened the gap,''
McNeely said. ``The one thing NT had that we didn't have was a
wonderful productivity suite. Now, with Star Office, people are
saying, `Why do I need the NT thing?''' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 2227EDT &QL; 
