<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7447 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-BOS &LR;      10-14 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS, NFL WARN: NO NEW ROAD, NO STADIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MEG VAILLANCOURT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The New England Patriots, the National Football League,
and Boston business leaders warned Thursday that without a new
access road, the team's proposed $250 million stadium in Foxborough
will not be built.
</P>
<P>
   While the Patriots and NFL officials insisted they were not
issuing an ultimatium, they said that an access road that would
make it easier for luxury suite patrons to leave the stadium is
crucial to marketing and financing the project. A vote by
Foxborough residents on a proposed zoning change to allow
construction of the access road may come as early as next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to draw a line in the sand, but we need to clear
up a misperception that we can somehow build the stadium without
this access road,'' said Andrew Wasynczuk, the Patriots' chief
operating officer. ``That's just not the case. Without this road,
the new stadium project cannot and will not go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   NFL officials went even further, noting that the league's
precedent-setting agreement to help finance the new Foxboro Stadium
played a key role in keeping the team from moving to Hartford,
where Connecticut had promised the Patriots a publicly financed
stadium package worth more than $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NFL's financing is contingent upon the access road,'' NFL
executive vice president Roger Goodell said in a telephone
interview. ``When we reached an agreement with the state and town
officials on a new stadium last spring, everyone agreed it included
a new access road. For the project to move forward, we need all the
parties to live up to their commitments.''
</P>
<P>
   But in Foxborough, a small group of residents whose homes abut
the proposed access route off North Street said they think the
Patriots are bluffing. And with a town vote on the project expected
next month, the opponents are pressing their neighbors to reject
the access road.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can just build a stadium without the road, or build
another road somewhere else,'' said Karen Lovejoy, a North Street
resident. ``It's not do-or-die.''
</P>
<P>
   Traffic consultants for the Patriots and supporters of the plan
including the town's three selectmen, an independant town
consultant and state highway officials point to studies suggesting
that the access road would actually improve traffic for Foxborough
residents.
</P>
<P>
   North Street is now open to general stadium traffic on game
days, but the access road would be restricted to less than
one-third of premium seat holders and Foxborough residents. As a
result, the team argues, most North Street residents would see a
clear improvement in game day traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some residents are not convinced. ``I don't belive they
will make it better for me,'' said Pam Boudreau, another North
Street resident. ``I don't see why luxury seat holders can't just
wait another 15 minutes to preserve my neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   But ensuring easy access is a crucial element in the team's
marketing strategy as it continues to hawk luxury suites to
Boston's corporate community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the access road, you might as well put out a tombstone
over the whole deal,'' warned Boston attorney Paul Kirk, who led
the effort to keep the Patriots in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Access has always been a key element, not just for the guy
with a cigar and big Cadillac, but for the average fan and
Foxborough residents,'' said Boston advertising executive Jack
Connors. ``You can't suddenly separate one element of the
package.''
</P>
<P>
   Team owner Robert Kraft pulled out of the Hartford deal in late
April, when it became clear Connecticut couldn't deliver on its
promises and after the NFL and local business leaders brokered a
last-minute deal with Governor Paul Cellucci, Senate President
Thomas Birmingham and House Speaker Thomas Finneran to provide $70
million in infrastructure assistance for a new Foxboro Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In return, NFL officials, anxious to retain the television
revenues from the much larger Boston media market, agreed to
contribute to the financing for a stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The bill passed by the Legislature requires construction of an
access road for the new stadium. However, to build the road,
Foxborough must first change the town's zoning code, a move that
requires a two-thirds vote at a town meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Keenly aware of the signs around town opposing the access road,
team officials have stressed that under a proposed agreement, the
town would receive a significant increase in stadium revenues _
from $1.1 million to $1.8 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   The new 68,000-seat stadium would have roughly 80 luxury suites,
costing between $150,000 to $300,000 for a package of 12 to 36
seats. In addition, there would be 6,000 club seats. While about
half the luxury seats have been sold, the remaining seats will be
marketed after the town gives the project final approval, team
officials said. The Patriots hope to play their first game in the
new stadium in 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
