<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7448 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-HUMMER-COLUMN15-C     10-14 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HUMMER-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    N.Y. trash talk its only fire left
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is little suspense left for the field of play.
The New York Mets can't hang. Couldn't a month ago; can't now. They
need to be swept away, taking the Bobby Valentine dugout pantomime
with them.
</P>
<P>
   So, we turn to the seats for our entertainment. While the Braves
are busy transforming Flushing from proper noun to verb, we can be
amused by the clever antics of the New York fans. They're so cute
when aroused; almost human.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect to hear things we've never heard before,'' said one
of the Shea Stadium favorites, the Braves third baseman, Chipper
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Really? Never before? These are ballplayers, not monks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I wish you could sit in the dugout and hear it,'' Jones
said. ``Sometimes clever. Sometimes offensive. Most any comment has
a lot of those magical four-letter words.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Atlanta fans are fair-weather, then these people are the
storm. They enjoy being the angry red on the Doppler radar of
sports. Either way, the attitude in the stands will make no
difference in the final result. Just that the louder the voice, the
sweeter the moment when it is silenced.
</P>
<P>
   The stage is set for some interesting background noise when the
NLCS resumes here Friday. The Shea mob targeted Jones while he was
ruining the Mets' regular season. And he fired back, writing them
off as fashion pretenders, just killing time until they could slip
into their fall wardrobe of Yankee pinstripes.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than further inflaming the situation, they'd be better
off just letting C. Jones snooze. They need to get some new Eddie
Perez or Brian Jordan material. Maybe Andrew Dice Clay can rip off
a few low-brow put-downs for them in time for Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   Jones has another hope. ``Maybe he (John Rocker) will get booed
before I do _ but somehow I doubt it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves' hyperactive closer has earned himself special notice
from the friendly folk of the five boroughs. There's not nearly
enough trash talk in baseball, but Rocker may be trying to fix
that. ``To hell with New York fans,'' he declared after Wednesday's
win. ``They're stupid anyway. We beat them 20 out of 26 times, and
they still say we (stink). Well, if we (stink) so bad, how come
they can't beat us? They're a tired act.'' On a Thursday morning
Atlanta radio spot, Rocker promised plenty more smack after the
Mets were dismissed. He's probably saving the A material for Yankee
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday afternoon, when the team emerged for an off-day workout
at Shea, Ryan Klesko came out in Rocker's jersey. ``I'm Rocker's
dummy. He'll stay inside for a few minutes. If it's safe, he'll
come out,'' Klesko joked. Rocker later came out with ``Klesko'' on
his back, and they all laughed off the tension.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, he's just a good ol' Georgia boy who doesn't see a lot of
hospitality here,'' said his protector. The real test of Klesko's
nerve, however, would be to slip into the Rocker-wear tonight, when
there are people in the seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he's one of the guys who said something, but please
don't tell me what it was,'' manager Bobby Cox said of his
mercurial closer.
</P>
<P>
   All this is fun to talk about. It fills in the competitive
cracks in this series. As for practical impact, there isn't any.
Rocker says he loves the abuse _ ``I prefer playing before a
hostile crowd to one that's cheering me,'' he said. The Braves are
a good road team _ 47-34 during the regular season, even expressing
much love for the Astrodome during the Division Series. They don't
need approval to play well.
</P>
<P>
   Bring on a full-throated New York. It really shouldn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
