<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FEDERALISM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FIDDLING WITH FEDERALISM  
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, Oct. 15:
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court's ongoing reappraisal of the limits of federal
power moved into new and treacherous terrain on Wednesday when the
justices heard arguments in one of the term's most significant
cases _ a test of Congress' authority to bind states to the federal
law barring age discrimination in employment and, more broadly, its
authority to enforce the fairness principles embedded in the 14th
Amendment's equal protection clause.
</P>
<P>
   Bolstered by the court's recent string of lamentable 5-4
decisions elevating states' rights at the expense of federal power,
a lower appeals court ruled that Congress could not subject states
to federal lawsuits by employees who charge they are victims of age
bias. The court's response here, and in two other prominent
federalism cases this term, will tell whether the agenda of the
``states' rights five'' _ Chief Justice William Rehnquist and
Justices Antonin Scalia, Clarence Thomas, Anthony Kennedy and
Sandra Day O'Connor _ includes a radical narrowing of congressional
leeway to legislate national remedies to protect basic civil
rights.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate outcome may not be known for months, but the
comments by some of the justices were not heartening. ``The statute
does not mention the 11th Amendment,'' said Justice O'Connor,
suggesting she believes that the federal age-discrimination law at
issue violates the court's 1996 edict that Congress may wipe out a
state's sovereign immunity only when going after some specific
discriminatory harm and when it unequivocally indicates it is
overriding that immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the facts show otherwise. Congress amassed piles of
testimony and other evidence before concluding that age
discrimination is a national problem that afflicts public as well
as private employers. Furthermore, by defining the terms
``employer'' and ``employee'' to include the states, and by
expressly allowing private lawsuits against a ``public agency,''
Congress made no secret of its intent to override the 11th
Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Scalia said Thursday that he found it ``extraordinary'' that
Congress had concluded that arbitrary and irrational age
discrimination was a violation of the Constitution's guarantee of
equal protection in the absence of a court decision defining it as
such. But Congress traditionally has gone further than the courts
in affording legal protection to vulnerable groups, and the very
language of the equal protection clause gives Congress that right.
</P>
<P>
   Scalia also said Thursday that he did not find age
discrimination to be irrational as a general matter. The danger is
that this glibly dismissive attitude will become the basis for a
sweeping constitutional ruling constricting the ability of Congress
to define and legislate protection for civil rights, and calling
into question a slew of existing civil rights laws, including the
Americans with Disabilities Act, the Equal Pay Act and even,
potentially, a portion of the 1964 Civil Rights Act.
</P>
<P>
   To hold states immune from private age-discrimination suits in
federal court, the government argues in its brief, ``would be an
extraordinary and unwarranted departure from both text and
history'' of the Constitution. It can only be hoped that, upon
careful reflection, a majority of justices will agree.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
