<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0477 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7460 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     10-14 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBITAILLE IN GREAT SHAPE TO PASS HIS IDOL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ What child is this leading the league in goals in
Year 1 after Gretzky? He's from Quebec, but it's not Vincent
Lecavalier.
</P>
<P>
   He's solid as a gold bar, but it's not Patrick Marleau.
</P>
<P>
   He's goofy, but it's not Joe Thornton.
</P>
<P>
   Luc Robitaille is 33, but he's playing like it's 1988. That 20
on the Kings left wing's jersey could pass as his age. Neither
Father Time nor any opposing skater has been able to slow him out
of the gate in his 14th NHL season.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille has seven goals and 10 points in five games for the
Kings (3-1-1), who play at Calgary tonight. San Jose's Owen Nolan
was second with six goals going into Thursday's game against
Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille has triggered more flashing red lights than the
entire Philadelphia Flyers team had before Thursday and they're
supposed to be thisclose to the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly nobody expected the 171st pick in the 1984 draft to
one day be thisclose to catching his childhood idol _ Maurice
``Rocket'' Richard _ on the NHL's all-time goal scoring list. And
yet there he stands at 524 goals, 21 shy of supplanting Richard as
the league's 17th most prolific goal scorer.
</P>
<P>
   At his current breakneck pace, Robitaille would overtake Richard
shortly before Thanksgiving. Not that we're counting any blessings
before they've been bequeathed.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. fans have been tantalized like this before, most recently
in late May when Dodgers outfielder Raul Mondesi sat atop the
league in home runs. Mondesi's brush with glory lasted about as
long as an odd-man rush.
</P>
<P>
   It would be presumptuous to say this could be Robitaille's
crowning season, especially with that 63-goal jewel from 1992-93
embedded in our memories. If Robitaille never reaches that number
again, he shouldn't fret:
</P>
<P>
   It's quite conceivable nobody will.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL didn't have a 50-goal scorer last year. It certainly
wasn't for a lack of trying that Anaheim's Teemu Selanne, the
league leader, came up three goals short.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scoring 30 goals today is a lot harder than it was seven years
ago,'' said Robitaille, who managed 39 in 82 games in 1998-99.
``The goalies today play a different style than they used to.
They're too good.''
</P>
<P>
   Goaltenders are getting bigger, stronger and more athletic.
Unlike the upright netminders of yesteryear, they'll fall to the
ice at the drop of a shooter's shoulder, effectively taking away
the lower half of the net.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille has changed with the times. In the summer of 1998, on
the heels of his fourth consecutive mediocre, injury-marred season,
he stepped up his conditioning routine. Since then Robitaille has
attacked the weights with the same ferocity he does loose pucks in
and around the crease.
</P>
<P>
   He has worked himself into such great shape _ the better to give
his shots a lift _ his muscles didn't lodge a single protest
despite being subjected to five games in eight nights to start the
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just a lot stronger,'' Robitaille said. ``I feel better
physically and mentally. When I get in battles in front of the net
I feel really confident because I know I can (stand my ground).''
</P>
<P>
   It helps that his linemates have much better aim than any
paperboy. Jozef Stumpel and Ziggy Palffy are terrific at reading
the ice and putting the puck right there on the doorstep for
Robitaille. Their passing is pretty enough to make a grown man
whistle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys are such skilled players,'' Robitaille said.
``Playing with them you're going to get more scoring
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   You're also bound to pick up a little Slovakian. That's the
native tongue of both Stumpel and Palffy. They've already taught
Robitaille how to say ``I'm doing good.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeez, don't they know he's incapable of bragging in any
language?
</P>
<P>
   A few other phrases Robitaille has overheard, well, he can only
guess their meaning. ``The other day Stumpy and Ziggy were talking
in Slovakian and I think they were mad at each other,'' he said,
laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that's not the Canadian ``eh'' punctuating Robitaille's
sentences, it's a contented ``heh, heh, heh.''
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille is happy, he knows it and he's not afraid to show it.
It's a far cry from his days with the New York Rangers, two endless
seasons that saw Robitaille endure injuries and insults.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were tough years in New York,'' Robitaille said,
referring to the 1995-96 and 1996-97 seasons that preceded his
return to L.A. ``It's not that I didn't like New York. I just
forgot that it's still a game and you've got to enjoy it. I put a
lot of pressure on myself to be the player I thought I could be.''
</P>
<P>
   L.A. fans, having watched Robitaille grow from a kid who could
barely speak English to the Kings' gracious spokesman, have a
proprietary interest in him. He is from Canada, but he is of
Southern California. He is L.A. hockey's bridge from Marcel Dionne
to the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille never thought he'd stick around long enough to catch
Richard, the former Montreal superstar. He never considered himself
that good. To him, he's just, you know, Lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It certainly would be an honor to pass him,'' Robitaille said.
``It's pretty special we're even able to talk about it today.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow comes with no guarantees. Gretzky, a teammate of
Robitaille in L.A. and New York, didn't muster more than 38 goals
in any season after his 33rd birthday. Then there's Mark Messier,
another New York teammate, who had 47 goals at age 35.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille can't be sure how the pucks will fall for him. All he
knows is he'll keep playing hard until his _ ahem _ luck runs out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I play every game like it's my last game,'' Robitaille said.
``We'll see what happens in the end.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
