<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 22:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7464 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TYCO-SELLOUT-ART-NYT &LR;      10-14 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TYCO-SELLOUT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE TYCO'S DEFENSE, SHARES FALL AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, N.Y., Md.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Investors brushed aside Tyco International's
aggressive defense of its accounting practices Thursday, pushing
its stock down $10 more, to $87, amid fears about the company's
three-year acquisition spree.
</P>
<P>
   The selloff has dropped shares of Tyco, one of the highfliers of
the current bull market, by 18 percent since the start of the week,
when an investment manager wrote a detailed critique of the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Tyco's chief executive, L. Dennis Kozlowski, said he was
outraged by the ``false and baseless'' report, which was published
by David W. Tice, a Dallas fund manager and prominent short-seller.
Speaking to Wall Street analysts in a conference call Thursday
morning, Kozlowski added, ``There is no risk that investors will
wake up one day and find out'' that ``there's something wrong with
the way we've been recording revenue or the way we've been
recording margins.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts continued to support the company Thursday,
saying they thought its earnings remained on course for this year
and next. ``It was very reassuring,'' said Jack Blackstock, an
analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, referring to the call.
</P>
<P>
   But investors are clearly alarmed, reflecting both broader
concerns about the health of the stock market and specific worries
about Tyco, which has spent about $30 billion on acquisitions over
the last three years. Tyco sells electronic components, fire
prevention devices, alarm systems and medical products, among other
items.
</P>
<P>
   Separate from Tice's criticisms, a well-known evaluator of
corporate accounting methods issued warnings about two of Tyco's
acquisitions, AMP Inc. and the United States Surgical Corp., before
the conglomerate took them over.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Financial Research and Analysis Inc., run out of
Rockville, Md., by Howard Schilit, told clients in March 1998 that
AMP's earnings were weaker than they appeared because the company
had adopted new accounting methods and was experiencing a rise in
inventories. Tyco bought AMP, then the world's biggest maker of
electronic connectors, for $12 billion in April.
</P>
<P>
   The research center also warned clients twice in 1996 about
United States Surgical, which had long drawn criticism for its
financial practices. Tyco bought the medical supplies company in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   The center has won a following for calling attention to earnings
troubles before the stock market has reacted to them.
</P>
<P>
   J. Brad McGee, a Tyco spokesman, said that AMP's business had
since rebounded and that United States Surgical had solved its
accounting problems before Tyco bought it. ``They're completely
different companies today,'' McGee said.
</P>
<P>
   Investors began dumping shares of Tyco this week after they
found out about the critical report by Tice's firm. It said that
Tyco had taken overly large write-offs related to its mergers to
inflate future earnings and that its cash flow had been deceptively
weak.
</P>
<P>
   The company said Thursday that Tice did not bother to call the
company so that executives could explain the situation. As an
example, Mark H. Swartz, Tyco's chief financial officer, cited
Tice's highlighting of the large amount of money set aside for job
cuts even after many layoffs had been announced. In fact, Swartz
said, payments to former employees must continue even after they
leave.
</P>
<P>
   Tice stood by his report Thursday and said the company had not
returned his firm's phone calls.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
