<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7478 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-SENATE-VOTE-NYT &LR;      10-14 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SENATE-VOTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE SENATE'S HARMFUL VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Friday, Oct. 15: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's forceful and focused performance at
Thursday's news conference must mark the beginning of a sustained
White House effort to limit the damage inflicted by the Senate's
reckless vote Wednesday against the nuclear test ban treaty. It
will be up to Clinton to convince other nations, including those
that have already signed the treaty, like Russia and China, and
those that have not, like India, Pakistan and North Korea, that the
United States remains committed to observing its provisions and
eventually ratifying it in a new Senate vote. In these and other
ways, his administration must demonstrate America's continued
determination to reduce nuclear dangers throughout the world. The
Senate should want to send exactly the same message. Unfortunately,
it did not.
</P>
<P>
   With its abrupt scheduling, rushed debate and needless negative
vote on the test ban treaty, the Republican Senate majority all but
abdicated its constitutional responsibility to play a thoughtful
and deliberative role in the shaping of American foreign policy. It
also undermined Washington's ability to provide diplomatic
leadership on one of the most important questions facing the world
today _ controlling the development and spread of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   With the United States now the world's foremost military and
economic power, senators as well as presidents must rise to the
challenge of international leadership, helping to project the moral
vision of the American people onto the global arena. Too many
senators failed this crucial test.
</P>
<P>
   Senators have a complex and serious role to play on foreign
policy matters. Their duty is not to assent passively to every
presidential initiative, but to engage their own minds and
consciences, particularly on grave questions of war, peace and
treaties. Too many Republican senators shortchanged that duty by
allowing the majority leader, Trent Lott, and a handful of
committed treaty opponents to turn the test ban issue into a
partisan arm-wrestling contest with the White House and Senate
Democratic leadership.
</P>
<P>
   At no time in the ludicrously compressed Senate debate was the
country offered a serious alternative Republican view of how to
contain the alarming development of nuclear weapons in South Asia
and their potential spread to such troubled areas as the Middle
East and the Korean Peninsula. Instead, many opponents spoke as if
the United States could afford to turn its back on international
arms control treaties and address the spread of nuclear weapons
solely through superior military strength. As Clinton noted
Thursday, that kind of armed isolationism makes little sense and
offers no real security at the dawn of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   America's most honored foreign policy tradition is
bipartisanship. The Senate so rarely votes to reject major treaties
that the last comparable precedent was Woodrow Wilson's defeat over
the Treaty of Versailles nearly 80 years ago. That disastrous
decision weakened Washington's voice in international affairs. This
one threatens to do the same unless Clinton manages to keep alive
some momentum for nuclear arms control and the Senate returns to
its traditions of serious and constructive foreign policy debate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 2243EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0481 </DOCNO>
