<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROOKLYN-FILM-STUDIO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE NIRO AND PARTNERS DISPUTE GIULIANI VERSION OF NAVY YARD DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Reeling Thursday from the collapse of a deal to build
a $150 million sound stage complex at the city-owned Brooklyn Navy
Yard, actor Robert De Niro and top executives of Miramax Films
disputed Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's account of where the deal stood
before it fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Giuliani said that the city had made no formal
commitment to Miramax, and he cited the word ``explore,'' which
appeared three times in the press release that first announced the
project, as evidence that there had been no agreement other than to
explore the plans.
</P>
<P>
   But in a statement released Thursday, De Niro and Harvey
Weinstein, the president of Miramax, said: ``In getting us to agree
to a press conference on May 3 to announce the plan, the mayor told
us that we had a deal. All that remained to do was `dot the i's and
cross the t's.'''
</P>
<P>
   De Niro and Weinstein also said they thought that the city would
have benefited more from working with them. ``There is no question
that our proposal, from the leading film producers on the East
Coast, is better for Brooklyn and the needs of the city,'' they
said.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing Wednesday that the deal with Miramax had fallen
through, Giuliani said that the project would go forward, but that
it would instead be built by a different development group, headed
by Douglas C. Steiner, the son of David S. Steiner, who is a New
Jersey financier.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said that the Steiner group offered ``a much better
deal for the city'' that would provide about $60 million more in
rent revenue and would not require the city to make a $25 million
loan for the project, as the Miramax deal would have.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, at his daily news conference at City Hall on Thursday,
reacted angrily to the assertion that there had been a more formal
commitment to Miramax. ``I think I showed you the press release
yesterday,'' the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   Told that regardless of the release, De Niro and Weinstein had
disputed the mayor's account, Giuliani said: ``Well, that's some
other world. That's some other world, other than the world of
equity, fairness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word in the press release, repeated three times, is
explore. It was written as explore, it meant explore. Explore means
there is no deal to any sensible, fair and honest person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
