<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS QUESTIONS OLYMPIC OFFICIALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Members of a congressional investigating
subcommittee subjected representatives of the Olympics to sharp
questioning Thursday over allegations of corruption in Atlanta's
and other cities' applications to have the games awarded to them.
</P>
<P>
   The comments of the congressmen, such as Rep. Ron Klink's
assertion that the International Olympic Committee ``has allowed a
shameful system to continue,'' gave an indication of how the
questioning is likely to go when Juan Antonio Samaranch, the
Olympic committee's president, appears before the panel on Dec. 15.
</P>
<P>
   The governing body of the International Olympic Committee is to
meet in Lausanne, Switzerland, on Dec. 11 and 12, and Francois
Carrard, the director general of the Olympic committee, said that
it would introduce changes to meet allegations that the Olympics
had been awarded to cities by a self-perpetuating group of
selectors more interested in lavish gifts than the best sites for
the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Klink, a Pennsylvanian, is the ranking Democrat on the panel,
the commerce subcommittee on oversight and investigations, and
members of both parties jumped in with their skeptical questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Richard Burr, R-N.C., said that Congress should give
serious consideration to a bill that would remove the tax deduction
that American corporations get for sponsoring the Olympics, an
action that could cripple the games.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., who is the co-sponsor of that bill,
said, ``The culture of greed and corruption that led to the Salt
Lake City scandal has been flourishing for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Waxman was referring to the lavish gifts and other improprieties
that were discovered after the 2002 Winter Games were awarded to
Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the subcommittee, Rep. Fred Upton, R-Mich.,
said: ``We were hoping that Salt Lake City's actions were an
aberration, but, sadly, as the Atlanta report so graphically
confirms, Salt Lake City was not an aberration.''
</P>
<P>
   The report he referred to was made by Griffin Bell, a former
attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   Klink asked William Payne, the former chairman of the Atlanta
committee for its 1996 Olympics, to explain huge expenditures made
by the committee for people who would be selecting the Olympic
site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta officials paid $11,987 for the IOC official from Libya
to travel from Tripoli to Zurich to Geneva back to Zurich to
Atlanta then to Chicago then back to Atlanta then to Zurich then to
Malta and finally back to Tripoli,'' Klink said.
</P>
<P>
   After listing many similar trips by another Olympics official,
this one from Ireland, Klink asked Payne, ``Weren't you trying to
buy his vote?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, we weren't,'' Payne answered.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Payne acknowledged that ``Atlanta's bidding
effort included excessive actions, even thought processes, that
today seem inappropriate but, at the time, reflected the prevailing
practices in the selection process and an extremely competitive
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Those kinds of practices should not be permitted in
the competition for future Olympic bids.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 2245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
