<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVER TIME, BRUINS' VETERAN DEPTH VANISHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With seven senior starters, UCLA is one of the
least experienced teams in the Pac-10. But youth shines brightest
when the Bruins substitute; 16 of their 22 second-string players
are freshmen and sophomores.
</P>
<P>
   The dearth of veteran depth is traceable to 12 players who have
quit the team in the last three years _ including the man who would
be quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent departure was left tackle Kris Farris, who
bypassed his senior season and entered the 1999 NFL draft. But for
long-term impact, nothing tops the forced retirements of two
members of coach Bob Toledo's first recruiting class.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Anselmo Zamano was challenging for a starting job as
a freshman in 1996 when he shredded every ligament in his knee at
Michigan. Several surgeries later, Zamano can run, but a return
seems unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was going to be a super player,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Dylan Aquino, who would be a junior this season, was
considered Cade McNown's eventual successor, but a congenital
neurological problem in his neck forced him to quit in '96.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought he'd be our starter (this season),'' Toledo said.
``He was going to be a good quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Other departed players include: cornerback Damian Allen (track
and field); defensive lineman Jesse Simms (did not enroll);
linebackers Ramogi Huma (medical) and Mike Wiley (medical);
fullback Mark Verti (medical); and linemen David Plenty-Hawk
(personal), Scott Weigand (personal), Matt Pentecost (track and
field), Jeff Wright (personal) and Dave Wilford (grades).
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a lot of guys either hurt or leave,'' Toledo said.
``That's why (the 60-man travel squad) has 40 freshmen and
sophomores.''
</P>
<P>
   Tailback tales: In DeShaun Foster's absence (sprained ankle),
senior Keith Brown and junior Jermaine Lewis once again will share
the tailback duties. They combined for 105 yards against Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   If Brown or Lewis is injured, seldom-used redshirt freshman
Kenny Pritchett, of Crescenta Valley, will be promoted to
second-string.
</P>
<P>
   And just in case, the Bruins snared walk-on Mike Vanis off the
scout team and practiced him with the starters.
</P>
<P>
   Infection update: As of Thursday evening, reserve guard Ed
Anderson was the only player expected to miss Saturday's game
against Cal because of an upper respiratory infection that has
afflicted 15-20 players.
</P>
<P>
   Review of the week: Defensive tackle Pete Holland, a history
major and six-time member of the director's honor roll, has agreed
to review a book each week for the Daily News. This week: ``A View
from Above'', by Wilt Chamberlain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although somewhat autobiographical, this book is not about
Chamberlain's life story. Rather, it's a collection of opinions
(`Wiltisms') and observations made by one of the NBA's most
outlandish alums. In it, we learn not how Wilt became Wilt, but
what being Wilt has taught him about the world _ a world about
which he has a unique perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ```View' is not a masterpiece of literature, but its content is
as compelling as any fiction. Some of his opinions and statistics
are astounding enough to memorize, from the 100-point game to the
20,000 _ well, you know. Overall, the book is an incomparable and
honest insight into the man who himself was peerless.''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2{ sacks (out of four).
</P>
</TEXT>
