<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-EARNS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING EXECS, ANALYSTS UPBEAT ABOUT EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Thanks in large measure to significant improvements in
its once-troubled commercial airplanes unit, The Boeing Co.
Thursday delivered a stronger than expected quarterly earnings
report that delighted analysts and sent its stock soaring nearly 8
percent on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Executives were upbeat about the future and the progress that
has been made in turning around the company's core business.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial profit margins are much better than previously
forecast, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Asia is bouncing back from its economic woes, they said, and
Boeing will be able to maintain production of its most profitable
commercial airplane _ the 747 _ at two per month in 2000. That
alone will result in an additional $1 billion in revenue next year.
</P>
<P>
   And 2001 is looking better for airplane deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had an outstanding quarter _ strong results, solid program
performance, some significant wins and improved outlook for the
future,'' Boeing Chairman Phil Condit said during a morning
conference call with analysts and the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``In short,'' he added, ``we are making real progress toward our
goals.''
</P>
<P>
   For the third quarter, Boeing had profits of $477 million, or 52
cents a share. That was 37 percent higher than for the third
quarter of 1998. Excluding non-recurring items, third-quarter
earnings per share were 56 cents in 1999. The consensus estimate of
analysts surveyed by First Call had been that Boeing would earn 49
cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's revenues rose 4.4 percent to $13.28 billion from $12.72
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street reacted by sending Boeing's stock up sharply. It
closed at $43 5/8, up $3 1/8 a share. On a day when stocks were
generally mixed, Boeing accounted for 16.8 points of the Dow's
advance of 54.45.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very, very good quarter,'' said Peter Jacobs of
Seattle's Ragan-MacKenzie firm. ``Clearly, the commercial airplane
operations are on the road to recovery. While they still have a
ways to go, they are ahead of schedule and there is an increased
level of confidence that they can continue to show solid
improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's commercial airplane unit accounts for about 60 percent
of the company's business.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, as Boeing attempted to ramp up production to
record levels, its commercial operations fell apart. Production
lines in Renton and in Everett were disrupted by bottlenecks and
planes were delivered late to customers. The problems cost Boeing
billions in unanticipated charges.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Boeing suffered a loss of $178 million in 1997, its
first red ink in a half century. Commercial boss Ron Woodard was
fired last September and replaced by Alan Mulally, one of the stars
of the company's successful 777 program.
</P>
<P>
   But production in the factories began to slowly improve,
especially in the second half of 1998. Even so, some analysts were
predicting late last year that Condit himself was in trouble and
might be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   There is no longer such talk on Wall Street. Boeing recently
negotiated a new labor contract with its machinists and Condit was
credited with playing a key role.
</P>
<P>
   Production at Boeing's factories has steadily improved this
year. With one quarter left in 1999, production efficiencies under
a new management team are clearly starting to kick in, analysts
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's commercial airplanes unit earned $501 million on
revenues of $8.5 billion in the third quarter, compared with a loss
of $142 million on revenues of $7.8 billion a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into Thursday's conference call, analysts were
especially interested in Boeing's commercial profit margins for the
quarter. That's one of the best ways to judge the company's
improving efficiency, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing did not disappoint.
</P>
<P>
   Although commercial revenue was down about 16 percent from the
second quarter, margins were up. (Revenue was down because Boeing
delivered fewer airplanes in the third quarter, though it remains
on target to deliver a record 620 planes this year).
</P>
<P>
   Boeing delivered a record 559 airplanes in 1998, and made
nothing on them.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial group posted a 3.9 percent profit in the first
quarter of 1999 and 4.3 percent in the second quarter. For the
third quarter, the commercial margin was 5.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Debby Hopkins, Boeing's chief financial officer, said the
company's margin forecasts for 1999 and 2000 have been revised
upwards.Commercial margins in 2000, previously forecast to be 1 to
3 percent, will instead be from 5.5 to 6.5 percent, she said.
</P>
<P>
   For 2000, Boeing's margins for all its businesses will range
from 5.5 to 6.5 percent. That's up from earlier projections of 3.5
to 5 percent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Total revenue will be down in 2000, which means Boeing will be
under even more pressure to improve margins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our challenge is to attempt to have 2000 earnings be equal or
exceed 1999,'' she said. ``And that requires us to get to operating
margins of around 7 percent for the total company.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Boeing will deliver a record number of planes this year,
it has said it will deliver only 480 planes next year, a result of
Asia and a slowing demand worldwide for new airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, revenue in 2000 will be about $49 billion, or about
$9 billion less than the $58 billion forecast for 1999, the company
said Thursday. That's an improvement of about $1 billion over
previous projections. The new figure reflects the production of 10
more 747s next year.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than producing 14 jumbo jets in 2000, Boeing will build
24.
</P>
<P>
   ``Due in part to the improved Asian economy, we are able to
maintain 747 production rate at two per month through 2000,''
Condit said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Boeing has not yet announced its projected deliveries
for 2001, it had previously warned 2001 would be worse than 2000.
That may not be the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``With that strengthening of the Asian market, right now we are
saying that 2001 looks sort of like 2000,'' Condit said. ``It was
not that long ago that we thought 2001 would be significantly less
than 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs, the industry analyst, said he was figuring that Boeing
would deliver only 426 planes in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take a couple more quarters for investors to fully
believe that's possible,'' he said of Condit's comment that 2001
deliveries may match those in 2000. ``Boeing will have to show a
good rebound in landing new orders which have been very soft this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's commercial orders are down significantly this year. It
lags well behind European aircraft maker Airbus Industrie.
</P>
<P>
   Airbus had 343 orders in the first nine months compared with 154
for Boeing.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing had 480 firm orders through the third quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Whitlow, who tracks Boeing for Safeco Corp., said Airbus is
winning more than 65 percent of new airplane orders this year. For
all of 1998, Airbus had about 46 percent of the total orders for
commercial jets with more than 100 seats.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Airbus is even beating Boeing on orders for widebody
jets, which has long been Boeing's market strength, Whitlow said in
an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a concern,'' he said. ``Airbus continues to make market
share gains ... It's a worrisome trend.''
</P>
<P>
   Condit said Thursday he expects Boeing's order book to improve
in the fourth quarter. A big order from International Lease Finance
Corp. that was announced at the Paris Air Show in June has not yet
been added to Boeing's tally because contract details are still
being worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the total, Condit said he does not worry about
orders. The key is deliveries, he said. By that measure, Boeing is
far ahead of Airbus.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really matters is what comes out the factory door and
what gets paid for,'' Condit said. ``This is the only industry in
the world that I know of that tries to track on an order rate.
Everybody else works on sales, or deliveries.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
