<SLUG> BC-NY-LEGIS-PAY-445&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. COURT BACKS LAW TO WITHHOLD LEGISLATORS' PAY WHEN BUDGET IS
LATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ New York's highest court upheld a bitterly
contested law Thursday that calls for withholding the pay of state
legislators when a state budget is late, bolstering efforts to
speed up the state's notoriously slow budget-making process.
</P>
<P>
   In a 6-1 ruling, the Court of Appeals overturned a lower court
decision that declared the new law unconstitutional on the ground
that it had the potential to coerce the state Legislature into
passing a budget and thus curbed its legal authority and
independence.
</P>
<P>
   In December, as part of a deal with Gov. George Pataki to raise
the salaries of lawmakers for the first time in a decade, the
Legislature agreed to pass a law that would penalize legislators if
a budget was not in place by the April 1 deadline: They would not
be paid until one had been passed.
</P>
<P>
   The law, the only one of its kind in the nation, was considered
an important victory for Pataki, a Republican whose tenure has been
marked by passage of the latest budgets in state history. That
happened despite his promise to deliver budgets on time, which he
made in 1994, when he first ran for governor.
</P>
<P>
   But the law was immediately challenged in court by 14 Democratic
state legislators, who maintained that it gave the governor
coercive powers over the Legislature that were unconstitutional.
The 14 plaintiffs either voted against the new law or were elected
in November and had not taken office when it passed.
</P>
<P>
   In a strongly worded decision May 21, Justice Richard Huttner of
state Supreme Court in Brooklyn found that the law gave the
governor a coercive power over the Legislature, violating the state
constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``When even one legislator, by dint of economic circumstance, is
coerced into passing a budget that may require him or her to
sacrifice conscientiously held beliefs, then the entire process is
tainted,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The Court of Appeals rejected the plaintiffs' claim of coercion.
Writing for the majority, Judge Joseph Bellacosa said that all
lawmakers ``are entitled to the presumption that they act only in
accordance with and fulfillment of their oaths of office.''
</P>
<P>
   The court also rejected the plaintiffs' assertion that the new
law violated the constitutional separation of powers by
transferring power from the Legislature to the governor, noting
that the law had been passed by both houses of the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Legislature has decided to restrict itself and discipline
its own work and power in this fashion,'' Bellacosa wrote. He added
that the law was a ``credit to the legislative branch's internal
management practices,'' not a surrendering of power.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The decision elicited predictable responses from both sides. The
law's opponents said that it could subvert the legislative process,
while its supporters said that it gave lawmakers a powerful
incentive to do their work in a timely manner.
</P>
<P>
   State Senate Republican Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, who was
one the law's chief sponsors, issued a statement Thursday afternoon
chiding Democrats for bringing the lawsuit instead of focusing on
completing the budget on time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that this issue has been resolved by the court,'' he said,
``I once again urge all parties to renew the effort to enact budget
reform so that we can help restore the public's confidence in our
ability to do our jobs well and to do them within the parameters
set by law.''
</P>
<P>
   But Assemblyman Alexander Grannis, a Democratic Assemblyman from
Manhattan who was one of the plaintiffs, said the ruling was not
just a setback for lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed,'' Grannis said. ``But the real losers are
the citizens of New York, who will never know whether we have
passed a budget because we believed it was the right budget or
because we wanted to get our pay to feed our families.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the legal wrangling it spurred, the law did not produce,
in its first year, anyway, the result its supporters desired: the
adoption of a budget on time. Instead, lawmakers adopted a budget
Aug. 4, 126 days into the current fiscal year, tying the record for
lateness.
</P>
<P>
   To get by, many legislators borrowed money or dipped into their
savings accounts. If anything, some lawmakers said, the law served
only to deepen the hostilities between the Legislature and the
governor, whose pay was not withheld.
</P>
<P>
   For more than two decades, it has been almost impossible for a
timely budget to be adopted in Albany. The budget has been late 21
times since 1975, largely because the Legislature has been divided
during that period, with the Assembly controlled by Democrats and
the Senate in the hands of Republicans. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
