<SLUG> BC-NY-KKK-RALLY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KLAN TO SUE CITY AFTER BEING DENIED RALLY PERMIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., N.J., N.Y.)  (mk) 
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Ku Klux Klan group plans to sue the administration
of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani after being denied a permit to hold a
``white pride'' rally in New York City, leaders of the white
supremacist group said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department turned down the Klan's application on
Wednesday night, citing a state law that prohibits people wearing
masks from congregating publicly, except at authorized masquerade
parties.
</P>
<P>
   Klan leaders, who refused to march without their fearsome white
hoods and masks, called the state's antimask law unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our First Amendment right'' to wear masks, said the
rally's organizer, Jeffery Berry, the national imperial wizard of
the Church of the American Knights of the Ku Klux Klan. Berry, of
Butler, Ind., said hoods are essential to the Klan. ``It's no
different than a bride wearing her veil, or the wives of Indians
and Arabs wearing theirs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Civil Liberties Union plans to represent the Klan,
saying that challenges to antimask laws had been successful in
Tennessee and Indiana. ``People have a right to engage in peaceful
rallies, even if their message is repugnant, bigoted and
wrong-minded, which the Klan message is,'' said Norman Siegel,
executive director of the civil liberties group, which has
represented other hate groups that have been denied rally permits.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel said Supreme Court decisions protect the right to
anonymous political activity. The masks also protect the identity
of Klan members, who fear political retribution for their extreme
views, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The group applied for a permit to hold a rally of 50 to 80
people outside the state Supreme Court in lower Manhattan on Oct.
23.
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani administration has denied rally permits to other
contentious groups and fought losing court battles to keep them
from marching.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Giuliani praised the Police Department's decision to
deny the permit. ``Why wouldn't you hold a hate organization to the
letter of the law?'' he said, adding that the Klan is a
``disgusting, horrible organization that represents the very worst
of American history, and maybe it represents the very worst of what
can exist in a human soul.''
</P>
<P>
   James Sheely, the Klan's grand dragon for the Realm of New York
and New Jersey, said the American Knights wanted to be the first
Klan group to march in New York City, with its many parades. ``It's
getting to the end of the century, and we should be the ones to
make history in the largest city in the United States,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 2250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0487 </DOCNO>
