<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-AIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: NEW YORK LEADS ON CLEAN AIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Friday, Oct. 15: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki has decided to force power plants in New York
State to make dramatic cuts in the smokestack emissions that cause
smog and acid rain, beyond the reductions mandated by federal law.
This is a salutary move that will not only help New Yorkers but may
well have important repercussions nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's plan, which needs no legislative approval, would cut
two kinds of pollution _ sulfur dioxide, the main cause of acid
rain, and nitrogen oxide, which causes smog and also contributes to
acid rain. The sulfur dioxide cuts, to be achieved by 2007, would
exceed federal requirements for that year by 50 percent. The
nitrogen oxide cuts would exceed federal targets by about 25
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The move sends two pointed messages _ one to the Midwest, the
other to Washington. For years, New York and other Northeastern
states have suffered from windblown pollution originating in aging,
coal-fired power plants in a half-dozen or so Midwestern and border
states. Recent calculations by clean-air officials in Albany
suggest that no more than 20 percent of the acid rain problem in
the Adirondacks and other upstate areas arises from the state's own
power plants. However, the Midwestern and border states have argued
that New York has long inflated these figures and, further, should
take action against its own dirty plants before asking them to do
the same. Pataki has now called their bluff.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Pataki's plan provides a model for fair competition
in the power industry that Congress, which has not yet figured out
how to deal with the uncertain new world of utility deregulation,
would do well to emulate. Under deregulation, consumers will be
able to buy their power from almost anywhere, and inevitably they
will gravitate to the cheapest producers. Unfortunately, the
cheapest power tends to be produced by the dirtiest plants, those
using plentiful, inexpensive coal. That puts the newer, cleaner but
more expensive gas-fired plants at a competitive disadvantage. The
Pataki plan would level the playing field, at least inside the
state, because New York's coal-fired plants will now have to invest
in expensive systems to filter pollution.
</P>
<P>
   But because consumers will someday be able to buy power from
anywhere in the country _ including coal-fired plants in the
Midwest _ New York's action will count for little unless Congress
levels the playing field nationally, requiring dirty power plants
elsewhere to make similar investments in pollution controls. There
are several bills before Congress that would require such
investments, end the special ``grandfather' clauses that have long
exempted Midwestern plants from federal rules, require significant
investments in clean-air technologies and encourage energy
efficiency and renewable energy sources. But these will go nowhere
without significant White House leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, most of the leadership on clean air these days
seems to be found in the Northeast, particularly New York. There, a
political odd couple _ Pataki and Eliot Spitzer, the democratic
attorney general _ have between them devised a creative legal and
regulatory strategy to compensate for Washington's indifference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 2253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0488 </DOCNO>
