<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7637 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-BELEN-NYT &LR;      10-14 0388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BELEN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Mich.)  
 FREDERICK BELEN, 95, HELPED AUTOMATE POSTAL SYSTEM  (mk) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frederick Christopher Belen, a Washington lawyer who helped
speed the work of the country's growing post office through the
establishment of regional distribution centers and the five-digit
ZIP code, died on Wednesday at Arlington Hospital in Virginia. An
Arlington resident, he was 95.
</P>
<P>
   Belen had a long engagement with the U.S. Post Office, before it
became the Postal Service, at a time when its work load increased
many times.
</P>
<P>
   A former congressional aide, Belen had served as counsel, chief
counsel and staff director of the House Post Office and Civil
Service Committee from 1946 to 1961, when he was appointed
assistant postmaster general for operations.
</P>
<P>
   He served as deputy postmaster general, the second in command,
from 1964 to 1969. In addition, he was a former director of special
studies for the department.
</P>
<P>
   He helped to design, start and oversee the automation of mail
processing and delivery. The innovations of the 1960s included a
network of regional distribution centers and the zone improvement
plan inaugurated in 1963, familiarly known as the ZIP code.
</P>
<P>
   The code's first three digits denote the section of the country
to which an item is destined, while the next two signal a certain
local post office or zone of the addressee. For being the chief
architect who put the system in place, the Post Office Department
gave him its first Benjamin Franklin Award ``for exceptional
leadership'' in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Lansing, Mich., Belen graduated from Michigan State
University in 1937 and earned a doctor of law degree at George
Washington University in 1942. He then served as an officer in
World War II and helped organize the domestic intelligence and
security operations of the Army Transportation Corps.
</P>
<P>
   After retiring from the post office, he practiced law, handling
legislative and postal affairs for clients like United Parcel
Service.
</P>
<P>
   He was president of the National Democratic Club, a political
and social gathering place in Washington, in 1974-75.
</P>
<P>
   Belen's survivors include his wife of 56 years, Opal Marie
Sheets Belen; a son, Frederick Jr. of Herndon, Va.; a sister, and
three grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 2317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0489 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7639 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-LAKE-NYT &LR;      10-14 0231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-LAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMAS LAKE, 80, EX-HEAD OF ELI LILLY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., Pa.)  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thomas Lake, the former president of Eli Lilly &AMP; Co., the
multinational pharmaceutical concern, and former chairman of the
Lilly Endowment, one of the largest private foundations in the
nation, died on Sunday at his home in Carmel, Ind. He was 80.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was melanoma, said a spokeswoman for the endowment,
Gretchen Wolfram.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a coal miner, Lake was born on Jan. 6, 1919, in
Westmoreland County, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   He graduated from Temple University in Philadelphia and worked
as a pharmacist until he enlisted for service in the Army in 1941.
Upon being discharged in 1945, he became a major in the Medical
Administrative Corps.
</P>
<P>
   He began his career in sales at Eli Lilly in 1946 and became
president in 1973. He retired in 1976 but remained a director until
1989.
</P>
<P>
   Lake, who was also active in the effort to renovate downtown
Indianapolis in recent years, was the chairman of the Lilly
Endowment from 1977 to 1992 and was its president from 1977 to
1984. The foundation is a leading source of grants for education in
theology and for community development projects, among other
things.
</P>
<P>
   Lake is survived by his wife, Marjorie; a daughter, Karen Lake
Buttrey of Indianapolis, and one sister, Katherine Snyder of New
Kensington, Pa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
