<HEADLINE>
POSTAL SERVICE WILL ALLOW SIGN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Private mailbox holders will avoid the stigma of
having to identify their addresses as ``PMBs,'' the U.S. Postal
Service has declared.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the agency announced late in the day, customers who
rent mailboxes can also use the number sign -- also known as or the
tic-tac-toe sign -- in their mailing addresses and still expect
their mail will be delivered. The new rule, which is designed to
cut postal fraud, is expected to go into effect in April, USPS
spokeswoman Terri Bouffiou said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The decision may seem minor -- there's not that much difference,
after all, between a PMB and a . But business owners were furious
when the post office first suggested the PMB change, saying it
would make their legitimate businesses -- previously ``located'' in
Suite 200 or Unit 150, for example -- appear suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of mailbox sites also accused the Postal Service of
trying to drive business to the quasigovernmental agency's own post
office boxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision is good news for us because it would have had a
big impact if everyone had to use PMB in their address,'' said
James Bae, manager of Mail Box World in suburban Northridge.
``People would have probably decided just to get a post office box
instead.''
</P>
<P>
   Private companies usually charge $10 to $12 per month, compared
with $5 a month for a post box, but offer additional services such
as mail forwarding, parcel preparation and delivery through
companies like Federal Express.
</P>
<P>
   Briti Haynes, owner and manager of Wall Street Connection in
Tarzana, said many of her customers had expressed reservations
about using PMB as part of the address.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people use us as their business mailing address, and
the PMB would have made them look questionable,'' she explained.
``They didn't like it at all. I don't know what their reaction will
be about the number sign, but I don't think it will be as
negative.''
</P>
<P>
   The USPS, which kicked up a strong negative reaction when it
proposed that all mail destined for privately rented boxes carry
the PMB designation, portrayed its decision as a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new regulations strike a balance between protecting
privacy, supporting small business growth and enhancing our arsenal
in the fight against mail fraud,'' said Chief Postal Inspector
Kenneth Weaver in a written statement.
</P>
<P>
   As previously proposed, the new rules will still bar renters
from using the potentially misleading terms suite, office, bureau
or unit No. If those are used, the mail will be returned to sender.
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
