<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-HOLOCAUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISS OFFER IS ANOTHER TEST FOR HOLOCAUST SURVIVOR
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Her name is not as important as her unhappy past,
which comes back to stalk her every now and then.
</P>
<P>
   What you need to know is that she was once a young woman in
Poland, and, being a Jew, she had to flee when the Germans invaded
in 1939. But there was no refuge in the Polish countryside, not for
her. She spent the next years as a slave laborer in a series of
factories in Germany and Poland. The end of World War II found her
in the Bergen-Belsen concentration camp. Later, she made her way to
America and, ultimately, the Lower East Side of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   This unadorned recitation of basic facts does not do justice to
her ordeal. Be assured that she went through a lot. And now, in her
80s, she is reluctantly reliving it all over again so that she can
assert her claim to compensation from a $1.25 billion fund that
Swiss banks propose to create.
</P>
<P>
   You have probably heard of the fund. Through it, the Swiss hope
to wash their hands of lawsuits accusing them of having profited
from the blood, sweat and tears of victims of the Holocaust. Late
next month, a federal judge in Brooklyn is supposed to decide if
this billion-dollar solution amounts to a fair settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, there are bureaucratic hurdles to surmount before
anyone sees a dime. One is a questionnaire, with a deadline of next
Friday for completion, asking Holocaust survivors to tell their
stories in detail _ not just Jews but also Gypsies, homosexuals,
Jehovah's Witnesses and people with physical or mental
disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The six-page form can be daunting, especially for someone
getting on in years. That was certainly true for the woman from the
Lower East Side, who sought guidance from Beth Zeidel, a social
worker at Selfhelp Community Services, a New York agency that
assists those who suffered Nazi persecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had to go get the scraps of paper that she'd kept,'' Ms.
Zeidel said. ``Just having to sit there and go over it again in
this pointed way was traumatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``She did not cry. She does not cry, this particular lady. She's
not a histrionic type. But when she said to me, `I don't want to go
into any more detail,' I knew that was it. We had to stop and have
some tea. It was a way for her to come back to the present.''
</P>
<P>
   This woman is hardly alone in her anxiety. Elihu Kover,
Selfhelp's director of social services, says that since July his
agency has led 1,300 Holocaust survivors through this phase of the
Swiss settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Many are traumatized by having to make another painful journey
through time. Others are confused by a process that has its share
of complexities, including the questionnaire, which is intended
merely to give information to the court. Those qualifying for
possible reparations fall into broad categories, naturally
including people who had Swiss bank accounts, but also those who,
like Ms. Zeidel's client, were slave laborers for companies that
may have banked in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they are not obligated to fill out the questionnaire
to stake a claim, some survivors cannot shake a fear that all will
be lost if they miss next Friday's deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the confusion is the fact that the Holocaust,
suddenly, is being relived on many fronts. Reparations settlements
are in the works not only with the Swiss banks but also with
European insurance companies, Austrian banks, German companies that
used slave labor and museums holding art once looted by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   Billions are at stake. And still ahead is perhaps the trickiest
question of all: how to divvy up the money. Do you simply cut each
victim a check, or do you devise something arguably more creative?
</P>
<P>
   A billion dollars _ or two or three _ will not stretch far if
spread among all Holocaust survivors, estimated by the World Jewish
Congress at 500,000 worldwide and 40,000 in the New York region.
For that reason, some say it would be far more effective to pool
the reparations money, to create a health insurance fund, for
example.
</P>
<P>
   Among those urging this solution is Menachem Rosensaft, founding
chairman of the International Network of Children of Jewish
Holocaust Survivors. ``If you provide 10 years' worth of medical
coverage, you will, unfortunately, cover the vast number of the
survivors,'' Rosensaft said.
</P>
<P>
   He said ``unfortunately'' because it is lost on no one that the
clock is running. At Selfhelp, 59 percent of the clients are over
80. For some, it is getting late, very late indeed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
