<HEADLINE>
EX-TROJAN BARNUM DELIVERS MESSAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Just in case USC wasn't taking its rivalry with
Notre Dame seriously, former fullback Terry Barnum delivered a
fiery speech after practice Thursday, while brandishing the
symbolic Shillelagh, which goes to the winner of the contest.
</P>
<P>
   The usually soft-spoken Barnum, who also played for Alemany
High, forcefully addressed the team on the importance of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our half of the rivalry, we need to bring the emotion
back. There needs to be some understanding of what this game
means,'' Barnum said. ``This is a part of their legacy. This is the
game they will remember. There's nothing like playing Notre Dame at
Notre Dame.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnum, who is the business manager for USC's school of Letters,
Arts and Sciences, and is working on his master's degree, was asked
to speak to the Trojans by coach Paul Hackett.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of what record a team has, this is the game people
remember,'' Barnum said.
</P>
<P>
   Barnum's comments were greeted by applause from the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terry's got a lot of fire and pride,'' quarterback Mike Van
Raaphorst said. ``It's interesting to hear from a guy who didn't do
too well against Notre Dame and UCLA. And how he remembers his time
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said he will take the Shillelagh, which is a Gaelic war
club and resembles a wooden mallet, to South Bend and place it in
the locker room for the team to view before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the guys said don't take it on the plane, we don't
want to give it back,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Running back shuffle: It appears tailback Sultan McCullough and
perhaps even Malaefou MacKenzie or Frank Strong could get more
carries behind starter Chad Morton this week, as Hackett tries to
offer a different look against Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chad will take a couple series, then will have another guy
take a series,'' Hackett said. ``Attacking a defense with a guy
that doesn't have the same style can shake them up.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said McCullough would probably be the No.2 tailback, but
MacKenzie and Strong would also play.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't about Chad. You need all of them in a game like
this,'' Hackett said. ``You've got to control the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Ready or not? Wide receiver Kareem Kelly said it's not easy to
tell if the offense will improve from last weekend based solely on
practice performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always have good practices,'' Kelly said. ``It all depends
on the game on Saturday. We just need to execute.''
</P>
<P>
   Best against the best: Hackett has had USC's first-string
offense going against the first-string defense this week. He said
he would continue this method the rest of the season, as the
Trojans begin holding shorter practices, particularly once daylight
savings time ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quality of the work is the most important thing,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Soward progresses: Wide receiver R. Jay Soward continues to
recover from his concussion, although Hackett said he is not quite
100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was better (Thursday),'' Hackett said. ``I'm counting on
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Weather forecast: The latest weather report from South Bend,
Ind., calls for showers Saturday with a temperature in the mid-50s.
That's about a 30-degree dropoff from last week, when the Trojans
played Arizona in 95-degree heat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
