<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAD-LAWYERS-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATES' PAYMENTS TO LAWYERS BRING CONTINGENCY-FEE BATTLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 14th graf to correct day suit was filed) (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) (th) 
 By BARRY MEIER and RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A growing wave of lawsuits by cities and states against makers
of tobacco, guns _ and now lead paint _ has reignited a fierce
debate over the role of lawyers and the enormous fees they can earn
in legal actions brought by public officials.
</P>
<P>
   The issue erupted after prominent plaintiffs' lawyers, hired by
state attorneys general to sue cigarette makers, earned billions of
dollars in contingency fees as a result of the $246 billion in
settlements with the companies. Now some of those same lawyers,
whose earnings are contingent upon their winning a percentage of
any jury award or settlement, have been hired by states and cities
to sue gun makers and lead paint producers.
</P>
<P>
   As part of business counteroffensive against the trend, the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce will soon begin an intensive lobbying campaign
to get legislatures to drastically restrict states' use of
contingency lawyers. Recently, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas also
signed a law, backed by companies, that sharply limited the ability
of the state's attorney general to hire contingency-fee lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The question has split legal experts. Economically strapped
elected officials need the skills and resources of outside lawyers
to handle difficult cases, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It levels the playing field because the other side is relying
on very skilled lawyers,'' said Robert L. Rabin, a professor of law
at Stanford University.
</P>
<P>
   But the interests of those lawyers can conflict with those of
the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fees can be out of line with the amount of work and effort
that is actually put in,'' Rabin said.
</P>
<P>
   Some cities suing the gun industry have decided to use their own
lawyers, rather than outside counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Under the legislation proposed by the Chamber of Commerce, any
outside lawyer who contributed more than $250 to the campaign of a
public official would be barred from being hired to pursue a
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Wootton, the executive director of Institute for Legal
Reform at the United States Chamber of Commerce, said that
provision would restrict influence peddling. Plaintiffs' lawyers,
though, have contributed largely to Democratic candidates, while
the business interests they sue have traditionally supported
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The law would also prohibit a state from changing any laws that
could affect litigation while the state was suing an industry or
even contemplating such a lawsuit, Wootton said.
</P>
<P>
   Wootton said limiting the use of contingency lawyers was a vital
issue for industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is one of the biggest threats facing American
industry today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The latest such challenge came on Tuesday when Rhode Island
Attorney General Sheldon Whitehouse said his state would sue eight
paint companies and a lead industry group to seek payment for the
treatment of children poisoned by lead paint and for its removal.
</P>
<P>
   The case will be handled by the law firm of Ness, Motley,
Loadholt, Richardson &AMP; Poole of Charleston, S.C., which represented
some two dozen states in tobacco cases, earning hundreds of
millions in fees in the process. Rhode Island will pay 17 percent
of any award or settlement to the firm, which is financing the
lawsuit and talks with other states about similar actions.
</P>
<P>
   Other tobacco veterans are also posed to jump in. Richard
Scruggs, a Pascagoula, Miss., lawyer who represented that state and
some 20 others against cigarette makers, has had talks with public
officials interested in suing. And Steve Berman, a Seattle lawyer
who represented several states, including Washington, in their
tobacco case, said he has discussed lead paint lawsuits with two
attorneys general.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers have challenged in court contentious industries that
have successfully fought legislative restrictions or regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Many legal experts believe that such high-powered law firms can
play a valuable role in public litigation because they have
financial resources to spend years, if necessary, tracking
documents, interviewing witnesses and aggressively fighting
pretrial motions.
</P>
<P>
   John Coffee, a professor of law at Columbia University said he
believed that it would be a ``disaster'' for the public if the type
of legislation being promoted by the Chamber of Commerce was
adopted.
</P>
<P>
   But Coffee also voiced concerns about potential conflicts
between lawyers who donate heavily to the campaigns of officials
who can hire them. And other legal experts said that outside
lawyers could have a financial stake in settling a case that might
be at odds with the broad public's goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public might have been interested in getting more
concessions from cigarette companies in return for taking less
money'' said Susan Koniak, a professor of law at Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   Berman, the plaintiff's lawyer in Seattle, said he believed that
outside lawyers representing states cut the best deals possible in
striking settlements with tobacco companies. But he acknowledged
that some of the huge legal fees awarded in those cases had fueled
the larger controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, lawyers representing the first three states that
settled _ Florida, Mississippi and Texas _ were awarded $8.2
billion in fees. The staggering fees prompted public uproar,
particularly in Texas, where one lawyer, Mark D. Murr of Houston,
who appeared to play little role in the litigation, sought $260
million in fees.
</P>
<P>
   Faced by a state investigation, Murr, whose request was
supported by the former Texas Attorney General who hired him,
backed down. But this year, Republican lawmakers with the backing
of business groups passed legislation requiring the state attorney
general to have contingency-fee contracts approved by a board
appointed by top state officials. Legal fees could not exceed
$4,000 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Utah legislators also passed a bill this year requiring that
state's attorney general to get approval from the governor before
filing a civil lawsuit. But after state Attorney General Jan Graham
threatened to challenge its constitutionality, she struck a deal
with lawmakers under which her office will keep the governor
appraised of any litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Cities who are heading the legal assault against gun makers have
taken different stances on outside lawyers. While some like New
Orleans, Atlanta and Newark. N.J., have hired lawyers involved in
tobacco cases under contingency deals, others like Chicago are
using their own lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Berman, the Seattle plaintiff's lawyer, said those various
approaches have apparently created some conflicts. Recently, for
example, when lawyers representing several cities suing gun makers
and a few states considering such actions meet with manufacturers
cities who had hired outside lawyers were excluded from the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Along with suing gun makers and paint producers, some of the
tobacco lawyers like Scruggs have also filed actions against health
maintenance organizations, claiming that they failed to provide
policyholders with promised benefits.
</P>
<P>
   And Coffee, the law professor, said he would not be surprised if
similar actions by public entities like cities soon followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look over the horizon, the filings on behalf of state
plaintiffs tend to come after the lawsuits filed on behalf of
individuals,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 2324EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0494 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7651 &Cx1f; tth-z
r a BC-KENNEWICK-MAN-SPI &LR;      10-14 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KENNEWICK-MAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL: ANCIENT KENNEWICK MAN APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN ASIAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The controversial bones known as Kennewick Man look
more Asian than European or Native American, potentially
jeopardizing tribal legal claims to the remains.
</P>
<P>
   A court-appointed scientific panel concluded in a report
released Thursday that the skeletal remains look most like the
Ainu, an indigenous sub-population in Japan with ancient roots in
southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kennewick man has the strongest (skeletal) affinity with
southern Asians, not Native Americans or Europeans,'' said Joseph
Powell, a physical anthropologist at the University of New Mexico
and member of the panel.
</P>
<P>
   But this ethnic identification will not end the battle over who
controls the remains.
</P>
<P>
   New radiocarbon dating tests to be released in a few weeks could
tip the balance in favor of Native American claims.
</P>
<P>
   Should the tests confirm the 9,000-year-old estimate of the
bones, then the federal government is obliged to declare the
remains Native American, said Frank McManamon, chief archaeologist
for the U.S. Interior Department and lead scientist on the
Kennewick Man panel. Under federal law, ``Native American'' is
defined as any population living here before the arrival of
Christopher Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   If existing tribes can then show a direct link to Kennewick man,
they will control the remains and, scientists fear, the bones will
be lost to further study.
</P>
<P>
   Proving a link could require comparing the DNA of Kennewick Man
and existing Native American tribes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it will be necessary,'' said Alan Schneider, the
Portland, Ore., attorney representing scientists suing for access
to Kennewick Man.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't accept the federal government's time-dependent
definition of Native American,'' Schneider said. The only possible
way for modern Native Americans to establish any direct connection
with these bones, he said, would be if DNA testing demonstrates a
shared genetic history.
</P>
<P>
   Kennewick Man has become a test challenge to the federal Native
American Graves Protection Repatriation Act of 1990, which gives
Indian tribes authority to claim remains deemed Native American.
</P>
<P>
   Eight leading scientists have sued in U.S. District Court in
Portland for the right to examine the remains because the bones
could help with the study of prehistoric human migration in North
America.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Magistrate John Jelderks last year convened a panel of
experts to answer the question of whether Kennewick Man is Native
American or not. It was that panel's findings that were released
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like asking if the woolly mammoth is either an Asian or
African elephant,'' Powell said. ``We did the best we could.''
</P>
<P>
   But the whole debate is frustrating, Powell said, particularly
since the ethnic identification of such ancient remains may not
mean that much anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were asked to do a (racial) typology of the remains and
stick them into these existing categories,'' he said. ``It's like
saying there are only three colors in the world and we were
supposed to pick one.''
</P>
<P>
   In reality, Powell said, humans should be viewed as a color
spectrum _ especially farther back in time. ``At some point, we all
go back to the same ancestor,'' Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   The question, he said, is whether today's racial categories mean
much when looking at people 9,000 years ago. But that's not the
question the federal judge ordered Powell and his colleagues to
answer.
</P>
<P>
   Powell said the bones look most like an Asian type but not much
like modern Asian skeletons.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't look like any modern group,'' Powell said. ``What
this means in terms of its connection to the tribes, we don't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   The connection is not just academic because of the scientists'
challenge of the federal law governing control over ancient
remains.
</P>
<P>
   The law as written is simple, but Kennewick Man shows in
practice it is anything but.
</P>
<P>
   The bones washed out of the Columbia River in Washington state
in July 1996 and immediately became the focal point of a dispute
between local tribes and a group of scientists led by Doug Owsley
of the Smithsonian Institution.
</P>
<P>
   Richland, Wash., archaeologist Jim Chatters initially identified
the bones as an ancient ``Caucasoid'' _ a largely obsolete
anthropological term (like Mongoloid or Negroid) that has
persistently been misinterpreted in media reports to indicate the
bones appeared to be that of an ancient Caucasian.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just won't go away,'' Chatters said Thursday. ``I get
blamed for that but I never said Caucasian. ... I'm exhausted with
all this.''
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of ancient Europeans peopling the New World
thousands of years before Columbus was seized upon by some
scientists who sought to block Indian claims on the bones.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Stanford, a Smithsonian anthropologist and one of the
plaintiffs seeking to study Kennewick Man, has repeatedly
emphasized that without study ``you can't rule out'' the chance
that an ancient European somehow ended up on the Columbia Plateau
9,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford is a leading proponent of the notion that Europeans may
have made it to the New World before the Asian migration across the
Bering Strait.
</P>
<P>
   Most scientists believe the Americas were first populated by
ancient Asian people who walked _ or perhaps used boats _ to cross
over from Siberia to Alaska when global sea levels were much lower.
</P>
<P>
   David Meltzer, a paleoanthropologist at Southern Methodist
University, said ``there's no archaeological evidence to support''
Stanford's theory of an early European migration to America.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the myth of the ancient white man prompted a group
devoted to Norse mythology called the Asatru Assembly to also lay
claim to the bones of Kennewick Man based on their belief that he
might be a wayward Viking.
</P>
<P>
   The legal battle over control of the remains has severely
limited study of the skeleton. Nonetheless, some information about
the ancient traveler has come to light.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Stein, a University of Washington archaeologist, and Gary
Huckleberry, an archaeologist at Washington State University,
evaluated sediments collected with the bones and found ash from the
massive volcanic explosion of Mt. Mazame nearly 7,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it appears to be at least that old,'' Stein said.
</P>
<P>
   John Fagan, a private archaeologist from Portland and an expert
in stone tools, evaluated the spearpoint fragment found embedded in
Kennewick Man's hip. Fagan believes the spearpoint _ a prehistoric
style known as a Cascadia point _ was stabbed in Kennewick Man
sometime during his teenage years.
</P>
<P>
   In general, Kennewick Man was estimated to be a well-muscled man
in his 40s or 50s who had led a rough life.
</P>
<P>
   The bones are being held for the duration of the lawsuit in
secure storage at the Burke Museum on the campus of the University
of Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 2326EDT &QL; 
