<SLUG> BC-SUPERIOR-PARTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEEL MAKER BENEFITS FROM INDUSTRY SURGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Superior Industries International Inc., a wheel
maker for numerous vehicle manufacturers, is expected to report a
big gain in third quarter earnings Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A survey of six analysts by First Call pegs Superior earnings at
50 cents a share, up from 28 cents in the year ago period.
</P>
<P>
   Superior's earnings report was expected to be issued before the
market opened.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been saying we're comfortable with the First Call
estimates,'' said R. Jeffrey Orenstein, the company's investor
relations officer.
</P>
<P>
   The prior year's third-quarter results reflect the impact of a
strike by auto workers against General Motors Corp.
</P>
<P>
   That work stoppage reduced Superior's shipment of wheels to the
big auto maker during the second and third quarters.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, the company's production is up in step with
that of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   For example, BMW said this week 1999 is shaping up to be its
best year in the United States, with sales up 19 percent to 116,308
units through September. The company's global sales are up 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Superior is an original equipment manufacturer for the German
auto maker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Superior continues to perform very well and benefit from a
strong industry buildup,'' said analyst Eric Goldstein at Bear
Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hoselton at McDonald Investments Inc. also gives kudos to
Superior's management.
</P>
<P>
   ``The management at Superior is excellent. They have been able
to translate that higher production rate down to their earnings.
These guys are good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
