<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-EVANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARL EVANS, 89, PIONEERING BIOCHEMIST 
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ill., Md.) (mk) 
 By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Earl Alison Evans, a pioneering biochemist who built up one
of the nation's leading biochemistry departments at the University
of Chicago, died on Oct. 5 at a hospital in Chicago, where he
lived. He was 89.
</P>
<P>
   Evans, a professor emeritus and former chairman of the
department of biochemistry and molecular biology at the university,
was an early researcher into the use of radioactive isotopes to
study metabolism and the use of a group of viruses known as
bacteriophages to study the workings of DNA.
</P>
<P>
   He also pioneered the use of a short-lived carbon isotope, 11C,
produced in the cyclotron at the University of Chicago by his
colleague Louis Slotkin, and used it to show that animal cells,
like photosynthetic plants, were capable of using carbon dioxide
for the synthesis of carbohydrates, a process called CO2 fixation.
His work with the isotope brought him the Lilly Medal in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   In 1942, he became chairman of the department and recruited
acclaimed scientists including Konrad Bloch, who won the Nobel
Prize in 1964 for his radioactive-tracer work on cholesterol
biosynthesis. Evans stepped down as chairman in 1972, but continued
to teach until 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Born on March 11, 1910, in Baltimore, Evans earned his
bachelor's degree from Johns Hopkins University and a doctorate
from Columbia University. He joined the faculty at Chicago as an
instructor in 1937.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his work at Chicago, Evans spent one year, 1939, as a
research fellow with Hans Krebs, who won a Nobel Prize in 1953.
During World War II, Evans was the principal investigator in
malaria research for the federal government's Office of Scientific
Research and Development. After the war, he was the scientific
attache in the U.S. Embassy in London for two years.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by a son, David Lasswell of Chicago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 2338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991014.0497 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-14 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7660 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-PAKISTAN-MILITARY-1ST     10-14 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-MILITARY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILITARY LEADER DECLARES HIMSELF PAKISTAN'S CHIEF EXECUTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS throughout; note new byline and dateline) (rk) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan _ The new military ruler of Pakistan imposed
martial law shortly after midnight Friday, suspending the
constitution, dismissing the Parliament and dashing hopes of a
quick return to civilian rule in the world's newest nuclear power.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Pervaiz Musharraf, the army chief who led a brutally
efficient but bloodless coup on Tuesday night, also proclaimed
himself chief executive of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   His soldiers sealed off the Parliament and its legislative
offices here in the capital, and they continue to hold Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif and some of his closest aides under house
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   As dawn broke Friday, the Parliament, the Supreme Court and the
prime minister's headquarters were deserted, without a soldier in
sight.
</P>
<P>
   The declaration came in the form of a broadcast in the middle of
the night. Pakistan's government-run television station, seized by
Musharraf's forces Tuesday night. It displayed, in tose-up,
a copy of what looked like a hastily drafted document declaring
martial law in everything but name. Instead, the document referred
carefully to a ``state of emergency.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole of Pakistan will come under the control of the armed
forces of Pakistan,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   The constitution of Pakistan does not permit the army to remove
a prime minister or Parliament unless the military formally
suspends the constitution under martial law.
</P>
<P>
   The declaration was drafted Thursday as Musharraf and his
lieutenants met at the army's general headquarters in Rawalapindi
with the figurehead president of Pakistan, Rafiq Taraz, and several
of the nation's leading constitutional scholars.
</P>
<P>
   The coup against the increasingly unpopular prime minister,
Sharif, was a cause for celebration in the streets and the salons
of Pakistan. But the news of the declaration of a state of
emergency may be more sobering.
</P>
<P>
   There had been hope here that Musharraf, whose swift coup was
evidently well prepared and executed, also had a plan to hand
control of Pakistan back to civilian rulers in a matter of days or
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But for now the governance of 135 million people, the leadership
of a 500,000-man army and the control of a simmering political and
military confrontation with India, Pakistan's nuclear-armed
neighbor, is in the hands of a man who, in his own words, is ``not
a political or constitutional expert.''
</P>
<P>
   The army was the last remaining institution in Pakistan with
real power, since Sharif, though he was elected by a landslide in
1997, squandered much of his own power and authority while trying
to strip the courts, the presidency and rival political parties of
theirs. The result, Mussaraf said in his address to the nation this
week, also broadcast in the dead of night, was that ``all the
institutions'' of civil society had ``been played around with and
systematically destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan has endured military rule for 25 of its 52 years as a
nation, and some of those years were marked by violent repression.
But the army seized power, in part, because political leaders in
Pakistan repeatedly have proved themselves unable to lead.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Sharif was dismissed by the president _ legally, under
the constitution _ for corruption and incompetence; his
predecessor, Benazir Bhutto, was twice dismissed, in 1990 and 1996,
on essentially identical charges.
</P>
<P>
   Though the United States had cautioned against a coup, it has
worked closely with military rulers in Pakistan before. The last
military dictator of Pakistan, General Mohammad Zia ul-Haq,
received more than $3 billion in military aid from the United
States and served as a close confidant of the Central Intelligence
Agency and a Cold War ally of Washington's in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   He died in a still-unexplained air crash in 1988, ending an
11-year reign that began when he arrested and hanged his
predecessor, Prime Minister Zulfiqar Ali Bhutto, Ms. Bhutto's
father.
</P>
<P>
   International calls for a return to democracy mounted in the
days since the coup. In his news conference on Thursday, President
Clinton addressed the coup's leaders, saying: `` `You should not do
it. It's not necessary, it will hurt your economy and endanger your
future.' That is our message to Pakistan, and we hope they will
move to a civilian government as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Musharraf moved quickly to purge the government of potential
enemies. He dismissed and arrested the military intelligence chief,
Lt. Gen. Khwaja Ziauddin, who went to Washington last month to warn
the CIA about the growing likelihood of a military coup. He also
fired the chief of the national airline, Shaheed Kahkan Abbassi,
whom the army accused of conspiring with Sharif to capture or kill
Musharraf as he returned to Pakistan on Tuesday evening on a
commercial flight from Sri Lanka, where Sharif had sent him on an
official visit.
</P>
<P>
   In what appears to have been a coordinated move, the Pakistan
International Airlines jet carrying Musharraf was denied permission
to land at the nation's largest airport, in Karachi, at the very
moment Sharif dismissed the general. As the plane ran short of
fuel, the army, in a swift response, seized the control tower and
within hours had taken control of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Musharraf had been Sharif's handpicked choice for army chief a
year ago. But the two men have been at loggerheads over Sharif's
decision to withdraw the Pakistan-backed forces that occupied a
section of Indian-held Kashmir over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   The military felt that Sharif had bowed to pressure from Clinton
by agreeing to the pullout, and then tried to blame the military
for the failed military adventure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-99 2341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
