A7662 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-KSWISS-EARNINGS-LADN     10-14 0348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KSWISS-EARNINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
K-SWISS PROFITS REBOUND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- K-Swiss Inc., which has been hammered by Wall
Street recently, reported it had more than tripled its
third-quarter profits to come in at the top end of analysts'
predictions.
</P>
<P>
   The athletic shoemaker, which saw its stock decline 30 percent
on Oct. 5 in the wake of a disappointing Y2K orders forecast,
posted earnings Thursday of $9.34 million, or 80 cents a share,
compared with $3.03 million, or 26 cents a share, in the 1998
period.
</P>
<P>
   It had disclosed on Oct. 5 that profits would range between 70
and 80 cents a share, and the First Call forecast from two analysts
tracking the stock was 75 cents. Sales more than doubled to $80.13
million, slightly above the company's forecast.
</P>
<P>
   The impressive numbers, issued after the stock market closed,
may not carry much weight on Wall Street since Steven Nichols,
chairman and president, issued a warning in a statement that opened
by saying he was pleased with the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very nature of the footwear industry and its reliance on
futures orders, however, keeps us constantly looking past immediate
results and focusing at least six months in advance,'' he said.
``Initial indications from our backlog reflect some uncertainty and
cautiousness among retail accounts, a disproportionate share of
which was concentrated in some of our larger customers, due to the
current selling environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Nichols said selling of current shoes continues to be strong and
the company's research had found strong consumer acceptance of
first-quarter offerings.
</P>
<P>
   K-Swiss stock gained 75 cents to close at $17 a share Thursday
but it has lost more than 40 percent of its value this month and is
70 percent below its all-time high of $57.75 in late May.
</P>
<P>
   Nine-month earnings also more than tripled, rising to $29.36
million, or $2.55 a share, from $8.33 million, or 77 cents a share,
and sales rose 94.1 percent to $235.88 million.
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
